<HEADLINE>
APACHE COMMUNITY FINALLY GETS HOME TELEPHONE CONNECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BYLAS, Ariz. _ Just let Cherrill Williams go on about living in
a town without telephones.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Paul, was working beneath their mobile home a year
ago when it fell off a jack and trapped him. Frantic family members
went to the only pay phone in this Apache tribal community of 2,000
people.
</P>
<P>
   But it was out of order.
</P>
<P>
   They finally found someone a half-hour later with a car phone to
summon an emergency helicopter from Safford. By the time it finally
arrived, Cherrill already had dug Paul out with her hands.
</P>
<P>
   So, Cherrill arrived early Tuesday and got one of the best seats
in the Bylas community gymnasium for the big day _ dedication
ceremonies for 400 new home telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was so excited when her telephone line was
connected Monday night that she immediately made 10 calls and then
slept with it in her hand.
</P>
<P>
   Others said they talked all night. Call it pent-up gossip.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal officials like Vice Chairman Velasquez Sneezy called it a
crowning achievement on the cusp of the millennium, a chance to
learn what all the technology was about in the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   ``But remember,'' he warned the crowd in the gym. ``Pay your
bills or the phones will go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite being on a major highway in eastern Arizona, U.S. 70,
Bylas has had only 12 telephone lines for decades. And nine of
those 12 lines were exclusively for law enforcement and emergency
services. Two of the lines were in private homes and then there was
the single pay phone, on the side of the fire station.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency workers said they have broken up numerous fights there
among the many people waiting their turn. Not to mention the times
they've been awakened at 3 a.m. by people wanting change.
</P>
<P>
   US West had strung lines through the middle of Bylas years ago.
But charging a $3,000 connection fee was a lot more than members of
this impoverished community could pay.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the San Carlos Apache Telecommunications Utility took
over the service and received a $14 million loan in 1997 from the
rural-development arm of the U.S. Department of Agriculture to
install the lines.
</P>
<P>
   It's about time, said Luther Victor, director of emergency
services in Bylas.
</P>
<P>
   Victor said that during his 13 years on the job, 20 houses have
burned to the ground needlessly and at least 10 people have died
due to traffic accidents and medical conditions. All could have
been prevented, Victor said, by having telephones at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, people with an emergency better have hoped they had a
good vehicle. Or a strong pair of legs to get them to the police
station.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were more advanced when we used smoke signals,'' quipped
Verna Cassa, a San Carlos Tribal Council member.
</P>
<P>
   Worse yet was trying to get on the receiving end of urgent
messages.
</P>
<P>
   They almost all came into the Police Department and tended to be
parceled out to those who were in favor with whomever was in power
with the tribal administration in San Carlos, 30 miles down the
road.
</P>
<P>
   That left the homes of Bryant Moses and the Rev. Billy Grant as
the only two outposts with phone contact with the rest of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Moses said his unlisted number has circulated throughout Bylas
over the years, leading to a daily pipeline of people to his
doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got so bad for incoming calls that we finally started
saying, `OK, I have a pen right here' before, click, hanging up on
them,'' Moses said. ``Thank God we got some more phone lines in
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant and his wife, Rita, who have a Pentecostal church on the
outskirts of town, said they always tried to help people in
distress. They even passed along messages to relatives of members
of the Geronimo Hot Shot forest-firefighting team when they fought
fires in other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very stern with people who tried to use our phone just
to chat,'' Billy Grant said. ``I got so frustrated because I was
answering calls all the time from businesses where people from
Bylas had listed me as a reference because there are so few phones
here.''
</P>
<P>
   There was one notable omission in all the hoopla around town
Tuesday, however.
</P>
<P>
   Someone forgot about connecting phone lines to the San Carlos
Tribe's district headquarters in Bylas, office director Ophelia
Robertson said. She looked sadly at a discarded cell phone on her
desk; it had quit working months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tribal Council is always sending messages to me through
the Police Department to go out and find this and that person
because they need to go to a special council meeting in San
Carlos,'' she said. ``I think I better keep the engine running.'' &QL; 
Mark Shaffer can be reached at (602) 444-8057 or at
mark.shaffer(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
