<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-BOSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX DEFEAT YANKEES, 5-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hideki Irabu is blessed with two great talents. He
can throw a baseball very hard, and with equal force he can throw
away good will with exceptional timing and efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu's manager hopes he succeeds and establishes himself once
and for all in the Yankees' rotation, and the fans at Yankee
Stadium _ desperate to embrace anyone who can propel the Yankees
out of their funk _ want to accept Irabu.
</P>
<P>
   When he hustled to cover first base on Tuesday night, they gave
him a standing ovation, and Irabu proceeded to fall apart within
his next nine pitches. Mike Stanley slammed a three-run home run
off Irabu and the Red Sox won, 5-2, moving two and a half games
ahead of the Yankees in the American League East.
</P>
<P>
   Boston (27-17) has won three of its first four games this season
with the Yankees (24-19), who have scored three runs or fewer in 8
of their last 13 games. They went 1 for 8 with runners in scoring
position on Tuesday night, prompting Manager Joe Torre to forgo
batting practice for Wednesday's game with the Red Sox; the Yankees
don't have to report until 11:30 a.m., 95 minutes before the first
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always thinking of ways to do something to help this
club,'' Torre said. ``This game is made up of good times and bad
times, and right now, we're a little flat.''
</P>
<P>
   All in all, Irabu pitched adequately, matching Boston's Brian
Rose in a 1-1 tie through the first five innings. When a pitcher's
fastball is exceptional, when it appears to cut through the bats of
opposing hitters, in Japanese it is said that the fastball has
kire. Translated literally, the word means slice.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu's fastball had kire against the Red Sox in the early
innings, good enough to overwhelm Jason Varitek on a swinging
strikeout with runners on base in the second inning, good enough to
splinter the bat of Darren Lewis. The only run he allowed came on a
two-out bloop single.
</P>
<P>
   But Irabu seemingly has a knack for turning something good into
something much less than that. He will often follow a dominant
performance with two poor outings, and club officials will fret
over his consistency. The best example of his gift for timing came
on the last day of the Yankees' training camp in Florida, when
Irabu failed to cover first base in the final inning on what should
have been the final out of an otherwise fine outing.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Daubach pulled a grounder toward the right side of the
infield leading off the sixth inning on Tuesday night, and Tino
Martinez dived ove to his right and gloved the ball. Suddenly,
there was Irabu, sprinting to cover first, nimbly reaching high to
catch the throw from Martinez and step on the bag, far more
graceful and determined than any fat toad.
</P>
<P>
   With their sense of history, the 37,715 fans at Yankee Stadium
stood and roared, and Irabu grinned. Teammates tried suppressing
their laughter, Martinez needing his giant first baseman's mitt to
cover his face. ``I was impressed,'' Irabu said later, referring to
the fans' knowledge of his past trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Had Irabu gone on to win the game, this could have been a
beachhead toward improved relations between Irabu and the fans. But
Nomar Garciaparra beat out an infield hit, Troy O'Leary walked and
Stanley pounded a fastball _ a thigh-high fastball over the inner
half of the plate that catcher Jorge Posada wanted thrown farther
inside _ into the left field stands. Shortly thereafter Irabu
departed to scattered boos once more.
</P>
<P>
   One bad pitch, Torre said later in excusing Irabu. One bad pitch
in an otherwise good outing. But Torre did not offer any excuses
for the lame offense needing a jump start.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a break from batting practice will do that, though Don
Zimmer tried this already during his tenure as the Yankees' interim
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the Yankees' more slump-ridden members, Chuck Knoblauch
and Paul O'Neill, started well on Tuesday night, Knoblauch
hammering a lead-off home run off Rose. Two batters later, O'Neill
drove a low fastball between Boston's outfielders in right and
center, the ball rolling to the wall, and O'Neill gained momentum
as he turned at first and second.
</P>
<P>
   When he slid into third base with a triple, he sat in the dirt
for a few seconds, as if to reacquaint himself with the feeling the
extra-base hit; this was his first in 16 games. Many of the fans at
Yankee Stadium, with whom O'Neill has built great collateral, stood
and clapped, understanding the significance of the hit. It was
going to be a good night, it seemed.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams struck out and Martinez grounded out, stranding
O'Neill at third, and for the next five innings the Yankees barely
touched Rose, who changed speeds and threw strikes. Later, Chili
Davis credited the Boston right-hander for pitching a good game.
</P>
<P>
   Davis knows, however, that last year the Yankees feasted on
right-handers like Rose, underpowering and inexperienced pitchers.
The Yankees would work the count and get some runners on base,
weaken a pitcher, and then pounce.
</P>
<P>
   They're doing none of that these days. ``We'll see him again,
hopefully,'' Davis said. ``And it'll be a different offense then.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, for the Yankees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
