<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PIRATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BEAT PIRATES, 8-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ No matter how ridiculous it would have sounded at
the start of the season, Masato Yoshii is the ace of the New York
Mets' staff right now.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii turned in another sterling performance tonight to win his
fourth straight start, allowing two runs on five hits in six and
two-thirds innings of an 8-3 victory over the Pittsburgh Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   After Mike Piazza and Brian McRae each homered and drove in
three runs, Yoshii (5-3) now has two more victories than any other
member of the Mets' starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   And to think, less than a month ago, when his earned run average
was 7.52 after four starts, the Japanese right-hander was on the
verge of being run out of the major leagues. Now his era is 3.98,
best in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``People wanted to write him off over spring training and a
couple of starts,'' Manager Bobby Valentine said. ``I thought it
was rather embarrassing to their judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is criticizing Yoshii anymore. In his last five starts,
Yoshii has allowed six runs (five of them on solo home runs) in
312/3 innings, an earned run average of 1.71. And the Mets are 5-0
in those starts.
</P>
<P>
   When the club hurriedly re-signed Yoshii to a two-year, $5
million contract during General Manager Steve Phillips's brief
leave of absence last fall, many within and without the
organization felt the Mets had overpaid him. And after his poor
start this season, there was speculation that Yoshii might be
demoted to the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Yoshii pitching well and his fellow starters, Al
Leiter, Rick Reed and Bobby Jones, bothered by injuries and high
era's, he might be justified in asking for a raise.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's for the off season,'' Yoshii said through his
translator, Kota Ishijima. With a laugh, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine again praised the way Yoshii worked with Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just kind of get this feeling when he doesn't want to throw
a pitch,'' Piazza said. ``But it's funny. He doesn't shake me off.
I don't know if he doesn't want to hurt my feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   McRae said that Yoshii has his teammates' confidence. ``The way
he's throwing, you know he's going to give you a good outing,''
said McRae, who left the game with a bruised left hand that neither
he nor Valentine thought was very serious. ``He's pitching like he
did last year when we didn't score him any runs.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, two pitches into the game, Yoshii was trailing, 1-0,
after allowing a lead-off home run to Al Martin. But Yoshii has
been susceptible to home runs. And since he changed his position on
the pitching rubber on May 2, the only runs Yoshii had allowed were
on solo home runs _ four of them in 25 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Another solo homer was little cause for concern then, even it
was still 1-0 entering the fourth inning. The Pirates''
hard-throwing Kris Benson _ the No. 1 overall selection of the 1996
draft _ had limited the Mets to one hit and two walks. But then
Piazza belted a breaking ball an estimated 443 feet into the third
deck for his ninth homer of the year and the score was 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Benson, whose fastball was clocked as high as 95 miles an hour
on Tuesday night, seemed shaken. Robin Ventura followed with a
hard-hit single to right-center, and Edgardo Alfonzo drew a
full-count walk.
</P>
<P>
   McRae was up next. Benson left another breaking ball over the
plate, and McRae crushed it over the right field fence for a 4-1
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Giles opened the bottom of the fourth with a double and
Yoshii then hit Kevin Young with a pitch. But after Giles took
third on Jason Kendall's fly to right, Yoshii struck out Ed Sprague
and caught Jose Guillen looking, and the 4-1 advantage was intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't get rattled very often,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   That attitude might explain why Yoshii shook off the early
season criticisms.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might not believe this, but I've been playing this game
for a long time,'' Yoshii, who played 13 seasons in Japan, said.
``How people judge me, it doesn't bother me anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
