</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-LEAFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAPLE LEAFS DEFEAT SABRES, 6-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ When Dwayne Roloson gave up four goals in Game 1 of
the Sabres-Maple Leafs Eastern Conference final series, he was seen
as sort of a super substitute, a successful replacement for Dominik
Hasek, the injured Buffalo goalie. That was because Roloson's
teammates scored one more goal than the Maple Leafs to win the
opener, 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   But when Roloson gave up five goals on the first 22 Toronto
shots on Tuesday night, he didn't seem so successful. Although the
Leafs let a three-goal lead shrink to one for a brief part of the
third period, they pulled away for a 6-3 victory at Air Canada
Center to even the four-of-seven-game series. Games 3 and 4 will be
on Thursday and Saturday nights in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   And, back on the other side of the border, the questions will
continue and the pressure will increase. Will Hasek regain his
health in time to return to this series? If not, will his team be
able to reach the Stanley Cup finals without him?
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel much better than two days ago, I feel a big
improvement,'' Hasek said on Tuesday morning. Hasek spent Monday in
Buffalo, seeing doctors and getting magnetic resonance imaging
tests and bone scans. He began taking an anti-inflammatory
medication, he said. Coach Lindy Ruff of the Sabres also said there
is a possibility that Hasek will take an injection of cortisone, a
pain-killing medication. Hasek also is getting massage and
ultrasound treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel much more strength in my leg,'' Hasek said. ``It's day
to day. Today, I feel pretty optimistic. I hope I will be back in
the series. Until you go on the ice, you don't know. Maybe tomorrow
I will skate. If not tomorrow, for sure on the day after. It just
depends on how I feel tomorrow. Maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Sullivan, Sylvain Cote, Sergei Berezin, Yanic Perreault,
Steve Thomas and Gary Valk scored for Toronto, all at even
strength, although Valk's came into the empty net after Buffalo
pulled Roloson for an extra attacker in the final minute. Stu
Barnes scored twice for Buffalo and Jason Woolley once for Buffalo,
all on the power play. Barnes' second goal cut the Toronto lead to
one goal, briefly, midway through the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto dictated the mood of the game with two goals in a span
of 18 seconds during the 11th minute of the game. The first was by
Steve Sullivan, one of the smaller Leafs at 5 feet 9 inches and 155
pounds, at the end of a long and eventful shift. When Roloson left
his net to play the puck, Sullivan confronted him in the right-wing
corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave him a hack and he grabbed my stick,'' Sullivan said.
``I had to go get it.''
</P>
<P>
   When he did, his teammates were still putting pressure on
Roloson and the Sabres, who could not clear the puck. Sullivan
finally knocked it over the goal line at 10 minutes 28 seconds
before he was cross-checked into the net. During the ensuing
wrestling match among players, both Sullivan and Roloson ended up
bare faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their player cross-checked me,'' Sullivan said. ``It's not
like I was in there of my own will. I lost my head gear. I fell on
him, then he lost his headgear.'' Roloson, asked if Sullivan was an
annoyance, replied, ``I don't pay any attention to him.'' But when
Mats Sundin sprang Cote for a breakaway after the next face-off,
Roloson gave up another goal on the next shot to make it 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, asked about Sullivan's role, said: ``He was a feisty
little guy. Maybe he got their goalie off his game a little bit.
Sometimes, you can get in a goaltender's kitchen.'' Sullivan said:
``You've got to get in there and get dirty and show you'll go where
the big man will go.'' Roloson, discussing the Leafs' pressure on
the first goal, said a team has a good chance of scoring ``any time
you get three or four whacks at a puck.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams said the Leafs had played the run-and-gun style that
brought them success in the regular season. ``We don't really want
to play run and gun,'' Sullivan said, not entirely convincingly.
Mike Peca, the checking center who is the captain of the Sabres,
was more assured. ``We're getting caught up in a run-and-gun
style,'' said Peca, who finished with a minus-three in the
plus/minus ratio.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo's third goalie is Martin Biron, a rookie. Ruff, earlier
in the day, indicated that using him was not totally out of the
question.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek, for each of the last two seasons, has won both the Hart
trophy and the Vezina trophy as the most valuable player and best
goalie in the National Hockey League. Once again this season, he is
a candidate for both awards. He is known for his athletic and
unorthodox style in which he stops pucks by making sprawls and back
flips, sometimes kicking out his padded legs. The groin injury,
which idled him during the regular season for 12 games and returned
during the second-round series against Boston, prevents him from
dropping to the ice to stop first shots and then quickly jumping
back up to stop rebounds, he said. Groin injuries are particularly
vexing to goalies, who rely on quick movement of the lower body. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of his injury, Hasek said: ``I cannot do it. If I
cannot do it, the best I can do is stay off the ice and let the
other goalie play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
