<SLUG> BC-H&AMP;R-BLOCK-SUED-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCHISEES SUE H&AMP;R BLOCK OVER TAX-PREPARATION SOFTWARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GENE MEYER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Two dozen H&AMP;R Block franchise owners, who
estimate their businesses prepare 20 percent of the tax returns
Block handles each year, are suing the Kansas City company,
alleging unfair competition.
</P>
<P>
   The group's multimillion-dollar lawsuit in Jackson County
Circuit Court contends that Block's sale of tax-preparation
software in stores and on the Internet violates longstanding
agreements to not compete with franchise owners on their home turf.
</P>
<P>
   The group, which comprises H&AMP;R Block tax-service office owners
from Florida to the Pacific Northwest, also says Block's planned
purchase of McGladrey &AMP; Pullen LLP, the nation's seventh-largest
public accounting firm, violates the agreements. That company
offers tax preparation and related services in places that many of
the franchise owners serve.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks about $10 million in damages, based on the
volume of business during the tax season that ended last month,
said Kirte Kinser, a Dallas lawyer representing the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Block were traveling Tuesday and could not be
reached for comment. But Block thinks the lawsuit is without merit
and will present its case vigorously, said Todd Ransom, a company
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute involves the terms of franchise agreements that
Block and the franchise owners struck in the 1960s and 1970s, when
the company was rapidly expanding its network of tax-preparation
offices across the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The franchise owners allege in their lawsuit that, according to
the agreements, Block either must give up the rights to its
trademarks in places where it competes with franchise holders or
pay the holders 55 percent of the revenue it receives in those
territories.
</P>
<P>
   Also named as defendants in the lawsuit are two Block
subsidiaries, Block Financial Corp. and HRB Royalty Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The 24 franchise owners who filed the lawsuit operate about
1,300 of the 9,000 H&AMP;R Block Tax Service offices that are open in
the United States during peak filing season. Their properties are
in Alabama, Arkansas, North Carolina, Kentucky, New York, Virginia,
Michigan, Florida, Iowa, Oregon, Utah, Washington and Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
