<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS AREN'T ALONE IN STORY OF WEST'S DECAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In the KeyArena locker room after the April 27 game
between the Jazz and Sonics, Utah's Jeff Hornacek was making a face
like a kid eating his first bite of liver.
</P>
<P>
   The source of the wrenched visage was pain from the ordeal of
bending his knee sufficiently to put on his socks.
</P>
<P>
   Hornacek faithfully attempted to answer my questions about the
game, but after awhile I said, ``How can you play on that knee?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not bad,'' he said, flinching.
</P>
<P>
   Typical stoic Jazz answer. Typical decayed Jazz body.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's a month later, the perpetually worn 37-year-old knee
has had no respite or surgery, and Hornacek for a week has been
trying to defend Portland's Isaiah Rider, who is bigger, stronger,
younger, faster and altogether better.
</P>
<P>
   That little disparity explains matters as well as any.
</P>
<P>
   The kings of the West _ Sonics, Rockets, Lakers and soon the
Jazz _ are dead, and dying.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz staved off their demise for a night, winning Tuesday
night in Salt Lake City to close their conference semifinal deficit
to 3-2 against Portland. But the Blazers will end the Utah season
this week, meaning the last five Western Conference champions will
have been eliminated before this season's conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   The false season of '99 has been hard on the old guard. The Jazz
won in '98 and '97. The '96 West champs, the Sonics, well, you know
what happened there. The West kings (and NBA titlists) in '95 and
'94, the Houston Rockets, were first-round victims of the Los
Angeles Lakers, who themselves were swept by the San Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   Which is a way of saying that as inept as the Sonics looked in
failing to make the playoffs by a game, a number of their most
intimate rivals this decade have established that the Sonics didn't
corner the market on self-destruction.
</P>
<P>
   True, the rivals made the playoffs. Try selling that consolation
prize to the fans of the Jazz and Rockets, not to mention the
Lakers, who, while not a recent conference champ, may have been the
biggest Western bust of all precisely because of that.
</P>
<P>
   The egregiously expensive arrival of Shaquille O'Neal in L.A.
during the summer of '96 was supposed to herald a dynasty. Instead,
it has meant next to nothing, except to cut his commute time to the
music and movie studios.
</P>
<P>
   In season-ending series the last three springs, the Lakers have
a 1-12 mark, and none of those series was even a West final.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's final Laker game in the decrepit Forum, echoed with the
chants of ``Ed-dee! Ed-dee!'', a bit of sarcasm over the trade to
Charlotte of popular guard Eddie Jones.
</P>
<P>
   That represented a monumental diss of Jerry West, who has
generally been accorded the label of the NBA's pre-eminent
front-office strategist. Apparently, West has come down with an
acute case of the stupids.
</P>
<P>
   Some would make the same allegation for the Rockets and their
popular coach, Rudy Tomjanovich. Adding Scottie Pippen to the mix
of Hakeem Olajuwon and Charles Barkley worked about as well as
tossing a lynx into a bag of wolverines.
</P>
<P>
   Each power fell for somewhat different reasons. But the
contention is here that almost none of it was a case of the stupids
(although an exception can be made for Sonic president Wally Walker
regarding Jim McIlvaine).
</P>
<P>
   If there is a thread, it is that the lockout-poisoned season
ruined teams that had significant roster changes.
</P>
<P>
   Houston had eight new players, the Sonics six and a new coach.
The Jazz didn't change much except physiologically, and that nearly
eliminated them in the first round against Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   The two good teams who were the most stable through the lockout,
Portland and San Antonio, are about to reap the rewards.
</P>
<P>
   The compressed schedule of 50 games in 90 days was destructive
in ways hard to quantify but painfully apparent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking at our roster, seeing eight new players, and I
was watching our coaching staff, and it hit me they couldn't
teach,'' Carroll Dawson, the Rockets' basketball VP, told the
Houston Chronicle. ``They didn't have a chance to get the new
players grounded in our system.''
</P>
<P>
   All teams played a similarly brutal schedule, but teams with a
lot of holdovers managed better the freakishness.
</P>
<P>
   No team managed it well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Points were down, turnovers were up and well-played games were
an exception throughout the league,'' Dawson said. ``It hasn't been
a year to turn on the TV and see pretty basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   The trend continues in the playoffs, which have been almost
uniformly excruciating. In Game 4 Sunday in Portland, the Blazers
had just 22 field goals, only 10 of which were assisted _ 10
assists for a whole team! _ and the Blazers still won.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another jaw-dropping number: The two Western semis played
that day combined for 158 free throws among the four teams. If this
is sports entertainment, give me chess.
</P>
<P>
   The worst qualitative season in the NBA's modern history is
wiping out the establishment in the West, not to mention the game
itself.
</P>
<P>
   It would be pathetically fitting to see the eventual champ come
from the eighth seed in the East.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 0046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1327 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BBA-REDSOX-YANKEES-BOS     05-26 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
SOX' ROSE WON'T WILT AGAINST YANKEES
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-REDSOX-YANKEES-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By GORDON EDES 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sense and sensibility suggest it is only a matter of
time before the Yankees restore order to this corner of the
universe.
</P>
<P>
   But that small band of renegades known as the Sons of Jimy
Williams keeps knocking the planets out of alignment, making it
mighty tough for Boss Steinbrenner to look down upon all he has
created and pronounce it good.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, winning for the 15th time in 18 games and third
time in four meetings with the Yankees, once again made things
messy where near-perfection once reigned, blunting the Bombers,
5-2, behind nerveless rookie Brian Rose and home runs by Mike
Stanley and Nomar Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   Did somebody say rookie?
</P>
<P>
   ``I caught his first start two years ago, and he was firing
stuff at me with every confidence a 10-year veteran has,'' said
Stanley, the refried Yankee who has worn pinstripes twice but
tossed them in the hamper Tuesday night with a three-run home run
off Hideki Irabu that broke a 1-1 tie in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not easy to do in this place,'' Stanley said of Rose,
``but it just shows you those much overused words, poise and
confidence, he has.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose, who shut out the Yankees on six hits for seven innings
last Wednesday in Fenway Park, limited them to a run on three hits
in six innings in their own playground Tuesday night before handing
the game over to a bullpen that bent but didn't break, Tom Gordon
racking up consecutive save No. 51 in a 1-2-3 ninth.
</P>
<P>
   With two wins in six days against the World Series champions,
Rose is well on his way to shedding that temporary occupant sign
over his locker and establishing permanent residence on Yawkey Way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I belong, no doubt about it,'' the 23-year-old
righthander said. ``I think I proved that two years ago. Now, I've
got to prove to myself that I can pitch like this every time.''
</P>
<P>
   He will get no argument from his manager. ``I just feel like
he's here and he's going to pitch good,'' Williams said. ``I
believe in his makeup and his skill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look at it as where we're playing. I know where we're
playing, but I like what we are, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The wise guys nodded knowingly when Chuck Knoblauch hit Rose's
second pitch over the left-field fence, just beyond Troy O'Leary's
reach, and two batters later Paul O'Neill drove a ball into the
right-center-field gap for a triple.
</P>
<P>
   It was one thing for the kid to shut down the Bombers last week
when he was safe at home, stands packed with family, fiancee, and
friends from South Dartmouth, Mass. It was quite another to expect
him six days later to walk into the hostile environs of the South
Bronx, where the first miscreants were escorted off the premises
shortly after legendary PA announcer Bob Sheppard delivered the
starting lineups.
</P>
<P>
   But the Brian Rose on display this spring has been the one whom
Sox fans glimpsed only on the coming-attractions trailers more than
a year ago, when he was advertised as the best homegrown pitching
prospect of the Duquette generation.
</P>
<P>
   This was the Rose who could just as easily be in Montreal today
as the price for Pedro Martinez, if Expos general manager Jim
Beattie hadn't selected Carl Pavano instead.
</P>
<P>
   This was the Rose not intimidated by the sight of O'Neill, 90
feet away from becoming another Yankees run. Rose turned his
attention plateward, calmly striking out Bernie Williams and
inducing Tino Martinez to tap out to second baseman Jose Offerman
to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't comfortable with my footing,'' Rose said. ``Once I
got into the stretch, I was able to get my foot in the hole. Having
a guy on base really helped me, because I was more comfortable in
the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I came to Yankee Stadium, I wasn't playing and
I was in awe of the place and how the crowd gets in the game. But
that chance to be here last year helped me to focus on me and Jason
(Varitek, the Sox catcher). Instead of `Wow, this is Yankee
Stadium,' I just focused on getting guys out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees wouldn't have another hit until O'Neill lined a
one-out single to center in the sixth. When Rose fell behind
Williams, 3 and 0, pitching coach Joe Kerrigan was moved to pay a
visit, but Rose kept his manager in the dugout by inducing Williams
to lift a short fly to left, then dropping a killer curve for a
called third strike against Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   That would be his 85th and last pitch of the night, as he donned
his warmup jacket, strode the length of the dugout accepting
congratulations, and disappeared up the runway to the visitors'
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a clean game,'' Jimy Williams said, ``and Brian set
the tone of the game by the way he pitched.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Rheal Cormier took the mound for the seventh, he had
inherited a 5-1 lead, Garciaparra driving a Dan Naulty pitch into
the left-field seats in the top of the inning for his first Yankee
Stadium home run and the fifth Sox run.
</P>
<P>
   The first four came off Irabu, who couldn't suppress a smile
when the Yankee Stadium crowd of 37,715 saluted him with a mock
cheer after he covered first base on Brian Daubach's smash to Tino
Martinez. It was Irabu's failure to cover on a similar play in
spring training that brought down the Wrath of George on his head,
and the now infamous ``fat . . . toad'' quote.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Irabu wasn't accustomed to the exertion required to make
the play on Daubach, because he found himself in a swamp of trouble
soon thereafter. Garciaparra beat out a hit to the shortstop hole
and stole second, O'Leary walked on four pitches, and Stanley went
deep for his fourth home run _ only the fifth time this season the
Sox have hit a three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees scored in the bottom of the inning with two hits off
Cormier and a sacrifice fly off Derek Lowe, but that's as far as it
went, Stanley squeezing Chad Curtis's foul fly to end it.
</P>
<P>
   The lead over the Yankees in the American League East is now 2
1/2 games, but Sox manager Williams would almost have you believe
that if you didn't tell him, he wouldn't even know. Others may want
to talk about the big picture. Williams sees the season in
wallet-sized photos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever little bit I do,'' he said Tuesday night, ``and I
don't know what I'm doing, is prepare mentally for today's game and
see what happens. And tomorrow, I'll try to do the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   And some nights a rose blooms in the desert, other nights in the
Bronx. That's just the way it is in Jimy Williams's world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 0048EDT &QL; 
