<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1328 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURDER-PLOT-LADN     05-26 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURDER-PLOT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENMARK NATIVE ACCUSED IN LOS ANGELES MURDER-FOR-HIRE PLOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY TROY ANDERSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The owner of two Danish American Farms markets
was held on $3 million bail Tuesday after he was accused of a
murder-for-hire plot, but his son said his father was framed.
</P>
<P>
   Former Bell Canyon resident Flemming Willi Larsen, 56, is
accused of soliciting an undercover investigator to kill a former
business associate and cripple his former North Hills, Calif.,
store manager, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had to do with business deals,'' said Lt. Al Michelena of
the Los Angeles Police Department's robbery-homicide unit. ``I
think he felt these people might have cheated him. He had financial
problems and he may have believed these intended victims had
responsibility for his problems.''
</P>
<P>
   But Larsen's son, Westlake Village, Calif., resident Flemming
Larsen Jr., 30, said his father was framed by a man who owes him
$50,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad is clean as a whistle,'' Larsen Jr. said. ``He doesn't
have a rap sheet. He's been totally framed and entrapped. There is
no question about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Larsen appeared in the Van Nuys Courthouse in the suburban San
Fernando Valley on Tuesday for a bail hearing in the case. The
judge set bail at $3 million, fearing that Larsen might attempt to
flee to his native Denmark, where he maintains a residence with his
wife, Bente Ravn Larsen, 41.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested Larsen on May 13 on suspicion of soliciting the
murder of former business associate Gerald Winkler and the
crippling of former North Hills store manager Mike Simon after a
meeting with an undercover officer at a North Hollywood restaurant,
said Deputy District Attorney Larry Diamond.
</P>
<P>
   Larsen pleaded not guilty at his arraignment May 17 to two
counts of solicitation of murder and one count of solicitation of
assault with a deadly weapon. His preliminary hearing is set for
June 15 in Van Nuys.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to clear his name,'' said Pasadena attorney James
Sussman, Larsen's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   The case came to light Monday when police released information
about Larsen's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Larsen and his wife were the owners of the popular Danish
American Farms markets in North Hills and Simi Valley. The North
Hills market opened in 1977 and closed abruptly in January 1998
when employees arrived at work to find a sign saying the store had
gone out of business.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the closure, customers and suppliers were stuck
with $1.5 million in worthless scrip and unpaid bills. The market's
owner, Bente's Fine Foods Inc., filed for Chapter 7 bankruptcy
shortly after the closure. Byron Moldo, the bankruptcy trustee, is
now holding $250,000 in assets liquidated from the store, said
Encino bankruptcy attorney Alan Nahmias.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1997, Larsen opened a second store in Simi Valley. It
closed after an electrical fire in December 1998, causing a loss of
$1.5 million in groceries.
</P>
<P>
   Michelena said the FBI contacted investigators May 11 based on
reports that Larsen was attempting to solicit a murder.
</P>
<P>
   An undercover investigator met with Larsen on May 13 at a North
Hollywood area restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   In the meeting, the detective told Larsen, ``I kill people for a
living. Is there anybody you want to get rid of?'' Larsen Jr. said,
repeating what he says he heard in the taped recording of the
meeting given to him by his father's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking facetiously, his father said, ``Yeah, my landlord,''
referring to Winkler, a former business associate who owns the
building Larsen leased for his North Hills market, Larsen Jr. said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about Mike Simon, Larsen responded: ``That's too good
for him. He belongs in a wheelchair,'' according to Larsen Jr.'s
account of the taped recording.
</P>
<P>
   Larsen and Winkler have sued and countersued each other, Diamond
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their relationship goes back quite some time,'' Diamond said.
``They may have been involved in some real estate transactions
together. He thought Simon had cheated him out of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Diamond received numerous telephone calls from Danish newspaper
reporters Tuesday, saying they were interested in Larsen's case.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Larsen's finance manager in Denmark, who owed
him $10 million to $12 million, died, Larsen Jr. said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was ruled a suicide,'' Larsen Jr. said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
