<HEADER>
A1330 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     05-26 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS, LAKERS HAVE SAME PROBLEMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Is it the smog again or has the Los Angeles sports
scene turned into a big blur?
</P>
<P>
   Lakers. Dodgers. The most major of our major-league franchises.
Can you tell one from the other anymore? And can you tell one year
from the next?
</P>
<P>
   Are you sure those were the 1999 Lakers who faded into history
by losing to the San Antonio Spurs the other day, or could they
have been the '98 Lakers or the '97 Lakers?
</P>
<P>
   How do you distinguish these underachieving Dodgers from the
underachieving Dodgers of last season and the underachieving
Dodgers of the season before that?
</P>
<P>
   Let's test.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some statements uttered by Lakers and Dodgers _ and
Lakers and Dodgers observers _ in the past few years. Try to match
each with the speaker and the team under discussion.
</P>
<P>
   The quotes:
</P>
<P>
   1. ``We don't trust one another yet. That's the only thing we're
missing.''
</P>
<P>
   2. ``We have to learn how to win here.''
</P>
<P>
   3. ``They (are) splintered by clashing personalities that
couldn't pull together for each other when the going got tough.''
</P>
<P>
   4. ``(The players) have to learn to trust each other.''
</P>
<P>
   5. ``I don't think we're that far away, with (the talent) we
have here.''
</P>
<P>
   The speakers:
</P>
<P>
   a. Magic Johnson, on the '96 Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   b. The Daily News, on the '97 Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   c. Jerry West, on the '97 Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   d. Kevin Malone, on the '99 Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   e. Kurt Rambis, on the '99 Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   The matches:
</P>
<P>
   1, a; 2, d; 3, b; 4, e; 5, c.
</P>
<P>
   Players change. Coaches change. Managers change. GMs change.
Owners change. The teams' personalities never seem to change.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are always high on talent but low on desire.
!ital!Always.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are always high on talent but low on teamwork.
!ital!Always.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers and the Dodgers are good enough to win if only they
acquire the intangibles. They (begin ital)never do(end ital).
</P>
<P>
   Hello, desperation, our old friend.
</P>
<P>
   These indeed are desperate times for L.A. sports fans, now that
the Lakers are out of the playoffs, the Dodgers have sunk to third
place, and neither team has won a championship since both did it in
1988.
</P>
<P>
   Our best hope for winning a professional title anytime soon
probably rests with that yet-unborn NFL franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The most frustrating of all the frustrating aspects of the
Lakers' and Dodgers' parallel futility is not that they keep
falling short but that they keep falling short for roughly the same
reasons, year to year and team to team.
</P>
<P>
   When Derek Harper called a players' meeting during the regular
season, he implored his Lakers teammates to ``look in the mirror.''
Did they see themselves or the Dodgers?
</P>
<P>
   Did Shaquille O'Neal see Kevin Brown _ his opposite number, the
number being $100 million, each a superstar in his own right but so
far a flop at the winner's role of making teammates better?
</P>
<P>
   Did Kobe Bryant see Raul Mondesi _ each an ultimate bundle of
talent, each limited by his own self-confidence?
</P>
<P>
   I remember reading that by age 33, one is pretty much stuck with
his or her personality, bad habits and all. A theory dreamed up by
a 32-year-old chain smoker, no doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it applies to sports franchises, too. They develop
personalities that can't be shed even as the teams are made over on
the surface.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers turned 33 in 1991; the following season
they won an L.A.-low 63 games, and they've been trying to get over
that ever since. The Los Angeles Lakers turned 33 in 1993; by the
following year they'd had two losing seasons in a row, and they've
been trying to regain their self-esteem ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's an L.A. thing, the old accusation that our teams take
on the personality of their fans, slow to get interested and quick
to head for the exits.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it makes as much sense as any of this.
</P>
<P>
   I thought this was a figment of my imagination until I came
across a quote from Malone, the Dodgers' general manager, seeming
to endorse the idea that a weird brand of institutional memory is
at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take time to change some of the lingering
attitudes of yesteryear,'' Malone said. ``There's a reason the
Dodgers haven't won for 10 years, and you can't change that in only
30 games.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how those attitudes of yesteryear endure is a mystery
perhaps best solved by a psychiatrist. You could imagine the
coaches and veterans of '96 handing down bad thoughts to the
youngsters of '97, who become the coaches and veterans of '98 and
pass the disorders on to the veterans and youngsters of '99....
</P>
<P>
   Except for the fact the dysfunction of the past few years has
persisted even as the Dodgers and Lakers went through some of the
most complete personnel turnovers in their histories.
</P>
<P>
   What's the answer?
</P>
<P>
   I don't know, but I did glance up at the Forum Club tunnel
during the Lakers' Game 3 loss to San Antonio and notice Jerry West
chatting with none other than Kevin Malone. Maybe they were
discussing a group rate on an exorcist. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 0056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1331 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BBA-REDSOX-YANKEES-BOS     05-26 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
HUNGRY SOX SHOW BITE IN BIG APPLE
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-REDSOX-YANKEES-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Dan Shaughnessy 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After 80 years of nonstop indignity and abject
humiliation, maybe this is the year the Red Sox take some revenge
on the hated Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   We know that Pedro Martinez can beat anybody. Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night
confirmed that Brian Rose can beat Hideki Irabu. What's next _ Pat
Rapp snapping Roger Clemens's 18-game winning streak Thursday
night?
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in a while, the New York stories are all good
stories for this Boston baseball edition. The Sox beat the Bombers
again Tuesday night, riding Rose to a 5-2 victory and moving to 2
1/2 games ahead of Club Steinbrenner. The Sox have won 15 of their
last 18, including three of four from the Yanks over the last nine
days.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Stanley, an ex-Yankee who drilled a game-breaking,
three-run homer, said, ``You can fall into that preseason talk that
we're not going to be any good, but we're not doing that. We're
getting great pitching and there's a confidence on this team. We're
seeing ourselves do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The indomitable Pedro added, ``I think we're real. We're playing
the baseball we're capable of playing. We're doing the little
things. It's too early to tell, but we do believe.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox are doing the little things. Tuesday night Jose Offerman
went from first to third on a routine groundout by John Valentin.
It was a Jackie Robinson play, the kind we haven't seen through the
years. Offerman wound up scoring when nine-year minor leaguer Brian
Daubach followed with a bloop single.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman, Daubach, Rose . . . This is turning into one of those
``contributions from everybody'' seasons that are the mark of a
winner. Callups Juan Pena, John Wasdin, and Rose are an aggregate
7-0. Rose, a Massachusetts native, has three big-league victories,
including two in a week against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always grow up as a kid watching games in Yankee
Stadium,'' said the low-key righty. ``But I'm just trying to go out
there and keep this team in the ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Yankees are reeling and Joe Torre told them to
forget about batting practice before Wednesday's rare afternoon
game. Because the Big Apple is agog over the Knicks (Spike Lee is
expected to have his own locker at Madison Square Garden before the
end of the New York-Indiana series), the Yankees have been able to
remain somewhat anonymous during their mid-May mini-slump. But you
can be sure Mr. Steinbrenner is impatient. He did not expect his
125-win championship edition to be looking up at the Boston Red Sox
on May 26.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's New York Daily News (which now features star
columnist Mike Barnicle), Filip Bondy wrote a sentence I thought
I'd never read: ``The Yanks stand a game and a half behind Boston,
still comfortably slotted ahead of Kansas City in the formative
wild-card standings.''
</P>
<P>
   Whoa. Get back, Loretta. The Yankees? Comfortably slotted ahead
of Kansas City in the wild-card standings? That's sarcasm, right? I
know sarcasm when I see it.
</P>
<P>
   Boston manager Jimy Williams is doing his best to downplay this
torrid stretch of precision baseball. Williams spent the early part
of Tuesday at the 32d annual meeting of the Benevolent Loyal Order
Of The Honorable Ancient Red Sox Die Hard Sufferers Of New York
(BLOHARDS). This group of high-rolling New Yorkers convenes
whenever the Red Sox come to the Apple, and Tuesday's midtown
luncheon was highlighted by a lively exchange between Williams and
the curious BLOHARDS members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only have 120 to go, what the hell are we talking about?''
Williams said when the members boasted about Boston's surprising
first-place standing in the American League East.
</P>
<P>
   The manager was at his obtuse, George Bush best, answering
questions with questions and spilling out rounds of non-sentences
and nonsequiturs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lefthanded hitters?'' answered Jimy when asked about the Sox'
lineup. ``Don't know about that. We've got ballplayers. Kids who
play hard. Don't know about lefthanded hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bret Saberhagen? On rehab. Pitching at Akron. Don't know why
he picked Akron unless he needs tires for his car.''
</P>
<P>
   On it went. Right though the end of Tuesday night's game, when a
New York journalist asked Williams about ``making hay'' while the
Yankees are struggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hay? I grew up on a farm. I really did. Baled hay. Three-wire
barbs. You get real hungry doing that. Go get lunch. But as far as
what you're talking about, I have no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Same here, Jimy. We're all scratching our heads. But the Red Sox
are making hay while the proverbial sun shines. The Sox now are
assured of leaving New York in first place. Who knows? Maybe
they'll sweep the Yankees with the vaunted trio of Rose, Mark
Portugal, and Rapp. It's the spring of 1999, when elephants fly,
Yankees sink, and everything's coming up Rose's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
