<HEADLINE>
JAZZ PLAYERS HIT ALL THE RIGHT NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ If the Portland Trail Blazers are going to be
the ones who overthrow the defending Western Conference champions,
they will take a few bumps and lumps into the next round.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Malone and the Utah Jazz will make sure of that.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting to avoid missing the conference finals for the first
time in three seasons, the Jazz executed their offense, defense and
other season-saving tactics while clobbering Portland, 88-71,
Tuesday night at the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   Utah's Game 5 victory in the Western Conference semifinals
forced Game 6 Thursday at Portland's Rose Garden. The Blazers lead
3-2 in the best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   But the Jazz turned up the heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came strong,'' Portland's Rasheed Wallace said. ``We just
have to be a little more physical. We got our butts kicked.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone delivered the first boot.
</P>
<P>
   The Utah forward and MVP favorite scored 11 of his game-high
23-points in an emotionally charged and hard-hitting first quarter.
He set the tone that Utah would battle to stay alive _ especially
when his elbow opened a gash above the right eye of Portland's
Brian Grant late in the opening period.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers knew then they were in for a rough night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a little bit more energy than we've had,'' Utah coach
Jerry Sloan said. ``We've got more confidence in what we're trying
to do. But I've always said the first person to win four games is
the winner. This doesn't mean anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Only six of 131 NBA teams that were down 3-1 have ever come back
to win a seven-game series. Still, Utah won for the sixth time in
its past seven elimination games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some close calls in the last couple of years where
we needed to keep winning,'' Malone said. ``It's no different now.
We're looking forward to (Game 6). If (the Blazers) say they're not
feeling a little pressure, they're lying because they're supposed
to close us out because we're old, we can't do this, we're
predictable.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference Tuesday was that old could have been called
experience. Utah was smooth and did everything it wanted. The Jazz
ran their pick-and-roll almost flawlessly, set high picks that
freed up point guard John Stockton, created open shots, came up
with loose balls, and held Portland to 34 percent shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used all of their tactics,'' Portland reserve guard Greg
Anthony said. ``The biggest adjustment we have to make is play
harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland always seems to fight a double-digit deficit from the
time Utah took a 16-6 lead. After getting to within 49-44 at the
start of the third, Portland never got any closer than 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers, who had been the picture of poise in the series,
lost their cool.
</P>
<P>
   Tempers flared the most when Utah led 72-58 with 8:45 left in
the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Referee Ron Garretson whistled Grant for a technical foul after
he pretended to throw the ball into Malone's back after grabbing a
rebound. That set off Portland coach Mike Dunleavy.
</P>
<P>
   Dunleavy leaped from the bench and charged at Garretson to argue
the call. On the preceding possession, Portland was called for an
elbow when Grant threw head-high elbows around after snaring a
rebound. Dunleavy was so animated that Anthony and assistant coach
Tim Grgurich rushed in to pull their coach away.
</P>
<P>
   Intervention did not prevent Dunleavy from picking up a
technical.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Grant and Malone stood at center court, nose-to-nose,
and exchanged words as if a first-round bell was about to sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he didn't like me and I said I didn't like him,''
Malone said of his encounter with Grant. ``We established that, and
now we know where each other is coming from. In the playoffs you
don't have to like me. I don't play this game for you to like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant was still seething after an earlier encounter with Malone.
Grant left the game with a nasty cut above his right eye after
catching a Malone elbow to his face. Grant rolled on the court like
a suffocating fish as blood spewed from his forehead while Utah's
Bryon Russell scored a dunk on the other end.
</P>
<P>
   The league might review the incident because Malone grabbed a
rebound with his left hand and threw his right elbow toward Grant.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were on Brian's back all night long,'' Dunleavy said,
speaking for his power forward, who did not talk to the media after
the game. ``From the first quarter on, he was being pushed around.
When he threw the elbows, it was out of frustration. I don't think
he even knew it was a violation. It was the right call, but I
thought he got hit in the head again before he did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Once order was restored after the fourth-quarter unrest, Utah's
reserve guard Howard Eisley missed both technical free throws
assessed on Dunleavy and Grant. Portland then used a 6-0 run that
eventually cut Utah's lead to 74-64.
</P>
<P>
   But Shandon Anderson immediately buried a 3-pointer, and the
Jazz outscored the Blazers 14-7 in the final six minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
