<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN WINS PIVOTAL STATE SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In a closely watched special election that was
the catalyst for repealing New York City's tax on commuters,
Republicans on Tuesday held on to a pivotal State Senate seat from
Rockland and Orange Counties.
</P>
<P>
   The victory by Thomas P. Morahan preserves the Republicans'
36-to-25 majority in the Senate. Truly competitive legislative
races are rare in New York, and this one, with implications for the
long-term control of the Senate, was one of the hardest-fought and
most expensive in memory, drawing the involvement of politicians
from across the state.
</P>
<P>
   With all precincts reporting, Morahan, minority leader of the
Rockland County Legislature, had 52 percent of the vote, to 47
percent for Kenneth P. Zebrowski, the Democratic majority leader of
the County Legislature. James Henderson, the Green Party candidate,
had 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Morahan's better-financed campaign, which featured heavy
advertising on cable television, rested heavily on the message that
as part of the Senate majority, he would be able to deliver state
spending to the district.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, Zebrowski attacked Morahan's votes against
abortion rights and gun control, unpopular positions in the
district, and the Democrats had the advantage in voter
registration. But they still fell short. Turnout, always a factor
in close races, was low _ a little more than 20 percent _ which
both sides agreed aided the Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering the voter registration, I'm very happy with this
margin of victory, because I knew it was going to be tough,''
Morahan said.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Morahan overwhelmingly carried the district's
Hasidic Jewish communities, which have been allied with Gov. George
Pataki, a Republican, and which the governor aggressively courted
in this campaign. Sen. Martin Connor, the Democratic minority
leader, said it was their votes that gave Morahan the victory.
</P>
<P>
   The contest was waged largely by proxy, with Pataki and the
State Senate majority leader, Joseph Bruno, campaigning and raising
money for Morahan. U.S. Sen. Charles Schumer and State Comptroller
H. Carl McCall led a long list of Democrats who campaigned for
Zebrowski.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone lines to the Rockland County Democratic Committee's
offices were severed on Tuesday night, hindering the party's
get-out-the-vote efforts, and Democrats suggested it was Republican
sabotage. ``My suspicion is it would be extraordinary coincidence
if it was not someone connected with our opponent's campaign,''
said Sen. Eric T. Schneiderman of Manhattan, chairman of the Senate
Democratic Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Republican officials denied any connection with the incident,
and some implied that the Democrats, themselves, had done it to
provide a ready excuse in case Zebrowski lost.
</P>
<P>
   For an election with just one seat at stake, this one drew
inordinate attention, thanks partly to the commuter tax, a levy on
the incomes of suburbanites, including those in Rockland and
Orange, who work in New York City. Early this month, both Morahan
and Zebrowski pledged to eliminate the tax, which generates $360
million a year for the city. The promise was widely seen as hollow;
legislators had tried before and failed. But in a flurry of
one-upmanship, the Senate and Assembly passed the measure, over
howls of protest from Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, and Pataki said he
would sign it.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in both parties estimate that well over $1 million was
spent on the Senate contest in the 38th District, an extraordinary
sum, particularly with the abbreviated campaign schedule of a
special election.
</P>
<P>
   At stake was one of the few true swing districts in the state,
one that encompasses all of Rockland County and southern Orange
County. The Republicans' margin in the Senate is not large, and it
has relied on keeping in their column several districts where
Democratic registered voters outnumber Republicans. A loss of two
or three seats would weaken Republicans' iron control over
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The seat had been held by Joseph R. Holland, who left earlier
this year to become Rockland County's social services commissioner.
He had wanted to leave at the end of his last term, but party
leaders, afraid that the high turnout of a general election would
benefit Democrats, prevailed upon him to run for re-election last
November, then resign this year, setting up the special election.
</P>
</TEXT>
