<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLIVARES, ANGELS STAY ON HOT STREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Omar Olivares admitted during spring training he was a
little perturbed about having to win a job in the starting
rotation. After all, he thought he pitched well enough last season
to warrant a spot.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of whining about it, he earned the spot in the
rotation and has carried his spring success into the regular
season. Tuesday night before 20,398 at Edison Field, Olivares _
with a big lift from Garret Anderson (two homers) _ pitched the
Angels to a 4-1 victory over the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe next year I don't have to do it again,'' Olivares said
about earning his place in the rotation. ``I've been pitching
pretty good the last couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the Angels' third win in a row and their fifth in seven
games. They moved to within one game of .500 (22-23) and have a
chance tonight to reach .500 for the first time since April 17,
when they were 6-6.
</P>
<P>
   Game time was 2:01, the fastest game the Angels have played in
nearly six years. They played the Indians in 2:01 on July 17, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares (5-3) made sure the game went quickly, throwing strikes
and getting the Orioles hitters to swing early in the count.
Olivares, who gave up one run and six hits in eight innings, leads
the team in victories and has the best ERA (3.02) among the club's
starters.
</P>
<P>
   He got a boost from Anderson, whose two home runs marked the
first multiple-homer game of his career. Darin Erstad also homered
for the Angels. All three homers came off Orioles starter Scott
Erickson (1-6. Anderson surpassed Mo Vaughn for the team lead in
homers with 10 and is on a pace for 36. His career best is 16, set
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't ask me to hit home runs, they ask me to drive in
runs,'' said Anderson, who is hitting .297 and has 28 RBI (second
on the team behind Vaughn's 31). ``As you get older, you find out
what pitches you can do things with. That's what I'm finding out.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, however, said he doesn't feel like he's swinging the
way he can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still not where I want to be right now,'' he said. ``Up to
now, I feel I've been inconsistent at times. As the summer goes on
you'll see more consistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got a couple of balls he could handle,'' Angels manager
Terry Collins said. ``I think he realizes with Tim (Salmon) and
Jimmy (Edmonds) out, we need him to drive the ball a little bit and
he's done that. We're not asking him to be a home run hitter, just
be the good hitter he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Olivares began spring training in competition for the No.5 spot
in the rotation with Jarrod Washburn and Jason Dickson. But Dickson
injured his shoulder and Olivares clearly outpitched Washburn.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares, however, has not pitched like a No.5 starter. He leads
all the starters in victories, has the only complete game and leads
everyone on the staff except Chuck Finley in innings pitched.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he's exceeded expectations, but I know he came
into spring training determined, thinking, `That spot is mine to
keep,''' Collins said. ``He worked hard, he pitched great and
didn't look back.''
</P>
<P>
   Olivares, though, struggled early on Tuesday as he got the ball
up and the Orioles hit him hard. Brady Anderson led off the game
with a single, Mike Bordick followed with a double off right
fielder Todd Greene's glove, and B.J. Surhoff ripped a fly ball to
right-center field that was caught by Anderson and went for a
sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   But Olivares cruised from there. He yielded only one hit over
the next four innings, then was aided by a double-play ball in the
sixth. He gave up a two-out double by Surhoff in the eighth but
stranded him there. Most important for Olivares, he walked only
two.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to nibble, nibble, nibble,'' Collins said. ``This year
he has not done that. His command is better. In games, he's around
the plate, he cruises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
