<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALMON INJURY MIGHT SPUR TRADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Right fielder Tim Salmon will have the cast on his
left wrist removed in one week, at which point he'll have the wrist
reexamined.
</P>
<P>
   That's when things will get interesting.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are hoping the sprain -- sustained May 3 when trying
to make a sliding catch -- will be healed enough for him to begin
rehabilitation. The minimum amount of rehab time is two weeks,
which would bring him back the second week in June.
</P>
<P>
   The worst-case scenario, though, would be that the wrist
ligaments have not healed sufficiently and he'd need season-ending
surgery. If Salmon can't come back anytime soon, the Angels will
place a higher prioritiy on making a trade.
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly, the Angels nearly pulled off a trade that would have
landed outfielder Butch Huskey from the Mariners. In the deal, the
Angels would have sent left-handed reliever Mike Holtz (currently
pitching at triple-A Edmonton) to the Yankees. But the Mariners
nixed what would have been a three-way deal because they demanded
pitcher Ramiro Mendoza from the Yankees and the Yankees refused.
</P>
<P>
   Another player who is rumored to be available is Dodgers first
baseman Eric Karros, who is not getting along well with Dodgers
manager Davey Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Angels general manager Bill Bavasi refuses to speculate on
potential trades but says the club is always looking to improve.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn's sprained left ankle continues to limit him to the DH
spot, but on June 4 the Angels begin a stretch of six consecutive
games in National League ballparks (three against the Dodgers and
three vs. the Giants).
</P>
<P>
   The plan is to rest the ankle as much as possible over the next
nine days and allow Vaughn to play first base against the Dodgers
and Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's starting to take ground balls today, and we'll see how it
reacts to that,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said. ``My money's
on him. He'll be out there. Let's wait nine days and see where
we're at.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins hinted he is leaning toward skipping Steve Sparks' next
start in the rotation, which would be Friday against Kansas City.
Because of Monday's off day, Collins can move everybody up in the
rotation and still give them their normal four days between starts.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Finley would start Friday in Sparks' place. Sparks is 1-4
with a 6.04 ERA in nine starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels and Orioles play the second game of their three-game
series tonight starting at 7:35. Tim Belcher (3-3, 8.23 ERA) will
start for Anaheim against Baltimore's Sidney Ponson (4-3, 4.53).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
