A1348 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      05-26 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS BLAST TWINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ John Halama found out how it feels to be a
Mariners starting pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   As the rookie left-hander labored through the first inning
Tuesday night, walking four Minnesota Twins, shortstop Alex
Rodriguez came to the mound. He had a few words for Halama: ``We're
going to get 10 runs. Don't worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   That prediction reassured the pitcher, even if it undersold the
Mariners' offense. Seattle pounded the Twins, 15-5, getting four
home runs and, eventually, solid pitching from Halama.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want him to lose perspective of the situation,''
Rodriguez said. ``They had two runs on the board, but I was very
confident that the way we were swinging the bats, we were going to
score some runs. I wanted him to be a part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Halama gave up two runs in the first and another pair in the
third, then sat back and watched the first eight Mariners score in
the top of the fourth. After the rally, Halama was pulled aside
again, this time by manager Lou Piniella.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a four-run lead,'' Piniella told him, ``(but)
you're already at about 70 pitches. If you want to be around to
give yourself a chance to win, get aggressive, throw strikes and
challenge the hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's words were already coming true. Halama listened to
Piniella, too, and turned things around. He blanked the Twins in
the fourth and fifth and improved his record to 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that kind of fired me up,'' Halama said of Piniella's
talk. ``I went out there and started getting strike one instead of
ball one, like I was doing the first few innings. You get strike
one and strike two and then, boom, they have to hit my pitch
instead of me giving in to the hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's rookie starter, Gary Rath, did not fare as well. He
held the Mariners hitless his first time through the order, but
Butch Huskey singled to start the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   A balk and wild pitch brought Huskey to third, and Matt Mieske
singled him home. Russ Davis followed with his 10th homer, bringing
the M's within 4-3, and Rath was done a walk and a single later.
</P>
<P>
   This, then, is what greeted Twins rookie Rob Radlosky as he made
his major-league debut: two on, none out, a one-run lead, Rodriguez
on deck and Ken Griffey Jr. in the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Hunter singled and the game was tied. Rodriguez doubled
and the Mariners led. Griffey homered _ and the rout was on. Two
innings later, Butch Huskey would homer off Radlosky to increase
the M's lead to 10-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to go back and think about it, and I don't really
remember anything,'' Radlosky said of his first game. ``I remember
the pitch to Griffey, and I remember the pitch to Huskey. Other
than that, it's a blank.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's homer was his major league-leading 18th, and clanked
off the first seat in the first row inside the left-field foul
pole. It extended his career-best hitting streak to 14 games, and
ended an eight-up, eight-in scoring spree the Mariners also enjoyed
on April 11 against Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners finished their scoring in the ninth, when Mieske
did what he so often does off left-handed pitching. The right
fielder bashed a three-run homer off Benj Sampson, giving the M's
their 15-5 lead and pushing Mieske's average to .529 off
left-handers.
</P>
<P>
   It was just his third start this month, but he's made the most
of his limited time. Mieske is batting .406 this season, first on
the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just try to keep myself ready to contribute,'' Mieske said.
``Last year with the Cubs, we went to the postseason and it was an
awesome feeling. I think we can do that again here. I'm a veteran,
I've been around awhile, and being on a winning team is much more
satisfying than doing well personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if I make a lot of money. If you play a lot, you
know that's your reward _ you get paid for at-bats and numbers. To
me, it's not that important. If I get a chance, great. If not, I'm
content with what I'm doing. I think that's what helps make me
successful: I don't get bitter or upset.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
