 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The price of victory keeps going up for the Astros.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Astros won a pitchers' duel with the Colorado Rockies 2-1
Tuesday night when Carl Everett's single scored Bill Spiers in the
12th inning.
</P>
<P>
   But the Astros' infield, with Ricky Gutierrez and Ken Caminiti
already on the disabled list, took another hit when Jack Howell
pulled his right groin fielding a ground ball. After the game,
Howell became the sixth Astro this season to be placed on the DL.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dropping like flies around here,'' closer Billy Wagner
said. ``We have to hold it together until some of the other guys
get healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night was a battle of which team would be left standing
in the end as the matchup between two of the National League's most
potent offenses produced only three runs. After former Astros
righthander Darryl Kile shut out his ex-teammates on four hits over
seven innings, the Astros rallied with two runs _ both coming
courtesy of Everett.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado scored in the first inning, then lefthander Mike
Hampton teamed up with Scott Elarton and Wagner to hold the Rockies
scoreless the final 11 innings. Wagner struck out five batters in
two innings, and Elarton (3-1) retired the side in order in the
12th inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always scary playing the Rockies, especially in the late
innings,'' Wagner said. ``You can get by a few innings, but when it
gets down to the seventh, eighth and ninth innings these guys turn
it up a notch.''
</P>
<P>
   So do the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros tied the game at 1 with two outs in the eighth inning
when Jeff Bagwell walked and Everett delivered a double into the
left-field corner. Four innings later, facing Colorado reliever
Mike DeJean (0-2), Everett sent a hard grounder off the glove of
third baseman Vinny Castilla with the bases loaded for the Astros'
second extra-inning victory of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros finally broke through in the 12th when Craig Biggio
walked to lead off the inning, stole second and advanced to third
on a fielder's-choice bunt by Spiers.
</P>
<P>
   DeJean intentionally walked Bagwell to load the bases. Derek
Bell hit a roller in front of the mound, which DeJean scooped to
the plate for the force. Everett ended the game with a shot past
third base, scoring Spiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lucky, and we accept all luck and charity because we
sometimes give it out,'' manager Larry Dierker said. ``Sometimes we
don't always have the best luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado let the Astros off the hook, too, replacing Kile after
the seventh inning. Kile, who spent the first seven years of his
major-league career with the Astros, matched Hampton in a classic
pitching duel that produced only one run and eight hits through
seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Kile scattered four hits in seven shutout innings, striking out
five and walking four.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton was equally impressive, holding the Rockies to one run
and five hits in nine innings. He struck out six and walked three.
After walking the first two batters and allowing Castilla's
run-scoring single, Hampton was virtually untouchable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only incentive I have is to go out and win games I
start,'' said Hampton, who is 4-0 with a 0.95 ERA over his last six
starts. ``The team batted in the eighth and played some great
defense and picked me up.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, however, Hampton was more concerned with Howell,
who went on the DL around the same time last season with a
dislocated left wrist. Howell pulled his right groin in the third
inning while trying to field a ground ball by Chris Sexton. The
ball deflected off Hampton's glove, and Howell scooped it up but
fell to the ground in pain as his throw sailed wide left at first
base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I already apologized to Jack,'' Hampton said. ``That ball was
in my glove; he shouldn't have even had to think about getting a
hand on the ball. It's unfortunate because it did happen. I should
have caught that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
