<HEADER>
A1366 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-26 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John P.Lopez
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
JUST when the writing on Jose Lima's cap is looking like something
you might find on the back of a fortune cookie's proverb, the
cookie crumbles some more.
</P>
<P>
   In case you've lost track, or feel like playing Fool's Lotto,
those numeric tributes to the Astros wounded are: 11, 12, 16, 18,
19, 21 and 25.
</P>
<P>
   Just when the Astros think their injury list can't get any
longer, it does. The room left on Lima's cap gets tighter. The
gloom in the clubhouse feels heavier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were vulnerable before,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker
said. ``We've been at the end of it for a while. Now, we're past
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But what's this? The Astros keep winning.
</P>
<P>
   And that might be the lasting tribute for this 1999 Astros
season, which keeps getting better and better even as it looks
worse.
</P>
<P>
   It's not always what is on Lima's cap but what's under it _ a
superb pitcher, learning more about the game every day and
tinkering with dominance.
</P>
<P>
   It's not always about what Shane Reynolds is not all about _
being the ace of the staff _ but what he is all about. Consistency.
A wicked forkball. Wins.
</P>
<P>
   And like 21,720 Astrodome fans witnessed on a long, wild Tuesday
night, it's not always what starter Mike Hampton can't do _ win,
which he had done five times in a row before getting no-decisions
Thursday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But it's what he can do. Hampton went nine superb innings,
foiled everyone, fiddled with the corners of the strike zone and
kept his injury-riddled team in a game it finally squeezed out in
12 innings, 2-1 over the Colorado Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first three guys are getting to the point where they're
about as reliable a staff as those teams we had in the 1980s,''
Dierker said. ``We're not too far off on our fourth guy, either,
but those top three are just getting so consistent. And right now,
they might have to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the injuries are only stacking up.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Tim Bogar was the latest scratch from Dierker's
lineup, after a hamstring twinge lingered from Monday night's win
over the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   And just three innings into Tuesday night's game, third baseman
Jack Howell bare-handed a squibber by Chris Sexton and severely
pulled his right groin muscle trying to make the play. The injury
was severe enough that Howell had to lie on the turf for several
moments, agonizing over the pain.
</P>
<P>
   Look for Howell on a disabled list near you. And while Bogar's
injury is not considered as severe, everything can look like
traction and IVs when a club already is so thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get guys hurt, usually a good club can bring in
another good player off the bench,'' Dierker said. ``But now you
don't have a bench. You start to wonder what you're going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But look at the scoreboard. Astros 2, Rockies 1.
</P>
<P>
   For all the gloom of the night over the injuries, for all the
players Dierker has had to keep scratching from the lineup while he
and general manager Gerry Hunsicker scratch their heads over it
all, the ball keeps rolling right.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the standings. Look at how the pain from all the
injuries continues to run only skin deep, as the Astros continue to
be the best team in the National League with their 28-16 record.
</P>
<P>
   Look at how it just keeps hurting so good, how pitching
continues to be the soothing balm for what ails the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, whose battle with the Rockies' Darryl Kile was
monumental, looked worthy of the win. He gave up just five hits and
one scratched-out run in the Rockies' first, after Hampton opened
slowly by giving up a pair of walks.
</P>
<P>
   Through five of the next seven innings, Hampton faced the
minimum against a team known for racking up wild rallies. In the
bottom of the eighth, Hampton's teammates finally tied the game at
one on a Jeff Bagwell walk and a two-out double by Carl Everett.
</P>
<P>
   Four innings later, Hampton looked like just another interested
spectator when Everett rolled one under Vinny Castilla's glove for
the game-winning RBI, but he was much, much more.
</P>
<P>
   His quality start, like those from Lima and Reynolds, was the
reason the Astros won despite the pain of it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a little lucky,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they were. The bench was thin, and the injuries were
mounting. But Hampton came through and the bats ultimately did,
too.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies threw a few helmets and weren't exactly quote
machines in the wake of the outcome. But when you're good, clutch
and opportunistic and have three of the best starters in the
league, these things happen.
</P>
<P>
   It was bitter loss for the Rockies, sure. But, hey, that's the
way the cookie crumbles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
