<HEADER>
A1386 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNIVERSE-AGE-SFCHRON &LR;      05-26 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSE-AGE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AT 12 BILLION YEARS OLD, UNIVERSE IS STILL GROWING FAST  &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A team of cosmic observers has concluded that the universe is
about 12 billion years old _ a far more precise date than previous
estimates _ and that it is expanding at an accelerating pace that
will essentially continue forever.
</P>
<P>
   The report by the worldwide team of 27 astronomers is based on
eight years of observing remote galaxies and the stars within them
using NASA's powerful Hubble space telescope, which is orbiting
some 300 miles above the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Headed by Wendy Freedman of the Carnegie Institution's
observatories in Pasadena, the team measured the distance from
Earth of some 800 flickering stars, known as Cepheid variables,
embedded in 18 galaxies as far as 65 million light-years away.
</P>
<P>
   Cepheids pulsate at a known rate and have long been used to
measure cosmic distances. They also provide vital clues to the rate
at which the universe is expanding _ a mysterious and long
controversial number known as the Hubble Constant.
</P>
<P>
   Freedman and her colleagues believe their measurement of the
Cepheids provides the strongest indication yet that every galaxy in
the universe is now speeding away from every other galaxy at a rate
that increases by 160,000 miles an hour for every 3.3 light-years
that each galaxy finds itself away from Earth's own Milky Way.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all these years, we are finally entering an era of
precision cosmology,'' Freedman said Tuesday in announcing the
findings at NASA in Washington. ``Now we can more reliably address
the broader picture of the universe's origin, evolution and
destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering that a single light-year is equal to about 6
trillion miles, such speeds are almost inconceivable. Even harder
to grasp is the fact that the Milky Way itself is part of this vast
explosion. What that means is that we're not at the center of the
universe, after all; instead, we're like a single raisin in a vast
lump of dough that is rising in an oven where all the other raisins
are moving away from each other, faster and faster as the oven gets
hotter and hotter.
</P>
<P>
   That rate of expansion for the universe, known as the Hubble
Constant, is named after Edwin Hubble, who first found evidence for
the expansion in 1929. Since then, other astronomers have used the
Hubble Constant to estimate the age of the universe as anywhere
from 10 billion to 20 billion years old.
</P>
<P>
   Freedman and her colleagues now calculate that their rate of 70
kilometers per second for the Hubble Constant is accurate to within
10 percent. That's an unprecedented precision, considering that
past calculations have varied from as slow as 50 to as fast as 100
kilometers per second for every 3.3 light-years of distance _ a
distance known in cosmology as a megaparsec.
</P>
<P>
   To Freedman and her colleagues, an uncertainty of only 10
percent is tiny compared with previous and highly controversial
uncertainties of 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Or as Robert Kirshner of Harvard told reporters with a smile
Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to disagree by a factor of two, and now we're just as
passionate about 10 percent. A factor of two is like arguing
whether you have one foot or two, but 10 percent is like arguing
about one toe _ plus or minus one piggy.''
</P>
<P>
   The argument will surely go on, however. Allan Sandage, a
distinguished Carnegie Institution astronomer who also bases his
work on Hubble telescope observations, disagreed strongly with the
Freedman team Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sandage has a much different calculation for the Hubble Constant
and argued that the universe could be anywhere between 14 billion
and 18 billion years old, depending on its total mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``If NASA is giving the impression that the problem is solved,
then we would dispute that,'' he told the Associated Press. ``They
have announced a final number, and they are not correct.''
</P>
<P>
   Another eminent dissenter is cosmologist Charles Lineweaver of
the University of New South Wales in Australia. Lineweaver has
analyzed the background microwave radiation that still permeates
the universe as a faint residue of the Big Bang, the incandescent
explosion that marked the beginning of the universe, according to a
widely accepted theory. In a report being published Friday in the
journal Science, he concludes that the universe is most probably
about 13.4 billion years old, give or take 1.6 billion years.
</P>
<P>
   Freedman, however, does not claim that her team's number is
``final,'' and agrees that the universe might well turn out to be
13.5 billion years old, depending on what its total mass is.
</P>
<P>
   And that's another mystery: All the measured mass of all the
stars and galaxies in the known universe is still not enough to
account for its observed expansion rate.
</P>
<P>
   Old theories that the gravity of the universe would eventually
cause it to collapse many billions of years from now _ in what
astronomers have termed a ``Big Crunch'' _ are now widely
discarded.
</P>
<P>
   But to keep the universe expanding, there must be something else
as yet unmeasured to act as a repulsive force. While many
physicists and astronomers refer to that unknown mass as subnuclear
particles of ``dark matter,'' others _ like veteran supernova
hunter Saul Perlmutter of the University of California's Lawrence
Berkeley Laboratory _ hold that some mysterious other force is
speeding the expansion of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence derived from studies of exploding supernovas,
Perlmutter and his colleagues say, ``is forcing us to consider the
possibility that some cosmic dark energy exists that opposes the
self-attraction of matter and causes the expansion of the universe
to accelerate.'' Together with astrophysicist Neta Bahcall and
physicist Paul Steinhardt of Princeton, Perlmutter is also
publishing a report in this Friday's issue of Science.
</P>
<P>
   However precisely scientists ultimately pin down the universe's
rate of expansion, the weight of evidence suggests that it should
continue accelerating indefinitely. And Freedman's team backs that
forecast up.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the Washington briefing Tuesday, Michael Turner of
the University of Chicago said: ``In 400 to 500 billion years,
we're only going to be able to see a very few neighboring galaxies.
The stars will be dim and the universe will become a bleaker and
bleaker place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
