<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE PARKING COP EARNS HIS SALT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ PHANTOM MENACE: Is there a more heinous crime
in this city than stealing parking spaces?
<P>
   Well, there are about 25 fewer spacejackers now that the
Department of Parking and Traffic busted up what is believed to be
San Francisco's first parking-sticker counterfeit ring.
</P>
<P>
   Chalk it up to the alert work of a parking control O &LR; officer who
was new on the job. He was working Nob Hill and noticed that while
most resident parking stickers are stuck to rear bumpers, as per
instructions, suddenly many stickers were being displayed in rear
windows. The fake stickers, as it turns out, were printed on cheap
paper that wouldn't stand up to the elements.
</P>
<P>
   The officer _ who prefers to remain anonymous, so let's call him
the Lone Meter Ranger _ nosed around and noticed that many of the
back-window stickers didn't look quite right.
</P>
<P>
   Bingo (as the cops say), an investigation by the Police
Department's fraud unit that, over time, identified 25 bogus
permits. A week ago, a fleet of trucks swooped into the area and
towed eight cars.
</P>
<P>
   Will more be towed?
</P>
<P>
   ``If the people are that stupid,'' says Tony Novello, the DPT's
enforcement director.
</P>
<P>
   The eight owners claimed their cars and were pumped for
information, and now it will be up to the D.A. to decide whether
they will be charged with misdemeanors and face $500 fines.
</P>
<P>
   What about Mr. Big, who, according to my source, almost surely
works at the Fairmont Hotel and was making the phony stickers with
his computer and selling them to fellow employees for $200 a pop?
</P>
<P>
   Police aren't saying whether they have a suspect, but the
offense is a felony.
</P>
<P>
   What's important is that the city is a fairer place today, and
we owe it all to the Lone Meter Ranger.
</P>
<P>
   MY BAD: I mentioned an ancient pothole on Pine St. that had
achieved landmark status and was named Piney the Elder and was
finally filled in by city crews. I said that the hole was on Pine
near Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry. I was using my NATO map. Pine and Sacramento don't cross,
of course. Maybe after the next earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   SAY ``F- DEATH AND CHEESE'': A photographer does what he must to
get his shot. Larry Keenan, whose classic photos of the San
Francisco beat poets and people like Bob Dylan are part of a beat
retro art exhibit at SkyDeckcq &LR;  in the Embarcadero (through July
3), remembers when he got an opportunity to shoot the great Allen
Ginsberg.
</P>
<P>
   Keenan was invited to Ginsberg's apartment, and: ``Allen soon
rolled up his rug, sat down and chanted `F_ death' for about an
hour. Peter Orlovsky, Michael McClure, Bruce Conner and I joined
in. I felt a little guilty because my dad, who was supporting me in
school and buying my film and photo equipment, was a mortician.''
</P>
<P>
   Man, those beats knew how to have a good time. And was it just
me, or did you also think Keenan was going to say, ``Alan &LR; Allen
rolled up his rug, sat down, and smoked it''?
</P>
<P>
   MORE CLINKERS: Yes, more nominations for worst invention of the
20th century. Marvin Chandler wonders how people survived before
the electric toothbrush, the electric pencil sharpener and the
electric carving knife.
</P>
<P>
   Honey, this is one tough Thanksgiving turkey. Hand me my ``Li'l
Butcher'' power knife and my safety goggles, please.
</P>
<P>
   SO SUE ME: At Sushi Chardonnay, on Union, it's all the sushi you
can eat for a fixed price. But, at the bottom of the menu, this
note: ``For each remaining piece of sushi or rice left on your
plate, there will be a charge of $1.''
</P>
<P>
   David Pressman says this is far more effective as a
plate-cleaning plea than his mom's old ``Children are starving in
Europe'' routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me, sir, I counted the grains of rice left on your
plate and you owe us another $5,674.''
</P>
<P>
   EAGER BEAVERS: We at The Chronicle want to make sure nobody is
deprived of the opportunity to subscribe. But Phil Gravitt wishes
our subscription department wouldn't call him twice a month,
because he's been a subscriber for 16 years (thank you, Phil).
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear that The Chronicle is for sale,'' Phil says. ``If the
paper is sold, when the new owners take over, will the former
Chronicle owners phone the new people every month and say, `Want to
buy t &LR; The Chronicle?' ''
</P>
<P>
   HUNGRY MAN, MAN: One more memory of Ginsberg from Larry Keenan:
``He asked me if I would like some coffee and served it to me in a
metal bowl that looked like a dog dish. He kept asking, `Are you
finished with that, man?' The bowl seemed very important to him,
and it was making me uncomfortable. When I finally said I was done,
he grabbed the bowl and filled it with breakfast cereal. I was
using his only bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Now THERE was a beat, man.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
