<HEADER>
A1590 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUMBLING-ROBBERS27-CO     05-26 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUMBLING-ROBBERS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio robbers aren't too flashy, but they're keeping busy
 &HT;    By Wes Hills
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Compared with their romantic, swashbuckling
counterparts of the 1920s and 1930s, some of the area's recent bank
robbers are a rather disappointing lot.
</P>
<P>
   Often homeless and unemployed, they frequently lack the basic
necessities of their profession.
</P>
<P>
   No flashy, souped-up getaway cars. No masks. Some aren't even
armed with an intimidating weapon.
</P>
<P>
   As a career move, bank robbery has little future.
</P>
<P>
   The average take is about $1,000, 68 percent bank robbers are
caught in this area (8 percent above the national average) and they
face up to 25 years in prison if armed, according to the Federal
Bureau of Investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these grim risk-reward stats, bank robbery is up sharply
in the nine-county Dayton area during the past two years. The FBI
reports 33 bank robberies so far this year and 53 for 1998,
compared to 34 for all of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned about the surge, several area bank presidents and
their heads of security plan to meet today with Montgomery County
Sheriff Gary Haines, representatives from the FBI and the Dayton
Police Department, according to Diana Schoenberger, spokeswoman for
Fifth Third Bank.
</P>
<P>
   These are the tales of four who got caught.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with an age-old tradition of giving daring robbers
memorable handles such as Machine Gun Kelly or the Sundance Kid,
consider their new-age counterparts _ the Gentleman Bandit, the
Mutt and Jeff Robbery Duo, and accused who might be called the
Dumpster Diver.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn Steven Morgan's own account of robbing the Fifth Third
Bank in Trotwood on May 11 earns him the title of Gentleman Bandit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I caught a bus in downtown Dayton which brought me to the
Salem Mall,'' Morgan, 41, wrote for police shortly after his arrest
within minutes of the robbery. ``While on the bus I wrote the note
which I gave to the teller. I saw several banks and decided to rob
the 5/3 because I believe I could have a better getaway.''
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a black shirt, khaki pants and burgundy ballcap,
Morgan said he entered the bank and handed the teller a note
reading, ``This is a robbery. 100s, 50s, no alarm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The teller gave me the money and I stated, `Have a nice day.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan's getaway was brief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran around the building and ran past the National City
Bank,'' he wrote. ``I ran next to a house where I discarded the
clothes I was wearing and placed the money ($6,890) inside my shoe.
I sat on the porch of the house, then I decided to go to Value City
so I would have other persons around.''
</P>
<P>
   Those other persons soon turned out to be Trotwood police.
</P>
<P>
   Not one to play the tough guy, Morgan quickly decided to get his
role in two other bank jobs off his chest as well.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan also described his code of robbery ethics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never threatened any of the tellers verbally nor in the
notes,'' he told police. ``I was never armed with a firearm when I
committed a bank robbery. I never intended to hurt any of the
tellers and I accepted any amount of money given to me by the
tellers even if it was a small amount.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan said he only got about $500 in his first bank job and
just $350 in the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad about scaring the tellers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the case of Donnie D. Tunstall, who might be dubbed
the Dumpster Diver.
</P>
<P>
   While Morgan said he robbed banks for money to ``get a new
start'' in Atlanta, Tunstall might have decided to charge into the
Bank One branch at 1158 W. Third St. on Jan. 25 with a sawed-off
shotgun because he was tired of living in a trash bin.
</P>
<P>
   Tunstall, of the Dempsey Dumpster near Mercer Avenue and South
Broadway Street, fired his cheap, single-shot shotgun into a wall
of the bank during the robbery, police said.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't remain at large much longer than Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton police Lt. Randy Beane said citizens in the area led him
to the Dumpster, where police found $4,068 in cash in a pillowcase
and several personal items, including bedding.
</P>
<P>
   Tunstall hadn't reloaded the shotgun before Beane raised the lid
to the Dumpster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it just seems someone's looking after you,'' Beane
shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   Tunstall's attorney, assistant Federal Public Defender Beth
Goldstein Lewis, said Tunstall had lived in the trash bin for ``a
substantial amount of time'' before the robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Tunstall, who faces up to 25 years in prison, now has a home at
a federal medical center, where he is being evaluated for his
competency to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Behnken and Lito P. Sorio were Dayton's Mutt and Jeff
Robbery Duo.
</P>
<P>
   Sorio, who stands 5-foot-1 and weighs 115 pounds, was the
lookout. Behnken, a former Brink's employee who stands 6-foot-1,
was the brains who put together the plan to rob the Brink's armored
car service at 4395 Springfield St.
</P>
<P>
   That plan quickly went awry when this not-so-dynamic duo chose
as their weapons supplier an undercover FBI special agent.
</P>
<P>
   Behnken ``discussed a plan to conduct extensive surveillance of
the Brink's building from the woods directly behind'' the building
and ``provided a diagram of the interior of the Brink's building,
the location of security cameras alarms and the like,'' according
to court records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behnken, a former private detective and U.S. Marine, also
discussed various types of ammunition and its ability to penetrate
various objects, and asked about bullet-resistant vests and
rappelling harnesses. At the conclusion of the meeting, Behnken
provided $200 in cash to the undercover agent and agreed to
purchase three 9 mm handguns and ammunition, an AR-15 rifle and
three vests for a total price of $1,100.''
</P>
<P>
   What had driven Behnken and Sorio, who had no prior criminal
records, to such desperate measures?
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the conspiracy, Behnken was separated, drinking,
unemployed and homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Sorio was working 87 hours a week at two jobs to help support
his mother, sister, sister's child and pregnant girlfriend while
trying to raise the funds to have a brain tumor removed from his
2-year-old son in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 28, Rice sentenced Sorio to two years' probation, with
the first four months on home detention with work release.
</P>
<P>
   Rice based the sentence, in part, on his finding that Sorio's
small stature would make him ``extremely vulnerable'' to assaults
from prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Behnken was sentenced to 21 months in prison April 21.
</P>
<P>
   None of the recent bank robbers measure up in either style or
bravado to the infamous Kurt ``Meatball'' Hardendorf, who was
quickly captured by the FBI after he robbed the Gem City Savings
and Loan Association in November 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Hardendorf became a suspect after he strolled down Main Street
handing out $50 bills to passers-by.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after his release from prison, Meatball again found
himself in the media spotlight in June 1973 after he robbed the
downtown Third National Bank, armed with a pillowcase.
</P>
<P>
   He quickly supplied FBI agents with a motive.
</P>
<P>
   The pitcher on the softball team at his former prison was
nearing 60 and Meatball said he wanted to try out for the spot.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Carl A. Weinman quickly granted Meatball's
wish.
</P>
<P>
   Wes Hills writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
