<HEADER>
A1591 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN27-CO     05-26 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Presidential, and human, dilemma
 &HT;    By Stebbins Jefferson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ I wonder whether Thomas Jefferson had a
sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   I can recall only his serious pronouncements on self-evident
truths that continue to inspire, even when one knows the author of
the Declaration of Independence was a slave owner. Apparently,
Jefferson, our third president, believed he could keep separate the
private and the public, the ignobility of one never compromising
the nobility of the other.
</P>
<P>
   Recently in Charlottesville, Va., Jefferson's double life
merged. During a family reunion at Monticello, his and his white
wife's alleged descendants met his and black slave Sally Hemings'
supposeddescendants _ ``supposed'' because neither group has been
confirmed by DNA tests. They ate together and toured the historic
home. The children, black and white, laid flowers on his grave and
recited the Lord's Prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Reading about that ceremony, I was struck by the ironic humor
ofJefferson, an American icon, caught in the same predicament as
many other men, less learned and less prominent, who also chose to
forget that truth will out, and often at the most inopportune
times, such as those surrounding death and burial.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in a small town, I learned at an early age about the
private truths death liberates from the suppression of public lies.
One night after midnight, when I was still in grade school, a woman
who lived around the corner knocked on the door of our neighbor,
who owned a car. From my bedroom window, I could hear the woman
begging him to help her carry someone home.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, I learned that a prominent deacon and community
leader who lived in another part of town had died in his sleep
during the night. Talk was that his wife had discovered him cold
beside her the next morning and called the funeral home. I
suspected a different scenario only after hearing the grown-ups
comment on the deacon's wife's great dignity and restraint even
though the woman who had brought her husband home wailed louder
than anyone else at his burial. Only then did I attach significance
to the fact that the woman's son had the same first name as the
departed deacon and was called ``Junior.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the passing of an affluent bar owner, notorious
for his womanizing. At his funeral, he was laid out in a casket so
plush, one wondered if he would want to leave it when the trumpet
sounds on that great getting-up morning. Speculation was rife as to
whether his widow, who was childless, would acknowledge his
offspring, several of whom lived in the area. She didn't. When they
arrived at the viewing, she ordered the undertaker to close the
casket and proceed to the burial _ immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Many a family has been split, not over who will inherit material
things left by a man but over who will be listed in the funeral
program as surviving children. So I would suggest that all
Jeffersons on both sides of the color divide consider the example
of a long-suffering wife who rose above the fact that her late
husband had carried on a long, sustained relationship with another
woman in our town. In the funeral cortege, the wife shared the
first car with the other woman and listed all of his children on
the program, those born both within and outside the marriage. Even
our town's most meddlesome gossips were at a loss for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Some will consider comparing Jefferson's plight to that of such
men a sacrilege. After all, he was a widower, and his property, the
slave Sally Hemings, was half-sister to his deceased wife and said
to be so much like her they could have been twins. Whatever. Like
lesser men, Jefferson apparently made private choices he knew to be
inconsistent with public morality. He lived a lie. ``He who permits
himself to tell a lie once,'' he wrote, ``finds it much easier to
do it a second and a third time, til at length it becomes
habitual.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, his black descendents are fighting for the right to be
buried in the family plot at Monticello. I wonder whether Jefferson
would be amused.
</P>
<P>
   Stebbins Jefferson is a columnist for The Palm Beach Post.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
