<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What you missed by sleeping in
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The first person to hitchhike at the new
airport?
</P>
<P>
   Me.
</P>
<P>
   See, what happened was, Sunday morning a little after 8 when I
was getting ready to leave Austin-Bergstrom International Airport,
I couldn't find the enormous outdoor parking lot where I had left
my car about three hours earlier. I asked directions, and I was
told I should take the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   I walked to the shuttle bus and told the driver I was headed to
lot A12. Fine, he said, get on this bus.
</P>
<P>
   When we got out toward where you are leaving the new airport to
turn onto Texas 71, I sensed I had screwed up. So I asked the
driver where the heck he was going. The driver said he was going to
Robert Mueller Municipal Airport, which closed Saturday. I told him
that didn't do me much good because my car was parked at the new
airport, which we had just left and was now in the driver's rear
view mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really sorry, man,'' the driver said, opening the bus door
to let me out onto the side of the road that leads back into the
new airport. ``So am I,'' I said. ``'Cause now I got to walk about
five miles.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I think it would have been only about a two-mile hike
back to my car. I put my thumb out and started walking backward
down the side of the road toward the new airport, which I could see
in the distance. Fortunately, Precinct 5 Constable Bruce Elfant,
who was driving by, recognized me, picked me up and gave me a ride
to my car.
</P>
<P>
   There were some other firsts of note Sunday morning during
Austin-Bergstrom's first day of business. This is a beautiful
airport. If Mueller is an outhouse, then this place is indoor
plumbing. It even smells good because of the chorizo and eggs
coming out of the Matt's El Rancho booth.
</P>
<P>
   First guitar case spotted: about 5:45 a.m., being carried by
Jennifer Bowles, a University of Texas law student. ``I don't play
it, though,'' she said. She explained that it belonged to a friend
in Mexico who had left it in Austin. And she was flying to Mexico
City to return it.
</P>
<P>
   First L.A. rock band spotted: Other Star People about 7:20 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The band members in black clothing were a little grumbly. They
said they were lugging their guitars on the long walk to Gate 21
because the curbside computer was down. So they couldn't check them
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's OK because we like Austin,'' said band member
Precious Finch, who was wearing a faux leopard jacket.
</P>
<P>
   First guy spotted wearing those Bubbaland-style yellow yardstick
suspenders that you can buy at Home Depot: Contractor Lloyd
Goehring of Xeno Sound Inc., at about eight minutes before 7 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a good place to hang all my dangling electronics,''
said Goehring, who had a pager and a cell phone attached to his
yardstick suspenders.
</P>
<P>
   He was checking the sound system that pipes out the music by
Willie Nelson and others at the new airport.
</P>
<P>
   First guy spotted in the airport in a Hawaiian shirt: Austin
computer programmer Richard Zoch.
</P>
<P>
   Zoch was the second person to get off the first plane to arrive
at the new airport. American Flight 1911 from Dallas landed at 7:49
a.m. Zoch and his girlfriend, Cari Waggoner of Austin, the first
person to arrive at Austin's new airport, had just gotten back from
Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   So what was Zoch's first question about the new airport? ``Where
is baggage claim?''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, man, don't ask me. I can't even find my car.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
