<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 11:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1593 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINOR-COLUMN27-COX     05-26 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    My 'allowance' doesn't allow for sweet dreams
 &HT;    By Emily Minor
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ There was this huge traffic jam the
other morning in West Palm Beach. Some woman, cute as can be, was
standing at the southeast corner with this little Martha
Stewart-esque straw basket. I'm pretty sure the handle was
stenciled with sprigs of holly. And she was hollering at people,
strangers, potential killers if the truth be known, asking for
money.
</P>
<P>
   I know this because, well, she was me.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. I still have a job, although you may
hesitate to call it that. But about a month ago, I read an article
in a money magazine about family finances. According to them, the
most important thing in a couple's life is not great sex or
simpatico political views or how easily you talk over your frozen
Stouffer's dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1 component for happy married life is financial
stability.
</P>
<P>
   Say what?
</P>
<P>
   I have to admit, I was a little confused. So I asked the woman
at the doctor's office if she knew what that meant. And that's when
she told me about this thing some families do. It's a little
money-management trick she said works for a lot of people. She's
Hispanic, so this might be something they do only in
Spanish-speaking countries.
</P>
<P>
   It's called a budget.
</P>
<P>
   And that's how the Minor family, all three of us, came to earn
our weekly allowances.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you as out of touch as I was _ in the past, I'd
just sit down, do the money, get depressed, then go buy something
to cheer me up _ here's how this allowance thing works. I hesitate
to call it a ``bizarre ritual,'' but, well, you decide.
</P>
<P>
   You and your husband sit down and calculate how much you spend
on family expenses _ groceries, household bills, etc. _ and set
that money aside. That's family money.
</P>
<P>
   Now, decide how much money each of you needs to make it through
the week. Gasoline. Haircuts. Shoulder massages. Lunch money. And
remember, the Playboy Channel goes on his list.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've established an equal dollar amount _ the amount each
of you needs to survive for seven days _ realize right up front
neither of you could survive on this. So, multiply it by three.
</P>
<P>
   That's your weekly allowance!
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works at our house. Every Friday, I get $100.
Cash. My husband gets the same amount and our son gets $10. These
payouts are not tied to any chores or duties. We get this money
simply for being alive. Isn't America great?
</P>
<P>
   I have to say I like it. I mean, the days go by so much quicker
when you spend half your waking hours scheming of ways to sneak $5
from his wallet. And finally, after all these years, I know where
my money goes.
</P>
<P>
   I spend my money on lunches, gasoline, trips to the drugstore,
overdue fees at Blockbuster and 7-Eleven Slurpees for my kid, who
is saving his money for a Nintendo 64.
</P>
<P>
   There are some gray areas in this family budget thing, things
that you'll have to work out. Like the other day when my husband
was home sick with a bad head cold, I spent $28 of my own money on
cough medicine, cold tablets, Puff tissues and a newspaper. I
didn't have the heart to ask him to pay me back. And besides, I've
already taken $85 from his wallet.
</P>
<P>
   But I must be feeling guilty because I think that was the night
I had the weird dream. The one where I was standing at the busy
intersection begging for money. People were driving by and flinging
$100 bills at me, just throwing them out the window left and right.
I wonder if it's because I was naked?
</P>
<P>
   Emily Minor writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
