<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 11:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1594 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN27-COX     05-26 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Proof missing kids can be found
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The tot's mother, Anna Mary Thompson, was the
only girl in a family of eight brothers. She lived with her mother,
Jennie Waker, while her husband, Arthur, and five of her brothers
served overseas. Family life was full of anxiety for loved ones in
the war. Nobody worried about the sunny towheaded baby, safe at
home in Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, a nurse, advertised for a nanny to care for the child
while she worked. The new nursemaid, Mary Wilkey, charmed everyone
during her first day at work. On the second day, she told the
family she was taking Ronnie to the barbershop.
</P>
<P>
   She never returned.
</P>
<P>
   A reward was posted, and the community raised funds for the
return of the child. The FBI became involved, and Arthur Thompson
was called back from service in France.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, as one false lead after another was pursued,
almost everyone gave up, Ronald Thompson said, except Dayton
detective Rudolph Rado, Anna Mary and Arthur Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a strong lady, and she kept hoping and hoping he'd
come back,'' Bob Waker of Dayton said of his sister, who died in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the ordeal took its toll on the family. ``It was rough to
know he was out there somewhere,'' Waker said. ``When you hear
about cases like the Kettering girl, you really feel for the person
because you know what it's like not having someone there. It's a
hollow feeling _ there's someone who should be there, who isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkey was actually Lois Tipp, and Ronnie wasn't the only child
she snatched. Another boy, under eerily similar circumstances, was
taken from a home in Detroit. He was given the name Bobby and the
Tipps began raising their ``family'' in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1950, Charley Joe Tipp saw Bobby's body carried out
of the refrigerator of the Woodside Screwball Inn, the Tipps' bar.
</P>
<P>
   Lois Tipp had shot him.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the middle of the night, she took Bobby outside, laid him
on the ground, and blew his brains out,'' Ronald Thompson said.
``Then she wrapped him in a sheet and put his body in an unused
refrigerator in the back of the tavern.''
</P>
<P>
   Charley Joe slept through it all. But days later, neighbors
complained about the stench, and detectives investigated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there when they took him out of the refrigerator,''
Thompson said. He can't say any more about it, other than, ``That
was my brother. My brother Bobby.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Tipp was identified as a missing Detroit boy. Lois Tipp
was indicted on murder charges but never tried. She was committed
to a state hospital in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing photos of Tipp, Anna Mary Thompson and her mother
traveled to Florida to visit the woman, whom both identified as
``Mary Wilkey.'' It wasn't until March 1952 that she saw her son
again. ``That's Ronnie,'' she declared. ``That's our baby, in and
out.''
</P>
<P>
   By that time Ronnie, still known as Charley Joe, was living with
Robert Tipp in Indiana. Playing on the playground that day, he was
told to come to the principal's office. ``I walked down the hall,
my heart pounding, afraid I was in trouble. I can recall there was
a lady sitting in a chair. She could have been the mother of any of
the students.
</P>
<P>
   ``That lady sitting in the chair was my mother and it was the
first time she had seen me in eight years. It took every ounce of
her human strength to keep from reaching out and grabbing me. A
mother's love is the most powerful thing on the Earth. She never
doubted who I was.''
</P>
<P>
   But the family's fight wasn't over. It wasn't until after a
dramatic custody battle in court in January 1953, in South Bend,
Ind., that Ronnie Thompson was returned to his family.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Lewis Hammond, in awarding custody to the Thompsons, said,
``Anybody can see the striking resemblance between the picture of
Ronnie and Charley Joe.'' Even Robert Tipp's attorney withdrew his
client from the custody case, in ``light of the indisputable
evidence'' that Lois Tipp had never given birth.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone was convinced of the boy's identity, it seemed, except
Ronnie himself. When asked how he felt about his new parents, he
said, ``OK, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson recalls walking out the door of the courtroom with two
strangers, his parents.
</P>
<P>
   He came home to two brothers, Bobby and James. A third brother,
William, was born after his return. In one month, he gained 20
pounds and seemed to be thriving, but the wounds were deep.
</P>
<P>
   The long search for Ronnie, the many trips around the country,
had taken a toll on his family as well. The Thompsons eventually
divorced. Arthur Thompson died in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy to make his mother angry, Thompson noted, other
than when he expressed doubts about his identity. ``She knew who I
was,'' he said. ``She fought hard for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Tragedy continued to stalk the family. Bobby Thompson died in a
1969 house fire that injured other family members. Surviving
brothers William and James still live in the Dayton area.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Thompson, the youngest of Ronald's three sons, died in
1991 in a fall from the old Sunshine Skyway Bridge near St.
Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Thompson, the owner of a repair shop in Sarasota, is
content with his life today. Married for 23 years to his wife
Linda, he revels in his five grandchildren, including twins born
last week. ``I'm going to spoil them,'' he boasted. ``This is my
childhood. I've earned it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, ``I will never get over what happened to me. I
keep people at arm's length. I have a big wall around me.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a wall only one person, perhaps, has completely broken
down. Not surprisingly, it was his mother, the one who would have
broken down any door to get to her boy.
</P>
<P>
   Before she died, Thompson told her, ``I know you are my mother,
and I am your son.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
