<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1595 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDLIFE-JOURNEY27-COX     05-26 1474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDLIFE-JOURNEY27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wyoming ranchers inexhaustible - but never tireless
 &HT;    (EDS: This is Installment 12 on Ron Wiggins' midlife journey to
Mount McKinley)
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALVA, WYOMING _ My reader-inspired West Palm Beach,
Fla.-to-Alaska road trip included a western swing into Canada that
forced me to choose between:
</P>
<P>
   1. The revolting banana slugs of the Pacific Northwest
(suggested by Carol Buetens of Stuart, Fla.) and
</P>
<P>
   2. The insidious blood-sucking leeches of the Mahoney ranch in
eastern Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't be both. Ultimately, I was drawn to the leeches,
thanks to the pitch by Beverly Ciotti of West Palm Beach: ``If
you're seeking a true working ranch experience,'' she wrote, ``then
the Mahoney ranch is the place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be sure to take a dip in the reservoir, but watch out for the
leeches.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mahoneys _ Gerald, 64, Betsy, 59, and their married
daughter, Beth Riley, 32 _ not only own a 10,000-acre ranch strewn
amid mountains, ravines and small canyons, they pasture cattle,
grow oats and alfalfa, guide hunters, lodge vacationers and sell a
unique type of watering tank to 17 states.
</P>
<P>
   And they do it all themselves, assisted by one hired hand.
</P>
<P>
   When I called the Mahoneys on the road a half day out from their
place, I mentioned Beverly Ciotti's letter and asked if it would be
convenient for me to board a day or two. My timing was not the
best.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some turkey hunters staying with us,'' Betsy said,
``but you come on out and Beth will find some room for you. I have
meetings tonight and tomorrow, so I'm afraid I won't be around
much.''
</P>
<P>
   To get to the Mahoney ranch, I was told to take a left on the
first gravel road at Alva, population 50, and then drive forever.
Their plain but comfortable two-level house is 3.5 miles from a
town so small that the phone book has only a yellow paragraph. The
nearest Wal-Mart is an hour and a half up the road in Spearfish.
</P>
<P>
   Beth was home cooking up pot roast with vegetables. She was
expecting her dad with the hunters any moment. The group included
the host of a syndicated hunting show, a companion and a camera
man.
</P>
<P>
   ``They left at 4:30 this morning so I expect they're starving,''
Beth said. ``Mom usually cooks, but with her gone today, I guess
they'll take their chances with my cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   Betsy, a recently retired teacher, is kept busier than ever as a
consultant. Beth, like her mom, taught school, but two years ago
she decided to learn ranching from her dad. Her older brothers are
long gone, ``like most of the boys around here.''
</P>
<P>
   I could guess why the brothers left. ``It was the hideous
blood-sucking leeches in your reservoir, wasn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yes, the leeches,'' smiled Beth. ``If you swim in the
reservoir, you will deal with the leeches. I guess Beverly told you
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   As to why her brothers rejected ranching, she shrugged. ``Not
many people want to work this hard.''
</P>
<P>
   At 9:20 p.m., the turkey hunters triumphant roared into the
yard, and after a superlative meal, excused themselves, explaining
that they would be up at 3:30 a.m. to do it all again.
</P>
<P>
   When Gerald Mahoney lingered to chat, I begged him to follow his
guests to bed, knowing that he would have to guide them 6 miles
into the property. ``It's all right,'' he said resolutely. ``We'll
be back in the morning and I'll catch a nap.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney said he welcomed the chance to tell how his grandfather
started the ranch with a homestead grant signed by Teddy Roosevelt,
and added acreage little by little.
</P>
<P>
   When Gerald was 17, his father gave him several parcels, all
mortgaged to the hilt. ``I wasn't legal, but our neighbor who held
the paper made me a handshake deal so long as I didn't miss a
payment.''
</P>
<P>
   The day of the handshake deal is gone and with it, Gerald fears,
is ranching as his generation knew it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just ranch or farm anymore,'' he said softly. ``You
have to get something else going. I can tell you this: Nobody who
farmed in Wyoming last year made money on what they grew.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's been coming to that for years and the Mahoneys have
always found a way. Gerald hasn't killed a deer or an elk on his
property for 30 years, but he guides hunters who do.
</P>
<P>
   Many visitors are regulars who come around just to stay a spell
and drive a tractor and mend fence with Gerald and now, Beth.
``It's a change,'' he said. ``It relaxes them somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   At length, Gerald excused himself, assuring me that Beth would
have some time in the morning to show me around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beth has always been a hand,'' Gerald said, a compliment in
these parts. ``More than that, she has a head for it. She sees
ahead, what needs to be done. A lot of good hands can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time I awoke, the hunters were long gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on, we'll grab one of the trucks and take a look around
and maybe see some critters,'' Beth said with a cheerfulness that
bordered on the superhuman, considering that she had gone home the
night before only to return in time to cook a 4 a.m. breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   A short half mile into the ranch I saw thousands of yards of
fencing, ton upon ton of baled hay, and everywhere evidence of
unceasing labor. Indeed, there is so much work to be done on a
ranch that it takes three men and a strong boy just to imagine it.
</P>
<P>
   What was her typical work day like?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if you heard me on the phone with the neighbor,
but today he's inoculating stock, so soon as I catch me a horse,
I'll go over with our hand and help out. Tomorrow, he'll send
somebody over to help me move the cattle.''
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't clear on the reference to catching a horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one I want was worked pretty hard yesterday, so he might
take some persuading,'' she laughed.
</P>
<P>
   As we passed dozens of plump yearlings, Beth corrected my
assumption that they belonged to the Mahoneys. ``We fatten them up
for the owner and get paid according to how much weight they gain
over the summer. Three hundred pounds is good.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy if the cattle could just be left alone to eat
grass. Naturally, there's more to it. The animals must be neutered,
inoculated and rotated to new pastures to keep the grass healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Beth likes the yearlings. ``They're funny, like adolescents. Get
them into a new field and they gallop around and chase each other.
Like teenagers, they can also be uncooperative. In fact, they're
good at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Dad gets back,'' she said, as we ended our tour, ``make
him tell you about his water tank invention. It's something we're
real proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald lifted a strand of barbed wire to let me into a pasture
where a huge tire lay on its side. The tire measured 12 feet in
diameter. It was sealed on the bottom with a layer of cement so it
would hold water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventeen years ago I was at a mine where they use those tires
on earth-moving machines. When they told me they had to pay to
dispose of them, it gave me an idea.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to make a machine to cut the tire for a watering
tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watering tanis are made of steel or Fiberglass. Both freeze
and crack in the cold and have to be replaced every few years.
Plus, you have to anchor them with posts to keep the cattle from
pushing them around.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody pushes around Mahoney's Giant Rubber Water Tanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uncut, each tire weighs 8,000 pounds. When I remove the rim,
they still weigh 5,000 pounds. Set one down, it stays put. I truly
believe a couple of bulls could fight in the middle of one and not
hurt it.''
</P>
<P>
   The rubber tanks can freeze and melt without cracking or
leaking. In 17 years of selling on average 1,000 water tanks a year
to ranchers and farmers in 17 states, he has yet to replace one.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've heard of a win-win situation? This is win-win-win-win
situation,'' Gerald said with something approaching fervor. ``The
mine makes a little instead of paying for disposal, the truckers
make a little, the farmer saves, and I make a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The rubber tanks cost $400 delivered. When one farmer tried to
get a better price, Gerald countered. ``Tell you what. I'll show
you my expenses and you show me what you'd pay for another tank,
and I'll swap you my profit for your savings.''
</P>
<P>
   The farmer laughed and paid the price.
</P>
<P>
   As Max and I left the Mahoney spread, it was with good thoughts
in my mind. A fellow could retire out here and run a few hundred
head of leeches in the reservoir for medical labs. Fatten the
leeches on unsuspecting dude ranch guests, and you have the makings
of a horror-Western starring Billy Crystal: City Suckers.
</P>
<P>
   As Gerald Mahoney taught me, you can make it out here, but
you've got to diversify.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Wiggins writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
