<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUPLES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Do you have what it takes to play matchmaker?
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In ``Notting Hill,'' Julia Roberts plays
a global movie goddess who stumbles into Hugh Grant's bookstore and
shoplifts his commoner heart.
</P>
<P>
   But Hugh's competition for her affection comes in the
intimidating, glamour-boy shape of Alec Baldwin. Alec Baldwin?!
Does Hugh stand a chance?
</P>
<P>
   To find out, you'll have to see the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, we remain skeptical about how this toothsome twosome
will gel on screen. They just don't seem like a matched set.
</P>
<P>
   Julia has an easygoing, All-American effervescence, while Hugh
has made a career of playing the easily flustered, buttoned-down
Brit.
</P>
<P>
   She's tall and leggy; there's something schlumpy about his
posture. She's known for her great set of choppers. His teeth are
nothing to smile about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't pick the two of them to go together,'' says Denise
Winston, a professional matchmaker based in New York City. ``It
would seem to me she'd be too strong of a personality for Hugh
Grant, who is subdued and quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   Her vote goes to Alec Baldwin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see them physically together,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   That may be because Alec and Julia _ both splendid specimens of
their gender _ are about the same on the attractiveness scale. And
scoring similarly, say researchers, is the key.
</P>
<P>
   Charles T. Hill has the ivory-tower proof. The psychology
professor at Whittier College in Whittier, Calif., tracked dating
couples over a two-year period, and later followed 231 married
couples for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   He found that not only did the daters pair off with people of
similar attractiveness, but also that looks often helped determine
a relationship's longevity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The couples that stayed together tended to be better matched
than those who broke up,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   When couples are mismatched, the power balance between the two
gets thrown out of whack. The more attractive person is perceived
by both as having more power, in part because the looker feels like
he or she has other alternatives, Hill says.
</P>
<P>
   But he hastens to add that attractiveness is just one factor
among many.
</P>
<P>
   And not even the most important one. Similar ages, SAT scores
and educational plans are more pivotal because they influence the
ability of a couple to communicate.
</P>
<P>
   While matchmakers acknowledge most people want a good-looking
partner, attraction based solely on looks is ``going to wear off
after three or four dates,'' says Mitchell Brandt, president of
Great Expectations dating service, which has a Boca Raton location.
``The person with charisma and bonding power will win out.''
</P>
<P>
   So that may explain the ultimate mating head-scratcher: grizzled
rock stars paired off with gorgeous supermodels. Pick a couple: Ric
Ocasek and Paulina Porizkova, Rod Stewart and Rachel Hunter, Keith
Richards and Patti Hansen, Billy Joel and Christie Brinkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times you'll find a woman who is very attractive, and
that's her strong suit,'' Brandt says. ``She wants someone less
attractive because that's her (area of) power and control.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill also has an explanation: ``Think in terms of resources.
Who's got the resources _ whether it's fame, power, money.''
</P>
<P>
   Meaning that stretch limos and soldout stadiums can make up for
bad posture and crooked teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Staci Sturrock writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
