Coconut cake. (Langhenry, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN _ A weekly beer column by the Michael
Skube of the Atlanta Journal-Constitution. This week: Duel of
Atlanta's daring new India Pale Ales. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-CYBERSPICE _ A weekly column looking at the plethora of
recipes on the Internet. (Parham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-IMPROMPTU _ Impromptu, casual , carefree. Pick your colors,
use things you have around your home, decorate around them. Serve
take-out or home cooked food. But keep it simple, refreshing and
fun. Sue Smith is a master at such spur-of-the-moment parties.
Running to the store and gathering up olives, cheeses, breads.
Marinating fresh fruits with liqueurs and freezing them in a loaf
for festive, icy slicing. Scatter a few fern fronds on top and she
has an easy attractive table. Siders on two or three other local
impromptu entertainers. (Crider, Austin American-Statesman). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-SOUP _ Specialty of the House: strawberry soup. (Austin
American-Statesman freelancer, not for use by NYTNS clients).
</P>
<P>
   DIETITIAN _ Answers to questions about calorie content of chai,
toxicity of Vitamin E and specific concerns for feeding people with
AIDS. (Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-BBQ _ Steve Raichlen, author of the award-winning cookbook
The Barbecue Bible, believes that cooking over an open fire was the
impetus that made us human. ``Grilling began civilization,'' he
says. ``Touch the roof of the cave with your torch and you have
art. And you need language to say `pass the salt.''' (Dayton Daily
News). 14. WITH PHOTOS and LAYOUT.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BBQ-RECIPES _ A Memorial Day menu from The Barbecue Bible: smoky
burgers, baked beans and grilled sugar-dipped pineapple.(Dayton
Daily News). 26.
</P>
<P>
   STYLE-CHEFWEAR _ Television and other media have elevated chefs
to celebrity status in the 90s, so it's only natural that ``chef''
fashion has emerged. Chefwear, a line of clothing that used to be
marketed exclusively to working chefs, found last year that almost
20 percent of their business came from home cooks who wanted to
wear the baggy pants with crazy prints and boxy white shirts like
their chef idols. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, May 30.
</P>
