</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 1)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at
</P>
<P>
   q&AMP;a(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: What happens to the items people leave at the Vietnam
Veterans Memorial in Washington?
</P>
<P>
   A: The items are collected by National Park Service rangers and
are identified, catalogued and stored as museum artifacts at the
Park Service's museum resource center in suburban Washington. Items
may be loaned to other museums for exhibition, but otherwise aren't
available for viewing. The resouce center isn't open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A recently published a list of people on a best-dressed
list, and included Serena Linley, described as Princess Margaret's
daughter-in-law. I knew Princess Margaret had one or two daughters,
but not a son. Can you clarify?
</P>
<P>
   A: Princess Margaret and Anthony Armstrong-Jones (Lord Snowdon)
had two children, David and Sarah. Serena Linley, who made Eleanor
Lambert's International Best-Dressed List for 1999, is the wife of
David, who is titled Viscount Linley. So she indeed is Princess
Margaret's daughter-in-law. Serena's husband, a furniture designer,
goes by David Linley for business purposes. He paid a visit to
Atlanta in November, showing off his exclusive work to Neiman
Marcus customers and guests at a luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've read that the name of the pilot of the Stealth fighter
downed in Yugoslavia hasn't been disclosed publicly. But wasn't his
name clearly pictured in news clips of the aircraft wreckage?
</P>
<P>
   A: As the Pentagon has explained, although an aircraft may have
one person's name painted on it, many other pilots also are able to
fly it. In other words, there are far more pilots and crew members
than there are aircraft. The name you saw wasn't the pilot involved
in this crash, said Pentagon spokesman Bryan Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I just returned from Hawaii, which is a five-hour flight from
Los Angeles. Since that is completely over water, with no reason
for a sonic boom to disturb anyone, is any airline likely to begin
using a Concorde on that route?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. The Concorde is operated only by British Airways and Air
France, the two airlines whose governments financed the development
of the supersonic aircraft. Several routes for regularly scheduled
flights have been attempted in the past _ Los Angeles to Honolulu
not among them _ but were abandoned because of a lack of sufficient
passenger loads to justify the high cost of the aircraft's
operation. The only routes with regular Concorde service are New
York-London and New York-Paris. Charter flights on any route are
possible if sponsors can sell enough seats, but other than that,
regular West Coast-Hawaii supersonic flights aren't in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A novel I'm reading talks extensively about Cheyenne
Mountain, a missile warning center in Colorado. What is this site
like, and is it possible for the public to visit?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Cheyenne Mountain complex was built between 1961 and 1966
in a hollowed-out mountain near Colorado Springs. It houses a
number of NORAD (North American Aerospace Defense Command)
operations centers in 15 steel buildings which are resting on large
steel shock absorbers to reduce the effects of potential nearby
warhead blasts. All early-warning attack systems would send their
warnings of missile attack threats to this complex so NORAD could
assess them.
</P>
<P>
   The complex is staffed by about 1,700 personnel of the U.S. and
Royal Canadian air forces. The facility can be shut off from the
world _ except for communications _ by shutting its 25-ton blast
doors, and it can remain self-sufficient for more than a month if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The Cheyenne Mountain Air Station holds public briefings at its
visitors center three times a week most of the year. Visitors
cannot go inside the mountain; the tour consists of a multimedia
presentation only. Requests to participate must be called in two
months before the desired briefing month: 719-474-2238 or 2239.
Online information is available at www.spacecom.af.mil/norad or you
can write to CMOC/J5P, 1 NORAD Road, Suite 101-215A, CMAS, CO
80914-6066.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the United States the only country supplying aircraft for
the NATO air campaign over Yugoslavia?
</P>
<P>
   A: The United States is supplying most, but not all, of the
aircraft in the campaign. According to a report by The Associated
Press, of the total number of NATO aircraft participating in the
missions as of last week, 687 were from the U.S. Air Force, Navy
and Marines. The U.S. has about 900 more aircraft in reserve, the
AP added. About 300 aircraft were from other NATO countries,
including Britain, France, Italy, Belgium, Canada, Luxembourg, the
Netherlands, Norway, Portugal and Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When I was young, in 1933 or '34, I saw a German dirigible. I
was told it was told it was the Graf Zeppelin. What can you tell me
about it?
</P>
<P>
   A: The LZ-127 Graf Zeppelin is considered the most successful
rigid airship ever built. While it was among the fastest rigid
airships ever flown, capable of reaching a maximum speed of about
80 miles an hour, it wasn't the longest. At 776 feet, it was about
28 feet shorter than another German airship, the Hindenburg.
</P>
<P>
   The Graf Zeppelin captured the imagination of the world when it
made a global trip financed in part by American newspaper publisher
William Randolph Hearst. He put up the money to keep the airship
flying in exchange for exclusive U.S. rights to a story about the
trip, which started at Friedrichshafen, Germany, and included
Lakehurst, N.J.; a return to Friedrichshafen; Tokyo; San Francisco;
Los Angeles; and Lakehurst again, where it ended.
</P>
<P>
   The Graf completed the trip in 12 days, 11 minutes, with a full
passenger load traveling in comfort and style. After it moored at
Lakehurst, Hugo Eckener, the airship's developer, was treated to a
tickertape parade in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1928 and 1937, when it was decommissioned, the Graf flew
590 flights totaling more than 1 million miles, including 144 ocean
crossings. During its nine years of service, it carried more than
13,000 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it legal to sell a 33-cent postage stamp for 40 cents?
</P>
<P>
   A: In a word, yes. To be sure you'll pay no more than face
value, buy your stamps from the U.S. Postal Service or a retail
outlet that has a formal consignment agreement with the Postal
Service not to impose any surcharge. ``There's nothing to preclude
any retailer or individual who has no formal agreement with the
Postal Service from charging whatever the market will bear,'' said
Postal Service spokesman Michael Miles. He cited selected
supermarkets as examples of outlets that have agreements not to
charge more than face value.
</P>
<P>
   End Take 1
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
