</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 2)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I have seen the racial makeup of inmates on death row. Can
you give me a breakdown by gender, age, and religion?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Justice Department says the NAACP Legal Defense and
Educational Fund tracks death row statistics. The group can provide
a partial answer to your question. Of the 3,565 people known by the
fund to be on death row nationally as of April 1, 3,515 (98.6
percent) were male, and 50 (1.4 percent) were female. No
information was available on the inmates' religious affiliation,
and the only age information showed that there were 65 juveniles
(no age parameters specified).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whatever happened to Dory Previn, former wife of conductor
Andre Previn? She was a songwriter for movies and a performer. The
last I heard, she was in a mental institution.
</P>
<P>
   A: The lyricist, singer and novelist, whose age is given
variously as 69 or 73, seems to have dropped out of public view.
She suffered a nervous breakdown and spent time in a mental
hospital after Andre Previn left her for actress Mia Farrow, with
whom he had twin boys more than a year and a half before the
Previns' divorce in 1969. In a 1993 interview with the Irish Times,
she said her illness was schizophrenia.
</P>
<P>
   After the divorce and her hospitalization, she took her revenge
about the affair between Farrow and her husband by writing and
recording songs such as ``Beware of Young Girls,'' which clearly
related to Farrow.
</P>
<P>
   Dory Previn retired from the music industry in the 1970s and
moved to Massachusetts with her new husband, artist and actor Joby
Baker. Her only public foray since came in 1997 when she and Andre
Previn were reunited professionally for a performance of ``The
Magic Number'' at Avery Fisher Hall in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have an update on the condition of Patrick Ireland,
the Columbine High School student who was shown on TV falling out
of a window into the arms of the SWAT team after being shot?
</P>
<P>
   A: He's participating in a full schedule of rehabilitation from
the brain injury treatment team at Craig Hospital in Englewood,
Colo., said hospital spokesman Kenny Hosack. Ireland was
transferred on April 27 to the facility, which cares exclusively
for patients with spinal cord and brain injuries, for
rehabilitation for multiple wounds, including gunshots to the brain
and a foot.
</P>
<P>
   He continues to make steady progress, and he and his family and
the staff at Craig are encouraged by his progress, the hospital
reported on May 19. He is getting more neurological return to his
right arm and leg, and he's beginning to be able to grasp with his
right hand. His right foot brace will come off in several more
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat is aware that therapy for the injury to his brain will be
long term, and he is up to the challenge,'' Hosack said. Ireland
will remain an inpatient at Craig until around the end of June,
then will return to his home and continue long-term therapy on an
outpatient basis.
</P>
<P>
   People wishing to send cards to Ireland and Sean Graves, another
wounded Columbine student at Craig, should mail them in care of
Craig Hospital, 3425 S. Clarkston St., Englewood, CO 80110.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm mystified about a tax deduction that just started showing
up on my paycheck. It's listed as FED/OASDI/DIS. Can you explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's no new tax. How a pay stub lists deductions is up to
the employer, said Patti Patterson of the Social Security
Administration. OASDI is Old Age Survivors and Disability
Insurance, and is another term for FICA (Federal Insurance
Contributions Act), she added. It could be that your pay stub
previously listed this as FICA.
</P>
<P>
   The OASDI tax rate for 1999 is 6.2 percent on earnings (up to a
cap of $72,600), plus 1.45 percent for Medicare (no earnings cap),
for a total rate of 7.65 percent, Patterson said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where does the expression ``The handwriting is on the wall''
come from?
</P>
<P>
   A: Often heard as a portent of doom, it's a variation of ``The
writing is on the wall.'' It was inspired by a passage in the Bible
(Daniel 5: 25-31). Belshazzar learned that he was about to lose his
kingdom when the words ``Mene, mene, tekel, upharsin'' appeared on
the wall of the palace. Translated from the Aramaic, they mean
``Numbered, numbered, weighed (and) divided.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the interpretation, from the New King James Version:
``God has numbered your kingdom, and finished it. You have been
weighed in the balances, and found wanting. Your kingdom has been
divided, and given to the Medes and Persians.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has there been any restitution by the U.S. government for the
survivors of the 1995 terrorist bombing of the federal building in
Oklahoma City?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Justice Department didn't state any specific amounts, but
said ``millions of dollars'' in federal funds have been used to
assist survivors and families of victims. Federal emergency funds
initially provided temporary housing for victims displaced by the
bombing, and loans for housing repairs and to assist small
businesses, said Justice spokeswoman Chris Watney.
</P>
<P>
   Under a separate program administered by the Oklahoma Crime
Victims Compensation Board, victims received reimbursement from
federal, state and donated funds for medical bills, counseling
expenses, lost wages and lost support, Watney added. And federal
terrorism funds enabled 341 survivors and family members to travel
to Denver to attend the trials of the bombing defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, for certain kinds of crimes, a defendants may
be ordered to pay restitution to their victims for losses suffered
by their crimes, Watney said. After his conviction, Terry Lynn
Nichols was ordered to pay $14.5 million for his part in the
Oklahoma City bombing. Although the restitution order has been
upheld on appeal, Nichols continues to challenge the validity of
this order.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A TV reporter said Fleet Week is one of New York's biggest
events. What is it, and where can I get information?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's New York City's annual salute to the armed forces, Fleet
Week '99, May 26-June 2, will include a series of military
demonstrations and a parade of ships, hosted by the Intrepid
Sea-Air-Space Museum. Vessels of the U.S. Atlantic Fleet, Coast
Guard, Royal Navy and Royal Canadian Navy will be in New York,
berthed at Piers 86 or 88 near USS Intrepid, a decommissioned
aircraft carrier, and at Naval Station Staten Island. Details are
available online at www.intrepid-museum.com/ or by calling
212-245-0072.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who made Eleanor Lambert's International Best-Dressed List
this year?
</P>
<P>
   A: There actually are two lists:
</P>
<P>
   Women: Aerin Lauder, Brooke Douglass de Ocampo, Eliza Reed,
Patricia Herrera and Princess Marie-Chantal of Greece, all
described by The New York Times as ``part of the so-called junior
social crowd''; Paris fashion muse Victoire de Castellane; Serena
Linley, a daughter-in-law of Princess Margaret; Marian McEvoy,
editor of Elle Decor; Jade Jagger, a daughter of Mick Jagger; and
actresses Uma Thurman, Cameron Diaz and Gwyneth Paltrow.
</P>
<P>
   Men: Prince Pierre d'Arenberg; Italian businessman Count
Ruffredo Gaetani; Phillips Hathaway of Sotheby's; Lord Hindlip of
Christie's; banker Thomas Kempner; Prince Michael of Kent; Kenneth
Chenault, head of American Express; Tony Duquette, decorator and
set designer; John F. Kennedy Jr.; rock singer Lenny Kravitz; and
actors Rupert Everett and Dylan McDermott.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article about Padre Pio, who was beatified on May 2 by
Pope John Paul II, said he had marks or wounds like Jesus. Can you
explain? Were they self-inflicted or were they real?
</P>
<P>
   A: There has been some disagreement on this point. Padre Pio, a
Capuchin monk who lived in seclusion in southern Italy and died in
1968 at age 81, is the first priest since St. Francis of Assisi in
the 13th century acknowledged by the Vatican to have borne
stigmata, the physical wounds of Jesus on the cross.
</P>
<P>
   A Vatican investigator in the 1920s concluded that Padre Pio was
a ``hysteric,'' implying that the wounds were self-inflicted,
possibly with acid. But the Vatican later accepted that they were
authentic. The wounds were said to have disappeared, leaving no
scars, the day before Padre Pio died.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic Online's entry on the priest states that on Sept. 20,
1918, Padre Pio was kneeling in front of a large crucifix when he
received the visible marks of the crucifixion. That item also says
the priest, born in 1887 as Francesco Forgione, experienced other
mystical phenomena, such as emitting a powerful floral scent and
having the ability to be in two places at once.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I get into the lottery to buy tickets for the 2000
Super Bowl in Atlanta? I neglected to save the information when it
was printed previously.
</P>
<P>
   A: You'll have to act fast. The NFL distributes about 500 pairs
of tickets to fans through a random drawing. Requests must be
received by June 1. Send your request, with name and address, by
certified or registered mail to: NFL Super Bowl Tickets, 280 Park
Ave., New York, NY 10017. The drawing will be held in October.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I get a schedule of the films to be shown on Turner
Classic Movies?
</P>
<P>
   A: On the Internet, visit www.TCM.turner.com for information and
film schedules, or order the Now Playing Guide by calling
1-800-826-1002 or writing Now Playing, P.O. Box 55826, Boulder, CO
80322-5826. The guides are issued monthly; subscriptions are $9.97
for one year, $19.94 for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard on Paul Harvey News that the Army is now recognizing
witchcraft as a religion. Is this true?
</P>
<P>
   A: A Texas newspaper originally reported on a congregation at
Fort Hood that calls its members Wiccans. Their belief, Wicca, is
derived from pre-Christian religion. Army spokeswoman Elaine
Kinellas said the Army respects the rights of all its members to
have access to worship in the manner they choose, and doesn't pass
judgment. So the Army indeed does recognize the wiccans, just as it
does other beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Very few people are involved. Kinellas said this congregation is
lumped into the ``other'' category of beliefs, which in total
represents less than 2 percent of all people in the military.
</P>
<P>
   End both takes.
</P>
