<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1605 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-THRIFTSHOPS27     05-26 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-THRIFTSHOPS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sensational bargains to be found in thrift stores
 &HT;    (EDS: Art available.)
 &HT;    By Christi Mays
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Admit it. The first thing you think about when you
see a great dress in the window of a department store is its price.
</P>
<P>
   You stride into the store and nonchalantly make your way to the
dress display. You touch the fabric, then pick up the item,
pretending to examine it from all angles, but you're really busily
scanning the garment for that little white price tag.
</P>
<P>
   You're dying to know how much the little number would set you
back, but don't care to be so obvious about checking the price,
especially with a sophisticated saleswoman hovering around you.
</P>
<P>
   She looks away. Here's your chance. You lift the tag only to see
multiple digits, too many to count, while your heart sinks. If you
didn't know better, you'd think the dress was made of gold threads
for what the store wants for it.
</P>
<P>
   There are wiser ways to spend your hard-earned money but still
look like a million bucks, experts say. Ever considered stopping by
that thrift store you pass by everyday on the way to work? It may
surprise you. For about the same amount of money you nearly paid
for one dress, it's possible to purchase an entire wardrobe, says
Lorraine Brooks, manger of Caritas Thrift Store in Waco.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can buy very fashionable merchandise at a very, very
reasonable price,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Roddy is living proof. On a recent trip to the thrift
shop, she found seven exquisite dresses and the total for all of
them was less than $55.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know your brands, you can come in here and find
beautiful clothes at low prices,'' she said, pointing to the most
expensive dress she was purchasing for $15. ``You go into
Dillard's, and you're going to pay at least $200 and something.''
</P>
<P>
   She said shopping thrifts saves her hundreds of dollars each
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful opportunity to use your money wisely, and we
have a lot of people who do that very thing,'' Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   Those little white tags that hang on clothing items are the main
reason people shop thrifts. It's easy to find nearly new, and in
some cases, brand new clothing, much of which is brand-name stuff _
like Calvin Klein jeans for less than $5 or a Guess sweatshirt for
$3.50.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can come in here with $100 and buy for a family of five
or six and even have shoes and socks,'' said Bettye Hicks, store
manager of a Salvation Army Thrift Store.
</P>
<P>
   People from all walks of life shop thrifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of people, who I'm sure have average or better
incomes, shop here because it's wise to shop at thrift stores,''
Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   There was a stigma for a long time that the people who shopped
at thrift stores were low-income, said Angela Abeles,
communications director for Goodwill Industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really not the case,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In an advertizing campaign, Gov. George Bush's wife, Laura, has
partnered with Goodwill in Austin to try to change the stigma
that's attached to people who shop at Goodwill, Abeles said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of customers who come in for the first time who
say, `I can't believe you have so much stuff in here and brand new
items' or `I can't believe I found this dress.' They're really
surprised at what we have to offer, and I think that's what brings
them back,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is thrift shopping helping to recycle clothing, another
reason to shop thrifts is that the money generated at most thrift
stores goes toward helping the community _ whether it be to find
food and shelter for the homeless, to counsel battered women or to
provide jobs and training for the poor and disabled.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the profits go to training and development of people who
are at the poverty level or can't read or have lost limbs or are
veterans,'' Abeles said of the purpose of Goodwill.
</P>
<P>
   There are some downsides to shopping thrifts, including the fact
that there is usually only one of each item available. But if you
find an item you just can't live without but it's two sizes too
big, it's usually inexpensive enough to buy the item and still have
money left over to get it altered.
</P>
<P>
   On the upside, shopping thrifts means lots of variety. And if
you go back to the same store a week later, or even the next day,
you'll see something different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoppers are able to find things on a day-to-day basis because
of so many donations that come in daily,'' Abeles said. ``It allows
us to continually put out and place items in the stores.''
</P>
<P>
   THRIFTY TIPS
</P>
<P>
   Here are some pointers for thrift shopping:
</P>
<P>
   _ Look for sale items. Stores, including Goodwill, have weekly
sales with merchandise up to 75 percent off. Some stores have
monthly half-off sales. Other stores have yearly yard sales. Some
stores also have sale racks and sale bins.
</P>
<P>
   _ Always inspect clothing thoroughly before purchasing it. Check
zippers, elastic and buttons. Look at the seams and hems. Always
look for stains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some stains are removable,'' said Bettye Hicks, store manager
of Salvation Army Thrift Store. ``If it's a good outfit and you
wanted it, I wouldn't let the stain deter me if I thought I could
get it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if you can't get the stain out, you're not out a
significant amount of money.
</P>
<P>
   _ Have a general idea of what you need and your sizes, Hicks
suggests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we're dealing in used clothes, sometimes the sizes
aren't in the clothes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shop, shop, shop. If you can't find that black skirt in your
size at one store, your may find the perfect skirt the following
week or in another thrift store.
</P>
<P>
   Christi Mays writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
