A1608 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKIN-PROTECTION27-COX     05-26 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKIN-PROTECTION27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Science/Health: Protecting skin from the sun
 &HT;    (EDS: Art available.)
 &HT;    By Christi Mays
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Soaking up the hot rays of the summer sun without
protection is like giving skin cancer an open invitation to form on
your skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are still thinking a tan is beautiful and the sun and
tanning beds are safe,'' said Dr. James Mason, a dermatologist. ``I
think older people are getting the picture when they see the bumps
and skin spots come up, but younger people feel like they're immune
to these types of problems and don't think about it until it's too
late.''
</P>
<P>
   According to surveys from Coppertone Solar Research Center,
about nine in 10 people say they are concerned about preventing
skin cancer and almost all consumers agree that sun exposure is a
major cause of skin cancer and premature aging of the skin.
However, only 36 percent of the population say they use sunscreens
more often than in the past. Only about half say they regularly use
a sunscreen with an SPF (sun protection factor) of 15 or higher and
a quarter say they use no sunscreen.
</P>
<P>
   Skin cancer is the most common of all cancers and one out of
every five people in the United States develops it during his or
her lifetime, according to the American Cancer Society.
</P>
<P>
   Skin cancer, bump, spot and wrinkle development differ with each
person, Mason said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amount of sun it takes to cause skin cancer is
cumulative,'' he said. ``Two hours here, 20 minutes there, 15
minutes there. It all adds up.''
</P>
<P>
   People with light complexions, fair hair and light-colored eyes
are more at risk for skin cancer. However, darker-skinned people
also can develop skin cancers, including malignant melanoma.
</P>
<P>
   Melanoma, the most dangerous type of skin cancer, can look like
moles with irregular coloration in shades of black, brown, white or
blue, and have ragged, uneven borders. If detected early, it can
often be treated successfully. If not treated, it can spread to
other organs and result in death.
</P>
<P>
   Non-melanoma skin cancers may look like pearly, flesh-colored
bumps or scaly bumps.
</P>
<P>
   Any change in a preexisting mole, birthmark or beauty mark is an
indication of skin cancer. Look for changes in color and increases
in size or thickness or texture.
</P>
<P>
   The American Cancer Society suggests conducting self-exams of
the skin every one to three months to check for suspicious-looking
moles or funny-shaped dark spots that increase in size. Any skin
problem should be checked out immediately with a dermatologist.
</P>
<P>
   Here are more tips on reducing the chances of getting skin
cancer:
</P>
<P>
   _ Wear protective clothing, like tightly woven shirts with long
sleeves, wide-brimmed hats or bonnets and sunglasses, Mason
suggested.
</P>
<P>
   _ Avoid spending too much time outdoors from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. _
the peak time of day when maximum sun damage occurs. If your shadow
is shorter than you are, you're more likely to sunburn.
</P>
<P>
   _ Look for sunscreen with a sun protection factor (SPF) of 15 or
higher. The higher the number, the longer the protection will last.
Look for waterproof and sweatproof sunscreens. For hassle-free
protection all day long, slather on sunscreen in the morning and
reapply using a new spray-on formula. To help make the chore fun
for kids there are new colored lotions that look purple, blue and
green but disappear when rubbed in.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coat children frequently with sunscreen and keep children
younger than six months out of direct sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wear sunscreen even if you're sitting in the shade. Even if
the sun is blocked from overhead, rays can reflect off water, sand
and concrete. You can also sunburn on an overcast day because up to
80 percent of the sun's rays can penetrate clouds. According to
Coppertone Solar Research Center, these rays can account for 80
percent of a lifetime exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Christi Mays writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
