<HEADLINE>
HOW TO MAKE HIDDEN FILES TRULY HIDDEN, AND WHY MONITOR CONVERGENCE
IS GOOD
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
c.1999 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I was wondering if you could tell me about the hidden
attribute for folders or files in Windows 98. It doesn't seem to
work on my computer.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when I right-click on a folder and go to
Properties, there are several check boxes that one can select, one
of which is called Hidden. However, when I checked it, the only
thing that changed was the way the folder looked. It was
translucent, but I could still see it. Is there any way that I can
prevent other people who use my computer from seeing certain
sensitive files or folders?
</P>
<P>
   A: There actually are two settings you must check in order to
make hidden files and folders truly hidden.
</P>
<P>
   The first is in the Properties dialog box for the file itself.
</P>
<P>
   This will result in that ``translucent'' icon you mentioned. But
then you also must tell Windows to hide the hidden files and
folder. While this may seem silly, there's a very good reason for
it.
</P>
<P>
   To completely hide hidden files and folders, open any folder.
Click on View, then Folder Options, then click the View tab. You'll
see a Hidden Files category _ under this, check Do Not Show Hidden
Files or Folders. Now, the things you want to remain unseen will be
invisible _ until someone changes that particular setting, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of hidden files and folders is to keep those who
don't know what they're doing from messing with sensitive
components. But there are times when you might want to see
something that is normally hidden _ when troubleshooting or
manually moving files around. That's why you have the ability to
turn off hidden files and folders.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently began having problems with my NEC monitor. I've
had it a long time, but I really like it, so I took it to be fixed.
The technician said all that needed to be done was to fine-tune
something called the convergence. I asked her what that meant, and
her answer was so full of gobbledy-gook that I don't know what she
actually said. Can you tell me what ``convergence'' is in a
monitor?
</P>
<P>
   A: Just as in a television set, a computer monitor works by
having a set of electron beam guns fire at a screen coated with
particles. When the electrons hit the screen, the chemicals glow.
Each gun is responsible for a specific color _ red, blue, green _
and when the colors come together, they form a realistic image.
</P>
<P>
   Convergence is when the beams all focus tightly on the same spot
on the screen. This is what produces a nice, crisp look on a
monitor. If you were having a problem with this _ called
misconvergence _ then the guns weren't lining up just right. Things
probably seemed out of focus, text had a rainbow-like aura and the
corners of the screen were fuzzy.
</P>
<P>
   The technician had to align the guns so they converged on the
screen at the same point. Modern monitors let you adjust this
yourself with onscreen controls.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Thanks for your review of Internet Explorer 5.0. I downloaded
it and really like it. I particularly like the Radio Bar, which
lets you play Internet radio stations. However, I have a problem.
When I launch the browser, the Radio Bar isn't there. I go to View,
Toolbars, then Radio, and it appears. But the next time I start
IE5, it's gone again! Is there any way to make it stay permanently?
</P>
<P>
   A: This is another one of those situations, similar to the
previous question, where there are two settings you must change to
get a single result.
</P>
<P>
   Look under Tools, Internet Options, then Advanced. In the
Multimedia area, there's a checkbox called Always Show Internet
Explorer Radio Bar. Click it, and the bar should stay visible.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect the Radio Bar was an afterthought for the Internet
Explorer 5 team, which may explain why it doesn't behave like all
the other toolbars in the browser.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Maybe Computing columnist
Dwight Silverman can help. Send e-mail to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call 713-220-2000 and enter
access code 1001.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
