<HEADLINE>
VIDEO CARD GAME GETTING COMPETITIVE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
c.1999 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For serious computer game players, there was only one type of
video card worth considering for 3-D graphics six months ago _ one
that used the Voodoo2 chip from 3Dfx Interactive.
</P>
<P>
   The cards built around Voodoo2, such as Diamond Multimedia's
Monster II or Creative Labs' 3D Blaster Voodoo2, were the fastest
around and provided a gorgeous look when using the OpenGL 3-D
graphics system, or 3Dfx's own Glide scheme.
</P>
<P>
   These were add-in cards, which supplemented but did not replace
a PC's standard graphics adapter. The complication of adding a
second graphics card into a finicky PC was worth the trouble to
intent gamers, who consider onscreen speed a sort of high-tech Holy
Grail.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that was then. This is now.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 3Dfx announced plans to merge with Richardson,
Texas-based STB Systems, which makes graphics cards. No longer
would 3Dfx simply supply its chips to other card makers. The
company changed its name to simply 3dfx (note the lower-case ``d'')
and began cranking out its own 2-D and 3-D cards with a new chipset
_ the Voodoo3.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, fans rejoiced.
</P>
<P>
   The Voodoo3 is faster _ much, much faster _ than the Voodoo2.
And, because it can handle standard Windows graphics as well as
3-D, it eliminates the hassle factor.
</P>
<P>
   But 3dfx's competitors weren't standing still. While it can be
argued that, for now, the Voodoo3 remains the fastest 3-D card out
there, it may not hold that claim for long. And, it may no longer
be the best 3-D game option.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DIFFERENT APPROACHES TO 3-D
</P>
<P>
   I tried out a Voodoo3 3000 card ($180), which is designed for
computers that have an AGP graphics slot. A less-powerful version,
for users who require a graphics card that fits in a PCI slot, is
available in the Voodoo3 2000 ($130).
</P>
<P>
   I also tried out a competitor's card, though unfortunately not a
retail version. Nvidia, another graphics chip company, supplied me
with a reference board built around its new Riva TNT2 chips.
Companies such as Diamond will be producing cards with these chips
_ the Diamond Viper V770 ($180) should be available soon, if it's
not already on store shelves.
</P>
<P>
   The two cards represent very different approaches to 3-D
graphics. The Voodoo3 doesn't do much to advance the now-classic
Voodoo ``look,'' focusing instead on raw speed. In fact, some
detractors have called it the ``Banshee2'' _ a reference to another
3dfx product that offered both 2-D and 3-D capabilities, but cut
back a bit on the latter.
</P>
<P>
   The TNT2 is almost as fast as the Voodoo3, but produces a much
prettier look. This is not to say that the Voodoo3 doesn't look
great _ it does _ but the TNT2 takes the graphical appearance to a
new level.
</P>
<P>
   And an even faster version of the TNT2, call the TNT2 Ultra,
also will be offered by card makers. I'll be looking at one soon.
</P>
<P>
   To test the look and playing speed of the cards, I used Q3ATest,
a preliminary version of the upcoming Quake III Arena from id
Software. Like the previous installments in the Quake series, it's
a first-person, hunt-it-down-and-kill-it game in 3-D, but the
emphasis in this version is on multiplayer death match, where
people play against each other on a network or over the Internet.
Its beautiful environments require a powerful 3-D graphics
accelerator, and it's tailor-made for either of these cards.
</P>
<P>
   I also tried them out with Quake II, as well as Microsoft's
Flight Simulator 98. All games and cards were used on a Dell
Dimension T500 PC, with a 500-megahertz Pentium III chip and 256
megabytes of memory.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SHORT OF NIRVANA
</P>
<P>
   The Voodoo3 3000 runs at a clock speed of 166 megahertz and has
16 megabytes of video memory. This allows it to display resolutions
of up to 2,045-by-1,536 pixels. However, the Voodoo3 is limited to
16-bit color rendering, or 65,000 colors. (Through some internal
conversions, 3dfx says the Voodoo3 actually has 22-bit color
capability).
</P>
<P>
   But, it cannot display 32-bit color, or 24 million colors,
considered the Nirvana of game display.
</P>
<P>
   The TNT2 card I tried had 32 megabytes of video memory and a
clock speed of 120 megahertz. (Be aware that the companies that
will actually sell this card likely will ratchet that speed up a
bit.) The TNT2 can display 32-bit color at resolutions up to
2,045-by-1,536, and does so beautifully.
</P>
<P>
   The Voodoo3 is incredibly fast _ in most of my tests, it nudged
out the TNT2 at resolutions of 1,024-by-768 and lower. At higher
resolutions, though, the TNT2 won because it has more video memory.
The Voodoo3 began to run sluggishly with Quake III Arena above
1,024-by-768, while the TNT2 didn't start bogging down until it got
to 1,600-by-1,200. Also, the TNT2's performance suffered very
little when running at 32-bit color.
</P>
<P>
   While the Voodoo3 is fast, its graphics just can't match the
richness of the TNT2 card. Note that this is only for those games
capable of 32-bit graphics. Quake III Arena is 32-bit enabled;
Quake II is not.
</P>
<P>
   But even with 16-bit games such as Quake II and Flight
Simulator, I still like the overall look of the Nvidia card better.
</P>
<P>
   How are these cards for 2-D? Both are blazing when working in a
Windows desktop, playing video and working with educational and
children's software. You couldn't lose either way.
</P>
<P>
   But if you are serious about 3-D games, there is a clear choice
here, and it's any card that uses Nvidia's TNT2 chips.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-21-99 1316EDT &QL;
</P>
