<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Swapping Motherboards Probably Makes Sense  
 By David Einstein   
 c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Question: &LR;  I currently have a Windows system with a 233 MHz
chip that I got about a year and a half ago. I've been doing some
upgrades since then. I increased my memory to 128 megabytes, added
a recordable CD-ROM drive, a larger hard drive and a faster modem.
Now I'd like to replace the chip with a 500 MHz Pentium III. But to
do that I'd have to replace the computer's motherboard. Is that
worth it, or should I just get a new computer?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  My friend, you are an ideal candidate for motherboard
replacement surgery. Everything else that matters already has been
upgraded, so adding a fast Pentium would give you a
state-of-the-art system. However, the chip you're considering is
expensive _ around $700. A motherboard will cost you anywhere from
$85 to $150, depending on the number of expansion slots and whether
it has on-board sound and video. So you're probably looking at a
minimum of around $800. And that's if you do the upgrade yourself
(considering all the other stuff you've added, it should be easy
for you). If you have someone else do it, add another $100 to the
total.
</P>
<P>
   Is it worth it? I'd say so, because a brand new 500 MHz Pentium
III computer (without a monitor) would probably run you at least
$1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Two Questions Answered
</P>
<P>
   Q: I would like to know if America Online is an Internet browser
or an Internet service provider or both. Also, how many browsers
are there on the market, and which one do you like best?
</P>
<P>
   A: Hey, that's two questions! But since I'm in a kindly mood,
I'll answer them both. AOL is an Internet service provider, and its
software has a built-in browser, which happens to be a customized
version of Microsoft's Internet Explorer 4.
</P>
<P>
   Right now there are just two industrial-strength browsers in the
market. One is IE, which now is into version 5, and the other is
Netscape Navigator, which comes as part of Netscape Communicator
(version 4.6 was just released). Both are free downloads
(www.microsoft.com/ie and www.netscape.com).
</P>
<P>
   There are two other alternatives worth mentioning. One is Opera,
a $35 browser offered by a Norwegian company
(www.operasoftware.com). The other, which is free, is an early
version of a new kind of streamlined browser by NeoPlanet, and you
can download it at www.neoplanet.com. In a brief test-drive, I
found it to be quite fast and elegant.
</P>
<P>
   Just the Fax
</P>
<P>
   Q: I need to use my computer to send faxes, but Windows 98
doesn't seem to have a fax program. That's odd, because I seem to
recall that both Windows 3.1 and Windows 95 had one. What's the
story? And is there a workaround for this problem?
</P>
<P>
   A: Here's the deal. Microsoft Fax is included on the Windows 98
CD, but it doesn't install automatically when you install Windows.
You can install it yourself, however, like this: Put your Windows
98 CD into the CD-ROM drive, choose the Browse This CD option and
click your way to tools/ oldwin95/message/us. Double-click wms.exe
to install Windows Messaging. Then double-click awfax.exe to
install the fax program. Now restart your computer, and then
double-click the Inbox icon on the desktop. This will launch a
wizard that will guide you through the process of setting up
Microsoft Fax.
</P>
<P>
   If you have Microsoft's Outlook 98, there's another option open
to you: You can download a free copy of WinFax Starter Edition from
Symantec. To get it, go to Add/Remove Programs in the Windows
Control Panel and double-click Outlook 98 in the list of available
programs. Click Add New Components and choose Install from Web.
Then follow the instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Now, why did Microsoft leave the fax software out of Windows 98?
It probably has to do with the company's relationship with
Symantec. If Windows 98 had built-in faxing, you wouldn't need the
Symantec program that's available for Outlook, would you?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; TIP OF THE WEEK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Backing up information on your hard drive used to be a pain, but
Windows 98's Backup utility makes it easy. Based on technology from
Seagate, the disk drive company, it lets you back up an entire disk
or just selected folders and files. And you can back them up to any
floppy, Zip or tape drive. You'll find the Backup utility by going
to Start/Programs/Accessories/System Tools.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
David Einstein is West Coast bureau chief of Forbes Digital Tool.
Got a question abouw Fwmputing? E-mail it to computers(AT
SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-19-99 2100EDT &QL;
</P>
