<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SENATE-INTERNET-FILTERING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE EYES LAW TO BLOCK CHILDREN'S ACCESS TO INTERNET SEX 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN   
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Type in the words ``teen jobs'' into an Internet
search engine and it will lead you to a list of sites about careers
_ and to sites that feature pictures of nude teenagers and graphic
sex acts, as was demonstrated Thursday at a Senate hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers on the Senate Commerce Committee also saw how easily
an Internet site advocating hatred of Jews could be pulled up by
simply putting in the name of a Chicago newspaper World Wide Web
site incorrectly.
</P>
<P>
   If the panel's chairman, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., and Sen.
Fritz Hollings, D-S.C., have their way, many schools and libraries
will be required to place Internet filters on their computers so
students cannot access Web sites dealing in sex, violence and
illegal drugs simply by typing in seemingly innocuous words like
``teen jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The senators are pushing legislation that would require those
schools and libraries receiving federal subsidies for Internet
service to block access to sites that each local school and library
deem inappropriate for children.
</P>
<P>
   More than 6,000 schools, 13,000 school districts and 5,000
libraries receiving federal Internet subsidies would come under the
law. Thousands more schools and libraries could be affected if they
seek and receive the federal subsidy.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also wants access banned to other sites that provide
detailed instructions on how to make bombs and drugs as well as to
a myriad of so-called ``hate'' sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neo-Nazi propaganda, images of burning crosses, racist
literature, religious bigotry, messages and images of unimaginable
hatred and cruelty are just one click away from our children's eyes
and mind,'' McCain told a committee hearing Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Howard P. Berkowitz, chairman of the Anti-Defamation League, an
organization that combats racism and prejudice, testified that the
search for the word ``Holocaust'' will yield serious historical
articles along with some ``hate'' sites.
</P>
<P>
   His organization has designed Internet filters that block access
to the hate messages but allow access to the historical material.
He said the anti-hate filtering software could be downloaded free
of charge from his group's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   While Berkowitz said he supported the thrust of McCain's bill,
he said he didn't think the courts would uphold the mandatory use
of filtering by schools and libraries.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the American Civil Liberties Union and the
National Education Association criticized the bill as too broad.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill would impose a one-size-fits-all federal solution on
communities throughout the country,'' said Barry Steinhardt,
associate director of the ACLU.
</P>
<P>
   He said parents and libraries should remain free to consider
other approaches to Internet safety, including parental supervision
of Internet use by minors.
</P>
<P>
   The Center For Democracy and Technology, an advocacy group
working to protect free speech on the Internet, points to
``kid-oriented'' search engines as another option. For example, if
a kid-oriented search engine, such as the one available at
www.edview.com, is used to search ``teen jobs,'' it will not pull
up any sex sites.
</P>
<P>
   McCain agreed that parental supervision is important but said
much of the time children spend on the Internet is spent outside
the home.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Nickerson, the chief executive officer of Seattle-based
N2H2, a maker of Internet filters, said many schools and public
libraries with computers already use filtering software.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that some libraries are opposed to filtering on First
Amendment grounds that it inhibits free speech.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would require libraries to put the software on
one computer but not all of them so adults have free access to
information.
</P>
<P>
   Nickerson said filtering software has dramatically improved
since it was first introduced a few years ago. Early filters would
block access to medical sites containing information about breast
cancer along with sex sites when the word ``breast'' was typed into
a search engine.
</P>
<P>
   Newer filters block access to specific World Wide Web sites.
Nickerson's firm has 75 people researching new sites to see what
type of information they contain so they can keep their Internet
filtering programs up-to-date.
</P>
<P>
   Nickerson admitted that many teenagers and technically-savvy
children could find ways to get around the filtering programs. He
argued that filters block access to sex and other Web sites that
are inadvertently accessed by the majority of children who are
simply trying to do homework assignments.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate approved the Internet filtering legislation last
year, but the House didn't consider the bill.
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at
jenniferhearstdc.com.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-20-99 1814EDT &QL;
</P>
