<HEADER>
A1655 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-BURGER-RECIPES1S     05-26 1615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BURGER-RECIPES1STTAKE27-C </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delicious ways to build a better burger
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why would anyone need a recipe for the original
cooking-by-instinct dish?'' writes Bobby Flay in his new cookbook,
``Boy Meets Grill'' (Hyperion, $32.50).
</P>
<P>
   We agree that burgers are so easy that for many, we've done our
job by simply reminding you to pick up some ground beef and
charcoal before the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But then, we always have something to add.
</P>
<P>
   Like pine nuts or feta cheese. Black olives or horseradish Dijon
mustard. How about stuffing those turkey burgers with a little Brie
cheese?
</P>
<P>
   Flay advises that quality ingredients and a little care in
cooking will make the difference between an OK burger and a
spectacular one.
</P>
<P>
   He uses fresh ground chuck because leaner meats aren't as tasty,
he said. And of course, there are alternatives to beef, like
turkey, lamb and tuna.
</P>
<P>
   Remember to preheat the grill, either allowing the charcoal to
heat for about 45 minutes or the gas grill for about 10 minutes.
Flay says high heat is best _ it will sear the burgers and seal in
the juices. He likes to cook with the grill covered _ though he
understands this can be as debatable as whether to use a gas or
charcoal grill.
</P>
<P>
   His other key advice is to flip the burgers only once _ moving
them more often will increase the chances of sticking and
crumbling.
</P>
<P>
   Some other things to keep in mind:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Form hamburgers with wet hands to avoid sticking.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Avoid flattening with a spatula. When pressed, flavorful
juices escape, leaving burgers dry.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  As another safeguard against sticking, oil the grill or oil
the food. Brush a light coating of cooking oil on the grate just
before placing foods on it. Flay prefers oiling food, though
burgers may not require it. Simply brush the meats lightly with
olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Remember the safest way to eat ground meats is well-done _
that's 160 degrees on a thermometer or until the juices run clear
and there's no pink in the middle of the burger.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, don't forget the condiments. Salsas, spreads, sauces
and relishes can take a great burger over the top.
</P>
<P>
   BEYOND THE BASIC BURGER
</P>
<P>
   We know that a loose ground beef patty sprinkled liberally with
salt and pepper, grilled and topped with a fresh slice of tomato
and a crispy lettuce leaf can hardly be improved upon. And of
course, ketchup, mustard and mayo will always be favorites. But
there is room for creativity. Here are some quick ideas for jazzing
up the basic burger:
</P>
<P>
   Mix-ins with ground meat:
</P>
<P>
   Italian sausage
</P>
<P>
   Salsa
</P>
<P>
   Chopped onions or peppers
</P>
<P>
   Shredded cheese, like Monterey Jack or mozzarella
</P>
<P>
   Crumbled cheeses, like blue and feta
</P>
<P>
   Tomato or vegetable juice
</P>
<P>
   Jalapenos
</P>
<P>
   Green olives
</P>
<P>
   Barbecue sauces
</P>
<P>
   Whole-kernel corn
</P>
<P>
   Bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   Cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   Fresh or dried herbs
</P>
<P>
   A splash of sherry
</P>
<P>
   A dash of Teriyaki sauce
</P>
<P>
   Toppers:
</P>
<P>
   Bacon
</P>
<P>
   Salsa
</P>
<P>
   Guacamole
</P>
<P>
   Sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Smoked cheeses, like Gouda
</P>
<P>
   Cucumbers
</P>
<P>
   Sprouts
</P>
<P>
   Thousand Island dressing
</P>
<P>
   Fried green tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Mango chutney
</P>
<P>
   Mushrooms, grilled or raw
</P>
<P>
   Basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   Beyond buns:
</P>
<P>
   Pita
</P>
<P>
   Sliced bread
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser rolls
</P>
<P>
   Submarine rolls
</P>
<P>
   Tortillas
</P>
<P>
   English muffins
</P>
<P>
   Flatbreads
</P>
<P>
   SAFE GRILLING
</P>
<P>
   We want your Memorial Day weekend to be memorable for all the
right reasons _ not because friends and family are struck with a
food-borne illness. So here's some important food safety
information to keep in mind:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cook hamburgers until they are well-done. The best way to
ensure this is to use an instant-read thermometer, which you can
purchase at the grocery store. Ground meats should reach at least
160 degrees. If you don't have a thermometer, juices should run
clear and there should be no pink in the center.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wash hands, surfaces, cutting boards and towels often in hot,
soapy water. Use separate cutting boards for meats and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Defrost and marinate meats in the refrigerator, not at room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use a separate platter for raw meats and cooked meats. That
means once the meat is cooked, put it on a clean platter, not the
one you used to bring the meat to the grill.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Store leftovers promptly _ within two hours. The sooner the
better. Reheat leftovers to 160 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Hamburgers With Double Cheddar Cheese, Grilled Vidalia Onions
and Horseradish Mustard
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10-15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 6-8 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This is Bobby Flay's favorite combination. The horseradish Dijon
shows how easy condiments can be. Flay likes to hollow out the buns
so he basically has crust.
</P>
<P>
   For the mustard:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely grated fresh horseradish, or prepared
horseradish, drained
</P>
<P>
   For the burgers:
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 pounds freshly ground chuck (slightly coarse grind)
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   For the onions:
</P>
<P>
   2 Vidalia onions, sliced crosswise 1/2 inch thick (do not
separate into rings)
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil for brushing
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   16 (1-ounce) slices Cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   8 hamburger buns
</P>
<P>
   8 leaves romaine lettuce
</P>
<P>
   8 1/4-inch-thick slices beefsteak tomato
</P>
<P>
   (2 tomatoes)
</P>
<P>
   For the mustard: In small bowl, mix mustard and horseradish.
Serve at room temperature. May be refrigerated up to 1 week.
</P>
<P>
   For the burgers: Divide chuck into eight 5-ounce burgers and
season on both sides with salt and pepper (handle as little as
possible and form the burgers loosely). Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   For the onions: Preheat a gas or charcoal grill to high. Brush
the onions with olive oil on both sides and season with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Grill onions and burgers. Cook onions 3 to 4 minutes on each
side. Cook burgers 3 to 4 minutes on each side for medium rare.
(Although not recommended for safety reasons.) During the last
minutes of cooking, top each burger with 2 slices of cheese, cover
the grill and let the cheese melt, about 1 minute. Split the buns
and toast on the grill, cut side down, until golden. Place a burger
in each bun and top with lettuce, onions, tomato and mustard
mixture. Arrange on a large platter.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (burger, onions and 1 tablespoon mustard): 701
calories, 52 grams protein, 44 grams fat (percent calories from
fat, 57), 24 grams carbohydrates, 174 milligrams cholesterol, 836
milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Incredible Burgers
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 33 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling and warming time: 1 hour, 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 58 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This recipe calls for old-fashioned slow cooking in a smoker and
some unusual mix-ins, like ginger ale. But our tester said the
burgers drew raves. He used JW Dundee's Honey Brown for the
steaming liquid. The recipe is courtesy of a new cookbook,
``Barbecue America: A Pilgrimage in Search of America's Best
Barbecue,'' by Rick Brown and Jack Bettridge (Time Life Books,
$24.95).
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds ground beef
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons minced red onion (save trimmings for smoker's
water tray)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon garlic salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon lemon pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon barbecue sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ginger ale
</P>
<P>
   16 ounces beer
</P>
<P>
   4 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1 cup apple cider
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, mix beef, red onion, garlic salt, lemon pepper,
barbecue sauce, egg and ginger ale. Form into 8 patties. Cover with
plastic wrap and refrigerate for 1 hour. Remove meat from
refrigerator and let it come to room temperature (about 20
minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Preheat smoker to 220 degrees. Pour beer and water into water
tray. Add cuttings and skins from onions to the water. Combine
apple cider, vinegar and olive oil in sprayer. Place burgers on
oiled grill. Cook burgers for about 50 minutes, spraying
occasionally with apple cider mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 288 calories, 25 grams protein, 17 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 54), 5 grams carbohydrates, 112
milligrams cholesterol, 367 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Pine Nut Burgers
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 12 minutes
</P>
<P>
   These Italian-style hamburgers are juicy, crunchy and yummy. We
served them on regular buns, but you can shape them like rockets
and stuff into long Italian hard rolls. They'll be most excellent
once the tomatoes, parsley and basil start coming in from the
backyard gardens.
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds lean ground beef
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 large cloves garlic, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Parmesan or Romano cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup pine nuts
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup finely chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   6 hard rolls or buns
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Lettuce leaves
</P>
<P>
   Thick tomato slices
</P>
<P>
   Whole basil leaves for garnish
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, mix ground beef, onion, garlic, bread crumbs,
cheese, pine nuts, parsley, eggs, salt and pepper. Form into 6
round or rocket-shaped patties about 1 1/2 inches thick.
</P>
<P>
   Grill over medium-high heat until browned and crisp, about 6
minutes on each side.
</P>
<P>
   Wipe rolls with oil, then tuck in burgers, lettuce and tomatoes.
Garnish with whole basil leaves. _ From: ``America Loves
Hamburger'' by Linda West Eckhardt (Wings Books, 1994)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 499 calories, 36 grams protein, 27 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 48), 28 grams carbohydrates, 198
milligrams cholesterol, 491 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
