<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BURGERS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Building a better burger, ideal for Memorial Day
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finally. Summer's here.
</P>
<P>
   Well, almost. Everyone knows Memorial Day weekend is the
unofficial start of summer and the summer grilling season.
</P>
<P>
   The lazy months ahead are sure to afford many opportunities for
showing off your grilling finesse. But this weekend, why not start
with the basics: burgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the mention of grilling and it's the first thing I think
of,'' Bobby Flay writes in his new cookbook, ``Boy Meets Grill''
(Hyperion, $32.50). ``There's absolutely nothing better than a
great burger on the grill, seared dark brown and dripping savory
juices, covered with melted cheese and grilled sweet onions.''
</P>
<P>
   Flay is the chef of two restaurants in New York, Mesa Grill and
Bolo, and the star of two Food Network television shows, ``Hot Off
the Grill'' and ``Grillin' and Chillin.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Flay was in Atlanta last week to promote the book, so we hit him
up for a few tips. Of course, it may seem a little funny to take
grilling advice from someone who grew up on the Upper East Side of
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   But Flay is quick to point out he spent many summers grilling
beachside in Sea Girt, N.J. There, he concedes, the food often
tasted like lighter fluid, like many home-grilled goods.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he's perfected his techniques, working in some of
New York's top restaurants and grilling at his weekend home on Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
   His book shows how to grill everything from steak to snapper.
But it begins with burgers and condiments, the most familiar and
accessible of all grilled foods.
</P>
<P>
   Flay's favorite is simply a patty of ground chuck liberally
sprinkled with salt and pepper and cooked ``until it's crusty,''
then blanketed with two slices of cheddar cheese. He likes to top
it with thick slices of grilled Vidalia onions and horseradish
mustard.
</P>
<P>
   But he offers more elaborate concoctions, such as a turkey
burger stuffed with brie and topped with slices of grilled green
apples _ so good the first time he made them, he ate three.
</P>
<P>
   We offer recipes for both inside this section, along with a few
others we came up with, such as a juicy pine-nut Parmesan burger
and rosemary oregano lamb burgers.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the ingredients, there are some techniques to keep in
mind. Flay isn't about to enter into the debate over gas grills vs.
charcoal grills. He uses gas because he likes to grill so
frequently, but he respects both.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what, Flay said it's important to get the grill hot
and to cook burgers over high heat. ``I don't know why people are
afraid of the heat. They act like if they get too close, they'll
commit a crime,'' said Flay.
</P>
<P>
   He encourages high heat and ``getting intimate'' with the grill
_ that is, getting to know its hot spots and cool spots. Burgers
often do well in the center of a grill for the hot and even heat.
</P>
<P>
   The next most common mistake, Flay said, is moving the food
around too much, which can cause it to stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think they are actually preventing sticking, but in
fact they are causing it,'' he said. ``About 98 percent of what I
cook on the grill, I only flip once.''
</P>
<P>
   Flay is experienced enough to know by touch when a burger is
done. If you don't want to cut into the burger to see if its
pinkness is gone, you can use an instant-read thermometer to assure
it has reached 160 degrees _ the temperature required to kill all
possible agents of food-borne illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Once the burgers are cooked and on the platter, they'll be most
at home surrounded by a number of condiments and toppings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to put lots of different relishes, condiments and
salsas out on a table and make a few suggestions, but basically let
the guests choose,'' said Flay.
</P>
<P>
   It's practically a foolproof plan for the first official long
weekend of sun and fun. After all, ``grilled hamburgers are one of
the greatest things in the world,'' Flay said.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
