<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yummy cake is just right for company
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Billie Sims of Sandy Springs (Ga.) requested a
recipe for a coconut cake using fresh coconut and sour cream, Dr.
Gail Dalton of Atlanta said the one her mother-in-law, Eileen
Dalton of Bassett, Va., has been making for more than 20 years came
to mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is fabulous and often use it for company. It needs
to be made two days prior to using, so you get all the work out of
the way early if you're having a dinner party. It freezes well and
you can keep the cake on hand for long periods of time, in case an
uninvited guest drops in.''
</P>
<P>
   She calls it Yummy Coconut Cake.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Yummy Coconut Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30-35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Refrigeration time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   For the cake:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup soft shortening (or 1/4 cup shortening and 1/4 cup
butter, softened)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups sifted all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   4 egg whites, stiffly beaten
</P>
<P>
   For the filling:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 (16-ounce) container sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1 (8-ounce) container Lite Cool Whip (thawed)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   3 cups grated fresh coconut
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease and flour two 9-inch round
cake pans. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   To make the cake: In a medium mixing bowl, cream together the
shortening (and butter, if using) and sugar. Add milk and vanilla.
In another bowl, sift together flour, baking powder and salt. Mix
flour mixture into shortening mixture alternately with beaten egg
whites. Pour into prepared pans. Bake 30 to 35 minutes. Remove from
oven and cool on racks about 15 minutes. Remove from pans and
continue to cool about 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare filling: In a large mixing bowl, combine
confectioners' sugar, sour cream, Cool Whip and vanilla. Mix well.
Stir in coconut.
</P>
<P>
   When cake has cooled, split layers horizontally into two layers
each. Spread filling between layers and on top and sides of cake.
Refrigerate about 1 hour. Remove from refrigerator, cover tightly
with plastic wrap, and freeze for 2 to 3 days.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to serve, remove from freezer and allow cake to sit
at room temperature for 10 minutes before slicing.
</P>
<P>
   Leftovers may be refrozen.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 547 calories, 6 grams protein, 27 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 44), 72 grams carbohydrates, 20
milligrams cholesterol, 294 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe requests
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jan Stittleburg of Lilburn misses Hellman's One Step dressing,
which is no longer available, and hopes for a recipe to help her
duplicate the potato salad she made with it. ``It was a mildly
tangy, mayonnaise-based salad. I'd add my own potatoes and some
celery and onions, and it was great. Do you have any recipes for a
similar potato salad? Any suggestions on the spices used would be
greatly appreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   Contacting the column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests for this column should be sent to Recipe
Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box
4689, Atlanta, GA, 30302. Include a daytime telephone number.
E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Where to write
</P>
<P>
   Send food news to Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. The
deadline is noon two Mondays before publication.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
