<HEADER>
A1660 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN     05-26 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duel of Atlanta's daring new India Pale Ales
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The familiar fish is hooked upright and hung smack in the middle
of the Atlanta skyline. It's a weird sight, an upstart brewery's
maritime logo side by side with the city's gleaming monuments to
power and progress.
</P>
<P>
   On the eye-catching yellow label you read, ``The Beer You've
Been Training For!'' The fish appears to be a red snapper, but
there is no question about the beer.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after three young Coloradans began boiling barley malt
in a warehouse off Fulton Industrial Boulevard, Sweetwater Brewing
Co. has brought forth what its followers have been waiting for _ a
West Coast-style India Pale Ale, hopped to the heavens and daring
Atlanta's other microbreweries to follow.
</P>
<P>
   India Pale Ales are the chic thing with microbreweries, the
chance to show what they can do with hops.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, another Atlanta microbrewery has debuted its own
IPA. Dogwood for some reason calls it Breakdown IPA, with a label
that brings to mind Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   Both are IPAs, and neither has much in common with the other.
Dogwood's, in fact, tastes more like an Extra Special Bitter, with
a malt profile that mutes the hops to the point of dignified
reserve.
</P>
<P>
   In a British-style IPA this wouldn't be surprising, except that
Dogwood's Crawford Moran calculates the beer has nearly 70
International Bitterness Units of hop _ twice what you'd find in a
London pint. Yet the Dogwood, at least on paper, is supposed to be
hoppier than the Sweetwater. You'd never know it.
</P>
<P>
   Sweetwater's Fredrick Bensch claims 57 IBUs, and you taste every
one of them. They're right up front. For the unaware, the label
gives fair warning. ``This mammoth IPA,'' it says, ``is defined by
generous quantities of premium hops.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoppy, for sure, but not mammoth. The two are not always the
same, and however much one welcomes this exuberant IPA from
Sweetwater, you wish there were more malt to back up all that
hoppiness. It's a beer that many hopheads are going to enjoy and
celebrate, but theirs is often a one-dimensional appreciation. What
they're looking for is the hop flavor, not the fuller satisfaction
of complexity.
</P>
<P>
   That's the difference between many American pale ales and IPAs
that give the hops free rein and a smaller number of domestics _
notable examples are some of the Rogue beers and Tuppers' Hop
Pocket Ale _ that give the beer a firm malt backbone. There's more
going on with these beers, and the palate detects it.
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds like criticism, it's more in the way of praise
with reservation. Until now, only a few of the city's brewpubs _
namely, Max Lager's, Percy's Fish House and U.S. Border Brewery &AMP;
Cantina _ were going all the way with hops. Its three
microbreweries played it safe. Then, last year, Dogwood
reformulated its pale ale, dry-hopping it with Cascades and giving
it more character.
</P>
<P>
   And now Sweetwater has raised the bar several notches higher.
Whatever its shortcomings, Sweetwater IPA is a breakthrough. It's
one thing for a brewpub to put a highly hopped beer on tap, knowing
it can be taken off in three months, and quite another for a
microbrewery to make the longer-term investment in storage,
packaging and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   But Sweetwater's done it. And, as usual, it's done so in its own
way. ``I went to Washington (state) and British Columbia last
year,'' head brewer Bensch says, ``and tried every IPA I could
find. I was looking for something different.'' In the end, he
returned to one he brewed when he was with Marin Brewing Co. in
California, an IPA that bucked the trend toward Cascade hops and
instead showcased East Kent Goldings.
</P>
<P>
   East Kents are a highly floral variety used in English ales but
not in concentrations like this. In an English ale their presence
is subtle. Put your nose to a pint of Sweetwater IPA and you think
you've put it into a magnolia at full bloom.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard not to like this unfiltered, dry-hopped beer, and you
can only applaud the ambition. Now, if Sweetwater can just firm up
that malt backbone.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, you wish Dogwood had been better able to
bring out the four varieties of Washington state hops in its nicely
malted Breakdown IPA. As it is, this isn't really an IPA.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing we weren't 100 percent satisfied with is the
dry-hopping,'' Moran says. ``The flavor and aroma will be more
present with this next batch (due out in late May or early June).''
</P>
<P>
   You hope that next batch also holds a head better than the
initial one. For whatever reason, the Breakdown IPAs I sampled left
neither a lace on the side of the glass nor a head that lasted for
even a minute. You wondered if it was the beer that had broken
down.
</P>
<P>
   PICK OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   A piece last month about Miller Lite's claim to be ``a true
pilsner'' elicited responses from some two dozen readers and one
from the Miller Brewing Co. Somehow there is a chasm of
misunderstanding as to what a pilsner is. I'll be happy to leave
this dispute to Miller's marketing folks and to those readers who
don't think Miller Lite is a pilsner any more than pandas are
bears.
</P>
<P>
   But in the weeks since, I've come upon an interesting _ and
quite enjoyable _ beer that describes itself simply as being in the
``pilsner style.'' In other words, it doesn't claim to be the
genuine article.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Scrimshaw, made by North Coast Brewing Co. in Mendocino
County, Calif., is better than most pilsners available in this
country _ and it's not even in the lager family. Scrimshaw (the
name refers to an American folk art of carving and engraving whale
ivory) is a cream ale, top-fermented like all ales but golden in
color and medium-light in body.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a crossover beer for us,'' says North Coast's Tom Allen.
The company is best known for its Red Seal Ale (available now in
Atlanta) and No. 38 Stout, a well-made Irish dry stout, but ``we
wanted to do a lighter-bodied beer that would appeal to a wider
range of people.''
</P>
<P>
   They call American mass-market lagers ``lawn mower beers,'' and
that's how I became acquainted with Scrimshaw. It's unfair to judge
any beer under circumstances that call for ice water or Gatorade _
my usual libation on the lawn _ but I knew this was a beer that
deserved better.
</P>
<P>
   Cream ales were once popular in the Northeast, and many
Americans recall the green 7-ounce bottles of Little Kings Cream
Ale, made in Cincinnati. In this century, cream ales have often
been blended with lagers, giving them a bit of crispness while
retaining their slightly sweet character.
</P>
<P>
   Scrimshaw is an ale all the way, although it uses traditional
lager hops, Tettnang and Hallertau, and has the easy drinkability
of a Munich Hellas. If anything, it's more in the softer Munich
style than in the drier pilsner style. At 20 IBUs, it's not hoppy,
but neither is it bland. It's a beer that seems to know exactly
what it's supposed to do, and does it without advertising hype and
without false pretense.
</P>
<P>
   There are some beers you wouldn't allow even on your lawn. This
is one you'd welcome into the house.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
