<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Free lunch? Maybe _ and lots more freebies
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you are one of those people who combs through newspapers and
magazines looking for ads and coupons offering free samples,
rebates, offers and sweepstakes _ you ain't seen nothing yet. If
you haven't discovered all the free stuff on the Internet, brace
yourself. It is not an exaggeration to say you could spend days,
weeks, months, maybe your whole life, surfing joyfully from one
site to another, filling out forms and e-mailing your vital
statistics to different sites, then sitting back and waiting for
the bounty to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Just on the food front, there are enough spices being offered to
last a lifetime. Enough coffee and tea to float a battleship.
Enough candy to keep dentists happy forever. There's pasta, rice,
beef jerky, couscous, sauces of all kinds, even ostrich meat _ all
free.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, nothing is ever really free. You should be aware that
when you give a company your e-mail address and other personal
information, you are providing them with a lot of valuable
demographic data that can be sold to marketers, researchers and
others that, for one thing, could result in a lot of unwanted
e-mail. Some of the sites will assure you that they don't do that,
but some don't. Then again, you may love all those e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   That said, all you have to do to propel yourself into the
freewheeling world of free stuff on the Net is to call up any
search engine, type in ``free stuff'' and hang on.
</P>
<P>
   Here is just a small taste of some of the free food sample sites
and general free sites that we found in just one foray.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Get a free sample of Heritage Fair Greens Seasoning at
www.heritagefare.com/hfguest.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Calling all ``Cybercajuns'' _ the All Cajun Food Co. at
www.allcajun.com/index.html will send you a sample of Bruci's Blend
Zydeco Seasoning, a Bon Manger cookbook and product brochures _ all
for the price of an e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nu-Salt Salt Substitute wants you to give their product a try
at www.nusalt.com/sample.html. Recipes, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Go to www.sannella.com/auntiebellums
</P>
<P>
   /FLChristop.html and sign up for free samples of Aunti Bellum
pralines.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Get free samples of Jelly Bellys in 40 flavors from blueberry
to watermelon at www.jellybelly.com/.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Samples of J.S. Bach classic chocolates can be had at
cgi.imall.com/stores/classicchocolates
</P>
<P>
   /classicchocolates.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For a sample of Los Mochis Fresh Dried Tomatoes see
www.tsi.com.mx/Mochis-Fresh-Dried/.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Want to give couscous a try ? The Royal Duchess Co. will send
you a 10-ounce sample of this Moroccan staple at
www.royalduchess.com
</P>
<P>
   /sample.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A sample of Stretch Island Fruit Leather, which is 100 percent
fruit, dried in a bar with no chemicals or preservatives, is sent
to the first 50 people who request it each day. See
stretch-island.com/.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  GENERAL FREE STUFF
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The coupon store: www.kcweb.com/fl/vpmain.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Totally free food stuff: www.TotallyFreeStuff.com/food/.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More free stuff:
</P>
<P>
   www.thefreesite.com/.
</P>
<P>
   VEGETABLE
</P>
<P>
   Stuffed Artichokes
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 50-60 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This is from a site where you can get free samples of a salt
substitute at www.nusalt
</P>
<P>
   .com/recipes/stuf.html.
</P>
<P>
   1 cup seasoned salt-free bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons finely chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons minced green pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 small garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon oregano, crushed
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon Nu-Salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   3 medium globe artichokes, stemmed, trimmed and washed
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, combine bread crumbs, onion, green pepper,
garlic, olive oil, oregano, Nu-Salt, pepper and water. Pull leaves
of artichokes down and fill each leaf with about 1 teaspoon
stuffing. Place artichokes in saucepan. Pour about 1 inch water
into saucepan. Bring to boil. Cover and simmer 45 to 55 minutes, or
until leaves pull out easily, basting occasionally. Add more water
if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 92 calories, 3 grams protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 48), 11 grams carbohydrates, trace cholesterol,
62 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
