<HEADER>
A1662 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-WEB-SPORTS-COX &LR;      05-26 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-WEB-SPORTS-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
A point-and-click away, live games, interviews and fan chats are
online 
By Guy Curtright  
c. 1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Waiting for the 11 p.m. TV news or the morning
newspaper for your sports scores is becoming as old-fashioned as
basketball shorts that don't cover the knees or a pullover,
double-knit baseball jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the Internet, instant scores and statistics are just a
click of the mouse away.
</P>
<P>
   All you need in addition to a computer is an Internet provider,
a browser and a little knowledge about the best Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Be sure to sign up for unlimited Internet access time. With the
NBA and NHL playoffs heating up and a long baseball season ahead,
you probably will be spending a lot of time in front of a computer
screen if you are a real sports fan.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the advent of cable and ESPN has there been such a
change in the way fans can follow sports. Call it the pre-Web and
post-Web eras.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, who would have dreamed that you could:
</P>
<P>
   _ Get up-to-the-minute statistics and play-by-play progress on
most pro games, plus plenty of college action.
</P>
<P>
   _ Listen to broadcasts of all major-league baseball games on a
computer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Instantly converse with other sports fans in all parts of the
world as you follow the action.
</P>
<P>
   What a treat it is to hear Georgia native Ernie Harwell, 81,
call a Detroit Tigers game in his final season at the mike while
you sit at home in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Broadcast.com, you no longer have to fiddle with a
radio dial trying to pick up a distant signal.
</P>
<P>
   To listen to pro and college broadcasts, you'll have to download
RealPlayer software. But it's free at www.real.com. Don't bother to
pay for the enhanced version, RealPlayer Plus.
</P>
<P>
   The games to be covered each day can be found at
www.broadcast.com or at sites for the individual leagues or
colleges. There is about a 90-second delay on the broadcasts, but
that's a small drawback.
</P>
<P>
   You also can ``watch'' a game live on your computer. Several
``virtual'' sites provide animated game action. To access the game
screens, you will need to download a free program called Shockwave
(www.macromedia.com
</P>
<P>
   /shockwave).
</P>
<P>
   CBS Sportsline offers Baseball Live
(www.cbs.sportsline.com/u/sports/mlb/1999/today). It gives a full
baseball field with animations of each pitch and hit. It offers
statistics on each player, and you can chat with other fans
watching the game.
</P>
<P>
   TotalCast is the name of another service
(www.totalbaseball.com). The graphics aren't as sharp as
Sportsline's, but it does show the location of every pitch in the
current at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Most baseball fans, however, probably would pass on the graphics
and stick with the updated scoreboards and in-progress box scores
on such sites www.majorleaguebaseball.com
</P>
<P>
   If you're a basketball fan, you won't be disappointed by NBA.com
(www.nba.com). Would you expect anything less than a slick,
new-millennium site from the NBA? Courtside Live provides running
statistics and play-by-play info on all playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's official Web site (www.nfl.com.) is as good as it
gets. If you really want to have fun with your PC, spend a fall
Sunday afternoon there.
</P>
<P>
   It has an always-changing NFL scoreboard, and you can follow any
game you want, play by play, with the statistics adjusted after
each play. If you play fantasy football, this site is a must. One
more click brings you to the virtual game. Again, statistis are
updated as you watch the ball move up and down the field. No, it's
not like being at the game, but it just might be better than
sitting in front of the TV listening to some NFL announcers.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every major college football program has its own Web
site, usually a subsection of the school's Web site. Don't sell
these sites short. Collegiate sports information departments have
embraced the Internet as well as any group.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet also offers the opportunity to ``chat'' with some
of your heroes. ESPN (www.espn.go.com) regularly offers fans a
chance to ask questions of sports figures. So do most of the league
sites. You can e-mail your favorite baseball star through the
Players Association site (www.bigleaguers.com).
</P>
<P>
   So, chat away as you follow all the playoff and baseball action.
Just think, the millennium isn't even here yet and it's already a
new age for sports fans.
</P>
<P>
   TOP WEB SITES FOR SPORTS FANS
</P>
<P>
   General sports information
</P>
<P>
   _ The Sporting News (www.sportingnews.com): Everything you want
to know about baseball, football, basketball and hockey, plus four
Dave Kindred columns per week.
</P>
<P>
   _ CNN/Sports Illustrated (www.cnnsi.com): Special online columns
from SI writers, plus a preview each Wednesday of that week's
magazine. Also live audio of CNN/SI, if it's not on your cable
system.
</P>
<P>
   _ ESPN (www.espn.go.com): This would be the top site if you
didn't have to pay for some of the best stuff _ like columns from
Peter Gammons and Chris Mortensen. Insider stuff costs $4.95 per
month.
</P>
<P>
   _ CBS Sportsline (www.cbs.sportsline.com): Good site for
real-time game updates of all pro and college sports, but again you
have to pay for the best columns.
</P>
<P>
   _ USA Today (www.usatoday.com/sports/): All the stories from the
print edition, plus updated stats and other information. Good
college site.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball
</P>
<P>
   _ Major Leagues (www.majorleaguebaseball.com): Link to live
radio broadcasts of National and American League games, as well as
team sites and notes. Regular player chats.
</P>
<P>
   _ Baseball America (www.baseballamerica.com): Outstanding
coverage of the minors, as well as best site for the June draft.
Minor-league stats and boxscores.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fastball (www.fastball.com): One of the oldest baseball sites
on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball
</P>
<P>
   _ NBA (www.nba.com): Up-to-the-second updates of each playoff
game, plus player chats and links to official team sites _
including the Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey
</P>
<P>
   _ NHL (www.nhl.com): Coverage of this year's Stanley Cup
playoffs, as well as plenty of history and bios on all the players.
The NHL Players Association also has a good site (www.nhlpa.com).
</P>
<P>
   Football
</P>
<P>
   _ NFL (www.nfl.com): Instant play by play of all games and
constantly updated stats make this site a must for NFL fans on
Sunday afternoons. Plus outstanding team sites and bio information.
</P>
<P>
   Other sports sites
</P>
<P>
   _ NASCAR (www.nascar.com): Official site of Winston Cup racing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Motorsports (www.goracing.com): Everything from Indy Cars to
the World of Outlaws.
</P>
<P>
   _ Golf (www.golfweb.com): Coverage of tour action, plus a search
engine to find any 18-hole course in U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Curtright writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
