<HEADER>
A1680 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-DOMAIN-NAME25-COX     05-26 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-DOMAIN-NAME25-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Registering domain name to get easier 
By Omar Gallaga  
c. 1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ My editor, Bob, got curious about domain names
the other day and went to the Web site of Network Solutions Inc.,
the company in charge of doling out Internet domain names. He did a
domain name search out of curiosity to see who owns
``www.bob.com.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft?'' he moaned. ``How the hell did they get to use my
name?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they used to have a piece of software called `Bob,'''
I told him. ``It wasn't all that successful.''
</P>
<P>
   For anyone who's ever coveted a particularly juicy domain name
(sorry, ``starwars.com'' and ``maytheforcebewithyou.com'' were
snagged, let's just say, a long time ago), there's good news afoot.
</P>
<P>
   The process of registering a domain name, which is simpler than
it used to be, is still not as effortless as it could be. But soon,
it will be a little easier and likely cheaper if a plan to include
more registrars and add new domain suffixes is successful.
</P>
<P>
   The new plan, administered by the government's nonprofit group,
The Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers, began its
first huge step recently by adding companies that can register
domain names for users and companies.
</P>
<P>
   Those five companies are the first step in taking domain
registration control away from Network Solutions, which has been
the sole assigner of domain names. Those new registrars, which
include America Online and Register.com, are just the beginning. An
additional 29 registrar companies are to be announced at the end of
June, and they are expected to include such heavy hitters as AT&AMP;T
and Verio.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the biggest obstacle is setup _ the five initial
companies are still testing their software and eliminating bugs
before going live.
</P>
<P>
   Sascha Mornell, a director of marketing at Register.com, said
the addition of new registrars will be similar to the deregulation
of the long-distance phone business, which, among other things, has
meant discounts and better service for customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competition always brings in better pricing, better service
and faster change,'' Mornell said. ``And right now, it's a
laborious process to get domain names registered. I think that's
about to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Mornell's company, based in New York, estimates the number of
domain names registered will grow from about 6 million currently to
100 million over the next three years. The growing number of domain
name owners means new services must make it easier to manage
domains and easier to register them.
</P>
<P>
   Competition will probably mean lower prices for registering a
domain. Currently it costs $70 to register a domain in addition to
what an Internet service provider charges to host the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   As more companies come online offering domain registration,
other issues will hopefully be addressed. Cybersquatting, the
practice of buying up domain names for the sole purpose of selling
them at an inflated price later, may be challenged with legislation
and new standards for registration.
</P>
<P>
   Domain name disputes _ when a copyright holder sues someone else
for using their company's name as a domain, for instance _ will be
addressed in the courts and a legal precedent will eventually be
set on who has the right to use a name.
</P>
<P>
   And the dwindling number of available ``.com'' and ``.org''
addresses is leading to the introduction of new suffixes including
``.info,'' ``.firm'' and ``.store.'' The addition of these may lead
to even more confusion in what is becoming an increasingly
convoluted World Wide Web, but the cure for that lies in better
search engine technology.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, in a booming Internet economy, it's still difficult
for most users to find information on the Internet. Search engine
technology must evolve dramatically and the way we navigate the
Web, which currently is less than intuitive, must also improve.
</P>
<P>
   Which is all to say that we can expect to see a lot more
``first-time-home-pages.org'' and ``obscure.companies.com'' finding
a home on the Web as the street signs of the Internet become easier
and cheaper to erect.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-23-99 1545EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
