NYT-05-26-99 1156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 11:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1673 &Cx1f; taf-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMALL-SHIP-VOYAGES-AR     05-26 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALL-SHIP-VOYAGES-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL SHIP CRUISES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special one-shot feature culled from The New
York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate is
not prohibitive _ contact New York Times Sales Executive DEBRA
WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 By EVERETT POTTER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    This summer, consider leaving the automobile at home and
exploring America from the deck of a windjammer, a paddlewheel
steamer or a barge.
 &HT;    From the mighty waters of the Mississippi to the Napa River in
California, all-American small ship cruises have become
increasingly popular ways to vacation. There are voyages on vintage
vessels like ``Victory Chimes,'' a 99-year-old retired working
schooner that sails on Maine's Penobscot Bay.
 &HT;    There are replicas, like the ``Queen of the West,'' a
paddlewheel steamer that plies the Columbia, Willamette and Snake
Rivers in Washington and Oregon.
 &HT;    There are also ships like ``Spirit of Discovery,'' modern
vessels built for exploration, that are used in California wine
country.
 &HT;    These cruises reward passengers with a sense of discovery and an
opportunity to see American history come alive. Whether the theme
is Cajun country, Mark Twain or Lewis &AMP; Clark, there's an essential
aspect of Americana that takes on fresh meaning to anyone who has
ever gone on a small ship cruise.
 &HT;    Small ships, in this case, mean vessels that accommodate
anywhere from 20 to 440 people. They're a far cry from the
2,000-plus passenger cruise ships that ply the Caribbean.
 &HT;    These cruises are quieter, slower and less hectic. Daily shore
excursions are a vital part of such trips. The cost depends upon
the boat, cabin size, cruise length and season, but such cruise
prices usually include all meals and entertainment, and many
include the cost of shore excursions as well. Here's a selection of
small ship cruises around the country.
 &HT;    Alaska Sightseeing Cruise West (4th &AMP; Battery Bldg., Suite 700,
Seattle, Wash. 98121; 206-441-8687; www.cruisewest.com) has
eight-day cruises on the Columbia and Snake Rivers in Washington
and Oregon.
 &HT;    Down in California, the same company offers four- and five-day
cruises through wine country, on the Napa and Sacramento Rivers.
This cruise line uses 54- to 102-passenger expedition-style
vessels, like ``Spirit of Glacier Bay,'' the same ones they use in
Alaska's Inside Passage in summertime. Running from September to
November, four-day wine country trips start at $595.
 &HT;    American West Steamboat Company (601 Union St., Suite 4343,
Seattle, Wash. 98101; 800-434-1232; www.columbiarivercruise.com)
has the ``Queen of the West,'' a 163-passenger paddlewheel steamer.
They offer four and seven-day cruises on the Columbia, Snake and
Willamette Rivers through the heart of Oregon and Washington.
 &HT;    The cruise follows the trail blazed by explorers Lewis &AMP; Clark
in the early 19th century, with such modern-day excursions as a
jet-boat ride into Hells Canyon. Running from February through
December, four-day cruises start at $645
 &HT;    Delta Queen Steamboat Company (1380 Port of New Orleans Place,
New Orleans, La. 70130; 800-543-1949; www.deltaqueen.com) offers
hundreds of departures on the Mississippi River, as well as the
Ohio, the St. Croix, the Illinois, the Kanawha, the Cumberland and
the Tennessee Rivers and the Intracoastal Waterway.
 &HT;    Offering what are arguably the most famous river trips in
America, the Delta Queen has three- to 14-night cruises aboard
three paddlewheel steamers: the 174-passenger ``Delta Queen,'' the
416-passenger ``Mississippi Queen'' and the 436-passenger
``American Queen.''
 &HT;    There are upwards of 24 different theme cruises each year,
ranging from ``Gardens of the River'' to ``Big Band'' cruises. The
ships run year-round and three-night cruises start at $660.
 &HT;    Maine Windjammer Association (P.O. Box 1144P, Blue Hill, Me.
04614; 800-807-WIND; www.sailmainecoast.com) is comprised of 13
traditional tall ships, including ``Victory Chimes,'' ``Grace
Bailey'' and ``Mary Day,'' that range in size from 64 to 132 feet
on deck. All of the ships are privately owned and operated. Each
windjammer carries between 20 and 44 passengers.
 &HT;    The fleet departs from the ports of Rockland, Rockport and
Camden, located in the mid-coast region of Maine, about two hours
north or Portland. They sail on three- to six-day cruises
throughout the islands of Penobscot Bay from May until October.
Rates start at $350 for three-day cruises.
 &HT;    RiverBarge Excursions (201 Opelousas Ave., New Orleans, La.
70114; 888-238-0125/www.riverbarge.com) has four- to 10-day trips
on a hotel barge, the ``River Explorer.''
 &HT;    The vessel is actually two interlocked oil barges, complete with
dining room, entertainment area and 99 staterooms. The
198-passenger vessel is pushed, not towed, on the Mississippi,
Ohio, Missouri and Cumberland Rivers, as well as the Intracoastal
Waterway and the Atchafalaya Basin.
 &HT;    There are theme cruises such as ``Cajuns and Creoles,'' which
travels through the Atchafalaya Basin and the lower Mississippi, as
well as ``America's Junction,'' along the Ohio River Valley.
Running year-round, four-day trips start at $740.
 &HT;     (Everett Potter is a New York-based free-lance writer.)  
 &HT;     c.1999 Everett Potter  
