<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY'S-JEWEL-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S DOING IN WEIMAR 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this special one-shot feature culled from The New
York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate is
not prohibitive _ contact New York Times Sales Executive DEBRA
WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
</P>
<P>
   TWO COLOR SLIDES are available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By EDMUND L. ANDREWS &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who imagines the former East Germany as grim, gray and
dominated by Stalinist architecture is in for a surprise in Weimar.
Even during the four decades of Communism, this small city in
Thuringia was protected as a cultural jewel.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Weimar's history as home to many of Germany's
greatest writers and composers, notably the poet Goethe, Communist
authorities took pains to preserve many of its stately homes and
historic flavor.
</P>
<P>
   And when the European Union named Weimar this year's cultural
capital, its ninth such designation but the first from a formerly
Communist country, the pace of restoration and renovation became
frantic.
</P>
<P>
   Financed in large part with money from western Germany, city
officials have lined up an extraordinary calendar of concerts, art
exhibits, theater and dance from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   They have also tried to weave together the three major
historical legacies that shaped this city. The first is Weimar's
golden era in the 18th and 19th centuries, encompassing the time
when Goethe wrote his epicdrama ''Faust,'' and others living and
writing in the city included the poet and dramatist Schiller, the
composers Liszt and J.S. Bach and Gropius, founder of the Bauhaus.
</P>
<P>
   The second, tragic legacy is that of Hitler and the Third Reich,
when Weimar was a way station for prisoners taken to Buchenwald,
about six miles outside the city.
</P>
<P>
   Buchenwald has been preserved as a memorial to victims of the
Holocaust since the late '50s and draws thousands of tourists every
year.
</P>
<P>
   The third legacy is Communism, which split Germany until the
Berlin wall fell in 1989. Like all of eastern Germany, this city
still struggles with the financial and cultural adjustment to a
capitalist system run largely by western Germans.
</P>
<P>
   Information on the year's festivities is available at
www.weimar1999.de; ticket orders: (49-3643)240024, fax (49-3643)
240025.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EVENTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The cultural calendar includes scores of programs devoted to
Goethe, whose 250th birthday is on Aug. 28, and all kinds of
interpretations of ''Faust.''
</P>
<P>
   One version directed by Janusz Wisniewski and performedby the
Dusseldorf Theater has been nicknamed the ''80-minute Faust.'' The
show has been described by its promoters as a jarring adaptation
set in a surreal time of the ''futuristic Middle Ages.''
</P>
<P>
   The production will take place June 17 to 20 at 8:30 p.m. at the
Kubus Theater in Goethe Park; $20.50 to $27.85, at 1.77 marks to
the dollar. '
</P>
<P>
   ''Urfaust, a Subjective Tragedy,'' by the Spanish writer
Fernando Pessoa and staged in German by the Theatre UBU from
Montreal, contrasts a modern angst-ridden Faust with one obsessed
by the search for meaning. At the Redoute, Ettersburger Strasse,
June 4 to 6 at 8 p.m.; tickets,$20.50 to $27.85.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the biggest concerts will take place on the days
surrounding Goethe's 250th birthday. In a program whose theme is
reconciliation, Zubin Mehta will conduct a joint performance of
Mahler's Second Symphony by the Israel Philharmonic Orchestra and
the Bavarian State Orchestra. Tickets for the open-air concert on
Aug. 28 at 8:15 p.m. at the Park Tiefurt, just east of town along
the Ilm River,are $20.50 to $75.70.
</P>
<P>
   The park will be the site of another outdoor concert on Aug. 30
at 8 p.m., when Kurt Masur will conduct the Jeunesses Musicales
World Orchestra in Beethoven's Concerto in D for Violin, as well as
Tchaikovsky's Second Symphony; $20.50 to $75.75.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHAT TO SEE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Weimar has a storybook cuteness reminiscent of Williamsburg in
its newly restored state. It is also a small city of only 62,000
inhabitants, and many historic sights are within easy walking
distance of each other. Many side streets are closed to most cars,
but travelers who find a hotel in town won't need to drive.
</P>
<P>
   The old market square, or Marktplatz, is surrounded by lovingly
restored buildings, including the Rathaus, or City Hall, and the
neo-classical Hotel Elephant, rebuilt in 1938, which has attracted
guests from Bach to Hitler. The interior has been renovated in the
Bauhaus style with Art Deco details.
</P>
<P>
   From there, visitors can stroll down winding cobblestone streets
to the cathedral at Herder Platz, the newly restored Deutsches
National Theater and the homes of Goethe, Schiller and Liszt.
</P>
<P>
   Goethe spent much of his professional life in his house and
garden at 1 Frauenplanweg, not only as a poet but also as a
part-time scientist and a regional government official.
</P>
<P>
   The large Baroque building, constructed in 1707-09, has been
meticulously preserved, complete with his large library and a
studyhousing the books he was reading at the time of his death.
Open 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. daily; admission, $4.50.
</P>
<P>
   Next to the Goethe House is the Goethe National Museum, which
features a new, permanent exhibit about Goethe and his time. It
includes manuscripts and letters; $4.50.
</P>
<P>
   Another key stop is the Stadt schloss Museum of contemporary art
at 1 Burgplatz. The museum, in a sprawling Baroque palace with a
courtyard big enough for open-air concerts, has attracted a broad
range of European art, from 16th-century paintings to contemporary
works, and will be the site of many of theart exhibits this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But the Stadtschloss is also appealing because of its character
and its idyllic location overlooking the wooded parkland of the Ilm
River. Open 10 a.m. to 6 p.m.; admission, $3.50.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the city is the reminder of a more recent, grimmer past.
At Buchenwald, the former concentration camp consists of two
separate sites: a massive memorial built by the East German
government and the remnants of the camp itself.
</P>
<P>
   The entrance to the camp is through an iron gate that bears the
chilling inscription, ''Everyone Gets What He Deserves.'' Though
much of the camp was razed and is now open fields, the preserved
buildings include some of the prison cells, a disinfection chamber
and the crematorium. Admission is free. In the summer, hours are
9:45 a.m. to 6 p.m., Tuesday through Sunday. Visitors can pick up
Bus No. 6 in Goethe Platz downtown for Buchenwald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHERE TO STAY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Weimar has a few big hotels and many smaller ones; even the
cheapest places are clean and secure.
</P>
<P>
   The Hotel Villa Hentzel, 12 Bauhausstrasse, (49-3643) 86580, fax
(49-3643) 865819, is a comfortable old hotel in downtown that has
been nicely renovated and offers all the basic amenities at a low
price. Its 13 antiques-filled rooms come with cable television,
private baths and floor-to-ceiling windows. Double room with
breakfast, $85 to $107.
</P>
<P>
   Budget: Bargain hunters can find excellent deals at the small
pensions that have been converted from private homes. One of the
more upscale of these is the Pension Savina at 60 Meyerstrasse,
(49-3643)86690, fax (49-3643) 866911. Its 12 rooms have showers,
computer connections, mini-kitchen and cable TV. And there is a
sauna and solarium. Doubles: $78, including breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Luxury: The city's most famous establishment is the 102-room
Hotel Elephant, 19 Markt, (49-3643)8020, fax (49-3643) 802610, now
part of the Kempinski chain. Situated on the central market square,
it was constructed as a government building in 1542 and converted
to a hotel in 1741, with Bauhaus and Art Deco interior. Doubles:
$175 to $220.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHERE TO EAT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Weimar has many small cafes and restaurants, and guides say that
the Residenz Cafe, looking out overthe Ilm at 4 Grunemarkt, is the
oldest cafe in Germany. Today it is a gathering spot with a vaguely
bohemian feel that draws many of the actors and workers from nearby
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   The Scharfe Ecke, 2 Eisfeld, (49-3643) 202430, is one of several
small homey restaurants in the historic section. It serves
Thuringian specialties like the meat-filled dumplings known as
klossen and the spicy Thuringian bratwurst. The walls are decorated
with kitschy German paintings, the ambiance is old-fashioned, the
waiters are friendly to children. Meal for two with wine: $30.
</P>
<P>
   At the Felsenkeller, 37 Humboldstrasse, (49-3643) 850366, the
beer comes from its own microbrewery. It accompanies good
Thuringian cuisine in a wonderful location just a few steps from
the Nietzsche House on a quiet street of meticulously renovated
houses. Picture windows in the back look out onto the woods.
</P>
<P>
   The Felsenkeller offers a range of German meat and fish dishes,
as well as Thuringian specialties such as bierfleisch, pork
marinated in beer and served like goulash. Dinner for two with wine
is about $34.
</P>
<P>
   One of the city's best lunchtime bargains is the ACC Galleria
Cafe next to the Stadtschloss Museum, 1 Burgplatz, (49-3643)
851161. At this little cafe, the chef's daily specials are the best
bet. What the menu lacks in choice it makes up for in creativity
and price. Though the cooking tends toward French, recent specials
included a vegetable paella and an apricot chicken curry. The price
is $6.25 a person, with drinks extra. Open 11 a.m. to 5 p.m. only.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ---- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Edmund L. Andrews is the European economic correspondent for
The Times, based in Frankfurt.)
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Edmund L. Andrews &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
