<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ICE-CREAM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-END ICE CREAMS GET EVEN MORE GOURMET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sales of super-premium ice creams _ those gourmet ice creams
with more fat and calories and, usually, higher prices than regular
ice creams _ jumped more than 10 percent in 1998, according to the
Grocery Manufacturers of America. And it seems that more companies
are going for the freezer.
</P>
<P>
   One of the latest is Godiva. The heretofore maker of gourmet
chocolates and coffees has joined up with Dreyer's (makers of
Edy's) and is selling what they call ``ultra-premium'' ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   As best as we can tell, ``ultra-premium'' ice cream isn't
nutritionally different from ``super-premium'' ice cream. A 4-ounce
serving of Haagen-Dazs chocolate contains 270 calories and 18 grams
of fat. An equal serving of Godiva Belgian Dark Chocolate has 280
calories and 17 grams of fat. When you're dealing with numbers that
high, 10 calories and a gram of fat aren't going to make a big
difference.
</P>
<P>
   At $3.19 for a 12.5-ounce carton, Godiva's Ultra Premium ice
cream costs slightly more than Haagen-Dazs or Ben and Jerry's,
which come in 16-ounce containers for about the same price.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to taste, Godiva's flavors are rich and deep and
there was just the right amount of raspberry swirled through the
Chocolate Raspberry Truffle flavor. As for texture, Godiva is much
like Edy's. Other flavors include Ivory Chocolate Chip, Chocolate
Hazelnut Praline, Pecan Caramel Truffle and White Chocolate
Raspberry.
</P>
<P>
   Also new to the market is Jeremy's MicroBatch Ice Creams. This
upstart company was created by Jeremy Kraus, who as a student at
the University of Pennsylvania in 1997, decided the beer industry's
microbrew process should be applied to ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy's produces super-premium ice creams in limited edition
flavors such as Fuzzy Navel, Classic S'mores, Chocolate Overload,
Coffee Extravaganza and Cinnamon Bun. According to press materials,
flavors will be discontinued on a rotating basis. After sampling
the Coffee Extravaganza _ a bittersweet coffee ice cream with
chocolate swirls and chunks of brownies _ we decided that by
changing flavors, Jeremy had a good gimmick that would bring us
back again and again.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy's sells for $3.29 a pint, on par with Ben and Jerry's and
Haagen Dazs. And each carton is printed with a phrase parents will
find irresistible: ``P.S. A portion of all proceeds goes to pay off
my college loans and other worthy causes.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the International Ice Cream Association, which is
part of the International Dairy Products Association in Washington,
D.C., these are the top ice-cream flavors:
</P>
<P>
   1. Vanilla
</P>
<P>
   2. Nut flavors _ all combined including butter pecan, maple
almond, etc.
</P>
<P>
   3. Chocolate
</P>
<P>
   4. Fruit flavors such as peach, strawberry, black cherry
</P>
<P>
   5. Neopolitan
</P>
<P>
   6. Candy mix-in flavors including toffee crunch, caramel swirls,
etc.
</P>
<P>
   7. Cookies and cream
</P>
<P>
   8. Chocolate chip
</P>
<P>
   9. Mint chocolate chip
</P>
<P>
   10. Vanilla and chocolate combined
</P>
<P>
   11. Fudge marble
</P>
<P>
   12. Cookie flavors such as cookie dough
</P>
<P>
   13. Coffee and mocha flavors
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect coffee and mocha to be at the bottom of the list
for long. It's the fastest-growing category, according to the
association.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 1216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
