<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1722 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRILLED-VEGGIES-ART-H     05-26 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRILLED-VEGGIES-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN AMERICAN TRADITION FOR VEGETARIAN TASTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Photos available on the Wieck database.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To get up to speed on the hottest trend in grilling, stay away
from the meat section. Everything you need is in produce.
</P>
<P>
   Grilled vegetables, more popular in other parts of the world
than in this country, are fast becoming mainstream fare in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it the portobellification of the American diet,'' said
Steven Raichlen, author of ``The Barbecue! Bible'' (Workman
Publishing, 1998). ``There are more and more vegetarians in this
country, especially if you look at Generation X. They don't need
convincing. They're believers already.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, vegetables possess an enormous range of flavors and
textures. In many ways they are more interesting than meat.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be a vegetarian to enjoy grilled vegetables,
their skins slightly charred, grate marks making a picturesque
pattern across their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   More people are using their backyard barbecue to prepare
vegetables for a most basic reason: The grill is probably the best
and easiest way to cook them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The high dry heat of a grill has a way of caramelizing the
sugars in a vegetable and making it as sweet as possible,''
Raichlen explained. ``Take a red bell pepper, for example. The
flavors you get when it's grilled are extraordinary. Also, there's
a tradition for this at country fairs, but if you've never tasted
corn roasted on a grill, you don't know what you're missing.''
</P>
<P>
   Raichlen recommends stripping the husk back on an ear of corn,
similar to how you would peel a banana. The husk will act like a
handle, giving you something to grip. Then brush the ear with
either olive oil or melted butter before placing it on the grill.
In minutes the kernels will start crackling as they turn a
beautiful brown.
</P>
<P>
   Yono Purnomo, chef-owner of Yono's and Bumpers in Albany, N.Y.,
also is an advocate of grilling vegetables. He likes to baste
peppers, eggplant or asparagus with teriyaki or balsamic vinegar
(or a combination) along with a bit of olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no better way to cook them. This is a way to really
appreciate the vegetable,'' Purnomo said. ``You taste both the
texture and the flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no reason to invest in a special thin-screened grate to
place on your grill when cooking vegetables, according to Raichlen.
Simply cut peppers and zucchini and other vegetables thickly so
they don't slip through the grill's normal grate. If you are
grilling smaller vegetables, such as okra, or produce that tends to
break up, like onion, use a bamboo skewer, preferably one presoaked
in water.
</P>
<P>
   Also, not every vegetable works well on the grill. Firm, dense
root vegetables, such as potatoes or rutabagas, are best prepared
by other methods. If you insist on putting them on the grill,
Raichlen recommends par-boiling them first in order to cook them
thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   When grilling vegetables, be cool in the face of the heat. Don't
be quick to turn the veggies; they need some visible browning, if
not blackening, to bring out all their flavors.
</P>
<P>
   ``To truly profit from the caramelization process,'' Raichlen
explained, ``you need some browning. You can always scrape off
charred skin if it gets too burnt.''
</P>
<P>
   A tangy marinade will give most vegetables a piquant flavor,
though it isn't necessary to soak them for very long. We have
included the recipe for a personal favorite, mint marinade, that
takes advantage of the fresh mint now available. Save a quarter cup
of the marinade to splash on your favorite vegetables after you
have grilled them to perfection.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINEAN GRILLED EGGPLANT
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 6)
</P>
<P>
   3 small (4 to 6 ounces each) Italian eggplants
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried oregano or 1 teaspoon dried basil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sweet or hot paprika
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon hot red pepper flakes, (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper, to taste Heat the grill to
high.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the eggplants in half lengthwise; do not trim off the stem
ends. Mix the garlic and oil in a small bowl. Brush the mixture
over the cut sides of the eggplants. Combine the herbs and spices
in a small bowl and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to cook, arrange the eggplants, cut sides down, on
the hot grate and grill until nicely browned, 3 to 4 minutes.
Lightly brush the skin sides of the eggplants with the oil mixture.
Turn the eggplants with tongs and brush the top with the remaining
oil. Sprinkle with the dried herb mixture and salt and black pepper
to taste. Continue cooking the eggplants, cut sides up, until the
flesh is soft, 6 to 8 minutes more. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   OKRA, TOKYO-STYLE
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 4)
</P>
<P>
   1 pound fresh okra (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Asian (dark) sesame oil or extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Heat the grill to high.
</P>
<P>
   Trim the tips off the stems of the okra, but do not cut into the
pods. This would expose the insides to air, making the okra slimy.
Lay 4 or 5 okra side by side in a neat row at the end of a cutting
board. Stick a bamboo skewer through each end of each piece. The
idea is to hold them flat for grilling. Transfer the skewered okra
to a platter. Lightly brush both sides with sesame oil (or olive
oil, for a Mediterranean touch) and season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to cook, arrange the okra on the hot grate and grill,
turning with a flat spatula, until tender and lightly browned, 4 to
5 minutes per side (8 to 10 minutes in all). Serve the okra at
once, letting everyone remove their own skewers.
</P>
<P>
   Note: When buying okra, choose smallish pods of uniform size.
They should be about the length and width of your forefinger. Look
for crispy, springy, bright green pods, avoiding okra that look
brown or shriveled.
</P>
<P>
   GRILLED TOMATOES, CENTRAL ASIA-STYLE
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 4)
</P>
<P>
   8 fresh, ripe tomatoes or plum tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh dill Heat the grill to high.
</P>
<P>
   Thread the tomatoes on the skewers, brush with oil, and season
with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to cook, place the skewers on the hot grate and grill
the tomatoes, turning as necessary, until the skins are charred and
blistered and the flesh inside is hot and soft, 8 to 12 minutes in
all. Ease the tomatoes off the skewers with a fork, then sprinkle
the tomatoes with dill and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The above recipes are from Steven Raichlen's ``The Barbecue!
Bible'' (Workman Publishing, 1998)
</P>
<P>
   MARINADE
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 3/4 cup)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup red-wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons chopped fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons dried basil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Combine the olive oil, red-wine vinegar, white wine, mint,
basil, oregano and salt and pepper in a bowl and whisk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
