<HEADLINE>
STUDY SHOWS SMOKING BANS DON'T HURT RESTAURANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Predictions that tourists would abandon cities
and states that banned smoking in restaurants haven't come true,
according to a study published Wednesday by a leading tobacco
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton A. Glantz, a professor of medicine at the University of
California at San Francisco, and colleague Annemarie Charlesworth,
looked at hotel revenues and tourism rates in three states and six
cities that had non-smoking ordinances for at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   Their study, published in the Journal of the American Medical
Association, found no cases in which hotel receipts dipped. Tourism
and hotel revenue actually rose in most places, the researchers
found. That contrasts with predictions by the tobacco industry and
its allies in the restaurant industry, which had said tourism would
drop after smoking was banned or restricted.
</P>
<P>
   California has outlawed smoking in restaurants since 1995 and in
bars since the beginning of 1998. As of March 1, 134 communities
had restaurant smoking bans on the books, according to Americans
for Non-Smokers' Rights. Maine recently passed a ban on smoking in
restaurants, and similar laws are being considered in Honolulu and
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   A previous study of restaurant receipts by Glantz and others
also found that restaurants did as well or better after smoking was
banned.
</P>
<P>
   Since that study, Glantz said smoking ban opponents shifted
their arguments to claim that tourism _ especially among Asians and
Europeans _ would fall since those visitors would not be able to
smoke in restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The authors also looked at international tourism in New York,
San Francisco and Utah and found that more Japanese travelers went
to California and more Europeans went to New York City after
smoking was restricted. They found no significant change in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Besides California and New York City, the authors looked at
hotel revenues in Utah and Vermont and in Boulder, Colo.; Flagstaff
and Mesa in Arizona; and Los Angeles and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Humber, president of the Virginia-based National Smokers
Alliance, an industry-funded group in Virginia, said he doubted the
validity of the study since Glantz is such a well-known
anti-tobacco activist.
</P>
<P>
   He also said looking at aggregate tax receipts for hotels may
not give a true picture of the effects of the anti-smoking laws
since the country is in the midst of an economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is impossible to say what has actually occurred,'' Humber
said. ``It could be simply that there are diminished profits that
would have grown at a faster pace or greater rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Glantz said he compared the rate of increase in tourism in the
locations studied against national norms and found no difference.
He also said his study is credible because it was based on data
collected by agencies like state and city taxing authorities and
the U.S. Department of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went out and collected objective data from people with no
interest in the outcome,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Harrington, co-owner of Harrington's Bar and Grill in
San Francisco, said Glantz's assertion that smoking bans don't hurt
business simply isn't true.
</P>
<P>
   At her tavern, which serves many tourists, she said traffic
dropped 10 percent after the ban took effect. Six months later,
when the restaurant added an outdoor patio where smoking was legal,
the number of customers surged, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My position is that individual business that put their life
blood into their businesses have been hurt by this (ban), and I
know because I know these people, and it makes me angry,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
