A1747 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-POP27-COX     05-26 0228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-POP27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An interpretation of old folk blues _ as only Moby can do
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Give Moby this: He's unpredictable. After helping to spearhead
the electronica revolution in the early '90s with such indelible
dance singles as ``Go,'' this controversial vegan Christian mix
master has veered off in seemingly a hundred directions.
</P>
<P>
   On 1996's ``Animal Rights,'' he switched off the keyboards and
plugged in the guitars for an abrasive attempt at hard-core punk.
The next year, he released ``I Like to Score,'' a fusion of hip-hop
rhythms and movie themes. He's even dabbled in ambient symphonies
under the pseudonym Voodoo Child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Play'' is Moby's blues album. Several tracks, including
``Honey'' and ``Find My Baby,'' set early 20th-century folk-blues
tunes to cutting-edge dance beats. It's an effective fusion,
exposing the killer grooves in those scratchy old records while
imbuing the synthetic instrumentation with a welcome dose of
humanity.
</P>
<P>
   If only Moby had explored this idea more. Many of the album's 18
tracks are standard-issue electronica, such as the inert
``Porcelain,'' which saps the soul out of the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Play''
</P>
<P>
   Moby. V2 Records. 18 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Doug Hamilton
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
