<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Thursday,
May 27. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News Desk
at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE: Students in Oak Park High School's building trades class
are working on site instead of the classic ``shop class;'' they've
built a four-bedroom house from the ground up and have placed it on
the market for $135,000. Jennifer Taylor. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   WAGE: The lowest salary percentage increase in years _ a measly
1 percent _ is on the table for faculty and staff throughout the
University of Missouri system during the curators meeting Thursday.
The low increase comes after several years of good increases, but
some professors and administrators worry that if such tiny
increases continue, the University of Missouri could slip even
further in salaries in comparison to other public research
universities. Right now, it's about halfway down the scale. A
1-percent increase could hamper recruiting efforts for good
professors. Lynn Franey. Graphics.
</P>
<P>
   OWEN: Following the investigation into the death of Owen Hart.
We'll check police, MAST and coroner's office for any comments and
records. Also checking with WWF for any comments or decisions on
dangerous stunts. Christine Vendel. 12.
</P>
<P>
   BOAT _ Open boarding on the Kansas City area casino boats begin
what could be a slow process of approval, probably going into
effect in September or October. Missouri Gaming Commission meets
Wednesday (today) in St. Louis to consider that issue plus General
Assembly '99 rules changes, including electronic tokens, stiff new
penalties for underaged gamblers and sweepstakes regs. Rick Alm.
</P>
<P>
   FORD (business) _ Ford officials unveil a new product line at
their Claycomo, Mo., assembly plant. With more details on jobs and
the product. By Randolph Heaster. Photo
</P>
<P>
   PAY (business) _ Payless Cashways Inc. could be opening its
first new store in a few years. tentative. Jennifer Mann
</P>
<P>
   STAFF _ So, Michael Eisner ``earned'' $575 million last year. I
suppose he did it alone? And is anyone surprised that companies are
having trouble retaining top executives who have all the money they
could ever need. At Work column. By Diane Stafford.
</P>
</TEXT>
