A1752 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-MINIS27-COX     05-26 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of recently released CD's
 &HT;    By Richard L. Eldredge, Sonia Murray and Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ``Party Doll and Other Favorites''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Chapin Carpenter. Columbia. 17 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, this collection, which features live and rare tracks from
Mary Chapin Carpenter's 10-year recording career, is a reminder of
how daring a vocalist she once was. Carpenter's slide, which began
in 1994 with the patchy ``Stones in the Road,'' shows no signs of
stopping with ``Party Doll.'' The album is a cheat. The
singer-songwriter's last studio project was released three years
ago. Two new tracks and a mixture of hits, soundtrack tunes and
tribute album was all she could come up with this time? Only the
older material, such as ``He Thinks He'll Keep Her,'' pushes the
envelope. The best that can be said about ``Almost Home?'' the
paint-by-numbers new single, is that it's a toe-tapper. Carpenter
used to be able to engage our hearts and brains as well.
</P>
<P>
   _ Richard L. Eldredge
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  R&AMP;B
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Blaque''
</P>
<P>
   Blaque. Track Masters/Columbia. 14 tracks. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   You'll be going boom baby, boom baby, boom. And I'll be going
ooh baby, ooh baby, ooh. Uh-huh. Lyrically, things don't get much
better than the chorus to ``808,'' Blaque's current No. 7 R&AMP;B
single. But the Atlanta trio's debut is a more enjoyable album than
those inane words imply. These proteges of Lisa ``Left-Eye'' Lopes
offer simple, often love-struck pleasures that are smartly
produced. And if there's any similarity between the group Lopes is
in (TLC) and the group Lopes is behind, it's that both acts seem
like independent women who'd be fun to hang out with. Other than
that, Blaque is a more urban group that pops when it unexpectedly
segues into '60s doo-wop on ``I Do,'' seems just as comfortable
covering Cindy Lauper's ``Time After Time'' and is actually quite
affecting when it's merely going boom baby, boom.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Different Kind of Love''
</P>
<P>
   C Note. Epic. 12 tracks. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   C Note is a toothsome foursome of Orlando schoolgirl bait whose
distinguishing characteristic is the Latino heritage of
three-fourths of its members. With the recent success of Ricky
Martin and other Latin-tinged popsters, the timing couldn't be
better. Most of the music here is standard-issue R&AMP;B lite, but the
slight tropical flavor is more than welcome. ``Spanish Fly'' is
miles ahead of the other tracks in almost every way, and, not
coincidentally, it has a very pronounced Latin groove. The vocal
arrangements are overwrought, to put it mildly, and the
individuals' solo turns can make Whitney Houston seem restrained.
It seems that C Note and its handlers felt a need to prove that the
quartet can carry a tune. They forgot that you can carry a tune too
far.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
