<HEADER>
A1757 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-RYAN27-COX     05-26 0218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RYAN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beach invasion is riveting in `Ryan'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   The terrifying, 24-minute assault on Omaha Beach at the start is
so amazing, the sequence almost overshadows the rest of Steven
Spielberg's WWII epic. It shouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   This tale of a squadron of soldiers sent behind enemy lines to
rescue one soldier achieves cumulative power through indelible
moments: The sight of a guy picking up his own severed arm. A
terrified French schoolgirl crying in the rain. Sudden death in a
damp green field. A hand-to-hand fight climaxing in the slow,
perversely intimate slide of a knife into a struggling chest. These
are vignettes from a nightmare world.
</P>
<P>
   If only Spielberg had extended the same unsentimental rigor to
the entire movie: ``Ryan'' suffers from the cheesy wraparound
device of having the aged Private Ryan visiting the memorials to
slain soldiers. The second-hand sentiment is only underscored by
John Williams' cliched military music.
</P>
<P>
   The strong cast includes Tom Hanks, Tom Sizemore, Giovanni
Ribisi, Jeremy Davies and Matt Damon. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
