u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-PIES-BOS &LR;      05-26 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-PIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIE TOSSERS FIND THAT QUEBEC HAS HAD ITS FILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Quebec has had a bellyful of ``pie terrorists,'' and
is starting to hurl criminal charges at the political pastry
throwers who, in recent months, have gotten in the faces of many
prominent figures.
</P>
<P>
   The crackdown on the ``Entartistes,'' as the cream pie
anarchists call themselves, is winning high praise from news
columnists and others who usually delight in taking aim at the high
and mighty _ but who say the pie throwers are far more pompous than
the politicians they harass.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are nothing more than out-of-control aggressors who are
to democracy what germs are to public health,'' stated Pierre
Bourgault, a political commentator for Journal de Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   The pie tossers, part of a loosely-bound international group
based in Belgium, have lately been hyperactive in Quebec, mounting
attacks with cunning and precision. Their hapless targets are
almost always creamed at public events where television cameras and
photographers are sure to record the humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   The Entartistes _ roughly translated, pie-ers _ released a hit
list this month with Quebec-born pop singer Celine Dion and
Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien holding top spots.
</P>
<P>
   But now the targets are striking back.
</P>
<P>
   Stephane Dion, Canada's minister for intergovernmental affairs _
and no relation to the singer _ took a pair of pies in the face two
weeks ago, whapped while handing out slices of cake to homeless
people at a Montreal soup kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Unamused, Dion filed criminal complaints against his assailants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my duty as a citizen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Far from being hooted as a humorless stiff, Dion's response is
winning huzzahs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the pie is supposed to be a joke, but these pie
throwers are really bullies, and not funny at all,'' said Christine
Fortin, a volunteer at the soup kitchen. ``An event that was
supposed to raise money to help the poor was instead ruined.''
</P>
<P>
   Police are expected to bring charges against two Quebec
followers of Noel Godin, the 52-year-old Belgian anarchist who for
nearly three decades has organized pie attacks against politicians,
business leaders, artists, and celebrities. Godin's most recent
victim was Bill Gates, the billionaire chairman of Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In Quebec, pie anarchists have ambushed a dozen or so prominent
people in recent months, ranging from Montreal's mayor, Pierre
Bourque, to Anglo-rights crusader William Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   In Dion's case, the pie throwers issued a press release accusing
him of ``making political capital on the backs of the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   That seems a harsh assessment of the former University of
Montreal professor who regularly spends weekends doing volunteer
work, but Quebec's pie throwers are much given to strident
rhetoric, and refuse to make apologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take full responsibility for our gesture, we don't see it
as a criminal act at all,'' a spokesman for the movement,
identifying himself only as Pop Tarte, told Montreal newspapers.
``The pie has always been linked to humorous, nonviolent protest.''
</P>
<P>
   But Quebec police say a pie in the face is no joke _ it's
assault under the criminal code.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take complaints seriously, investigate, and issue charges
where appropriate,'' said a spokeswoman for the Montreal Urban
Police.
</P>
<P>
   A 19-year-old pie hurler named Bruno Caron made Canadian legal
history this week when he appeared in court in Montreal _ wearing a
red rubber nose _ and pleaded not guilty to a charge of assault
with a pastry. It is the first time anyone has been charged with
assault in Canada for a pie attack.
</P>
<P>
   Caron is accused of pushing a cream-filled pastry shell into the
kisser of former Quebec premier Jacques Parizeau earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Parizeau, in turn, became the first politician in Canada so
enraged by the attack he filed a formal criminal complaint, winning
wide support from callers to radio talk shows and other Quebecers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The case highlights a new trend,'' wrote news analyst Philip
Authier in the Montreal Gazette. ``It may no longer be politically
correct to throw pies at politicians in Quebec.''
</P>
<P>
   Quebec's pie throwers are believed to be the only active cell in
North America of the Brussels-based Internationale des
Anarcho-patisseurs, or International Pie Anarchists, which also
claims to have ``nonviolent terrorists'' plotting whipped cream
havoc in Britain, Switzerland, and France.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a burlesque terrorism,'' founder Godin recently told the
Sunday Telegraph, a London newspaper. ``We do not wound our
victims, they are only wounded in their self-love.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
