<HEADER>
A1816 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-PIPES-ART-BOS &LR;      05-26 1364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-PIPES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME, PIPES STARTS WITH THE PERSONAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Richard Pipes's new book, ``Freedom and
Property,'' marks a twofold departure for the Harvard historian. A
study of the connection between political liberty and private
ownership, it devotes only one of its five sections to Russian
history, the field in which Pipes has earned a reputation as one of
the West's foremost authorities on the Kremlin. And for all that
``Freedom and Property'' is a work of vast scholarship and daunting
erudition, it has its roots in deeply felt personal experience.
</P>
<P>
   Freedom carries a special meaning for him. Pipes, 75, came of
age in one of the century's darkest times and places, the interwar
years in (itals)Mitteleuropa,(unitals) where his family ran afoul
of both Soviet and Nazi oppression.
</P>
<P>
   Two uncles lived in the Soviet Union, and one of them perished
in Stalin's purges. Growing up in Poland, Pipes and his parents did
not feel the touch of totalitarianism until the late '30s. Pipes
heard Hitler's speeches over the radio and saw its effects on
Polish anti-Semitism (``horrible,'' he says).
</P>
<P>
   Surviving the German bombardment of Warsaw, he and his parents
used forged passports to flee the occupation. Guards stopped the
family at the Austrian-Italian border: The documents lacked Gestapo
authorization. After a considerable delay, the refugees were told
they could proceed _ on condition they not return to German soil.
``We said OK,'' Pipes says, with a laugh that's long and heartfelt.
</P>
<P>
   Ten months later, they reached the United States. ``It was so
stable,'' he says. ``I remember reading an advertisement in Life
magazine for some insurance company: `Unforeseen events should not
affect the course of a man's life.' I remember thinking, `These
people are living in the 19th century!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Two decades would pass before Pipes fully felt at home amid that
stability, and how it finally came to pass suggests why property,
as well as freedom, carries a special meaning for him. Pipes and
his wife, Irene, bought a summer house, in New Hampshire, in 1960.
``All of a sudden I established this connection to the soil,'' he
recalls, ``and I've had wonderful years familiarizing myself with
the trees and the wildflowers.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a rare private glimpse behind the thick public hide Pipes
has grown over many decades of often-fierce scholarly combat.
``He's fundamentally changed the way people view Russia,'' says S.
Frederick Starr, chairman of the Central Asia-Caucasus Institute of
Johns Hopkins University's Nitze School of Advanced International
Studies. ``I don't think there's anybody, left or right, who
doesn't take him seriously,'' adds Robert Conquest, the author of
``The Great Terror'' and a senior research fellow at Stanford
University's Hoover Institution.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there are few scholars, especially on the left, Pipes has
not tangled with at one time or another. ``He has plunged into the
middle of some ferocious debates,'' says Starr, a friend and
sometime antagonist. ``He is intellectually rugged. . . . He has
taken his share of hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Pipes has given as good as he's gotten. ``In general, almost
everything that has been written in the field (of Soviet history)
since the '60s has been quite wrong,'' he matter-of-factly
declares. It's a characteristic statement, demonstrating his talent
for bluntness and taste for sweeping dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   Pipes has never disguised his scorn for revisionism in his
field, with its comparatively benign interpretations of Soviet aims
and actions. At the same time, he does not shrink from taking on
more conservative colleagues. Just last month, The New Republic
published Pipes's bruising review of the University of California
at Berkeley's Martin Malia and his new book, ``Russia Under Western
Eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   The image Pipes presents in person is hard to square with a
history of intellectual bellicosity. True, he has the heavyset
bearing of an old fighter, but his sad, pouchy eyes have a faraway
look. Instead of a growl, one hears a melodiously inflected English
of indeterminate origin. As a youth, Pipes's interests were
aesthetic and he wanted to become a musician or art historian.
Instead, he collects art, particularly prints by the Japanese
artist Hiroshige.
</P>
<P>
   Pipes describes himself as a ``conservative anarchist'' (``a
conservative because I have great respect for tradition, . . . an
anarchist because I don't like anyone telling me what to think'').
It's an ideological combination that long ago made him a party of
one _ a formidable party of one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't that I want to be controversial,'' Pipes says. ``I
don't want just to be attacked, but it happens that I very often
am. I tremendously value my intellectual independence and being
able to say what I want, which made life very difficult for me when
I was in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Pipes went down there twice: to work as a consultant for the
Central Intelligence Agency at the end of the Ford administration,
and to serve as director of East European and Soviet affairs for
the National Security Council during the first two years of the
Reagan administration. His government service substantially raised
both Pipes's profile and his controversy quotient.
</P>
<P>
   For the CIA, he headed an outside group, known as ``Team B,''
brought in to analyze Soviet strategic objectives. Its hard-line
findings helped lay the foundation for Washington's eventual
abandonment of the policy of cooperation with the Soviets known as
detente. Working on the NSC, he helped guide the US response to
such events as the declaration of martial law in Poland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never made history but I certainly played a part in
historical events,'' Pipes says. ``It was a great experience, and I
think I contributed something to destroying the Soviet regime.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a statement he makes with no small pride. Pipes never
concealed his intense enmity toward the Soviet Union, either in his
policy writings, such as ``Survival Is Not Enough'' (1984), or his
scholarly works. Indeed, the dedication of his magnum opus, ``The
Russian Revolution'' (1990), reads ``To the victims.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Soviet fully reciprocated Pipes's hostility. Pipes
was ``anathema under the old regime,'' notes Yevgeny Volk, a policy
analyst in the Moscow office of the Heritage Foundation, a
conservative US think tank. ``No quotes from Pipes in the media
were allowed _ just criticism of some of his sayings or him
personally as an `imperialist adept' and `antisovietchik.' '' The
Kremlin even published a book called ``Richard Pipes: Falsifier of
History.'' Starr recalls a visit to Pipes's office some years ago
and finding him showing off a stack of copies.
</P>
<P>
   It is Pipes who has had the last laugh. ``What people say now is
very common, `Oh, yes, he was right.' Now I do like to hear that,
but it doesn't matter to me since I knew I was right.''
</P>
<P>
   Pipes has held emeritus status at Harvard since 1996 but hasn't
visibly slowed down. ``The energy isn't quite what it was when I
was younger,'' he concedes, ``but I put in my five hours a day of
work.''
</P>
<P>
   He travels to Russia less than formerly. During the Gorbachev
era, Pipes would go twice a year. Now it's more like once every 18
months. He'll be in Moscow in July to lecture and doesn't expect to
be cheered by what he'll see.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now they are very open to all kinds of demagogic
appeals. The country will survive, it will muddle along, but I was
very hopeful in '91, '92, that they would take a more democratic
course. They're now at a crossroads. I don't think there's the
slightest chance Communism will come back . . . but it's entirely
possible that they'll go to some kind of authoritarian regime _ and
that would be consistent with their traditions. They like a strong
government. For very good historical reasons, Russians have never
been very good at spreading power laterally. Power there has always
been perpendicular.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
