<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUNT-DRAMA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK THEATER GOES UNDERGROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By   FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two women, MeMe and Catty, get on the subway. A
teenage boy approaches them, hawking candy bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cut the act, kid,'' Catty hisses. ``You'll probably just use
the money to buy drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   The other passengers start to take notice. A scruffy-bearded
rider throws his head back and laughs.
</P>
<P>
   MeMe gives the kid a dollar, asks him his name, tells him hers.
The boy huffs, ``Just because you give me a dollar doesn't mean I
have to get in a conversation,'' but then stops and blurts out,
``Oh, my God! You're my mother!''
</P>
<P>
   What?
</P>
<P>
   ``And you,'' he turns to Catty. ``You must be my Aunt Catty, the
ex-prostitute!''
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, the passengers overhear, MeMe turned her love-child
over to her own mother, who sold him on the black market _ just as
she had sold Catty, MeMe's sister, to a brothel.
</P>
<P>
   Hugs and commotion all around over the reunion.
</P>
<P>
   As the three exit, a young man rises from his seat and announces
to the passengers, ``You've been watching Episode 8 of `Subway
Soaps,' '' and hands out fliers telling them how to find out what
happens next.
</P>
<P>
   The stunt-drama is the creation of CeCe Pleasants, 23, and Katie
Massa, 25, aspiring actress-comedians who frequent the downtown
comedy-club circuit by night and work temp jobs at a bank by day.
</P>
<P>
   Their show goes on every Wednesday night at 8, along the Number
1 subway line, starting at West 86th Street, down to Canal Street,
and back to 86th again. Each episode lasts about three minutes _
the duration of two subway stops. Then the actors rush to the next
car and perform it all over again before a different audience, all
together seven times downtown, seven times up.
</P>
<P>
   It's something that could probably happen only in New York,
where real-life melodramas take place on the subway every day, and
where thousands of young actors are looking for any kind of job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to figure out a new venue for our sketches,''
Pleasants says afterwards. ``We figured why not the subway.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To stage a fight, a reunion, an engagement on the New York
City subway _ it's a regular dream come true,'' Massa adds.
</P>
<P>
   There are 14,883 members of Actors Equity, the professional
performance-artist's union, in New York City. Andy Valvano, who
works at Backstage, the weekly newspaper that advertises auditions,
figures there must be at least another 30,000 aspiring actors
outside Equity.
</P>
<P>
   Even for the average Equity member, the median income from
acting last year amounted to $6,278. For non-Equity performers, the
situation could only be worse. ``It's an ugly scene out there,''
Valvano sighs.
</P>
<P>
   So where are Pleasants and Massa hoping to go with ``Subway
Soaps''? Do they pray for some bigtime agent to ride the train one
Wednesday night, spot their genius, and make them famous?
</P>
<P>
   They laugh uproariously at the notion. ``It would be enough to
get out of having to do temp work,'' says Pleasants, who commutes
to Manhattan from a basement apartment in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want a cult following,'' adds Massa, who lives in a
matchbox-size studio in Chelsea. ``An HBO special wouldn't be bad,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Their guest-stars in this episode are friends from the same
world of dreamers. The son is played by Max Lance, a 14-year-old
stand-up comic who regularly takes the commuter train in from
Westport, Conn., to perform at comedy clubs. The leafleteer is
Danny Cohen, another regular of the downtown clubs who also played
a mad doctor in an earlier ``Soaps'' episode.
</P>
<P>
   The shows on this Wednesday night go well. Several passengers
just sit there, reading their book or newspaper, as if nothing
unusual were going on. Others watch, entranced or bemused.
</P>
<P>
   A well-dressed passenger who insists his name is William Gates
turns to the stranger sitting next to him and comments, ``The
script needs a little work, but the enthusiasm is there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I did the same thing with an improv company in Brooklyn 20
years ago,'' says one woman who does not give her name.
</P>
<P>
   Others are less sure it's a show. Cadmen Garcia, a social worker
on her way home, gets upset when Catty tells the teenage boy to get
lost. ``You treat a boy like that?'' she screams. ``Don't worry,''
she assures him, pulling a dollar bill out of her wallet. ``Not
everybody's like her.''
</P>
<P>
   In another car, a bearded man with a yarmulke berates the boy.
``You shouldn't sell things on the subway, it's against the law!''
he yells. ``Stop bothering people, OK?''
</P>
<P>
   In still another car, the passengers look at each other
obliquely, some whispering to their neighbors, ``Whaddaya think,
it's an act? It's a skit?''
</P>
<P>
   When Cohen stands up with the leaflets and says, ``You've been
watching Episode 8,'' they all sigh and laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very clever,'' says one woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, this is New York,'' returns another.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
