<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1819 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PICNIC.SIDE-SFCHRON &LR;      05-26 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PICNIC.SIDE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: These sidebars about food safety and kitchen 
 gadgets that are helpful outdoors are moving as part of a 
 three-take package. The main story, PICNIC, offers ideas for 
 picnics in four settings _ city, country, trailside and 
 seashore. PICNIC2 contains recipes for each setting.  
   
   
 A FEW TIPS FOR KEEPING PICNIC FOOD SAFE  
   
   
 By Kim Severson  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _ To enjoy a picnic, it pays to learn a little
science. &HT;    Understanding the relationship among bacteria, temperature and
time can keep a picnic from turning into a medical emergency, says
Linda Harris, a microbiologist in the food science and technology
department at the University of California at Davis.
 &HT;    Pathogens like listeria and E. coli grow best at body
temperature, or about 96 degrees. They hate environments under 45
degrees and above 160, but they thrive and multiply quickly at
anything between.
 &HT;    In a warm environment, harmful pathogens double in number every
20 minutes. Two hours is the magic cutoff, Harris says. If food has
been out of the cooler more than two hours, toss it. If it's very
hot outside _ close to 95 degrees _ throw out food after an hour.
 &HT;    That rule applies to perishables such as meat and salads, but
cut fruit can be dangerous, too, she says. People tend to leave raw
cut fruit out longer than other foods, but because cut fruit
doesn't have an acidic environment that helps retard pathogens, it
can be a prime breeding ground for bacteria passed on from cutting
boards of unwashed hands.
 &HT;    To make your picnic safer, follow these guidelines compiled from
UC Davis food experts and the U.S. Department of Agriculture:
 &HT;     Pack smart.  Use a cooler with plenty of space. Pack foods that
have already been chilled. Because cold air is heavier than warm,
put the ice or gel packs on top. Freeze items like juice boxes and
use them to supplement ice. And consider using two coolers _ one
for perishable food and another for high-traffic items like soda
and unpeeled fruit.
 &HT;     Keep clean.  Soap and running water are not always available at
picnic sites. So avoid cross contamination by bringing separate
utensils to use while cooking and serving meat. Don't serve cooked
meat on the unwashed platter that held raw meat.
 &HT;    If possible, wash your hands and cutting surfaces with a soapy
sponge carried in a self-sealing bag and rinse with water. As a
last resort, use anti-bacterial towelettes or gels.
 &HT;    Keep raw meat, poultry or fish well wrapped so drippings don't
contaminate other foods.
 &HT;    Keep food and utensils covered until serving time. Flies, other
insects and household pets can carry salmonella.
 &HT;     Keep cool . Prepared foods like salads and casseroles should be
taken out of the coolor just before serving.
 &HT;    And don't put that cooler in a hot car trunk. Keep it in the
shade at the picnic or campsite. Keep the lid on. And don't shy
away from the mayonnaise dressing on the potato salad. Mayonnaise
got a bad reputation when it was more commonly made with
salmonella-bearing raw eggs. Commercial mayonnaise is pasteurized,
making it much safer. But that doesn't mean it would be safe to eat
after two hours at room temperature.
 &HT;     Cook it completely.  Partially cooking foods with the intent of
finishing cooking at the picnic site is a bad idea. Travel time
allows lots of opportunity for bacteria to breed at optimum
temperature.
 &HT;    When you cook fish or meat on site, be patient. Cooks often
sample meat before it is completely cooked or get impatient and
serve it before the internal temperature is hot enough to kill
pathogens.
 &HT;     Check your food . As an extra precaution, do what Harris does.
``When I go to a picnic or a barbecue, I do a lot of touching the
side of the bowls to make sure it's still cold. If it's not cold,
or the meat isn't hot, I won't eat it.'' Of course, she adds, ``you
have to do it sort of casually to not insult the hostess.''
 &HT;    For additional information, all the USDA Meat and Poultry
Hotline at (800) 535-4555.
 &HT;      
 
 
 
 TAKE ALONG A FEW COMFORTS FROM THE KITCHEN  
   
   
 By Jennifer Straus  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Preparing a picnic basket is like setting up a
little kitchen away from home. Here are some items to carry along
to make the day more pleasurable:
<P>
   &UR; Knife and cutting board. &LR;  If you are doing some preparation on
site, make sure to have these two essential items. Wrap the knife
in a dish towel, or use a plastic knife guard. Finding a flat
surface can be difficult outside, so the cutting board can double
as a place to rest a wineglass or anything else that stands a
chance of tipping.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pocketknife.  &LR; Take one that has a few extra gadgets, such as a
corkscrew and bottle opener. Some even have a set of tweezers,
which could come in handy in case of a bee sting or picnic table
splinter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pre-moistened towels or baby wipes. &LR;  These can be extremely
helpful, especially if you are serving greasy foods. They also help
keep hands sanitary in lieu of soap and water.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Salt and pepper.  &LR; Bring seasoning in festive shakers as an easy
way to perk up the picnic site as well as the food. And don't
forget other condiments, such as mustard or butter, and a small
knife for spreading them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ice. &LR;  Make sure you have enough ice or gel packs to keep
perishables and drinks cold for the duration of your outing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Water &LR; . This is an easily overlooked addition to the picnic.
Take plenty, especially if you will be hiking to your location or
if it is a hot day.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Blanket or tablecloth &LR; . A pretty spread for the ground not only
protects people and food, but it also defines your picnic area and
sets a tone for the meal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Plastic bags.  &LR; A few extra self-sealing bags can be useful for
packing out leftovers, used cloth napkins or treasures like leaves
or seashells.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Citronella candles. &LR;  They're an easy way to keep bugs away
while adding some panache to the picnic.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that, depending on where you're going and how many
people are invited, several small containers could be easier to
haul than one large one. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
