<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT WASN'T JUST `TEASING,' JUDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What does it mean to be safe in school?
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the shooting massacre at Columbine High
School, we have framed that question in the shadow of blood,
bullets, and homemade bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with a ruling that would hold school districts liable for
sexual harassment by students, the US Supreme Court has broadened
our lens. No metal detector, no security system, no armed guard can
protect our daughters from the kind of assault the deeply divided
court addressed this week.
</P>
<P>
   In a 5-4 decision, the high court ruled that students are
entitled to protection from straying hands, as well as stray
bullets. The right of girls to an education means that schools must
intervene in cases of sexual harassment between students.
Indifference will invite legal sanction.
</P>
<P>
   The majority opinion, written by Justice Sandra Day O'Connor,
makes very clear that the provisions of Title IX apply not to
``simple acts of teasing and name-calling among schoolchildren''
but to behavior ``so severe, pervasive and objectively offensive
that it denies its victims'' an equal education.
</P>
<P>
   As significant as the protection offered to schoolgirls by the
court's majority is the vehemence of the dissent, written by
Justice Anthony M. Kennedy. To read that dissent is to know that
our culture, far from consensus on gun control, has also barely
begun to sort out its feelings about sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   To extend federal civil rights protections to schoolchildren
being harassed by their peers is to interfere with ``routine
problems of adolescence,'' Justice Kennedy wrote, prompting one to
ask what the judge thinks is routine.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling came in the case of Davis v. Monroe County Board of
Education. Aurelia Davis sued the school board in Forsyth, Ga.,
after teachers ignored her complaints that her 10-year-old
daughter, LaShonda, was being harassed by a fifth-grade classmate.
For months, he verbally and physically abused her. Her grades
dropped. She skipped school. She contemplated suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``A teenager's romantic overtures to a classmate (even when
persistent and unwelcome) are an inescapable part of adolescence,''
wrote Justice Kennedy. What, one wonders, did Justice Kennedy find
``romantic'' about the actions of LaShonda Davis' tormenter. Was it
when he slid a doorstop into his pants and made sexually explicit
gestures to her during gym class? Was it when he groped her in the
hall? Was it when he whispered crude obscenities to her in the
middle of class? Was it when he pleaded guilty to sexual battery?
</P>
<P>
   No one pretends that all sexual harassment complaints are as
unambiguous as this one, but to deny the pervasiveness of the
problem in our schools is to leave girls isolated, defenseless, and
alone. With luck, what happened in Littleton last month is teaching
us something about boys and anger, depression and neglect. What
happened in Forsyth has no less to teach us. What is it that makes
sexual aggression more immune from sanction than violence in other
forms?
</P>
<P>
   Justice Kennedy is certainly right to say that children's
behavior is primarily the purview of parents. But haven't we
learned that adults are not always as attuned to children as they
should be? Isn't labeling the actions of LaShonda's tormenter
``immature,'' as Justice Kennedy did in his dissent, trivializing a
10-year-old girl's suicide note?
</P>
<P>
   ``The real world of school discipline is a rough-and-tumble
place where students practice newly learned vulgarities, erupt with
anger, tease and embarrass each other, share offensive notes,
flirt, push and shove in the halls, grab and offend,'' Justice
Kennedy wrote. ``It is a far different question, however, whether
it is either proper or useful to label this immature, childish
behavior gender discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   How should we label it, then? If LaShonda experienced the
``routine'' manifestation of a growing boy, what did 13 people
experience when Dylan Klebold and Eric Harris erupted with anger?
``Immature, childish behavior'' or ``murder?''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Kennedy insisted ``the only certainty flowing from the
majority's decision is that scarce resources will be diverted from
educating our children.'' To the contrary, maybe now we will teach
them the lessons that really matter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara's e-mail address is mcnamara(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
