<HEADLINE>
A FEW TIPS FOR KEEPING PICNIC FOOD SAFE  
   
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 EDITORS NOTE: These sidebars about food safety and kitchen  gadgets
that are helpful outdoors are moving as part of a 
 three-take package. The main story, PICNIC, offers ideas for 
 picnics in four settings _ city, country, trailside and 
 seashore. PICNIC2 contains recipes for each setting.   By Kim Severson  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
SAN FRANCISCO _ To enjoy a picnic, it pays to learn a little
science. &HT;    Understanding the relationship among bacteria, temperature and
time can keep a picnic from turning into a medical emergency, says
Linda Harris, a microbiologist in the food science and technology
department at the University of California at Davis.
 &HT;    Pathogens like listeria and E. coli grow best at body
temperature, or about 96 degrees. They hate environments under 45
degrees and above 160, but they thrive and multiply quickly at
anything between.
 &HT;    In a warm environment, harmful pathogens double in number every
20 minutes. Two hours is the magic cutoff, Harris says. If food has
been out of the cooler more than two hours, toss it. If it's very
hot outside _ close to 95 degrees _ throw out food after an hour.
 &HT;    That rule applies to perishables such as meat and salads, but
cut fruit can be dangerous, too, she says. People tend to leave raw
cut fruit out longer than other foods, but because cut fruit
doesn't have an acidic environment that helps retard pathogens, it
can be a prime breeding ground for bacteria passed on from cutting
boards of unwashed hands.
 &HT;    To make your picnic safer, follow these guidelines compiled from
UC Davis food experts and the U.S. Department of Agriculture:
 &HT;     Pack smart.  Use a cooler with plenty of space. Pack foods that
have already been chilled. Because cold air is heavier than warm,
put the ice or gel packs on top. Freeze items like juice boxes and
use them to supplement ice. And consider using two coolers _ one
for perishable food and another for high-traffic items like soda
and unpeeled fruit.
 &HT;     Keep clean.  Soap and running water are not always available at
picnic sites. So avoid cross contamination by bringing separate
utensils to use while cooking and serving meat. Don't serve cooked
meat on the unwashed platter that held raw meat.
 &HT;    If possible, wash your hands and cutting surfaces with a soapy
sponge carried in a self-sealing bag and rinse with water. As a
last resort, use anti-bacterial towelettes or gels.
 &HT;    Keep raw meat, poultry or fish well wrapped so drippings don't
contaminate other foods.
 &HT;    Keep food and utensils covered until serving time. Flies, other
insects and household pets can carry salmonella.
 &HT;     Keep cool . Prepared foods like salads and casseroles should be
taken out of the coolor just before serving.
 &HT;    And don't put that cooler in a hot car trunk. Keep it in the
shade at the picnic or campsite. Keep the lid on. And don't shy
away from the mayonnaise dressing on the potato salad. Mayonnaise
got a bad reputation when it was more commonly made with
