finishing cooking at the picnic site is a bad idea. Travel time
allows lots of opportunity for bacteria to breed at optimum
temperature.
 &HT;    When you cook fish or meat on site, be patient. Cooks often
sample meat before it is completely cooked or get impatient and
serve it before the internal temperature is hot enough to kill
pathogens.
 &HT;     Check your food . As an extra precaution, do what Harris does.
``When I go to a picnic or a barbecue, I do a lot of touching the
side of the bowls to make sure it's still cold. If it's not cold,
or the meat isn't hot, I won't eat it.'' Of course, she adds, ``you
have to do it sort of casually to not insult the hostess.''
 &HT;    For additional information, all the USDA Meat and Poultry
Hotline at (800) 535-4555.
 &HT;      
 
 
 
 TAKE ALONG A FEW COMFORTS FROM THE KITCHEN  
   
   
