little kitchen away from home. Here are some items to carry along
to make the day more pleasurable:
<P>
   &UR; Knife and cutting board. &LR;  If you are doing some preparation on
site, make sure to have these two essential items. Wrap the knife
in a dish towel, or use a plastic knife guard. Finding a flat
surface can be difficult outside, so the cutting board can double
as a place to rest a wineglass or anything else that stands a
chance of tipping.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pocketknife.  &LR; Take one that has a few extra gadgets, such as a
corkscrew and bottle opener. Some even have a set of tweezers,
which could come in handy in case of a bee sting or picnic table
splinter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pre-moistened towels or baby wipes. &LR;  These can be extremely
helpful, especially if you are serving greasy foods. They also help
keep hands sanitary in lieu of soap and water.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Salt and pepper.  &LR; Bring seasoning in festive shakers as an easy
way to perk up the picnic site as well as the food. And don't
forget other condiments, such as mustard or butter, and a small
knife for spreading them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ice. &LR;  Make sure you have enough ice or gel packs to keep
perishables and drinks cold for the duration of your outing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Water &LR; . This is an easily overlooked addition to the picnic.
Take plenty, especially if you will be hiking to your location or
if it is a hot day.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Blanket or tablecloth &LR; . A pretty spread for the ground not only
protects people and food, but it also defines your picnic area and
sets a tone for the meal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Plastic bags.  &LR; A few extra self-sealing bags can be useful for
packing out leftovers, used cloth napkins or treasures like leaves
or seashells.
</P>
