<HEADLINE>
EDUCATION CHIEF CARLIN GOES OUT SWINGING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Making his parting shots as he prepares to leave
public service, outgoing Board of Higher Education chairman James
F. Carlin declared that colleges and universities are on the edge
of a swift decline because no one _ university presidents,
trustees, nor faculty _ is willing to stand up against declining
standards and rising tuitions.
</P>
<P>
   As he defended his combative style and his record, Carlin said
in an interview that he was done with public service but not with
higher education, and plans to take his crusade for improvement
national, as part of a coalition of reform-minded businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   And he showed little sign of backing away from the premises that
have guided his sweeping revisions to the state's public colleges
and universities over 3 1/2 years: Faculty unions resist
improvements to teaching and learning; university presidents are
too busy raising money to demand change; colleges are so interested
in filling seats that they accept students who aren't qualified,
then pass them through courses far short of rigorous; and all the
while, costs rise and quality declines.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they were getting less and colleges were charging less,
maybe people wouldn't care as much, or if colleges were charging
more but people were getting more,'' Carlin said. ``But most people
will agree, we're paying more and getting less.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you agree we have some problems, if we as a nation want
higher education to work better, we've got to figure out who's in
charge on campus, and the problem is, nobody's in charge, nobody
who has the authority to make decisions and make changes.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem begins, Carlin said, with the sheer explosion of
higher education in this country, with 3,600 colleges creating a
$200-billion-a-year enterprise that employs 2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Academics get all upset when you call it a business, but it's
such a big enterprise that there is tremendous pressure on all but
a couple hundred of the 3,600 colleges in this country,'' Carlin
said. ``They'll do anything to fill the chairs.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he said, admissions standards have been lowered, so
more students require remedial education, and graduation
requirements have been eased.
</P>
<P>
   Carlin spares few in his scorn, criticizing both faculty and
university administrators for not doing enough to cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tuition and fees have gone off the Richter scale, parents are
mortgaging their homes, dipping into their 401Ks, deferring
retirement so they can pay for these tuitions, and the colleges
just stand there with a stack of loan forms,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Trustees, he said, have neither the time nor the interest in
demanding changes. Presidents do not want to challenge the faculty.
And the faculty itself, he said, does not want intervention from
the presidents or the trustees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The few people who recognize the problems in higher education
and want to make it better and are willing to stand up and tell the
truth and propose reforms,'' he said, ``are pretty much out there
by themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   While he has, predictably, made enemies among the faculties of
the state colleges and universities, Carlin has also successfully
demanded changes in Massachusetts: moving remedial education to the
community colleges, raising admissions standards, and lowering
tuitions.
</P>
<P>
   But the professors unions, who are working on a contract
extension that expires June 30, have argued that he simplifies the
situation too much. They grant him few accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   For example, William Murphy, the president of the state college
professors union, argued in an interview last week that reducing
the price of tuition has made parents and students think that
public education in Massachusetts is somehow less valuable.
</P>
<P>
   Carlin's constant attacks on the unions, Murphy and others say,
only serve to worsen the reputation of the state colleges and
university in a state where public education is already the poor
cousin to more estalished, prestigious private schools.
</P>
<P>
   But Carlin, a self-made millionaire, recalled his own experience
as a middle-class student attending a public university in Florida
to explain his crusades to cut tuition and demand higher
performance from unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If not for that University of Florida $75 tuition, I would
have gone into the US Army, like a lot of my friends did,'' he
said. ``So when people ask me why I do these things, I did it for
the kids and for the parents. What burns me is, every time you
would raise a point to the faculty about teaching a few more hours,
or say student evaluations ought to be published, they would say,
`Stop attacking higher education, stop being the enemy of the
students.' Well, thanks to what this board has done, kids are
paying $30 million less to go to the University of Massachusetts,
in the aggregate, and their degree is worth more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
