<SLUG> BC-PICNIC2-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ALL-AMERICAN PICNIC  
 
 
 SOUTHERN-FRIED CHICKEN
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 EDITORS NOTE: These are picnic recipes for outings in
four  settings _ city, country, trailside and seashore. The
package, 
 which moves in three takes, also is made up of PICNIC, the main 
 story, and PICNICSIDE, sidebars on food safety and kitchen 
 gadgets to take along.
<TEXT>
<P>
   From Brad Levy, Firefly restaurant, San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 fryer chickens, about 3 pounds each
</P>
<P>
   2 cups vegetable oil or solid vegetable shortening, or as needed
</P>
<P>
   Spice Mixture
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground red chile (New Mexico or ancho)
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons granulated garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon granulated or powdered onion
</P>
<P>
   Pinch celery salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons pepper
</P>
<P>
   Coating
</P>
<P>
   2 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 cups buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Cut each chicken into 8 serving pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Mix together the paprika, ground chile, garlic, onion, celery
salt, salt and pepper. Sprinkle the spice mixture on the chicken
pieces heavily enough that the color of the skin barely shows
through. Refrigerate for 5 to 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Coating:  &LR; Combine the flour, salt and pepper in a
medium-size shallow bowl. Pour the buttermilk into another
medium-size shallow bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Piece by piece, dip the chicken first in the buttermilk, then in
the seasoned flour, coating well. Shake off any excess flour and
place the pieces on a sheet of wax paper; do not let them touch
each other. Refrigerate for 15 to 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Pour 1/2 inch of vegetable oil into a large, heavy skillet (or
add the solid vegetable shortening). Heat the oil to 325 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Piece by piece, place the chicken skin-side down in the hot oil.
Do not crowd the pan or the temperature of the oil will drop and
the chicken will not cook properly. Fry until the pieces are dark
golden-brown, turning once or twice. This should take 10 to 20
minutes (dark meat takes longer). Be sure the pieces are cooked
through; cut into a piece or two. There should be no trace of pink
near the bone.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the chicken pieces to a rack to cool, then refrigerate
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 568 calories, &LR;   &LR; 49 g protein, 17 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 33 g fat (8 g saturated), 179 mg cholesterol, 179
mg sodium, 1 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MIDWESTERN POTATO SALAD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   From Brad Levy, Firefly restaurant, San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 pounds new potatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped red onion
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Boil the potatoes in their skins until just tender; drain. Peel,
if desired, and cut into 3/4-inch chunks. Place the potatoes in a
bowl. Add the parsley, celery and red onion.
</P>
<P>
   Mix together the mayonnaise, mustard, pepper, vinegar, sugar and
salt. Add to the potato mixture and gently stir until the potatoes
are evenly coated with dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8 to 10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 487 calories, &LR;   &LR; 5 g protein, 45 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 33 g fat (5 g saturated), 24 mg cholesterol, 405 mg sodium, 5 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; URBAN PICNIC &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; GRILLED ASPARAGUS SANDWICHES WITH SPRING ONION VINAIGRETTE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   From Nancy Frumkes DeLong, Modern Catering.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces spring onions
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup rice wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Zest of 4 blood or navel oranges
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   40 spears jumbo asparagus
</P>
<P>
   4 mint sprigs, leaves cut into chiffonade
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   8 pita breads
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Finely dice the onions; place in a bowl and add the vinegar. Let
steep for 30 minutes. Add the orange zest, then stir in the olive
oil.
</P>
<P>
   Snap off the tough ends from the asparagus. Grill or barbecue
them lightly, until tender. Cut the spears into 2-inch lengths.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the warm asparagus in the vinaigrette until well coated.
Stir in the mint, and season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Pack the salad into a plastic container with a tight-fitting
lid.
</P>
<P>
   Shake well before opening. Serve the asparagus wrapped in soft
pitas, like tacos.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 315 calories, &LR;   &LR; 9 g protein, 39 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 15 g fat (2 g saturated), 0 mg cholesterol, 342 mg sodium, 3 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; LOBSTER BISQUE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   From Nancy Frumkes DeLong, Modern Catering. This recipe was
adapted for home kitchens from Modern Catering's more traditional
version. Traditional lobster bisque calls for using rice as a
thickener and grinding up the lobster shells, which can be hard on
your food processor.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped carrot
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   4 parsley stems
</P>
<P>
   4 sprigs thyme
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   4 live lobsters, about 11/4 pounds each
</P>
<P>
   1 cup Cognac
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   2 quarts chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   2 quarts water
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   2 cups heavy cream, reduced to 1 cup
</P>
<P>
   Finely chopped chives for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in a large, heavy stock pot; add the onions,
celery, carrot, bay leaves, parsley stems and thyme; sweat over
very low heat until tender. Do not let the vegetables color.
</P>
<P>
   Add the tomato paste and cook for 5 minutes longer. Remove from
heat and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Bring 4 quarts of heavily salted water (it should taste like
saltwater) to a boil. Add the lobsters, one at a time, cooking each
for 7 minutes. Immediately plunge the lobsters into ice water. When
cool, remove the tails from the bodies. Remove the meat from the
tails; cut it into smaller pieces and set aside, reserving the
shells.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the legs and claws from the bodies, set aside. Remove the
shells from the bodies, discarding the rest except for any bits of
meat. Place all of the shells, the legs and claws under a clean
towel and crush them with a rolling pin or a bottle of wine.
</P>
<P>
   Return the vegetables to the heat, add the shells and bodies.
When hot, add the Cognac; reduce for 3 minutes. Add the wine, and
reduce for 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the chicken broth and water, bring to a low boil and reduce
for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the stock through a fine-meshed strainer into another stock
pot and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a heavy saute pan. Whisk in the flour and
cook for 5 to 8 minutes, stirring frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Bring the stock to a boil and whisk in the roux. Cook at a low
boil for 10 minutes, stirring occasionally. Skim any foam that
forms during the cooking process.
</P>
<P>
   Add the cream; the amount can vary according to how rich you
like it.
</P>
<P>
   Strain the soup one more time and heat through. Stir in the
reserved lobster meat.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the bisque into a thermos.
</P>
<P>
   Serve hot, garnished with chives.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 555 calories, &LR;   &LR; 22 g protein, 21 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 38 g fat (22 g saturated), 194 mg cholesterol, 379
mg sodium, 0 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; PICNIC BY THE SEA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SOFT-SHELL CRAB SANDWICHES WITH AVOCADO, FENNEL &AMP; REMOULADE SAUCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   From Mark Franz, Farallon restaurant, San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 heads fennel
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   4 soft-shell crabs (ask your fishmonger to clean them for you)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup yellow cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   8 slices sourdough bread, lightly toasted on one side
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Remoulade Sauce (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   2 ripe avocados, pitted, peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Trim the fronds and long stems from the fennel and discard.
Quarter the fennel bulbs and remove the hard core. Thinly shave the
fennel on a mandoline, or slice with a sharp knife. Toss in a
mixture of lemon juice and water to prevent discoloration; set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Season the crabs with salt and pepper. Place the flour, cornmeal
and beaten eggs in 3 separate bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Dredge each crab first in flour, then in egg wash, and finally
in cornmeal, shaking off any excess.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a nonstick pan until just lightly smoking; add
the crabs and saute over medium heat for 3 minutes. Turn the crabs
and cook for 3 minutes longer. Transfer the crabs to paper towels
to drain.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To assemble the sandwiches:  &LR; Place the slices of sourdough on a
counter, toasted-sides up. Spread all slices with remoulade, then
top half of them with avocado, drained and patted-dry fennel, and
crab. Top with the remaining slices of bread and leave whole.
</P>
<P>
   These sandwiches are messy; wrap and place them in a suitable
plastic container.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 735 calories, &LR;   &LR; 29 g protein, 68 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 40 g fat (7 g saturated), 127 mg cholesterol, 904
mg sodium, 10 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; REMOULADE SAUCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   From Mark Franz, Farallon restaurant, San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons drained and chopped capers
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon anchovy paste
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped tarragon
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped chervil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients in a bowl; mix to blend well.
</P>
<P>
   If not using immediately, cover and refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 1/2 cup.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER TABLESPOON: &LR;   &LR; 75 calories, &LR;   &LR; 0 g protein, 0 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 8 g fat (1 g saturated), 7 mg cholesterol, 123 mg
sodium, 0 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; PANNA COTTA WITH CITRUS STRAWBERRY SALAD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   From Mark Franz, Farallon restaurant, San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Ingredients: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 envelope unflavored gelatin
</P>
<P>
   2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 vanilla bean, split and scraped, or 1 tablespoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Citrus-Strawberry Salad (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Pour the milk into a small bowl and sprinkle the gelatin over
the surface. Allow it to stand for 5 minutes, until the gelatin
absorbs the milk and softens.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the cream, sugar, vanilla beans and vanilla pod in a
saucepan; bring to a simmer. Remove from heat and cover. Let steep
for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Reheat the cream mixture to approximately 100 degrees (just warm
to the touch). Stir in the softened gelatin. Continue to stir until
the gelatin has dissolved. If using vanilla extract, stir it in
now. Strain into a 2-quart plastic container with a tight-fitting
lid. Refrigerate for at least 4 hours. May be made 1 day ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING (without fruit): &LR;   &LR; 370 calories, &LR;   &LR; 4 g protein, 21
g &LR;   &LR; carbohydrate, 31 g fat (19 g saturated), 114 mg cholesterol,
51 &LR;   &LR; mg sodium, 0 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; CITRUS STRAWBERRY SALAD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   From Mark Franz, Farallon restaurant, San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Ingredients: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 tangerines or oranges
</P>
<P>
   1 pint strawberries, hulled and quartered
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the water, orange juice and sugar in a saucepan. Bring
to a boil, remove from heat and let cool to room temperature. Chill
in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Peel the tangerines, removing as much pith and skin as possible,
then cut the segments from the membranes.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the tangerine segments and strawberries in the chilled
syrup. Spoon into a plastic container with a tight-fitting lid.
Refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, spoon the fruit and syrup over servings of panna
cotta.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 105 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 27 g carbohydrate,
0 &LR;   &LR; g fat, 0 mg cholesterol, 2 mg sodium, 2 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; PICNIC ON THE TRAIL &LR;   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; STEAMED VEGETABLE DUMPLINGS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   From Brenda Buenviaje, Oritalia restaurant, San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Ingredients: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Asian sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup finely diced white onion
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces seitan, cut into small dice
</P>
<P>
   Kernels from 1 ear of fresh corn
</P>
<P>
   3 asparagus spears, sliced into thin rounds
</P>
<P>
   2 packs enoki mushrooms, trimmed and separated
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons sake
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon sambal oelek or curry powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup finely sliced scallions
</P>
<P>
   1/2 package potsticker wrappers (30 wrappers)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oils in a saute pan over high heat. Add the garlic and
onion and saute for 4 to 5 minutes, until the onion is translucent.
Add the seitan, corn kernels, asparagus and enoki mushrooms; saute
for 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the ginger and sake and simmer for 4 minutes. Remove from
heat. Season with soy and sambal or curry. Mix in the scallions.
Let cool to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To assemble:  &LR; Place 1 wrapper on a work surface. Spoon 1
teaspoon of the filling in the center. Moisten the outer edge of
the wrapper with a pastry brush dipped in water. Hold the wrapper
in one hand and gently bring the 2 sides together, keeping the
filling in the center. Crimp the edges together, keeping the back
edge straight while pressing the front edge onto it in pleats. Make
sure the seal is tight or the dumpling will fall apart while
steaming.
</P>
<P>
   Continue the procedure until all filling has been used. You
should have about half of the wrappers left. Wrap well and
refrigerate for another use.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly oil the bottom of a bamboo or metal steamer. Place the
dumplings in a single layer inside. Cover and steam for 7 to 8
minutes, or until the wrappers are cooked.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 30 dumplings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER DUMPLING: &LR;   &LR; 35 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 3 g carbohydrate,
2 &LR;   &LR; g fat (0 g saturated), 2 mg cholesterol, 83 mg sodium, 0 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; STIR-FRIED UDON NOODLES WITH MORELS &AMP; FRESH PEAS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   From Brenda Buenviaje, Oritalia restaurant, San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/2 small onion, thinly julienned
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup Shaoxing rice wine
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sliced morels
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh peas (about 1 pound unshelled)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable stock or water
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons low-sodium light soy sauce, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 pound udon noodles, cooked al dente, rapidly cooled in ice
water, and drained
</P>
<P>
   4 cups young spinach leaves
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons thinly sliced scallions
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a saute pan; add the garlic and onion and
saute over medium-high heat until the garlic is toasted and the
onion is lightly caramelized. Deglaze the pan with rice wine.
</P>
<P>
   Add the morels and peas; simmer for 5 minutes. Add the stock and
simmer for 5 minutes longer, until the peas are tender. Add the
lemon juice and soy sauce to taste. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Heat another saute pan until smoking, then add the vegetable
oil. Add the cooked and drained noodles and stir-fry over high for
1 minute.
</P>
<P>
   Add the morel mixture and the spinach. Stir-fry over high heat
until the noodles absorb the cooking liquid. Toss in the scallions.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer to a plastic container and let cool. Cover tightly and
refrigerate until ready to pack for the picnic.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 420 calories, &LR;   &LR; 13 g protein, 65 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 12 g fat (4 g saturated), 16 mg cholesterol, 567 mg
sodium, 2 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
