<HEADER>
A1828 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TASTE-STEAK-SFCHRON &LR;      05-26 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTE-STEAK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel
of  professional tasters tries a different product available in 
 supermarkets.    TASTER'S CHOICE: Panel Puts Steaks to the Test  
   
 By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  For many people, Memorial Day marks the beginning
of summer and, perhaps more important, the beginning of grilling
season. So a lot of people will be throwing steaks on the barbie
this weekend, but deciding which one _ both cut and brand _ is a
challenge.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Consumers have to be aware and educated,'' says Bala Kironde,
owner of Preferred Meats, which sells meats to many Bay Area
restaurants. ``If you're buying from a certain ranch or company,
it's more involved than just the type of cattle. It has to do with
the feed, the breed of cattle and where the cattle is bought
from.''
</P>
<P>
   Many meat packers are branding their meats these days so markets
are full of steaks labeled from Niman Ranch, Harris Ranch and
Coleman. Most steaks also carry a grade _ Prime, Choice or Select _
given by the U.S. Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Grading is based on the age and physique of the animal and the
marbling (fat) within the meat. Prime comes from young animals and
has the most marbling which translates as flavor. It's the most
expensive and hardest to find. Most is exported to Japan and much
of the rest ends up on restaurant tables.
</P>
<P>
   Most steaks available at supermarkets are Choice. These also
come from young animals but have less marbling than Prime. Select
is even leaner meat, with little marbling and traditionally less
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Today's panel tasted eight New York strip steaks, which many
consider their favorite steak. The steaks ranged in price from
$6.49 per pound to a staggering $17.98 per pound. Two steaks were
Prime grade, five were Choice, one was Select, and one ungraded.
(Niman Ranch steaks are graded for the producer but the grades are
not stamped on the meat.) Surprisingly, the Prime steaks scored too
low to rate.
</P>
<P>
   Each steak _ all but one were close to 1 inch thick and each
weighed approximately 12 ounces _ was seasoned with a half teaspoon
of a salt and pepper mixture _ 10 parts kosher salt to one part
freshly ground black pepper. Then they were grilled to medium rare.
The panelists also viewed the steaks before they were cooked.
</P>
<P>
   Despite uniform seasoning and preparation, there were definite
differences in flavor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Niman Ranch  &LR; ($12.95 per pound at Cafe Rouge in Berkeley; call
415-552-0181 for other locations or to order direct) was the
favorite by almost 10 points over the next closest brand. Four
panelists would buy it; one might buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Two panelists thought the appearance, which didn't reflect much
marbling, belied the fabulous flavor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised,'' said Bill Niman, owner of Niman Ranch,
when asked about the discrepancy. Contrary to popular thought, he
does not believe that marbling always correlates with flavor. He
attributes his meat's flavor to the older age of his cattle
(they're usually slaughtered at 2 years instead of the industry
standard 15 months). That means they have been fed longer, which
contributes to the development of flavor. The type of feed _ Niman
Ranch uses grain exclusively _ also plays a big part in the meat's
taste, Niman says.
</P>
<P>
   Second place went to  &UR; Harris Ranch Choice &LR;  ($8.99 per pound at
Cala). One panelist thought the meat was tough, and another
commented on the visible lack of marbling. But three panelists
enjoyed the steak's flavor. Four would buy it; one might buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Just two points lower was &UR; Angus Certified Choice &LR;  ($10.99 per
pound at Andronico's). Three panelists liked the flavor and
texture, but one described it as bland. Four would buy it; one
might buy it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Coleman Choice  &LR; ($12.99-$13.99 per pound at Whole Foods and
some other markets) came in fourth. Two panelists thought the steak
was too chewy _ Coleman claims its beef is bred to be leaner _ but
others liked the ``beefy taste'' and two described it as a ``great
piece of meat.'' One said it ``melts in the mouth.'' Four would buy
it; one would not.
</P>
<P>
   Scores dropped dramatically after fourth place, but the best of
the rest was  &UR; Mollie Stone's Choice, &LR;  supplied by IBC ($10.49 per
pound pound at Mollie Stone's). One panelist thought it looked
great but that ``looks were deceiving.'' He described the steak as
``dry, mealy and lacking in flavor.'' Three others complained about
the chewiness, and another said he would buy it, but it was not his
top choice. Two might buy it; three would not.
</P>
<P>
   Three steaks scored too low to rate: Draeger's Prime (the meat
counter would not identify the packer), Angus Certified Prime (at
Andronico's) and Safeway (IBP Select Grade). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Panelists were John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Shelley Handler,
consultant and food writer; Donna Katzl, chef-owner, Cafe For All
Seasons, San Francisco; Roland Passot, chef-owner of La Folie in
San Francisco and Left Bank in Larspur and Menlo Park, Calif., and
Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San Francisco. All products are
tasted blind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
