<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACTORS AFFECT GROWTH FUND PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Which company manages your growth mutual fund? The answer has
mattered more in the last year than perhaps ever before.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the best and worst fund families has
rarely, if ever, been greater when it comes to growth investments.
The entire roster of big fund companies, usually performing within
a comparatively narrow band when it comes to growth vehicles, have
been all over the map.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has never been anything like this,'' said William
Dougherty of Kanon Bloch Carre, a Boston consulting firm that
tracks mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Growth funds, which own stocks a manager hopes will grow faster
than the rest of the market, comprise the single-largest investment
category of the mutual fund industry.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors owning poor-performing growth funds can just take
their business elsewere. But many retirement-oriented shareholders
are locked into one fund company by a defined contribution plan and
don't have the option to move their money to a competitor.
</P>
<P>
   There are a handful of reasons for the wide range of investment
performances, but the types of stocks a management company prefers
and the style of its managers clearly has made the biggest
difference. Another factor: the growing impact of more concentrated
investments inside individual funds and across entire management
company portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   Kanon Bloch measured the investment performance of growth and
aggressive growth funds at the nation's 45 largest mutual fund
companies. It measured the performance of every fund family and
ranked each of them top to bottom.
</P>
<P>
   The best-performing company over a yearlong period ended March
31, Janus Capital Corp., and the worst over the same time, Merrill
Lynch, would not come as a great suprise to fund followers.
</P>
<P>
   But the gap between their performances and the range of other
fund family returns between the two extremes is striking.
</P>
<P>
   The Janus growth funds earned an asset-weighted average of 53.8
percent during that 12-month period. Merrill's funds, weighted in
the same fashion, lost 13.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Performance by the other 43 fund families measured by Kanon
Bloch covered a lot of territory. Thirteen other companies were at
least 10 percentage points better or worse than the median return
of 10.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Investments was easily the largest competitor in the
field with $223 billion of growth fund assets measured. It earned
an asset weighted 21.8 percent, better than all but six of the
companies tracked by Kanon Bloch.
</P>
<P>
   Go through the same calculations, this time measuring growth
fund performance another year back, and the story changes. The best
performance for the year ended March 31, 1998, was 53.5 percent and
the worst recorded a 26.9 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   Just five fund companies fit within that performance range in
the more recent year. The rest earned something less or nothing at
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason is style of investing, growth over value and large
capitalization over small cap,'' said Dougherty. ``It really became
a nightmare for anyone who believed in asset allocation to reduce
risk. It worked against you.''
</P>
<P>
   Growth stocks, already in favor, appreciated at the even greater
expense of value stocks, which can also be found in some growth
fund portfolios. Large company stocks, particularly tech giants
like Microsoft Corp., continued to roll while no one seemed to want
to buy smaller stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Investment companies like the Pioneer Group Inc. in Boston,
which offer growth funds but lean toward value investing, have
suffered through below average performance.
</P>
<P>
   Very recent trends, over the last six weeks, seemed to have
shifted in favor of value stocks and some smaller issues. But
analysts insist it is too early to call it evidence of a market
reversal or just a temporary style blip.
</P>
<P>
   As the market heaped most of its rewards on a small number of
stocks, the concentration of investments at fund companies took on
a more pronounced effect. Companies in the right place seemed to be
run by geniuses. Others who dug in with big bets on out of favor
investments were run over.
</P>
<P>
   Janus turned in blockbuster returns in part because its growth
funds owned so many of the same highly popular stocks, like
Microsoft and Dell Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Concentration of investments across an entire fund company is
nothing new. Fidelity was accused of ``group think'' among its
managers who owned the same stocks when the company's funds were
performing poorly two years ago, but the attention diminished
mostly because performance has bounced back.
</P>
<P>
   Concentration inside individual fund portfolios has also had an
impact on companywide performances. In a stock market with a narrow
list of winners, concentration became a path to strong fund
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's because of the success in recent years of the
managers who have concentrated,'' said Walter S. Frank, chief
investment officer at IBC Financial Data. ``In fact,
diversification was the dirty word because it cost you.''
</P>
<P>
   It can also cost managers who put their eggs in the wrong
basket. The dismal returns at Merrill Lynch's growth fund group is
mostly a dim reflection on Merrill Lynch Growth, a big fund with a
concentrated portfolio and terrible returns.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch Growth, which invests in fewer than 50 small- and
midsized stocks, lost nearly 31 percent over the 12 months ended
March 31.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
