<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOODNEWS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;       
   
 FOOD IN THE NEWS  
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 EDITORS NOTE: Food, nutrition and health studies bombard us,
but  the seemingly endless information is often as confusing as it
is 
 enlightening. With Food in the News, The Chronicle's Food staff 
 aims to change that. This regular round-up column will make 
 practical sense of the latest nutrition-related studies _ as 
 well as offering offbeat but tantalizing snippets of other food 
 news to put on your plate.  By Kim Severson 
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; America's food pyramid is getting another upgrade,
this time in an effort to make 2- to 6-year-olds eat better.
<P>
   The new food guide pyramid for young children, released
recently, is a kid-friendly version of the adult pyramid, featuring
foods such as waffles, tortillas, yogurt and boxes of juice.
</P>
<P>
   Early food experiences are crucial to establishing food
preferences and patterns throughout life, says Agriculture
Secretary Dan Glickman.
</P>
<P>
   The names of the six food groups have been simplified, and the
graphics streamlined so the concept is easy to understand. For
example, the fats and sweets category at the tip of the pyramid
features a picture of a lollipop, a stick of butter and the advice,
``Eat less.''
</P>
<P>
   Servings are kid-sized and food suggestions based on children's
preferences. For example, meat recommendations rely more on cold
cuts and ground beef than on fish. Kids need to eat two servings of
fruit a day, compared to the two to four recommended for adults. A
serving of fruit might be a melon wedge or a quarter cup of dried
fruit, such as raisins.
</P>
<P>
   The pyramid also features drawings of children engaged in
physical activity to emphasize the importance of exercise as part
of a health approach to eating.
</P>
<P>
   Look for details at government offices, schools and child care
centers. Posters and guides outlining the new pyramid are being
shipped to 70,000 elementary schools, 100,000 day care providers
and 45,000 government feeding programs.
</P>
<P>
   And there's one more twist. The Department of Agriculture has
teamed up with 11 food companies that have agreed to use the
pyramid in marketing and educational efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The USDA will make sure nutritional claims and marketing efforts
by companies such as Kellogg, Dole and Quaker Oats are accurate,
and in return the manufacturers will push the new pyramid in
marketing and educational campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Or download your own copy of the new pyramid on the Internet at
 &LR; www.usda.gov/cnpp/. &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Stats for the Barbie &LR;
</P>
<P>
   When you're waiting for the meat to grill at your Memorial Day
barbecue, entertain your guests with a few barbecue facts:
</P>
<P>
   Americans will cook out 2.9 billion times this year, mostly
between May and September.
</P>
<P>
   During that peak period, the nation will consume a staggering 7
billion hot dogs.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of charcoal grill owners say they will buy a gas
grill next time.
</P>
<P>
   Beef is star of the barbecue, showing up as the main protein
choice in six out of every 10 of those barbecues.
</P>
<P>
   If that beef is in the form of a burger made from regular ground
meat, it will contain 20 grams of fat. For comparison, four ounces
of skinless chicken breast contains 4 grams of fat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
