<HEADER>
A1835 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PICNIC-SFCHRON &LR;      05-26 1751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PICNIC-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 EDITORS NOTE: In this package, moving in three takes,
The  Chronicle offers ideas for elegant picnics in four settings _ 
 city, country, trailside and seashore. The other takes are 
 PICNIC2, recipes for picnic foods, and PICNICSIDE, sidebars on 
 food safety and kitchen gadgets for the great outdoors.   SUMMER QUARTET: Four Memorial Day picnics where the food 
 harmonizes with the setting  
   
 By Kim Severson  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
   
 PICNIC BY THE SEA 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark Franz, Farallon &QL; 
 &QL; 
Oysters on the Half Shell
</P>
<P>
   Smoked Salmon Roulade With Osetra Caviar
</P>
<P>
   Soft-Shell Crab Sandwiches With Avocado, Fennel and Remoulade
Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Spring Salad With Fava Beans, Artichokes and Morel Mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   Panna Cotta With Citrus-Strawberry Salad
</P>
<P>
   Beverages: Navarro Vineyards 1997 Anderson Valley Dry
Gewurztraminer ($14)
</P>
<P>
   B &AMP; G 1997 Vouvray ($7.50)
</P>
<P>
   Or freshly brewed fruity iced tea
</P>
<P>
   ( recipes included)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; A COUNTRY PICNIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Brad Levy, Firefly
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Southern Fried Chicken
</P>
<P>
   Midwestern Potato Salad
</P>
<P>
   Watermelon
</P>
<P>
   Homemade Ice Cream
</P>
<P>
   Beverages: Hess Select 1997 California Chardonnay ($10.95)
</P>
<P>
   Or Talus 1996 California Zinfandel ($8)
</P>
<P>
   Or locally brewed India Pale Ale
</P>
<P>
   ( recipes included)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; URBAN PICNIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Frumkes DeLong, Modern Catering
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lobster Bisque
</P>
<P>
   Grilled Asparagus Sandwiches With Spring Onion Vinaigrette
</P>
<P>
   Strawberries with Vanilla Sugar
</P>
<P>
   Shortbread Cookies
</P>
<P>
   Iced Mochas
</P>
<P>
   Beverages: Hogue 1997 Washington State Chenin Blanc ($8)
</P>
<P>
   Or Julian Chivate 1997 Gran Feudo Spanish Rose ($9)
</P>
<P>
   ( recipes included)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; PICNIC ON THE TRAIL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Buenviaje, Oritalia
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steamed Vegetable Dumplings
</P>
<P>
   Mustard-Wrapped Quinoa Pilaf Dolmas
</P>
<P>
   Grilled Asparagus and Pickled Beet Salad
</P>
<P>
   Stir-Fried Udon Noodles With Morels and Fresh Peas
</P>
<P>
   Savory Crepes With Chevre, Basil and Watercress
</P>
<P>
   Berry or Melon Salad With Thai Dill and Mint
</P>
<P>
   Pear Tarts or Scones
</P>
<P>
   Beverages: Cold mineral water and fruit shakes
</P>
<P>
   ( recipes included) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Outdoors, the ordinary act of eating becomes
extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   With apologies to food writer M.F.K. Fisher, consider the
oyster. A fresh oyster eaten at a restaurant has its appeal. But at
the seashore, where the ocean spray echoes the oyster's briny
juice, the diner becomes more attuned to the food at hand and the
place it has come from.
</P>
<P>
   n the same way, a salad composed of woodsy morel mushrooms and
spring fava beans has much more character eaten alongside a trail
than at a kitchen counter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're out there in the middle of nature, all your senses
are awakened,'' Oritalia chef Brenda Buenviaje says.
</P>
<P>
   That is among the many reasons we love picnics. But not just any
combination of food and nature will do. In a peak outdoor dining
experience, the food goes one step further, reflecting the
environment in which it's eaten.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, we asked four Bay Area chefs to match a Memorial
Day picnic menu to a specific place and discuss the accessories
they'd add to evoke a whole that's much greater than the sum of its
parts. Each chef contributes two recipes and suggestions for other
dishes to round out the day. Chronicle wine writer Gerald D. Boyd
suggests bottles to match the baskets.
</P>
<P>
   Though the menus vary in complexity, each chef emphasizes food
that requires little on-site preparation, preferring _ as we all do
_ dishes that can travel well and be served in the containers in
which they were packed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Picnics aren't rocket science,'' says Farallon chef Mark
Franz. ``Remember, this is Memorial Day weekend. You're supposed to
relax and be outside.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PICNIC BY THE SEA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Franz grew up eating and playing on Bay Area beaches. He is also a
former Alaska fishing guide who now presides over an undersea
fantasy in San Francisco at Farallon, where seafood is the star.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we used to do when I was younger was big pig roasts and
clambakes,'' he says. Franz suggests scaling back from such
elaborate on-site efforts _ but that doesn't mean the food can't be
spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   In his seashore picnic, Franz starts with a stop at a local fish
market or an oyster seller like Point Reyes Oyster Co. to pick up a
dozen fresh oysters to pop open at the beach.
</P>
<P>
   The stars of the picnic are soft-shell crab sandwiches with
avocado, fennel and remoulade sauce on sourdough. Franz pairs them
with a simple, sturdy salad based on spring ingredients. Avoid
salads featuring lettuce, he advises. They simply won't transport
well or hold up in the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Dessert is a simple panna cotta with citrus strawberry salad
that sets up in the plastic container used to transport and serve
it.
</P>
<P>
   A flat-top cooler with lots of ice is essential to keep food
cool at the beach. It also serves as a fine makeshift table.
</P>
<P>
   Any of several area beaches is an option, but Franz suggests
finding one out of the wind, such as Drake's Beach in Point Reyes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; Accessories:  &LR; A surfboard or Boogie board, sunscreen and movie
magazines. Franz suggests no radio. The sound of the ocean is the
best music, he says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Beverage matches:  &LR; Crab is a low-fat shellfish, while avocado
is rich and buttery, so wines with flavor and fruit work well. Look
for Navarro Vineyards 1997 Anderson Valley Dry Gewurztraminer ($14)
or B&AMP;G 1997 Vouvray from France ($7.50). Sparkling wine would also
match with oysters and caviar, or forgo any alcohol and opt for a
jug of freshly brewed fruity iced tea.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; A COUNTRY PICNIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Memorial Day is about honoring those who have fought for &UR;  &LR; our
country, so Brad Levy, chef at Firefly in San Francisco, has
created a basket reflecting classic American fare.
</P>
<P>
   Levy grew &UR;  &LR; up eating American-style picnics in his native St.
Louis. He also has a list of customers who expect him to call when
he puts fried &UR;  &LR; chicken on the Firefly special list.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think of the picnics we had as kids, they always
involved lots of relatives, hamburgers and hot dogs, and a ball
game in the afternoon,'' he says. Instead of barbecue, Levy's
southern fried chicken, served cold and eaten out of hand, is the
centerpiece of his basket. In addition to the chicken, he suggests
a mayonnaise-based Midwestern potato salad.
</P>
<P>
   If you're picnicking close to the car, consider hauling along an
old-fashioned ice cream maker. A batch of soft, fresh ice cream is
quintessentially American, and the cranking can keep kids busy
while adults relax. Choose a public park with picnic tables, or
bring along blankets and stretch out on the grass. Golden Gate Park
is an obvious choice, but a neighborhood pocket park with a patch
of green and a few teeter-totters can be equally charming.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Accessories:  &LR; A radio tuned to a baseball game, a Frisbee and a
good collection of American short stories.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Beverage matches:  &LR; Chicken and potato salad need a wine that
lifts the lightness of the bird while standing up to the richness
of the salad. Try Hess Select 1997 California Chardonnay ($10.95)
or Talus 1996 California Zinfandel ($8). A good locally brewed
India Pale Ale is another option.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE URBAN PICNIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; As the general manager of Modern Catering, Nancy Frumkes DeLong
spends her days creating cutting-edge food for the San Francisco
Museum of Modern Art and art events. She has designed a picnic that
combines the upscale sensibility of San Francisco dining with the
urban flavor of the city's man-made environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the city, you're around people all the time. You're usually
working, so you're entirely focused on that,'' she says. ``An urban
picnic allows you to look around at where you are, to really notice
where you live.''
</P>
<P>
   Her menu is elegant with simple but sophisticated touches.
Lobster bisque is the centerpiece, served with grilled asparagus
sandwiches with spring onion vinaigrette on pita bread.
</P>
<P>
   The right containers to carry it all are essential.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted this modern, elegant, polished food to merge with
the gritty construction going on in the city right now,'' DeLong
says. So pack the food in a construction worker's lunch pail. Keep
the soup hot and mochas cold in industrial thermoses or vintage
plastic ones. Use good-quality cloth napkins and silverware to add
an upscale contrast to a down-and-dirty city location.
</P>
<P>
   DeLong suggests eating your urban repast in a rooftop garden, on
a fire escape with a view or on the steps of a public edifice like
the Federal Building. Or consider an urban park, such as Yerba
Buena Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Accessories:  &LR; Sleek sunglasses, a chess set and a book on San
Francisco history or architecture.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Beverage matches:  &LR; Choose an off-dry, fruity white or pink wine
to counter the richness of the bisque. Try Hogue 1997 Washington
State Chenin Blanc ($8) or Julian Chivate 1997 Gran Feudo Spanish
Rose ($9).
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; PICNIC ON THE TRAIL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Although her food is a sophisticated fusion of Asian and
Mediterranean ingredients and cooking styles, Oritalia chef Brenda
Buenviaje spends a lot of time in the simple quiet of the woods.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco chef regularly travels to Colorado to visit
her partner and to hike, and also takes to local trails to relieve
the stress of a professional kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Her meal is a vegetarian repast light in weight and ingredients.
It's designed to be satisfying and restorative and to match hikers'
heightened appetites.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a feast for the trail,'' she says. But bring more food
than you think you'll need. ``You're exerting yourself more than
you realize, so you find yourself hungrier than you think you
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Her picnic includes snacks along the way, like steamed vegetable
dumplings. She also creates dolmas of blanched mustard leaves
stuffed with quinoa pilaf, toasted almonds and diced fresh
mozzarella.
</P>
<P>
   Stir-fried udon noodles with morels and fresh peas is the
centerpiece of the picnic at your destination. Pair the noodles
with a portable salad _ try grilled asparagus and pickled beets.
For dessert, consider scones or tarts made with pears, or toss
together a salad of berries or melons with fresh chopped basil,
mint, lemon juice and powdered sugar.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Accessories:  &LR; Bug spray, binoculars and a good guide to local
birds, plants or mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Beverage matches:  &LR; Instead of hauling wine or beer bottles in a
backpack, pack plastic bottles of clear, cold mineral water and
fruit shakes blended with lots of ice just before hitting the
trail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
