<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1836 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SECRET-SALAD-SFCHRON &LR;      05-26 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-SALAD-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECRETS OF SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the
recipe  for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the 
 chef's secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow 
 in optional trim.    &HT;     By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; What's more American than Maine lobster and
martinis? At Ricochet, the two classics are combined into an
innovative and vibrant appetizer.
<P>
   There's a lot going on in chef David Wolfskill's lobster martini
_ sweet chunks of seafood, refreshing strips of English cucumber,
creamy cubes of avocado, tender baby lettuces and bursts of tart
lime segments. The dressing, however, brings these elements
together.
</P>
<P>
   The vinaigrette, which includes vermouth, olives and Champagne
vinegar, is creamy and light because the ingredients are whirled in
a blender.
</P>
<P>
   All the elements of the salad are then coated individually with
the silken dressing, ensuring that everything is properly dressed.
</P>
<P>
   The lobster martini is an impressive appetizer to make at home
because it's relatively easy and much of the work can be done
ahead. If you don't want to use lobster, substitute shrimp or rock
shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   The lobster martini has understandably become a popular
signature dish at this West Portal restaurant. The dining room has
a comfortable lived-in look that could double as a ski lodge. With
mirrors on the walls, bison heads, a fireplace and brick walls,
it's a cozy setting for the creative American menu.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Ricochet Restaurant and Bar, 215 W. Portal Ave. (at 14th &LR; 
 &LR; Avenue), San Francisco; (415) 566-5700. Open for lunch and &LR; 
 &LR; dinner Tuesday-Sunday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; The blender.  &LR; Making the vinaigrette in a blender emulsifies the
ingredients and gives the dressing a silken, creamy texture. It
retains the same consistency even when stored overnight in the
refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lime segments.  &LR; The bursts of tangy lime help to clear and set
up the palate for the next bite.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Applying the vinaigrette.  &LR; Dressing each ingredient separately,
then tossing them together allows the cook to perfectly season each
item.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; RICOCHET'S LOBSTER MARTINI &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces cooked lobster meat
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces peeled and seeded English cucumber, cut into sticks
</P>
<P>
   1 ripe avocado, peeled, pitted and cubed
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces baby lettuces
</P>
<P>
   About 1/3 cup Olive &AMP; Vermouth Vinaigrette (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   1 lime, peeled and segmented
</P>
<P>
   3 dill sprigs, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Salt if needed
</P>
<P>
   4 pimiento-stuffed olives
</P>
<P>
   1 lemon, cut into wedges
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Place the lobster, cucumber, avocado and lettuces in separate
bowls, toss each with some of the vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   Combine all the dressed ingredients in a large bowl; scatter in
the lime segments and dill and toss again. Taste and add more
dressing, and salt, if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the mixture onto serving plates, or into oversized
martini glasses. Top each with an olive and add a lemon wedge on
the side.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; Shrimp or rock shrimp may be used instead of lobster.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 246 calories, &LR;   &LR; 18 g protein, 9 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 16 g fat (2 g saturated), 81 mg cholesterol, 419 mg sodium, 4 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; OLIVE &AMP; VERMOUTH VINAIGRETTE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Note: This dressing keeps well in the refrigerator for several
days. Shake or stir before using.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons Champagne vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup dry vermouth
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons brine from olive jar
</P>
<P>
   1 small shallot, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped pimiento-stuffed olives
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the olive oil, vinegar, vermouth and olive brine in a
blender; add the shallot and blend on high speed for 1 to 2
minutes. Add the olives, salt and pepper and blend again quickly.
Taste and adjust seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer to a jar with a tight-fitting lid and refrigerate until
ready to use.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER TABLESPOON: &LR;   &LR; 49 calories, &LR;   &LR; 0 g protein, 0 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 5 g fat (1 g saturated), 0 mg cholesterol, 61 mg
sodium, 0 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
