<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1837 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COSTLY-PHARMACEUTICAL     05-26 1665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSTLY-PHARMACEUTICAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ARTHRITIS DRUG CREATES DILEMMA OVER COSTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Emma Moreno was in constant pain.
</P>
<P>
   Getting out of bed, climbing stairs, rising up from her chair
were all things she dreaded because of the agony they would cause.
At times, the 42-year-old computer programmer, who suffers from
arthritis, resorted to using a cane to walk.
</P>
<P>
   But in January, her doctor prescribed Celebrex, a new
anti-inflammatory drug. ``It brought me back to life. Simple as
that,'' said Moreno, who lives in Lynn, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   For Moreno, Celebrex is a savior. But for insurance companies,
it's a potential nightmare. At nearly $3 a day, it represents a
crippling budget buster. By contrast, ibuprofen, another
antiarthritis drug, costs only about 20 cents a day.
</P>
<P>
   The dilemma over Celebrex is a familiar and wrenching one for
health insurers, as medical science continues to crank out amazing
drugs that carry mind-boggling price tags. The drug pipeline is
bulging with new potential medications that promise to treat
everything from cancer to the common cold. With every breakthrough,
however, comes a vexing question: Is it worth it?
</P>
<P>
   At stake in the Celebrex saga are billions of dollars spent
every year on nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs. These NSAIDs
have been associated with about 107,000 hospitalizations for
stomach bleeding and other gastric complications and 16,500 deaths
a year, according a 1998 article in the American Journal of
Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Because Celebrex promises far fewer stomach ulcers, its maker,
G.D. Searle &AMP; Co., is marketing it as a leap in technology that
could render ibuprofen obsolete. After four months on the market,
Celebrex is the most successful drug launched in recent history.
</P>
<P>
   For health maintenance organizations and patients who pay for
their own medications, however, Celebrex raises tough questions
about how much one should pay for the reduced risk of ulcers,
particularly given that Celebrex works no better than its
inexpensive ibuprofen counterpart at reducing inflammation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a real dilemma we face,'' said Dr. David Cochran,
associate medical director for Harvard Pilgrim Health Care, the
region's biggest HMO, which like other HMOs faces millions of
dollars in additional spending on Celebrex alone should the drug
catch on with large numbers of its patients. ``A real dilemma.''
</P>
<P>
   A murky area
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed ``superaspirin,'' Celebrex treats arthritis pain by
reducing joint inflammation. Like aspirin, ibuprofen, and other
nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs, Celebrex inhibits the
production of cyclooxygenase, an enzyme that helps the body
manufacture prostaglandins, the primary culprit for inflammation
and pain.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with ibuprofen and other NSAIDs is that they keep
the body from producing ``good'' cyclooxygenase, called Cox-1, as
well as ``bad'' cyclooxygenase, or Cox-2. Among the many benefits
of Cox-1 is that it helps make a thick mucous lining in the stomach
to buffer against gastric acids and prevent ulcers. Because
traditional NSAIDs cut down Cox-1, many people who take ibuprofen
and other NSAIDs experience upset stomachs, gastrointestinal
bleeding, and ulcers.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrex is the first drug to target only Cox-2, which is
responsible for inflammation, while sparing Cox-1. Searle &AMP; Co.
argues that this aspect makes Celebrex safer than other NSAIDs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that Celebrex represents a significant advancement
for millions of Americans,'' said Joseph Papa, president of Searle
U.S., a division of G.D. Searle based in Skokie, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   For HMOs, the argument for Celebrex isn't as clear cut. For one
thing, Celebrex hasn't been proven to work any better than
ibuprofen or naproxen at relieving inflammation. Also, many doctors
are skeptical of Celebrex's claim of reducing ulcers. Clinical
trials involving over 13,000 patients show that 2.7 percent of
patients with rheumatoid arthritis taking Celebrex experienced
``gastroduodenal ulcers'' compared to 17.6 percent of patients who
took naproxen. But the link between these findings, which document
tiny amounts of bleeding, and serious ulcers has not been fully
established, a caveat the US Food and Drug Administration required
Searle to prominently display in its marketing materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is still a murky area despite the fact that it's being
promoted as a panacea,'' said Dr. Joseph Gerstein, medical director
of Tufts Health Plan, the second-largest HMO in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lee Simon, an authority on cyclooxygenase at Beth Israel
Deaconess Medical Center in Boston, who has done research for
Searle, summarizes the scientific case this way: ``Not all
endoscopic proven ulcers have bad outcomes. But everyone who has a
bad outcome has endoscopic ulcers. Since most ulcers are
asymptomatic, it's not clear.''
</P>
<P>
   The value equation
</P>
<P>
   Cochran of Harvard Pilgrim acknowledges that Celebrex can be
good for patients who can't tolerate ibuprofen's side effects. The
question, however, is who those people are. The task isn't as easy
as one might think since upset stomachs can be caused by numerous
problems that are tough to diagnose. Also, there's no way to
predict who will develop ulcers from NSAIDs.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, HMOs have a difficult time deciding who should get
Celebrex, as is often the case for new drugs that have not yet
proven their merits and drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge is in figuring out who is likely to be in
trouble and who can get the most benefit out of Celebrex,'' Cochran
said. ``Frankly, we can't do that perfectly. If we give it to
everybody, it's a bank buster. If we give it to no one, that's not
good either.''
</P>
<P>
   The financial effect of Celebrex on Harvard Pilgrim can be
dramatic. If 50 percent of Harvard Pilgrim's patients on
traditional NSAIDs were to switch to Celebrex, the increased cost
could reach $18.6 million a year, according to Harvard Pilgrim's
internal documents. The hit would come at a bad time for Harvard
Pilgrim, which lost an unprecedented $54 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a wonderful example of something we face over and
over,'' said Dr. Joseph Dorsey, medical director of Harvard
Pilgrim. ``This is a graphic example. But sadly, it is not an
unusual one.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Merck &AMP; Co. received federal approval to begin
marketing Vioxx, another Cox-2 inhibitor that is being sold at the
same wholesale price as Celebrex _ $2.02 a pill.
</P>
<P>
   To help stem the financial bleeding that could result from
Celebrex, Harvard Pilgrim and Tufts are requiring patients to get
approval from the HMOs before they cover the drug, at least for
now.
</P>
<P>
   Searle executives, who are eager to have HMOs allow unrestricted
access to their drug, argue that Celebrex actually helps HMOs save
money by cutting down on the number of hospitalizations resulting
from NSAID-related ulcers and reducing the need for other
medications, such as Prilosec and Zantac, used to treat the side
effects of taking NSAIDs. For some HMOs, Prilosec and Zantac rank
among the most costly medications. An estimated one-third of
patients with osteoarthritis and half of patients with rheumatoid
arthritis who take prescription NSAIDs also take antiulcer
medications, according to Pfizer Inc., which co-markets Celebrex.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you combine the total picture, it always results in
cost-savings,'' said Paul Kiser, an executive director of Searle in
charge of marketing drugs to HMOs. ``For every dollar spent in
NSAIDs, two dollars are spent on treating their side effects.
That's a very significant value equation.''
</P>
<P>
   Most successful launch
</P>
<P>
   Searle's marketing efforts have paid off, creating strong demand
among both physicians and consumers. In the first 15 weeks since
its launch on Jan. 22, more prescriptions have been written for
Celebrex than any other new drug in the history of the
pharmaceutical industry, exceeding even Viagra, the much ballyhooed
anti-impotence drug introduced a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   More than 3.5 million prescriptions were written for Celebrex in
those first 15 weeks, compared with 3.3 million prescriptions for
Viagra during its launch, according to IMS Health in Plymouth
Meeting, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrex has captured 20 percent of the $5 billion annual NSAID
market. It has also eaten away at the $2.7 billion over-the-counter
analgesic market dominated by Tylenol, an acetaminophen that treats
arthritic pain but not inflammation. As a result, the makers of
Tylenol, McNeil Consumer Healthcare in Pennsylvania, have jumped
into the fray, launching a television advertising campaign earlier
this year aimed at preventing Tylenol consumers from switching to
Celebrex.
</P>
<P>
   Searle, in turn, launched a $25 million advertising blitz this
month to promote Celebrex to consumers. The ads, titled ``Enough is
Enough,'' exhort people to ``ask your doctor or pharmacist'' to a
crescendo of lofty music.
</P>
<P>
   These ads, aimed at ginning up patient interest, are a sore
point for HMOs and their doctors, who say they are besieged with
patients demanding expensive new drugs and driving up drug costs,
which have been the fastest growing medical expense for many HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ads often make drugs look very good, but they don't
discuss any downside,'' said a frustrated Dr. Steven Flier, head of
Affiliated Physicians Group, which has 79 doctors in the Boston
area.
</P>
<P>
   While it is unclear how the Celebrex saga will unfold, what's
clear is that the constant tension between drug innovations and
their costs is not going away. Indeed, the drug industry is
currently testing over 1,000 drugs, the largest number ever in
clinical trials, according to the Pharmaceutical Research and
Manufacturers of America in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physicians are increasingly put in the position of having to
deal with patients' often inflated expectations about a new drug,''
Flier said. ``Just because it is new doesn't mean it is an
improvement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 1338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1842 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-ART-BOS     05-26 1518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINORITIES WHO SHATTER MYTHS, GLASS CEILINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By all accounts, Wendell J. Knox is an anomaly.
</P>
<P>
   As the 50-year-old president and chief executive of Abt
Associates Inc., a public policy research firm in Cambridge, Mass.,
Knox controls $140 million in assets and employs 900 workers
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   His career at the firm, which spans three decades, is a telling
example of the changes that have occurred in certain segments of
corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   But, as the African-American chief executive of a predominantly
white firm, Wendell Knox is a rarity: Less than 2 percent of all
private sector executive positions are held by people of color,
even though they now hold substantially more professional,
administrative, and supervisory jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that there are barriers,'' concedes Knox.
``But your own skills and efforts make a big difference, and so do
mentors. In fact, I would say that mentors are a key driver, though
certainly not the only thing that counts.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, minority workers held only 1.8 percent of the private
sector's then 2 million official and managerial jobs, according to
the US Equal Employment Opportunity Commission. By 1997, the number
of minorities in those positions had surged to 12.9 percent of 5.3
million private sector managerial and official jobs, with
African-Americans holding 6 percent; Latinos, 4 percent; and
Asians, 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As those numbers increased, the focus on workplace diversity
moved from how to get minority professionals into the pipeline, to
why some talented and highly committed people of color have not
made it into the executive ranks.
</P>
<P>
   When former US budget director Franklin Raines, an
African-American, announced he was leaving to become chairman and
chief executive of Fannie Mae, a top mortgage company with more
than $390 billion in assets, the nation took notice. And when
Polaroid named Joseph Parham senior vice president as well as
president and chief executive of the firm's eyewear division, some
in the industry applauded the move.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes 47-year-old Kenneth Chenault, set to become chief
executive officer of American Express Co. in two years, a move that
will make him one of the highest ranking African-American at a
Fortune 500 company.
</P>
<P>
   Why do some minority professionals succeed in corporate America,
while others never fully realize their potential?
</P>
<P>
   Intrigued by that question, Harvard Business School professors
David A. Thomas and John J. Gabarro spent six years studying the
careers of 54 senior executives and managers at three major US
firms who had ``made it.'' They also studied 34 white executives,
and minority and white professionals for comparison purposes. The
result, ``Breaking Through: The Making of Minority Executives in
Corporate America,'' (Harvard Business School Press, 1999) is a
massive primer for professionals seeking to understand success, and
employers who wish to foster diversity in their upper ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, lead author and a consultant to several major US firms,
maintains the latest diversity debate is about economic
participation, and what many feel is the pinnacle of success: the
executive office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a corporate society,'' he said. ``Today's heroes
are Microsoft's Bill Gates, and the Silicon Valley entrepreneurs.
They are corporate titans. So, the real test of whether people of
color will be fully integrated into American society is whether
they can achieve positions of power and leadership in for-profit
organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   The book stemmed from Thomas' own frustration trying to locate
material on the upward mobility of black, Latino, and Asian
executives, and finding that just about all the research dealt with
people who had not succeeded. ``The emphasis was on people who were
stuck under the glass,'' he said. ``That is the dominant picture,
but it is not the full picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas and Gabarro examine whether a firm's corporate culture
and an employee's individual talent can intersect in such a way as
to enable some minorities to break through the glass ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   One example of the impact corporate environment can have on a
minority executive's career is Polaroid's Parham. Originally from
West Medford, Mass., Parham, 49, joined the company 26 years ago as
a supervisor on the graveyard shift. A manager and mentor not only
helped him navigate the company's political waters, but also
advised him to get an MBA at a critical juncture in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Parham says he was allowed to stretch, grow, and make mistakes.
He believes the culture at Polaroid, which fostered
experimentation, contributed to his advancement. ``CEOs are not
born CEOs,'' he said. ``They are trained over time. They are given
assignments that stretch them, and when you stretch, you don't
necessarily do everything right.''
</P>
<P>
   Parham recalled one instance when he was put in charge of
launching a new business, but it began to lose money. Angered by
the losses, one supervisor questioned whether Parham should be in
charge. Then, one of Parham's mentors stepped forward. ``He said,
`No one else can do this as well as Joe. Let's give him more time.
He'll turn things around.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas notes that making it into the upper ranks is difficult,
but not impossible, even though many minorities are frequently
forced to prove they are not inferior.
</P>
<P>
   ``With each change of job position or department, they find
themselves needing once again to establish credibility and to
counter and covercome stereotypes,'' writes Thomas. ``Meeting such
challenges requires time, effort, and mental energy not required of
their white colleagues.''
</P>
<P>
   One consequence is that some minorities internalize others'
negative views and lower their own expectations, becoming bitter
and behaving in ways that support stereotypes. Others, said Thomas,
withdraw and fail to seek help or build the kind of alliances that
could help them succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas and Gabarro maintain minority executives who break into
the executive ranks tend to be more motivated by the internal
rewards they receive on the job than by external rewards. They are
challenged by job assignments that produce internal growth, they
were mentored along the way, and, as a result, they have a greater
understanding of the political and social dimensions of their
workplace. Finally, their expertise in a particular field helps
them garner respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone who loves the work will be able to sustain himself
during that period when he feels he should be going faster,'' said
Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Take Clarence Williams, an African-American executive who grew
up in Washington. The son of a homemaker and an engineer whose
aspirations were stymied by racism, he joined a large electronics
firm in New England in the 1970s after a stint in the military and
graduating from a top engineering school.
</P>
<P>
   When Williams walked into the company laboratory the first day,
he thought he knew what to expect. He was not prepared for the
wall-sized banner that greeted him: ``George Wallace _
prosegregation former governor of Alabama, for president!''
</P>
<P>
   But Williams persevered. His love of the work, his skill, and
his mentors all made a difference. ``I think there are some
minorities who have not been in the right place at the right
time,'' reflected Williams. ``Initially, I could have been under a
supervisor who was out to hammer me. Had I been, I could have been
disillusioned very early in my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Richardson, a top performing salesman at a Fortune 500 firm,
was passed over five times for promotions even though his company
was growing rapidly. By contrast, a white male who had joined the
company around the same time, with similar skills, education and
family background, was promoted a year after he was hired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richardson had been the number one sales person in his region,
and was in the top 10 percent in terms of performance for three
years running before he was tapped for a sales management
position,'' said Thomas, who interviewed both Richardson and
Williams for the book. As in the book, the two men are not
identified in this column by their real names.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson stayed and was eventually promoted to a senior
executive position, with control over several hundred employees,
but his climb took longer.
</P>
<P>
   Knox's story is different. He was a 20-year-old senior at
Harvard University when he landed an internship at Abt Associates
in 1969. The company was only four years old and was growing
rapidly, and Knox was able to grow along with it. He was also given
more and more responsibility by supervisors who liked and trusted
him and, later, by owner Clark Abt.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the founder and CEO, there is no question that he (Clark
Abt) was instrumental,'' said Knox. ``I also had other key
relationships with others in the firm _ there were multiple
mentors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
