<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1847 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-RUSSELL-HONDO-BOS     05-26 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RUSSELL-HONDO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVLICEK OWES A LOT TO EX-TEAMMATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- John Havlicek played alongside Bill Russell for seven
seasons and has six rings to show for it. Named one of the top 50
players of all-time and a 13-time All-Star, Havlicek is among the
most honored in the Celtics' pantheon of greats. There's no doubt
in his mind who put him there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy was incredible,'' Havlicek said of Russell. ``No one
won in this town like he did. And make no mistake, it was all
because of him. We all knew that.''
</P>
<P>
   When Havlicek showed up for his first visit to Boston Garden in
1962, it happened to be at a playoff game. The Celtics had made him
their first draft choice, and were giving him and Jack ``The Shot''
Foley a tour of the house. Included was a meeting with Russell.
</P>
<P>
   That meeting was very brief and to the point. Russell had other
things on his mind, like Wilt Chamberlain. But later, when Havlicek
was on the team and carrying the bags and the sound machine, he saw
another side of Russell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a great feeling for the way he played the game and I
think what he liked about me was my work ethic,'' Havlicek said.
``We had a great relationship. I can remember showing up and every
young player in those days wanted a car and a car stereo. I had a
car. He spent one afternoon driving me around town to buy a stereo,
looking to find the best deal. That made an impression on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Havlicek plans to be in on the festivities Wednesday when
Russell is honored on the 30th anniversary of his final season as a
player and his final NBA title. When Havlicek joined the Celtics,
the team already was an NBA champion four years in a row and five
of six. Those titles happened to coincide with the arrival of
Russell.
</P>
<P>
   Havlicek didn't know much about the Celtics' center or, for that
matter, the Celtics in general. Or the NBA. He had little time at
Ohio State for watching what NBA games were available on television
while concentrating on basketball and baseball. He had never even
seen an NBA game until he showed up in Boston that spring day.
</P>
<P>
   Once he became Russell's teammate, he quickly understood what
the fuss was all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing most people don't realize,'' Havlicek said, ``is how
good an offensive player he was. Every play we ran _ and we had
seven of them _ started with Russell and ran through Russell. He
called them when he was the player-coach. That's what a lot of
people don't understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defensively,'' Havlicek went on, ``well, you know he would be
your ace in the hole. You always knew that if you got beat, he
would come over to help. But you also knew that if that happened,
you had to get to his man. The last thing you wanted to have happen
was for the man you were supposed to be guarding, who Russell was
now guarding, miss the shot, which would usually happen, and for
Russell's man, who you were supposed to be guarding, get the
rebound. Then he'd get angry. That would infuriate him. He was
helping you. You had to help him.''
</P>
<P>
   Havlicek also marveled at the way Russell played the mental
game. If there was a two-on-one break, for instance, Russell would
simply eliminate one side of the floor and make it harder for the
break to succeed. The righthanded shooter, for instance, would be
put into a position where he had to shoot into Russell's left hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very smart in a lot of ways people couldn't see or
didn't realize,'' Havlicek said. ``He would try to play his man a
different way every time. One time he'd stay off. Another time he'd
put a body on him. He'd say to himself, `What did I do before that
I can change?'
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing he would do every now and then when we had a
game under control was allow a player to complete a play. Then, if
that same play came up again in a close situation, the player might
be thinking he'll make it when in comes Russell out of nowhere. It
was uncanny the way he did that.''
</P>
<P>
   There also was the celebrated Russell tummy. Before most big
games, Russell had a habit of throwing up. It relieved him, and the
Celtics invariably went on to win the game. They lost very few when
Russell was playing on an empty stomach.
</P>
<P>
   There was one time, however, when the Celtics were preparing in
silence for a seventh game and then went onto the floor for
warmups. Normally, the team would stay out on the floor for the
national anthem and the start of the game. On this day, however,
Red Auerbach summoned the team back to the locker room and Havlicek
had no idea why. He was expecting some big pep talk from the coach,
although, he added, ``For a seventh game, no one has to say very
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Havlicek went on, ``Red told us to sit down. Then he turned to
Russell and asked, `Did you throw up yet?' Russell said no.
Auerbach was very superstitious and he knew that Russell always
threw up before important games. So he sends Russell into the
bathroom and we're all sitting there and we can hear him throwing
up. Then he comes out of the bathroom with a smile.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, the Celtics went on to win the game. They
usually did when Russell was there, regardless of the status of his
digestive system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
