<SLUG> BC-FASHION-FUSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUSION IS THE FASHION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From designer Maurice Malone's new record company to Vogue's
supplement on music and style to rapper Master P's sports
management company, record company, and clothing company, there's a
revolution brewing in popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   Rappers are launching clothing lines. Designers are starting
record labels. Sports magazines are publishing style guides. The
name of the game is fusion, and extending your brand name is the
ticket to greater glory _ and gold.
</P>
<P>
   The heavyweights in these industries are emulating each other's
winning styles to arm themselves for the marketplace of the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
   Who needs an advertising budget anymore? ``You can use your
music videos and your artists on your label to show your clothes,''
says Malone, who has designed sportswear under his Mo Jeans and
Malone Sport labels since 1994. He launched the company Hostile
Takeover Records in December with the rationale: ``You can talk
about your clothes in the songs and hype the name,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, magazines, apparel companies, and musicians share
the same target audience, so the ability to cross over is not
surprising. The popularity of a flashy music producer/rapper like
Sean ``Puffy'' Combs is enough to convince consumers to try his new
clothing line, Sean John, and his new lifestyle/fashion magazine,
Notorious. (He's co-publisher.) Likewise, hip-hop clothing brand
FUBU is focused enough on athletics that its new official NBA
collection _ which features FUBU and NBA team logos on apparel _ is
a natural progression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cross-promotion only makes sense,'' says Chris Wilder,
executive editor of The Source Sports, a one-year-old sports
magazine whose coverage includes sneaker previews and spreads of
athletic clothing. The Source Sports is patterned after its sister
publication The Source, an 11-year-old hip-hop music, cultural, and
political magazine. ``The same people who are buying hip-hop
clothing are buying hip-hop music'' and watching sports, says
Wilder.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is gaining momentum at a time when boundaries that
have traditionally divided areas of culture are breaking down.
``Fashion has become part of the entertainment world,'' says Todd
Boyd, a professor of critical studies at the University of Southern
California's School of Cinema and Television. ``You don't have to
be an actor or a musician to be a celebrity anymore. Supermodels
are very visible celebrities.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it's supermodels who've been bumped off the covers
of many fashion magazines by a new force in fashion _ pop and
hip-hop divas. For Vogue's Music &AMP; Style supplement in April (which
featured stories on the music and fashion industries), the magazine
chose singer Lauryn Hill for its cover.
</P>
<P>
   The supplement is ``the logical evolution of the Hollywood and
fashion collision that's going on now,'' says Katherine Betts,
Vogue's fashion news director. ``It seems designers who reached out
to Hollywood are now reaching out to the music world. . . . And a
lot of young musicians, especially in the hip-hop world, want to
wear designer clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Sports and music have always been connected to fashion in
various ways, of course. ``Sports has probably been the main
influence on men's fashion in the 20th century,'' says Valerie
Steele, chief curator of the museum at the Fashion Institute of
Technology in New York. ``Especially the mania for sneakers and
sweats.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Hilfiger, the brother of designer Tommy Hilfiger, is also
vice president of public relations for Tommy Jeans and founder of
the record label AH! ``In the '60s, everybody wanted to check out
the Stones and Jimi Hendrix to see what they had on. Rock stars
always made fashion statements,'' he says. ``I remember Tommy used
to look at album covers and wonder where to find Mick Jagger's
snakeskin boots or leather pants.''
</P>
<P>
   But recent cultural developments have made the combination of
the trio all the more appealing financially. With business casual
dress codes gaining popularity in the workplace, there are more
opportunities for consumers to wear sports- and music-inspired
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no longer ghettoized as a youth thing,'' says Steele.
``Suddenly Wall Street guys are wearing baseball caps backwards (to
and from work). The insignia of being cool and hip is wearing
sporty clothes. The clothes have all the association of people who
are strong and physically confident _ and by extension, virile and
competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   The reign of hip-hop as a dominant cultural force has also
played a major role. ``Hip-hop is a materialistic lifestyle. To
express themselves in their songs, artists talk about the cars they
drive and the clothes they wear,'' says Malone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason a lot of artists are going into fashion themselves
is because they realized they were making money for other companies
by talking about their clothes in their songs. They weren't getting
paid for it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, many of the people involved in the trend don't have
the expertise or background necessary to become CEOs of record or
clothing companies. But in today's society, experts say, it doesn't
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more money you have, the more power you have. In our
culture, you can market yourself in any way you want if you have
enough backing,'' says Jill Carey, assistant professor of fashion
history at the Institute of Fashion Technology at Lasell College in
Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole trend toward one company doing everything has been
evolving over the past 15 years. It's a mega mentality. It kind of
reminds me of Wal-Mart. That's a mega store. These are mega people.
And I don't think we're critical anymore. . . . Andy Hilfiger?
There's no negative connotations associated with him. I don't know
what he sounds like. But most people are open to listening.''
</P>
<P>
   At least two trendsetters say their motives for launching record
companies aren't strictly financial. Malone, a Detroit native, has
been involved in music for years. In the early 1990s, he operated a
night club and a clothing store called the Hip Hop Shop, where he
hosted open-mike nights for rap artists to compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music is something I knew I would do eventually,'' he says.
``I wanted to wait until I could finance the project and make it
work.'' So far, Malone has signed Proof, a Detroit rapper, and
Bullets and Gunsmoke (BAG), a rap group from Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Hilfiger, who sings and plays the guitar and bass, has also
been linked to music for years. ``I played in a lot of bands,''
says Hilfiger, who plans to release his own classic rock album next
year. ``When I started working for Tommy, I started dressing a lot
of groups. My department became an A&AMP;R department. I got demo tapes
and letters. Musicians wanted sponsorships, product placements, and
they wanted to be models. We became a whole music department
through fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Before long, Hilfiger was dressing Snoop Doggy Dogg and Coolio
for ``Saturday Night Live'' and consulting with Quincy Jones's
record label Qwest Records. ``Quincy told me to start bringing him
music,'' says Hilfiger, who has about 1,000 demo tapes in his
office. So Hilfiger started AH! last September. ``I'm a talent
scout for Quincy. I sign the group. He distributes and markets
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hilfiger empire continues its expansion plans. Tommy
Hilfiger has declared 1999 the year of music since 90 percent of
his promotions are music-related. The company is sponsoring concert
tours for the Rolling Stones, Lilith Fair, and Britney Spears. All
those musicians will wear Hilfiger items onstage. Its ads in
fashion magazines depict staged scenes from those concerts.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also financing an upcoming exhibit in New York at
the Costume Institute of the Metropolitan Museum of Art tentatively
titled ``Icons of Rock Style.'' The exhibit, which will run from
December to March 2000, will spotlight classic rock performers and
their influence on fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music is an integral part of my life and my career
inspiration,'' says Tommy Hilfiger. ``As a company, it makes sense
for us to be involved in the music industry because music is of
interest to our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Where will the trend end? Will rappers one day own sports
franchises? Malone says he plans to produce movies eventually.
``That's what I originally wanted to do before I got into
fashion,'' he says. ``After `Star Wars' came out, I intended to be
a special-effects artist.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment though, Malone has his hands full. With so many
professional basketball and football players hanging out at his New
York office to check out his latest sportswear designs, Malone is
scheming. ``I'm really interested in getting these guys some
suits,'' he says. ``They need special sizes. When they go to their
own tailor, the tailors don't do that good a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking `Hmm. There's a good market.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
