<HEADLINE>
IN RETIREMENT, NUN STILL FINDS INSPIRATION ON CANVAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 50 years as a member of the Dominican order of St.
Catharine, Kentucky, Sister Dorothy Briggs's greatest love is still
what it's been almost all her 75 years _ trying to create beauty on
an empty canvas.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after decades of teaching in elementary school, high school
and college _ a typical career for nuns of her generation _ Briggs
has retired to Massachusetts, where she can devote hours to her
passion for painting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when I was a kid my mother couldn't get me out of the
house sometimes because all I wanted to do was paint,'' said
Briggs, whose work has been shown in churches in several states.
``I can get a lot of what I feel inside of me on the canvas. It's a
very powerful way of expressing yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Briggs is a fast painter, sometimes producing a painting in an
hour or two. She even took a 10-year sabbatical from to 1978 to
1988 just to have more time to paint. She paints landscapes and
portraits and her genre has ranged from bold expressionism to stark
realism. She has painted in oil and water colors and dabbled in
pencil and pen.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in what was one of her favorite projects as an
artist, she painted portraits of three dozen children who live on
her block. ``They were beside themselves when they saw their
portraits hanging in an art show,'' Briggs said with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   But Briggs hasn't spent her entire time as a nun just painting.
Besides teaching, Briggs also founded the Massachusetts chapter of
Citizens United for Rehabilitation of Errants, a national prison
reform group.
</P>
<P>
   She started the group after befriending a prisoner at the
Massachusetts Correctional Institute in Walpole.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have this massive prison industry that has no impact that I
can see on reducing violence in this country,'' said Briggs. These
days, Briggs is active in a campaign to reduce the telephone fees
charged to the relatives of prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really unfair because these aren't rich people we're
talking about,'' said Briggs, who holds two degrees in painting
from Italian universities. ``It's really a telephone tax.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of her time, though, is spent in her studio. ``I've been
very fortunate to be able to spend a big part of life working at
the thing I love to do,'' she said. ``Everyone should be able to
say that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
RELIGION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _The Vatican has forced a retired Canadian bishop with a
reputation as a reform-minded activist to withdraw as featured
speaker at an upcoming conference in Atlanta of the International
Federation of Married Catholic Priests.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Remi De Roo, the former bishop of Victoria, British
Columbia canceled his appearance because the Vatican said the July
conference includes several groups that dissent from church
teaching on issues ranging from married priests to the ordination
of women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that the mere presence of a Catholic bishop, let
alone the fact that he is a featured speaker, would be a great
source of possible scandal and confusion to the faithful,'' stated
a letter to De Roo from the apostolic nuncio's Canadian office.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, dated April 8, was published in the most recent
edition of the National Catholic Reporter, a weekly newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the desire of the Holy See that you remove your name
from the proposed speakers' list and refrain from attending the
aforementioned conference,'' said the letter signed by Monsignor
Luigi Bonazzi.
</P>
<P>
   De Roo could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   But organizers of the conference, which is expected to draw 300
activists from different countries, blasted the Vatican's move.
</P>
<P>
   ``Human rights and reconciliation is the theme for our Atlanta
meeting and we are very disappointed that the Vatican has chosen to
run away from dialogue which could bring about great healing to the
massive numbers of men and women who have been hurt by insensitive
church rules and policies,'' said Anthony Padovano, vice president
of the International Federation.
</P>
<P>
   _An accrediting agency has withdrawn its threat of placing
Hellenic College/Holy Cross School of Theology on probation in the
wake of a sexual abuse scandal involving a seminarian at the Greek
Orthodox school in Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The New England Association of Schools and Colleges said it was
satisfied with the changes proposed by Hellenic College to clarify
the role of the Greek Orthodox Church in internal school affairs,
including personnel decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The church's national leader allegedly had four priests fired
because they refused to cover up an incident of alleged sexual
misconduct by a seminarian at the theology school, sources said.
Their firings two years ago sparked heated controversy and calls
for the resignation of Archbishop Spyridon, the embattled leader of
the nation's 2 million Greek Orthodox.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commission commends Hellenic College/Holy Cross for taking
seriously and working hard to respond to our concerns,'' stated a
letter from the accrediting agency to the school.
</P>
<P>
   Dates
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(The Spiritual Life, c/o Diego Ribadeneira, Box 2378, Boston, MA
02107-2378; e-mail religion(at)globe.com.)
</P>
