<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF ONLY OUR LEADERS ENTHUSED ABOUT SCHOOLS AS MUCH AS SPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week's Globe had these Page One headlines: ``State leaders,
Menino back Red Sox aid,'' and ``All roads led back to
Foxborough.'' Last week also saw this headline atop the Metro
section: ``Budget faulted for lack of summer school buses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``State leaders'' was about using taxpayer money _ up to $200
million _ for a new Fenway Park. ``All roads'' was on the
``heroic'' effort to keep the Patriots in Massachusetts by dangling
$70 million in public funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Budget faulted'' was about how Boston has mandatory summer
school for students who are failing to meet standards, but no money
for buses. Most mandatory summer programs provide buses.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday on Page One the Globe had a photo of Governor Paul
Cellucci throwing a football to a Patriots' official and a photo
inside of Senate President Thomas Birmingham signaling a touchdown
at the ceremony celebrating the signing of the $70 million bill. It
makes you curious what the news would look like if this enthusiasm
were turned toward the schools. The following is a fictitious
rewrite of last week's news, adapted from the actual stories:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --State leaders, Menino Back school aid
</P>
<P>
   Two days after the Boston Public Schools announced plans to
build a new system, the state's top political leaders and Boston
Mayor Thomas M. Menino all agreed Tuesday that the schools should
get substantial public aid to complete the project.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran also signaled his tentative
support for giving the schools more state aid for infrastructure
than the $70 million the New England Patriots whined for as part of
the deal to construct a new football stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``A college degree is worth $600,000 more over a lifetime than a
high school diploma,'' Finneran said. ``Today's 55,000 Boston
Public Schools students would make $33 billion more with BAs. That
means far more in income taxes than the $10 million a year the
Patriots say they contribute. So the potential economic impact of
good schools certainly seems greater.''
</P>
<P>
   Finneran added that because the schools are in an urban
environment, infrastructure needs will be greater, including
buildings, smaller classes, teacher quality, and after-school
programs. The system, so skewed that Boston Latin admissions became
a race war, earned a D from Education Week for resource equity.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran said he supports giving Menino new taxation powers as a
way to help the city assemble the best schools possible. ``We gave
the mayor revenue streams for the new convention center to help
fund the purchase of the site and as an incentive to approve the
new hotels that would be needed,'' Finneran said. ``I'm open to
giving the city the tools it needs for this project, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --All roads led back to public schools
</P>
<P>
   It took just one day to debate and approve a bill that should
make Massachusetts public schools a beacon of education.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday's vote may never have happened if a couple of old
friends had not bumped into each other in a Washington hotel
ballroom last December, an encounter that sparked a six-month
campaign to keep families from fleeing to private schools.
</P>
<P>
   At a dinner honoring Nobel Prize winner David Trimble and John
Hume, Boston lawyer Paul G. Kirk Jr. spotted his pal Daniel Rooney,
the Pittsburgh Steelers president and an outspoken critic of
National Football League teams getting taxpayer money ahead of
schools. The NFL's worth would make the Fortune 200.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went over and gave him a little tease about his bleeding
heart,'' Kirk said. ``Dan said, `Well, what are you going to do for
the 64 percent of fourth graders who do not read at grade level?''
</P>
<P>
   Vouchers and charter schools looked like a done deal. But Rooney
and Kirk, longtime friends through Irish charity circles, were
already working the phones. Rooney started with Governor Paul
Cellucci. ``Then I talked to Father Monan next,'' Rooney said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. J. Donald Monan, the chancellor of Boston College, was
also tired of sports subsidies, given the athletic scandals on his
own campus. He was a significant force among the widening group of
mostly Irish Catholic executives trying to spread the faith that
the public schools could be saved for the Bay State. He gave Rooney
names of people to call, people whom would become part of the inner
core of civic leaders known as Operation School Back _ rallying the
business community to assure full college aid for every graduate,
if and when a quality system got built.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston group crafted an opinion piece for the Globe that
triggered strong statements of support, most importantly from
Beacon Hill. The seed planted by Kirk and Rooney had sprouted.
Everyone signed on to fully support the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci went on the set of ``The Tonight Show.'' Jay Leno gave
a nod to the governor during his opening monologue, asking him what
was happening with vouchers and charters.Cellucci sat smiling with
his thumb up in the air. ``They're staying,'' the governor shouted,
``in the public schools!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Budget faulted for lack of sports subsidies
</P>
<P>
   In many urban school districts across the country, pro sports
teams have had a free ride. But in Boston, where summer school is
mandated for the first time, the Red Sox and the Patriots will have
to find their own way to finance their projects.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians say they can't provide welfare to teams when the
parents of the 6,500 children in grades 2, 5, 6, 7 and 8 have to
scramble to change job schedules, work out baby-sitting deals with
relatives, and piece together a day that will have their child in
summer school four hours a day _ and safe afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The criteria change was met with widespread confusion among
teams. But Red Sox legend Ted Williams said, ``I can't wait to see
the new school system when it's done. I want Boston to have the
best. If any city needed new schools, they need it. I won't shed a
tear if the fans put schools ahead of a new Fenway Park.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
