<HEADLINE>
MAINE CHEF SHARES THE SMOKY SECRETS OF GRILLING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (Includes recipes)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Maine _ By the time Sam Hayward builds a fire in the
grill at Fore Street restaurant and begins trimming a hanger steak,
another cook has slipped beside him to bone a 35-pound Gulf of
Maine halibut that was just delivered. A third starts slicing
enormous loins from a Caribbean yellowfin tuna that has such an
intense blue-red color, you have to look closely to see it's not
beef.
</P>
<P>
   All of these are destined for the grill or a wood-fueled oven _
both lit early in the day and stoked late into the evening, the
oven with kiln-dried mixed hardwood, the grill with applewood.
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow, like today, the room and even the street outside will
carry traces of the wood's irresistible smoky essence. The scent
will be clinging to the lilacs and seeping into everyone's sweater.
Pretty soon it will be everywhere, as the nation begins its
summerlong enchantment with this American backyard aroma. But at
Fore Street, where grilling takes place in an open kitchen in full
view of the customers, wood rules the menu all year long.
</P>
<P>
   Fore Street, which sits on Portland's revitalized waterfront,
resembles a theater, with cooks in the front of the restaurant
working the grill and the wood oven, while most of the diners
overlook the action from a mezzanine one step up. By day, the place
feels like a play in dress rehearsal, more relaxed than the real
show.
</P>
<P>
   Hayward's fire, for instance, began without much fanfare. He
combined an applewood log with some hardwood charcoal and crumbled
three of Tuesday's menus to give the flames a head start.
</P>
<P>
   While the cooks on either side prepare the dinner menu, Hayward
continues his trimming instruction. The lesson takes place at the
restaurant's grill, which is used intermittently during the day. By
dinner, hanger steaks will be sizzling alongside large, thick
triangles of the tuna and perhaps a venison steak or a flattened
whole quail. Ingredients that can't take the intense heat of the
grill but will benefit from some smoke _ like a dish of
rope-cultured mussels or jumbo oyster mushrooms _ are cooked in the
wood oven.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever isn't smoky on the menu complements what is: clusters
of Maine fiddleheads, Damariscotta River oysters, crisp arugula
with balsamic vinaigrette, a soft-shell crab dusted with cornmeal,
strands of sauteed broccoli rabe, a few grilled asparagus layered
with wild Maine ramps and sorrel.
</P>
<P>
   The hanger steak is a key player on the restaurant's menu. When
owners Sam Hayward, Dana Street, and Boston businessman Victor Leon
opened Fore Street two years ago, they wanted a signature grilled
steak. After some experimentation, says Hayward, the restaurant's
chef, hanger steak won the billing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking for something relatively inexpensive that
would distinguish us,'' he says. ``We tried skirt steaks. We
planned on a big, thick porterhouse for two. The skirt steak
required more trimming than the hanger, and it was quite chewy,
even though the flavor was great. Some people equate quality with
tenderness, and we didn't want to fight that cultural prejudice. We
ran the porterhouse, and sometimes it would sell and other times it
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanger has ``a deeply satisfying beefy flavor,'' Hayward says.
It looks something like brisket, he says, though it's not lean.
``There's a fair amount of granular suet-like fat.'' As the fat
melts on the grill, it bastes the meat.
</P>
<P>
   Hanger is called ``onglet'' in France, where it appears mostly
on bistro menus. ``It's also called the `butcher's cut' because the
butcher often took it home,'' Hayward says. Fore Street's hangers
are shipped here from Boston wholesaler T. F. Kinnealey (who has a
retail shop in Milton, Mass.).
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of trimming seems daunting, but it becomes less so
as you watch the tip of Hayward's sharp knife barely scraping
through the fat and sinew to reveal lean meat. ``Each hanger can be
divided into two lobes,'' he says, ``once the seam that anchors
them together is removed. A hanger weighs 1 1/2 to 2 pounds, and
there's 40 percent trim.'' The trimmings will be browned in a hot
oven for sauce.
</P>
<P>
   He removes the seam of sinew and, as predicted, the meat falls
into two lobes. Then he trims each lobe until he has two lean,
slender tails, similar to stubby pork tenderloins, which make two
10-ounce portions. By day's end, Fore Street will have about 60 of
these on hand.
</P>
<P>
   The steaks go into a marinade of pureed, caramelized shallots,
where they sit overnight. Now Hayward grills a steak that has been
marinating since the day before. He lets it fall, clinging shallots
and all, onto the hot grill. He turns it frequently, but it hardly
spends 10 minutes on the fire. Because Fore Street sells so many
orders of hanger, the steaks are always on hand, waiting in the
marinade.
</P>
<P>
   As he turns the meat, Hayward explains that this fire isn't as
hot as the restaurant normally uses. ``But it's probably as hot as
a fire at home. I use a Weber at home.'' Like all chefs, he would
like to redesign the Weber to make it friendlier for the cook. He
would add a rollback hood. On his charcoal-fed Weber, he has to
lift off the top and set it somewhere when it isn't in use.
</P>
<P>
   Fore Street's grill is 6 feet long and about 10 inches deep. The
racks pull off in sections, so the cooks can stoke one side of the
fire while food cooks on another.
</P>
<P>
   He pulls the steak off the grill with tongs. ``Hanger is
traditionally sliced with the grain,'' he explains. ``We slice it
against the grain.'' The meat is medium-rare, with long
brisket-like strands, as promised. ``If you cook it to well done,
it's no longer tender.'' He heaps the slices in the center of the
plate, then spoons over a sauce made from the browned meat
trimmings, white wine, and a veal stock simmered to a gelatinous
quality.
</P>
<P>
   At dinner, the hanger comes with several accompaniments: mashed
potato gratin, sauteed broccoli rabe, steamed turnips, and, in
season, fiddleheads, all set around the steak in a no-nonsense
presentation. Hayward dislikes anything pretentious. ``I was served
a steak that sat on a potato cake recently,'' he says. ``When I cut
into the meat, the potatoes went flying to the edge of the dish.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayward made his reputation by treating ingredients almost
reverentially, hardly interfering with their inherent flavors, and
never subscribing to high architecture on the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Taste counts for a lot. He calls the hanger sauce ``a real jus
with a roasty flavor.'' He believes that when meat is trimmed, some
of the flavor is lost. The point of the sauce, he says, ``is to try
to reincorporate that taste, rather than adding a lot of extraneous
flavors.''
</P>
<P>
   Marinades, too, are used to strengthen flavors, rather than to
indiscriminately add tastes that conflict with the food.
``Marinades also help things stay moist when you're using a big
heat source.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayward, 50, came to cooking from the music business. Thirty
years ago, he played double bass with a rock band that opened for
Bonnie Raitt and J. Geils. Maybe that's why words like ``harmony''
and ``balance'' keep creeping into his descriptions of food.
</P>
<P>
   A loyal southern Maine clientele has followed Hayward from his
first restaurant, 22 Lincoln in Brunswick, to the Harraseeket Inn
in Freeport, and now to Fore Street. In this establishment, as in
the others, his purveyors play an important role. A former
dishwasher at 22 Lincoln now supplies him with much of his produce.
Farmers and growers from all over Maine bring in chickens, wild
mushrooms, and game birds.
</P>
<P>
   Quail from Foggy Ridge Game Bird Farm in Warren are lying in a
bowl on the table. Before Hayward transfers the birds to the
cutting board, he wipes it with a cloth dipped into a mild bleach
solution. ``We do this every time we go from one meat to another,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly, in a dozen cuts, he removes a quail's backbone,
flattens the bird with its flesh side up, lifts out the center
breastbone, removes the rib bones that hug the breasts, and bones
the thighs. He makes short cuts in the meat and pulls out the
bones. ``We were always taught scrape, scrape, scrape,'' he says.
``I think that breaks up the meat. Get in there and do a little
surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   The birds are marinated in shallots, maple syrup, salt, pepper,
olive or peanut oil, tamari, and crushed juniper berries. Hayward
sets the quail skin-side down over the hot coals, the ``knees''
tucked up to the breastbone, and the wings tucked behind. The
flattened quail is called ``spatchcocked,'' and the technique can
be applied to chicken, too.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1868 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-GRILL-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     05-26 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-GRILL-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 PORTLAND, Maine: ... chicken, too.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A spatchcocked quail seems to fit neatly into the hollow of
Hayward's tongs. When he turns it, the skin is caramel-colored. ``A
little sugar in the marinade tends to make quail darker,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   For the diner, the quail dish includes a thick slice of blanched
and grilled celery root, a slice of grilled foie gras, giant
grilled morel mushrooms, and a little syrupy game stock made with
mushroom trimmings and Madeira.
</P>
<P>
   Beautiful ingredients, honestly cooked.
</P>
<P>
   Only the backyard is missing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
GRILLED MUSSELS IN ROASTED GARLIC BUTTER
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A dish similar to this is cooked inside the Fore Street
restaurant's wood oven, which gives the mussels a faintly smoky
quality. It's one of the most popular dishes on the menu. Chef Sam
Hayward says that you can adapt the technique to the grill using
two skillets. He has an old camper's trick to keep the skillet from
getting ruined on the open fire: ``Rub the bottom of the pan with
Ivory soap, and the sooty black stuff comes off easily.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 head garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) unsalted butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup dry vermouth
</P>
<P>
   1 pound mussels, debearded and thoroughly rinsed
</P>
<P>
   Squeeze of lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oven to 450 degrees. Rub the garlic with oil and set it
in a baking dish. Roast the garlic for 1 hour or until it is very
tender. When it is cool enough to handle, pull off the cloves and
squeeze the garlic flesh onto a cutting board.
</P>
<P>
   With the tip of a blunt knife, scrape the garlic until it is
broken up. Transfer it to a bowl and blend in the butter.
</P>
<P>
   Scrape the garlic butter onto a piece of plastic wrap and roll
the wrap around the butter to form a short column. Refrigerate the
butter for several hours or until it is firm.
</P>
<P>
   Cut 2 thick slices of butter and set them aside. (Use the
remaining butter to serve over grilled fish, pork, or chicken.)
</P>
<P>
   Light the grill. When the coals are gray, pour the vermouth into
the bottom of a heavy skillet with a flameproof handle. Add the
mussels _ make only one layer _ and sprinkle them with lemon juice,
salt, pepper, and the butter.
</P>
<P>
   Invert a second skillet on top of the first and set the skillets
on the hot fire. As soon as you see steam escape from the pan,
remove the top and shake the pan constantly so the butter
emulsifies with the mussels' liquor.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle with parsley and wrap a napkin around the handle of the
pan. Serve at once, in the skillet.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2 as an appetizer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
GRILLED SPATCHCOCKED QUAIL IN MAPLE-TAMARI MARINADE
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Spatchcocked'' means flattened, and in order to do that with
poultry, you have to remove the breastbone that runs between the
breasts. If you like, you can also remove the feathery rib bones on
the breasts and the thigh bone. The marinade, adapted from Fore
Street's, will work with Cornish hens and small chickens, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 shallots, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons pure maple syrup
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil or peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons tamari
</P>
<P>
   2 juniper berries, wrapped in cloth and crushed with bottom of
skillet
</P>
<P>
   8 quail, or 4 Cornish hens, or 1 (3 1/2-pound) chicken
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a bowl, combine the shallots, maple syrup, salt, pepper,
olive oil, tamari, and juniper berries. Stir them just to mix them
thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   Set the quail on a cutting board, breast-side down.
</P>
<P>
   Using a scissors, cut up each side of the backbone. Push the cut
edges open. You will be looking straight down at the breastbone.
Make a 1-inch cut at the wishbone end until you reach a purple
bone. Pick the bird up in your hands and fold back both cut edges
of backbone so you break the flesh away from the breastbone. With
your fingers, pull out the purple triangular breastbone. (You can
stop there or continue boning, removing the long, slightly rubbery
membrane that runs to the bottom of the breastbone. Then remove the
feathery bones that cling to the breast and the thigh bones.)
</P>
<P>
   Tuck the wing pinions behind the breastbone. Bend the legs so
the ``knees'' of the bird meet in the center of the breasts.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange the quail in a large shallow dish and pour the marinade
over them. Turn them in the marinade until they are coated all
over. Cover tightly with plastic wrap and refrigerate for at least
24 hours or as long as 48 hours, turning them several times.
</P>
<P>
   Light the grill. Remove the birds from the refrigerator. When
the coals turn gray, set the birds on the grill, skin-side down.
</P>
<P>
   Grill the birds for 10 minutes, then turn them and continue
cooking, turning every 10 minutes, until they are cooked through.
The quail will take about 15 minutes. (The hens will take 20
minutes, the chicken 35 minutes. You will need to cover the grill
when cooking the hens and chicken.)
</P>
<P>
   Remove the birds from the grill. Cut them into quarters and
serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
HANGER STEAK IN CARAMELIZED SHALLOT MARINADE
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hanger is the signature steak at Fore Street. If you can't find
it, ``flank is more dense, but it will work the same way,'' says
Hayward. The sauce takes time (and real veal stock). At home, you
can improvise with chicken stock, but make sure you roast the steak
trimmings to add to the sauce later. At the restaurant, each diner
gets half a hanger steak, but it's such rich meat that this
adaptation divides each whole steak into 4 portions instead.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 whole (1 1/2 pounds) hanger steak
</P>
<P>
   6 shallots, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   Trimmings from hanger steak
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil, for sprinkling
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 carrot, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 stalk celery, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup white wine
</P>
<P>
   2 cups veal stock
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Remove the center ``seam'' from the hanger steak so the meat
falls into 2 lobes. Thoroughly trim each lobe, setting the
trimmings aside. Cover the steaks with plastic wrap and refrigerate
them.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oven to 450 degrees. In a roasting pan, combine the
shallots, garlic, and steak trimmings. Drizzle with oil and toss
thoroughly. Roast them in the hot oven for 45 minutes, turning
often, until the steak trimmings are golden and the shallots are
caramelized.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the trimmings and garlic from the pan (reserve them for
the sauce). Puree the shallots and let them cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   Rub the meat with olive oil, shallots, salt, and pepper. Cover
the meat tightly with plastic wrap. Refrigerate for at least 24
hours and as long as 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a saucepan, melt the butter and cook the onion,
carrot, and celery for 10 minutes, stirring often, until they
soften. Add the wine and bring to a boil. Let the mixture simmer
for 5 minutes. Add the veal stock, meat trimmings, and garlic, and
bring to a boil. Lower the heat and simmer, skimming often, for 30
minutes or until the sauce reduces and is flavorful. Strain the
sauce into a clean saucepan and set it aside.
</P>
<P>
   Light the grill. When the coals turn gray, add the hanger steaks
and cook them, turning often, for about 10 minutes or until they
are medium-rare inside.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the steaks from the grill. Reheat the sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Slice the steaks against the grain and arrange the slices on 4
dinner plates. Spoon some sauce over each serving. Serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
