<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1869 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      05-26 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVIL GENIUS? JOKESTERS AND MEN IN BLACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Sam Kinison died in 1992 after a drunk driver plowed
head-on into his car, more than a few folks saw it as a classic
slice of God-don't-like-ugly payback. Kinison was the
mailbox-shaped, high-decibel comedian who used his 15 minutes to
spew some of the most mean-spirited ``jokes'' in recent memory at
anyone who happened to fall onto his indiscriminate hit list. He
made viciously offensive AIDS jokes, had more ``bitches'' in his
act than your local animal shelter, and was temporarily banned from
NBC for a crucifixion skit. Even his younger brother's suicide was
fair game.
</P>
<P>
   But beneath the bile, was Kinison a comic genius? That's the
contention of some of today's best-known comedians in this month's
GQ, which is devoted to all things comic. ``While the casual
observer remembers him as the comic equivalent of a monster
truck,'' writes Lucy Kaylin, ``the pros uphold him as a total
original.'' Most say what made Kinison special was his delivery _ a
paint-peeling scream fashioned at backwater holy-roller revivals
where, as a Pentecostal preacher, he first learned to work a room.
Richard Belzer says literally shrieking at an audience was more
theater than stand-up, and Chris Rock maintains that Kinison's
trademark scream made him ``the only guy in the last 25, 30 years
to do something new comedically.'' Kaylin makes an
almost-persuasive argument, but there's still the sense that
Kinison may simply be another recipient of what photographer Cecil
Beaton once said also benefited James Dean, Marilyn Monroe, and
Jesus Christ _ ``a kind of recompense for dying young.'' From Joan
of Arc to Tupac Shakur, nothing so benefits a lasting reputation as
an early death.
</P>
<P>
   In the same issue, Devin Friedman highlights the best black
comedians white America has never heard of _ unless they're fans of
Black Entertainment Television's ``Comic View'' or HBO's old ``Def
Comedy Jam.'' From Bernie Mac to Cedric the Entertainer to D.L.
Hughley (who sadly has watered down his bawdy,
hands-inside-the-vehicle-at-all-times act for his TV sitcom, ``The
Hughleys''), a host of African-American comedians are selling out
arenas and bringing in the Benjamins, all without mainstream or
crossover _ read ``white'' _ support. Still, comedians such as Mac
crave integrated audiences even though what Friedman dubs ``the new
chitlin circuit'' keeps Mac in those snappy suits he favors.
``Segregated comedy is sad,'' he says. ``People are missing out.
Too many people paved the way for us for this (expletive) to be
going on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heart &AMP; Soul, the sistahgirl health magazine, offers its special
section on men, and how women can better understand them. (Not
surprisingly. it's a pretty small section.) It's a fairly typical
woman's health magazine subject, although since this is geared
toward black women, there are headings like ``Why Is He Frontin?''
in a story about deciphering men's moods. Much better, ``From Boys
to Men'' considers positive ways to raise productive sons. It's an
especially timely piece in the wake of the school shootings that
have many wondering about the mindset of today's boys and teens.
But it's also mindful of the special challenges in raising black
boys who must shake off society's racism as well as antiquated and
myopic notions of what truly constitutes being a man.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the New York Times's Maureen Dowd tagged Nancy
Reagan's unscheduled on-air call to ABC News during President
Clinton's first inauguration as ``the political equivalent of the
hand-from-the-grave scene in `Carrie,' '' I've been an unabashed
fan. The comment was a little nasty, laugh-out-loud funny, pop
referential, and so dead on target, it was a wonder anyone had the
gumption to think such a thought, let alone put it in print. It
provided a delicious taste of things to come when, two years later,
Dowd landed a coveted op-ed spot, and began her biweekly column,
``Liberties,'' in the Times. Of course, if you believe Gay Jervey
in Brill's Content, it's easy to find Dowd amusing when you aren't
caught in the crosshairs of her column.
</P>
<P>
   Dowd, who won the Pulitzer Prize last month, has laid to waste
everyone from President Clinton to Woody Allen, but her critics
believe she too often favors style over substance. ``Few people
question Dowd's talent or her column's entertainment value. But
does she inform?'' Jervey contends. ``Dowd's critics suggest that
she only goes skin deep, and that she would never sacrifice a punch
line for evenhandedness. However keen her observations _ and there
are few better at crystallizing character, nuance, and scene _ her
obsession with personality leads her to shortchange discussion of
substantive issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The notoriously private Dowd is also taken to task for keeping
such a low profile. She doesn't give interviews, stays off the
political talk show merry-go-round, and even turned down Robert
Redford when he asked her to do a cameo in his film, ``Quiz Show.''
Yes, Jervey makes some good points in showing Dowd has, at times,
been a little fast and loose in jumping to her sharply worded
conclusions. But all the caterwauling begins to sound like so much
sour grapes. Dowd has a Pulitzer, and may well be the most-read
columnist in the Times. She's the Beltway's undisputable Queen of
Buzz _ so what if she has better things to do than wax
wrong-and-strong with the Sunday morning talking heads? Only in
this age of eager, unworthy celebrity, could someone be scolded for
daring to maintain her privacy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
