A1871 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASIANS-SPYING-HNS &LR;      05-26 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIANS-SPYING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIAN AMERICANS FEAR SPY SCANDAL WILL CREATE A BACKLASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANNIE NAKAO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Ching-Sen Yeung, who has molded thousands of new
Americans here as a teacher of citizenship classes for the past two
decades, bristles at what she sees as a cloud of suspicion settling
over Chinese Americans in the wake of the congressional probe into
alleged nuclear espionage by China.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone did something wrong, they deserve some punishment,''
said the 74-year-old retired educator. ``But most important, you
cannot accuse all of the Chinese community. This is really
terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Allegations that the United States lost its nuclear secrets to
China in two decades of espionage were released Tuesday in a
bipartisan House report.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Asian-American scientists and engineers in sensitive
defense-related work are being viewed with suspicion, community
leaders say. What's more, they worry that unfair stereotyping is
painting Asian Americans once again as outsiders in their own
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly we're in the McCarthy era, where being Chinese
American was synonymous with treason and espionage,'' said L.
Ling-chi Wang, ethnic studies professor at the University of
California at Berkeley. ``That's what the effect is. It really is
an outrage.''
</P>
<P>
   The Asian Pacific American Legal Center in Los Angeles has
already talked to a half dozen Asian-American scientists who feel
that their career prospects have been irreparably harmed, said the
center's executive director, Stewart Kwoh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at a dinner with one of them the other night, and he
just sat there looking so bleak,'' Kwoh said. ``He said the
environment at his company was such that you just feel you're being
scrutinized _ just because of the way you look.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a sensitive issue for many Asian Americans, who felt they
were linked unfairly to the 1996 election fund-raising scandal
involving illegal foreign donations simply because of their race.
The contributions of many Asian American donors were questioned
because they had Asian-sounding names.
</P>
<P>
   Citizenship and loyalty issues go deep for Asian Americans, who
have been the only racial group to be barred from immigrating to
the United States and obtaining citizenship in their early years in
this country. In California, Asians were barred from owning land at
one time.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, the loyalty of 120,000 West Coast people of
Japanese descent was questioned in World War II. They were
imprisoned in internment camps even though two thirds were U.S.
citizens. No espionage was ever proved.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get into these foreign spying issues, we can't help
but refresh our memories about what happened to the Japanese
Americans in World War II,'' Kwoh said.
</P>
<P>
   Such incidents ``tend to foreignize us again,'' said Bill Hing,
a visiting law professor at the University of California at Davis.
``There's little distinction (made) between Chinese Americans and
Chinese abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hing and others say that unlike press coverage of the
campaign fund-raising controversy, the media so far have been
restrained in reporting the nuclear-spying allegations. And Asian
American groups have been more organized. The Organization for
Chinese Americans has already written Rep. Christopher Cox,
R-Calif., who chairs the committee that produced the 700-page
report on China's spying, urging him to be mindful of its impact on
Chinese Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But some politicians have already angered Asian Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., who chairs the Senate Select
Committee on Intelligence, has remarked on NBC's ``Meet the Press''
that the Chinese are ``very crafty people.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Wu, Howard University law professor and commentator, said
Shelby ``doesn't distinguish between Chinese foreign nationals,
Chinese graduate students and Chinese Americans, some of whom are
fifth-generation Californians. ... That should be troubling.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Smith, R-N.H., in an April speech confused Bill Lann
Lee, acting assistant attorney general for civil rights, with Wen
Ho Lee, the Los Alamos, N.M., scientist who is alleged to have
passed nuclear secrets to the Chinese government but who has never
been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is guilt by racial association,'' said Wu. ``This
gives Asian Americans insight into African-American complaints
about racial profiling. Asian Americans should now understand what
African Americans are talking about when they say too many African
American men are pulled over by (police) officers for no basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights leader Henry Der said the spy allegations will have
an impact over the next year. ``Many Chinese Americans are going to
feel battered between now and the next election,'' said Der.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the educational and socioeconomic achievements made
by Chinese Americans in this country, Chinese can still be
stereotyped, demonized and abused. That, to me, is the most
sobering thought in all these controversies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
