<SLUG> BC-APPETIZERS-SIDE-FOOD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEMPT THOSE TASTE BUDS WITH VARIETY OF CANAPES  
 (ADV: WITH APPETIZERS-FOOD) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY WALKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Canapes are little one-bite savories that are
garnished.
</P>
<P>
   The base is something stiff, such as Melba toast, thinly sliced
toasted bread, crackers or a slice of cucumber or zucchini. The
base can be cut into cute shapes, such as diamonds or triangles, or
something fancier if you want to give your cookie-cutters a
workout.
</P>
<P>
   Vegetables can also be turned into one- or two-bite canapes, as
Martha Stewart taught us by piping flavored cream-cheese spread
into blanched snow peas. Cherry tomatoes (cut a thin slice off the
base so they'll stand up), Belgian endive leaves and mushroom caps
are other possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Cooking: Techniques From Expert Chefs,'' by Sarah Labensky
and Alan Hause (Prentice Hall, $49.95), points out that spreads for
canapes can be flavored butters, cream cheese or a combination of
both. (Mix the chopped or pureed flavoring plus seasoning into
softened butter or cream cheese.) The spread can be the principal
ingredient of the canape or applied sparingly to affix a garnish to
the base. Tuna, egg or chopped shrimp salads also can be used as
spreads.
</P>
<P>
   A few of their ideas for spreads and several possible garnishes
include:
</P>
<P>
   Blue cheese spread garnished with grape half, walnuts, pear
slice, watercress.
</P>
<P>
   Deviled ham garnished with cornichon (tiny pickles), sliced
radish, mustard butter.
</P>
<P>
   Horseradish butter garnished with smoked salmon, roast beef,
smoked trout, pickled herring, capers, parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Pimento cream cheese garnished with smoked oyster, sardine,
pimento, parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Shrimp butter garnished with poached bay scallops, shrimp,
caviar, parsley. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
