<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1887 &Cx1f; tic-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPETIZERS-FOOD-AZR &LR;      05-26 2638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPETIZERS-FOOD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANET CANAPE: A NEW WORLD ORDER FOR APPETIZERS  
 (ADV: WITH APPETIZERS-SIDE-FOOD)  
 (ART ADV: PHOTO IS BEING SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY WALKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - You've made salsa so many times you can do it in your
sleep.
</P>
<P>
   And the last time you served California Dip at a party, you
found the whole bowl of onion-soup-sour-cream concoction hidden
under a plant as you cleaned up afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Salsa is a wonderful thing. Dips will be ever with us. But maybe
it's time to get a new appetizer life. Maybe it's time to soar
beyond chips and dips.
</P>
<P>
   Just in time for Memorial Day entertaining _ and for your dinner
parties from now into the new millennium _ let's explore the World
of Canapes, Hors D'Oeuvres and Appetizers.
</P>
<P>
   The old world was a giant Cheese Ball Planet, circled with olive
satellites, bristling with cheese squares stuck on toothpicks.
Imagine zooming from that world into a more sophisticated, elegant
place, where the cheese ball has morphed into a layered Stilton
torta; where water crackers replace tortilla chips; where
California Dip has fallen into the ocean. Permanently.
</P>
<P>
   First, let's learn the language of Planet Canape. Hors d'oeuvre
is pronounced (begin ital) ohr durv. (end ital) This
most-misspelled of French culinary derivations means a ``very small
portion of hot or cold foods served before a meal to stimulate the
appetite or at a social gathering in lieu of a meal,'' according to
``Webster's New World Dictionary of the Culinary Arts.''
</P>
<P>
   An appetizer (you know how to say that) has two definitions in
this same source: ``finger food served before the meal to whet the
appetite, used synonymously with the term hors d'oeuvre''; and
``the first course of a meal, usually small portions of hot or cold
foods intended to whet the appetite; also known as a starter.''
</P>
<P>
   Crudites are raw vegetables, collectively called (begin ital)
kroo dee TAY (end ital) when you want them to look or sound more
French on your appetizer table.
</P>
<P>
   A canape (begin ital) (KAN uh pay) (end ital) is one type of
hors d'oeuvre. It's a flat little base, such as bread, toast or a
cucumber slice, spread or topped (or both) with something savory.
Canapes are one bite. Caterers almost have to specialize in canapes
because they are so easy to serve on trays by circulating servers.
Canapes can be spread or topped with many things.
</P>
<P>
   Cheese is the basic building material, the DNA, of much life on
Appetizer World. It can be served either on its own or in
combination. The latest fetish is for feta, which can be blended
into cream cheese to soften its tang for universal acceptance. (Use
this trick with any strong cheese.) Layered cheese ``pates'' are
fun to make, with layers in between of pesto, red pepper or
mushroom purees, or whatever you can dream up.
</P>
<P>
   But there are many other regions to explore in Appetizer World,
such as the newly discovered olive mixes that are so trendy right
now. Nothing could be easier. Just buy different kinds of exotic
olives at the nearest deli (case or store) and combine with garlic,
olive oil and fresh or dried herbs. Let marinate a while under
refrigeration, then serve at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Olives also are the base ingredient of tapenade (ta-pen-AHD),
one of the ingredients you can smear on a canape base or layer with
cheese.
</P>
<P>
   In the '50s version of Cheese Ball Planet, olives and squares of
cheese were threaded on colored toothpicks, then stuck into a
grapefruit or other round vegetative substance for party buffet
display.
</P>
<P>
   Today's olives are from Middle Eastern countries; modern cheeses
from around the world are artfully displayed whole. And toothpicks
have lengthened into skewers, which can hold any number of
easy-to-serve grilled marinated meats or mushrooms. Often, a sauce
accompanies these little brochettes. Perhaps you have a favorite
barbecued chicken recipe you could adapt into a skewered hors
d'oeuvre. Or do a chef's trick: Use a long sprig of fresh rosemary
as a skewer.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllo dough has its own special culture, led by a tribe of
cooks who have learned how easy it is to use the frozen phyllo. See
the recipe for Mushroom Phyllo Triangles below and read the
directions on how to use it. You can concoct your own savory
filling. Follow these directions, substituting your filling, and
fill your freezer with your own customized ready-to-bake
appetizers.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have mastered phyllo, filling ideas will flood your
synapses: chutney and cream cheese; spinach and feta
(spanakopita!); any kind of cooked, drained sausage, such as
chorizo, with jalapeno jelly. This list could be endless.
</P>
<P>
   Crusts such as phyllo are essential. Another quintessential hors
d'oeuvres blast-from-the-past was the cream puff stuffed with a
savory filling (still delectable, by anyone's standards). The
updated recipe for Chile Cheese Puffs combines today's flavor
favorites (pickled jalapenos, shredded cheese, green onions) in
puffs that are mixed in the blender and baked in minimuffin cups.
What could be easier?
</P>
<P>
   Check out the selection of Asian doughs available, and imagine
the tasty fillings you could wrap them around. Start with crab and
cream cheese. But what about bits of salmon? Or lean curry-seasoned
hamburger? Finely chopped vegetable bound with a bit of your
favorite seasoning sauce? Pan fry or deep fry, and serve with a
tangy dipping sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Keep an eye open for possible crusts. Could you stuff a round of
tortilla into a minimuffin cup and bake it, then fill it? Of course
you could. Or line the cup with masa. Or pie dough.
</P>
<P>
   With hot hors d'oeuvres, it's essential to serve them soon after
cooking. Plan to bake them in batches and designate a server.
Whatever you choose to make, flavors should be distinctly different
from any dinner planned for later.
</P>
<P>
   Or make the meal one big appetizer array, varying the choices.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, you even could serve a dip. One you can make ahead is
hummus, which is nearly so ubiquitous it might become the
California Dip of the late 20th century. Puree drained garbanzos
with lemon juice, tahini sauce (sesame paste), a little salt, lots
of garlic, and maybe some cumin and cayenne. Keep adjusting
seasonings until it tastes right.
</P>
<P>
   On the best of all Appetizer Worlds, you even would serve
salsa. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mushroom Phyllo Triangles &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From Scripps Howard News Service) &QL; 
 &QL; 
2 tablespoons butter (about)
</P>
<P>
   1 pound mushrooms, cleaned and sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup low-fat sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 box (1 pound) phyllo dough, thawed according to package
directions
</P>
<P>
   Melted butter for brushing dough
</P>
<P>
   Melt 2 tablespoons butter in large skillet. Add mushrooms and
saute until soft. Combine with sour cream, parsley, salt and
pepper. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Carefully unfold phyllo dough and lay out on cutting board. Cut
crosswise into 1\-inch-wide strips. Make triangles one at a time,
keeping remaining dough covered with damp towel at all times. To
make each triangle, layer three strips of dough, brushing each
lightly with melted butter before stacking. Place 2 teaspoons to 1
tablespoon of mushroom filling on one end of buttered strips. Fold
up like a flag, starting at end with filling. (Take one corner and
fold over to opposite edge of strip to form a triangle; keep
folding over tightly until you reach the other end of the strip.)
Brush folded-up triangle with more melted butter. Repeat with
remaining dough strips and mushroom filling.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, triangles can be frozen for later use. Spread out
in shallow baking pan in single layer; as soon as triangles are
frozen, transfer to another container with tight-fitting lid, or to
freezer-quality zipper-lock bag. Thaw in refrigerator before
baking.
</P>
<P>
   If baking triangles right away, preheat oven to 400 degrees. Lay
out in single layer on shallow baking sheets and bake in preheated
oven until a nice golden brown, about 10 to 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 32 to 36 servings. Approximate values per serving: 50
calories, 1.6 g fat, 2 mg cholesterol, 7 g carbohydrates, 0.2 g
fiber, 1 g protein, 73 mg sodium, 28 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Toasted Ravioli With Italian Salsa &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From ``The Low-Fat, Low-Cholesterol Cookbook,'' by the American
Heart Association) &QL; 
 &QL; 
16 ounces bite-size cheese ravioli
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil spray, for baking sheets and tops of ravioli
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup non-fat or low-fat Italian salad dressing
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dried bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons salt-free Italian herb seasoning
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
Italian salsa:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
1 can (14.5 ounces) no-salt-added tomatoes with juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 small red onion, quartered
</P>
<P>
   1 hot banana pepper or 1/2 green bell pepper, seeded and ribs
removed
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh oregano or 1 teaspoon dried
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh basil or 1 teaspoon dried
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, halved, or 1/2 teaspoon bottled minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon balsamic vinegar or red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon sugar  &QL; 
Cook ravioli according to package directions, omitting any salt and
oil. Drain and cool at least 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, lightly spray 2 baking sheets with vegetable oil
spray. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Using pastry brush, lightly coat top of each ravioli with
dressing. Place on baking sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Mix bread crumbs and herb seasoning. Sprinkle over ravioli.
Ravioli may be refrigerated for up to 8 hours at this point.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
To make Italian salsa: Place all ingredients in blender or food
processor and process for 15 to 20 seconds. Set aside. (Salsa will
keep in refrigerator up to 4 days.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
To cook ravioli: Preheat oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly spray tops of ravioli with vegetable oil spray. Bake
ravioli 9 to 11 minutes. Drizzle salsa over ravioli or use salsa
for dipping.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 5 main-dish servings or 10 appetizer servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Approximate values per main-dish serving without salsa: 126
calories, 2 g fat, 7 mg cholesterol, 20 g carbohydrates, 6 g
protein, 220 mg sodium, 14 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
Approximate values per main-dish serving of salsa: 150.9 calories,
1.8 g fat, 0 mg cholesterol, 32.6 g carbohydrates, 13 g fiber, 6.8
g protein, 91 mg sodium, 9.1 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chile Cheese Puffs &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From the ``Cincinnati Post'') &QL; 
 &QL; 
3 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped green onions with tops
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup shredded cheese for tacos (or plain Cheddar)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons jalapeno slices, drained if canned
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   Additional chopped green onion, optional
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Preheat oven with rack in the middle to 425 degrees. Generously
grease 24 minimuffin cups (1 3/4 - by 1-inch each) and set in the
preheating oven to get hot.
</P>
<P>
   In a covered blender jar, blend eggs, milk, onions, cheese,
jalapeno slices, flour, salt and baking powder. Blend at medium
speed until well blended, about 30 to 45 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Fill the heated muffin cups about 2/3 full with the egg batter.
Sprinkle with additional chopped green onion, if desired. Bake
until puffed and lightly browned, about 10 minutes. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Note: Jalapeno slices from a can are milder than fresh chiles.
Adjust to taste if substituting fresh for canned.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 24 puffs. &QL; 
Approximate values per single puff: 23 calories, 1 g fat, 25 mg
cholesterol, 1.8 g carbohydrates, 0 fiber, 1.3 g protein, 43 mg
sodium, 45 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Shrimp Stuffed with Feta and Dill &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From ``The Junior League Centennial Cookbook: Over 750 Recipes of
the Most Treasured Recipes from 200 Junior Leagues,'' Doubleday) &QL; 
 &QL; 
4 ounces cream cheese, softened
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces feta cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons snipped fresh dill or 2 teaspoons dried dill
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of ground red pepper (cayenne)
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon coarsely ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds large shrimp
</P>
<P>
   Parsley and additional fresh dill sprigs for garnish
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
In a food processor fitted with the metal blade or in a blender,
mix the cream cheese and feta and blend until smooth. Add the lemon
juice, dill, salt, cayenne and black pepper. Blend the mixture
until well combined. Cover and chill for 1 hour, or until firm.
</P>
<P>
   Shell the shrimp, leaving the tail and first joint of the shell
intact. Cut a deep slit down the length of the outside curve of
each shrimp and devein. Place the shrimp in a large saucepan of
rapidly boiling salted water and cover with a lid for about 60 to
90 seconds, or until they turn pink and are cooked inside. Drain
the shrimp in a colander, refresh under cold running water, and pat
dry.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the cheese mixture to a pastry bag and pipe some cheese
stuffing into the slit of each shrimp. Arrange on a platter and
chill for 1 hour, or until the filling is firm. Garnish with
parsley and fresh dill sprigs.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 25 to 30 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 53 calories, 3 g fat, 47 mg
cholesterol, 0.8 g carbohydrates, 0 fiber, 6 g protein, 102 mg
sodium, 48 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Walnut Stilton Torta &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From ``The Junior League Centennial Cookbook: Over 750 of the Most
Treasured Recipes
</P>
<P>
   from 200 Junior Leagues,'' Doubleday) &QL; 
 &QL; 
2 packages (8 ounces each) cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 sticks ({ pound) unsalted butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup Port wine
</P>
<P>
   1/3 pound Stilton cheese, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup coarsely chopped walnuts, lightly toasted
</P>
<P>
   Toasted walnut halves and red seedless grapes for garnish
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Lightly butter a 5-cup decorative ring mold, fluted mold, or
several small ramekins or bowls. In a large mixing bowl, blend the
cream cheese and butter until light and fluffy. Mix in the Port.
Spread 1 1/2 cups of mixture into the mold. Press in half the
Stilton and half the walnuts. Add another 1 1/2 cups of the
cream-cheese mixture, then the remaining Stilton and walnuts.
Finish with the remaining cream-cheese mixture. Press with the back
of a spoon to remove any air pockets. Cover with plastic wrap and
refrigerate until firm.
</P>
<P>
   To unmold, wrap a hot towel around the mold. Run a knife around
the edge and invert the torta onto a serving platter. Garnish
around the base with walnut halves and grapes. Let stand 30 minutes
at room temperature before serving. Serve with water crackers or
baguette slices.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 large servings. &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 393 calories, 40 g fat, 111 mg
cholesterol, 2.4 g carbohydrates, 0.1 g fiber, 7 g protein, 348 mg
sodium, 90 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Artichoke Nibbles &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From ``Sunset All-Time Favorite Recipes``) &QL; 
2 jars (6 ounces each) marinated artichoke hearts
</P>
<P>
   1 small yellow onion, peeled and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fine dry bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon dried leaf oregano, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon hot red pepper sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 cups coarsely shredded sharp Cheddar cheese (about 1/2 pound)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced parsley  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Grease 8- by 8- by 2-inch baking pan;
set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Drain marinade from 1 jar artichokes into small skillet; discard
marinade from second jar. Coarsely chop artichoke hearts and set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Heat marinade in skillet. Add onion and garlic to skillet, set
over moderate heat, and stir-fry until glassy, about 3 to 5
minutes. Cool 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer to large bowl. Add eggs, bread crumbs, salt, pepper,
oregano, hot pepper sauce, cheese, chopped artichokes and parsley,
and mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into pan and bake uncovered about 30 minutes, until set
like custard. Cool slightly, cut into inch squares, and serve warm
or at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 64 servings. &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 22 calories, 1.5 g fat, 15 mg
cholesterol, .9 g carbohydrates, .3 g fiber, 1.4 g protein, 40 mg
sodium, 58 percent calories from fat. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
