<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, May 27:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 1{ pages on the continuing crisis over
Kosovo:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ The U.S. and others hold talks in
Moscow on the eve of the return to Belgrade of Viktor Chernomyrdin,
the Russian envoy. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ Developments on Kosovo from NATO
headquarters. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PENTAGON (Washington) _ Military developments on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ A look at the repressive atmosphere
in the former Yugoslavia: Two Australian CARE workers go on trial
for espionage; the opposition mayor of a Serbian city flees to
Montenegro. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   We are also considering, among others, stories on refugee
developments from Macedonia and from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (New Delhi) _ India bombs what it says are rebel
positions in Kashmir. Pakistan says some of the Indian bombs landed
in its part of Kashmir and puts its army on ``high alert.'' By
Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-COX-NUKE (Washington) _ Folo on the Cox committee report:
Reps. Chis Cox and Norm Dicks testify today in Congress, other
developments.
</P>
<P>
   LAST-SUPPER (Milan) _ The unveiling of Leonardo da Vinci's 1498
masterpiece ``The Last Supper'' after a major restoration. By
Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-TABLOIDS (London) _ There is an uproar as The Sun prints
a topless picture of Prince Edward's finance, just weeks before the
wedding. She says her engagement is ``ruined.'' Even another
tabloid says ``SHAME ON YOU'' to The Sun. All this comes during a
week of tabloid frenzy and criticism over tabloid reporters who
pose as non-journalists to trick famous people into revealing
secrets. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ A small group of Republicans
broke with their party and signed a petition to force a vote on
campaign finance overhaul, and Rep. Chris Shays makes a frontal
assault on Tom DeLay, the Republican whip, calling this a struggle
for the soul of the Republican party. He accuses Delay of
threatening to fund a primary challenge in his district. By Alison
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   REFORM-JEWS (Pittsburgh) _ In what could be a defining moment in
Reform Judaism, the Central Conference of American Rabbis, which
represents Reform rabbis, will vote today on a statement of
principles that will outline where Reform Judaism is heading in the
new century. There have been only three other sets of principles
promulgated since the establishment of the Reform movement about
150 years ago. The statement is controversial and is expected to
call strongly for a return to tradition: keeping kosher, going to
the mikvah or ritual bath, wearing yamulkes in synagogue,
increasing use of Hebrew, etc. By Gustav Niebuhr and Nadine Brozan.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-HOUSING-CODE (Miami) _ Hurricane Andrew blew the roof off
decades of shoddy building practices in South Florida, exposing
support columns filled with wadded-up newspapers instead of
concrete, and knocking down walls made with cheap particle board
that crumpled like cardboard in the driving wind and rain. The
hurricane brought much stricter building codes. But now, in a move
that has many people shaking their heads in bewilderment, the state
is proposing to supersede South Florida's higher standards and
allow builders to operate under a new, weaker statewide code that
would undo much of what was accomplished in the wake of the most
expensive natural disaster in the nation's history. By Rich Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CAMPAIGN (Somewhere in Texas) _ On the campaign trail with
Vice President Gore in Texas. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE-BRUTALITY (New York) _ U.S. Civil Rights Commission
holds hearings into police conduct in New York City. By Laurie
Flynn. &UR; (BU) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL (New York) _ The trial resumes for four other
police officers, after one, Justin Volpe, entered a guilty plea in
the sexual assault on Abner Louima, a Haitian immigrant prisoner.
By Joseph B. Fried.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CLONE-AGING (Undated) _ The scientists in Scotland who
created Dolly, the sheep that was the first animal that was a clone
of an adult, report that she may have a genetic aberration
suggesting that the genetic material in her cells was as old as the
animal from which she was cloned _ in effect, older than Dolly
herself. By Gina Kolata. (850 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEART-ATTACK (Undated) _ A New England Journal of Medicine
study of 100,000 patients has found that patients are far more
likely to survive a heart attack if taken directly to a hospital
that treats many heart attacks rather than being taken to whichever
hospital is nearest. By Denise Grady. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-CONTINGENCY (Undated) _ After months of weighing options,
businesses and governments are now being forced to decide just how
much they will invest in preparing for Year 2000 computer problems,
and suddenly contingency planning has moved to the top of many
companies' agenda. Unlike most repair work, contingency plans have
to take into account not just the computer user's own systems, but
all the outside forces the user cannot control. As a result,
executives and their project leaders are reluctant to discuss too
many details of their plans, for offending partners, inviting
lawsuits and, in some cases, alarming customers or the public. By
Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   EURO-CURRENCY (Undated) _ The euro extends its yearlong decline,
falling below $1.05 for the first time. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-MUSIC (Undated) _ AT&AMP;T Corp., Matsushita Electric
Industrial, Bertelsmann AG's BM and Seagram Co.'s Universal Music
Group agree to the joint development of a system to distribute
music over the Internet. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Developments at the Microsoft
antitrust trial. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-MAGAZINES (Toronto) _ Canadian and U.S. trade officials
announce an agreement averting a trade war over U.S. magazine
access to Canada's advertising market.
</P>
<P>
   ABC-PANASONIC (Washington) _ Panasonic and ABC announce that
Panasonic will provide the network with equipment to broadcast all
its pro football programming, including the Super Bowl, using
high-definition technology. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The weekly Economic Scene column. By
Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
