<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1895 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRESTLING-RATINGS-COX     05-26 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-RATINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ratings war blamed for wrestler's fatal fall
 &HT;    By Jeffry Scott
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a world of faked mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   But the death Sunday night of World Wrestling Federation
wrestler Owen Hart has brought reality tumbling down on a business
where outrageous stunts have become the norm, and driven cable TV
ratings sky high.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City, Mo., police are still investigating the accident
that killed Hart, 34. The pro wrestler plunged to his death while
being lowered by cable from the 90-foot ceiling of the Kemper
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday officials said an improperly connected harness may
have caused the 70-foot fall of the wrestler billed as the Blue
Blazer.
</P>
<P>
   Hart's elaborate feathered costume may have caught on his
release cord, activating the quick release, said Kansas City police
spokesman Floyd Mitchell. Hart was supposed to pull on the quick
release when he was just above the mat and drop into the ring.
``Either it was snagged on his clothes or he pulled it too soon,''
Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   The accident happened during an event called ``Over the Edge,''
which was televised on pay-per-view.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, officials at WWF's rival wrestling federation, World
Championship Wrestling, issued a statement Tuesday saying the WCW
has always adhered to rigorous safety standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``WCW utilizes a professional stunt coordination team with 20
years of experience, who supervises all stunts to assure the safety
of talent and fans at WCW events,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Competition between WWF and WCW _ which, combined, broadcast 15
hours worth of TV wrestling a week, reaching 35 million viewers _
has grown fiercer in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   The Hart family on Tuesday blamed both the WWF and WCW for the
accident because of the escalating war between the federations for
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Hart's brother, Bret, told ABC's ``Good Morning America''
Tuesday that his brother had been worried about the stunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was taken to him,'' Bret Hart said. ``There was a bit
of discomfort about the danger. But somehow over the weekend he got
talked into doing it again. He was very uneasy about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hart's sister, Ellie, said her brother ``was a sacrifice to the
ratings. That's how I look at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept on getting more and more far out with the gimmicks
and angles,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figured sooner or later somebody was going to end up with a
tragedy because of the direction wrestling was taking with both WWF
and WCW.''
</P>
<P>
   The WWF would not comment on safety.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, WCW President Eric Bischoff has criticized the WWF,
accusing the rival organization of pushing the envelope on
inappropriate material. But this week he sounded less judgmental.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, accidents like this happen,'' Bischoff said on
CNN on Monday. ``They happen on construction sites. They happen in
everyday life. And they do happen in our line of work.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, WWF's Mick Foley fell 15 feet from the top of
a cage through a table, then was thrown through the cage roof,
suffering a broken collarbone and losing some teeth.
</P>
<P>
   But WCW's Sting has been flying into the ring from the rafters
in a stunt similar to Hart's for more than a year _ without
incident.
</P>
<P>
   Competing Monday night shows from the WWF and the WCF have been
the top two cable programs for more than a year, routinely beating
out sports like basketball and baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Millions also tune in to monthly pay-per-view extravaganzas that
cost about $30 a pop and feature even more outrageous and
uncensored action.
</P>
<P>
   Another measure of wrestling's mainstream status: a former star,
Jesse ``The Body'' Ventura, was elected governor of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
