<SLUG> BC-HOME-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Home Section stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Thursday, May 27:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BATHROOM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BATHROOM-SINK (Undated) _ Just when you thought there was no one
left to leave you, the bathroom sink is leaving, too. Those broad
porcelain shoulders you leaned on each morning, gripped in each
hand, that bore the weight of the world for you as you woke,
staring blindly into the void, unaware of where or who you were
until the basin filled, the water stilled and your face rocked
safely into sight. Gone. Or going, with a loud, emptying suck. By
William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   PORCELAIN-TUB (New York) _ Imagine a prewar bathroom with a
deep, deep porcelain tub and gleaming (but not too gleaming) nickel
fittings: a wide sunflower shower head and those little porcelain
buttons marked with Hot and Cold in the middle of gutsy crossbar
handles. There are reproductions, of course, but the dream is the
real thing. It was my dream. By Donna Paul.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   URINAL (Undated) _ The last time a urinal was the center of
attention, it was signed by Marcel Duchamp and hanging upside down
in an show of avant-garde art. Today, the urinal has taken its
stand alongside the bidet and the working fireplace as the latest
must-have in the well-appointed bathroom suite. By Julie Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BATHROOM-FLOOR (New York) _ It could have been the ultimate faux
pas: Blake Sherlock and Andrew Sloan had just moved to New York to
create artworks (at their Sloan/Sherlock Gallery in Chelsea), and I
was asking if they would redo my bathroom floor. But then, their
art is made of shells and stones and other found objects turned
into richly textured mosaics. By Fred Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   URBAN-BEAUTIFICATION (Newton, Mass.) _ In the fall of 1998, the
Newton Pride Committee, the volunteer beautification army for this
grand old Boston suburb, took a quantum leap from planting tulips
and embraced wildflowers. By Ann Raver.
</P>
<P>
   AIR-CONDITIONING (Washington) _ As Memorial Day looms, few
pronouncements strike more terror in the hearts of dwellers than
those inevitable words, ``Hazy, hot and humid.'' For 73 percent of
all American homes, the most convenient _ though perhaps not
universally loved _ remedy for summer oppression is the
air-conditioner. According to Donald Albrecht and Chrysanthe
Broikos, co-curators of the new exhibit ``Stay Cool! Air
Conditioning America'' at the National Building Museum, little has
been more influential in 20th century building than the relentless
generic whir. By Patricia Leigh Brown.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Leslie
Land.
</P>
<P>
   Eds, there will be no HOME-IMPROVEMENT column this week.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other stories
from our partners: Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox News
Service, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona
Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles
Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
