<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1928 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHENRY-HOUSE-HNS &LR;      05-26 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHENRY-HOUSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O. HENRY HOUSE GETS NEW HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID UHLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ As a master of surprise endings, O. Henry would
have loved the plot twists.
</P>
<P>
   An old house where the famed short-story writer worked in San
Antonio has been moved and rebuilt downtown, on the site once
occupied by a cantina where O. Henry liked to tip a few in the
1890s.
</P>
<P>
   In another bit of irony _ considering the author's prison term
for embezzlement _ probationers will work in the house as tour
guides.
</P>
<P>
   About 250 people ate bunuelos (Mexican sweet pastries), listened
to a German oompah band and endured the steamy morning heat during
the dedication speeches and grand opening of the O. Henry House.
</P>
<P>
   David Carter, a retired San Antonio lawyer, spearheaded the
project to move the caliche limestone house to the property.
</P>
<P>
   O. Henry, whose real name was William Sydney Porter, rented the
house and worked in it in 1895 while writing columns and editing
the San Antonio section of his newspaper, the Rolling Stone.
</P>
<P>
   Convicted of embezzlement in 1898 while working as a bank teller
in Austin, Porter served three years in prison. He then went to New
York City, where he masked his past with a new name and found his
fortune. The author, whose best-known work is ``The Gift of the
Magi,'' lived hard. Friends found nine empty whiskey bottles under
a bed in his apartment when he died in 1910.
</P>
<P>
   Several of O. Henry's stories are set in San Antonio, including
``A Fog in Santone,'' ``The Higher Abdication'' and ``Hygeia at the
Solito.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter got help in moving the house from Caesar L. Garcia, chief
of the Bexar County Probation Office. Garcia found space for the
relocated building on a corner of his office's parking lot. Several
members of the Bexar County boot camp, a rehabilitation program for
young offenders, helped with heavy lifting on the construction
site.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, some probationers convicted of nonviolent, nondrug
offenses will start work as docents, giving free tours while
telling visitors about O. Henry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to cost the taxpayers anything,'' Garcia said.
``It's part of their community service.''
</P>
<P>
   The new location of the O. Henry house once was part of ``Little
Mexico,'' a collection of theaters and cantinas where the author
liked to hang out.
</P>
<P>
   With $30,000 from a charitable trust established by Carter,
workers numbered every block and beam in the house before
dismantling it, moving it and reconstructing it.
</P>
<P>
   The rebuilt house has been furnished with Victorian-era pieces,
including a table O. Henry is believed to have used. Pictures and
newspaper accounts about the author hang on the walls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 1453EDT &QL; 
