<HEADER>
A1956 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-VIOLENCE-HNS &LR;      05-26 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-VIOLENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV INDUSTRY SHOULD STAY OUT OF POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The television industry blinked.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two weeks, responding to pressure from politicians
and anyone else looking for a reason where there is no reason, the
industry has, by its attempts to play good citizen, admitted that
it's part of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   That problem is the unraveling of the social fabric, a kind of
sin TV has been blamed for since its inception.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, while unveiling its fall schedule in New York, CBS
said that a Mafia series called ``Falcone'' was held off the
schedule because it was too close to the Colorado killings. Never
mind that CBS has shows on its schedule that are extremely violent.
It was a useless goodwill gesture that said, in essence, ``We're
responding to the president's tirade against us by programming with
a conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the show will make it on the schedule at midseason
(when it has a better chance of succeeding).
</P>
<P>
   And Monday, The WB announced that the second installment of a
two-part season finale of ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' wouldn't be
shown in its regular Tuesday slot. Why? ``It is out of sympathy and
compassion for the families and communities that have been
devastated by the recent senseless acts of violence perpetrated on
high school campuses.''
</P>
<P>
   The episode in question involves a high school graduation.
</P>
<P>
   Right now high schools are gearing for their own graduation-day
ceremonies. The WB wanted to avoid copycat crimes. And what would
those be, precisely? The network did not send the second part for
review.
</P>
<P>
   But keep this in mind: ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' is a dramedy
about vampires and demons and how a precocious high school girl
kills them and thus, for the past four years, has saved her
fictional town.
</P>
<P>
   In short, this is a fantasy show. The finale revolved around the
town mayor _ who is a demon _ transforming into a 60-foot monster
of sorts and the graduating class having to fight him and his
vampire minions.
</P>
<P>
   A statement from Jamie Kellner, chief executive of The WB, said:
``Given the current climate, depicting acts of violence at a high
school graduation ceremony, even fantasy acts against 60-foot
serpents and vampires, we believe, is inappropriate to broadcast
around the actual dates of these time-honored ceremonies.''
</P>
<P>
   Blink, blink.
</P>
<P>
   Kellner is a good guy. He means well. He runs a network aimed
exclusively at people 12 to 34 (even though the network pulls in
many adults).
</P>
<P>
   But to believe that teen-agers are so impressionable they'll be
influenced by violent acts committed against a serpent or some
vampire is absurd. Did they not watch the week before? Or the week
before that? The television industry is cowering because people
want to find the inspirational source of the real- life demons in
Colorado and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a news flash: It's not ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' or
anything else on television.
</P>
<P>
   This knee-jerk, string-up-Frankenstein attitude is so far off
base as to be humorous, if the attendant paranoia and hysteria
weren't so worrisome for people who still believe censorship is a
bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   You want to find the source of the problem? Check the parents.
</P>
<P>
   If a parent is worried that a child is seeing too much violence
on television, screen the shows, limit viewing or pull the damned
plug. It's a TV set. It has an off button.
</P>
<P>
   That, at least, has always been the way to beat back hysteria
before this latest spate of on-campus craziness. But now, with TV
executives either trying to win Brownie points from Clinton and
Congress by looking like they're cutting back on violence, or
pre-empting shows because they fear some nut-job 13-year-old will
blow up his high school graduation (and all the vampires inside),
they are admitting that TV is the problem.
</P>
<P>
   So is it a fluke then that millions of other children grow up
just fine, go to college, get jobs, start families _ without
leaving a lot of carnage behind them? No, it's not. They had good
parenting and an understanding that what they watch on television
is fiction (particularly if it involves 60-foot serpents and
vampires).
</P>
<P>
   The last thing the television industry needs is a creative
chilling effect brought on by fears that it's the source of all of
our troubles. There is a ratings system in place. Pretty soon
there's going to be a V-chip. If self-censorship begins, quality
will suffer further.
</P>
<P>
   Parents _ at least the loud ones and those who worry for
everyone else _ are forever shouting that they need a say in what
their children watch. But they already do. Vote with the remote. If
you don't like a show, turn the channel. There are hundreds of
options out there.
</P>
<P>
   There's even a network, called Pax, dedicated to safe television
_ no violence, no swearing, no sex. See _ it's America. There are
choices. Go watch Pax.
</P>
<P>
   Let the rest of us watch Buffy slay vampires or perps get busted
on ``NYPD Blue.'' Give us that Mafia show on CBS (it will
counterbalance ``Touched by an Angel'').
</P>
<P>
   Don't give in to hysteria. Leave the decision-making to us.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
