<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1957 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLERGY-MOVING-SEASON-     05-26 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLERGY-MOVING-SEASON-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR PASTORS AND RABBIS, IT'S THE SEASON OF SAYING GOODBYE 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York Times
Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative CONNIE
WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or fax
her at (816) 822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By CHERYL HECKLER-FELTZ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   URBANA, Ohio -- Don Hilkerbaumer stood in front of his
Presbyterian congregation one recent Sunday to conduct his final
worship service here -- and to say goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   In the front row sat a despondent and tearful Polly Wilbur. For
the 13-year-old, Hilkerbaumer was the only pastor she had ever
known. And though his new church is only 40 minutes away, the break
from this congregation will be permanent, in accordance with
Presbyterian polity.
</P>
<P>
   Hilkerbaumer himself cried so often during the service, he
finally stopped in mid-sentence while delivering his sermon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever wonder why God made us in such a way that our
noses run when we cry?'' he sniffled loudly, as the congregation
laughed.
</P>
<P>
   This scene will be replayed thousands of times over the next
several weeks throughout the country. For American churches and
synagogues, the period between Memorial Day and Independence Day is
clergy-moving season.
</P>
<P>
   There are scandals, illnesses and other reasons that cause
pastors and rabbis to leave their posts abruptly. But most clergy
follow a well-ordered, time-tested moving season defined around
academic calendars and summer breaks.
</P>
<P>
   A rabbi in Sacramento also teaches Hebrew at a local university,
so she waits until the end of the academic year to accept her new
position.
</P>
<P>
   An Episcopal priest waits until the school year ends before he
moves his two elementary-age children to a new community -- with
hopes they can make a handful of friends before entering a new
school in late August.
</P>
<P>
   Like any other element of congregation life, each denomination
gives the event its own twist.
</P>
<P>
   While Presbyterians, Lutherans and Episcopalians typically honor
</P>
<P>
   their pastors with a Sunday evening potluck and tribute, United
Methodists and Roman Catholics seem less likely to overflow with
emotion. Their pastors move frequently and can be abruptly snatched
away at the whim of higher church officials. Goodbyes are sometimes
nothing more than a handshake and a pat on the back.
</P>
<P>
   In Southern and American Baptist churches and in almost all
African-American churches, the pastor's move can be genuinely
traumatic. He typically serves the congregation 15 to 20 years and
is usually not just a religious leader but a community force as
well, sitting on local boards like United Way, the Chamber of
Commerce and the YMCA.
</P>
<P>
   Reform and Conservative rabbis average eight to 12 years at one
congregation, and their reputation for community involvement is
second only to black pastors. Their good-bye dinners typically
include an audience that extends far beyond their own
congregations.
</P>
<P>
   Pastor-parish specialists from all denominations agree on three
golden commandments for departing clergy:
</P>
<P>
   --Thou shalt allow several weeks between the day thou announce
thine departure and the day of thy final service.
</P>
<P>
   This gives members enough time to adjust to the change and
prepare for the new clergy.
</P>
<P>
   Less than six weeks, and church members tend to feel robbed.
More than a few months, and they begin to wonder if the pastor is
actually leaving.
</P>
<P>
   --Thou shalt not allow thy final worship service to become a
tribute to thee.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the final service should closely follow the
congregation's traditional worship form but include what
denominations call ``The Release of Pastoral Duties.''
</P>
<P>
   In this litany, the congregation formally says goodbye to the
pastor or rabbi while forgiving him or her of any past mistakes and
thanking him or her for past contributions.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, the pastor or rabbi forgives members of the
congregation for their errors and thanks them for their
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the spirit of an ancient Hebrew covenant, the pastor
and congregation commit each other to God and part ways.
</P>
<P>
   --Thou shalt make a clean break.
</P>
<P>
   No fuzzy departures. No saying good-bye and then hanging around
to see if you can help out at the next wedding or funeral.
</P>
<P>
   A change in clergy means a change in leadership style, the
likely addition of new ministries and probably even alterations in
the worship services.
</P>
<P>
   The congregation must be allowed to develop a relationship with
the new clergy without interference from the former.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Cheryl Heckler-Feltz specializes in religion in American
culture and is author of ``Heart &AMP; Soul of the Nation: How The
Spirituality of Our First Ladies Changed America.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 1520EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1958 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREAT-MANAGERS-HNS &LR;      05-26 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREAT-MANAGERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUND ADVICE FOR GOOD MANAGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It all sounds so logical: Treat employees the
way you would want to be treated. Help them overcome their
weaknesses. And, of course, treat them all the same, so it doesn't
appear that you're playing favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Right? No, no and no. What you really should do is read ``First,
Break All the Rules: What the World's Greatest Managers Do
Differently,'' one of the best and most refreshing career books out
there.
</P>
<P>
   Written by Marcus Buckingham and Curt Coffman of the Gallup
Organization, the book outlines what Gallup discovered through
surveying more than 80,000 managers and 1 million workers over 25
years.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you have no desire to be a manager, don't ignore the
book. It might show you how you could do better _ and how your boss
could help.
</P>
<P>
   As the foundation for the book, Gallup looked at the most
productive workplaces. Through fine tuning its surveys, Gallup
discovered that in the best workplaces, employees gave strong
``yes'' answers to these 12 questions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Do I know what is expected of me?
</P>
<P>
   _ Do I have the materials and equipment I need to do my work
right?
</P>
<P>
   _ Do I have the opportunity to do what I do best every day?
</P>
<P>
   _ In the last seven days, have I received recognition or praise
for good work?
</P>
<P>
   _ Does my supervisor, or someone at work, seem to care about me
as a person?
</P>
<P>
   _ Is there someone at work who encourages my development?
</P>
<P>
   _ Does my opinion seem to count?
</P>
<P>
   _ Does the mission of my company make me feel like my work is
important?
</P>
<P>
   _ Are my co-workers committed to doing quality work?
</P>
<P>
   _ Do I have a best friend at work?
</P>
<P>
   _ In the last six months, have I talked with someone about my
progress?
</P>
<P>
   _ Have I had opportunities to learn and grow?
</P>
<P>
   A lot of supervisors might look at that list and figure they do
all those things. And they probably do, but not well enough. Do
people get praised every week? Do you really listen to their ideas?
Do you help them grow? Do you let morale get contaminated by one or
two disgruntled people? And do you know why they're disgruntled in
the first place?
</P>
<P>
   One great example in the book asked managers what they would say
to a talented employee who constantly shows up late for work.
</P>
<P>
   Some would fire him, saying they don't tolerate lateness. Others
would give him a series of warnings, or lock him out of the office
until he comes in on time. Still others would ignore it, as long as
he gets his work done.
</P>
<P>
   But the most effective managers had a simple answer: ``I would
ask why.'' That doesn't mean they wouldn't be lax or tough
eventually, but first they would treat the employee as an
individual, not assume that some office rule automatically took
precedence.
</P>
<P>
   The book says that the best managers meet with employees
individually at least every three months, partly to discuss
performance, but mostly to focus on what the employee wants to
accomplish _ and how the manager can help. They also ask workers to
keep a written record of their progress, mostly so the employees
are holding themselves accountable.
</P>
<P>
   Again, meeting with employees individually is hardly a new
concept. But not enough managers do it more than once or twice a
year, and their focus is more on the past than the future.
</P>
<P>
   The book says that besides hiring talented people, great
managers follow three steps:
</P>
<P>
   _ Define the right outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   Tell employees what you want, but let them choose how to get
there. If a saleswoman meets her goals, don't worry about how well
she fills out her call-reporting sheets.
</P>
<P>
   _ Focus on strengths.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom is that managers help employees overcome
their weaknesses, but the book says the best managers focus on
people's talents and manage around the weaknesses. That lets
workers devote time and energy to what they do best, not what they
do worst.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes managers can work around weaknesses by forming teams,
the book suggests, putting together the complementary talents of
two people.
</P>
<P>
   The book says the top managers spend more time with their best
people _ learning what techniques make them effective and trying to
get them to live up to their potential _ rather than focusing on
weaker employees, who might not have much potential to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   _ Find the right fit.
</P>
<P>
   A great waiter does not necessarily become a great manager; a
great teacher does not necessarily become a great principal. The
book says that the top leaders find other ways to reward people
besides promoting them.
</P>
<P>
   There are an awful lot of mediocre workers and managers in the
world, so when you come across greatness, you need to learn
everything you can. The same can be said for career books.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this one a must-read.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His e-mail
address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
