<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV30-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIAL DAY IRONY: ONCE AGAIN WE DEBATE THE USE OF GROUND TROOPS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 30)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It is ironic that on this Memorial Day, as we
salute those patriotic Americans who have given their lives for
their country, the great debate among the world's dominant
democracies is whether to commit combat troops to a new war.
</P>
<P>
   The reluctance of Bill Clinton and some of his fellow NATO
leaders to send troops to the defense of Kosovo is understandable.
It is an awesome responsibility to dispatch people into war knowing
some of them will be killed and some will be badly wounded.
</P>
<P>
   It is especially troublesome in a situation in which troops must
land in Albania, Macedonia and other countries bordering Yugoslavia
and then be transported through those countries into land-locked
Kosovo to fight Serbian forces that already have forced some 1.5
million ethnic Albanians from their homes and murdered thousands of
others.
</P>
<P>
   In two world wars plus combat in Korea, Vietnam and the Persian
Gulf, we have sent young people into battle in this century to
defend our nation and its policies.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, as in Vietnam under Presidents John F. Kennedy,
Lyndon Johnson and Richard Nixon, we have made grave mistakes while
undertaking what we considered to be an honorable and necessary
mission. Other times, as in World Wars I and II, we have emerged
with a clear-cut victory, achieving our stated goals.
</P>
<P>
   From those experiences we have learned that there can be no such
thing as ``a war to end all wars,'' which was Woodrow Wilson's
lofty description of the first world war.
</P>
<P>
   The only way war can be banished from the earth is for victims
to bow to the dictates and the brutality of aggressors. But that is
not acceptable. If it were acceptable, Nazi Germany could have
controlled Western Europe for the past half century, the Soviet
Union would continue to dominate Eastern Europe and Imperial Japan
would rule Asia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO was founded a half century ago to contain communist
aggression in Europe, and it has done an excellent job in
fulfilling that mission.
</P>
<P>
   Critics are right in contending that Bill Clinton should never
have indicated that combat troops were not part of the arsenal
ready to hammer Slobodan Milosevic and the Serbs. In doing so, he
provided Milosevic with reason to believe that he could win the
confrontation once NATO grew weary of sending bombers over
Yugoslavia every night. Only on May 18 did Clinton reverse himself
and say that he ``will not take any option off the table.''
</P>
<P>
   But keeping the troop option as a threat to Milosevic is quite
different from actually dispatching thousands of American, English,
French, German or Greek troops to fight Yugoslavians on their home
territory _ much of which is rough terrain.
</P>
<P>
   As a one-time anti-Vietnam activist, Clinton is more hestitant
than any recent president, with the possible exception of Jimmy
Carter, to send young Americans out to be killed or maimed on the
battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   Other presidents have sought to avoid war.
</P>
<P>
   In 1898, William McKinley agonized over how to persuade Spain to
adopt more humane policies toward Cuba, which it controlled. But
the sinking of the battleship Maine in Havana Harbor, killing 266
crewmen, and the clamor of the sensationalist press for war with
Spain was too much for McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   Although there was no irrefutable proof that Spain had really
sunk the ship, many Americans gloried in the slogan, ``Remember the
Maine! To Hell with Spain.'' McKinley ultimately sought and
Congress approved a declaration of war. After four months, Spain
sued for peace, and Cuba was granted independence.
</P>
<P>
   From 1914, when World War I began, Wilson sought desperately to
keep America out of the conflict. Like Clinton and Carter, he was
most reluctant to send Americans into combat.
</P>
<P>
   Even after a German submarine torpedoed and sank the British
liner Lusitania in 1915, killing 1,200 passengers including 120
Americans, Wilson resisted going to war. But finally, in April 1917
he conceded that German submarine warfare ``is a war against all
nations ... a war against mankind.'' He sought and won a
declaration of war.
</P>
<P>
   For more than two years, Franklin D. Roosevelt was able keep
America out of World War II while supplying England, the Soviet
Union and other allies with $50 billion in military supplies to
fight German aggression. But the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor in
December 1941, followed by Adolf Hitler's immediate declaration of
war against the United States, propelled us into the bloody
two-ocean conflict that did not end until 1945.
</P>
<P>
   When George Bush decided that Saddam Hussein's invasion of
Kuwait must be turned back, he assembled a grand coalition of
nations that in 1991 defeated Iraq in short order. But Britain's
Iron Lady, Margaret Thatcher, worried that Bush would not stay the
course, counseled: ``Remember, George, this is no time to go
wobbly.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even presidents who were reluctant to go to war committed
all necessary armaments and manpower to achieve victory once their
decision had been made.
</P>
<P>
   But not Bill Clinton, at least not so far. He may be absolutely
right in his reluctance to send American troops to fight in Kosovo.
But for months the impression he conveyed was that of a president
who is afraid to use the full power of the United States to defeat
the evil Milosevic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
