<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-MARTYR-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN-AGE FAITH CAN BE PASSIONATE, CLEAR-CUT AND HERO-ORIENTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    This week's Time magazine reported on the ``surge of teen
spirit'' in the wake of the Columbine High School massacre. For
Christian teens, Cassie Bernall, one of the slain girls, has become
something of an evangelical icon -- if not a martyr -- whose
witness has kindled a youth revival.
 &HT;    As a young teenager, Cassie experimented with witchcraft,
alcohol and drugs. Her parents, fearful for their daughter's life,
sent her on an intensive Christian retreat. Cassie became a
believer. She came home a changed person. She went to church and
Bible Club and became a good and well-liked student.
 &HT;    On April 20, one of her classmates killed her. Before shooting,
he asked, ``Do you believe in God?'' ``Yes,'' replied Cassie.
 &HT;    ``Why?'' he further tormented as he pulled the trigger. No
answer. She was dead.
 &HT;    The power of her story is obvious -- a girl so committed to her
faith that the threat of death could not dissuade her. Since
Christianity began, such stories have inspired and strengthened the
tradition. For two millennia, the church has lifted up
extraordinary faith as a model for all believers.
 &HT;    Martyrs are not unique to Christianity. In this century alone,
nearly every religion can list a host of martyrs -- Jews in the
Holocaust, Buddhist monks in Tibet, Orthodox Christians in Russia,
Muslims in Bosnia and Kosovo, Catholic and Protestant missionaries
in Latin America and Africa.
 &HT;    Sadly, religious persecution is not a relic of some darker age.
Being killed for one's faith is commonplace in much of the
contemporary world.
 &HT;    So why Cassie? Why is she any different than, for example, than
Christian martyrs in the Sudan?
 &HT;    Believers pick their saints because they can identify with them.
Truly saintly saints are difficult to emulate. How can American
teen-agers ever hope to be Mother Teresa or the Dalai Lama?
 &HT;    Cassie Bernall makes a good martyr because she was so ordinary.
She was a typical American teen-ager in a suburban high school --
just like the thousands of teen-agers who have elevated her to
contemporary sainthood.
 &HT;    But for all their ordinariness, saints must also be special.
Both secular and religious reports say Cassie seemed ``prepared''
for her death, ready for her ``divine appointment.'' In a letter
written before dying, Cassie said, ``I want to live completely for
God, it's hard and scary, but totally worth it.''
 &HT;    In private, Cassie quoted Jesus' teaching, ``If any man will
come after me, let him deny himself, and take up his cross.''
Meditating on this verse, Cassie said she wanted ``to find out what
it really means to suffer and to die with him.''
 &HT;    While this may seem like coincidence to secular journalists and
``divine appointment'' to saint-makers, it is really not that
unusual. This is just the stuff of evangelical piety -- a kind of
piety particularly appealing to teen-agers.
 &HT;    Having grown up in evangelicalism, I can be quite jaded about
that style of American Protestantism. However, as I read snippets
of Cassie's devotional writing, I felt transported 20 years back to
my own past. I could have written what Cassie wrote. Indeed, as I
glanced over some letters from college, I found I had quoted the
same verses and expressed the same passions as she had.
 &HT;    Cassie's death reveals a substratum of American piety -- often
overlooked by more sophisticated citizens. In Bible clubs and
prayer groups, Young Life meetings and youth revivals, millions of
American teen-agers channel all their energy and passion toward
God. Language like ``dying to self'' and ``giving all for Jesus''
carries youthful aspirations for love and fulfillment, meaning and
inner hunger.
 &HT;    Teen-agers, who live in a raw, edgy place, make exuberant,
committed believers.
 &HT;    Faith development experts say this is as it should be. Teen-age
faith is passionate, clear-cut, hero-oriented, and uncompromising.
For searching teen-agers, a jean-clad Cassie carrying the Bible is
a perfect choice for sainthood. And evangelical religion, with all
its literalism and moral line-drawing, is the perfect teen-age
religion. A potent combination resulting in a predictable revival.
 &HT;    As one ages, however, faith becomes more ambiguous, and deepens
its abilities to deal with paradox and difference. Cassie is not a
saint to whom I can relate. My heroes include people who have lived
life and understand faith's complexity -- folks like Martin Luther
King and Dorothy Day and Kathleen Norris.
 &HT;    Perhaps Cassie is a martyr, perhaps not. But she did me a favor:
for a moment she took me back to a time when my heart yearned to
give all to Jesus.
 &HT;    No questions. No doubt. Just me, God, and my Bible. Life was
simpler then.
 &HT;    I call it spiritual nostalgia. Some, I suppose, will call it a
miracle.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.1999 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
