<HEADER>
A1990 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEACEFUL-DEATH-HNS &LR;      05-26 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEACEFUL-DEATH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTOR ADVOCATES BIGGER DOSE OF COMPASSION FOR TERMINALLY ILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The elderly man was dying from multiple diseases
and pleaded with Dr. Daniel Tobin, then a third-year medical
student, not to do any more tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please, I beg of you, everything has been tested. All I want
to do is go home. Please send me home,'' the patient, 88, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we have to take these tests in order to help you,'' said
Tobin, echoing the approach he had heard from senior staff
physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Six days later, after having numerous painful procedures, the
patient stopped breathing. For 10 minutes, doctors tried
unsuccessfully to resuscitate him, sticking a catheter into his
neck and cracking his ribs in search of a heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   In the subsequent 17 years, Tobin has seen many more deaths. Now
a physician at the Stratton VA Medical Center in Albany, Tobin uses
that early experience to illustrate problems with the medical
system's approach to advanced illnesses in his new book, ``Peaceful
Dying: The Step-By-Step Guide to Preserving Your Dignity, Your
Choice and Your Inner Peace at the End of Life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a train that's been derailed,'' he said of the
medical system. ``Dying is a natural part of living and there has
to be a way for mainstream medicine to deal with this.''
</P>
<P>
   While heroic measures on a dying 88-year-old man represent one
extreme, Tobin views Dr. Jack Kevorkian, a proponent of
physician-assisted suicide, as the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole issue of suicide at the end of life misses the
point,'' said Tobin, 42. ``We want to see grace in living and grace
in dying.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I think Kevorkian is a nut, but what he's done is
elevate the conversation in everyone's living room.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when more people are talking about death and dying,
Tobin is one of a growing number of physicians who believe the
conversation between doctors and patients needs to begin when an
advanced illness is diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that most physicians are not comfortable with
this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the hospice movement in the United States has long
advocated a palliative approach to dying, such care is still not
routine.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown that hospice currently cares for only about
20 percent of the terminally ill in the United States and often
begins late in the process, sometimes during the final two weeks of
a patient's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't dying well in this country and we need to do
something about it,'' said Dale Larson, director of the counseling
psychology program at Santa Clara University in California and a
specialist in death and grieving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan's work is one of the responses to the problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In writing his book, Tobin drew upon his own experience at the
Stratton VA Medical Center, crafting FairCare, a step-by-step guide
to provide patients with information, support and guidance.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot program, operating in Albany since March, is scheduled
to start later this year throughout the VA Healthcare Network of
Upstate New York, including hospitals in Buffalo and Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of Tobin's approach is a multidisciplinary team of
specially trained nurse practitioners, doctors, social workers,
nurses and pain management specialists whose job is to make the
patient aware of his or her choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing is much more about living than dying,'' Tobin
said. ``We need to teach people how to listen to their patients.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To date, some 20 terminally ill patients at the Stratton VA
Medical Center have been referred to Tobin's FairCare program.
</P>
<P>
   One of them was James Widdis Sr., a Korean War veteran was
diagnosed with advanced liver and lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day is good, the next day isn't worth a damn,'' Widdis,
68, said on a recent visit to the Stratton VA Medical Center for
treatment. ``I'm getting sick of taking medications.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet both Widdis and his family say FairCare has helped ease the
burden of illness, if only by giving them enough support and time
to deal with the inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it's coming so we can prepare,'' said Widdis'
42-year-old son, Jim.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For more information about the FairCare Health System, contact
the Life Institute for FairCare Education at 518-462-3311, ext.
3154 or visit the Web site at www.faircare.org.
</P>
<P>
   (Sylvia Wood can be reached at 518-454-5445 or by electronic
mail at swood(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
