<HEADER>
A2002 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MY-FRONT-PORCH-NYTSF &LR;      05-26 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MY-FRONT-PORCH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WOMAN WHO DISCOVERED ENGLAND -- ON HER FRONT PORCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Moving halfway across the country from California to Tennessee
has not been the easiest thing I have ever done. Nearly two years
after the move, I still suffer from culture shock and protest when
anyone calls Memphis my ``home.''
 &HT;    There is, however, one place in Memphis where I feel at home: my
front porch. I have never lived in a house with a front porch
before. Our ninety-year-old house boasts a front porch that runs
the whole width of the house. There is a porch swing, white wicker
furniture with chintz cushions, a child's rocking chair, ferns and
flowering plants, and a vase full of blooms from the garden.
 &HT;    Come May, it is my favorite room in the house.
 &HT;    Until I moved to Memphis, I never knew I was a front porch
person. In California, we have decks, courtyards, and patios. These
private spaces conceal family life and personal time. Guests must
be invited in and through the house to share community with the
household in the back yard.
 &HT;    But front porches are different. In our neighborhood, the
household spills out onto the street. Up and down the block,
families play and work in public with one another. One neighbor
feeds her baby on the front porch. Another gathers neighborhood
news and shares it with all interested passersby. One family keeps
a mini-trampoline on their porch and we can watch their children
bounce. The teenagers across the street play guitar on their porch.
My daughter and I like to swing together or sit and eat popsicles
in our chairs.
 &HT;    In the evening, tired parents often flee to their porches with
glasses of wine or cups of coffee. We swap tips on child-rearing
and gardening. We try to outdo one another with stories on whose
house needs the most work. If you ever need to borrow something or
want to just visit, an accommodating neighbor is often on the porch
waiting for you.
 &HT;    Our porches are like a church. They serve as the foundation of
our community, a place to know one other and be known, to meet each
other's needs and to be with one another in need. The porch is
sacred space where intimate stories play on a public stage.
 &HT;    In his book, ``After Heaven: Spirituality in America Since the
1950s,'' Princeton sociologist Robert Wuthnow identifies two
spiritual styles in contemporary religion: seeking and dwelling.
 &HT;    ``In Western religion,'' he writes, ``habitation spirituality is
suggested in stories of the Garden of Eden and of the Promised
Land; it consists of temple religion; and occurs in the time of
kings and priests.''
 &HT;    ``A spirituality of seeking is tabernacle religion, the faith of
pilgrims and sojourners; it clings to the Diaspora and to prophets
and judges.... One is symbolized by the secure life of the
monastery, the cloister, the shtetl; the other by peregrination as
a spiritual ideal.''
 &HT;    Wuthnow believes that ``dwelling spirituality'' has given way to
``seeking spirituality.'' For most people, the idea of fixed place
has lost sacred significance in favor of spiritual journey.
 &HT;    There is, however, something odd about this in relation to my
porch. My neighbors are Wuthnow's seeker-types. With a couple of
exceptions, most of the people on my street have lived there less
than five years; most have lived in places other than Tennessee.
They are baby-boomer couples with young children who have chosen
the old neighborhood. Our families make up the porch-sitting
habitation spirituality. Seeking brought us to a neighborhood where
dwelling sustains us.
 &HT;    G.K. Chesterton once remarked that ``I am the man who discovered
England.'' He searched the world to find spiritual meaning only to
find what was always in front of him -- Christian faith.
 &HT;    T.S. Eliot wrote, ``And the end of all our exploring will be to
arrive where we started and know the place for the first time.''
 &HT;    Sometimes I think of Chesterton and Eliot when I sit on the
porch. Seeker that I am, I find it strange that a porch swing could
offer so much spiritual comfort. When I greet neighbors walking
children and dogs, or observe the seasonal changes in my garden, I
hear the strains of the old Shaker hymn in my head: ``'Tis the gift
to be simple, 'Tis the gift to be free, 'Tis the gift to come down
where we ought to be.'' The porch teaches me that in seeking we may
not always find but, at least, there can be rest.
 &HT;    Yes, there is the journey, all that restless seeking. But then
there is a May afternoon on the porch swing. Maybe I am just the
woman who discovered England.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.1999 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
