<HEADER>
A2013 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-26 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN SOLO IS NOT AN OPTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most uncomfortable situations while traveling that I
can recall occurred one morning aboard an airplane about to depart
from Philadelphia or Boston or some other city following a sports
event I had covered the previous evening with my boss.
</P>
<P>
   Frequent-flyer programs were in their infancy. Airlines were
offering double and triple miles to entice new customers, and as a
baseball reporter, I had earned a bushel of miles that summer.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike today, redeeming mileage for free trips or upgrades was
easy, too.
</P>
<P>
   So even though I was traveling on the cheapest available ticket,
I secured a complimentary upgrade, settled comfortably into a wide
leather seat, ordered a Bloody Mary and donned earphones, primed to
doze off to soothing music.
</P>
<P>
   Then I bolted upright in horror as the boss walked past me
toward his seat in the rear of the plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Er, here, sir, take my seat, please,'' I stammered, signaling
him back to the first-class compartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it's yours,'' he said. But the absence of a smile _ and a
hunch that he knew little about frequent-flyer upgrades _ convinced
me that I would likely be writing about Little League baseball the
next season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
UNSPOKEN RULES OF ROAD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I was reminded of this incident while reading a new book,
``Travel With Others Without Wishing They'd Stayed Home'' (Prince
Publishing, $16.95) by Nadine Nardi Davidson.
</P>
<P>
   Combining wit and insight, Davidson writes about the pleasures
and perils of traveling with your spouse, your lover, your parents,
your in-laws, your friends. And, yes, your boss.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, as in my case, we encounter awkward situations
through innocent happenstance. But as Davidson details, tact and
common sense often can help us avoid unpleasantries as we move
about this great world.
</P>
<P>
   She cites one instance when a partner in a law firm took a new
assistant to Philadelphia for a meeting on a case. They arrived at
dinner time.
</P>
<P>
   ``A friend gave me some restaurant suggestions for this
evening,'' the partner told the young man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry, I made a dinner date with an old girlfriend here. I
hope you don't mind dining without me?'' the young man replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, go ahead,'' the boss said.
</P>
<P>
   But he did mind, Davidson's story continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boss hated eating alone, and on his next trip he took a
different assistant _ a married one who wouldn't be looking up old
flames.''
</P>
<P>
   On a business trip, Davidson sums up, responsibilities to your
fellow travelers are paramount. And they don't end at 5:30 or 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Cornering the boss in the window seat of a Boeing 747 is not the
occasion, either, to ask for a raise, the author assures.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
UNFORGETTABLE TRAVEL MATES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Davidson's book is filled with humorous anecdotes about:
</P>
<P>
   _ the spouse who, disturbed by her husband's snoring, stepped
onto the hotel room balcony for peace and quiet, only to find the
door shut and locked behind her _ by the husband who didn't realize
she had left the bed _ and rain pelting upon her uncovered head and
body;
</P>
<P>
   _ the young woman who charmed her boyfriend into a marriage
invitation by agreeing to share his favorite pastime, sailing from
Mexico to Canada in a tiny vessel he had meticulously rebuilt, then
responded to his proposal: ``First, you've got to get rid of that
damn boat'';
</P>
<P>
   _ the woman who, after a series of misadventures during an
excursion with a fellow teacher in Russia, said, ``She's a fun
person when she's around, but she's not as careful as I like to be.
I don't think I'll go with her to the valley of the headhunters in
New Guinea.''
</P>
<P>
   She also emphasizes ways to enhance relations with traveling
companions: assigning responsibilities; assessing compatibility;
setting ground rules; dispersing advice; and taking sides.
</P>
<P>
   Bookstores stock or can order ``Travel With Others Without
Wishing They'd Stayed Home.'' Or call 888-837-2665 to order a copy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
