<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2020 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-POPULOUS-GAMES-NY     05-26 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-POPULOUS-GAMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEMALE SHAMAN WITH WAGNERIAN ZEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a video game genre gets long in the tooth and it seems that
there are no themes left to exploit (Green Berets,
extraterrestrials, comic books, cyberpunks, 3-D, been there, done
that), designers generally sit back, let their minds wander and
arrive at the next obvious solution: women.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting games were the first to incorporate fierce (albeit
scantily clad) female characters. Next came adventure games, with
Tomb Raider's Lara Croft, and first-person shooters.
</P>
<P>
   Now a god game has turned to virtual affirmative action. Witness
Populous: the Beginning, the prequel to Peter Molyneux's 1989
Populous, which spawned the genre.
</P>
<P>
   As in the original game, the premise is simple: You are a
shaman, the spiritual leader of a primitive tribe. Your destiny is
to become a deity. To achieve that, you must conquer every world
solar system, working from the outermost planet inward to the sun.
Raise armies, cast ballistic spells and crush the enemies who stand
in your way.
</P>
<P>
   It's the standard sky-god crusade, but with a twist: the shaman
is female, and everyone else in the tribe is a tiny, grunting,
blindly loyal man whose only job is to fight her battles and
bolster her magical powers with diligent worship.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, you're a queen bee bossing around the drones. Tell
the braves to build, and the huts go up. Send warriors to pray at
designated shrines and you get an extra burst of supernatural
firepower. Order the members of the tribe to attack an enemy
village, and they swarm across the planet to rumble with the enemy
as you unleash floods, lightning bolts, earthquakes, swarms of
insects and volcanic eruptions.
</P>
<P>
   In later stages of the game, you do this while chanting aboard a
hot air balloon. You are biblical Spice.
</P>
<P>
   Does it make the game more fun?
</P>
<P>
   Heh heh heh.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah. (Speaking as a video game jockette _ although video game
jocks seem to have more fun with Lara Croft than with Duke Nukem.)
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong _ the wrathful goddess thing wouldn't help
one whit if Populous wasn't a well-designed game in the first
place. Then it would be just a gimmick. But because the game is
good, the sex switch is an entertaining twist.
</P>
<P>
   Real-time strategy games need twisting more than any other genre
because they tend to get tedious. Most of them involve a
military-industrial complex, which means you've got a base, usually
on some barren moon, and you're mining some exotic ore. Mining,
mining, mining. And then refining. And building tanks. Lots of
tanks.
</P>
<P>
   And training commandos, also a highly industrial process.
There's usually also a research lab that produces nifty high-tech
weapons from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   Bigger guns. Fighter planes. Satellite laser cannons.
</P>
<P>
   Everything is meticulously specified and budgeted, so you can
feel as if you're running your own private Pentagon. Until the
finale, it's all about supply lines, training camps and hardware
requisitions. It's a management exercise. Until World War III. Pull
all the triggers at once, drop the bombs, watch the fireworks,
ta-da, game over.
</P>
<P>
   I always thought that was really boring. Of course, the
wholesale destruction is compelling. But for someone who is more
interested in action than logistics, it's hard to get excited about
the minutiae of military operations: the fuel supply, the
stockpiling, the length and caliber of the cannons, the obsessive
measurement of military prowess, the endless scorekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   Fake statistics and military lingo are supposed to make strategy
games more realistic. But come on. If you were a higher power
(celestial or otherwise) able to invade and subdue entire planets
with terrifying weapons, and you thought it was your destiny to
dominate the entire universe, would you bother with schematics?
Would you sweat the accounting?
</P>
<P>
   No. You would sweep in, rain fire on the enemy, rattle the
ground, throw lightning bolts and terrify anyone stupid enough to
put up a fight.
</P>
<P>
   And you would do it in a towering pre-Columbian headdress, or
something equally flamboyant, with broad theatrical gestures to
punctuate your conquests. Wreaking havoc on that scale is not about
number-crunching.
</P>
<P>
   It's opera.
</P>
<P>
   Populous embraces that principle with Wagnerian brio. In this
game, you're not just some barking general. You are a force of
nature. You don't need tanks and cannons. You can generate
tornadoes. You can bombard your enemies with flaming meteors. You
can erode the coastline and sweep villages into the sea, or make
hillside fortresses collapse into the valleys, then raise a volcano
to cover the rubble with molten lava. You can transform solid
ground into an impassable swamp. You can raise land bridges to
cross the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   All the catastrophes you cause are natural, rather than
man-made. So they're much more dramatic. The strategy also becomes
more dynamic because the environment is part of the game play and
not just a blank canvas for tactics. And at the end of the day,
it's more satisfying to harness plate tectonics and gale force
winds than it is to launch missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The power to alter the landscape makes the god game more godlike
(or more goddesslike, as the case may be), and Mother Nature does
wonders for the genre.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes all it takes is a woman's touch.
</P>
<P>
   Populous: The Beginning, developed by Bullfrog, published by
Electronic Arts; CD-ROM for Windows 95 and 98, $49.95; all ages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
