<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2022 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-MUNICH-HNS &LR;      05-26 1317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MUNICH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOT A LAYOVER TO FILL? TAKE A STROLL AND DISCOVER MUNICH ON AN
IMPROMPTU STROLL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MUNICH, Germany _ An afternoon in Paris, an overnight in London,
a morning in Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 100,000 Americans departing for Europe every day
this summer, many travelers will find themselves with layovers in
large cities. It can be a blessing or a curse.
</P>
<P>
   If you've explored the area before, these type of visits often
provide a welcome opportunity to rediscover favorite haunts, check
out a missed museum or look up an old acquaintance. But if you've
never seen the city, never sampled its wares or interacted with its
citizens, a short visit can prove daunting. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The cursed scurry about with thick guidebooks filled with
lists, checking off sights in the same manner they approach a
roster of household chores or a day at a theme park. They may see a
lot but savor nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Our best advice to first-time visitors with limited time is to
toss the reference book and do nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing, that is, but walk. Take a stroll, get lost in a
neighborhood. Pick a bench on a busy avenue, and feel the hum of
the city.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent visit to the Alps, I found myself with an afternoon
layover in Munich. Armed with a map and a few deutsche marks (very
few after converting U.S. dollars to Austrian schillings and then
deutsche marks), I set out to soak in the atmosphere with no agenda
and only one rule: Never spend more than two minutes inside any
building.
</P>
<P>
   This turned out to be one of the most rewarding experiences of a
10-day, five-city tour. Sometimes during my wanderings I consulted
the map; other times I let my sense of smell or my curiosity be my
guide.
</P>
<P>
   The following describes my walk.
</P>
<P>
   My ramble begins at the Karlsplatz, a busy intersection not far
from the train station. I enjoy the bustle of Neuhausetrasse and
Kaufingerstrasse, two pedestrian avenues that are lined with cafes
and stores, and that attract crowds, both posh and pierced. I
consider stopping at one of the many ``confiseries'' for a sugar
buzz, but instead just relish the whimsically shaped chocolates and
cakes from the dietary safety of the street.
</P>
<P>
   There's no missing St. Michael's Church, which boasts the
world's second-largest barrel-vaulted roof. But the roof probably
is not what will catch your eye as you trip down Neuhausetrasse.
The real treat here is Bavarian sculptor Hubert Gerhard's statue of
St. Michael and a troubled dragon. If you were to venture inside
the church, which dates to 1597, you would find the crypts of many
royals, including Mad King Ludwig II.
</P>
<P>
   At the Marienplatz, the center of old Munich, clots of
teen-agers smoke and neck in front of the Gothic-style Neues
Rathaus. Tourists are drawn to Munich's city hall for its famous
``Glockenspiel,'' whose colorful figures perform several times a
day during the summer, while teens, it seems, are inclined to mock
the tourists.
</P>
<P>
   St. Peter's Church, constructed in 1180 and the city's oldest,
is nearby. Seeking nourishment for my body, not my soul, I pass on
the opportunity to go inside the gloriously rococo church that
houses one of the city's more macabre relics: the jewel-covered
skeleton of St. Mundita.
</P>
<P>
   Instead I proceed around the corner to the Viktualienmarkt,
where large numbers of locals and tourists mingle in stalls of
fresh flowers and produce. The colorful farmer's market is filled
with little shops selling wine, beer and snacks to be eaten al
fresco at picnic tables and bars scattered around the plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Choices for lunch are seemingly endless: Pizza, pretzels and
bun-busting bratwurst are favorites. A smorgasbord of seafood
salads and entrees are available at Nordsee, an inexpensive
take-away chain popular in Bavaria. And then there's the beer.
Plenty of beer. I settle on salad and a bottle of ``weisswine''
purchased at a small but gleaming stall, and then share a picnic
table with an elderly gentleman sipping schnapps.
</P>
<P>
   Fortified, I take a series of turns to arrive on a tiny
pedestrian avenue known as Orlando. It leads to two Munich
classics: the Bayern Munchen store, where you can find just about
anything adorned with the red-and-white-blue logo of the city's
most celebrated soccer team, and Hofbrauhaus, Munich's most famous
beer hall. Hofbrauhaus is an institution and, during summer,
entertains and feeds several thousand visitors each night. The beer
is fresh, the food inexpensive and, despite the touristy Bavarian
entertainment, the scene is fun. But with my no-linger policy, the
Hofbrauhaus must wait for another time.
</P>
<P>
   (If you haven't visited Munich in the past couple of years, you
may be displeased by the news that a Planet Hollywood has set up
shop right across the narrow street from the Hofbrauhaus. Even
without a no-stop policy, we'd pass on this American eyesore.)
</P>
<P>
   Now it is on to Maximilianstrasse, with its expensive boutiques
and monumental architecture. This wide, busy avenue buzzes with
traffic, both foot and motor vehicle. I bypass the Art Nouveau
Kammerspiele theater, the Ethnological Museum and an impressive
statue of Maximilian II, the 19th-century ruler hailed for his
interest in industry and education.
</P>
<P>
   My feet are turned toward the Maximilianeum, an imposing
building located on high ground across the Isar River. The colorful
faade seems pure trickery when you skirt around it and discover the
jumble of offices that are home to two chambers of the Bavarian
Parliament. Two security guards leave their office just long enough
to tell this tourist to move along. Nothing to see here.
</P>
<P>
   I cut through a nameless riverside park where dogs outnumber
people. It is quiet and shady and seemingly miles from the
commotion of Marienplatz. I consider taking a break here to watch
the brown river water pulse downstream, but a glance at the map
shows that Munich's fabled Englischer Garten is teasingly close.
</P>
<P>
   Crossing the river again at Prinzregentenstrasse, I stop to
admire the golden Angel of Peace Statue, and then begin the walk
towards the Englischer Garten. It was a stroll not without peril as
I was nearly run over several times. Not by cars, but by bicycles.
Be aware of bike lanes that have been chalked on the sidewalk. You
are much more likely to be run over there than walking in the
street.
</P>
<P>
   Just across the street from the vast Bavarian National Museum,
Englischer Garten _ named for its 18th-century landscaping style _
is the world's largest and oldest recreational park. And it is here
where Munich's lovers stroll and children and dogs run free.
</P>
<P>
   There are miles of wooded trails to explore and a man-made lake.
Consider joining a pickup game of football (we call it soccer) or
volleyball. I took the opportunity to refresh, pausing at the
Chinese pagoda for a glass of wine.
</P>
<P>
   Taking another path out of the park, I emerge in front of the
U.S. Embassy, where Old Glory offers a friendly wave. It is just a
few steps to the Hofgarten, the former royal gardens. The
centerpiece of the formal gardens, which were designed about 1613,
is a 12-sided temple.
</P>
<P>
   Here I take a seat and watch a woman wage a frustrating battle
with the pigeons. Her predicament: She wants to feed only the
songbirds, but must shoo away the pigeons that zip back before her
seed hits the ground.
</P>
<P>
   After dawdling in the park, I head back toward the train
station. My layover is nearly over. Just time for a last stroll
down busy Neuhauserstrasse.
</P>
<P>
   The pedestrian mall is so crowded. A wanderer, I'm out of step
with the knots of people moving around me. I feel awkward and
foreign and good.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXXXXX &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For information about Munich and other destinations throughout
Germany, call 212-661-7200. Or access www.germany-tourism.de on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 1553EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2024 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-LITTLE-LEAGUE-(2T     05-26 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-LITTLE-LEAGUE-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE LEAGUE, BIG NETWORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (Attn: Ga., N.C.)  
 (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By BONNIE ROTHMAN MORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Hand is fanatical about Little League. A worker in a
disposable diaper factory, whose 11-year-old son plays ball, Hand
says he eats and sleeps the Bloomfield Little League in Macon, Ga.
He is the embodiment of Yogi Berra's saying, ``Little League is a
very good thing because it keeps the parents off the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, Hand has spent a lot more time indoors than out, in
his capacity as the Webmaster for the Bloomfield league. The result
of his blood, sweat and five 16-hour days of Web page work is a
musical, animated, photograph- and information-stuffed repository
for everything that the Bloomfield Little League
 &UR; (www.bloomfieldlittleleague.com)  &LR; program has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   The Bloomfield site's local flavor may be short-lived. This
month, Little League Baseball Inc., in Williamsport, Pa., is to
announce the formation of its own Web network that will work as a
closed communication system between headquarters and the leagues,
and will also enable every league, every team, every player and
virtually every volunteer to create a separate Web site by using
templates the head organization is having created.
</P>
<P>
   With 7,500 leagues in 99 countries, 200,000 teams, 3 million
players and 1 million volunteers, the network could be host to
4,207,500 individual Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The new Little League network is very likely to ease some
communications and make Web sites fun and easy for neophyte
Webmasters. But the plan seems to be a questionable call for some
local Little Leagues with lovingly constructed sites, because the
objectives of the home office clash with the very culture of the
Web itself: individual enthusiasts' pride in their highly personal
endeavors, bolstered by the regulation-resistant Internet that
spawned them. Some local league officials and Webmasters fear that
the Little League network will squash their individuality, stifle
sponsorship opportunities and make irrelevant much of their hard
Web work.
</P>
<P>
   One Webmaster who is apprehensive about losing his site's local
flavor is Bill Lindsey, Webmaster for the North Durham, N.C.,
Little League, which can be found at  &UR; www.ndll.org &LR; , at least for
now. ``The national organization has been very good at promoting
the Little League's autonomy for years,'' Lindsey said. ``Local
leagues aren't part of the national organization other than the
chartered use of the name. Now all of the sudden they're wanting us
to give up our individuality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow http://www.littleleague.org/2300513/ just doesn't roll
off the tongue,'' Charlie O'Reilly, the Webmaster of the
Rutherford, N.J., Little League site, said via e-mail
 &UR; (members.aol.com/rllinfo) &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   When told of this concern about the loss of domain names, Dennis
Sullivan, director of communications for Little League Baseball,
said that leagues wishing to keep their name would be able to
automatically reroute viewers to the Little League network.
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly _ who says his was the first official Little League Web
site in the nation when it went on line in 1995 _ is otherwise
thrilled at the notion of improved communication between the big
guns at Little League Baseball headquarters in Williamsport, Pa.,
and the little guys.
</P>
<P>
   The international Little League organization
 &UR; (www.littleleague.org) &LR;  is buoyant about the project and quick to
assuage local leagues' doubts. ``This will allow us to protect and
authorize use of the Little League trademark on the Internet and in
cyberspace,'' said Stephen D. Keener, chief executive of Little
League Baseball. ``We will be able to make sure that the
information and message that we want to communicate will be
information that we want them to hear.'' The network is an effort
by Little League Baseball to standardize and systematize
communication, Keener said.
</P>
<P>
   Every local Little League is expected to join the new network,
Sullivan said. ``If they're going to use the name Little League,
they have to use the server,'' he said. ``Little League not only
has the right but the legal or moral responsibility to control how
our good name is used.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every league that calls itself Little League is an official,
chartered league that has paid $1 per player per season to join the
program. Right now, any team can call itself Little League, on the
Web or off, and according to some local Little League officials,
many do. Thus, trademark protection is an understandable concern
for both the officials in Williamsport and local league officials
who pay the fees, stick to the rules and believe in the league's
philosophy of ``character, courage and loyalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Little League Baseball, with 100 paid employees serving three
million players, has been on line since 1994, when it set up a site
to promote that season's Little League World Series. In the 10 days
of the series, more than 250,000 people logged onto the site. By
1997, plans for the global network had started to take shape.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Little League network is being developed by Myteam.com, a
five-month-old company in Concord, Mass. Little League Baseball
says it will not pay any fee for the service; the site will be
supported by advertising and commerce. It is expected to be up and
running by September, said Elliot Katzman, chief executive of
Myteam.com. The company plans to develop Web sites for
nonprofessional national sports organizations, intramural sports
groups, and college and high-school teams. Little League is the
first and only organization to have entered such an arrangement
with Myteam.com. Today, the site at  &UR; www.myteam.com &LR;  is one page
with one bit of information: ``Coming soon!''
</P>
<P>
   The details of the vast Little League system _ from Web site
addresses to the amount of space granted to each site to the way
links will be handled _ have yet to be worked out, Katzman said.
One thing is clear: to get into the league network, Web surfers
will first have to go to the Myteam site, then navigate down to the
Little League site they want.
</P>
<P>
   The network will have two parts. One will be an intranet _ a
password-only network available to aid communication between local
leagues and Little League headquarters and accessible to Little
League players, parents and staff members. With this feature,
schedule and roster changes made at the local level will
automatically be available to the national organization, and
national communications to the local leagues will be eased as well.
The other portion of the network will be on line, with Web sites
for the general public.
</P>
<P>
   The intranet will offer a new feature for Little League in
cyberspace: it will allow listing the names of the young players.
Until now, Little League guidelines for Web sites prohibited the
listing of player names for security reasons. Officials in
Williamsport said they are confident that this will not put the
children in jeopardy. But it could affect the teams, said O'Reilly,
the Web master in Rutherford, who noted that publishing team
rosters and player statistics on the Web could encourage player
poaching.
</P>
<P>
   For local leagues already on line, the question of content on
the local sites has raised some hackles. The existing local Little
League Web sites were developed under guidelines that are at once
specific and vague. Unmonitored chat rooms are prohibited, as are
links to sites other than what Little League refers to as
``authentic'' Little League sites. These guidelines are not
expected to change, Sullivan said. For the most part, local
Webmasters have had no difficulty following them. If they follow
the guidelines, local sites can apply for and receive a seal of
approval from Little League Baseball, which is then featured on the
site. Roughly 1,000 sites have been approved.
</P>
<P>
   The North Durham Little League, however, has skipped requesting
approval for its three-year-old Web site because of the national
organization's rule rejecting links to unapproved sites, said
Lindsey, the North Durham Webmaster. Doing so is in violation of
the Little League charter, Sullivan said. But Lindsey said he
thought Little League would consider nonauthentic the sites
interpreting Little League rules and sites on sports medicine and
training that are part of the North Durham links page.
</P>
<P>
   Little Leagues rely on sponsorship and fund-raising dollars to
keep the ball in play, and many sites link to sponsors' sites.
Sullivan said any policy on linking to sponsors ``hasn't been
ironed out yet,'' although he added that he saw no particular
problem with the practice.
</P>
<P>
   Still, any hint that the links will be threatened makes some
local Webmasters nervous. Lindsey said: ``Little League very
strongly recommends that the local board is in control of its own
organization, the regular season is controlled by a local board of
directors, and I don't think they'd be very successful if they were
to try to demand that every Little League publish through their Web
site.''
</P>
<P>
   Other local Webmasters are not concerned. ``I think the
oversight from Williamsport is a very good thing,'' said David
Cooper, who runs the site for the Eagledale Little League in
Indianapolis  &UR; (www.infoteam.com/nonprofit/eagledalell) &LR; . On the
topic of creative restraints imposed by the template system of the
Web site designs, he said: ``There are always ways to make it look
a little different. You just need imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   How the transfer of exisiting local sites to the official
network server will happen is also a big concern of local
Webmasters. According to David Block, vice president of development
at Myteam.com and one of the company's founders, Myteam will enable
local leagues to easily import their existing Web pages to the
Myteam.com site.
</P>
<P>
   Local Webmasters, though, are skeptical. They worry that there
will not be enough space in the Myteam.com system for their
multimedia sites, that importation won't go as smoothly as
promised, that too much control will be levied by headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The local Little League board of directors in Macon has talked
about consulting a lawyer for advice. ``Little League is a very
powerful organization,'' said the Bloomfield league president, Kyle
Steele, by cellular phone while running the concession stand at the
local ballpark. ``While we're out there promoting Little League
just as hard as they are, they shouldn't stop us just because we're
not on their server.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bloomfield site, which is updated nightly by Hand after he
goes home from the ballpark, is the pride of the local league.
``When the kids say, `Hey, I'm on the Internet!' that's something
to see,'' Hand said. ``We're going to run our Web site until we're
told to shut it down or move it,'' Steele said, interrupting the
phone conversation to ask a Little League fan if he wanted ketchup
and mustard on his hot dog so the fan could get back to the field,
where wild cheering had just erupted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
