<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVE AGAPANTHUS TIME TO BLOOM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Q: I have lived at my current address for a year and a
half. I transplanted the agapanthus that were already here to
another bed, but have had only two scraggly blooms. What can I do
to encourage blooming? Should I cut the stems after blooming?
</P>
<P>
   A: Agapanthus, or lily of the Nile, is a perennial in our warm
climate. We enjoy these for the umbels of blue or white flowers in
late spring. Those in our garden are just beginning to open now.
The straplike foliage is dark green.
</P>
<P>
   Replanted agapanthus is not always as floriferous the next
spring. Give yours a second chance to become more established. It's
been my experience that agapanthus bloom best when the plants are
slightly crowded in a bed or slightly pot-bound. It is true,
however, that agapanthus bloom less when extremely overcrowded in
the garden.
</P>
<P>
   Agapanthus thrives in a sandy soil enriched with humus. Good
drainage is important. Agapanthus accepts full sun but also adapts
well in areas with winter sun and filtered summer sun as well as
those with morning sun and afternoon shade.
</P>
<P>
   Water well during the spring growing season, especially while
the plants are developing flower scapes. After blooming, water well
and fertilize with bone meal or superphosphate. Water moderately in
fall and winter, and fertilize again in early spring.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What can I do to prevent squirrels from stripping the bark
from my pecans?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you have tried the various repellents on the market, as
well as homemade concoctions such as hot pepper sprays, you might
wrap a sheet-metal collar around the trunk to prevent squirrels
from climbing up into the trees. Of course, they can jump from top
to top, but the collar may help. Humane traps also are helpful. The
squirrels may do some damage, but they usually don't create
long-term problems.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it too late to prune my hibiscus?
</P>
<P>
   A: Often pruning is done before new growth starts in spring, but
you can prune now. If only leggy stems need pruning, those branches
unpruned, of course, will continue to bloom. Flowering on newly
pruned branches will be delayed for a while. You can pinch back
hibiscus anytime during the growing season and between heavy
pruning. Using your thumb and forefinger, pinch off the youngest
foliage at the branch tips. This promotes bushy growth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, Garden Editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston 77210. The bulk of mail prevents
individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
