<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-GACHET-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALING ART: FRENCH DOCTOR'S COLLECTION AT THE MET IS
A  BLOCKBUSTER 
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH BAKER  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dr. Paul-Ferdinand Gachet was a modern painter's
dream: a physician who took artworks in payment.
</P>
<P>
   Gachet's generosity was its own reward. At his death in 1909, he
left his son and daughter the largest collection of works by
Vincent Van Gogh outside the artist's family and rooms full of
other impressionist and postimpressionist paintings by artists such
as Paul Cezanne, Camille Pissarro and Claude Monet.
</P>
<P>
   The American public gets its first look at Gachet's treasures in
``Cezanne to Van Gogh: The Collection of Dr. Gachet,'' which opened
Tuesday at the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Collection of Dr. Gachet'' is fascinating on many levels.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious is the sheer astonishment of seeing what a
wealth of great paintings Gachet once owned. The show culminates in
the large Van Gogh gallery, where a chillingly severe self-portrait
adjoins the great landscapes ``Dr. Gachet's Garden'' (1890) and
``Thatched Huts at Cordeville, Auvers'' (1890) and the notably
unlikable ``Cows (After Van Ryssel and Jordaens)'' (1890).
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most startling images in the exhibition catalog are
anonymous photographs of ordinary-looking rooms in the Gachet house
in Auvers, decorated with what are now priceless pictures by Van
Gogh and Cezanne.
</P>
<P>
   The catalog explains one secret of Gachet's eminence as a
collector: Apparently he never threw away or sold anything. Along
with incontestable masterpieces, he amassed great heaps of drawings
and prints by artist friends who interested no one but him, then or
now.
</P>
<P>
   We see here some of the souvenirs Gachet kept, including the
white cap he wears in Van Gogh's portraits of him and a
paint-smeared Van Gogh palette, on which not just colors but also
the artist's distinctive strokes lie at the ready.
</P>
<P>
   A big reason Gachet was such a good friend to advanced painters
of his day is that he and his son, Paul, were also amateur artists.
They emulated Cezanne, Van Gogh, Pissarro, Armand Guillaumin and
others by copying their works.
</P>
<P>
   The family's donations to French museums included many
paintings, watercolors and prints by Gachet, his son and others in
their circle. The exhibition displays some of the Gachets' and
others' copies of impressionist and postimpressionist pictures
alongside the originals, so we can compare them for ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 1950s, when the Gachet heirs made their major
gifts to the French state, scholars and less-qualified experts have
used the Gachets' art ambitions to impugn the authenticity of
various pictures by Van Gogh, Cezanne and others.
</P>
<P>
   Conservators have settled disputes over the works now on view,
ruling all of them genuine. Doubts still shadow some other pictures
thought to have been sold quietly by Paul Gachet in the decades
after his father's death.
</P>
<P>
   The Met show devotes a wall to Cezanne's oil sketch for his
bizarre early painting ``A Modern Olympia'' (1872-74) and copies of
it by Gachet _ who painted under the name Paul Van Ryssel _ and his
pupil Blanche Derousse.
</P>
<P>
   Even untrained eyes can see that the copies lack the impulsive
physical coherence of the original. This after-the-fact quality
keeps even the best of the copies on view from rivaling the
originals, but the chance to compare them is one of the great
features of the Gachet collection.
</P>
<P>
   His hoard was already legendary in the doctor's lifetime, partly
because the artists represented in it justly saw him as their
friend and ally. Gachet's celebrity began with the fact that he
attended Van Gogh from shortly before the artist mutilated his ear
until he died, two days after shooting himself, in July 1890.
</P>
<P>
   The Gachet family name reached another summit of fame between
1949 and 1954, when Gachet's son and daughter gave the French state
museums many important _ and until then little-known _ masterworks
collected by their father. Experts in academia and the press then
began their periodic skirmishes over authorship of some of the
rediscovered objects.
</P>
<P>
   But the pinnacle of notoriety came in 1990, when Japanese
businessman Ryoei Saito paid $82.5 million for Van Gogh's
``Portrait of Dr. Gachet'' (1890), making it the most expensive
artwork ever sold publicly.
</P>
<P>
   A second version of the painting is the emblem of the Met's
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   The names that grace ``The Collection of Dr. Gachet'' guarantee
that it will be a blockbuster. But for anyone who brings real
concentration to it, the show will be a far more complex,
instructive experience than ``Van Gogh's Van Goghs,'' which
recently brought unprecedented crowds to the National Gallery of
Art and to the Los Angeles County Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CEZANNE TO VAN GOGH: THE COLLECTION OF DR. GACHET
</P>
<P>
   Paintings, prints and memorabilia. Through August 15.
Metropolitan Museum of Art, 1000 Fifth Ave., New York, (212)
535-7710.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
