<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2039 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx14;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      05-26 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Tough Tomatoes &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Last year I attempted to grow tomato plants (six different
varieties, including heirlooms) on my 12th-floor balcony, facing
south-southwest. The skin of all the varieties was very thick. Why
would this happen? Is there anything I can do differently this year
to prevent this?
</P>
<P>
   A. You might start by choosing cherry tomatoes, said Dr. Martha
Mutschler, a professor of plant breeding at Cornell University who
specializes in tomatoes. ``Full-sized tomatoes in limited pot space
are more likely to be stressed,'' she said, and stress has many
negative effects, including limited growth, hence fewer fruits,
poor quality in the fruits that are produced, and greater
susceptibility to disease.
</P>
<P>
   After pointing out that perceptions of skin thickness tend to be
subjective, Dr. Mutschler said any problems in that department
would not have been a result of growing conditions. The texture of
the skin ``is in the nature of the variety,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it toughness,'' she added, and like softness and
firmness, it's part of the makeup of the tomato.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomatoes bred to be shipped long distances have especially tough
skins, but it's unlikely your heirlooms were similarly endowed. One
possible explanation is that stress made the flesh less juicy, and
that in turn made you notice the skin more than you otherwise might
have.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, most fruiting vegetables are not good candidates
for pot culture. They need a lot of leaf in proportion to fruit to
develop good flavor, and that means big plants. Though catalogs and
garden stores sell many varieties of tomatoes, squashes and
eggplants bred for container growing, their fruits tend to be as
reduced in flavor as the plants are in size.
</P>
<P>
   But don't despair. If you have room for a really big pot _ a
half whiskey barrel, for example _ you can have delicious cherry
tomatoes and have them for quite a while. The tastiest types, like
Sweet 100 and Sun Gold, make very large plants _ don't plant more
than two. But if you keep them well watered and well fed, they will
tolerate crowded roots and keep producing well into the fall.
Expect to do some pruning, and be sure to provide a teepee of
six-foot stakes or other tall, strong support.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Alkaline Soil &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I recently bought a house with a large yard, where I intended
to plant vegetables, herbs, fruit trees and flowers. But when I had
the soil tested, it was way too alkaline. How can I remedy this?  &QL; 
A. Most soils in the Northeast are naturally on the acidic side, so
the first thing to do is figure out why the test came out the way
it did. Perhaps it's an accident of nature. Your house might sit
squarely over a vein of limestone, in which case the remedy is a
combination of acidifying soil amendments (sulfur is the most
common) and learning to love the many plants, including pears,
asparagus, peonies and pansies, that prefer slightly alkaline
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But over-alkalinity might also be a gift from the previous
gardener. If he or she found acid soil and added too much lime in
an attempt to compensate, all you have to do is spread lots of
compost and a little peat moss, then wait a year or two for the
rain to right things.
</P>
<P>
   The happiest possibility of all is that the problem is simply a
bad sample. If a large part of the soil you had tested came from a
spot where old bricks (and their alkaline mortar) had been piled,
or from a place where wood ashes, another famous antacid, had been
dumped for years, it could have been alkaline enough to throw off
the reading completely.
</P>
<P>
   How can you tell what's really going on? Consult the trees and
plants that are thriving now in your yard and those of your
neighbors. Walnuts, wisteria, lilacs, columbines and white clover
do best in slightly alkaline soils. Spruces, white birch,
rhododendrons and violets all require acid conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 West
43d St., New York 10036, or by e-mail to gardening(AT)nytimes.com.
Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished questions
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 1604EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
