<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2047 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-RATINGS-0527-COX     05-26 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-RATINGS-0527-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV CONTENT CALLED INCREASINGLY OFFENSIVE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment categories
 &HT;    By Raven Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Television programs are more offensive than ever,
a media watchdog group said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of two weeks of programming from the November sweeps
periods of the last three years, the Parents Television Council
said it found foul language and sexual and violent content rose 31
percent despite implementation of an age- and content-based ratings
system. The group counted the incidences of foul language and
sexual and violent content for each hour of programming it studied.
</P>
<P>
   The networks studied included the ``big three'' -- NBC, CBS and
ABC -- and Fox, WB and UPN. Cable networks were not included in the
study. CBS was the least offensive network overall while ABC was
the most offensive, with Fox trailing closely behind, the group
said.
</P>
<P>
   There had been predictions the ratings system could backfire
because the entertainment industry might use it to insert racier
material into TV shows, Brent Bozell, chairman of the Parents
Television Council, said in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The data in this study suggests that is exactly what has
happened,'' Bozell said. He said he was disturbed by the airing of
shows with foul language and sexual and violent content during the
supposed ``family hours'' of 7 p.m. until 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   When the ratings system was implemented in January 1997, the
goal was to give parents a guide to suitable programming for
children, not to shape content. However, Sen. Joseph Lieberman,
D-Conn., an advisory board member of the watchdog group, said it
might be time for the Federal Communications Commission to consider
program content in deciding whether to renew a station's license.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the privilege of a license comes
responsibility,''Lieberman said. ``We're not talking about
censorship but whether the station is serving the public
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Sam Brownback, R-Kan., also an advisory board member for
the council, said that while there is no clear answer to the
question of whether networks use the ratings to ``go dirty,''
falling audience numbers should encourage networks to change their
programming.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the way for television to survive is through more
uplifting programs, Brownback said.
</P>
<P>
   Bozell encouraged the entertainment industry to voluntarily
``clean up its act.''
</P>
<P>
   As the case for the industry's influence on its audience becomes
harder to refute, he said, ``the growing amount of objectionable
material produced becomes more and more difficult to defend.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the National Association of Broadcasters
declined to comment on the council's findings, saying the
organization had not received the report.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
