<P>
   REFORM-JEWS (Pittsburgh) _ In what could be a defining moment in
Reform Judaism, the Central Conference of American Rabbis, which
represents Reform rabbis, will vote today on a statement of
principles that will outline where Reform Judaism is heading in the
new century. There have been only three other sets of principles
promulgated since the establishment of the Reform movement about
150 years ago. The statement is controversial and is expected to
call strongly for a return to tradition: keeping kosher, going to
the mikvah or ritual bath, wearing yamulkes in synagogue,
increasing use of Hebrew, etc. By Gustav Niebuhr and Nadine Brozan.
