<HEADER>
A2066 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-URINALS-ART-NYT &LR;      05-26 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-URINALS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FIXTURE NEVER INVITED HOME, UNTIL NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The last time a urinal was the center of attention,
it was signed by Marcel Duchamp and hanging upside down in a show
of avant-garde art. Today, the urinal has taken its stand alongside
the bidet and the working fireplace as the latest must-have in the
well-appointed bathroom suite.
</P>
<P>
   The architectural firm of Gwathmey Siegel &AMP; Associates, with
clients like Jeffrey Katzenberg and Steven Spielberg, has always
made bold architectural moves and pursued an aura of macho
modernism. No surprise, then, that it offers the urinal option to
all its residential clients. (A picture of one, in the Pacific
Palisades home of Kathleen Kennedy and Frank Marshall, crept into
publication, to the firm's dismay.)
</P>
<P>
   Philippe Starck, progenitor of the chichi boutique-hotel loo
(and the toilet-paper holder as rosebud vase), has designed a
urinal for the home that is a porcelain horn of plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Architectural salvage companies are in on the trendlet. Evan
Blum, the owner of Demolition Depot and Irreplaceable Artifacts in
Manhattan, has sold more than 100 antique porcelain and china
urinals to customers including restaurateur Keith McNally and
filmmaker Ethan Coen. And in a move more in character with his
World War II hero than his modern e-mailing entrepreneur, actor Tom
Hanks is said to be getting one for his new Manhattan apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the latest appliance,'' said Victoria Hagan, an interior
designer, who has ordered urinals for ``a couple of recent
projects,'' including the home of film director Barry Sonnenfeld,
who, she said, ``is very proud of his.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the new thing, like having a Sub-Zero in the kitchen,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   In these uncharted waters, conjecture as to ``why this, why
now?'' is speculative. ``It's a his-side, her-side thing,''
suggested Gerald Gendreau, an associate architect at Gwathmey
Siegel. The urinal is ``the male equivalent of the bidet,'' he
said, citing the expansion and separation of the male and female
bathing domains in larger houses. ``It's usually because you  &UR; can &LR; ,
not because you must,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ergonomics plays a role, said Suzanne Ardley, the author of
``Bathroom'' (DK Publishing, $12.95). ``I've talked with men
designers who assure me they are very sensible,'' she said, adding
that she imagined that people who are design conscious are
interested in function, ``and urinals are  &UR; so &LR;  efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   The selection of styles is unsurprisingly limited. (``They still
look municipal,'' Ms. Ardley said.) Starck's horn-shaped version
aside, the au courant style is the stainless-steel prison-issue
model manufactured by Acorn Engineering Co. in City of Industry,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Favored by minimalists and modernists seeking that
stripped-clean look, Acorn's indestructible fixtures are so popular
that the company has produced a new residential bathroom line,
Neo-Metro, with urinals at $1,300 to $1,900. They are not much
different from the prison edition.
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan architect William Georgis plans to install an Acorn in
the master bathroom of the Upper East Side town house he is
renovating. ``I saw it in a public bathroom in Miami,'' he said,
``and I immediately wrote down the company's name.''
</P>
<P>
   If the institutional look seems too harsh, massive 450-pound
porcelain antiques offer another: Victorian bordello. These
beauties are available in abundance at Demolition Depot in Harlem.
``I have every style of urinal known to man,'' said Blum, whose
stock of heritage fixtures, starting at $100, now includes those
ripped out of the Metropolitan Life Building as well as the Lyric
and Apollo theaters on 43rd Street.
</P>
<P>
   The Porsche of urinals, Blum said, was made by J.L. Mott between
1900 and 1920. With the look of a bidet bulked up on steroids, the
Mott urinal is topped off with an ornamental steel cap that
resembles a shiny fire hydrant. Such urinals can sell for as much
as $5,000, ``when you can get them,'' Blum said, adding that they
are usually set in concrete and require a jackhammer to free.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Schlenger of Jupiter, Fla., a retired auto-parts
manufacturer, had a urinal installed in his private bathroom. His
architect, Alex Gorlin of Manhattan, was perplexed at his client's
request but assumed it was a ``running with the wolves thing,'' he
said. Or perhaps the client just wanted his home to conform more to
his office, the architect suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people wonder why I have it,'' Schlenger said. ``But
I tell you this: It's a whole lot easier to use in the middle of
the night.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynda Schlenger, his wife and a collector of art ceramics, has
placed pieces of her collection in the bathroom. (Much more of it
can be seen at the Metropolitan Museum of Art.) ``The interesting
thing is people's reaction when I take them through,'' she said.
``You know, if I'd put it in the living room, people would have
thought it was a work of art.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
