<HEADER>
A2067 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-STILLER-GAROFALO     05-26 1555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-STILLER-GAROFALO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMEDY DUO IMPARTS DROLL WISDOM OF THE AGES IN `FEEL THIS BOOK' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    (``Feel This Book''; Ballantine Books; $22.95) 
 
By MIKE McDANIEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Do not judge Ben Stiller and Janeane Garofalo against coed
comedy teams of the past: Burns and Allen, Nichols and May, Stiller
and Meara, Jethro and Elly May.
</P>
<P>
   Ben and Janeane are on a more noble mission.
</P>
<P>
   They want to heal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looks are everything,'' they advise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rich people are happier,'' they bravely impart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dialogue, booths and Stoli are the linchpins of a successful
sexual liaison,'' they counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Solid (and some liquid) advice, all. And this is just a tiny
taste of what awaits those willing to part with $22.95 for Ben and
Janeane's first foray into the world of publishing. That sum, plus
tax, will get you ``Feel This Book'' (Ballantine Books).
</P>
<P>
   Subtitled ``An Essential Guide to Self-Empowerment, Spiritual
Supremacy and Sexual Satisfaction,'' the book is written not by
psychologists or psychiatrists but by ``highly paid actors and
comedians, who as such know more about neuroses than you can
imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben and Janeane have been dispensing advice _ to each other _
for more than a decade, through their brief union on Fox's ``Ben
Stiller Show'' (six whole months in 1992) to their brief union as
boyfriend-girlfriend (six whole minutes?) to big-screen projects
like ``Permanent Midnight,'' ``The Cable Guy,'' ``Reality Bites''
and the upcoming ``Mystery Men'' (they play superhero wannabes,
along with William H. Macy, Hank Azaria and Greg Kinnear).
</P>
<P>
   ``Feel This Book'' _ the title co-opts the title of Abbie
Hoffman's bio, ``Steal This Book,'' and dovetails with Garofalo's
upcoming portrayal of Abbie's wife, Anita, in the film, ``Steal
This Movie'' _ might not be worth $22.95, but it does speak to
those of us who have lost our way and lived to laugh about it. Ben
and Janeane do, recalling such horrible/hilarious events as their
brief coupling to Ben's 30-day trip down the road to self-discovery
(including a stop at difficult-to-find Port Pickney, Texas).
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to do more than have people ``feel'' their book, Ben and
Janeane sat patiently through a recent publicity session with the
press. Occasionally they even spoke. Here is some of what they
said:
</P>
<P>
   Question: ``What can you offer the followers of bogus gurus?''
</P>
<P>
   Janeane: We offer the wisdom that comes from doing series
television. The wisdom from having your name above the title of a
film, and a sweet back-end deal, and the wisdom of having had, at
one time in your life, Carrie Wyatt deliver your meals from a meal
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Ben: And also the experience of not ever having had one
successful long-term relationship. I think through those mistakes,
hopefully others can be led down the path of enlightenment and
spiritual empowerment.
</P>
<P>
   Question: ``It appears that both of you champion alcohol a
little bit, which is also a little different from other gurus.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben: I have to say that Janeane is so far ahead of the curve ...
</P>
<P>
   Janeane: Alcohol will keep your innards clean. I mean, drop a
penny in some wood alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Ben: Alcohol is used to clean wounds, but then when you drink
it, you're the bad guy.
</P>
<P>
   Janeane: Yeah, exactly.
</P>
<P>
   Question: ``Are you both enthusiasts of caffeine and nicotine as
well?''
</P>
<P>
   Janeane: Well, that speaks for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Ben: I am a major caffeine booster. Chocolate is underrated
also.
</P>
<P>
   Janeane: All these drugs fit into the ``Feel This Book'' plan.
Ben is a huge peanut M&AMP;M enthusiast. I've never seen anybody enjoy
peanut M&AMP;Ms more than him.
</P>
<P>
   Ben: Well, I think you know there are a couple of misconceptions
out there, like chocolate not being good for you. Chocolate makes
me happy, and I eat chocolate and I feel better.
</P>
<P>
   Janeane: It helps him direct films.
</P>
<P>
   Question: ``What would be your advice to couples at that
breaking point but who still think that somewhere deep in their
hearts they can maintain a friendship?''
</P>
<P>
   Janeane: If they don't have the financial backing that we've
enjoyed, I'd say walk away.
</P>
<P>
   Ben: I've had the experience of going around in circles for
years and years in a relationship. That cycle of together, apart,
together, apart can be emotionally very exciting on a level of
being able to keep your life totally in disarray. I encourage
anybody who wants to have an unhealthy relationship, just get
together with somebody who feeds into all of your neuroses and you
feed into all their neuroses and insecurities.
</P>
<P>
   Janeane: Right, you have to have somebody whose dysfunctions
dovetail perfectly with your own.
</P>
<P>
   Ben: And that's the perfect recipe for drama, which is the key
to any bad relationship. But in terms of trying to make it work, if
you've broken up and gotten together more than five times, that's
not a good sign. And if you've been engaged for more than five
years, it's probably never going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Question: ``So, five is your magic number?''
</P>
<P>
   Ben: I'd say five is the magic number.
</P>
<P>
   Question: ``When you were writing the book, did you have any
disagreements? What was the major tug of war you had?''
</P>
<P>
   Ben: Who was going to spell-check, who would actually have to
type it out.
</P>
<P>
   Janeane: Who was going to have to cut down the trees for the
paper.
</P>
<P>
   Question: ``There's a rumor that this relationship you two
reveal is itself a spoof that you made up for this book.''
</P>
<P>
   Janeane: I can prove that I used to dress up in the T.J.
O'Pooter-Toots mechanical bear costumes to entice Ben, and that I
damaged my spine.
</P>
<P>
   Question: ``Do you have photos of that?''
</P>
<P>
   Janeane: I have photos of me trying to seduce him in a
mechanical bear costume.
</P>
<P>
   Ben: And I have the dirty sheets. No, we had a little thing a
long time ago, and then, you know, all humor kind of springs from a
little nugget of truth. Hopefully a tree of comedy grows.
</P>
<P>
   Question: ``So it might have only been that one date, that one
night?''
</P>
<P>
   Ben: There was a couple of somethings.
</P>
<P>
   Question: ``Are there any other types of books you'd like to
spoof? How about the celebrity memoir?''
</P>
<P>
   Janeane: Well, this sort of was a combination of the New Age
celebrity memoir. So, we killed two birds with one stone on that.
</P>
<P>
   Ben: I'd like to write a novel, a stream of consciousness novel,
kind of in the ``Ulysses'' vein, from the point of view of a
Swedish supermodel that comes to America and is exposed to all the
glitterati, and just the fame and the craziness and the drugs and
write it entirely in Swedish, with no punctuation. I'm doing
research for it now, actually.
</P>
<P>
   Question: ``When you read each other's pieces, you must've
laughed out loud several times.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben: Yeah, I mean, I totally enjoyed Janeane's humor.
</P>
<P>
   Janeane: And I totally enjoyed my humor as well.
</P>
<P>
   Question: ``You have appeared in any number of projects together
and have another one coming up, `Mystery Men.' What is it that
keeps you reuniting?''
</P>
<P>
   Janeane: What keeps us reuniting? Well, we happen to be
next-door neighbors in real life. And it's just _ in the stand-up
comedy community, you kind of wind up wanting to work with the same
people a lot, again and again.
</P>
<P>
   Ben: It's not something that's planned out. We just happen to
have worked together since the beginnings of our careers, really.
It just kind of self-generates. It's nice to have a continuity
working with somebody you know and like, and we seem to have a
connection on a creative level that I enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Question: ``When is the best time to give up a grudge?''
</P>
<P>
   Janeane: I don't think there is a good time to give up a grudge.
</P>
<P>
   Question: ``With your family?''
</P>
<P>
   Janeane: Oh, no, no, especially with your family, because
they're with you for life. I think it's an important show of
internal strength and inner fortitude to hang onto the grudge.
</P>
<P>
   Question: ``Forget the fact that you had a relationship. It's
totally shocking to hear you're next-door neighbors. That's even
harder than being in a relationship with somebody. How did that
happen, and how is that working out? Do you fight over things like
cutting down trees and things like that?''
</P>
<P>
   Janeane: We live in New York City, so there are no trees to be
cut down. But he is always forever coming over to borrow a cup of
sugar, and it's at this point getting ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Ben: She makes a lot of noise.
</P>
<P>
   Janeane: I have my loud rock music.
</P>
<P>
   Ben: And other things ...
</P>
<P>
   Janeane: So he's always banging with a broom on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Question: ``Has anyone approached you about putting together a
radio or TV show where you could actually dispense advice?''
</P>
<P>
   Ben: Not yet, but I think it would be funny to do an infomercial
for the book.
</P>
<P>
   Question: ``Has there been any parental influence in the advice
you give in the book?''
</P>
<P>
   Janeane: No, none. I actually don't even know if my father has
read the book, let alone given any input.
</P>
<P>
   Ben: No, none.
</P>
<P>
   Janeane: As you know, my parents are Liz Taylor and Eddie
Fisher. So you would think they would have a lot of input in a book
like this.
</P>
<P>
   Ben: My parents are Mike Nichols and Elaine May.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXX &QL; 
 &QL; 
Stiller and Garofalo also read the audio version of ``Feel This
Book'' (Random House, $18).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
