<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. When I start up my Macintosh, I see an icon of a blinking
question mark on a floppy disk for a couple of seconds and then it
begins to boot up normally. Why does it do this?
</P>
<P>
   A. The blinking question mark means that the Mac is trying to
find its start-up device _ usually your computer's hard drive,
which contains the System Folder. If you have recently reset your
parameter RAM (the Mac RAM that controls things like date and time
settings) or installed iMac Firmware Update 1.0, you might see this
behavior. To fix it, go into Control Panels, select the one called
Startup Disk and click on the icon of your hard drive. The problem
should go away the next time you restart.
</P>
<P>
   If you ever boot up your Mac and get a flashing question mark
icon that won't go away, it means that the computer cannot find its
operating system software. There are a number of causes for this
problem, including damaged system software (which can happen during
a really bad crash), corrupted parameter RAM, problems in the
connections between your Mac and other hardware devices, or
mechanical problems with your hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   If the flashing icon won't go away, try to restart the machine
from the system software CD (or Disk Tools floppy) that came with
your Mac. There is a vaild System Folder on there, as well as a
small repair program called Disk First Aid. Third-party utility
programs like Micromat's Tech Tool Pro or Symantec's Norton
Utilities will also let you start your computer from the CD, and
they have a variety of diagnostic and repair programs to help fix
what ails your Mac. If none of these help, there may be a hardware
problem, which means a trip to your local repair shop may be in
order.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West
43d St., New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
Q&AMP;A(AT)nytimes.com.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 1624EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
