<SLUG> BC-BATHROOM-FLOOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND NOW MEET THE FLINTSTONE FLOOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FRED BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It could have been the ultimate faux pas: Blake
Sherlock and Andrew Sloan had just moved to New York to create
artworks (at their Sloan/Sherlock Gallery in Chelsea), and I was
asking if they would redo my bathroom floor.
</P>
<P>
   But then, their art is made of shells and stones and other found
objects turned into richly textured mosaics. On my floor, I
imagined, their work would make me feel as if I was walking
barefoot at the beach or wading in a river.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing really wrong with the bathroom except the
floor: the fixtures were fine, the walls were fine, the plumbing
was fine, but the floor was a depressing brown-and-white tile,
muddy in tone and mealy in texture, that gave the entire room a
depressing cast.
</P>
<P>
   I had been covering the floor with throw rugs, and had thought
about redoing it, but I didn't want to spend a lot of money. (This
is a rental apartment, and my landlord could ask me to remove any
alterations before I leave.) So, although I considered installing
green glass tiles, I never quite got around to it. I was afraid
they would be slippery or sharp. I did, however, price the job;
tiling my 20 or so square feet would have cost me about $800,
installed.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on a gallery visit, I saw the objects (including mirrors,
picture frames and vases) that the artists had encrusted with river
stones, and asked them _ gingerly _ if they would do my bathroom.
They said they would think about it (is this how Julian Schnabel
got started?), and about a month later, they called me.
</P>
<P>
   They already had a bushel of Indonesian river stones, in pale
green but with a great degree of variation, which they brought with
them when they came from California in October. (Similar stones are
sold at Smith &AMP; Hawken, in SoHo, for $4 a pound, as we discovered
when we ran short. They were a little more polished, and the color
was bolder.)
</P>
<P>
   The team began by covering my floor with patches of concrete,
into which they began setting the stones _ a far more painstaking
process than I had imagined. (I estimate that there are 1,200
stones in the floor.) After a 14-hour day, the stones were set; the
cement took 48 hours (during which I showered at the gym) to dry.
It was then that the floor was at its most eccentric. ``Don't stub
your toe,'' warned a friend, after seeing a photograph of the
irregular surface.
</P>
<P>
   But the topographic-map quality receded as soon as Sloan and
Sherlock began grouting, a process that took another full day. A
few more showers at the gym, to let the grout dry, and we were
done. Entirely maintenance free (true, it's a bit harder to mop
than a smooth tile floor, but only a bit), the floor reminds me of
a trip to Bali I took last year, when I lay in a river bed _on
stones not unlike these _ while cool water washed over me.
</P>
<P>
   The pair, who can be reached at (212) 675-2391, charged $650 for
materials and labor. They will consider other design commissions
(they just completed a fireplace with pique-assiette _ literally,
broken plate _ the name artisans gave to the craft of assembling
chipped china, shells, beach glass and the like), but warn that,
never having done this sort of thing before, they underbid my job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 1627EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
