<SLUG> BC-TV-RERUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SEASON WASN'T A TOTAL WASTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As reruns begin to flood your screen next week,
you might not think it's a great time for television, but you'd be
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The networks have cleared out the deadwood _ and a few lovable
shows with it, unfortunately _ and they have built the foundations
for next season. This is when hopes are at their highest in TV
Land. The networks are dreamers now and, for possibly the first and
last time, the critics are right there with them, hoping against
history that something great might be created for fall.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, cable channels are gearing up to fill the
summer void traditionally left empty by the broadcast networks.
More often than not, cable gives us the best new series and
certainly the best made-for-TV movies on the dial.
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, this is the time we look back at the close of the season
_ not in December, when all those year-end best-of lists are made.
That's not how the TV season works. It starts in September, has a
nebulously slated midseason between January and April, then ends
with a blast in May. Which brings us up to date.
</P>
<P>
   (Every year the networks promise they will program for summer
instead of closing shop. But they never get around to it.)
</P>
<P>
   As the season shuts down this week, it's only natural to look
back _ and ahead _ to what was and what will be.
</P>
<P>
   First, a pop quiz. Raise your hand if you remember these shows:
``Conrad Bloom,'' ``The Brian Benben Show,'' ``Guys Like Us,''
``DiResta,'' ``The Secret Diary of Desmond Pfeiffer'' and
``Hyperion Bay.''
</P>
<P>
   Anybody? And that was only the Monday lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the much-touted ``Encore! Encore!'' with Broadway star
Nathan Lane? How about ``Mercy Point'' with Joe ``Brother From
Another Planet'' Morton? Or ``Costello,'' starring some woman no
one had ever heard of? Ah, get a giant whiff of that nostalgia for
last fall.
</P>
<P>
   There was ``The Secret Lives of Men,'' television's attempt to
show what men really were talking about or feeling. Instead, we
learned they couldn't even carry their own golf bags during their
weekly round. ``Maggie Winters'' failed; so did ``To Have and To
Hold.''
</P>
<P>
   The latter was yet another cliched look at the Irish, who
suffered much abuse last season by countless shows trying to give
us ``family.''
</P>
<P>
   The dark ``Vengeance Unlimited'' failed, as did the perky Olsen
Twins in ``Two of a Kind.'' Another dreadful show aimed at kids and
parents was ``Brother's Keeper,'' and it, too, was laid low. Dennis
Farina as a resurrected swingin' private eye in ``Buddy Faro''
collapsed, sadly. ``Trinity'' _ the worst of the Irish lot (the
first spoken sentence was about potatoes burning) _ was axed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living in Captivity,'' one of two mysteriously clueless shows
about blacks and whites living together in the suburbs, never
caught on. Neither did ``Legacy'' or the revamped ``Fantasy
Island'' or Bo Derek's pathetic ``Wind on Water.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cupid'' _ a great show _ was destroyed prematurely by its
network (ABC). ``Holding the Baby'' and ``The Army Show'' _
relentlessly bad offerings _ were mercifully ended.
</P>
<P>
   And those were just the casualties of fall. When midseason came
around, others went down _ ``Strange World,'' William Devane's
``Turks,'' ``Payne,'' the Americanized ``Fawlty Towers,''
``Everything's Relative,'' ``Brimstone,'' the egregiously awful
``Sons of Thunder,'' ``Family Rules,'' ``Reunited,'' ``Rescue 77''
and the lovely, frail, little cartoon ``Home Movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Uh, thanks for the memories.
</P>
<P>
   It was a season that most television critics called the worst in
years, a new nadir. But was it really? We had ``The Sopranos'' _
the best show on television. ``Sports Night'' ignited the half-hour
dramedy with intelligence and feeling, a concept creatively dead
since ``MASH.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Will &AMP; Grace'' emerged as an excellent sitcom _ truly an
accomplishment in today's lowered-bar, loud-laugh-track environment
for comedies. ``Felicity,'' the buzz show of September, may not
have delivered on the hype but was unafraid to wear emotion on its
sleeve, a brave rarity in these times of ever- present irony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charmed,'' as paper-thin as the previous season's ``Dharma &AMP;
Greg,'' was a surprise for The WB. And Fox finally made a decent
non-animated comedy in ``That '70s Show.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was the midseason offerings that truly scored. Fox's
``Family Guy,'' ``The PJs'' and ``Futurama'' proved animation often
is better than live action _ the same can be said of UPN's
``Dilbert.'' Comedies that could show creative growth include CBS's
``Becker'' and ABC's ``The Norm Show'' and ``It's Like, You Know.
...''
</P>
<P>
   NBC hit a nerve with ``Providence'' on Fridays, sending networks
scurrying to find female-friendly dramas.
</P>
<P>
   Although summer series were few, HBO's ``Sex and the City''
proved to be one of television's finest series. And ABC scored with
``Whose Line Is It Anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   The ratio of hits to misses is low, but the quality of the best
shows was greater than in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What, then, can we look forward to in September, now that the
networks have offered up their goods (on paper, at least)?
</P>
<P>
   Well, we can hope some of the shows look as good as their
premises, while praying that others rise and surprise us.
</P>
<P>
   ``West Wing,'' a new NBC drama set in the White House from Aaron
Sorkin (``Sports Night'') and John Wells (``ER'') would have to be
considered a strong candidate. ABC has two potentially good dramas
in David Kelley's private-eye series, ``Snoops,'' , and
``Wasteland,'' a coming-of-age series from Kevin Williamson, who
did ``Dawson's Creek'' for The WB.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Haggis, who guided the excellent, short-lived ``EZ
Streets'' and ``Due South,'' could work some magic with a CBS pilot
called ``Family Law,'' about a woman who starts her own law
practice when her lawyer husband divorces her and takes the
clients, too.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Carter's new series for Fox, ``Harsh Realm,'' will be
closely watched just because of who he is (even though
``Millennium'' never caught on with viewers). And the lone comedy
that stands out is ``Action,'' from Chris Thompson (``The Larry
Sanders Show''), which satirizes the Hollywood film industry.
</P>
<P>
   Few others have premises or pedigree that would make anyone take
notice. Of course, cable will come up with something brilliant, or
we could find more quality at midseason. But even still, if you can
get four or five truly wonderful shows each season, that's enough _
even though it shouldn't be.
</P>
<P>
   Lowered expectations? Maybe. And perhaps we shouldn't stand for
it. But the fact is, there have been seasons in which we didn't get
four of five quality shows.
</P>
<P>
   Let's not be greedy or bitter just yet. Let's stay hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
