<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKBOOK-SEX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I'LL HAVE WHAT SHE'S HAVING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sex seems to be the hottest ingredient on the cookbook shelves
these days.
</P>
<P>
   The newest arrival is ``Easy Exotic,'' a luscious little volume
of recipes written by raven-haired, sloe-eyed Indian model Padma
Lakshmi. If a recipe for honeyed chicken legs doesn't get your
attention, the photograph of the author dressed in a black
nightgown looking longingly at leeks is bound to do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like water for chocolate; it's like sex for supper.
</P>
<P>
   I'm gravity-impaired enough to wish Lakshmi would take her
mangoes somewhere other than to my home and hearth. It's not enough
to know how to fricassee anymore; it appears I also need to know
how to, well, whatever.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so she's young: I can't compete with that. But her book
arrived on the high heels of ``Sophia Loren's Recipes &AMP; Memories.''
And there she is, with 60-something years of mileage. Sophia, on
the cover, posed over dead fish and looking scrumptious; high
cheekbones, gypsy eyes and firm forearms.
</P>
<P>
   Sophia Loren has always said, ``Everything you see, I owe to
pasta.'' Yeah, right. Give me a plate of pasta and I end up with
red spots on my blouse.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make a food editor stay out of the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   However, I might be able to manage, because the other book that
caught my eye recently was ``72 Market St.'' by Roland Gibert. This
tony little restaurant in Venice, Calif., is owned by the author
(who is also the chef), Tony Bill and actor Dudley Moore. Like many
things Californian, the book is well-designed and full of buff
people.
</P>
<P>
   Including, I will confess, waiter Robert Fegan. Fegan's
photograph goes Loren's one better. He's holding the dead fish and
looking tall and tan and lean and lovely up to his white dress
shirt in the Pacific Ocean. Now, there's surf and turf any woman
would order.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
