<HEADER>
A2114 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-PROJECTORS-ART-2T     05-26 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-PROJECTORS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL PROJECTORS USE FLASHES OF LIGHT TO PAINT A MOVIE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Ga., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MICHEL MARRIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the first $100 million worth of paying customers crammed
into movie theaters last week to see the highly anticipated ``Star
Wars'' film ``The Phantom Menace,'' few of them may have realized
or even cared that only 5 percent of its 130 minutes are free of
digital enhancements like computer-generated characters and
backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   But if George Lucas has his way, the entire movie experience may
be reduced to ones and zeroes.
</P>
<P>
   On June 18, Lucas' Lucasfilm company is expected to set up
screenings of ``The Phantom Menace'' in four theaters using new
digital projectors. The movie will be beamed into theaters by
satellite, then shown on the screen by filmless projectors _ a
radical departure from the traditional way movies have been shown
for the last century. The only thing that will be the same is the
popcorn and soda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is really great proof of concept,'' Lance Weiler
said of Lucasfilm's plans. In October, Weiler, co-founder of
Wavelength Releasing, an electronic cinema company based in Bucks
County near Philadelphia, digitally showed his own film, ``The Last
Broadcast,'' which he co-directed with Stefan Avalos.
</P>
<P>
   The full-length, digital whodunit was produced (also digitally)
for about $900 and beamed by satellite into a handful of theaters
and projected onto standard-size movie screens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Digital technology has invaded everything,'' said Weiler, who
envisions that digital distribution of movies will eliminate the
need of costly prints of 35-millimeterfilms as well as the expense
and time to ship them around the world. ``It only makes sense that
it is going to come into the distribution and transport of
movies.''
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the system is a new, second generation of digital
projector, said Tim J. Butler, the marketing and communications
manager at Digital Projection, a maker of projection systems in
Kennesaw, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   These expensive, yet modest-size projectors have quietly been
making their way into widespread use in private screening rooms,
post-production houses and in live presentations like the ``film''
sequences seen in televised award shows like the Academy Awards and
Grammys.
</P>
<P>
   But Butler said the next big leap forward for digital
projectors, which cost about three times the $30,000 price tag on
standard movie theater projectors, will be into multiplex theaters,
where they will have the potential to revolutionize how movies are
distributed, shown and watched.
</P>
<P>
   To the untrained eye, today's digital protectors look like
overgrown slide projectors. But they are vastly more complicated
and depend on microcomputer technologies and powerful xenon arc
light sources.
</P>
<P>
   The current generation, scheduled to be updated in a few months,
has more in common with a personal computer than a mechanical film
projector.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Levi, president of Digital Projection, explained that once
a film is in digital form and sent to a movie theater by satellite
or by electronic tape, it can be fed into the projector through a
simple cable.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the digital movie data goes through a seven-layered
processing board that is specialized to make video images look more
filmlike. The processor looks at such key picture elements as
resolution, color and brightness, and then reformats the signal
into the form of discrete instructions that are sent to three units
called digital micromirror devices, or DMDs.
</P>
<P>
   Each digital micromirror device contains 800,000 tiny mirrors.
(A newer model to be introduced soon by Digital Projection will
have 1.3 million mirrors in each of its three DMDs.) The mirrors,
so small that four of them across measure about the diameter of a
human hair, are able to tilt plus or minus 10 degrees on almost
microscopic hinges.
</P>
<P>
   Besides receiving digital information, each micromirror device
also receives a designated color of light, either red, green or
blue, made from white light refracted through a special dichroic
prism. Each mirror, which represents one pixel of the total
picture, is capable, Levi said, so it is either reflecting light or
not (which means its pixel is black), more than 1,000 times a
second.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The resulting light from each of the DMD's 800,000 mirrors is
sent back into the dichroic prism where all of the light is merged,
then directed through a lense and projected onto a screen for
viewers to see.
</P>
<P>
   Levi said the projector creates high-frequency pulses of light
that the human eye and brain integrate into pixels, and when all
800,000 pixels of light are seen they appear as a smooth,
continuous image that can contain up to one billion different
colors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It creates an image that so strikingly resembles film,'' said
Levi, who asserted that the brightness and resolution of movies
shown with digital projectors is superior to films shown with
standard mechanical projectors. ``It has a very continuous feel and
is very accurate.'' And because the film is preserved digitally, it
never shows dirt and wear and tear.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the American Museum of the Moving Image in
Queens, along with the Independent Film Channel and Wavelength
Releasing, the electronic cinema company, invited members of the
film industry and the public to judge digital projection for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Audiences gathered at the Directors Guild of America, a sponsor
of the program, in Manhattan to see films projected with
traditional and digital projectors and to listen to panel
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is most interesting to me,'' said Carl Goodman, curator
of digital media at the American Museum of the Moving Image, ``is
what, over time, these technological changes will do to the
esthetics of the medium.''
</P>
<P>
   But many filmmakers said that while they or intrigued by the
possibilities that digital projectors create for exhibiting movies,
most of the benefits will be had by studios. It will be some time,
if ever, when digital projectors affect the manner in which movies
are conceived and produced, many of them said.
</P>
<P>
   S.D. Katz, who directed ``Protest,'' a digital short film beamed
by satellite and shown last week at the Cannes Film Festival, said
audiences or not likely to see any real differences any time soon.
``Everyone is straining to look exactly like film,'' he said of the
budding digital projection industry. ``There is no reason for it to
change.''
</P>
<P>
   But if digital projectors become commonplace in movie theaters,
more movie makers might be encouraged to shot their work digitally
because the high cost of transferring their digital movies to film
would mostly be eliminated, said Dan Genetti, a production
executive at Palm Pictures, an entertainment company that has made
a number of digital movies, including a breakthrough feature last
year called ``Dance Hall Queen,'' said that digital projectors
might encourage more filmmakers to use digital cameras because the
high cost of transferring their work to film would be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get a reasonably priced way to deliver the movie,
which digital projection will do,'' Genetti said, ``you'll have an
inducement for people to work in the medium.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 1705EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
