A2139 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     05-26 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV13-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., JUNE 13, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: When I was repainting the windows on the outside of my
50-year-old house I noticed that the wood sill on a couple of the
windows seems to have rotted in several places. The wood feels soft
and spongy when poked with a screwdriver or putty knife, even
though in some places the paint still looks in good condition. Can
I repair these wood sills without having to replace them?
</P>
<P>
   A: If the rotted areas are relatively small sections then you
can usually repair the rotted places by patching with a two-part
epoxy putty or patching material. Dig out all soft and crumbly wood
fibers and scrape off any paint that is still over this area. Epoxy
will only bond firmly to bare wood that is completely dry, and the
surface should be rough. If the rot is quite deep, drive a couple
of screws partly into the solid wood under the rot in order to
reinforce the patch. Mix the epoxy according to the directions on
the package and pack firmly into the cavity on a day when
temperatures are well above 50 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We live in a condominium and share one wall with the
apartment next door. We can constantly hear our neighbors talking
and playing their TV set, so we put up an extra layer of 5/8''
gypsum board to soundproof our common wall. However, we can still
hear them and they can hear us. What can we do to really soundproof
the wall between our two apartments?
</P>
<P>
   A. Really effective soundproofing calls for building a
completely new, additional wall an inch or two in front of the
existing wall. This new wall should not touch the old wall at any
point and the space between the two walls should be filled with
acoustical fiberglass insulation. Finish the new wall with a layer
of sound-absorbing board then apply a layer of gypsum board over
this. Caulk with silicone rubber along the bottom and top of both
walls, and along the joint where the new wall joins the old walls
at each end.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The aluminum siding on the outside of my house is over 20
years old and the finish has started to chalk and wear off in
several places. I've scrubbed it down to get rid of the dirt, but
it still doesn't look great. Can this aluminum siding be painted,
or must it be replaced?
</P>
<P>
   A: Aluminum siding has often been painted successfully. You must
first scrub off most of the chalkiness, using a strong detergent
and then flushing thoroughly with lots of water. Allow the surface
to dry, then paint with two coats of a good quality acrylic latex
house paint recommended for use on aluminum siding. Follow
directions on the label as to thinning and preparation of the
surface.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My house has three wood beams in the dining room ceiling,
each going from wall to wall. The builder told me these were purely
decorative, although they are real wood that has been stained a
dark color. There are numerous cracks in these beams, several of
which are quite deep. Is there a chance that this poses any kind of
danger, and if they need fixing how is this done?
</P>
<P>
   A: Since the beams are purely ornamental, there is no danger or
risk. If the appearance bothers you the cracks can be simply filled
in with a wood putty of some kind, but this means they would have
to be refinished to hide the patches. If the beams are actually
supporting a load and thus are not purely ornamental, then a
builder or engineer should be called in to examine the structure.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``USING EPOXY TO FIX A ROTTED SILL''
goes with this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: After soft and rotting wood is scraped out, cavity can
be filled in with a two-part epoxy putty or patching compound.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
