<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2149 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-VIOLENCE27-COX     05-26 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-VIOLEN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 CE27-COX &HT;    SCHOOL VIOLENCE UNCHANGED OVER FIVE YEARS
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Students are just as likely to be victims of
violence in public schools as their predecessors were five years
previously, according to new surveys.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spite of a number of things that schools have done, and
despite the decline in violence nationally, the number of students
and teachers who report being victims of violence in and around
schools has not decreased,'' Humphrey Taylor, chairman of Louis
Harris and Associates, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the case of teachers, it has actually increased,'' he told
education and law enforcement officials at a briefing in the
National Press Club.
</P>
<P>
   MetLife commissioned his firm to conduct school-violence surveys
in 1993 and the fall of 1998. Responding in 1998 were 1,000 public
school teachers, 1,404 public school students in grades 3 through
12, and 100 law enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest survey:
</P>
<P>
   _ Among teachers, 16 percent said they had been victims of
violent acts in or around schools. That was up from 11 percent in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   _ Among students, the percentage reporting that they had been
victims of violent acts in or around schools was statistically
unchanged, at 24 percent in 1998 and 23 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   _ Among students, those who said they had personally carried a
weapon to school was statistically unchanged, at 12 percent in 1998
and 11 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Another dramatic finding is that 47 percent of the students
in grades seven through 12 said it is somewhat or very easy to get
a gun,'' Taylor said. ``This was before the shootings in Littleton
and Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   But on a day-to-day basis, the danger of being cut exceeds the
danger of being shot, according to the 72 percent of students who
say that at their own school at least a few students ``regularly
carry weapons such as handguns or knives to school.''
</P>
<P>
   What type of weapon? More of the students named knives (59
percent), razors (33 percent), scissors (30 percent), penknives (29
percent) switchblades (29 percent), pepper spray (24 percent), mace
(23 percent), box cutters (21 percent), than mentioned handguns (14
percent).
</P>
<P>
   Teachers and law enforcement officials were far more worried
about handguns.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to name weapons that students brought to school, 79
percent of the teachers named knives and 22 percent named handguns.
Among law enforcement officials, who tend to be called in only for
the most threatening situations, 92 percent mentioned knives and 49
percent mentioned handguns.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the briefing pointed out that schools remain far
safer than most places where children spend their time. All denied
that the lack of progress within schools was their fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably have 50 (anti-violence) programs that didn't exist
five years ago,'' said Frank Newman, president of the Education
Commission of the States. ``The question now is, 'Can we bring
these things up to scale?''
</P>
<P>
   ``With millions of students, there will always be the one
percent or two percent of the student population that we can never
reach,'' said Gerald Tirozzi, executive director of the National
Association of Secondary School Principals. ``As long as those kids
have access to assault weapons, there is nothing you are going to
do to keep those kids from coming in and murdering someone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe it or not, crime in schools is down,'' said William
Modzeleski, the federal Education Department's director of Safe and
Drug Free Schools. His statement, based on crimes reported to
police, was consistent with the survey's finding that students
don't report many violent acts.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
