<SLUG> BC-STATES-BUDGET </SLUG>
  THIS IS THE STATES NEWS SERVICE BUDGET FOR MAY
26, 1999. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, PLEASE CALL US AT
202-628-3100.
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA-WINE-INTERNET. A battle is brewing in Congress over
regulating sales of alcohol over the Internet. Two amendments,
passed last week by the Senate, would give the federal government
the power to regulate state liquor laws, the first such national
oversight since Prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   (800 words.) By Mark Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA-STUDY. (For the Hollywood Reporter.) The raunchy
content of prime-time television has increased despite voluntary
ratings on programs. Actually, it may be increasing because of
those ratings, according to a study completed by a television
watchdog group (300 words.) By Robin Brown
</P>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA-MCCAIN. Sens. John McCain and Orrin Hatch introduce
legislation to streamline telecommunications mergers (Brief.) By
Robin Brown
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-GEOGRAPHY-BEE. Name the present-day country in eastern
Africa that was once known as the French Territory of the Afars and
Issas. Can you name it? Greg Thaler, a Yarmouth eighth-grader,
knows the answer is Djibouti, and that's not all. Thaler answered
more than a dozen other questions correctly Wednesday to outlast
all but three of his competitors in the National Geography Bee,
pocketing a $500 savings bond and some well-deserved fame. (500
words.) By Charles Davant
</P>
<P>
   MICHIGAN-BEE. A Michigan teenager took third place in the
National Geography Bee. (300 words.) By C.J.Karamargin
</P>
<P>
   NEW JERSEY-BUS. Cautioning that the investigation into the
deadly Christmas Eve crash on the Garden State Parkway is ongoing,
the top federal highway safety official says faulty windows helped
cause the deaths of eight passengers. Kane
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA-BEE. Fourteen-year-old Raji Shankar got a $500
prize for being a finalist in the National Geography Bee. (400
words.) By Lisa Fine
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN-KIND-BALKANS. Upon arrival in the Balkans, Rep. Ron
Kind was met with the cheers of ``U.S.A., U.S.A.'' and ``NATO,
NATO'' from the refugees who had been forced out of their homes in
Kosovo by Serbian forces. The reactions the LaCrosse Democrat met
on his weekend in the Balkans confirmed his beliefs that NATO and
the U.S. need to do whatever is necessary to stop the terror of
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic. (500 words) By Elizabeth Hurt
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
