<P>
   COCA-COLA LAWSUIT
</P>
<P>
   COKE-IVESTER _Coca-Cola Chairman M. Douglas Ivester informed
employees today that he ``will personally increase'' his effors to
open the lines of communications with the company's minority
employees and will create a Diversity Advisory Council that will
meet regularly to discuss issues facing the company. The council
will be headed by Carl Ware and Jack Stahl, head of the company's
Africa and U.S. operations, respectively. In an interview Ware, who
directed a report on ways to improve black employee opportunities
at Coca-Cola, said he feels the company has ``a way to go'' to meet
the ``gold standard'' for racial diversity. He added, however, that
he does not believe the company discriminates in the way it treats
employees. (Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COKE-SIDE _ Coca-Cola sends out a message to employees informing
them not to destroy internal documents as the company faces a
racial discrimination lawsuit filed for three current and one
former employee. (Unger, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COKE-WARE _ Carl Ware, who directed a report on ways to improve
black employee opportunities at Coca-Cola, said on Wednesday he
feels the company has ``a way to go'' to meet the ``gold standard''
for racial diversity. He added, however, that he does not believe
the company discriminates in the way it treats employees. Ware,
president of the Africa unit of the soft drink company, said he
hopes all senior officers will do what he does: Make every effort
to identify top African American talent and mentor cultivate them
as the company does all top talent. Ware, Newnan native who has
been with Coke 25 years, said Ivester was one of his mentors and
had personally helped to cultivate other African American
supervisors. (Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SOCOMPANY _ Southern Co. holds its annual meeting (WEDNESDAY) in
Birmingham. The company recently continued a restructuring, with
Chairman and Chief Executive Bill Dahlberg giving up his
president's title, which now goes to Allen Franklin, head of
Georgia Power. (Quinn, Atlanta Jornal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ A rundown of the week's financial press. (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   COX-RYSHER _ Cox Broadcasting is exiting the business of making
TV shows, selling the rights to its production Paramount studios.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
