A2186 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKO-RED-WINGS-HNS &LR;      05-26 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKO-RED-WINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOCKEY TEAM'S DEPARTURE STINGS SMALL NEW YORK TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD FITZPATRICK  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENS FALLS, N.Y. _ Two decades ago, the Adirondack Red Wings
were the drawing card for a Civic Center that set Glens Falls apart
from other small cities. Ever since then, this has been a hockey
town.
</P>
<P>
   The Wings have been a source of community pride: They won four
American Hockey League championships.
</P>
<P>
   Fans like teen-ager Kristy Quackenbush plastered their bedrooms
with team photos and posters. And at the paper mills and catheter
plants that are the bedrock of Warren County industry, the local
team has long been the currency of daily conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better than talking about Finch Pruyn laying off,'' city
firefighter Daniel Girard said, speaking of one local mill, ``or
where we should have a truck route.''
</P>
<P>
   But like the Browns leaving Cleveland, or even the Dodgers
leaving Brooklyn, the Adirondack Red Wings have left ``Hometown,
USA'' behind. Last week, the Detroit Red Wings announced its AHL
franchise will not return. Instead, the team will skip a year, then
move to a new arena outside Toledo, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   And now, Glens Falls is faced with reinventing itself, having
lost what many residents came to see as its civic soul.
</P>
<P>
   On a grand scale, the team's loss to this upstate New York city
of 14,772 is a much smaller event than a major-league defection.
``But for a small town, it still has the exact same effect,''
Girard said.
</P>
<P>
   The impact is partly economic. The team pumped an estimated $6.5
million into the community each year, according to a 1996 analysis
by the Warren County Regional Economic Development Corp. The city
unemployment rate is already above the state average, standing at
5.7 percent in April, and now Glens Falls will lose a team with a
$1.6 million payroll and about 35 employees. The move also
jeopardizes the jobs of 14 Civic Center employees.
</P>
<P>
   The city is severing its contract with the Detroit organization
that ran the center and will either hire a new company or its own
people to run the place.
</P>
<P>
   But economically, the team's departure is by no means a fatal
blow. From Finch Pruyn to Glens Falls Cement, the area still has an
industrial base. And the economy is growing more high tech, with
two companies that provide television listings to newspapers, TV
Data Technologies and Tribune Media Services, which together employ
485 people.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, it seems, the impact of the Red Wings' departure
will have less to do with jobs or the economy than with civic
image, pride and soul. The area has an annual balloon festival and
an arts festival, but what will it do without the Wings?
</P>
<P>
   That's what Kristy Quackenbush, a 16-year-old from nearby Hudson
Falls, wants to know.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush has been attending games with her grandparents, Fred
and Mary Jane Quackenbush, since she was 5. It's been three years
since she missed a game at the Civic Center, where the concession
lady knows she always buys a medium Sprite between the second and
third periods.
</P>
<P>
   Kristy was in bed at 7:30 Monday morning when her dad broke the
bad news. At first, she didn't believe it. But then she saw the
newspaper headline ``Red Wings Ready to Fly.'' And she cried.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of fans are sad. But Girard said that like Brooklyn
Dodgers fans, some Glens Falls residents are also angry their team
is leaving.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some sound bitter when they talk about the Ilitch
family, which owns the Detroit and Adirondack Red Wings. ``They
don't care about friendship and loyalty. They care about the
almighty dollar,'' said Kay Saunders, the Glens Falls Common
Council president and one of the first to buy Red Wings season
tickets each year. ``I wish them the best on the road to nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the departure are clear. Attendance was
plunging, from an average of 5,154 per game in 1980-81 to 3,441
last season. Financial losses were mounting, with the team
expecting to lose more than $2 million next season. And the team
was facing competition, with the arrival of another AHL team, the
River Rats, based in a larger arena in nearby Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Civic Center was facing criticism for its
marketing and maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   There had been plenty of talk that the Red Wings might leave.
But fans expected to have at least one more season to say goodbye
to their heroes in red and white. The owners, however, said they
couldn't afford another year of red ink.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some feel cheated, but others wish the end had come even sooner,
given the team's dismal performance and falling attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had had Dr. Kevorkian, it would have been better to pull
the plug a couple of years ago,'' said Edward M. Bartholomew Jr.,
an attorney who was mayor when the Red Wings came to town.
Bartholomew was referring to Jack Kevorkian, the Michigan doctor
and proponent of assisted suicides.
</P>
<P>
   Many trace the team's departure to a 1990 decision that allowed
another AHL franchise _ now the Albany River Rats _ into the
region. The Red Wings received $1 million in exchange for letting a
competitor on its turf.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990 decision definitely hurt attendance in Glens Falls,
Civic Center Executive Director Don Ostrom said. But the AHL
encouraged Adirondack to allow competition nearby because the
International Hockey League was trying to make inroads in Albany,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ostrom said the Red Wings were bound to leave Glens Falls
eventually. The league is growing, moving to bigger cities with
bigger arenas, and the Civic Center has just 4,806 seats. In the
early 1980s, AHL teams played in places like Binghamton, N.Y., and
Erie, Pa. Now, they're in Philadelphia and Cincinnati. Player
salaries are up, and smaller venues are on the way out, Ostrom
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Adirondack Red Wings lost between $1.5 million and $2
million last season and expected to lose even more next season,
Ostrom said. ``The bottom line hasn't made sense in quite a
while,'' he said. ``The amazing thing is how Glens Falls ever had
an AHL team and was able to keep it for 20 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
