<HEADER>
A2187 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX     05-26 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA FEELS THE CALL OF A BELL-RINGING ISSUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   America, we need to rethink a very important issue. I've looked
at it from every angle and, frankly, that made my neck hurt.
However, I did conclude that Congress should pass some type of law
on personal phone calls. At the very least, we need a Bill of
Rights. It's just too difficult for employers to make a
hard-and-fast rule that's fair to everyone. Congress probably can't
do that, either, but at least we'd have a uniform policy, like the
Family Medical Leave Act.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the really large employers simply don't allow personal
phone calls, even if you say it's an emergency. They will take a
message and deliver it to the individual, but you can't speak to
anyone directly. That seems very harsh, but I understand it. If
you've got hundreds of employees on an assembly line and they're
constantly getting ``emergency'' phone calls, it interrupts
production and everyone suffers. Not to mention the poor operator
who has to take all the messages and make sure that they get
delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Other, smaller employers will call you to the telephone. But at
your annual review, they mention the ``excessive'' number of
personal phone calls that you've received. Oh, bother.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the real problem is that some people don't know what
constitutes an emergency. Many of these ``urgent'' calls are simply
personal calls that could wait. An emergency is an unexpected
occurrence that needs immediate attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honey, pick up some bread on the way home.'' or ``What are we
having for dinner?'' would not fall into that category. On the
other hand, ``I love you, I miss you, and what are you wearing
right now?'' seem to be emergencies to me.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, doesn't it seem like a personal call ought to be of a
private nature? Yet every time someone hangs up from a personal
call, they turn around and tell everyone within earshot what the
call was about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that was my wife reminding me about the party tonight; as
if I'm going to forget my son's first birthday party.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, ``I cannot believe that child called me at work to tell me
that her sister called her `pizza face girl!' ''
</P>
<P>
   My son called me once and said, ``Mom, I'm hungry and Dad won't
let me have any more chicken.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Put your Dad on the phone,'' I said. When my spouse picked up
the receiver, I asked him, ``Honey, why won't you let him have some
more food? He's a growing boy. I don't want him to fill up on
cookies and chips.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had four pieces already. There's one small wing and half
of a biscuit left, and I was trying to save them for you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, never mind. Please, remind the children not to call me at
work unless it's an emergency. See you later. Oh, by the way,
honey, what are you wearing?''
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
