<SLUG> BC-KEBABS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A SIMPLE CONCEPT EVEN A KID CAN LOVE: DINNER ON A STICK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   En garde _ barbecue season is officially here.
</P>
<P>
   Make this all-American holiday more international by stacking
dinner on a stick. From Morocco to Indonesia, from the shish kebabs
of Turkey to the yakitori of Japan, skewer barbecuing is one of the
oldest cooking techniques known to man.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the mists of time, man was a wanderer who fed himself by
hunting and gathering. He discovered fire, which he could make
anywhere, but he certainly didn't travel with a hide sack full of
Le Creuset. However, sticks were everywhere _ and they were
disposable.
</P>
<P>
   Barbecuing may be a basic technique, but its uses are many. From
appetizers to desserts, it's something to shake a stick at.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   TOOLS OF THE TRADE
</P>
<P>
   Disposable wooden skewers are widely available in several
lengths. Soak them in water or wine for 30 minutes before using, or
they will catch on fire while on the grill.
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary is a sturdy herb that, when stripped of its leaves,
makes an ideal skewer. The branch can be used fresh, but if you're
stripping rosemary for another use, set the branches aside to dry,
then use them for your next barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   Metal kebab skewers should be relatively narrow. Wide skewers
are used for kebabs made with ground-meat mixtures that are packed
onto skewers, such as the kofta of the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Use tongs to turn kebabs on the grill.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   TRICK OF THE TRADE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To get food from the kebab to the plate, hold the kebab at the
handle end with one hand. With the other hand, using pita bread as
your hot pad, push the food off the skewer onto the plates.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   TORTELLINI KEBABS WITH ROASTED TOMATO DIPPING SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-8
</P>
<P>
   Tortellini:
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces fresh or frozen cheese tortellini
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Roasted tomato dipping sauce:
</P>
<P>
   1 tomato, halved horizontally
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   6 basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sour cream (nonfat sour cream is acceptable)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Prepare medium-hot fire in grill.
</P>
<P>
   Bring large pot of salted water to boil for tortellini.
</P>
<P>
   Cook tortellini according to package directions. Drain well.
Toss with olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Brush cut side of tomato halves with a little olive oil. Grill,
cut side down, until tender and grill-marked, about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Peel tomato. On cutting board, in mortar and pestle, or in food
processor, chop tomato, garlic and basil until you have a fine
paste. Stir into sour cream. Add salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Thread tortellini onto skewers. They will stay on skewers best
if threaded through filled part of tortellini. Grill, turning once,
until lightly charred, about 2 minutes per side.
</P>
<P>
   Serve kebabs at once, passing dipping sauce on the side.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving with regular sour cream: 186
calories, 9 grams fat, 20 grams carbohydrates, 7 grams protein, 26
milligrams cholesterol, 124 milligrams sodium, 43 percent of
calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''The Vegetarian Grill'' by Andrea Chesman (Harvard Common
Press, $14.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   GARLIC-ROASTED POTATOES ON ROSEMARY SKEWERS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-6
</P>
<P>
   1 pound red or white new potatoes, each about 1 1/2 inches in
diameter
</P>
<P>
   About 1/2 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   6 sturdy rosemary branches
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Cut potatoes in half and place in medium bowl. Add 2 tablespoons
olive oil and garlic. Season with salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Strip almost all leaves from rosemary branches to form skewers,
leaving some leaves near slightly thinner end. Finely chop enough
leaves to measure 2 tablespoons and add them to potatoes. Toss
potatoes with oil and seasonings, coating thoroughly. Using thicker
end of each rosemary skewer as a point, thread potato halves onto
skewers, dividing them evenly.
</P>
<P>
   Grill directly over medium heat until skins begin to brown and
crisp, 25 to 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Pour vinegar into small saute pan over high heat and boil until
reduced to about 2 tablespoons, about 4 minutes (the vinegar will
be syrupy). Pour enough of remaining olive oil onto a serving
platter to form a thin layer. Sprinkle oil with salt and pepper to
taste. Drizzle warm vinegar over oil. Place skewers on platter,
turn potatoes in oil and vinegar, and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 208 calories, 14 grams fat, 20
grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 0 cholesterol, 6 milligrams
sodium, 60 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''Weber's Art of the Grill'' (Chronicle Books, $35)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
