NYT-05-26-99 1734EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2194 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUZZ-BOOKS-TEX     05-26 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUZZ-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONEST LOOK AT MILITARY POLICY DESERVES A SALUTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every Man a Tiger by Tom Clancy and Gen. Chuck Horner Military
history Putnam, $27.95
</P>
<P>
   Putnam is taking no chances with ``Every Man a Tiger,''
co-written by Tom Clancy and retired Gen. Chuck Horner.
</P>
<P>
   The nonfiction book focuses on Horner's distinguished Air Force
career, but it's packaged to look like the latest Clancy novel.
Clancy's name is emblazoned on the dust jacket in letters 2 inches
high. Underneath, Horner's name is legible if you happen to have a
powerful magnifying glass handy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``Every Man a Tiger'' is truly Horner's book, and not for
the obvious reason that it uses his career as the framework for
illuminating changes in U.S. military philosophy in the past 35
years. Horner was in the middle of a lot of history; from the
bloody morass of Vietnam to the bomb-riddled glory of Desert Storm,
where he served as commander of the Allied air assault.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Horner's commitment to honesty _ ``You only serve by
telling the truth as you saw it,'' he notes _ ``Every Man a Tiger''
will be mesmerizing even to readers not much interested in military
history. Besides his role as guide, Horner proves himself an
immensely ingratiating fellow. First-person bits and pieces about
his family and personal experiences flesh out a recounting of U.S.
military policy that, at times, is frightening in its lack of
flexibility and it dull-witted indifference to non-American
viewpoints.
</P>
<P>
   Clancy's role was to stitch together Horner's first-person
recollections with broader third-person commentary. The man knows
his military history. His deft touch is evident even in discussing
the most arcane military matters. He translates policy into blood
and bodies, setting up perfectly Horner's personal accounts of war
conducted in smoky, split-second confusion.
</P>
<P>
   The book's purpose, clearly, is to illuminate why U.S. military
policies had to change. Even the best writing _ and Clancy and
Horner distinguish themselves there _ can't disguise the thousands
of acronyms and occasional overreliance on military jargon. Then,
too, there is an obvious determination to give credit where it's
due, including to individuals whose names are less than household
words. We meet Gens. Norman Schwarzkopf and Colin Powell, and
they're presented in agreeable, three-dimensional detail. But
Horner insists _ properly, we can be certain _ that the real hero
of Desert Storm was Gen. Bill Creech, who was long retired by the
time Saddam Hussein's storm troopers crossed into Kuwait but whose
military reforms made it possible decades later for Schwarzkopf and
company to operate effectively thousands of miles away from
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Will ``Every Man a Tiger'' sell in the umpteen-hundred thousands
like ``Clear and Present Danger'' or ``Rainbow Six?'' Of course
not. Despite Putnam's best efforts, bookstore browsers attracted by
Clancy's name on the cover will determine quickly that this isn't a
Jack Ryan novel. But enough Clancy fans ought to purchase the book
to propel ``Every Man a Tiger'' onto the bestseller list. And those
who read the book will find the Clancy/Horner nonfiction team every
bit as entertaining as Clancy spinning a made-up yarn on his own.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is nooks editor of the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
