<HEADER>
A2196 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-HIKING-2TAKES-NYT     05-26 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-HIKING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING ONLINE ADVICE OF SEASONED TRAIL WALKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By VERNE G. KOPYTOFF  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From Memorial Day weekend to the end of summer, wilderness
trails across the nation surrender to hikers searching for a taste
of nature, spectacular views and isolation. During their treks,
most people (that is, most courteous people) leave behind
conveniences like cellular telephones and laptop computers.
</P>
<P>
   But the preparations for a walk in the woods can be enhanced by
digital research. Browsing through some of the hundreds of Web
sites that offer advice about camping equipment, trails and
backpacking techniques may be a good idea for experienced and
novice hikers alike.
</P>
<P>
   If only I had heeded the counsel on these sites, I would have
avoided the humiliation of my most recent trip in which I was run
off a mountain in the Sierras by mosquitoes and altitude sickness.
Next time I vow to be more prepared with ideas gleaned from the
Internet for dealing with risks like skunks (bury your clothes to
get rid of the smell) and untreated stream water (put in iodine
drops to prevent giardiasis).
</P>
<P>
   Most Web sites on hiking appear to be operated by amateurs who
simply want to tell others about a favorite peak or recipe for
granola. People who are considering a hike like the Appalachian
Trail, which stretches from Georgia to Maine, may want to read the
Web page of someone who has traveled the route.
</P>
<P>
   Hiking on the Web can also serve as a partial substitute for the
real thing. Backpacking enthusiasts who live in large cities,
seemingly thousands of miles from the nearest mountain, may get
some satisfaction in looking at photographs and maps of trails they
cannot readily get to.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICA'S ROOF
</P>
<P>
   www.americasroof.com
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, Mount McKinley in Alaska (elevation 20,320
feet) and Britton Hill in Florida (345 feet) may seem to have
little in common. But in fact, they are members of the same elite
club: Mount McKinley and Britton Hill are the highest points in
their respective states.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the obsession of America's Roof, a Web site that is
mostly devoted to the tallest natural location in each of the 50
states. It describes these summits and the trip to the top, often
with a welcome dose of criticism and even some social commentary
for those peaks diminished by less-than-spectacular scenery and
crowded trails.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in describing Mount Marcy (5,344 feet), the highest
point in New York, the site says ``the peak can be overrun in the
summer with hikers who sometimes have a tendency to pull out
cellular phones to make calls to their Manhattan offices.'' People
who want to climb Mount Marcy, the site says, may be better off
climbing nearby peaks.
</P>
<P>
   There is also information about the best time of year to visit
the high points, how long the hike will take and potential problems
with parking. Photographs of the summits, maps and links to weather
reports give visitors an idea of what to expect along the trail.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the high points are so accessible that visitors can
drive to the top, which probably makes them of little interest to
most hikers. For example, the tallest hill in Delaware, Ebright
Azimuth (elevation 442 feet) is in the middle of a road and next to
a communications tower. Also, the premise of the site, focusing on
a state's single highest point, proves to be its limitation. In a
big state, that hike may be prohibitively far away.
</P>
<P>
   For a destination that is closer to home, visitors may be better
off browsing a section on the site that lists the highest points in
each of the nation's 50 largest cities. Unfortunately, only a few
of these locations are described in detail, but, since they are in
urban areas, they hardly require special footwear.
</P>
<P>
   THE BACKPACKER
</P>
<P>
   www.thebackpacker.com
</P>
<P>
   Be prepared for mountain thunderstorms and cold weather. Invest
in a good pair of boots. Make sure that the trail you hike is not
so long or steep that you are left gasping for breath.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of motherly advice is the staple of the Backpacker, a
hiking Web site that has a lot to offer beginners: firsthand
accounts of mountain adventures, tips on camping gear, a chat room
and trail reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Among the strongest features on the site are the articles in
which authors tell of their experiences on the trail, like being
attacked by yellow jackets and getting heartburn from eating
freeze-dried food. But the stories all have the same ending: the
writers invariably gush about their passion for the wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep going back for more,'' said one writer who woke up in a
tent with an eye nearly swollen shut by a bite of unknown origin.
``I absolutely love backpacking.''
</P>
<P>
   Though these stories are intended to prepare visitors for the
realities of hiking, they thankfully do not advocate discomfort.
One article on how hikers can reduce the weight in their packs
recommends taking just one pair of socks (a rather inconvenient
choice because they must be washed at the end of each day) but
allowing room for a few ``goodies,'' like a sleeping pad, chess set
and Frisbee.
</P>
<P>
   A section called Beginner's Corner does a respectable job of
explaining the basics of equipment in a way that may be useful even
to some experienced hikers. Readers can learn, for example, that
external frame backpacks are easier to load than internal ones and
that moleskin used to prevent blistered feet is an adhesive pad,
not the hide of an insectivore.
</P>
<P>
   One area that could be greatly improved is the site's database
of hundreds of trails. The trails are rated on a score of one to
five stars, often with only cursory descriptions that indicate
little about the difficulty of the hike, scenery, crowds or why it
got the rating it did.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, this site is a good place to learn what hiking is
like, what equipment to buy and what precautions to take on the
trail. But anyone looking for a place to put this knowledge to use
may need to try other sites for good directions.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
