<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN PREGNANCY EXACTS A HIGH PRICE FROM ALL OF US
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When she was 13, Karla Ibarra had sex for the first time. Then
she started throwing up so much that it scared her.
</P>
<P>
   When Ibarra was a girl of 14, she gave birth to her own little
girl, Elizabeth, who will turn 3 Wednesday. Last year, Ibarra gave
birth to Jennifer.
</P>
<P>
   The high school sophomore sits now in the front room of an
apartment she shares sometimes with her babies' father. On another
day, she and the toddlers might be at her parents' home.
</P>
<P>
   One never knows for sure. That's why local teen pregnancy
experts count Ibarra among a growing number of teen-age mothers who
are homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we know that there are at least 60 homeless teen
moms at any given time,'' said Becky Nikolaisen, executive director
of Adolescent Pregnancy Prevention, a privately funded nonprofit
social service agency in North Texas. ``We know that over 50
percent of them drop out of school, so there are probably many
more. We don't know, but we have to assume that there are
hundreds.''
</P>
<P>
   Although teen pregnancy rates have dropped nationwide, the raw
numbers in Tarrant County have remained largely unchanged.
According to APP, the birth rate in 1992 was 39.6 per 1,000 teen
girls, compared with 33.6 per 1,000 in 1997, the latest year for
which figures are available.
</P>
<P>
   But in absolute numbers, more babies were born to teens in 1997
_ 1,174 of 1,503 pregnancies _ than in 1992, when 1,092 births and
1,592 pregnancies were recorded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't made massive strides in terms of eliminating teen
pregnancy in Tarrant County,'' said Jeff Rodriguez, director of
education at APP. ``And what many people don't realize is when a
teen-ager gives birth, we end up paying for it in a lot of
different ways and for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids are more likely to drop out of school; their
children are more likely to have learning and other physical
problems, to be incarcerated and much more at risk of being teen
parents themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   SO MANY MESSAGES
</P>
<P>
   Staying in school is a constant struggle for Ibarra, 17. If she
makes it to school at all, it is well past the 7:50 a.m. starting
bell. She has missed 18 days this year.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, she said, rain and another dizzy spell kept her and
her children at home. Ibarra thinks she might suffer from
hypertension, which was diagnosed while she was carrying Elizabeth,
but she isn't sure. She hasn't had time to go to the doctor. There
isn't time or space to do much of anything for herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't go out with my friends,'' she said. ``I used to be a
model. Now I want to be a cheerleader, but I can't because I have
to take care of the babies. I have to carry them everywhere I go.''
</P>
<P>
   In a lot of ways, Ibarra is typical of teen-age mothers.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, more and more girls are becoming pregnant at age
13. For another, more are having sex with boys and men two to five
years older than they are.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the trends, Rodriguez said, the bigger issue is the
quantity of sexual messages kids are getting.
</P>
<P>
   ``No other generation has been exposed to so many media messages
about sex. Pick up any CD jacket; you're going to see some really
irresponsible messages about having sex. See a movie; the couples
are never married, they never talk about contraception or disease
or other negative consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``And a third part is, you can have an educational talk about
values and waiting, but mom has a live-in boyfriend. The values
they learn at home are far more powerful in terms of influencing
their ideas about sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez would like to see a media campaign to raise awareness
about the dangers of teen-age sex, as previous campaigns have
centered on drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sexuality is a much bigger threat to teens than drugs,'' he
said. ``Seventy-five to 80 percent of teens are sexually active by
the time they are high school seniors. Drug use doesn't come close
to that.''
</P>
<P>
   THE VOICE OF EXPERIENCE
</P>
<P>
   As Ibarra explains her life, Elizabeth and Jennifer play with a
pink and white Barbie jeep in a corner of the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for having them, but I wish it could be different,''
Ibarra said.
</P>
<P>
   She works hard to get her homework done, to keep a clean house,
to have dinner ready for her boyfriend, to be an attentive mother.
</P>
<P>
   She pays a price. She stays up late and goes to school tired and
tardy. She brings home mostly bad grades.
</P>
<P>
   Now, every chance she gets, she tells her friends to guard
against pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of friends who, when they see my babies, they say
they want one,'' she said. ``I tell them not to, because it's hard
to have babies right now.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ibarra said she is determined to stay in school and keep
trying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I was a little, I wanted to be a police officer, and I
still want to, so that's why I want to finish school. And I want
them to see that I'm doing the right thing for them.'' .MDBU/.MDNM/
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
