<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2198 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-HIKING-2NDTAKE-NY     05-26 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-HIKING-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: good directions.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK-NEW JERSEY
</P>
<P>
   TRAIL CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   www.nynjtc.org
</P>
<P>
   The first problem any hiker encounters is choosing a trail. In
states like New York and New Jersey, that problem is compounded by
urban sprawl. Where's the closest trail when you're standing (in
full gear) in Grand Central Station?
</P>
<P>
   This site, the home page of the New York-New Jersey Trail
Conference, might help in that department. The organization _ whose
site recently proclaimed, ``Let Us Take You There!'' _ maintains
1,300 miles of trails in the two states and is dedicated to
protecting the environment.
</P>
<P>
   But finding a trail on this site is not as easy as it should be.
Limited trail information is sprinkled among several sections,
sometimes with descriptions of what to expect while hiking,
sometimes not.
</P>
<P>
   Major routes like the Highlands Trail, which when completed will
stretch from Storm King Mountain on the Hudson River in New York to
Phillipsburg, N.J., are given a relatively detailed treatment,
including information about navigating the route and distances.
Other hiking areas are simply listed and indicated on a road map,
though the organization offers more detailed free information about
a few trails by mail).
</P>
<P>
   The failings of the site are on display in a section promisingly
titled ``You Don't Need a Car.'' The site gives the encouraging
sales pitch that ``scores of wild forest and mountain trails'' lie
within a 50-mile radius of Manhattan's Columbus Circle and that
``public transportation can get you out of the city and into the
woods in 30 to 90 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   It then delivers on providing commendably detailed public
transportation information for a few dozen trails. But from reading
the site, a visitor gets no idea how long these trails are, whether
they are in woods or meadows, hilly or flat, paved or dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the site tersely counsels people who are wondering
where to go on the weekend to buy a specific hiking guide, ``pick a
random page, and go there.'' The counsel is similar for people who
need trail maps, of which the site provides few, and even those are
difficult to decipher.
</P>
<P>
   The site is more generous with information about trail news,
including openings, closings and conditions. Visitors may also find
it useful to browse through the organization's newsletter, which
lists volunteer opportunities and publishes occasional articles
about specific hiking trails.
</P>
<P>
   Casual urban hikers who are searching for a weekend adventure
may get some ideas by scrolling through this site.
</P>
<P>
   But once they focus on a specific trail, they will probably have
to look for more in-depth information at other Web sites or break
down and buy a guidebook, which the organization will gladly sell.
</P>
<P>
   THE LIGHTWEIGHT BACKPACKER
</P>
<P>
   www.backpacking.net
</P>
<P>
   Few people hike for the pleasure of carrying a heavy backpack up
a mountainside. Taking an extra pair of shoes and a big tent seems
like a good idea at home, but not when you are struggling up a
steep trail on a hot summer day.
</P>
<P>
   This Web site, titled The Lightweight Backpacker, tries to
relieve some of that unpleasant load. It provides advice for people
who are counting the ounces in their backpacks to the point of
using lightweight toothbrushes but not, as the site puts it, to
``eating worms.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the features on the site that most illustrates this
philosophy is ``The 18-pound, 3-Day Pack.'' It is a checklist of
all the equipment the site deems necessary for a three-day escape
to the wilderness, including sun block (1.2 ounces) and toilet
paper (1.5 ounces).
</P>
<P>
   The inventory, which is long and seems complete, does indeed add
up to just over 18 pounds. As such, it comes in at about half the
weight I carried the last time I tried to pack light. But it does
not take into account some frills you may want to consider, like a
book.
</P>
<P>
   Another part of the site is devoted to equipment reviews that
discuss quality and, of course, weight. For example, the light
toothbrush weighed only half a gram and was judged by four testers
to be adequate, but only on a temporary basis, because the bristles
were stiff and ``it was awkward to get to the back teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, some of the lightweight gear discussed here,
like titanium cookware and Gore-Tex clothing, is probably too
expensive for the average hiker.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, the site has instructions on how to make your own
lightweight backpacks, stoves and sleeping tarps (they weight less
than tents) at a fraction of the cost of buying them in a store.
</P>
<P>
   Scrolling through this site is intriguing and will probably get
visitors thinking carefully about how many pounds of equipment they
take on the next hike. While there is some information to interest
beginners, the emphasis on such a small slice of hiking probably
makes this site more appropriate for experienced backpackers.
</P>
<P>
   BACKCOUNTRY HOME PAGE: www.flash.net/bhphiker/BHP _ A good place
to look for links to sites about outdoor sports like hiking,
backpacking and orienteering.
</P>
<P>
   GREAT OUTDOOR RECREATION PAGES: www.gorp.com _ Named for a
favorite hiking snack, this site has articles about hiking and a
good selection of trail information, much of it sponsored by
equipment sellers.
</P>
<P>
   ESCAPING TO NATURE: www.outdoorphoto.com _ This showcase for the
work of a Texas outdoor photographer also offers advice about
cameras and photography.
</P>
<P>
   BASECAMP: www.bpbasecamp.com _ Articles about hiking gear and
backpacking techniques, some of which come from Backpacker, the
monthly hiking magazine.
</P>
<P>
   MOUNTAINZONE.COM: www.mountainzone.com _ Well-written articles
about hiking, often from exotic locations like Bhutan and
Kyrgystan.
</P>
<P>
   BACKPACKING CHECKLISTS: www.anguswong.com/camping _ Useful lists
of what to take on a backpacking trip.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN HIKING SOCIETY: www.americanhiking.org _ The home page
of a nonprofit volunteer group that builds and maintains trails
across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   COOL WORKS: www.coolworks.com/natprk.htm _ An online employment
site has listings for jobs at the nation's national parks,
preserves, monuments and recreation and wilderness areas.
</P>
<P>
   TRAILPLACE: www.trailplace.com _ A site dedicated to Appalachian
Trail through-hikers, those who attempt to walk the entire 2,160
miles.
</P>
</TEXT>
