r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-PARADOX-TEX     05-26 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-PARADOX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY WON'T AMERICA EMBRACE JESSE JACKSON AS A GREAT MAN?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember the day he took the microphone away from the president
of the United States?
</P>
<P>
   It was in the White House Rose Garden on a winter day in 1983.
The presidential primary in New Hampshire loomed ahead. The Rev.
Jesse Jackson's name would be on the ballot; so would President
Reagan's.
</P>
<P>
   Without the administration's approval, Jackson had just secured
the release of Navy flier Lt. Robert Goodman of Portsmouth, N.H.,
from captivity in Syria.
</P>
<P>
   So a news conference was under way. TV lights glared.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Reagan's every intention was that Jesse was to be
seen and not heard at the press conference,'' said Richard Hatcher,
Jackson's friend and adviser, in an interview with public
television years later.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson reached out and took the microphone _ as well as the
eyes of the nation _ away from the president.
</P>
<P>
   An enduring if not always endearing public servant, Jackson has
pushed mightily for social change for more than three decades. Even
his friends say he can push too hard, so hard he has caused doubt
about whether his motives are selfless.
</P>
<P>
   What keeps America from thanking Jackson, welcoming him with
open arms, telling him he is a great man?
</P>
<P>
   Talk to the people who have met him, known him, watched him.
They'll tell you Jackson is too attention-hungry. They'll tell you
that several things have hurt him: He is African-American. He is a
minister. He uses unconventional tactics. He achieves goals that
others cannot. He competes with those in power, although he has
said he won't run for president in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Baptist preacher from South Carolina has rescued
more than 500 people held prisoner by hostile nations: Syria, Cuba,
Iraq and now Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   And what happens?
</P>
<P>
   America shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   The nation watched almost silently when Jackson returned home
this month after negotiating with Slobodan Milosevic for the
release of three American prisoners of war. Only still shots were
taken at the White House reception.
</P>
<P>
   No TV cameras allowed.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Many are the characteristics that place Jackson in the category
of ``A Great American Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, 57, is bold. Brilliant. Dedicated. A visionary. A
humanitarian. A man of faith. A master of rhetoric and inspiration.
A leader, and an American original. It's been said he can ``preach
the riot out of a crowd'' and can look Sadaam Hussein in the eye
while appealing to his merciful side.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows what he wants. He just goes ahead, and God opens up a
way,'' said Viola Pitts, a longtime Fort Worth volunteer who served
with Jackson as a delegate to the National Democratic Convention in
San Francisco, July 1984.
</P>
<P>
   He is loved, and considered great, by millions _ although not by
the same people who organize news conferences in the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't surprised that there was little public acclaim,''
said Fort Worth Councilman Ralph McCloud, who met Jackson at a
political function in Fort Worth a year or so ago. Not only had
Jackson embarrassed the administration, but look at who he is: an
African-American Baptist minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he were not black, if he didn't have `Reverend' by his
name, I think he would have had a hero's welcome,'' McCloud said.
</P>
<P>
   The question of race haunts most conversations about Jackson,
and Jackson himself has cited racism.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our society has a way of cutting down our giants. That's not
just race,'' former Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young said in a PBS
interview in 1996. ``Jesse tends to think that that's sometimes
race. But I think they cut down Carter that way. I think they're
chopping at Clinton. To keep him from growing too far.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, as in all discussions about Jackson, there is the
question of ego.
</P>
<P>
   Ego wasn't so apparent in Martin Luther King Jr., who achieved
the status of ``A Great American Man'' and was known as a
``reluctant hero,'' a man who had to be convinced that he should
lead civil rights actions in Montgomery, Ala., during the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than a few close observers who are neither unthoughtful
nor ill-willed have found (Jackson) at times an insufferably
sanctimonious swaggerer _ he once actually had himself brought on
stage at a PUSH (People United to Serve Humanity) gala to the
splendoring paean of `Jesus Christ Superstar.' ... Yet he seems to
have a peculiar capacity for suddenly becoming wondrously larger
than all his unlikabilities,'' his biographer, Marshall Frady,
wrote in ``Jesse: The Life and Pilgrimage of Jesse Jackson''
(Random House, 1996).
</P>
<P>
   He's complex and mercurial, at one moment reciting Dr. Seuss'
``Green Eggs and Ham'' on ``Saturday Night Live,'' then surprising
us again with an ability to be as crass as he can be lighthearted.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, sitting in Washington National Airport with friends,
Jackson described an upcoming campaign trip to New York. He used
the words ``Hymie'' and ``Hymie-town'' in reference to that state's
large Jewish population. The conversation was overheard by a
reporter, who printed Jackson's slurs in ``The Washington Post.''
Jackson at first denied using the derogatory terms. Then, finally,
at a visit to a synagogue in New York, he publicly apologized,
saying he meant no offense by off-color remarks made at a moment
when his guard was down.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, there is the question of endurance. His 15 minutes
of fame have stretched to three decades, placing him well outside
the honeymoon stage of public love. And a good deal of that time he
has lived under the glare of TV lights, which tend to spotlight the
tarnish rather than the luster, and make us wonder if we can have
``Great Men'' anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Would George Washington, Thomas Jefferson or Abraham Lincoln
have survived the TV age, the age of full disclosure where
headlines are made of things that used to be mentioned only in
whispered remarks?
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe we should simply accept that ``Great Men'' are not all
pure of spirit. Those who give us inspiration or hope in the midst
of social change _ Cesar Chavez or Crazy Horse or even Mohandas
Ghandi _ probably were not easy guys to get along with all the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Thomas, media relations director for Jackson, said he's
been receiving a lot of media inquiries about why Jackson was not
better received on his return from Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've decided not to comment,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we shouldn't be too concerned about Jackson's status of
``greatness.'' Maybe we should just leave him alone and let him
work. Let him love the spotlight. Let him be bold. Don't worry if
he doesn't get enough face time with the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who pushes will not likely receive the proper respect.
And he will push on any door,'' says the Rev. Nehemiah Davis,
minister at Mount Pisgah Missionary Baptist Church and president of
the Fort Worth/Tarrant County branch of the NAACP. ``If he becomes
controversial or bothersome, it's because he has to be in order to
be effective.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jackson bio box:
</P>
<P>
   Born Oct. 8, 1941, in Greenville, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Ordained as a Baptist minister in 1968
</P>
<P>
   Aide to Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Founder, Operation PUSH (People United to Serve Humanity)
</P>
<P>
   President, National Rainbow Coalition
</P>
<P>
   Presidential candidate, 1984 and 1988
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
