<HEADER>
A2201 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX     05-26 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT-SO-GREAT PRETENDERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Young men singing in harmony.
</P>
<P>
   In all of pop music, there is no sweeter, more inviting sound.
Think of the Beatles. Think of the Temptations. Think of the Four
Tops. Think of the Jackson Five. Think of Harold Melvin &AMP; the Blue
Notes.
</P>
<P>
   Do not think of the Backstreet Boys.
</P>
<P>
   To the little girls of America, I apologize for what I'm about
to say _ not that you care much about what a fossil like me will
say about ``KEVIN HOWIE A.J. BRIAN AND NICK OMIGOD THEY ARE LIKE SO
CUTE!!!!''
</P>
<P>
   But it must be said: ``Millennium'' chomps. Big time.
</P>
<P>
   The songs _ forgettable. The lyrics _ ditto. The lead singing _
tepid. The harmonies _ thin.
</P>
<P>
   Sad thing is, I want the Backstreet Boys to be good. Really. If
every female under the age of 17 is going to buy something besides
Korn and/or Marilyn Manson, it might as well be good. After all,
previous generations had the acts named above; the current crop of
scream-ready girls ought to have their own worthy heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad these hapless little boys _ and, of course, the
omnipresent 'N Sync _ are the best they're being offered.
``Millennium'' is full of the sort of disposable pap that fades
from memory almost immediately after it's heard. The sentiments are
the usual (I love you/I miss you/Thanks for being our fans/I'm
lonely) and the lyrics tend to the extremely obvious, on the order
of ``You are my fire/The one desire/Believe when I say/I want it
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheesh. Hard to believe it's come to this. And what makes all
this goop so much worse is that these guys aren't even good
singers. There is not a distinctive voice in the bunch, not one guy
who leaps out (as Michael Jackson did, as Teddy Pendergrass did, as
Eddie Kendricks did) as a vocal ``presence,'' a guy who makes you
believe he's going through all this pain or happiness.
</P>
<P>
   Had there been a standout, said goop would have been much more
palatable: Boy groups have always sung about basic boy/girl
relationships, basic emotions; they're not here to tell us who to
vote for or what we should do about the latest crisis in Europe.
But in the hands of a Pendergrass or a Kendricks, such simple stuff
sounded as if a young man's very soul was at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Here, it's just an excuse to play connect the dots and make
millions. Throw in some acoustic guitars. A pleading
baby-I-want-you-back vocal now and then. Some hard (for them,
anyway) dance rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   Add a whole bunch of strings, throw in five pages of ads for
videos, T-shirts and the like in the CD book, and hope the kids
decide they still like you, even though you've decided to grow more
facial hair and get some tattoos.
</P>
<P>
   My bet is that ``Millennium'' will sell enormously well, but
that the Backstreet Boys will go the way of New Kids on the Block:
one more huge tour, and then the inevitable sales drop when all the
kids buying this realize there is so much better music out there.
</P>
<P>
   Like, well, just about anything. Girls, if you want to hear this
stuff done right, set aside your need to scream at cute guys _ hey,
that's what the posters being advertised in the CD booklet are for
_ and go out and invest in some classic Temptations, Four Tops,
O'Jays and so on. This is timeless music; ``Millennium'' is just
marking time.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
