<HEADER>
A2202 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUZZ-DAVIS-TEX     05-26 0361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUZZ-DAVIS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OH, NO ... IT'S THE RANDOM MENACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LISA DAVIS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I saw ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' at 10 a.m.
opening day, and may I just say, nobody should have to smell movie
popcorn that early in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   The critics are right: The acting is wooden, the plot is
nonexistent and everybody in the galaxy has really, really bad
hair. I don't care, because that army of battle droids is
absolutely the coolest thing I've ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   See, I'm in touch with my inner geek. It's cool.
</P>
<P>
   Think back, a long time ago, to the first Star Wars. The plot
was ridiculous and Mark Hamill couldn't act his way out of a paper
bag, but we were completely blown away by the special effects. Why
expect anything different this time around? Everything is just
ratcheted up a couple of notches.
</P>
<P>
   Where Star Wars had a barful of weird aliens, Phantom Menace is
swimming in computer-generated beasties (each one its own action
figure, I'm sure). Turns out the Force is even linked to alien
beasties called ``midi-chlorians,'' microscopic life forms that
live inside our cells. (Tough to sell the action figure on that
one.)
</P>
<P>
   Where Star Wars had a villain who hid his face, Phantom Menace
has one who paints his face. Plus, Darth Maul's lightsaber is twice
as long.
</P>
<P>
   Where Empire Strikes Back had Yoda, who merely words in order
funny spoke, Phantom Menace has Jar Jar Binks, whose barely
understandable alien patois sounds like a Muppet version of Bob
Marley. ``Breakfast,'' for instance, is ``brisky mornin'
munchin'.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Star Wars had ``May the Force be with you,'' Phantom
Menace has ... well, there is no clear catch phrase. Maybe ``brisky
mornin' munchin' '' will catch on.
</P>
<P>
   Where Return of the Jedi had that wild speeder chase through the
forest, Phantom Menace has an intense pod race. The vehicles crash
and burn, the announcers make stupid jokes, the drivers have bad
teeth and flippers _ wait a minute. That's not science-fiction.
That's NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
