<HEADER>
A2206 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     05-26 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV28-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICOS GO TO THE MAT
</HEADLINE>
  (For release May 28)  
(rk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was glad to read in the paper that more and more professional
wrestlers have taken the cue from Jesse ``The Governing Body''
Ventura and are getting into politics.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Backlund, Jeff ``Skunk'' Baxter, Jerry Lawler, John ``Jum
Johnny'' Defazio and ``Dirty'' Harry Venis are some of the other
wrestlers who have thrown their hats into the ring, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people that watch wrestling that don't give
a hoot about voting,'' Backlund said. ``But because of who's
running, they're going to vote. And when the people vote for me,
they're votin' for America.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Backlund's oration may not rank up there with ``Ask not
what your country can do for you, but what you can do for your
country'' or ``We have nothing to fear but fear itself,'' they are
words that are clearly resonating with many Americans.
</P>
<P>
   If we are to take this trend seriously _ and there is no reason
why we shouldn't _ the day is fast approaching when primaries will
be replaced by steel-cage, loser-leaves-town grudge matches and
lawmakers will give up their business suits for Spandex tights.
</P>
<P>
   The gentle art of consensus-building will be replaced by body
slams and flying drop kicks. Squirrelly evasions like ``I didn't
inhale'' will be replaced by more sinewy admissions like ``I didn't
mean to rip his face off'' or ``If I had known he was unconscious,
I wouldn't have smashed his head in with that folding chair.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears that the Mondale-era question of ``Where's the
beef?'' has finally been answered. The only question remaining is
whether the World Wrestling Federation will be able to do a better
job than Congress. The early answer is: Yes, but only with the help
of flatulent bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   I am referring specifically to a recent news story where Gov.
Jesse ``The Odor'' Ventura threatened to lock Minnesota lawmakers
in a room with his gassy bulldog, Franklin, if they did not work
out a budget deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they get locked in the room with (Franklin) and you feed
him some hamburger, I'd say we'd have a deal within 45 minutes,''
Ventura said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers, displaying uncharacteristic wisdom not to mention
a keen instinct for self-preservation, quickly worked out a budget
deal and the threat was never carried out.
</P>
<P>
   (Not to be outdone, the Pentagon has threatened to deploy
Franklin in Kosovo if the situation there does not improve within
45 minutes. Opponents of the plan point out that the Franklin Bomb
would constitute a violation of international chemical-warfare
treaties and would also be prohibitively expensive given the fact
that Pentagon-grade hamburger costs $200,000 a pound.)
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the political possibilities of Franklin are staggering.
After our newly elected wrestler-statesmen soften up the opposition
with a series of forearm smashes and cross-face chicken wings,
Franklin saunters in to deliver the final blow, so to speak. Trot
Franklin into an NRA convention while gripping a string of smoked
sausages in his teeth and by this time tomorrow we'd not only have
gun control, but also possibly a national ban on large-caliber
ground beef.
</P>
<P>
   Get Franklin's stomach to growl at the right time and the right
place and we'll not only get Social Security and Medicare fixed but
our public schools will be the envy of the world.
</P>
<P>
   If the wind is right, Dan Quayle may even stop jabbering about
family values and Murphy Brown, but that might be too much to ask,
even from a bloated bulldog.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
