<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ENDORSEMENTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH BACKED BY MAJORITY OF HOUSE REPUBLICANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A majority of the 222 Republicans in the House of
Representatives have endorsed Texas Gov. George W. Bush for the
party's presidential nomination, Bush's presidential exploratory
committee said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 115 GOP members of the House who support him over other
Republican hopefuls for the nomination in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This much congressional support for a Republican presidential
candidate, announced or unannounced, is unprecedented,'' Rep. Roy
Blunt of Missouri, a member of Bush's exploratory committee, told a
Capitol Hill news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls show that Bush, who has all but announced
his candidacy, is leading the other Republicans who have either
announced candidacies or are considering running for the party's
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Bonilla, R-Texas, said the overwhelming support for
Bush had to be discouraging to other potential GOP hopefuls who
seek help from lawmakers and their political organizations in
congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be a kick in the gut to a lot of them,'' said
Bonilla, another member of the Bush exploratory committee.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Republicans have announced or, like Bush, are
weighing campaigns. They are former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander,
conservative commentators Gary Bauer and Pat Buchanan, former Red
Cross President Elizabeth Dole, magazine publisher Steve Forbes,
Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, Sen. John McCain of Arizona, former Vice
President Dan Quayle and Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   For the Democratic nomination, Vice President Al Gore is being
challenged by former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only person in America who possesses the strength and
ability to bring cohesiveness to this nation's diverse political
landscape is George W. Bush,'' Rep. Barbara Cubin, R-Wyo., told the
news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush's vision for an America which leaves no group
behind, leaves no one out in the cold, promises to unite this
country and return real leadership to the White House,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement from Austin, Bush praised the exploratory
committee and House members who have pledged their support to a
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm particularly proud of these endorsements because the men
and women supporting me are extraordinarily close to their
constituencies and span the ideological spectrum of our party,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the son of the former president, has already picked up the
endorsements of several governors and state legislatures. But he
has insisted that he would not announce a decision about running
for the presidency until after the Texas Legislature adjourns at
the end of this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
