<SLUG> BC-FORBIDDEN-LOVE-2400(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS NAVAL ACADEMY CADETS LOSE EVERYTHING FOR LOVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
UNDATED:they go alone. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Krissy Shiroma is the kind of young woman Birk likes: She is
smart and independent, mature enough that he can imagine her at
dinner beside the prime minister of England or at a soup kitchen in
New York City. And she's funny. Her sense of humor is the first
thing he notices.
</P>
<P>
   They return to Uncle Julio's and they go to La Madeleine, and
another time they share a chocolate dessert at a bar called Austin
Grill. They go to a Robin Williams movie and to the National
Cathedral in Washington, D.C., where they like to sit in the back
pews and talk.
</P>
<P>
   They talk about Texas, about Paris, the Louvre, about his
travels and hers, and they talk until they can't resist the
attraction so they rent a hotel room in Bethesda. They rent a hotel
room in Fort Worth during Thanksgiving break, after she meets his
mom, and he takes her to his favorite restaurant, Joe T. Garcia's.
</P>
<P>
   Birk thinks what they have is special. They finish each other's
sentences, they say the same things at the same time. They're not
two people out for a one-night stand; they're two people falling in
love.
</P>
<P>
   They live separate lives during the day, two doors down the hall
from each other; but at night, he looks forward to e-mailing her
before lights out.
</P>
<P>
   He knows they are caught on the Friday before the Army vs. Navy
game. He's bounding down the hall to gather his squad before they
break into the Pentagon and hang the giant banner they made of 26
bedsheets that reads ``Beat Army!''
</P>
<P>
   His commanding officer stops him with these ominous words:
``Miss Shiroma can't go.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't until Monday that Birk's entire chain of command calls
him into his commander's office to say, ``We're taking Miss Shiroma
out of your squad, and we think you know why.''
</P>
<P>
   The formal hearing comes weeks later in the deputy commandant's
office, when the charges are announced: fraternization and sexual
misconduct. The commandant strips his privileges and tells Birk
that the superintendent will decide whether he stays or goes.
</P>
<P>
   Birk confesses, and the truth becomes his only consolation.
</P>
<P>
   He tells his commander they had a relationship for 2 1/2 months.
He explains that they never had sexual intercourse, although they
had sexual relations, but that they did nothing more than kiss and
hug in Bancroft Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Birk doesn't know who turned them in, but when he passes Krissy
in the hall, he can see how scared she is. They don't talk or say
it's over, although they both know it is. The dream comes first. It
always has.
</P>
<P>
   By now it's spring, and the others leave for spring break, but
they stay. They're left almost alone in the empty dorm, but they're
too afraid to talk, to e-mail, to say ``I love you'' anymore. _
</P>
<P>
   Birk walks into the superintendent's office on St. Patrick's
Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Midshipman Birk K. Billingsley reporting as ordered, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the desk sits the most important man at the Naval
Academy, Vice Admiral John Ryan. Birk's voice quivers when the man
asks if he has anything to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the time I get up in the morning until the time I go to
bed at night, I have thought about what I was going to say today
and what might convince you to not separate me from the Naval
Academy. This is the most humiliating, the most excruciating
experience of my entire life, and for good reason: This is the
biggest error in judgment that I've ever committed.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, I don't think an error in judgment is equivalent to a
character flaw. From the beginning I have told the truth, and I
don't regret my decision to do that. I have never tried to shift my
culpability and say I wasn't guilty. Regardless of the outcome of
your decision, I will walk away with my integrity intact and my
honor, and that, sir, is worth more than $93,000 or three years
enlisted.''
</P>
<P>
   Birk says his love for this institution will never end. ``It's
too much a part of me for that to happen. And I'm too much a part
of it.'' Then he falls silent, waiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were you there to hear the speech I gave at the beginning of
the year?'' Ryan asks.
</P>
<P>
   Birk says he was, but he wasn't listening. It didn't apply. Or
so he thought then.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubt you will be a success in whatever career path
you take ...'' the admiral began. ``... But I see no other course
of action ... than to separate you from the Naval Academy.''
</P>
<P>
   Birk nods, on the verge of tears. _
</P>
<P>
   Birk Billingsley and Kristina Shiroma have appealed the
superintendent's decision to kick them out of the U.S. Naval
Academy. They're back in Texas, waiting to hear from the secretary
of the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Birk says they don't see each other anymore, but after all this
is over ... well, who knows?
</P>
<P>
   He's been accepted in the astronautical engineering program at
Purdue University, and she's thinking about the University of North
Texas. Meanwhile, they wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret breaking the rules, and I regret making a mistake.
But I don't regret falling in love.''
</P>
<P>
   Birk asked a Naval Academy lawyer how often the secretary has
overturned the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather not answer that,'' the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   But Birk begged.
</P>
<P>
   OK. ``I've never heard of that happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Birk sighed. ``Thank you, sir. I just wanted to know.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
