<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, May 27, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Very cool air over the Northeast will help generate a deck of
clouds between 3,000 and 8,000 feet by midday Thursday. Light
showers will grow out of these clouds in the afternoon, especially
in New England. The combination of gusty breezes from the northwest
along with cloud cover will keep readings more than ten degrees
below seasonal levels.
</P>
<P>
   The boundary of this modified Canadian air mass will stretch
through the Gulf States. A large but weakening disturbance in the
jet stream over Texas will produce clusters of thundershowers; a
few will contain flooding rain in north central sections. Clouds
and showers will be drawn eastward along the Gulf Coast.
Thundershowers will be scattered over northern Florida, but
southern counties will be bright and hot.
</P>
<P>
   High-pressure centers over the Dakotas and Ohio Valley will
gradually merge as the cold front between them dissipates. The
front will produce a few showers as far east as Wisconsin, but the
largest concentration of storms will be along the Front Range of
the Rockies. Residual moisture in the central Rockies will promote
a few thunderstorms late in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Cool, moist air will stream into the Northwest as chilly weather
from the north Pacific is drawn inland. Clouds and light drizzle
will move into the Olympic Peninsula while the interior will stay
quite warm and sunny. Patches of low clouds and fog will occupy the
California coastline from San Francisco to San Diego. The deserts
of the Southwest will be sunny and seasonably hot as readings climb
into the triple digits.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Giant Onions
</P>
<P>
   Hail 4.5 inches in diameter bombarded Altus, Okla., on Tuesday.
The icy giants, like most hailstones, looked like onions, with
rings of clear and opaque ice. In the cold upper reaches of a
thunderstorm, hailstones grow as tiny water drops freeze onto them.
During freezing, some heat is given off. So, when water drops are
sparse, freezing is fast because little heat is released. In the
process, air bubbles are trapped, giving ice an opaque appearance.
When drops are plentiful, freezing is slowed by a greater release
of heat, allowing air to escape and the ice to look clear.
</P>
</TEXT>
