<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBIDDEN-LOVE-2400(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS NAVAL ACADEMY CADETS LOSE EVERYTHING FOR LOVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY BINGHAM 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is a Saturday when a young man from Dublin, Texas, strides
across the grounds of the U.S. Naval Academy.
</P>
<P>
   Across the campus, a freshman girl from Richardson, Texas,
readies to meet him. They are not supposed to date, so the senior
and the freshman agree to meet in the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   They have worked out a signal: If someone is coming, he'll flash
the hazard lights; she'll keep walking.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, he doesn't worry.
</P>
<P>
   He's in love with her. He thinks of nothing else. _
</P>
<P>
   Maryland can be unbearably hot in August, so the day Birk
Billingsley returns to the Naval Academy campus after summer break,
he's mostly thinking about the dormitory with no air conditioning.
Until a girl catches his attention.
</P>
<P>
   She's walking toward him, and her ``white walls'' uniform tells
him she is a freshman _ a ``plebe.'' Everything about her reminds
him of someone: Dark hair. Dark brown eyes. Short.
</P>
<P>
   He recognizes the name on her name tag. Kristina Shiroma. The
girl's sister graduated from the Naval Academy in 1997. Birk thinks
nothing more of the encounter until later, when he scans the list
of midshipmen assigned to his squad and finds her name.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks, ``What are the odds?'' The 4,000 midshipmen at the
academy are divided into four platoons, 30 companies and 360 squads
_ and she ends up in his? Birk shakes his head but thinks of other
things.
</P>
<P>
   All his life _ at least since the fourth grade, when he wrote a
paper about Alan Shepard _ Birk has wanted to be an astronaut. So
everything was done to get him here: He played varsity football,
ran for class president, earned an Eagle Scout badge, snagged a
congressman's recommendation, mailed his application so it arrived
the first day they were being taken.
</P>
<P>
   Birk left Dublin, and his home for the past three years has been
Bancroft Hall in Annapolis.
</P>
<P>
   It is a place of bricks and honor; where the smell of floor wax
drifts in and out of open windows; where every closet is arranged
dark to light, left to right; where every desk is arranged tallest
to shortest, left to right.
</P>
<P>
   The dormitory is ``the ship,'' the new school superintendent
says to the midshipmen who hear his speech this first weekend back
at school. Birk is there, but he doesn't listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``One last point, about fraternization, '' the admiral says.
``It usually begins innocently enough _ on a field trip, with
e-mail, at the smoking pits _ but it gets bigger, it gets out of
control and eventually it can ruin careers, lives and people. Don't
let this happen to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Birk doesn't listen because he knows the rules; his three years
have been exceptional. He's never been tempted to break the rules;
his fourth-grade dream has always meant more.
</P>
<P>
   In three years, he has participated in an exchange program with
the British marines, ridden a missile cruise for joint operations
with other navies, crewed a racing sloop to New England,
interviewed Apollo astronaut Jim Lovell, met astronaut John Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   Back from summer break, Birk is still high from his internship
at NASA. On his first day there, he looked at the astronauts around
him and thought, ``I've read books about you. And you. And you.''
</P>
<P>
   Birk left NASA thinking he'd be back. _
</P>
<P>
   The knock on the door comes early, before the 7 a.m. company
formation, but Birk already knows who's waiting. The plebes are
lined up against the wall, ready for ``come arounds.''
</P>
<P>
   It's his job as squad leader to pepper them:
</P>
<P>
   How fast can an F-14 go?
</P>
<P>
   What's the range of an F-28 fully loaded?
</P>
<P>
   Tell me the hierarchy of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Who are the members of NATO?
</P>
<P>
   How many votes do they have?
</P>
<P>
   The life of a plebe: no television; no radio; no music; up by 7;
in bed by 11; restricted to the grounds Sunday through Friday;
required to yell ``Incoming!'' when the meals arrive; required to
run upon entering the dorm, yelling ``Go Navy!'' or ``Beat Army!''
when rounding a corner.
</P>
<P>
   Birk remembers what it's like, so he plans a field trip to
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone bails except Midshipman Fourth Class Shiroma and
another plebe. It is a Saturday when they see the Constitution, the
Arlington National Cemetery, when they sit in an Uncle Julio's
Mexican restaurant with the other plebe, a young man from Georgia,
who asks, ``What's an enchilada?''
</P>
<P>
   Birk looks up at Kristina, and she looks up at him, and there is
the first spark of attraction. Birk feels it, and he believes that
she feels it, too.
</P>
<P>
   But back at the Naval Academy, she takes off running down the
hall, and he thinks to himself that it's too bad she's a plebe.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, she e-mails him and capitalizes the ``R'' in
Very Respectfully. Birk lectures his plebes to keep
``respectfully'' lower case, but he notices she has also written
``ha ha ha.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiles, and feels the attraction again.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few weeks, Birk writes back, and she writes back,
and somebody mentions Mexican food, and somebody mentions Uncle
Julio's, and they decide to go again. But this time they go alone.
_ MORE: &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
