<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2221 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LITTLE-LEAGUE-DAD-NYT     05-26 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITTLE-LEAGUE-DAD-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE LEAGUE: ONE FATHER'S FANATICISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LOWELL COHN   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ This is the story of how I recently became
a sports fan, a rabid, wild-eyed, out-of-my-skull fan.
</P>
<P>
   You have to understand I've been a sports columnist for 20
years. That means I'm not allowed to be a fan, because, obviously,
I can't let partisanship color my judgment. I'm supposed to be
detached and reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, I always prided myself on being a complete
professional. That was before my son joined the Little League.
</P>
<P>
   As background to my total, humiliating disintegration, let me
tell you what I did last weekend. On Saturday morning, my
11-year-old son had a baseball game. It started at 9 a.m., but he
had to be there an hour early for batting practice, fielding
practice, the usual pregame stuff. I had been up late the night
before at the Crushers' home opener. But that didn't prevent me
from crawling out of bed early and driving my kid to the game.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, I dashed home and wrote my Sunday column. I
finished just in time to drive to Safeway and buy two bags of
oranges, a large jug of water, paper cups, two boxes of CapriSuns
and two bags of Oreos. My son was playing a soccer game that
afternoon, and as you may have guessed I was the ``Snack Parent.''
</P>
<P>
   So there I was at home cutting the oranges into quarters and
stuffing them into a Zip-Lock bag. I lugged my kid and the snacks
to a field where he played soccer until dinner time. He and his
teammates hardly touched the oranges. I was up early Sunday for the
second Little League game of the weekend. If you're keeping count,
that's three games in a 24-hour period, all of which I attended.
</P>
<P>
   I would like to tell you I was calm and dignified, the perfect
parental role model. Forget that. As this baseball season has
progressed _ and I'm talking exclusively about the Little League
season here _ I have experienced an almost complete identification
with my kid. I refer to his team as ``us,'' something I never would
do with the Giants or A's. When he's at the plate, I'm up there
with him gripping the bat, staring at the pitcher. When he catches
a grounder, I'm out there gliding into position and catching that
grounder, too.
</P>
<P>
   And if he strikes out, I am the one who whiffs at the ball and
slouches to the dugout, my head down, my teeth clenched, my heart
broken, my manhood cast down in a shadow of failure.
</P>
<P>
   I mention the strikeouts because my kid's been striking out
lately. This is extremely distressing. To me. He seems fine with
it. As long as he gets to play, as long as he wears his snazzy
uniform, as long as his teammates accept him, as long as he gets to
eat the postgame snack, he's content.
</P>
<P>
   Not me. I can tell you confidentially I was worried about this
striking out from the start. My kid's only 80 pounds, which isn't
big as human beings go. At the beginning of the season, a Little
League coach phoned and said my son had been drafted into the
Little League majors. I always saw him playing this season in the
minors.
</P>
<P>
   I told the coach I'd get back to him. I was concerned. I talked
to Giants shortstop Rich Aurilia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how to raise your son,'' he told me. ``But my
philosophy is always to play at the highest level, to test
yourself. You develop faster that way.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so based on that advice I put my kid into the majors. He had
no problem making the transition. Me, I wasn't ready for the
majors.
</P>
<P>
   He started striking out three weeks ago. This led to lack of
appetite, sleeplessness, dizzy spells and general irritation. In
me, not in my kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relax,'' he would tell me. I couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   I took him to the batting cage, stuffed a ton of coins into a
pitching machine, and made him take 160 swings. I know because I
counted every one. I worked on the position of his feet, first
spreading them out, then bringing them close together. I told him
to choke up on the bat. Then I told him not to choke up. I showed
him how to rotate his hips to generate maximum power.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed confused by all this teaching. I told him he had a
loop in his swing. He didn't know what a loop is. I told him Mark
McGwire once had a loop. He'd swing under the ball and miss it by a
mile until he got rid of the loop. Everyone knows what happened
after that. My kid asked if he could hit home runs like McGwire if
he got rid of the loop. Sure, I told him.
</P>
<P>
   I thought about calling McGwire to ask how he got rid of the
loop. But something held me back. A few weeks ago, the Brewers were
in San Francisco playing the Giants. I bumped into Jim Lefebvre,
their batting coach, whom I've known for years. I considered asking
him about my kid's loop, but he seemed preoccupied with his own
hitters at the time. Anyway, I didn't have videotape of my kid's
swing for Lefebvre to study. So I let it slide.
</P>
<P>
   I'm happy to report in the Sunday morning game, my kid seemed to
be getting back his stroke. He grounded out to the pitcher his
first time up, but the loop was gone. He walked his second time up.
</P>
<P>
   When he came up the third time, the umpire called two strikes on
him. Believe me, both pitches were low and outside. You didn't have
to be a genius to know that. I stared hard at the ump so he'd know
he was dealing with an expert. I even groaned audibly.
</P>
<P>
   But my kid fought off some tough pitches, worked the count full
and then he hit a single past the shortstop. The game went into
extra innings and he got another single. So we're out of our slump
now. Which is to say, he's hitting again.
</P>
<P>
   And I finally got a good night's sleep.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
