<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON COMPUTERS AND GADGETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Line Is Out the Door At a Genealogy Library
</P>
<P>
   The Mormon Church's new genealogy Web site opened this week, and
immediately became known for attracting more Web traffic than the
library's servers could handle. Given the popularity of online
family searches, the slowdowns were probably inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   The site, www.familysearch.org, developed by the Church of Jesus
Christ of Latter-day Saints, gives millions of users access to the
world's largest genealogy library.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, the Mormon Church took up the task of collecting
resources to help anyone, Church members or not, find their family
trees. The Family History Library in Salt Lake City, where hundreds
of thousands of documents are catalogued, is known among
professional genealogists as the premier site for such research.
</P>
<P>
   Most searchers will find that once they've found some
information about their ancestors, they'll need to order other
documents that are not yet on line, like microfilms of original
records preserved in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   But at least, said David A. Lambert, a reference librarian at
the New England Historic Genealogical Society, people will be able
to get started at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this allows more people to preserve the past and take an
interest in their ancestors,'' Lambert said, ``that's a positive
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Guernsey &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reaching Out to Really Chat, Even With 10 Friends at a Time &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   People who use instant typed messages to ``chat'' on line can
now do so literally, by talking to each other through their
computers. Yahoo Pager, a system that enables people to type
messages back and forth in real time, has started a free service
called Voice Chat that allows up to 10 people to speak to one
another using microphones wired through their computers.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is an older technology called the telephone
that already permits conversations at a distance. But according to
Brian Park, the senior producer for Yahoo Pager, Voice Chat offers
advantages that the phone does not: free conference calls and
savings on long-distance calls. He acknowledged that Net
instability may cause breaks in some conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, teen-agers are flocking to the service at
pager.yahoo.com, Park said, partly because it enables them to talk
to one another on line while still communicating via typed
messages.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly talkative teens may have a problem with one limit
built into the service, however: to keep conversations chatty, the
service allows a person to talk for only about one minute at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Guernsey &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Turning a Nine-Button Keypad Into a Discreet Communicator &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New York design firm and a Scarsdale psychiatrist have teamed
up to turn the standard nine-button keypad of telephones, pagers,
Palm Pilots and even television remote controls into a full
keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   Thumbscript is an input system in which users ``draw'' letters
onto the keypad by pressing two keys: the first key represents the
beginning of the stroke, the second key represents the end. The
``5'' button serves as a visual midpoint. For example, the
tent-shaped letter ``A'' is formed by pressing 7, then 9.
</P>
<P>
   Thumbscript was the idea of the psychiatrist, Dr. Jeffrey Smith,
who is also an amateur engineer and wanted to design a keyboard
that could be operated with one hand. ``I wanted to be able to
write things down discreetly during sessions,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The idea for Thumbscript came to him one morning while he was,
significantly, on the couch. ``It occurred to me that you could
look at the keypad as a picture rather than as a series of
numbers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith took his idea to Smart Design, which tested the method and
developed a prototype input device. ``The question was, why would
anyone want to learn Thumbscript,'' said Smart Design's chief
executive officer, Davin Stowell. ``The answer is the need for
discreet communications. If you're in a location where you don't
want to speak on your cell phone _ for that level of functionality,
currently, you'd currently need two or three devices.''
</P>
<P>
   The company is in negotiations with hardware manufacturers to
provide Thumbscript on keypad devices. A version for the Palm Pilot
is available at www.thumbscript.com.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said users could enter 15 to 20 words per minute using
their thumb and 18 to 20 words per minute using a stylus on the
Palm Pilot, perfect for phrases like, ``Your hour is up _ we will
have to discuss that at your next session.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Headlam &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Device Confers on Computers A Welcome Touch of Stereo &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the market for MP3 music files, sophisticated games and DVD
movies grows, a computer's subwoofer capacity is becoming almost as
essential as chip speed. Future Power, a new computer company based
in Santa Clara, Calif., has developed a stereo amplifier and
digital graphic equalizer that makes home computers sound more like
stereos and less like, well, home computers.
</P>
<P>
   The device, called the New Q Gold, is about the size of a CD-ROM
drive and slips into a computer's open bay. It is made to work with
any sound card and increase a PCs audio output by up to 40 percent,
said Priscilla Lin, the company's marketing manager.
</P>
<P>
   The New Q Gold, which will go on sale in July, will cost $79. It
is also one of the features included in Future Power's new line of
low-cost computers.
</P>
<P>
   Sold under the series names Signature and Power, for business
use, and Advantage and Adventure, primarily for home use, the new
computers will start at $699 (without monitor).
</P>
<P>
   Michel Marriott &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IBM Devises a Program To Enliven On-Line Ads &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Can banner ads be effective or even (gasp) interesting? IBM's
new media group thinks so and, to that end, has released a new Web
development tool called Hot Media. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hot Media uses Java applets to let Web developers put animation,
audio and video into banner ads and online catalogs that don't
require users to download or configure plug-ins.
</P>
<P>
   ``A banner ad with Hot Media can get loaded in the browser and
running with only a 15K download,'' said Bill Pence, director of
development for IBM's Internet media group. Banner ads garner
click-through rates as low as 0.5 percent, Pence said. Tests using
ads intended to take advantage of the new tools found that number
jumped to 5 percent to 8 percent, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven E. Brier
</P>
<P>
   The Internet must be a community because now you can tell on
your neighbors. The Federal Bureau of Investigation and the
National White Collar Crime Center announced recently that they
were creating an Internet Fraud Complaint Center. Anyone who sees
signs of online identity theft, e-mail pyramid schemes or any other
Internet-based criminal activity will be able to go to the Web
site, which will be available in late summer, and file a brief
report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is so vastly different that it requires a new way
of looking at crime,'' said Richard L. Johnston, director of the
center.
</P>
<P>
   The Anchorage Daily News reported recently that a disgruntled
employee tried to hold his company's database hostage. The
employee, Gregory Todd Erkins, a computer systems operator for a
small real-estate firm, sealed up the company's records behind a
firewall and demanded $2,500 for their release, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Erkins was later arrested on charges including extortion. ``It
was just like if somebody broke into your home and you feel
extremely violated,'' Linda Garrison, the company's co-owner, told
The Daily News.
</P>
</TEXT>
