<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXILE-COMEBACK-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EXILE' COMES BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL DEAN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oregon today, Nebraska last week and Texas the next.
</P>
<P>
   The comeback trail is never easy, but 1980s country music group
Exile is gaining ground.
</P>
<P>
   And it may lead straight back to its glory days _ when No. 1
hits came one after the other and the band was nominated three
years in a row for Vocal Group of the Year by the Country Music
Association.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, group leaders Les Taylor, J.P. Pennington and the
rest are about three hours east of Portland, Ore., awaiting the
night's gig _ and what could turn out to be the promising future of
the re-formed band.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a hectic week,'' Taylor said. ``But I kind of like
it like that. And it's been going great.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working a lot, which we're thankful for, and we've
enjoyed every minute of this since we put the group back
together.''
</P>
<P>
   That was 2 1/2 years ago, when Pennington and Taylor decided to
end the broken-up band's self-imposed exile by re-forming in
December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Pennington had originally formed what would become Exile way
back in 1963. He put together a rock band called The Exiles that
toured with The Dick Clark Caravan of Stars in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Changing its name to Exile in 1973, the Kentucky-based band
enjoyed major pop success with the No. 1 song ``Kiss You All
Over.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, a group make-over to country music had the
newly joined Taylor as lead singer. The group had such No. 1
country hits as ``Woke Up In Love'' and ``Hang On to Your Heart.''
</P>
<P>
   But mid-1980s success led to late-1980s burnout for Taylor, who
left in 1988, and Pennington, who left in 1989. The other members
carried on with replacements until finally calling it quits in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   As singers, guitarists and songwriters, both Pennington and
Taylor enjoyed solo careers until a phone call in late 1996 fueled
the idea of a reunion.
</P>
<P>
   The call came from Steve Goetzman, who had been the band's
drummer and who was working with a booking agency in a management
company in Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called and said there's still a demand for Exile's music
out there; what do you guys think about putting the group back
together?''
</P>
<P>
   After an impromptu jam together in a Lexington, Ky., club _ near
where Pennington had formed The Exiles in 1963 _ the two decided to
re-form Exile.
</P>
<P>
   ``The end result was that J.P. and I put the group back together
with three new guys,'' Taylor said. ``And it still sounds great. We
enjoy bringing the music back together again. We've cut some new
stuff and are actively seeking another record deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Without a record contract and the benefit of record company
support, the new Exile is aiming for success the old-fashioned way:
performing plenty of live dates, writing new songs and generally
working as much as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year we put the group back together, we did 88
dates; the second year we did 113 and the third year we did about
120,'' Taylor said. ``And we expect that we'll probably do that
many this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very fortunate to be able to work this much without
having current product; we're basically still working off the hits
that we've had.''
</P>
<P>
   Those also include such '80s hits as ``I Don't Wanna Be a
Memory,'' ``Give Me One More Chance,'' ``Crazy For Your Love'' and
``She's a Miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You develop a style for yourself by writing your own
material,'' Taylor said. ``And that was the situation with Exile in
the '80s.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the group's material was written by Taylor, Pennington
and former bassist Sonny Lemaire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our harmonies were distinct, and I really think that helped us
a lot. We stood apart from the rest of the groups at that time,
which were only the Oak Ridge Boys and Alabama at that point, in
the early '80s,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   While much of country music in the 1990s has been dominated by
the rise of the solo artist, Taylor and Pennington are hoping that
the pendulum of tastes will swing back to favor the sound popular
in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it does,'' Taylor said. ``I think we're a lot more
serious about things, not that we weren't serious in the '80s, when
we were having the hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``When things start happening to you and you start becoming
successful, you kind of kid yourself or are a little bit naive
about the fact that it's not going to last forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``And nothing lasts forever. So we have a different approach to
that now.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
