<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2227 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PORCELAIN-TUB-ART-2TA     05-26 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORCELAIN-TUB-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PICKY BATHROOM RENOVATOR TELLS HOW IT'S DONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DONNA PAUL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Imagine a prewar bathroom with a deep, deep porcelain
tub and gleaming (but not too gleaming) nickel fittings: a wide
sunflower shower head and those little porcelain buttons marked
``hot'' and ``cold'' in the middle of gutsy crossbar handles. There
are reproductions, of course, but the dream is the real thing. It
was my dream.
</P>
<P>
   So when my search for a co-op apartment led me to an Upper West
Side prewar with warm eastern light, high ceilings and a bathroom
with 1929 fixtures, I was thrilled. The oversize tub, large
pedestal sink, white tiled walls and basket-weave patterned floor
were all original.
</P>
<P>
   What the charm camouflaged was the greenish-black mold and
mildew on the wall above the tub, which, after decades, had
organized itself into a pattern that resembled a Rorschach test.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the only problem. As soon as I moved in, I became
aware that the shower had a continual leak _ a persistent stream,
actually. To make matters worse, I absent-mindedly sat on the
pedestal sink, causing a crack the size of the Liberty Bell's
through the base. It was time to take action.
</P>
<P>
   The Battle Plan
</P>
<P>
   Renovating a down-at-the-heels bathroom to its prewar glory can
be a stone-cold sobering experience, as thousands of New York co-op
owners have learned. I budgeted what I thought was a reasonable
amount for a fix-up _ repair the leaky plumbing, replace the sink,
clean up the old grout _ and decided to act as the contractor
myself after consulting with an architect. The project seemed so
small; I thought, why not?
</P>
<P>
   The architect I called, David Mullman, took one look and said,
``Gut job _ rip it out and start over.''
</P>
<P>
   No way. Not only would that blow my budget, but also I knew I
couldn't cope with living in a construction site. Yes, there were
problems, but so much of the bathroom's charm was intact. I
wouldn't consider ripping it up.
</P>
<P>
   We moved to Plan B. The original shower body (the valve
mechanism in the wall that controls the water flow) and fittings
(commonly known as faucet handles) were beyond repair and had to
go. But how? If they were removed, the surrounding tile would be
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that it would be impossible to match the original tile,
Mullman came up with a stunningly elegant solution: Remove a
section of tile and replace it with a grid of completely different
handmade tile, using color in a Mondrian-style ``mural.'' The new
section, 44 inches square, would be set into the wall, framed by
half-round border tile. The new shower body and fittings would go
in the center of the grid.
</P>
<P>
   Tentatively, I visited Ann Sacks in Manhattan, where I saw
glass, ceramic and stone tiles in colors so vivid I was sorely
tempted to retile the entire bathroom. Returning to my senses, I
settled on handmade ceramic tiles in sea-foam blue and a
yellow-green.
</P>
<P>
   At the showroom, Tina Serpico is a wizard with dimensions and
calculations, an asset if you don't want to end up with boxes of
leftover tile. Ms. Serpico told me that another customer had
recently done a similar project, so Mullman and I headed uptown for
a look.
</P>
<P>
   The Reconnaissance Mission
</P>
<P>
   When Mary and Russell Selover bought an apartment in a prewar
building on the Upper East Side, they discovered a situation
similar to mine. ``A bad patch job,'' Ms. Selover called it. Ms.
Selover's goals had also matched mine: keep the costs down and
retain as much of the original bathroom as possible. ``Sure, the
tub is not perfect,'' she said, ``but that's part of the charm of
moving into a prewar building.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than trying to match the existing tile, Tom Hemmerick,
her architect, had created a checkerboard inset, which was
installed on the diagonal. The new mural looks as if it had been
there since the Hoover administration. Now I knew Mullman's plan
would work.
</P>
<P>
   Let No One Be Scalded
</P>
<P>
   When I set out to find the replacement shower body, I had no
idea that I was about to get an education in New York environmental
conservation law. I had intended to install new fittings in the old
configuration, with separate faucets for hot and cold water. This,
I learned, was not possible, because of Local Law 86.
</P>
<P>
   New York City implemented the law in 1996 to protect citizens
from harming themselves with scalding water. The law requires the
installation of either a pressure-balanced valve or a thermostatic
mixing valve.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure-balanced valve maintains the temperature by keeping
the proportions of hot and cold water balanced. But it will allow a
flow rate of only 3.5 gallons of water a minute, and the flow may
fluctuate.
</P>
<P>
   A thermostatic mixing valve can be set at a specific
temperature, which it will maintain. It will also allow higher flow
rates, generally 6 to 14 gallons a minute. And once the valve is
set, it will remain at that temperature. A shower body with a
pressure-balanced valve ranges in cost, roughly, from $75 to $300;
with a thermostatic valve, from $200 to $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   I found my way to the showroom of AF Supply in the Flatiron
district. This company has been in business since 1922 and has what
I believe to be the most complete selection of bathroom faucets and
fixtures in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, I chose a shower body with a thermostatic mixing
valve made by Dornbracht, even though it cost much more than I had
planned to spend. ``You want to put the best product you can behind
the wall,'' said Bennett Friedman, the director of sales and
marketing at AF. ``Once it's no longer accessible, you don't want
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginner's Luck
</P>
<P>
   Finding a plumber in New York is like hailing a cab in a
rainstorm: Persistence, however futile the effort may seem,
eventually pays off. It took six weeks, but I got five estimates,
ranging from $375 to $750. I hired Keith Simonelli, owner of Metro
Plumbing Authority in Brooklyn, not because his estimate was the
lowest _ it wasn't _ but because he came highly recommended and had
experience installing Dornbracht products.
</P>
<P>
   Simonelli was not only amazingly reliable but also enthusiastic
about the job. On the day he broke open the wall, he called me in
to have a look. ``There's 10 feet of pipe in there,'' he said
excitedly, pointing to the mazelike twists and turns of copper
pipe. Five hours later, he had installed the new shower body.
</P>
<P>
   Having obsessively worked out a schedule for each stage of work,
I was expecting the tile installer to come the next day. At the
last minute, the man canceled. It sounds trivial, but the domino
effect of one cancellation can bring a renovation to its knees.
It's a renovator's equivalent of the Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
   I needed the tile installer to complete his work before the
plumber could put the ``trim'' pieces (faceplate, handles and
knobs) in place. My wall was torn apart; I had no water. Within
minutes, I could feel the need for a shower creeping up my neck. So
I hired a replacement without seeing his work. I would regret it.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Tile and Error
</P>
<P>
   Initially I was charmed by the tile installer, and especially by
his Sicilian father, who had been working with tile for 40 years.
But their Old World method ended up being a bit more primitive than
what I had hoped for. The grout lines (the space between the tiles)
in the new grid were too wide, and once the tiles were in place,
there was nothing that could be done.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to get what is known as a ``tight'' grout line
with handmade tiles because of their irregular shapes, but a
skillful installer can produce grout lines of 1/8 to 3/16 of an
inch _ a desirable width for tiles like these, Ms. Serpico said.
Mine measure \ inch; in some places, they're even wider.
</P>
<P>
   Although the grout lines still annoy me, a friend who grew up in
Italy, where craft traditions coexist with a fine sense of
fatalism, remarked on how authentic the inset looked.
</P>
<P>
   My next mistake was significant: I paid the installer in full,
although he had to finish some details. It took months to get him
to return.
</P>
<P>
   The Truth About Tubs
</P>
<P>
   I learned an important lesson: Never hire when desperate, and
always inspect past work if the job involves aesthetics. Which is
exactly what I did when I decided to have my tub reglazed. I
trekked around the city and looked at jobs ranging from $300 to
$600. I didn't hire anyone. The pros I consulted told me not to
bother, that reglazing is impermanent.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the term ``reglazing'' is a misnomer. Leonard
Schechter, the founder of Urban Archaeology, explained that the
surface of the tub is actually sprayed with epoxy paint, which,
over time, will peel, chip and bubble. For a tub truly to be
reglazed, it would have to be removed and fired in a kiln _ not
only impractical but extraordinarily expensive.
</P>
<P>
   I listened. And hard as it was, I gave up the prospect of having
a shiny, new-looking tub. Mary Selover was right when she said that
the old stuff, even when it's not perfect, really is part of the
charm. Anyway, you gotta believe.
</P>
<P>
   From Tile to Tubs: A Sourcebook of Suppliers
</P>
<P>
   The Soho line of towel bars and hooks, designed by Thomas
O'Brien of Aero Studios, was inspired by skyscrapers of the 1930s.
Available in nickel, matte nickel or chrome; single robe hooks,
$153 to $168; an 18-inch towel bar, $462 in chrome, $485 in nickel
and $508 in matte nickel. At Waterworks, 469 Broome St. (Greene
Street) and 237 East 58th St.
</P>
<P>
   Made-to-order Robern bathroom cabinets with anodized aluminum
frames come in multiple sizes, colors (cobalt, black, red, green
and matte silver) and door options (mirrored, clear, sandblasted or
textured glass). Delivery: four weeks; $466 to $975 at Gracious
Home, 1220 Third Ave. (70th Street) and 1992 Broadway (67th
Street).
</P>
<P>
   The Novocento pedestal sink from Italy is made today just as it
was in the 1920s. Each sink is made in traditional craftsman style,
with hand-applied porcelain and glazes. The Novocento is priced
competitively with reproduction versions. It comes in three widths:
23{ inches, $695; 25 inches, $795; 27{, $895. At AF Supply, 22 West
21st St.
</P>
<P>
   Kaldewei tubs from Germany are made of steel and multiple layers
of enamel. Cast from molds that borrow technology from the
automotive industry, the tubs have clean shapes and an especially
smooth finish. They're also one-third to one-half the weight of
cast-iron tubs, and because of the layered enamel, they are
resistant to chipping. The Duo-pool, a 20-inch-deep soaking tub, is
$2,000 at AF Supply. For an extra $1,600, you can have a whirlpool.
</P>
<P>
   Oxo's Libro mirror in wenge wood opens like a book, with an
outside flap that incorporates a magnifying mirror. Opened, it
expands to 31{ inches. Oxo's freestanding Afro sink has a wenge
base and a stainless-steel basin and is a compact size for city
apartments. The Libro is $820; the Afro is $2,875 at AF Supply.
</P>
<P>
   Remsen's sleek but sturdy cross-handle bath fittings from the
Davinci Collection _ $430 for chrome, $480 for nickel or brass _
are high design made affordable. Custom finishes are available. At
AF Supply.
</P>
<P>
   This bathroom clothesline with 6 feet of nylon cord is $26.39 at
Gracious Home. The chrome disc is installed on one wall; a small
plate and hook on another.
</P>
<P>
   Chromtech and Chromwork floor tiles look remarkably like stone,
but they're solid porcelain, developed for commercial use. Easy to
clean and slip-resistant, the material is ideal for bathrooms. And
the cost is about half that of stone; installation fees are lower
as well. Chromtech comes in 12-by-12-inch squares; Chromwork in
18-by-18. Prices are $4.50 to $6 a square foot at Stone Source, 215
Park Ave. South (17th Street).
</P>
<P>
   An oversize acrylic tub was designed by Michael Graves for the
Hoesch Dreamscapes series. Made for mini-manses and not for small
apartments, it measures 6 feet in diameter and weighs 300 pounds.
The rim is a thick 6 inches, perfect for candles or glasses of
champagne. The price is equally hefty: $11,000, through Duravit;
(888) 387-2848.
</P>
<P>
   Watercolors, a new line of sandblasted glass tiles, come in
delicate shades with names like lakeshore, cascade and ivy. The
tiles are available in assorted sizes _ 4-inch squares, 6-by-12,
12-inch squares; $47.50 a square foot at Waterworks.
</P>
<P>
   Boffi's sleek, low rectangular sink is made of limestone from
Lecce, in southern Italy. It rests on a 31-inch-high base of
walnut, which includes space for towels. The sink alone is $3,689;
the base is $1,321. Three optional drawers will add another $629.
The sink will be available at Boffi's New York showroom, 150 East
58th St., at the beginning of September.
</P>
<P>
   Dolci tiles are a blend of transparent and opaque glass in jewel
colors. Best used as an accent tile, they are high-ticket items:
\-inch tiles are $2 each; 1[-inch squares are $5.34 in solids and
$10.68 in multitones. At Ann Sacks, 5 East 16th St.
</P>
<P>
   The limestone in Limestone Coordinates tiles comes from a quarry
in France, and the colors evoke Provence: blue, yellow, smoky gray
and creamy beige. Prices are $9 to $17 a square foot at Ann Sacks.
</P>
<P>
   ARCHITECT Mullman Seidman Architects; (212) 431-0770: fee for
small jobs, $150 an hour; for a bathroom like the one described,
$3,200 total.
</P>
<P>
   PLUMBING AF Supply Corp., 22 West 21st St.; (212) 243-5400:
Dornbracht shower body and components, including a hand-held shower
designed by Philippe Starck for HansGrohe, $2,354; Palladio
pedestal sink, $995; Dornbracht fittings for sink, $725; Samuel
Heath glass and chrome shelves, $246 each.
</P>
<P>
   Metro Plumbing Authority; (718) 492-7513: $600.
</P>
<P>
   TILE Ann Sacks, 5 East 16th St.; (212) 463-8400: $650 for a
44-inch square grid of No. 182 and No. 172 handmade tiles, and
white trim, No. 102.
</P>
<P>
   Installation: $1,000.
</P>
