<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2230 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASS-MOCA-ART-2TAKES-     05-26 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASS-MOCA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW ARTS CENTER OPENS AGAINST ALL ODDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH ADAMS, Mass. _ There is likely to be a huge sigh of relief
in this corner of the Berkshires on Sunday with the opening of the
$37 million Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art after 13
roller-coaster years and a last-minute scramble to install the
giant artworks it was designed to display.
</P>
<P>
   MASS MOCA, as the center has become known, is a marriage of art
and urban renewal fraught by politics, economic constraints and
uncertain artistic ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   The 13-acre grounds and cross-disciplinary programs (summer
offerings include the premiere of Walt Disney's latest movie,
``Dinosaur,'' and video and dance performances) have been designed
to give this sleepy, economically depressed town more attention
than it has drawn since its days as a bustling manufacturing center
in the late 1700s.
</P>
<P>
   Just days ago installers were scurrying to hang Robert
Rauschenberg's immense ``\ Mile or 2 Furlong Piece'' in a gallery
as long as a football field, screw together fluorescent light
fixtures for a series of works by Dan Flavin and attach neon
numbers to a piece by Italian sculptor Mario Merz so they would
appear to trail behind a bright red motorcycle placed 20 feet high
on a wall.
</P>
<P>
   Outdoors, workers were laying cobblestones in the courtyard and
cleaning up months of construction debris.
</P>
<P>
   That MASS MOCA is opening at all is a striking accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``MASS MOCA has had more lives than a cat, more ups and downs
than an elevator,'' said the mayor of North Adams, John Barrett
3rd. He lobbied for the project from the start, excited by the
prospect of creating about 100 new jobs and attracting 120,000
visitors a year to a blue-collar town that had always played second
fiddle to neighboring Williamstown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's giving this city credibility for the first time since the
last turn of the century,'' Barrett said. ``I could see from day
three that MASS MOCA could transform the community. It already
has.''
</P>
<P>
   Being in the midst of the Berkshires' lively arts scene, nearly
four hours from New York and three hours from Boston, gives MASS
MOCA hopes of luring a ready-made audience.
</P>
<P>
   Two million people a year already visit cultural institutions in
this part of Massachusetts, like Tanglewood in Lenox, summer home
to the Boston Symphony Orchestra, the Norman Rockwell Museum in
Stockbridge, Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival in Becket, and the
Williams College Museum of Art and the Sterling and Francine Clark
Art Institute, both in Williamstown.
</P>
<P>
   The new contemporary arts center is made up of a collection of
light-filled 19th-century factory buildings, home of the Sprague
Electric Co. until 1984, spread across carefully planned outdoor
spaces. Abandoned mills and overgrown courtyards have been
renovated to house 19 galleries, a 10,000-square-foot black-box
theater, an outdoor cinema, two courtyards for performance art,
5,000 square feet of rehearsal and production space and 60,000
square feet of office and retail space.
</P>
<P>
   There are also outdoor artworks like ``Tree Logic,'' a series of
upside-down trees by Australian artist Natalie Jeremijenko paid for
by the Clark Art Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have yet to have an artist who comes here who doesn't have
a big idea,'' said Joseph C. Thompson, MASS MOCA's director since
1988. ``These buildings have a heft that invites large gestures.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, few institutions have faced as many problems trying to
open. Over the years the project has been referred to as MEGALO
MOCA and a doomed white elephant.
</P>
<P>
   There was controversy over the commitment of millions of dollars
in state money, skepticism about the arts center's ambitions and
concern regarding its ephemeral collections.
</P>
<P>
   The center's genesis is described by Thomas Krens, now director
of the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum in Manhattan, who ran the
Williams College Museum of Art from 1981 to 1988. He said the idea
of the center came to him on Nov. 14, 1986, at 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was driving on this highway between Cologne and Frankfurt. I
had just left an art fair in Cologne where there was this young
dealer from Hamburg who couldn't afford a booth so he rented an
abandoned factory building. I was in the midst of building an
addition to the Williams College of Art, and I was aware that
17,000 square feet wasn't enough. I didn't have the capacity to
show large works of art. So I'm driving down this highway and I
have an insight, a flash.''
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to Williams, Krens went to see the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Krens showed up in my office and said, you've got this old
mill you're trying to get rid of that could be turned into a
museum,'' Barrett recalled. ``He talked about how they were doing
projects like this in Los Angeles. A week later he came back with
someone from the Dukakis administration'' in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Krens had a different site in mind, but then Sprague
Electric closed and its complex was for sale. (The buildings were
given to MASS MOCA in 1994 by American Annuity Group, which
absorbed Sprague.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The notion of transforming abandoned factory buildings into an
arts center was not new, but getting the government to underwrite a
museum meant to help an economically depressed city was a novel
achievement. Krens has since pulled that off in Bilbao, Spain, and
the Dia Center for the Arts is doing the same in the depressed
Hudson River town of Beacon, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Krens enlisted Thompson, a Williams graduate, to help gather
statistics and do feasibility studies. With the backing of Gov.
Michael Dukakis, the Legislature in 1988 approved a $35 million
grant for the project.
</P>
<P>
   There was talk that important collectors would promise portions
of their holdings for long-term loan to the museum, among them
Italian industrialist Count Giuseppe Panza di Biumo, who had more
than 200 artworks from the 1960s and 1970s. Thompson was named
director of the museum and Krens chairman of a cultural development
commission.
</P>
<P>
   Then catastrophe struck: Krens left Williams to become director
of the Guggenheim, and support for large-scale government-financed
projects was coming under fire as the state economy crumbled.
</P>
<P>
   At first it seemed that the Guggenheim connection might improve
the situation. Krens started seeing MASS MOCA as a satellite of the
New York museum. But the Guggenheim was facing financial problems
and the museum's board was not eager to take on new projects. Then
in 1991 the Guggenheim bought the Panza collection for $30 million,
though it agreed to lend parts of it to MASS MOCA.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988 Dukakis, a strong supporter of the project, was running
for president. But as his campaign fell apart, so did the
Massachusetts economy, recalled Thompson. Worse, contemporary art
was getting a bad name and support for government arts funding
collapsed. ``We were getting slaughtered,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   In the last days of his term Dukakis released part of the
promised $35 million. But when William F. Weld became governor in
1991, he overturned the approval, questioning the project's
reliance on public funds. He later relented on the condition that
the project raise $12 million privately.
</P>
<P>
   In five months Thompson gathered 650 pledges totaling about $1
million. ``Most of the money came from up and down Main Street,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, with pressure to keep the project broad-based
and economically viable, and with artists crossing over into video
and performance art, the vision of MASS MOCA has changed. ``It was
no longer just a museum but an arts center,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   But it took another two years to get the first check from the
state, $18 million for the first phase of the construction. Since
then the state has released another $4 million and Thompson has
raised the rest from private sources. Then came the issue of what
to put in the enormous galleries. The Guggenheim no longer seemed a
reliable partner, so Thompson began looking elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   One resource was the Dia Center for the Arts, with its
collection of 1960s and 1970s works. Dia, run by Thompson's friend
and colleague Michael Govan, was seeking a large space to house its
permanent collection to free up its building in the Chelsea section
of Manhattan for special exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   Govan, like Thompson, is a Williams graduate and, also like
Thompson, is a Krens protege.
</P>
<P>
   ``We considered MASS MOCA, but it wasn't a perfect fit,'' said
Govan. But it took time to reach that conclusion, and for months,
Thompson said, he counted on Dia's collection to fill its
galleries. Instead, Dia decided to stay closer to home, preferring
a similar situation in Beacon, an hour's drive from Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Then Krens stepped back into the picture, pulling together major
works from the Guggenheim's collection for loan. Other institutions
have lent as well, including Dia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're more than a lender,'' said Krens. ``I'm the founder of
MASS MOCA, I lobbied for its money. We're a collaborator.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said the Guggenheim had sent four staff members to help
MASS MOCA with its installations.
</P>
<P>
   The new arts center has just one curator and no art of its own.
Thompson intends for it to stay that way, at least for now. ``We're
an open shop, a platform for institutional collaboration,'' he
said. ``We don't plan to form a collection because we couldn't
begin to compete with the Museum of Modern Art or the San Francisco
Museum of Modern Art. But we'll commission works and if something
feels right then we'll try to acquire it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much good work that needs to be seen that never
gets a proper home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
