<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2239 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BATHROOM-SINK-ART-605     05-26 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BATHROOM-SINK-ART-605(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPSTART SINKS FIND A NEW LEVEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This from American Standard's Web site on bathroom
sinks:
</P>
<P>
   ``Choosing a sink is a personal decision. You'll share many
close moments together. Shaving before the job interview. Gargling
before the blind date. That's why you can't go home with the first
sink you meet.''
</P>
<P>
   And just when you thought there was no one left to leave you,
the bathroom sink is leaving, too. Those broad porcelain shoulders
you leaned on each morning, gripped in each hand, that bore the
weight of the world for you as you woke, staring blindly into the
void, unaware of where or who you were until the basin filled, the
water stilled and your face rocked safely into sight.
</P>
<P>
   Gone. Or going, with a loud, emptying suck.
</P>
<P>
   The old-fashioned, large-ledged lavatory sink is being pulled
down its own drain by fashion and the plumbing fixtures industry,
which has been steadily flooding the market with novel product
introductions that it hopes will create a thirst for new types of
bathroom sinks.
</P>
<P>
   Rising in the sink's shadow is the bowl _ an above-the-counter
unsink that sits on top of the vanity cabinet like a salad bowl,
hangs from the wall like a drinking fountain or rests on a pedestal
like a birdbath. It is featured in nonceramic materials like glass,
steel, stone and cement. And the new sink is nothing but lip, as
thin as a landlord's smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call them spaghetti bowls,'' said Bill Florio, the showroom
manager at New York Replacement Parts, a plumbing supply company on
the Upper East Side. ``They're actually called `vessels.' Fancy
name.''
</P>
<P>
   The vessel sink made a high-profile appearance this month at the
Kips Bay Boys and Girls Club Decorator Show House. Eric Cohler, a
New York interior decorator, deployed two traditional nickel sinks
``above water,'' on top of vanity tables. He has installed two
glass bowls and a stainless-steel mixing bowl as sinks in recent
jobs for clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can take anything and have a hole drilled in it,'' Cohler
said.
</P>
<P>
   The plumbing fixtures industry would like to believe that
vessels hold the wave of the future for the lavatory sink, given
the changing nature of the residential bathroom and the record
levels of spending on bathroom renovations _ more than 7 million
remodeling jobs were done in 1998, according to Kitchen and Bath
Business, a monthly trade magazine.
</P>
<P>
   But it could prove to be a pipe dream, especially when customers
wake to the reality of washing in a bucket. Designers seem eager to
sign on; average homeowners may be more cautious about getting
their feet wet.
</P>
<P>
   New York, for one, is not buying the idea, at least for the
master bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York City is 99 percent traditional,'' Florio said.
``They're not a big seller.'' With fewer bathrooms per living unit
to outfit than in suburban homes, most apartment households make
more conservative choices in important fixtures, based on
practicality before style, several local retailers said.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Sallick, president and chief executive of Waterworks, an
upscale bathroom products company in Danbury, Conn., that has 22
stores nationally, said vessels were trickling into a trend, but he
is doubtful that they are headed for the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an interesting alternative,'' he said. ``In a powder
room, it's decorative, unusual, but in a kids' or master bath, it's
not a great sink.'' He said that despite Waterworks' reputation for
stylish fixtures, vessels were not a big part of its sales. Only
one is on display in the New York store. ``We're trying to reflect
what our customers want,'' he said, ``not make something to create
a whole new level of demand.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Vessels were initially designer-driven products available mostly
from European manufacturers, but three models were introduced by
Kohler, the big Wisconsin-based company, two years ago in Chicago
at the Kitchen and Bath show, the industry's leading exposition.
Kohler now has 10 in its line, which is called Vessels.
</P>
<P>
   American Standard Cos., with $6.7 billion in global sales last
year, has now stepped into the ring with two vessels that it will
offer on the mass market in the fall. Vessel-style sinks range from
$350 for simple ceramic models to more than $3,000 for blown glass
and hand-turned terra cotta.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're probably twice as popular as they were two years
ago,'' said Wanda Jankowski, the editor of Kitchen and Bath
Business, who estimated that vessel sinks were 10 percent of
lavatory sales now. ``I think it's just getting started. The
baby-boomer generation hasn't spent its money yet, on vacation
homes or second residences. They're putting quality things in them,
and they're looking for the unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Bissell, the marketing manager for sanitary products at
Kohler, said the response to its Vessels sinks had been unexpected.
``There was no conception here that they would be broadly
popular,'' he said. ``We're flabbergasted. We've seen Home Depot
pick them up from wholesalers.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, with professional chagrin, ``We overestimated
consumers' desire for functionality.''
</P>
<P>
   Though designers might have discovered vessels to be
contemporary alternatives to traditional fixtures, as sinks, they
are the reverse of much of the progress achieved by indoor
plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were kicking around ideas based on old wash basins,''
Bissell said. (A word to the industry: An optional refrigeration
unit would provide ice to break on the surface each morning.) He
said his development team also looked for inspiration to
living-room art pottery and fruit trays for dining-room sideboards.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, part of the popularity of vessels is the changing
nature of the bathroom, which is being integrated en suite with
adjacent rooms like the bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where bathrooms in the past have been very sanitary-looking
environments, now they're becoming a room that people want to
furnish,'' said Garry Uhl, director of product design for American
Standard. Uhl, who uses vessels at home, anticipates that the new
sinks will be 30 percent of his company's lavatory sales within
five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a trend towards more furniturelike cabinetry,'' he
said. ``These vessels allow people to bring different styles of
furniture into the bathroom. If the sink is just a bowl on top of a
table, the table can be anything.'' In turn, water sources are now
spouting like natural springs in other parts of the bedroom, next
to makeup tables and dressing closets. The ``everything but the
bathroom sink'' approach helps make a decorative accent.
</P>
<P>
   But the market may dry as consumers get wet. As a fixture, the
vessel is under some obligation to function. Shaped like a
satellite dish, it tends to send as well as receive water.
</P>
<P>
   ``They splash,'' said Cohler, the interior decorator, who
insisted that this is the only drawback. He recommended keeping a
sponge handy.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Silverstein, a New York architect who has chosen vessels
for clients and is installing one for himself, recommended a towel.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be patient,'' he said. ``They're beautiful, but
they're not the most practical sink in the world.'' Silverstein
suggested them for ``relatively neat married couples, or single
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall-hung and pedestal vessels, which are without table surface
or cabinet, can be worse _ minimal and modern, a target with a
bull's-eye and no rings. You hit the center or else.
</P>
<P>
   There is also no wide ledge _ the hangover's handrail,
china-cool to the head. Nor is there the convenient shelf for the
toothbrush, drinking glass, contact lenses, lipstick, wedding ring,
wristwatch, ibuprofen bottle, soap, hand lotion, dental floss,
razor or any other unlikely item you might be working with at the
bathroom sink.
</P>
<P>
   Vessels also demand special plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is, you see all the plumbing under the sink,''
said Sheldon Malc, the manager of the Davis &AMP; Warshow
bathroom-fixtures showroom on the Upper East Side. ``So people want
in-the-wall plumbing. But a lot of buildings in Manhattan, for
instance, you can't do that.'' And because of vessels' height, he
said, few counter-mounted faucets will fit them, so faucets must be
mounted on the wall, compounding the problem.
</P>
<P>
   To their credit, vessels are willing to meet you halfway when
you wash, which has helped them find an audience. ``The vessel
brings the water to you,'' said Bissell of Kohler. ``Thirty inches
is standard for below-counter bathroom sinks, and most people are
not comfortable bending down to it. This is 34 to 36 inches, like a
kitchen sink.''
</P>
<P>
   Bissell said his industry was aware of a recent trend toward
installing kitchen cabinetry in bathrooms, because of the more
comfortable height. ``It's easier to shave, apply makeup,'' he said
of the vessel sink.
</P>
<P>
   Not always.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Barkan, a New Jersey interior designer who has specified
eight vessels for various residential jobs over the last two years,
finds herself directing their removal now, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did an apartment in the city, a pied-a-terre, with a
glass-bowl bathroom sink,'' she recalled. ``We had to rip it out.''
The client, Ms. Barkan said, couldn't get his head between the bowl
and the spout to wash his face. She also mentioned a ``wash-flow
control situation,'' which she clarified as ``spillage _ a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barkan has learned her lesson; the situation remains a sore
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're wonderful as objects of art,'' she said, closing the
subject sharply, like someone twisting a faucet tight. ``But
they're too much work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
