r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-EXERCISE-TEX     05-26 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-EXERCISE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW ABOUT A MOVIE WITH THAT TREADMILL? 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who says watching TV is bad for your health?
</P>
<P>
   Cardio Theaters with television monitors that offer individual
choices among all kinds of programming are keeping people
exercising longer and increasing the health benefits of traditional
fitness equipment, according to those who will stop striding,
pedaling and climbing long enough to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You lose your focus on exercise and end up watching TV,'' Bob
Abendschein says as he moves from the Stairmaster to the Lifecycle.
``I watch the business reports, and I can go 10 or 15 percent
longer.''
</P>
<P>
   TV monitors have been a mainstay at health clubs for more than a
decade. But high-tech cardio theaters take the concept to a new
level, offering individual headsets, satellite dishes and other
perks, including digital, wireless remotes that with a tap will
change the TV volume or station _ or help check a pulse rate.
</P>
<P>
   At one fitness center in Dallas, moms and dads in the cardio
theater can switch to an in-house station that constantly monitors
the children at play in the child-care room.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get bored. That's the No. One thing,'' says
Abendschein, who works for Union Pacific and works out at Larry
North Fitness of Fort Worth during his lunch hour.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal Davis, a general accountant with Union Pacific
Resources, says she did nothing to stay fit before she started
working out in the downtown Fort Worth fitness center's cardio
theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a lazybones,'' she admits. ``Now I come in about three
times a week and work out while I watch the news or the music video
station.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me feel better and more pumped,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   At Larry North's new downtown Fort Worth location, 10 TV
monitors curve around the bottom of a four-tier, darkened theater
with elliptical cross-trainers on the first level, treadmills on
the second, Lifecycles on the third and Stairmasters at the top.
</P>
<P>
   A satellite dish assures good reception of network and cable
programming, with CNN and ESPN current favorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have one woman who gets here at exactly 11:30 a.m. to watch
her favorite soap every day,'' says Jimmy Mak, general manager of
the fitness club. ``We get a lot of special requests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cardiovascular fitness is so important, but it can be pretty
boring to do,'' Mak says. ``You need to spend at least 20 minutes
at it to get the full benefits. A lot of our members come in and
spend 30 minutes exercising while they watch a 30-minute TV show.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to get people to work out longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps a lot,'' Donna Foreman says as she slows her torrid
pedaling. ``It keeps your mind off the fact that you are killing
yourself on the bike. It distracts you.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
