u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-U.S.-2TAKES-NYT     05-26 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIES WITH CHINA REMAIN STRONG DESPITE POLITICAL HOSTILITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL and ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ One recent afternoon, as the Chinese press continued
to rage against ``American imperialism,'' a 36-year-old lawyer
named Wang darted from the newly opened Starbucks back into the law
conference he was attending _ in place of an American delegate who
felt uneasy about traveling to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Wang, who wears loafers and cartoon neckties, went to college in
Portland, Ore. At his Chinese law firm he works closely with
American clients, and he still keeps in touch with dozens of
friends in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He shares the anger of his compatriots about the bombing of the
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade and finds it hard to believe that it
was purely a mistake. But like many Chinese today, he also cannot
imagine China getting by without the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many different types of interactions now:
economic, cultural and educational,'' he said. ``I think much would
be lost on both sides if those ties were sacrificed.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the current anti-American atmosphere here, Wang, like
many other Chinese approached on the streets in recent days, spoke
on condition that his full name not be used.
</P>
<P>
   Political relations between China and the United States have
entered a tense phase, battered by China's outrage over the attack
on its embassy and by a congressional committee's charges of
extensive Chinese military espionage.
</P>
<P>
   But even as geopolitics and the prospect of a strategic rivalry
drive the two countries apart, millions of personal and business
relationships form a thick social glue that binds them together.
Since China began to open up some 20 years ago, those ties have
multiplied with speed and gusto, long ago eclipsing the wary
political relationship.
</P>
<P>
   These diverse links tend to work against any severe
estrangement, many political experts and others in both countries
say, especially since American ties are strongest among China's
most influential groups.
</P>
<P>
   China's top three Communist Party leaders all have children who
were educated in the United States, just one more way the
relationship is vastly more complicated than the Cold War standoff
between the United States and the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``The glue is very deep,'' said Ezra Vogel, head of Harvard
University's Asia Center and a former national security official.
``Given the depth of contacts, openness and interdependence we have
now, it's hard for me to imagine that it could become unstuck.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every better-off family in Beijing seems to have
relatives studying or working in the United States, or working in
American joint ventures in China. The personal links are strongest
among the country's Communist elite, starting right at the top.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A son of Jiang Zemin, the president and head of the Communist
Party, studied at Drexel University in Philadelphia from 1986 to
1991, earning a Ph.D. in electrical engineering. The son, Jiang
Mianheng, is now a corporate executive in Shanghai, and he often
makes business trips to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Li Xiaolin, the 38-year-old daughter of Li Peng _ No. 2 in the
Communist Party hierarchy and believed to be a hard-line,
anti-American voice in the leadership _ did graduate work in
engineering at MIT. Now an executive with a Chinese government
power company, she visits the United States several times a year
developing bond offerings for power projects.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu Yunlai, the son of Prime Minister Zhu Rongji, spent a decade
in the United States, where he did graduate studies in business and
worked at Credit Suisse First Boston. Today he is a senior official
of the first Chinese investment bank, a joint venture between a
state-owned bank and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Close to 50,000 Chinese students attend American universities,
mainly in graduate schools. Many of the hundreds of thousands of
Chinese who studied in America stayed on to work there, but a
growing share of those who have studied abroad are returning to
work in China.
</P>
<P>
   Alumni clubs from universities like Harvard and Stanford thrive
in Beijing. And thousands of extended families here brag about the
grandchild with an American passport, born while the parents were
studying abroad.
</P>
<P>
   In business, American companies' direct investment in China
surpasses $21 billion. A few companies, including Motorola and IBM,
are believed to sell more than $1 billion worth of goods here each
year. A new Kodak film developing counter opens in China nearly
every day.
</P>
<P>
   Equally striking, though, are the multitudes of smaller private
exchanges and activities, which have mushroomed far beyond the
ability of either government to track.
</P>
<P>
   A group run by Ned Graham, a son of the Rev. Billy Graham, is
allowed to distribute Bibles to ``underground'' churches in the
Chinese countryside. A Hong Kong millionaire has paid for Chinese
army colonels to attend the Kennedy School of government at
Harvard, while Gloria's Place of Hope, a small New Jersey
foundation, has a waiting list of almost 600 Chinese children who
want to go the United States for heart surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The weeks since the bombing of China's embassy in Belgrade on
May 7 have been an awkward time for millions of people in both
countries as they wait to see how their personal, professional and
business ties will be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Many have sought to insulate their most precious relationships
with colleagues and friends from the hostile politics _ as well as
from their own anger over a bombing that many Chinese think was
probably intentional or at the least extremely reckless.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government has suspended official collaboration in
areas like military cooperation and human rights. Some private
contacts, too, have at least temporarily followed suit. A reception
for Cosmopolitan magazine was canceled. A party to kick off a new
master of business administration program offered by Beijing
University in conjunction with a consortium of United States
colleges was postponed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week we were going to host a delegation of American
insurance managers, but they canceled,'' said Yang Qi, a
27-year-old woman in a denim jacket emblazoned with a small
American flag, who works for a Chinese insurance company. ``There
has been tremendous outrage about the bombing, and of course it has
created some bad feelings. I myself have stopped eating at
McDonald's. But the outrage is directed at the American government
and not at the American people, and I think it will pass.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Many employees at joint venture companies said normal
after-hours socializing _ the dinners and the badminton games _ had
ceased. ``Everyone sits and does their work and nothing is said
openly, but there's an extremely awkward feeling in the air,'' said
a man wearing black jeans and aviator sunglasses who would give
only his surname, Hou.
</P>
<P>
   But in other cases the eruption of hostile politics barely
intruded on plans.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when the American Embassy in Beijing was still being
pelted with stones, angry Chinese were waiting outside the
consulate in Guangzhou _ for visas. Before the shattered glass in
the embassy had been swept up, as the official press continued its
attacks on American ``barbarism,'' Li Peng's daughter called
American officials with an urgent request to get documents
notarized.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days after the embassy bombing in Belgrade, a 176-member
delegation from Jiangsu Province arrived in California looking for
investment and trade opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese leaders hope, perhaps unrealistically, that the
economic ties they have cultivated to aid China's modernization can
be insulated from political conflict. American business executives,
now with millions at stake, tend to share that wish.
</P>
<P>
   Many educated Chinese are likewise trying to wall off
international politics from their own self-interest and their
personal lives.
</P>
<P>
   Guo Haobin, an affable 22-year-old who works for an
international trading company, said he was ``very angry and
agitated about the bombing, like all Chinese.'' But he said he
continued to treat American clients well, and when asked if he had
been to the United States, he answered, ``I haven't, but as soon as
I have the opportunity, I really want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when the visa section of the American Embassy reopened
on Monday, many of its shattered windows still covered with boards,
there were hundreds of applicants, mostly students wanting to get
back to American universities or parents eager to visit children in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``People have very contradictory points of view right now,''
said Shi Tao, a book editor who did graduate studies in Ohio.
``Personally, they want their sons and daughters to go to the U.S.
to get educated and have a better life. Or they have prospered and
for that reason want to keep beneficial contacts going. At the same
time, they think we should fight against the American imperialists.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think they can separate their personal needs from the
national point of view. But I worry that it will make some people
feel more angry and confused.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Chinese with their feet in both worlds insist that the social
and economic relations are too strong to destroy and hope that the
politics will ultimately be dragged along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the political tensions will affect all the other
ties,'' said Xu Xiaonian, chief of research at China International
Capital Corp., the investment bank that is a joint venture with
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relationship between these two countries has never been
easy, and I don't expect it to be smooth in the future,'' said Xu,
who received a Ph.D. from the University of California at Davis,
then taught at Amherst College in Massachusetts for many years.
``But I believe that it will move in a direction that will benefit
both countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, after spending 12 years in the United States, Xu
returned to Beijing to take his current job. ``I could have stayed
in Amherst and led the good life,'' Xu said. ``But the other part
of my life belongs in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Xu's wife and daughter have remained behind in Amherst, where
his wife works in the public library. ``It was just too beautiful
for them to leave,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
