<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: PUBLIC VS. PRIVATE GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Al Gore was critiquing his own performance. He knew he
had not done well. He had been onstage Tuesday afternoon with Bill
Clinton, who makes it look so easy. The president was the warm-up
act in Edinburg, a town of 40,000 near the southern tip of Texas.
He praised the vice president. He got the crowd ready. And then the
spotlight moved to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The speech was a snooze, and was immediately panned by the
reporters in attendance. Even Andrew Cuomo, a staunch Gore ally and
a good friend, damned the vice president with faint praise. ``The
president,'' said Cuomo, ``is a master communicator of historic
proportions. I believe he is one of the best ever. The vice
president is a very effective communicator.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview a few hours after the speech, Gore said, ``I
think I went too long today.'' He told me he had been ``carried
away'' by the personal stories he had heard in Sebastian, a
poverty-stricken border town that has benefited from the enterprise
zones championed by Gore.
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``I wanted to share those stories and that put an extra
10 minutes into the speech, which I should have whacked out of the
back end.'' But by the time he got to the back end, he couldn't
find a spot to make the cut. So he stayed with the lengthy prepared
text.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that the speech, overall, was not very good. The
personal stories were well received, but the speech was unfocused
and was laden with far too many personal greetings and too much
bureaucratic jargon. Al Gore has some good ideas, but you wouldn't
have known it from the speech on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president needs a couple of crackerjack speechwriters
and he needs a ruthless editor. Fast.
</P>
<P>
   During the interview, in response to questions about education
and the economy, Gore displayed the kind of persona _ intelligent,
energetic and committed to progress _ that would likely serve him
well if it were exhibited more often in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole theme,'' he said, ``is to keep the prosperity going
and use it to make sure that nobody's left behind.'' What must be
recognized, he said, is that education and the economy are
inseparable as policy matters ``because we are in an information
age, and that's more than a cliche; it's a reality.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that more than half of American businesses had trouble
filling job vacancies because of a lack of qualified applicants. He
noted that in a comparison of some 20 countries, 12th-graders in
the United States ranked near the bottom in math and science. Other
performance levels are comparably dismal. It is evident, said Gore,
that if the United States is to continue leading the world
economically, it cannot continue to lag so far behind in the
education of its children.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spoke quickly and at times passionately. He said too many
American schools were overcrowded, too many teachers were
overburdened and too many school buildings were in disrepair. His
top priority as president, said Gore, would be to bring a level of
improvement to the nation's schools that would be so great as to
seem ``revolutionary.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be. But Gore will never be president if he does not get
his act together. Whether you agreed with Ronald Reagan or not, he
had a clear and concise message. John F. Kennedy had brilliant
speeches penned by Theodore Sorensen and others. Gore will never
have the charisma or the performance skills of a Reagan or a
Kennedy, but there is no reason for him to be unable to formulate
and articulate a clear and compelling message.
</P>
<P>
   You call on the experts, you craft the message, and then you
travel the country pounding the message home. Gore has one
advantage. He actually has a message he believes in.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the interview, Gore said: ``I say to groups out
there, `Look, if you don't want a president who's going to take the
oath of office on January 20 at high noon 2001 committed heart and
soul to moving heaven and earth to bring revolutionary change to
our schools, vote for somebody else. But if that's what you want,
I'd like to have your support for me and for this agenda.'''
</P>
<P>
   Not bad at all. That's a lot better than losing your audience in
the first 10 minutes by introducing every two-bit bureaucrat and
party functionary in sight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
