<HEADLINE>
FORGET LIGHTSABER, HAN SOLO, GRAB A BRUSH! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURI NOTARO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - I had hoped that my husband would use his vacation
time to finish painting the outside of our house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did that last year,'' he mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you (begin ital) started (end ital) painting the house
last year,'' I informed him. ``But we don't live in Old Tucson. We
have to paint (begin ital) all the way around (end ital) the house,
not just the front!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told you I'm spending my vacation getting ready for ''The
Phantom Menace''!'' he informed me. ``I've waited years for this!''
</P>
<P>
   When my husband learned that the new ``Star Wars'' movie was
about to be released, I don't think he could have been happier than
if he had woken up one day to find that I had been struck mute. It
was, indeed, a red-letter day.
</P>
<P>
   He had been a ``Star Wars'' enthusiast since he saw the first
movie at the age of 7 and became immersed in ``Star Wars'' culture
and merchandise, even to the point of having R2-D2 Underoos.
</P>
<P>
   Before we were married, he confided that one of the darkest days
of his life was when his older brother and sister _ both of whom
had reached drinking age _ woke him up one night to tell him that
Darth Vader was in the living room and wanted to talk to him.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed appropriately for his audience with the enforcer of the
Dark Side in ``Star Wars'' pajamas, my then second-grade husband
eagerly gathered up both his large-size Han Solo and Luke Skywalker
dolls in case the evil lord might want to play.
</P>
<P>
   He ran into the living room only to find it empty, except for
the laughter of his siblings ringing off the walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could they be so cruel?'' I asked him, shaking my head,
still wanting to date him. ``But you wear real underwear now,
right?''
</P>
<P>
   At school, he went on to say, the kids would get together on the
playground at recess and re-enact their favorite ``Star Wars''
scenes, and, in even more tragic circumstances, my husband was
denied the right to be his foremost idol and hero, Han Solo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the tallest kid in the class,'' he said quietly, his
eyes glazed and looking far into the distance. ``And because I was
so tall, I was only allowed to play if I assumed the role of . . .
Chewbacca. It was my job to run around the playground, growling at
people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Children can be cruel,'' I said, patting his hand and trying
to soothe him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, well,'' he said as he looked away, his voice breaking,
``I guess it was better than not playing at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Several years later (the story continues), in a moment of
mistaken maturity, he relinquished his entire collection of ``Star
Wars'' toys to his younger cousin, even though at the time it was
tearing his little Jedi heart out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did you give your toys to him if you weren't ready to?'' I
asked.
</P>
<P>
   He looked at me and took a deep breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' he said, ``after you've reached a certain height
and are playing with certain things, even a large-size Han Solo,
people start to think that you're . . . retarded. Did you know that
if you hold a Slinky up to your ear and let it drop, it makes the
exact sound of a laser gun?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' was all I could say, even though I really wanted to add,
``you didn't go to a `special school,' did you?''
</P>
<P>
   So you see that even though the house-painting really needed to
be finished, there was no way I could deny him the joy of returning
to his childhood memories with ``The Phantom Menance,'' or ``TPM,''
as the real fans say.
</P>
<P>
   I even went to the shelf we keep our movies on and retrieved the
``StarWars'' trilogy myself so he could get ready for the big day,
and then I went back to work.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, however, after ``The Empire Strikes Back'' was over,
the house became silent as the VCR clicked off. I waited a moment
for my husband to pop in ``Return of the Jedi'' but heard nothing.
I raced into the living room, where I found only our rather portly
dog, Chigger the Hutt, chewing on an empty paper-towel roll my
husband had told me earlier that day was his lightsaber.
</P>
<P>
   He was gone.
</P>
<P>
   But I knew where to find him.
</P>
<P>
   I parked the car and walked up toward the front of the building
and scanned my eyes over the lawn chairs, coolers and assorted
bedding. I found him near the front of the line with a Slinky
dangling near his ear, demonstrating his discovery to a group of
guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honey,'' I said as I walked up to the front of the line,
``what are you doing? You're not going to . . . camp here to see
that movie, are you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told you I needed to get ready,'' he said harshly. ``And
don't you (begin ital) ever (end ital) call `TPM' a `movie' again!
It's a lifestyle!''
</P>
<P>
   One of the guys play-punched my husband in the arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this your mom, Chewy?'' he said, nodding toward me and
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   I gasped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am NOT his mother,'' I said, pointing my finger at the wise
guy. ``And he is NOT Chewy!''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's too tall to be anyone else!'' the wise guy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Careful, careful,'' said another guy dressed in a sheet and
holding an empty paper-towel roll, pointing at me. ``A female
Wookiee will tear a man's head off with one swipe of her paw to
protect her young!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you guys all go to a `special school'?'' I asked in
disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   ``School?'' the one in the sheet said. ``We don't go to school.
We're engineers at Intel. We're in a carpool.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to go, now, honey,'' I said, gently taking my
husband's arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to go!'' he yelled, pulling away. ``I want to
stay! They have the large-size Han Solo here!''
</P>
<P>
   ``AND a Farah Fawcett doll,'' the wise guy said, raising his
eyebrows repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   I took a step closer to my husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``All they have here is the doll,'' I whispered into his ear.
``But right after you left, Han Solo came over and is, AT THIS
MOMENT, in our living room, waiting for you to come home.''
</P>
<P>
   My husband looked at me for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really?'' he whispered back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' I confirmed as we began walking away from the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``And guess what? He said he'd help you paint!'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Laurie Notaro is a freelance writer. Send comments about her column
to the Rep, P.O. Box 2245 NF-19, Phoenix, AZ 85002; or by e-mail to
laurienotaro(at)usa.net. &QL;
</P>
