<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, May 27. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL (The Hague, Netherlands) _ International
Criminal Tribunal has indicted Slobodan Milosevic for alleged war
crimes. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PENTAGON (Washington) _ The Pentagon imposed a ban on
retirements from the Air Force to ensure enough forces are
available for the air campaign against Yugoslavia. By Steven Lee
Myers.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S. (Beijing) _ Political relations between China and the
United States have entered a tense new phase _ battered by China's
outrage over the attack on its embassy and by a Congressional
committee's charges of massive Chinese military espionage. But even
as geopolitics and the prospect of a strategic rivalry drive the
two countries apart, literally millions of on-the-ground personal
and business relationships form a thick social glue that binds them
together. By Elisabeth Rosenthal and Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ The chief Republican proponent of
campaign finance overhaul, Rep. Christopher Shays of Connecticut,
defied his party Wednesday by signing a Democratic petition
designed to force the issue to the House floor. He accused
Representative Tom Delay, the powerful House Majority Whip, of
offering to finance a primary challenge against him for his
independence, and cast the issue as struggle with DeLay over the
soul of the party. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEART-ATTACK (Undated) _ A New England Journal of Medicine
study of 100,000 patients has found that patients are far more
likely to survive a heart attack if taken directly to a hospital
that treats many heart attacks rather than being taken to whichever
hospital is nearest. By Denise Grady.
</P>
</TEXT>
