<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITING ``PAINFUL'' SCANDAL, HILLARY SAYS KEY IS TO KEEP TRYING  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, speaking in
unusually personal terms about her ordeal as a betrayed wife, said
in a prime-time TV interview Wednesday night that despite her
``painful'' experience, she still believes in ``forgiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton came across as a resilient partner working to rebuild
her marriage with President Clinton during the 25-minute interview
with CBS News' anchor Dan Rather on ``60 Minutes II.''
</P>
<P>
   She offered her most extensive comments to date on the
sex-and-coverup scandal that engulfed the White House 16 months ago
and nearly claimed Bill Clinton's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Fondly referring to her husband as ``Bill'' on two occasions,
Clinton said her experience had been ``painful, obviously for me
and for my family and for our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added: ``But I think no matter who you are or no matter
what you do or what's done to you, there's always the chance to try
to make it better _ that there's always the hope of forgiveness _
to forgive and to be forgiven.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said her willingness to forgive ``comes certainly from
my religious faith but it also comes out of my personal
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said she ``absolutely'' believes in redemption, adding:
``I've not only seen it in the lives of other people, I've seen it
in my own and in those I love around me.''
</P>
<P>
   The interview was broadcast as the first lady weighs setting up
an exploratory committee for a possible Senate bid from New York
next year.
</P>
<P>
   If she were to run for the seat of retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, D-N.Y., she would become the first presidential spouse in
American history to seek a seat in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview she never mentioned her husband's secret
dalliance with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky or the
coverup that triggered his impeachment by the House and subsequent
acquittal by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But the first lady referred to the episode elliptically in an
apparent effort to air the issue in an intimate, one-on-one setting
with a receptive television anchorman.
</P>
<P>
   Rather recalled that in a 1992 CBS interview, she ``seemed to
ridicule the idea of staying with a straying husband'' after
reports of his affair with a singer named Gennifer Flowers.
``Today,'' Rather continued, ``she doesn't talk about fidelity. ...
She talks about forgiveness ... and dealing with personal pain.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Clinton said, ``Sometimes things come totally out
of the blue, and something good or terrible happens to you _
neither one of which you could have predicted and probably
certainly don't deserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is not by any means fair or easy for anyone,'' she
continued. ``But part of what I think we're challenged to do is to
keep trying _ and to keep trying, not only on our own behalf but on
behalf of anyone we can touch and who we can help.''
</P>
<P>
   The interview was taped last Thursday in Littleton, Colo.,
following the Clintons' emotional visit with the families of
Columbine High School students killed in the murder-suicide raid
carried out by two disgruntled students on April 20.
</P>
<P>
   Discussing her reaction to her husband's infidelity, Clinton
said: ``You know, when you go through any kind of difficult
experience, you have a choice. I mean you can let it break you and
embitter you ... or you can take whatever you've experienced,
whatever pain or suffering, and decide that you're still going to
have faith, your faith in God, your faith in your fellow man, that
you're still going to believe that you can make a contribution to a
better life.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``Every single day we wake up, you can choose to be
cynical or hopeful. You can choose to be grateful or contemptuous.
You can make all those choices. And for me, it's not a very hard
choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said she felt ``really blessed'' by her experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people might look at this and think, `Oh, my gosh, you
know, with what she's been through, how can she say that?'''
Clinton said. ``Nobody would wish on anyone what we and the country
have gone through the last year and a half or so. But I've also
learned a lot and I have been able to share experiences with people
that have been extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather, insisting he wanted to ``respect your privacy,'' said
that sooner or later, if she runs for the Senate, New Yorkers will
ask, ``Why are you still with this man?''
</P>
<P>
   She looked away, laughed nervously and paused.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been together for I guess 28 years,'' she replied.
``We'll be married 24 years this year. And we have a deep and
abiding commitment to one another, and it's something that's been
part of our lives from really almost from the time we met. ... I
look back on all of those years together and it's just something
that means a great deal to both of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she had ever considered leaving her husband, Clinton
replied: ``I am not going to talk about that.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she continues to explore a possible Senate candidacy
from New York: ``I'm still thinking about it. ... I've been very
flattered by the people who've come to me and asked me to consider
it. And I'm obviously very interested.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons, now enjoying a six-day getaway on a 7,500-acre
plantation that serves as a conservation center in Yulee, Fla., are
expectetd to discuss her Senate plans. They are due to return to
the White House on Monday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton's New York supporters say they expect her to
announce the formation of the exploratory committee in late June or
early July.
</P>
<P>
   By creating the committee under the federal election law, she
could raise money for a possible full-fledged Senate campaign and
defray the costs of subsequent campaign trips to the state. She has
visited New York nine times since Jan. 1 with two more trips
planned in early June.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton denied any interest in an eventual campaign for
president. ``People have said that to me, but it's something I
don't take seriously at all,'' she said. ``It's not even in the
universe of my thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady and the president, in separate interviews with
Rather, said they planned to live in New York after leaving the
White House on Jan. 20, 2001. Mrs. Clinton has asked her
representatives to look for a home for the family in Westchester
County, the posh suburb north of New York City, according to a
report in The New York Times Magazine on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via email:
stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
