<SLUG> BC-WARCRIMES-CONGRESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGED TO HAND OVER INTELLIGENCE TO WAR CRIMES TRIBUNAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sixty-three Republican and Democratic lawmakers
urged President Clinton Wednesday to hand over sensitive
intelligence information to an international war crimes tribunal to
help prosecutors build a case charging Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic with genocide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can lead by example by actively compiling evidence of
Milosevic's deeds and providing all documentation to the
prosecutor's office at the tribunal,'' they wrote to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher H. Smith, R-N.J., co-chairman of a government
panel that tracks human rights issues, complained that the
administration had not provided enough ``usable information'' for
indicting and then prosecuting the Yugoslav leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The tribunal has called on Western powers to provide
``unprecedented state cooperation for the investigation into
Kosovo'' to include potentially sensitive intelligence information.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton administration officials have pledged full
cooperation, they have come under fire for not supplying enough raw
data _ satellite photos showing suspected mass graves and
electronic intercepts, for example.
</P>
<P>
   The International Criminal Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia
has been forced to rely in large part on eyewitness accounts from
ethnic Albanian refugees who have fled Kosovo, a province of
Yugoslavia's dominant republic, Serbia. The tribunal thus far has
indicted 84 people on war crimes charges, most of which are related
to the civil war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Nina Bang-Jensen, special counsel for the independent Coalition
for International Justice, which assists the tribunal in The Hague,
Netherlands, recently testified that the Clinton administration has
turned over only ``aggregate information.'' They are summaries of
intelligence that might not be useful as evidence in a court of
law, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The press for more U.S.-supplied information came as reports
circulated Wednesday that the tribunal was preparing to indict
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the U.N. court's chief prosecutor, Louise
Arbour, said in The Hague on Wednesday that investigators had
amassed ``evidence of war crimes on a massive scale.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright would not
comment on the report of an impending indictment. White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart, in Yulee, Fla., where President Clinton is
on vacation, also had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   House lawmakers introduced a resolution Tuesday asserting that
Milosevic is culpable for war crimes, crimes against humanity and
genocide.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Senate unanimously passed a resolution calling
for the ``vigorous investigation'' of genocide and other war crimes
in Kosovo. It urged the tribunal to issue indictments ``regardless
of their position within the Serbian leadership.''
</P>
</TEXT>
