<SLUG> BC-DIETITIAN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chai is a sweet drink, not a tonic
 &HT;    By Karen Collins
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: What is the drink called chai? Is it
nutritious?
</P>
<P>
   A: Chai is a hot or iced drink made of tea and brewed spices
such as ginger, cinnamon, cloves, nutmeg and cardamom. As long as
the chai is made only with spices and tea, it contain no calories
or fat and negligible sodium. However, each cup of chai is usually
sweetened with 2 to 5 teaspoons of honey, providing 40 to 105
calories.
</P>
<P>
   Many versions of chai also include about a half cup of steamed
milk, which adds a few more calories, and possibly fat.
</P>
<P>
   Research suggesting that certain spices may have antioxidant or
other health-promoting effects is still tentative, so for now enjoy
chai as a sweetened spice tea, not a health tonic. Some chai makers
also include herbs believed to provide health benefits, but be
careful, as some include herbs that have undesirable effects, such
as working as a laxative in a way that your intestinal tract
becomes dependent on them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've heard that people with AIDS or even HIV infection need
to be careful of what they eat. Careful of what?
</P>
<P>
   A: Although food poisoning is a risk for everyone, healthy
people can deal with small amounts of bacteria in food, while
people with AIDS or HIV infection have immune systems that have
been weakened, making them susceptible to developing serious
illness and suffering with infections that return again and again.
</P>
<P>
   Thorough cooking is vital: Poultry juices should come out clear
when pierced deeply with a fork, fish should be entirely opaque and
flake easily with a fork, and meat cooked until no longer pink
inside.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid any unpasteurized milk or cheese, and raw eggs or any
foods that contain them.
</P>
<P>
   Refrigerate leftovers right away, and thaw frozen foods in the
microwave or refrigerator only.
</P>
<P>
   At home, keep counters, sponges and towels clean, and wash
utensils and your hands with soap and hot water before and between
handling different foods.
</P>
<P>
   Raw vegetables are usually safe at home if you wash them
thoroughly, but avoid restaurant or grocery store salad bars.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
