<HEADER>
A2281 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-BBQ-RECIPES27-CO     05-26 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BBQ-RECIPES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Summer barbecues return with Memorial Day
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _
</P>
<P>
   The smoky taste of bacon and smoked cheese add to the grilled
flavor of these burgers.
</P>
<P>
   BACON AND SMOKED CHEESEBURGERS
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   6 hamburger buns
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   2 1/4 pounds ground chuck
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   12 thin slices bacon
</P>
<P>
   6 slices ( 1/4-inch thick) smoked Gouda or smoked mozzarella
</P>
<P>
   Preheat grill to high, or, if using charcoal, build a fire.
</P>
<P>
   Brush the cut sides of the buns with the butter and place cut
side down on the grill to toast. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the meat into six equal portions. Lightly wet your hands
with cold water, then form each portion into a round patty 4 inches
across. If you are not planning on cooking the burgers immediately,
place on a large plate and cover loosely with plastic wrap and
refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   Season patties with salt and pepper. Wrap each patty with 2
slices of bacon. The bacon strips should be placed perpendicular to
each other.
</P>
<P>
   Oil the grate. Grill the burgers until nicely browned, about 4
minutes. Turn with a spatula and continue grilling until browned
and cooked to taste, about 4 minutes for medium.
</P>
<P>
   Top the burgers with the cheese and let melt. Place on toasted
buns.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving: 539 calories; 31.5
g fat; 119 mg cholesterol; 576 mg sodium, plus salt to taste.
</P>
<P>
   If you fire up the grill early enough in the day, you can cook
the ``baked'' beans over indirect heat on the grill. Steve
Raichlen, author of the award winning cookbook, ``The Barbecue
Bible,'' adds some wood chips to the fire to add a smoky taste.
</P>
<P>
   It would be perfect if you also grilled the night before and had
some leftover smoked or barbecued pork or brisket and some
drippings to add to these beans. It's his optional suggestion. But
you can substitute some cubes of store-bought smoked pork chops or
ham.
</P>
<P>
   QUICK AND SMOKY BAKED BEANS
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 to 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces bacon, cut into slivers
</P>
<P>
   2 cups finely chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon grated fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 15-ounce cans Great
</P>
<P>
   Northern beans, drained and rinsed in a colander
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup firmly packed dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup molasses
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup barbecue sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup ketchup
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon prepared mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 cups diced smoked or barbecued pork, ham or brisket
(optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon barbecued meat drippings (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Set up the grill for indirect grilling.
</P>
<P>
   If using a charcoal grill, heat to medium. If using a gas grill,
place the wood chips in a smoker box and preheat to high. When
smoke appears, reduce heat to medium.
</P>
<P>
   Place bacon in a large, heavy pot (such as a Dutch oven) and
cook over medium heat until lightly browned, about 5 minutes.
Discard all but 2 tablespoons fat. Add the onion, garlic and ginger
and cook until the vegetables are soft, about 5 minutes. Remove the
pot from the heat and stir in the beans, sugar, molasses, barbecue
sauce, ketchup, Worcestershire sauce, mustard powder, prepared
mustard, vinegar and, if using, meat and drippings. Transfer the
beans to a heatproof dish.
</P>
<P>
   If using a charcoal grill, toss the wood chips on the coals.
Place the dish on the grill, away from the flames. Cover the grill
and bake the beans until thick, about 30 minutes. Season with salt
and pepper before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving (without added
meat): 247 calories; 7 g fat; 11 mg cholesterol; 536 mg sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Grilling fruit is a novelty for Americans, but the pineapples in
the store make this an easy dessert to do while the fire is hot.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to cut time, use the prepeeled pineapples available
in most produce sections. All you have to do is slice them. Note
that the a pretrimmed pineapple will only produce five or six
slices.
</P>
<P>
   GRILLED SUGAR-DIPPED PINEAPPLE
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 to 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   1 ripe pineapple, trimmed and cored
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons unsalted butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon lime zest
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dark rum, optional
</P>
<P>
   Preheat grill to high.
</P>
<P>
   Place the melted butter in a shallow bowl. Combine the sugar,
lime zest and cinnamon in a separate bowl. Bring both to the grill,
along with the pineapple slices.
</P>
<P>
   Oil the grate. Dip each slice of pineapple first in the butter,
then in the sugar mixture, shaking off the excess. Arrange the
pineapple slices on the hot grate and grill, turning with tong
until browned and sizzling, about 5 to 8 minutes per side. Arrange
slices on a platter.
</P>
<P>
   If using the rum, warm it in a small flameproof saucepan on one
side of the grill but don't let it boil. Remove from the heat,
light a long match and ignite the rum. Pour the flaming rum over
the pineapple and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   To trim pineapple, cut off the leafy top and slice off the rind.
Slice the fruit into 8 even rounds and remove the core from each.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving: 275 calories; 13 g
fat; 33 mg cholesterol; 4 mg sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
