<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BBQ27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Memorial Day rekindles America's love affair with backyard
grilling
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Barbecue and grilling _ you'd think we'd invented
them.
</P>
<P>
   But as we ritually launch summer with the Memorial Day barbecue,
Steven Raichlen is here to set you straight.
</P>
<P>
   It's man's oldest, most universal _ and easiest _ way to cook.
</P>
<P>
   As Raichlen sees it, grilling _ which is simply cooking over an
open fire _ is what made us human.
</P>
<P>
   ``We became the first animal that cooked.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, he says, laid the foundation for community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grilling began civilization,'' he says. ``Touch the roof of
the cave with your torch and you have art. And you need language to
say `pass the salt.'''
</P>
<P>
   Anthropologists might argue, but not with his conclusion that
the Western Hemisphere put a different spin on the age-old cooking
technique. In the Americas, people also barbecue. The difference is
food that is highly spiced and long cooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smoke cooking originated in the Western Hemisphere,'' he says,
and that's why it's an icon of American culture.
</P>
<P>
   If you hadn't guessed by now, Raichlen is on his way to
producing a new book. His first, ``The Barbecue Bible,'' (Workman,
$27.95) focused on grilling and barbecuing in the six, mostly
tropical ``barbecue zones'' that ring the planet. He spent three
years and visited 25 countries as he gathered recipes. Now he's
researching the evolution of barbecue in this country.
</P>
<P>
   In most of what Raichlen calls the world's barbecue belt,
grilling is a year-round, daily activity, often out of necessity.
In the United States, except for the South, it is seasonal.
</P>
<P>
   And the season is about to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Conveniently, Raichlen was in town to promote ``The Barbecue
Bible,'' which recently won a James Beard Association award as best
book on a single subject. But he'll be home for the holiday, and
he'll be at the grill like most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   It is the coincidence of the date, now the last Monday in May,
that accounts for the American penchant to pull out the grill for
the weekend party. Simply, it is the beginning of summer fun.
Unlike Thanksgiving and Christmas, there are no ritual foods,
though in this part of the country hamburgers and steaks on the
grill are synonymous with summer.
</P>
<P>
   And while Raichlen's book covers international barbecue, his
family Memorial Day menu is strictly American.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a rib day, it's a chicken day, it's a burger day.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, consider a menu that starts with burgers that
benefit from the additional smoky flavor of bacon and smoked
cheese. Raichlen, who lives in Florida, adds grilled corn. While
ours isn't fresh from the field, Florida supersweet corn is
available here. Or fix his barbecued baked beans, cooked on the
grill and flavored with smoke from wood chips. Later in the season,
you can do as he does and add some leftover barbecued meat and
drippings to the beans.
</P>
<P>
   And for dessert, stay at the grill and fix grilled sugar-dipped
pineapple. It's fine for kids, but can be flamed with rum for
adults.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
