A2283 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-IMPROMPTU27-COX     05-26 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-IMPROMPTU27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Got a minute? Throw a partyBy Kitty Crider
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ What's happening: Party!
</P>
<P>
   Date: Tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Address: Your place.
</P>
<P>
   While impromptu parties can strike the same fear as a root canal
in some people, for others it is as fearless as shopping for shoes
or logging onto the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, where casual is king, the spur-of-the moment
gathering _ be it same day or next-day _ gets a warm reception from
hosts and guests alike, whether it is sausages tossed on the grill,
a potluck or cheeses and olives picked up on the way home from
work.
</P>
<P>
   The key is to keep it simple. It can be paper plates and
plasticware or pottery and fresh flowers and still be surprisingly
effortless.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Smith, a native Austinite who entertains weekly, certainly
makes it look that way as she goes the fresh flower route. On a
recent afternoon, this assistant manager at Pottery Barn hit
Central Market about 4 p.m., and with $100 and less than an hour of
shopping, she put together a cocktail party for six that could
double for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping with only a general grocery list in her head, she
always selects items that look fresh, interesting and fit the
tastes of her guests. ``I know I want some cheese, some fruit, some
vegetables, some breads, some wine ...'' Her voice trailed off as
she checked out a selection of prepared dips, consulted a store
wine steward and scooped up olives and other munchies.
</P>
<P>
   By 6 p.m. the food was arranged on the table and she was
lighting candles: cute little tea lights in pewter holders, tall
tapers in candle sticks of staggered heights and colors. The
candles definitely are an optional touch, she says, but they add
style to even an impromptu party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pick your colors _ the things you have at home _ and decorate
around them,'' she suggests. Use casual decorations, simple bar
arrangements, flowers (the three-bunches-for-$10 kind) dropped into
vases with a minimum of arranging. Buy prepared food or make a
frozen fruit dessert the night before if you have time or have
planned that far ahead.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing the menu, dare to gamble and try some new cheeses,
breads, wines or recipes. It makes the party more fun for everyone
and keeps it from being predictable. Guests will hint to come back.
So, can you make it tonight?
</P>
<P>
   Fall back on these ideas for quick entertaining
</P>
<P>
   _ Take a solid plastic tote to the store for your flowers. When
you get home pour water in it until you can get the flowers into
vases. The same tote can be filled with ice and drinks and taken to
the park or lake.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use a colorful cachepot to hold napkins and silverware.
</P>
<P>
   _ Scatter fern fronds on a plain white cloth to give a summer
feel.
</P>
<P>
   _ Innovative use of a salad bowl set: In the large bowl, place a
smaller bowl upside down. Place a second small bowl right side up
on top of the upside-down one, using poster stickum to secure. Fill
small bowl with olives or nibbles, the larger bowl with crackers or
bread slices.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mix old and new: grandmother's glass plates with contemporary
bowls or flatware.
</P>
<P>
   Frozen Fruit Dessert
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 to 2 cups mixed fresh fruit (berries, peeled and chopped
peaches or mangos)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup Chambord (black raspberry liqueur) or orange liqueur
</P>
<P>
   2 cups vanilla yogurt
</P>
<P>
   Combine fruits with liqueur and macerate for 30 minutes,
stirring frequently. (Can macerate overnight.) Gently fold in
yogurt. Place in an 8-by-4-inch loaf pan. Freeze overnight. To
unmold, dip pan into bowl or sink of warm water until exterior of
dessert softens slightly. Turn upside down on a plate or tray and
unmold. Cut into slices. Serve garnished with additional berries,
if desired. Serves 8 to 10. This is a colorful refreshing dessert,
not overly sweet. _ Sue Smith
</P>
<P>
   Grilling and impromptu entertaining are as natural a combo as
beans and rice. And that's how Larry and Diane Lugo, owners of the
Mane Tamers hair salons, like to entertain on the spur of the
moment. Run by H-E-B and get some Taylor picnic links, borracho
beans, the makings for a Frito salad and a watermelon. Fire up the
grill.
</P>
<P>
   If son Levi is home from Texas Tech, they will call ahead and
have him start the Spanish rice and cook the beans from scratch.
Guests often join Larry on the patio while he grills the sausages
and burgers. ``We talk and visit and grill at the same time,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Diane stirs up a barbecue sauce and puts together the
Frito salad, ``one of our favorites,'' says the mother of three,
also a hairdresser.
</P>
<P>
   Their party strategy couldn't be easier:
</P>
<P>
   _ Use paper plates and plastic forks and cups.
</P>
<P>
   _ Serve yourself.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sit down and enjoy being with your family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   _ If someone gets up for seconds, offer to bring for others.
</P>
<P>
   Frito Salad
</P>
<P>
   1 head iceberg lettuce, washed, cored and torn into pieces
</P>
<P>
   2 tomatoes, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 avocados, peeled, pitted and chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 cups Fritos, crushed lightly
</P>
<P>
   Oil and vinegar dressing to taste
</P>
<P>
   Toss all ingredients, adding dressing to taste. Serves 8.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of help from your friends
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Sheree Rabe is a big believer in the no-fuss potluck
party. ``I do nothing to get ready for a party but get a casserole
or ham and a manicure.''
</P>
<P>
   Her guests bring the rest: the salads, the sides, the desserts,
even ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, that is fun _ getting to try new things. And if I have
a good time, I feel they do, too,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   For a large party, with a little more lead time, she always
books live music, one of her favorite ingredients for successful
entertaining, and certainly an Austin-flavored one.
</P>
<P>
   Rabe says entertaining is one way of getting her life back on
track. Her husband Jimmy, the cook in the family, was killed in a
traffic accident a year and a half ago. One of her challenges has
been to learn to entertain differently without him. That's where
good friends, who bring good food, make for a good party.
</P>
<P>
   Casual cocktail menu
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Brie with red grapes, Gala apple slices
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Salsa cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parmesan crisps (Just Croutons)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fresh mozzarella and yellow and red tomatoes, sliced
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Plain water crackers (Carr )
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sliced baguette, rye party bread
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Marinated black and green olives
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kalamata Olive Hummus (Tom's)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Blueberries, strawberries, blackberries
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sauvignon blanc (Villa Maria)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Red wine (Santa Cristina)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Microbrew beer, optional
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Vanilla tea (Taylors of Harrogate) or mango tea
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Frozen fruit dessert
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
