<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2298 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SC-HOMEMADE-CD-ART-NY     05-26 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-HOMEMADE-CD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SEMI-PROS THRIVE ON HOMEMADE CD'S AND PRIZES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: This story was previously skedded as SC-BOOKS.) 
(Eds.: Please note that EQ in parentheses has been used in the 2nd,
5th, 9th and 16th graf instead of the equal sign, which is
non-transmittable to some newspaper systems.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPARTANBURG, S.C. _ It is unlikely that a local string bean
named Baker Maultsby will be catapulted to international celebrity
by the songs about Wal-Marts, high school delinquents and
greasy-food joints that he recorded with a friend in his childhood
bedroom here.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if there is anything to be gleaned from Maultsby's
homemade CD, ``Bingo (EQ) Sin,'' and from the surprisingly robust
literary life in this mill town turned boom town, it is how
permeable the line can be these days between brand-name culture and
semi-professional culture.
</P>
<P>
   And if Maultsby seems to prefer the cholesterol at Hall's Grill,
which recently burned down in nearby Una, to the four Wal-Marts
around the area, his story is a reminder of how technology and
modern marketing can enliven local culture even as it threatens to
homogenize or extinguish it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I compare what we do with the way small presses can give an
unfiltered version of art, like Ferlinghetti and the Beat poets of
the '50s and '60s at City Lights,'' said Peter Cooper, co-writer of
most of the quirky songs he and Maultsby recorded in that house on
the Wofford College campus, where Maultsby's father is vice
president for academic affairs. ``I'm not sure what it says about
us that Allen Ginsberg came up with `Howl' and we came up with
`Fatback and Egg on Bun.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bingo (EQ) Sin,'' which bills itself as ``Direct from the
oddly evolving South,'' is the tiniest of minnows in the vast
cultural sea. Maultsby and Cooper, both 29, both former teachers
and both now journalists, recorded their songs on Cooper's Alesis
eight-track machine. It is a far cry from today's 64-track
recordings, but with adroit professional massaging at Monkey Finger
Studios in Nashville, Tenn., they recorded, packaged and made cover
and liner art for 1,000 copies at a cost of $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't know it's not a real record,'' Maultsby said
proudly.
</P>
<P>
   The songs have the texture of wry Southern fiction by someone
like Clyde Edgerton or Lewis Nordan and the amiably woozy mix of
country and rock loosely described as alternative country. No
Depression magazine, the bible of alt-country, praised the album as
``a witty, dead-on portrait of an Old South region struggling to
accommodate such modern abominations as theme restaurants,
superstore chains and urban sprawl.''
</P>
<P>
   But Maultsby, who has the earnest air of a small-town preacher,
sees the songs as a reportorial glimpse of a landscape that's one
part Old South funk, one part strip mall clunk and one part a
modern mix of the two, like the highway billboard near the BMW
plant on I-85 reading, ``Jesus: Coming to a Soul Near You.''
</P>
<P>
   The album's anthem is probably the first song, ``Four
Wal-Marts.''
</P>
<P>
   We got four Wal-Marts
</P>
<P>
   In the tricounty area
</P>
<P>
   An outlet mall
</P>
<P>
   It's bargain hysteria
</P>
<P>
   A new Burger King so our kids get jobs
</P>
<P>
   We don't need you big city snobs.
</P>
<P>
   It's small town America.
</P>
<P>
   The title song, ``Bingo (EQ) Sin,'' pines for the days before
legalized gambling when ``people used to know that bingo is a
sin.'' ``The Taco Belle'' is about a favored waitress at the
Monterrey Mexican Restaurant here. ``Pee Dee Man'' is about South
Carolina's humble Pee Dee River region (``You can keep BMW, I'm a
Pee Dee man''), and ```Ab Can Do It'' is a tribute to a local
sociology professor and reptile expert, Ab Abercrombie.
</P>
<P>
   The songs are not likely to jump to the top of the charts, but
the record has had some success. It has found a distributor, Redeye
Distribution in Chapel Hill, N.C., and it is sold by a worldwide
mail order company in California, Miles of Music. Maultsby has
played at clubs in Nashville and elsewhere and once sang ``Four
Wal-Marts'' in Atlanta with Robbie Fulks, an alt-country big timer.
And he hears from a radio station and a stray fan here and there.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is kind of cool,'' Maultsby said as he drove along the
nightmare sprawl of Interstate 85 between Greenville and
Spartanburg. ``I got a letter from a guy in, I think, Belgium, who
has a radio show and had been playing it. He asked us to send a
picture and whatever releases we have, which, of course, are
none.''
</P>
<P>
   They have a Web site, www.bakermaultsby.com, and are even
preparing to print more records.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we must have lost some,'' Maultsby said. ``We're down
to our last couple of boxes.''
</P>
<P>
   John Lane, a local poet, Wofford College writer in residence and
a co-writer for two songs on the album, said the notion that real
culture is the sole product of mass marketers like Random House or
Sony Records is relatively new.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go back to the modernists at the turn of the century,'' he
said. ``Ezra Pound and T.S. Eliot made their reputations on books
with editions of 1,000 or so.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, what's most striking about ``Bingo (EQ) Sin'' is how it
dovetails with the active literary life in Spartanburg, a town that
has never quite matched the aspirations of the boosters who in 1888
billed it as ``emphatically the gateway to the Western World.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 Lane and two journalists, Gary Henderson and Betsy
Wakefield Teter, formed the nonprofit Hub City Writers Project to
persuade local writers to write about Spartanburg to foster a sense
of place in the face of galloping sprawl and suburbanization.
</P>
<P>
   Their first book, ``Hub City Anthology,'' personal essays by two
dozen writers and artists, sold 2,000 copies in six months. Cooper
wrote an ambitious book on the town's musical history. Their next,
``Hub City Christmas,'' sold 3,000 copies in less than six weeks.
Last month Independent Publisher magazine named another of their
books, ``New Southern Harmonies,'' 1998's best short-fiction
collection in North America.
</P>
<P>
   Hub City's latest is a collection of radio commentaries with the
title ``The Best of Radio Free Bubba.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that Radio Free Bubba or ``Fatback and Egg on
Bun'' is ``The Love Song of J. Alfred Prufrock.'' And sometimes _
think opera, classical music or ballet _ the brand-name cultural
product is just plain better.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a reminder that local artists and communities have the
access to printing and electronic technologies to play in the
larger leagues. Hub City, of course, has its own Web site at
www.hubcity.org.
</P>
<P>
   And there are areas where smaller can be better, like the
Americana or alternative country scene, where the most admired
artists, like Jim Lauderdale, Fulks, Kieran Kane, Kevin Welch, Dave
Olney, Steve Earle and, until recently, Lucinda Williams tend not
to be played on sound-alike country radio or signed to major
labels.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bob Dylan came along today, he's not getting a recording
contract,'' said Cooper, making no claims to being Bob Dylan.
``They'd say, you're ugly, you sing funny and your songs have too
many verses. Technology can be a dangerous thing. It can suck the
life out of music. But it can also allow people who don't have a
lot of money to get in the game today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 1849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
