<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2301 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-U.S.-PRIVACY-8     05-26 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-U.S.-PRIVACY-805&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPE AND U.S. ARE STILL AT ODDS OVER PRIVACY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ After months of negotiations that had
appeared headed for success, the United States and the European
Union have veered away from each other in a dispute over privacy
protection that could disrupt trans-Atlantic electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   European authorities continue to insist that the United States
fails to provide enough consumer protection from companies that
collect and often resell personal information.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is important, because the European Union issued a
directive last year that in theory prohibits companies from
transmitting personal information to countries that do not offer
``adequate'' privacy protection.
</P>
<P>
   No one has tried to enforce the prohibition yet, and several
European countries have not even passed national laws to carry it
out.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue has alarmed many companies, because the directive
applies to activities as varied as airline reservations, banking
and online shopping.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials, led by the Department of Commerce, have been
trying to persuade European officials to accept a system under
which American companies would adopt a code of good behavior and be
allowed to regulate themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, both sides seemed intent on reaching a
compromise in time for a summit between President Clinton and
European leaders in Cologne on June 21.
</P>
<P>
   But as the negotiators prepare for a key meeting in Brussels,
Belgium, on Friday, officials on both sides say the discussions
have bogged down. If they fail to reach agreement on Friday, their
chances of doing so before the summit are low.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are right back to the old story that they want us to invent
a regime that looks like theirs,'' said David Aaron, undersecretary
of commerce for international trade, in a telephone interview.
``Well, we aren't going to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, European officials say they remain open to a
compromise in the next few weeks. ``I can tell you there are
problems, but the gap is consistently narrowing,'' said John Mogg,
the European Commission's director general for financial services
and the top European negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few days, experts on both sides have become
skeptical about a deal. While U.S. officials complain that Europe
is trying to impose ``data czars'' on the United States, European
officials charge that U.S. proposals would water down their
protections to the point of meaninglessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans still have the illusion that they can change the
directive, but they can't,'' said Spiros Simitis, a law professor
at Johann Wolfgang Goethe University in Frankfurt and an adviser to
the European Commission on the privacy directive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not bananas we are talking about,'' Simitis added.
``This is about what we consider a fundamental claim to privacy,
and therefore there is a limit to compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the dispute are deep differences about the need
for governments to protect privacy, particularly when it comes to
the use of personal information as a marketing tool.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union's directive requires that companies that
collect personal information, whether through routine business
transactions or through tracking the sites a person visits on the
Internet, must fully disclose what they will do with the
information and give people a chance to say no.
</P>
<P>
   It also requires that companies give people access to data files
about them and give them the right to correct errors.
</P>
<P>
   In principle, U.S. officials say they agree completely. But they
also argue that any system needs to be flexible, and they have
adamantly rejected demands to set up quasi-public enforcement
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. proposals call for giving companies ``safe harbor''
from the directive if they publicly embrace the European principles
themselves. Companies could join self-regulatory associations, such
as the Better Business Bureau, or simply make formal public
commitments to the principles on their own.
</P>
<P>
   European officials appear to be divided among themselves.
Officials close to the negotiations said that Mogg and others at
the European Commission in Brussels were generally satisfied with
the American approach and eager to reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But many individual governments, including Germany, were more
hostile. Many insisted that companies submit to some independent
regulatory association that could investigate complaints from
consumers and enforce changes.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron proposed that companies simply agree to cooperate with
European regulators, but European negotiators have rejected the
idea so far.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are also squabbling over how much time companies
should have in order to comply with the European rules. The United
States is pushing for about two years, and the European Union wants
to offer only six months.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As a practical matter, many companies are trying to shield
themselves by signing privacy contracts between their U.S. and
European branches. Citibank and American Express have had such
contracts for years, and many others are following suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``As things stand at present, we have such different standards
of privacy and data protection that it's very difficult to see them
reaching an agreement soon,'' said Robert Bond, a lawyer in London
who advises companies on information law.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you make the best of a bad job?'' he added. ``Business
has got to concoct its own solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   But many lawyers, as well as Aaron, are not sure that such
internal contracts will keep companies out of trouble. The privacy
laws can be interpreted differently in different countries, and the
directive specifically allows individuals to sue companies on their
own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
