<HEADER>
A2308 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAZZ-IMPRESARIOS-ART-     05-26 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAZZ-IMPRESARIOS-ART-3TAKES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE RIVALS, TWO JAZZ IMPRESARIOS AGREE TO DISAGREE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30)  
 (af)  
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics)George Wein and Michael Dorf _ impresarios of this
year's JVC Jazz Festival and the Bell Atlantic Jazz Festival
respectively _ have been butting heads for 11 years. In 1954 Wein
started the Newport Jazz Festival, which became the paradigm for
outdoor music events. After moving through several different
sponsors, it became the JVC festival in 1984. Dorf put on his first
jazz festival (called ``What Is Jazz?'') at the Knitting Factory,
his club in lower Manhattan, in 1988, scheduling it to compete with
the JVC concerts uptown. A cordial relationship developed, but it
broke down in 1997, when Dorf expanded, found a major sponsor
(Texaco), and called his giant festival the New York Jazz Festival.
This was the student rather stridently pulling rank on the teacher,
and a period of bad blood followed.
</P>
<P>
   Jazz is too small for a brand war like this, and detente was
probably inevitable. Friendly again, they're both committed to
making New York a city overrun with jazz each June, resolving that
too much at once is the best way to draw fans to the concerts. This
year, Bell Atlantic Jazz (the festival has a new sponsor) runs from
June 3 to 13 and JVC Jazz from June 14 to 27.
</P>
<P>
   As the head of Festival Productions, Wein, 73, produced 37 music
festivals around the world in 1998, including the New Orleans Jazz
and Heritage Festival; he almost sold the company to Black
Entertainment Television last year, but the deal did not go
through. As the CEO of Knit Media, Dorf, 37, runs a club and a
record label, and plans to open new branches of the Knitting
Factory in Los Angeles and Berlin. In a joint interview, at The New
York Times, the first they had ever done, they discussed a range of
issues, including their different theories on how to reach the
current jazz audience. Following are excerpts from their
conversation.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ben Ratliff. George, you've been a concert producer for nearly
50 years. Is there anything you could possibly have learned from
the ascension of Michael Dorf?
</P>
<P>
   George Wein. There are things happening every day and every year
that I cannot keep up with it for many reasons. I can't understand
the new technology and things like that, and I watch what he's done
with the Internet. I've given instructions now to my people about
getting sponsors for a festival, tell them we will get the artist
to sign for an appearance on the Internet as part of the deal. And
give them a national image. I mean, that's something I never did
before.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Dorf. Jazz is perfectly suited for the Internet because
it is a little more intelligent. It's not a mass-pop type of music.
The Internet allows us to find those niches, and when you can
aggregate all those audiences together, 75 people in Memphis and 32
of them in Stuttgart and 100 in Singapore, now you start building
up a really large audience that can come to jazz.
</P>
<P>
   WEIN. But I would never put a whole concert on the Internet.
Because, conceivably, it would get economically unfeasible with
programs that I do. If I ask Herbie Hancock to give me an Internet
program, he's going to want to be paid double, but we can't afford
that unless you got a sponsor paying for the whole thing. The basic
difference between what Michael and I do is economics. He has a
place where he can put people in; he uses _ and I don't mean this
as derogatory _ non-union musicians, young musicians. Every time I
present something I have to rent a hall. That affects the total
economic structure, and when I'm using Carnegie and Avery Fisher, I
have no freedom. I have to charge $40, $50, $60 for tickets because
the costs of hall and advertising is $50,000 before you pay your
artist. But last year was one of the best years we've had. This
year we're way ahead of last year. Ticket sales took off.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How do you account for that?
</P>
<P>
   WEIN. I think there's a lot of money around. People are making
money in the market. We broke all records at New Orleans this year.
There's an economic spirit in the air with the middle upper class.
They're spending money and going out. Restaurants are packed.
Everybody's doing more business.
</P>
<P>
   Q. In theory, your festivals reflect different attitudes about
what jazz is. People in general think of JVC as the mainstream jazz
festival and Bell Atlantic as the alternative. Is that still a fair
assumption?
</P>
<P>
   DORF. We certainly have had a much more open definition of what
jazz is. Most of that is about trying to expand the audience. When
a band like Medeski, Martin and Wood or any of that ``Grateful
Jazz'' genre is able to turn people on to Ornette Coleman or Sonny
Rollins _ because they cover a particular song or they invite
(those older musicians) on (stage) the way the Grateful Dead used
to have Ornette or David Murray come on to the stage _ to me that's
accomplishing a really great objective, which is turning a lot of
young people on to the music.
</P>
<P>
   WEIN. See, newness is something I don't think you can create.
New things happen in spite of everything. The minute you say I have
to be different, you have a problem. You ARE different if you are a
great artist.
</P>
<P>
   Q. And yet, Michael, your only concert at Town Hall this year is
Grover Washington Jr., who is more mainstream than mainstream. How
do you square that with any sort of alternative profile?
</P>
<P>
   DORF. Opening up for Grover is Bill Ware, a great downtown
vibraphone player who never will have an opportunity, unless we
provided this one, to play in front of 1,000 or 1,400 more
conservative jazz fans. So, getting the Grover fans turned on to
some of the stuff that we're doing downtown fits our objective. We
want to have both ends of the spectrum. All this stuff will go into
a jazz bin at Tower Records.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   WEIN. I went down to see John Zorn and Dave Douglas, and they
said, ``Well, what do you think _ isn't it something different?'' I
said, ``It's nothing different, it's music.'' I said, ``What is
different about music?'' I wanted to play them this year, uptown.
</P>
<P>
   Q. George, you've said that The New York Times made Michael Dorf
_ and that the paper made him at your expense. But a lot of
musicians feel that they made Michael Dorf, or at least that they
made what's widely regarded as a ``Knitting Factory esthetic.'' In
1997, a gathering of musicians, under the banner of the Noise
Action Coalition, voiced their concern that they weren't being paid
enough in the festival. So, Michael, you negotiated with the NAC,
and last year the fee went up to $100 per musician for a group of
up to six players; this year it's $200 per musician. This is a
great victory for musicians; does it make it harder to put on a
festival?
</P>
<P>
   DORF. Yes, it does. It makes it harder to put on as much music
as we used to. We have a budget, we have a realistic pie to work
from, and you can only cut the pie so many ways.
</P>
<P>
   WEIN. I can't accept that. Because I'm a musician, and I know
what it is to go out and earn a living playing music. I don't set a
price for the musicians when I pay them. I negotiate with each
musician on each individual deal. If I can't pay him and he wants
ridiculous money, I don't pay him.
</P>
<P>
   DORF. We had a difficult situation. The Knitting Factory has a
very symbiotic relationship with the music community. They all use
it as a place to improve their profile. And we always had a deal in
which the artist made 75 percent of the money that came in the
door. It was a relationship that worked very well and continues to
work well at the club. If 10 people come and pay 10 bucks, it's
$100 at the door, they get $75. And they understand I shouldn't be
going into my pocket to pay them $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   WEIN. Michael, it was the best thing that could happen.
</P>
<P>
   Q. That the musicians complained?
</P>
<P>
   WEIN. Yeah, it was the best thing. It brought you into a reality
of a situation that you're going to have to live with the rest of
your life. Because that's the reality: musicians have to make a
living, have to get paid.
</P>
<P>
   DORF. I don't think we're going to have the financial complaints
from the musicians anymore. I think that was a hiccup in our
growth. In terms of having this community problem, I don't think
we'll see that. It is a partnership, and if there's not pure open
communication, whether it's a one-on-one relationship with your
wife or significant other or in this case a partnership with the
whole community _
</P>
<P>
   WEIN. Michael, you are not a partner with the musicians. You are
the enemy. You are the exploiter. As you grow, that is the image
you will have with musicians. You are the Man. And the Man can
never be a partner.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You both have extremely difficult tasks: trying to sell
tickets to New York jazz audiences, who have seen everything and
regularly get a chance to see most jazz groups. Even though this is
the jazz capital of the world, is it harder to put on a successful
jazz festival in New York than in Montreal and Umbria, to name two
particularly good ones?
</P>
<P>
   WEIN. You know our problem? Not that the New York audience has
seen everything. You've seen everything. How many times can you
review Sonny Rollins? But the only time people won't come to see
Sonny Rollins is when they read that he's not doing anything new.
</P>
<P>
   DORF. I see it as a challenge for us. To put on something that
the critics haven't seen before.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Leaving the question of innovation aside, because it's so
hard to define, should jazz festivals offer a reflection of the
current state of jazz?
</P>
<P>
   WEIN. I think they should offer a reflection of jazz, which
includes the current, which includes the past. Why should my
people, who are 50, 60, 70 years old, be denied hearing Benny
Goodman's music and things like that because they don't reflect the
current state of jazz?
</P>
<P>
   Q. Every year you're competing with each other to book artists.
</P>
<P>
   WEIN. The only competition Michael gives me is in the press.
I've no feeling of competition with him for my concert stuff.
</P>
<P>
   DORF. But there's overlap on some programming.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Cassandra Wilson or Medeski, Martin and Wood, these are acts
that you could both play successfully.
</P>
<P>
   WEIN. I think we will get closer as we go along. For instance,
last year, I didn't want my artists appearing on his award program
(the Jazz Awards, produced by Knit Media). This year, I don't care.
</P>
<P>
   Q. As I remember, part of the problem was that you were going to
receive one of the awards, and you didn't want to receive an award
from Michael.
</P>
<P>
   WEIN. I didn't think Michael was in the position to give me an
award. I should be giving Michael an award. I still don't think
(Knit Media's sponsorship of the Jazz Awards) is right. You know,
I'll go along with it because you're doing it. But I think it
should be done by an institution of some sort, the Smithsonian or
something.
</P>
<P>
   DORF. And I wouldn't disagree with that. The only reason we
decided to do it was because no one else was doing it.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Michael, the message I've been hearing from you is that
unless jazz can combine with other forms of music, it's not really
going to find an audience.
</P>
<P>
   DORF. No, I think you need to bring new people into the room to
listen to it. We have to somehow figure out what that 13-year-old
or 12-year-old is listening to and how can they make a connection
between Chuck D and Ornette Coleman or Don Byron or what Steve
Coleman or Greg Osby's been doing with hip-hop.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   WEIN. I agree with Michael in this respect. I have always
believed that you must put on more than just pure jazz. And the
only way jazz will ever die is if the musicians stop playing jazz.
Jazz can never be more than a minority music. Everybody cannot like
the highest quality things. But if we cultivate that minority _
we're a country of 250 million people. If you have 2 percent of
them that like jazz, you've got 5 million jazz fans. You've got to
cultivate those 5 million jazz fans. You can't look for the 98
percent. Forget them, they're going to go out for the Rolling
Stones or the Beatles, or whatever it is. But we need a Miles
Davis. We need a Dave Brubeck. We need somebody that sells records.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is there anybody on the horizon that could do that?
</P>
<P>
   WEIN. That I don't know. I tell all groups, all musicians: Stop
making a different record every time you play. Get a group and work
on a sound. It's all about a sound that people remember, not how
great you blow. And that's the way you must establish identity. The
Modern Jazz Quartet stayed selling out concerts, right until the
time they quit. That group sound is what sells jazz; the greatness
of the music has to be within the structure of a group.
</P>
<P>
   DORF. There were 35,000 new CDs released in 1998, and that was
not the case four years ago, so there's limited shelf space in
retail. There's limited air space to play these on the radio. Why
I'm pushing on-line is that you now have virtual shelf space. You
have virtual dials, and you can program your jazz to your computer
and listen to whatever you want. And if you look at the sales on
Amazon.com or CD Now, you'll see jazz is now represented by about
10 percent of sales. So when you really can democratize the ability
of people to listen to the music that they want to, jazz is going
to have a much higher market share than it currently does.
</P>
<P>
   WEIN. He's absolutely right. I don't know what he's talking
about, but he's right. If I knew what he was talking about, he
might be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Michael, George has criticized certain aspects of your
festival.
</P>
<P>
   WEIN. I haven't criticized; I've commented on it.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is there anything about George's festival that you would do
differently?
</P>
<P>
   DORF. The only suggestion I've made in the past was to have more
unknown opening acts on the stage.
</P>
<P>
   WEIN. It keeps people away.
</P>
<P>
   DORF. It's hard, it's a lot easier to say it than it is to
actually implement it. And I see that in my own event. But I really
force that. I try and have one unknown name on every big bill, and
give that artist an opportunity for exposure.
</P>
<P>
   WEIN. There is no question that he would take a lot of things I
do and keep them and take a lot of things I do and change them.
Because he is what he is. And that's why he and I have built up an
affinity. Because I recognize that this kid doesn't stop. Look, I
think Michael and I are going to be doing a lot of things together
in the future if I last long enough. We understand each other.
</P>
</TEXT>
