<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Thursday, May 27, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Susan Leh at the Daily News, (818) 713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTHY-COLUMN (LOS ANGELES) _ Three girls have won the
all-city synchronized swimming competition, even though they don't
have a pool to practice in. The represented Cleveland High School,
which hasn't had a pool since it became unsafe during El Nino. The
practiced on dry land and backyard pools _ and still beat teams
with pools from around the city. By Dennis McCarthy. (Will move in
the ``a'' national and ``n'' state news files.)
</P>
<P>
   ART-THEFT (Los Angeles) _ The former director of counseling at
UCLA was indicted on charges of stealing an original oil painting
by 19th century American impressionist Arthur Wesley Dow. Jane
Crawford allegedly stole ``Frost Flowers, Ipswich 1889'' from the
university in 1994 and sold it for $200,000, through a middleman,
to a New York art gallery. By Troy Anderson. (Will move in the
``a'' national and ``n'' state news files.)
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-DEADLINE (Los Angeles) _ Los Angeles County government
will miss a deadline it agreed to, some two years ago, to set up a
process for welfare payments to be sent to bank accounts by
``direct deposit.'' By Douglas Haberman. (Will move in the ``a''
national and ``n'' state news files.)
</P>
<P>
   AIRPORT-RESOLUTION (Los Angeles) _ With Glendale now on record
approving a curfew and the airport commission proposing a downsized
terminal, the stage is set for a resolution of the longstanding
logjam in the airport's bid to move and expand its terminal. By Lee
Condon. (Will move in the ``n'' state news file.)
</P>
