<SLUG> BC-R-LAST-SUPPER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER A 20-YEAR CLEANUP, A BRIGHTER, CLEARER `LAST SUPPER'
EMERGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING for all needing.)   (bl)  
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ After 20 years of painstaking chipping, dabbing
and scrubbing, Leonardo da Vinci's ``Last Supper'' is at long last
restored and ready to be shown Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It is the public's first chance in 20 years to see the painting
_ one of the world's most famous and most copied artworks _
unencumbered by scaffolding, easels and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   If Michelangelo's newly restored Sistine Chapel shocked visitors
with its vibrant, even garish colors, Leonardo's masterpiece may
prove just as startling for different reasons. Stripped of
centuries-old retouchings, grime, grease and dust, ``The Last
Supper'' has regained astonishing light and clarity as well as
details of the banquet food that had long been forgotten. But it is
also mottled with large beige patches that signal just how much of
the original art work is lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Last Supper,'' commissioned by Ludovico il Moro, a
Milanese duke, in 1494 and completed in 1498, is a work of art as
famous for its fragility as for its artistic power. Leonardo used
an experimental technique to paint it on a damp wall of the
refectory of Santa Maria delle Grazie, and it began deteriorating
and inviting touch-ups almost as soon as it was completed.
</P>
<P>
   This latest restoration, the seventh since 1726, may not be the
last, but in Italy, it is being heralded as a milestone of
boldness, patience and craftsmanship. ``This is the most important
restoration of the century,'' Italian Culture Minister Giovanna
Melandri told reporters this week. ``No one can say any longer that
this is not Leonardo.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics, mostly in the United States, Britain and France,
vehemently disagree. Jacques Franck, an art restoration consultant
to the Louvre and the Armand Hammer Center for Leonardo Studies at
UCLA, argues that it was a mistake to remove most of the previous
restorations, as there was too little left of the original work to
have esthetic meaning. He last saw the painting in 1995 when it was
three-fourths completed. ``Why remove historical paintings if you
don't retrieve anything? Sixteenth, 17th- and 18th-century
restorers were faithful to what they saw at the time,'' he said.
``This is not Leonardo, it is merely fragments of bottom layers of
the underlying original.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even hundreds of years ago, art lovers were complaining that
``The Last Supper'' was so badly damaged and painted over that it
had lost its soul. It depicts the moment at which Christ tells his
Apostles that one of them will betray him before dawn.
</P>
<P>
   In 1566, architect Giorgio Vasari complained that all he could
see on the wall was a ``blinding spot.'' Charles Dickens, who
viewed ``The Last Supper'' in 1845, was more dismayed. ``Apart from
the damage it has sustained from damp, decay or neglect,'' he
wrote, ``it has been so retouched upon, and repainted, and that, so
clumsily, that many of the heads are, now, positive deformities.''
</P>
<P>
   Hailed as a masterpiece as soon it was completed, ``The Last
Supper'' was treated with far less reverence in later centuries. In
the 17th century, a door under the painting was enlarged to ease
passage from the refectory to the kitchens, cutting off Christ's
legs and feet. Napoleon's invading troops used the refectory as a
stable and amused themselves by throwing bricks at the Apostles'
heads. In 1943 an Allied bomb fell on the building, causing the
roof and one wall to collapse. The wall on which ``The Last
Supper'' was painted was buttressed by sandbags and miraculously
escaped intact.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1970s, art historians all over the world were concerned
that what was left of ``The Last Supper'' could soon crumble
altogether under the ravages of neglect, humidity and pollution.
The Italian authorities decided to undertake a major restoration,
and in 1978 selected Pinin Brambilla Barcilon, a respected art
restorer, to direct the project.
</P>
<P>
   Like the wall painting she worked on, Mrs. Brambilla's
appearance has lightened _ her once dark brown hair is now
snow-white. ``It has been a slow and difficult climb that step
after step, centimeter after centimeter, fragment after fragment,
carried us to a new reading of the expressive intensity and colors
we believed had been irretrievably lost,'' she told reporters this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Leonardo, a tireless inventor, had wanted to work slowly, and he
tried to paint ``The Last Supper'' as if it were a giant painting
on wood or canvas, applying tempera grassa, pigment mixed with egg
and linseed oil, to a dry plaster wall primed with lead white. The
experiment quickly proved far less durable than traditional fresco,
a rapid technique that binds color to wet plaster. In the course of
stripping away grime and glue, the restorers say they resurrected
buried elements, for example on the banquet table: rolls, finger
bowls, translucent wine glasses, a fish platter, an orange.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was what was most new and unexpected to us,'' Giuseppe
Basile, the director of Italy's Central Restoration Institute and
the restoration coordinator said. ``This still life anticipates
Caravaggio by a century.''
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, the colors were faded, brown and drowning under
coats of later artists' retouchings, as well as plaster, varnish
and even glue. Now there are rich hues of periwinkle, lapis and
turquoise.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also broad dapples of beige, a light watercolor
the restorers painted on unsalvageable areas, to cover up the most
glaring blanks, without actually repainting da Vinci's work. ``We
didn't want to create a false icon,'' Basile said. ``We tried to
suggest the image, without repainting it, and we tried to lessen
the impact of the blanks, and still make clear what is not
original.''
</P>
<P>
   Basile said that almost half of Leonardo's original work was
saved. Critics say that less than 20 percent remains. Some of the
most outspoken opponents, including James Beck, a New York-based
art historian known for his attacks on Italian restoration
techniques, complain that Italy should not have moved ahead
unilaterally with the restoration but should have first consulted a
team of international experts, as was done with the Sistine Chapel.
</P>
<P>
   Basile was unapologetic. ``Actually, we considered forming an
international committee to give us some political cover from all
the polemics,'' he said. ``Then we decided we didn't need to cover
ourselves. This may sound presumptuous, but in matters of art
restoration, Italians don't need foreign assistance; foreigners
come to us to study how it is done. The Dutch don't need help
building dikes, and Italians don't need help restoring art.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even some Italian experts say that the Milan officials acted
hastily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the restorer did the very best job she could have done
under the circumstances,'' said Maurizio Seracini, director of
diagnostic services at Editech, a high-tech art restoration
laboratory in Florence. He was consulted on the project, but only
after the decision to intervene had already been made. He added,
``The question nobody asked, let alone answered, was was it
necessary. I myself have not seen definite, scientific proof that
restoration was really needed, yet a surgeon asks not only can I
operate, but should I? Art should be no different.''
</P>
<P>
   The damage or rescue is now complete. To preserve the restored
art work, visitors will walk through a labyrinth of air-filtration
chambers that eliminate dust and pollution. They will see ``The
Last Supper'' in groups of no more than 25, by reservation only.
</P>
<P>
   Pietro Marani, a fine arts expert who also helped coordinate the
restoration, said he did not expect restorers to be called in again
in his lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hope is that it will last longer than earlier attempts.
But we aren't presumptuous enough to believe it will last forever.
Nothing lasts forever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
