<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-STATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINAL PREPARATIONS MADE FOR SHUTTLE LAUNCH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla., _ NASA made final preparations late
Wednesday for the launch of the shuttle Discovery and a crew of
seven on a supply mission to the new international space station.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery's launch from NASA's Kennedy Space Center was
scheduled for 6:49 a.m. EDT Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The flight is the first for a shuttle this year, and it will
break a 163-day hiatus, the longest since NASA's 1986 Challenger
accident caused a 32-month shutdown. The latest hiatus was prompted
by Russian financial difficulties, which have stalled the
production and launching of the new station's initial crew module.
</P>
<P>
   With a successful liftoff, Discovery should rendezvous and dock
with the first components of the new station late Friday. However,
the linkup could be delayed until Saturday if the shuttle lifts off
a few minutes later than planned.
</P>
<P>
   A shuttle crew joined the first U.S. and Russian modules last
December. The outpost will not be staffed permanently until after
the Russian crew module, also known as the service module, is
launched in late November from Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Led by commander Kent Rominger, Discovery's crew plans to
transfer nearly 2 tons of supplies and equipment into the station's
American Unity docking compartment and Russian Zarya power and
control module.
</P>
<P>
   The supplies include laptop computers, clothing and spare parts
for the first resident astronauts and cosmonauts.
</P>
<P>
   During a near seven-hour spacewalk, Discovery astronauts Dan
Barry and Tammy Jernigan plan to install small Russian and U.S.
cargo cranes on the exterior of the outpost. The cranes will be
used later to replace large power storage batteries on the station
as well as other bulky cargos.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-day mission may be extended by another day to give the
shuttle crew more time for cargo transfers, two equipment repairs
and potentially a second spacewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery crew members, Russian cosmonaut Valery Tokarev and
Canadian astronaut Julie Payette have trained to replace 18 ampere
meters in the Zarya module's solar power generation system. The
ampere meters in Zarya are not properly charging the half-dozen
batteries launched on the power module last November.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle crew also plans to repair the Unity module's
satellite communications system, a direct link between the station
and NASA's mission control center in Houston. The system faltered
in early March.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
