<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2348 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-ART-90     05-26 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-ART-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA LAUNCHES AIRSTRIKES IN KASHMIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(rm) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Indian combat jets and helicopter gunships
attacked a large guerrilla force dug into the snow-capped mountains
of Kashmir Wednesday, sharply increasing tensions in the
nuclear-armed subcontinent.
</P>
<P>
   The raids were the most serious confrontation between Pakistan
and India since the bitter rivals both exploded nuclear bombs a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Experts said the conflict would test how well the two countries
could manage such tensions now that the stakes are so much higher.
</P>
<P>
   New Delhi has charged that Pakistan is sponsoring Islamic
militants in a carefully devised land grab. The two waves of
airstrikes on Wednesday, one just after dawn and another in the
afternoon, were intended to dislodge a force of 500 to 600
well-equipped invaders who have crossed a 50-year-old cease-fire
line between India and Pakistan and taken strategic positions along
high ridges in the Himalayas, Indian military spokesmen said.
</P>
<P>
   The infiltrating force ``consists of a large number of
well-trained Afghan mercenaries and Pakistani regular army
troops,'' Indian Brig. Mohan Bhandari said at a military briefing,
claiming that Pakistan's involvement in the intrusion was obvious
from the amount of coordination and logistical support required to
sustain the operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any escalation of this conflict will be entirely the
responsibility of Pakistan,'' the brigadier said. His warning later
in the day drew a defiant response from a Pakistani military
spokesman, Brig. Rashid Quereshi, near Islamabad, who said: ``The
Pakistan armed forces reserve the right to retaliate by whatever
means are considered appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pakistanis placed their military on ``high alert.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our view is that this is serious,'' said a U.S. Embassy
official in New Delhi. ``This is not being viewed by the Indians as
another summer infiltration of the usual order. On the other hand,
I think there is a desire on the Indians' part to treat this as a
limited phenomenon _ to respond forcefully in a limited way.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, a U.S. State Department official mentioned that
India's Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee and his Pakistani
counterpart, Nawaz Sharif, have discussed the recent confrontation
by telephone. ``We encourage them to stay in touch,'' the official
said.
</P>
<P>
   The territory of Jammu and Kashmir borders both India and
Pakistan and has been the chief cause of two of the three wars the
two nations have fought since gaining their independence in 1947.
In the complicated give-and-take that accompanied the partition,
predominantly Muslim Kashmir ended up as part of predominantly
Hindu India.
</P>
<P>
   The countries were drawn into combat, and an ensuing cease-fire
divided Kashmir in two. Ever since, India has insisted the
territory is theirs while the Pakistanis argue that the Kashmiris
themselves should be allowed to choose which nation they prefer.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual for Islamic militants to cross the cease-fire
line into India, but the force that was discovered in early May was
exceptional not only for its size but also its location. The
intruders occupied a 30-mile stretch of inhospitable terrain
ordinarily abandoned to the cold and ice. They reportedly ambushed
an Indian patrol sent to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Aerial surveillance showed that the militants were dispersed
among two dozen or more well-fortified positions around the towns
of Dras and Kargil. Rather than the usual hit-and-run invaders,
these units had snowmobiles, artillery and huge stocks of supplies,
according to the Indian military.
</P>
<P>
   The operation had the earmarks of months of planning. Indeed,
the Indians say they concluded that it was likely preparations were
underway even as the two nations were engaged in promising peace
talks last February. At those meetings the prime ministers of the
two nations signed the ``Lahore Declaration'' in which they pledged
efforts to resolve the Kashmir dispute.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two weeks, the Indian army and the militants have
exchanged artillery fire. The militants hold the formidable
advantage of the high ground, a superiority the Indians themselves
have successfully enjoyed in a 15-year-long conflict with the
Pakistani army in an area around the Siachen Glacier in remote
Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side has used air power during the long Siachen
campaign. The assault with planes and helicopters Wednesday
represents an escalation in the mountain combat. The Indians say
they have been careful not to invade Pakistani air space, but the
Pakistanis said that a number of bombs landed on their side of the
cease-fire line.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1989, there has been a militant separatist movement among
India's Kashmiri Muslims _ and a massive military response to it by
India. Some estimates attribute as many as 30,000 deaths to
fighting between rebels and security forces.
</P>
<P>
   Islamic ``freedom fighters'' from several nations, especially
Afghanistan and Pakistan, have routinely entered the fray,
considering it a holy war. The Pakistani government admits to
offering these soldiers moral and political support while the
Indians claim the assistance is financial and military as well.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Pakistan's Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz denied any
knowledge of the Islamic combatants that have so concerned the
Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knows where they come from and who they are,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Here in new Delhi, such statements are largely seen as
implausible. Instead there is considerable speculation about what
the Pakistanis have been up to _ and whether forces in the military
are acting on their own or with government approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's never before been this kind of an attempt to realign
the border, which can be treated as an act of war,'' said India's
Maj. Gen. V. R. Raghavan, retired, who once commanded the army in
Kashmir and is now a respected military analyst. ``But what kind of
response did the Pakistanis expect? It defies military logic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps some Pakistanis feel emboldened by the great
equalizer. They have nuclear weapons and now they believe the
military asymmetry between the two nations is undone. But there are
limits to this dangerous game. If certain thresholds are crossed,
things can very easily get out of hand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
