<HEADER>
A2349 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBITUARY-SAVAGE-BOS &LR;      05-26 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-SAVAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REV. THOMAS SAVAGE, 51; HEADED ROCKHURST COLLEGE IN MISSOURI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rev. Thomas J. Savage of the Society of Jesus, a former
president of Rockhurst College in Kansas City, Mo., died of asthma
complicated by pneumonia May 10 in Campion Health Center in Weston,
Mass. He was 51.
</P>
<P>
   Father Savage was president of Rockhurst College, a Jesuit
school of about 3,000 students, from 1988 to 1996. During his
tenure, he opened a continued education center at the school and
acquired the National Seminars Group, a provider of education and
training programs that serves 500,000 students annually at 300
locations in the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Father Savage was an outgoing man who reached out to the
community surrounding the college's downtown campus. He acted in
school plays and was cohost of the radio call-in show ``Religion on
the Line.'' He danced every year at the annual Rockhurst Christmas
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Father Tom was a showman,'' said Rev. Patrick Rush,
vicar-general of the Catholic Diocese of Kansas City-St. Joseph at
a memorial service for Father Savage on May 18. ``His life was a
virtuoso performance of humanity, of Catholic Christian
spirituality, of Jesuit mission.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Robert Hill, minister of Community Christian Church in
Kansas City, who cohosted the radio show with Father Savage and
Rabbi Michael Zedek, called Father Savage a ``bridge-builder
between the rich and poor, the outsider and the insiders, the
Catholic and the Protestant, Kansas City and the world.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a member of the Kansas Board of Trade and cochairman of
Focus Kansas City, which created a master plan for the city.
</P>
<P>
   Father Savage studied architecture at Catholic University of
America in Washington, D.C., prior to entering the Society of Jesus
in 1967. He subsequently earned degrees in philosophy and sociology
at Boston College and a master's degree in divinity at Weston
School of Theology in Cambridge, Mass., before he was ordained to
the priesthood in 1979. He then earned a graduate degree in city
planning at the University of California, Berkeley and a doctorate
in public policy administration at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his mother, Viola, of Medford, Mass.; two brothers,
Rev. James of Cambridge and Robert of Villanova, Pa.; and three
sisters, Evelyn Ternollo of Medford and Claire Keon and Marilyn
Herrick, both of Wakefield, Mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 1932EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2351 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE27-COX     05-26 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE DRAWS DISTINCTIONS WITH BUSH ON GUN ISSUES
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Vice President Al Gore, concluding a two-day visit to
Texas on Wednesday, contrasted himself with Gov. George W. Bush on
two gun-related issues.
</P>
<P>
   Gore sided with cities wanting to sue gun manufacturers, and
opposed the expansion of laws allowing concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore did not mention Bush by name, it was clear that
the vice president intended to draw distinctions between himself
and Bush, the front-runner for the Republican nomination, on a
high-profile issue that seems to favor the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   At a discussion of school safety in a visit to Dallas's W.E.
Greiner Middle School for the Performing Arts with his wife,
Tipper, Gore unexpectedly added a new wrinkle to his recent
comments about the school shootings in Littleton, Colo., and
Conyers, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the Colorado state legislature had retreated after
Littleton from a proposal to make it easier to carry concealed
weapons, Gore said, ``I would call on leaders everywhere to
reconsider _ we don't need more concealed weapons in our malls and
our movie theaters and on our streets.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``and I don't think it's time to take steps to prevent
the kind of lawsuits that many cities are filing to protect their
citizens. I think it's time to protect schools and to protect
families and to make sure it's more difficult for children and
convicted felons and those who are unstable to gain access to
guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in his first term as governor, signed legislation allowing
Texans to carry concealed handguns. He also has opposed forcing gun
retailers to include child safety locks on the weapons they sell.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Bush indicated he would sign into law recently
enacted legislation barring local governments in Texas from suing
gun manufacturers. The legislation pre-empted discussions in
Houston about joining other cities in such suits.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to the vice president avoided any direct reference to Bush
as they spoke with reporters while traveling to Houston for a Gore
fund-raising event, his last stop on a three-day campaign trip
before returning to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if Gore included Bush when he addressed himself to
``leaders everywhere,'' Gore communications director Laura Quinn
said he was referring to ``all leaders.'' Pressed to elaborate, she
replied, ``All means all.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also called on the Republican-controlled House to approve
legislation that passed the Senate last week _ on his tie-breaking
vote _ requiring background checks on customers at gun shows. ``Now
is the time not to be silent about an issue like that,'' he said.
``Now is the time ... to make it a law of our land.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's visit to the Greiner school included an in-the-round
question-and-answer session with students, teachers, parents and
local officials of the type frequently used by Gore and President
Clinton during their campaigns in 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The students complained to the vice president of too much
violence in movies and on television and the availability of guns
and drugs _ but mostly of parents not spending enough time with
them.
</P>
<P>
   But twice, when questions arose about allowing prayer in
schools, Gore cited federal Education Department guidelines that
limit religious expressions in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's response contrasted with his policy
proposal Monday in Atlanta that would provide government subsidies
to religious organizations that deal with social problems.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 1936EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2352 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE27-COX     05-26 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE DRAWS DISTINCTIONS WITH BUSH ON GUN ISSUES
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Vice President Al Gore, concluding a two-day visit to
Texas on Wednesday, contrasted himself with Gov. George W. Bush on
two gun-related issues.
