u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-NYT &LR;      05-26 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S., RUSSIA AND E.U. APPEAR TO MAKE NO PROGRESS IN KOSOVO TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Negotiations toward a solution to the Kosovo crisis
broke up unusually late Wednesday night with no clear evidence of
progress, but representatives of the three sides in the talks _
Russia, the United States and the European Union _ planned to try
again Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, the U.S.
representative, said there had been ``good talks,'' but refused
further comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians indicated earlier that their special envoy, Victor
Chernomyrdin, was prepared to fly to Belgrade on Thursday,
suggesting that an agreement was at hand on a single peace proposal
to present to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision to resume talks, as reports circulated of a
pending indictment of Milosevic by a tribunal for war crimes,
appeared to throw those plans into doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, at least, there was not much to indicate that either
Talbott and Chernomyrdin or the European Union representative,
Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari, were inclined toward
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   The only point on which there was public agreement between
Russia and the United States was the principle that Kosovo should
remain a part of Yugoslavia in any peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   There has been speculation that the negotiators were discussing
a partition of Kosovo. Both Ivanov and Talbott said that option was
not being considered.
</P>
<P>
   NATO bombing has been trying to press the Milosevic regime to
end what United Nations officials call a gruesome campaign of
murder, rape and forced exile against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
NATO leaders say the bombing will not end until Milosevic withdraws
all armed forces from Kosovo and allows the refugees to return
under the protection of an international military force led by NATO
troops.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by the Russians, Milosevic has hung tough, insisting that
some of his forces be allowed to remain in Kosovo and that NATO's
bombing be halted before any peace accord is signed.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic also has insisted that NATO countries involved in the
bombing be banned from any peacekeeping force, a demand
Chernomyrdin is not pushing in the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Early Wednesday, after meeting with Russian Foreign Minister
Igor Ivanov, Talbott gave no ground. He was unyielding on NATO's
insistence that Serbian forces be completely removed from Kosovo
before refugees return.
</P>
<P>
   ``There cannot be Yugoslav forces _ that is to say the special
police, the Yugoslav military, the paramilitaries _ still inside
Kosovo,'' he said, adding that ``the position of Washington the
matter is unchangeable.'' Talbott kept the door open to a Yugoslav
presence in Kosovo sometime later, ``within the framework of
clearly-defined and thoroughly detailed functions under strict
international supervision.''
</P>
<P>
   He also effectively invited Russia to join any international
force stationed in Yugoslavia, and later Wednesday, in Stockholm,
Ivanov said that was a possibility _ if the Kosovo problem was
taken out of NATO's hands and put under the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   That would require a resolution by the Security Council, which
would in turn require the consent of Milosevic's two principal
supporters in the conflict, Russia and China.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov flew to Sweden to meet with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan and his special envoys for the Balkan settlement. U.S. and
Russian officials say the negotiations are focusing on the
composition and mandate of any peacekeeping force and the
conditions under which NATO might suspend its bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Almost lost in the swirl of these negotiations is the question
of whether Milosevic will agree to whatever the Russians and NATO
propose. Chernomyrdin has periodically consulted with Milosevic but
Russia generally has had little success in persuading Serbia to
follow its lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
