<SLUG> BC-GOP-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE REPUBLICAN MEMBERS SUPPORT BUSH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ More than half of the 222 Republican House members
Wednesday pledged their support for Gov. George W. Bush's
presidential campaign, a display of solidarity Rep. Henry Bonilla,
R-San Antonio, called a ``kick in the gut'' to other would-be GOP
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   One of those other candidates, former Vice President Dan Quayle,
complained bitterly Wednesday that the Republican establishment was
making a ``colossal mistake'' by stampeding to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this thing is just a rush to judgment,'' Quayle said
in an interview with The Associated Press. Quayle trails far behind
front-runner Bush in his bid for the White House in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Roy Blunt, R-Mo. and a leader of Bush's presidential
exploratory committee, led another 114 House members in publicly
backing the governor, whom Blunt said ``will have tremendous
grass-roots support in their districts.''
</P>
<P>
   Blunt said Bush's House supporters stretch from rural to urban
congressional districts. Bush, in a prepared statement, expressed
gratitude for the support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm deeply appreciative of the efforts of Congressman Blunt
and his entire team in putting together this strong vote of
confidence,'' Bush said. ``I'm particularly proud of these
endorsements because the men and women supporting me are
extraordinarily close to their constituencies and span the
ideological spectrum of our party.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla, who stood with Blunt at the Capitol, said the ``strong
announcement'' of support should be a warning to other Republicans
considering a presidential run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be a kick in the gut to a lot of them,'' Bonilla
said of the announcement. ``Endorsements are ... a huge fundamental
building block of a campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   But Quayle shrugged it off, saying party leaders are so eager to
win that they're rallying behind an early candidate largely because
he leads polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it shows that there is a genuine nervousness in the
Republican Party and they're trying to go with polls rather than
ideas _ and that is a colossal mistake. It may feel comfortable
today, but down deep if you think you're going to win this on what
public opinion polls say 18 months out, I beg to differ,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you show nervousness like that,'' he said, ``you are in
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz. and a likely Bush
opponent for the GOP presidential nomination, said the senator's
campaign was not surprised by the congressional support for Bush.
The governor fits in well with the Washington establishment while
McCain is a maverick who has challenged the status quo and will
appeal to a broader base of voters, added spokesman Howard Opinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole's fledgling presidential campaign also played
down the House members' endorsement of Bush. ``When she becomes the
nominee next spring, she looks forward to welcoming them into the
fold, each and every one,'' Dole spokesman Ari Fleischer said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
