<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-ART-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANIAN VILLAGES HIT BY SHELLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORINI, Albania _ The fighting in Kosovo spread Wednesday to
four small villages inside Albania, which Western European and
Kosovo rebel officials said were shelled by Yugoslav army forces
from over the border. Two people died in the attack, an Albanian
man and his daughter, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The sound of artillery and machine-gun fire echoed around the
hills, and puffs of smoke could be seen from the border crossing
here, the main point of entry for Kosovar Albanians fleeing into
Albania. The shells were lobbed both by Yugoslav soldiers and
rebels of the Kosovo Liberation Army, who said they had attacked a
Serbian post early Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the morning, amid reports that Serbian forces were
digging in near the border, NATO planes bombed the area near Zuhr,
one of the towns from where Kosovo fighters said the Yugoslav
shells were being fired. But Kadri Kryeziu, a spokesman for the
KLA, said the NATO attack was merely a ``coincidence.''
</P>
<P>
   For weeks now, relief officials have been trying to overcome the
reluctance of many refugees from Kosovo to move farther south away
from the border. Wednesday, they said the shelling underscored the
need to move the refugees away from the town of Kukes, only 10
miles from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It proves once again how volatile the security situation is up
there and how urgent it is to get those people out of the tented
camps,'' said Melita Cunjic, a spokeswoman for the U.N. high
commissioner for refugees. ``If the tented camps were to be
shelled, there would be unbelievable casualties.''
</P>
<P>
   There are still 100,000 refugees living in Kukes, some 33,000
living closely clumped in tent cities. Wednesday was the second day
that NATO buses have moved people from Kukes to one of two camps
now open near the coast in western Albania.
</P>
<P>
   There are plans to establish half a dozen camps where refugees
can live until _ and if _ they are able to return to their homes in
Kosovo, as NATO has promised. Already, roughly 300,000 refugees
have moved away from the border largely on their own, though many
are reluctant to leave, concerned that it will be harder to find
separated family members.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, several rockets fired by Serbs from Kosovo landed in
Albania less than five miles from Kukes _ and the attack Wednesday
was hardly the first incident along the Kosovo-Albanian border.
Since the NATO bombing began in March, hardly a day has passed
without some skirmish between Serb and Kosovo rebel forces, most of
them farther to the north.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, about 50 artillery and mortar shells landed in the
area of Kasaj, between Tropoje and the border post of Kamenica,
where the KLA has a major route into Kosovo from Albania.
</P>
<P>
   On May 11, several hundred Yugoslav troops actually occupied two
villages, Kamenica and Zogaj, for several hours. The Albanian
military says that two civilians were killed and 15 wounded.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials say they will not tolerate such incursions into
Albania. Both international and Albanian officials say they do not
believe Serbia is trying to invade or gain territory. Rather, they
say, the Serbian tactic appears to be both to stop the Kosovo
rebels and generally to destabilize the border, giving NATO yet
another problem to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose is to involve Albania into the conflict,'' said
First Capt. Albert Mullai, a spokesman for the Albanian Defense
Ministry. He said, however, that Albanian soldiers are under orders
not to fire on the Serbs. One of the Albanian military's major
goals, he said, is ``to keep calm.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Yugoslav shells landed on four Albanian villages
along the border _ Pogaj, Kishaj, Vlahena and Cahani _ according to
Andrea Angeli, a spokesman for the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, which monitors the fighting along the
border. In Cahani, he said, a house was hit by an artillery shell,
killing two people.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Kryeziu, the KLA spokesman, identified the dead as Musa Cahani,
a 59-year-old farmer, and his daughter, Merita, 20. The other 200
villagers fled, hiding in concrete bunkers built in the 1970s as
protection in case of a foreign invasion. Both Cahani and Vlahena
have been hit by Yugoslav shells during the crisis but no one died.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA recently opened up a route into Kosovo from the area
around these villages, which officials say support the rebels.
Kryeziu said the rebels attacked Yugoslav forces, from inside
Serbia, in the town of Gorozhup, about three miles from the border,
starting at 4 am Wednesday. The fighting continued into the
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fighting, 330 refugees crossed from Kosovo into
Albania Wednesday through the border crossing here, Angeli said. He
said another 240 refugees came from Macedonia to a camp near the
city of Korce in southeastern Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Relief officials said Korce could grow into yet another large
refugee encampment if Macedonia, unhappy as host to hundreds of
thousands of Kosovar Albanians, begins expelling the refugees from
its borders.
</P>
<P>
   Angeli said the people who arrived from Macedonia Wednesday went
voluntarily. He declined to speculate on whether they were the
first of a large wave of refugees to arrive there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to wait and see,'' he said. ``At this stage we
don't know how many will be coming.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
