<SLUG> BC-KIDS:COVER/FACES:RICKY-MARTIN-art-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC SPOTLIGHT: RICKY MARTIN 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 Includes one color slide of singer Ricky Martin at a press
conference after the 1999 Billboard Latin Music Awards ceremony at
the Miami Beach Fontainbleu Hotel in Miami Beach, Fla. (CREDIT:
Photo by Amy E. Conn.) 
 By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICKY MARTIN
</P>
<P>
   Home base: Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Age: 27.
</P>
<P>
   Claim to fame: Ricky Martin's the latest cute-guy pop sensation,
with a No. 1 single, ``Livin' La Vida Loca,'' and a way-anticipated
new record. Martin's self-titled disc, his first English-language
effort, came out two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting factoid: He's a former member of Mexican boy band
Menudo. Ironically, a new version of Menudo is mounting a comeback
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The story so far: Even though Ricky Martin has sold millions of
records in other parts of the world, he has remained virtually
unknown here. Until now. Now, Martin is expected to become
larger-than-life, thanks to his good looks, his latest single and
his first English-language album.
</P>
<P>
   And he's off to a good start: He has made appearances on MTV and
Saturday Night Live, and his recent in-store appearances in Los
Angeles and Florida have attracted crowds of 5,000-7,000 people.
Local radio stations are trying to bring him in for a local
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   History lesson: Martin got his first taste of musical success as
a founding member of Menudo. After he left the group, he appeared
on Broadway in ``Les Miserables'' and had a short stint on the ABC
soap opera ``General Hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   All the while, he had been working on his musical career. His
last album, last year's ``Vuelve,'' sold 5 million copies
worldwide. Sales of his new disc are expected to double. Brace
yourself for Martin mania.
</P>
<P>
