<HEADLINE>
MOVIE REVIEW: ``THE MUMMY'' 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 Includes one color slide of actor Brendan Fraser in a scene from
the movie ``The Mummy.'' (CREDIT: Photo by Keith Hamshere.
Copyright 1999 Universal Studios.) 
 By ANGELICA LARA 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``THE MUMMY''
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Brendan Fraser and Rachel Weisz.
</P>
<P>
   Plot: Three thousand years ago, Pharaoh's high priest and
mistress were having an affair and after being discovered, the
priest is cursed and put to death. In 1926, a large band of
explorers find the burial place and unleash both the curse and the
mummy.
</P>
<P>
   Why go see it?: ``The Mummy'' shows Brendan Fraser at his best,
performing both action and comedy, which he delivers extremely
well. The only problem: some scenes were far to gory for younger
kids.
</P>
<P>
   Reasons for rating: PG-13 for a suggestive situation, gory
scenes of live mummification and language.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewer's 1 - 10 rating: 8.5.
</P>
<P>
   ALSO PLAYING: ``Entrapment''
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Sean Connery, Catherine Zeta-Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: PG-13, for some language, sensuality, and drug content.
</P>
