<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS:TRENDS-HIP-STUFF-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRENDS: WEIRD, FUN STUFF TO COLLECT 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 By KELLY DEGARMO 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Foot Looks
</P>
<P>
   It's sandal season, and that means devoting more attention to
your feet (like washing with deodorant soap and clipping your
toenails, for starters). For a way-cool look, try a funky nail
polish, temporary tattoo, bindi gem or toe ring. Use your allowance
to spring for a pedicure or, better yet, invite friends over for a
manicure/pedicure party and get creative.
</P>
<P>
   Power In a Can
</P>
<P>
   Want to hear the latest gimmick in R/C cars? This summer, Tyco
introduces Canned Heat, a remote-control car packaged in a can. The
lid twists off to become the radio transmitter that controls the
micro-sized vehicle. The canister doubles as a storage container.
It operates on four AA batteries and sells for $19.99. The coolest
part? One of vehicles is a VW Beetle.
</P>
<P>
   Online Marketing
</P>
<P>
   Just about every hot-selling toy nowadays has a Web site. It's a
great marketing tool for companies to promote their products. Betty
Spaghetty has her own award-winning site, which recently received
an Addy Award for its graphics and interactive elements. Unlike
some sites, Betty reveals her privacy policy and encourages kids to
get their parents' permission before entering contests. Be wary of
typing personal information such as home or e-mail addresses or
birth dates into a Web site without first talking to a parent or
guardian about how the information might be used.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Spaghetty goes online at www.bettyspaghetty.com.
</P>
<P>
   Morph Madness
</P>
<P>
   Transformers gain another species. Welcome Animorphs. You've
heard about ``Animorphs,'' the popular Nickelodeon television
series based on the Scholastic book series. ``Animorphs'' is about
a group of five teen-age friends who change into fierce animals to
defend the world from an alien invasion. Naturally, there are cool
new Animorph toys from Hasbro based on the characters from the
series ($9.99 each). Each toy ``morphs'' from a human into a
ferocious animal. Beast Wars, watch out.
</P>
<P>
