<HEADLINE>
NEW MUSIC SPRINGS UP 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 Includes one color slide of The Backstreet Boys. (CREDIT: 1999 Jive
Records) 
 By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With new efforts from Tim McGraw, Snoop Dogg and, oh, yeah, the
Backstreet Boys, May's a huge month for new CDs. Here's a look at
some of the biggies.
</P>
<P>
   Country singer Tim McGraw's ``A Place in the Sun.'' Out now.
</P>
<P>
   Robbie Williams, ``The Ego Has Landed,'' the debut effort from
the latest English pop sensation. Out now.
</P>
<P>
   Snoop Dogg's ``Top Dogg.'' Came out May 11.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Martin's self-titled effort. Martin's the former Menudo
member who's now working on a solo career. This is his first
English album. It came out May 11.
</P>
<P>
   Backstreet Boys return with ``Millennium,'' while friendly
rivals 'N Sync turn up on the Tarzan soundtrack. Both come out May
18.
</P>
<P>
   Texas _ a pop-soul band from, uh, Scotland _ returns with its
new disc, ``Hush.'' Came out May 18.
</P>
<P>
   Insane Clown Posse returns _ oh, great _ with its latest effort,
``The Amazing Jeckel Brothers,'' featuring guest appearances by
Snoop Dogg, ODB and The Jerky Boys. Came out May 25.
</P>
<P>
   MTV VJ Jesse Camp releases his first record, ``Jesse and the 8th
Street Kidz,'' featuring Stevie Nicks and Cheap Trick singer Rick
Nielsen. We're not making this up. May 25.
</P>
<P>
   Country singer John Michael Montgomery also has a new record,
called ``Home to You.'' Came out May 25.
</P>
