<SLUG> BC-KIDS:TEENSTALK-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVICE ABOUT CRUSHES, SCHOOL 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR TeensTalk: I am 16 and I think I'm in love with my history
teacher, who is 22. I tried talking to my sister about it, but she
laughed it off as a silly crush. I don't have a ``silly'' crush.
This is serious. I think he even thinks I'm smart and cute.
Sometimes he forgets what he is saying and smiles real big at me. I
want to talk to him outside of class. My parents have nine years'
difference in their age. If I want to date him, I will. It's my
life. _ In Love.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR In Love: It is your life, but you need to consider all the
aspects of this relationship. Many people, at one time or another,
have admired a teacher or someone they look up to. Many times,
though, the other person does not feel the same.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the admiration is shared by both people. The
teacher has to be careful, though. He is not supposed to get into a
relationship with a student. He can talk with you in class, but he
should not be dating you. This is to protect you and other students
from getting hurt. It is a policy. Enjoy your class and teacher,
but consider guys closer to your age.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR TeensTalk: I am an elementary school student. I sometimes
have trouble understanding the teacher or reading words. I don't
want the other kids to make fun of me, so I do not say anything. My
teacher is nice. My mom says to let her know. _ Don't Understand.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR Don't Understand: Many students have a learning disability,
and it is determined in the elementary grades. Your teacher will be
very understanding. You need to let her know, and she can request
to have you tested to determine your learning abilities.
</P>
<P>
   The testing could determine your needs and really help you
understand your schoolwork and improve your grades. So talk to your
teacher, or your mother can set up a conference to have you tested.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Do you have a problem or concern that needs an answer? The Class
Acts TeensTalk panel _ headed by Kathy Pope, a counselor at a Texas
junior college _ is comprised of teenage students who care about
other students. Write to: TeensTalk, c/o Class Acts, The New York
Times Syndicate, 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
