<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-JEWS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFORM JUDAISM'S LEADERS BACK GUIDELINES FAVORING TRADITIONAL
RITUALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By NADINE BROZAN with GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ The governing body of Reform Judaism, the largest
and most liberal group of American Jews, on Wednesday approved by a
wide margin a set of guiding principles that open the door to
increased use of traditional rituals like wearing skullcaps,
keeping kosher and praying in Hebrew that were set aside at the
movement's founding in this country in 1854.
</P>
<P>
   The 324-68 vote of the Central Conference of American Rabbis,
following three days of fierce debate here, ended with cheers and
celebratory songs, and concluded two years of debate and
disagreement over how best to express what it means to be Reform
Jew.
</P>
<P>
   In a measure of the passions raised by the revisions,
participants at the organization's annual conference, which began
Sunday here at Rodef Shalom Congregation, labored until late
Tuesday on the new set of principles and then postponed the vote to
allow for even more time for discussion Wednesday. But despite the
feeling among many people that compromises considered necessary for
acceptance in the 1.5 million Reform community rendered it too
vague, the platform passed decisively. It was only the fourth
platform issued since Reform Judaism, a movement started in Germany
in the early 19th century, was established in the United States,
and the first one in 23 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is different about this statement is that it calls on
people to take seriously the whole array of tradition,'' said Rabbi
Paul Menitoff, executive director of the conference, which has
1,700 members.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time in decades, certainly in 25 years, that
Reform rabbis and lay people have discussed what we are about and
tried to clarify where we are as a movement,'' said Menitoff,
describing the document as portraying Reform Judaism as ``a broad
tent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can feel at home in this tent if you're nontraditionally
oriented, or if you traditionally oriented,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh Principles _ which are meant to be guidelines and
suggestions, not enforceable rules _ are an effort to redefine
Reform Judaism, away from what some of its leaders describe as a
``minimalist'' identity concerned largely with social ethics,
toward a more spacious faith in which adherents feel many
traditional expressions of Judaism are fully open to them.
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, the document reflects a broad phenomenon that
goes well beyond Judaism, of a reviving public interest in
spiritual matters and practices, a hallmark of life in the United
States at the close of the 20th century. Among Reform Jews, that
has meant an increase in the number of men wearing skullcaps and
prayer shawls in synagogues, along with a greater use of Hebrew in
services.
</P>
<P>
   The document, said Rabbi Charles Kroloff of Westfield, N.J., who
took office as president of the conference Wednesday evening,
``reflects the move toward taking tradition more seriously,'' a
process long under way but one that he said had ``particularly
accelerated for the last 10 to 15 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Kroloff added, the principles acknowledged ``lots
of respect'' for Jews who did not feel inclined toward traditional
practices.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its relative brevity, the document also recognizes and
encourages another broad and distinct current within the Reform
movement, in the growing receptivity among national Reform
organizations and local synagogues toward groups once considered to
be on the margins of Judaism _ gay and lesbian Jews, members of
interfaith couples and recent converts.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the movement has ordained openly gay rabbis and
begun public classes to teach unaffiliated Jews, interfaith couples
and interested non-Jews about Judaism's basic principles, an effort
that has fostered a small stream of conversions in many cities.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to both these tendencies _ the move toward tradition
and greater reaching out _ the document specifically encourages
``public and private prayer,'' the study of Jewish tradition and
``other mitzvot, sacred obligations,'' while also declaring the
movement to be ``inclusive,'' open to people ``regardless of their
sexual orientation.''
</P>
<P>
   But its greater message may be one of helping the movement forge
a new understanding of what it is within Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   It was the highlighting of an openness to tradition that drew
the document so much attention and controversy within the Reform
movement, ever since the first draft was drawn up more than a year
ago by Rabbi Richard Levy, the conference's outgoing president,
whose term ended Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's great support for encouraging Reform Jews to look at
the whole tradition and incorporating as much into their lives as
calls to them,'' he said ``If it calls to them to cover their
heads, they should be able to do that,'' he added. ``If it calls to
them to approach God bareheaded, they should be able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The document that Levy wrote more than a year ago underwent six
drafts as rabbis and lay people from around the nation offered
ideas and criticisms. In an extensive critique of one of the
document's earlier drafts, Robert Seltzer, professor of Jewish
history at the City University of New York, wrote in Reform Judaism
magazine that encouraging ritual practices would be useful if such
observances ``have meaning for us.'' But, he added, ``we must guard
against turning Reform Judaism into Conservative Judaism Lite.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Harry Danziger, senior rabbi at Temple Israel in Memphis,
Tenn., explained that the platform will not judge anyone who does
not observe rites and rituals. He said, ``It says, here is the big
tent within which you stand, and here is a broad view of Jewish
heritage out of which you will make your personal religion. No one
ideology replaces or triumphs over another.''
</P>
<P>
   The platform will be taken back to synagogues and congregants at
a time when, religious leaders agree, there is increased yearning
on the part of Jews to find meaning outside the stress of daily
life and the press of materialism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is moving so fast, we are caught up with computers
and making money and people feel less good about life,'' said Rabbi
Constance Golden, associate rabbi at the Old York Road Temple Beth
Am in Abington, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Lance Sussman, the rabbi of Temple Concord in Binghamton,
N.Y., and associate professor of American Jewish history at the
State University of New York in Binghamton, who voted against
passage of the principles, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``The statement doesn't really address the religious needs of
Reform Judaism at this time. It doesn't show the way to faith and
doesn't explain what redemption is in Reform terms. What it has
succeeded in doing is marking the direction of the movement with
more tradition. I hope to serve as a bridge to the tens of
thousands of Reform Jews who will be uncomfortable with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Acceptance of the principles in no way marks the end of the
debate. Rabbis are now expected to organize meetings and study
sessions to translate what they mean into concrete terms. Both
members of the clergy and congregants will be invited to write
commentaries, and it is in those that numerous questions raised by
the platform are expected to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   As Rabbi Laura Geller, senior rabbi of Temple Emanuel in Beverly
Hills, Calif., put it: ``It is an incredible teaching tool. For too
many people Reform Judaism is a Judaism of minimalism, of what we
don't do. This will enble people to think about what calls them.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Sheldon Zimmerman, who as president of the Hebrew Union
College-Jewish Institute of Religion is responsible for the
education of future rabbis, said: ``This is a beginning, not an
end. The real story will be what we do with it now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
