<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ROCKET IS READY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He played in Boston the year after Yaz retired. He
lived in Winter Haven. He played for Ralph Houk, Johnny Mac,
Tollway Joe, Daddy Butch, and Kevin Kennedy. He was at Shea in '86.
He went ballistic in Oakland in '90. He loved Mrs. Yawkey and
loathed Dan Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   It is May 27, almost one year to the day since Roger Clemens
last lost a ballgame and tonight Clemens will be on the mound, in
pinstripes, facing the first-place Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, Yankee fans. We're more than a quarter of the way
through the 1999 baseball season and the reigning World Champs from
the Bronx are still a game and a half behind the mighty, mighty
Bostons.
</P>
<P>
   While the rest of his new teammates basked in the glow of
Wednesday's 8-3 Yankee victory over the Red Sox, Clemens put on
black pants, black shoes, a black shirt, and his game face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be there,'' he promised. ``I'll be there.''
</P>
<P>
   We hope so. The Rocket was accused of ducking the Red Sox when
he first came off the disabled list, but there was no getting
around his former team this week.
</P>
<P>
   This is going to be weird and wild. When he was with the Red
Sox, Clemens would wipe sweat on the Babe Ruth monument after
warming up in the visitors' bullpen at Yankee Stadium. He was one
of the few Sox players who understood the irrational fears of
Boston fans. He and Wade Boggs are the only members of the
star-crossed 1986 Red Sox who are still playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't look good in pinstripes,'' said John Valentin, the
only Sox player who spent considerble time with Clemens. ``In a
way, this is just another game, but it's not really another game.
Obviously, we would like to do well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be exciting. He hasn't been a Red Sox
for a while, so it's kind of going away. I still remember when he
first came back to Boston and I got a couple of hits, but then we
went to Toronto and he pretty much struck me out three times.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an emotional guy,'' said New York manager Joe Torre.
``That's why he's won as many Cy Youngs as he has.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens's start comes at a good time for the Yankees. The New
Yorkers would like some carryover from Wednesday's convincing win
and could claim a 3-3 split in the home-and-home series if they
beat Boston. Clemens carries in an American League record streak of
18 consecutive victories. He last lost May 29, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have been putting pressure on their starting
pitchers, but Wednesday shielded Orlando Hernandez from stress by
scoring eight runs, including six in the first five innings _ four
on Tino Martinez's grand slam on an 0-2 pitch from John (straight
up for Jose Canseco?) Wasdin.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are doing their best to take the Sox seriously.
Torre referred to Boston as the ``hot club in the league,'' adding,
``I don't anticipate that club is going away at all. They've got
Ramon Martinez coming back and they've got some numbers. They've
got some people that can pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   New York general manager Brian Cashman added, ``Through this
date, they've played better baseball than we have. They have a lot
of people who've done a lot of things in this game.''
</P>
<P>
   There's quiet confidence in the Yankee clubhouse. Veterans Paul
O'Neill, Tino Martinez, Chili Davis, and Chuck Knoblauch don't seem
particularly distressed about Boston's early-season surge. But
they've all been struggling at the plate and are looking to break
out as May turns into June.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a team, we have a lot of confidence,'' said Martinez.
``When you struggle, everybody seems to press. Hopefully, this game
today can get us kick-started and get us on a hot streak.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill, who is 5 for 9 since all the talk about moving him out
of the third spot in the batting order, said, ``We're trying to
turn things around. The way we've had trouble scoring runs has put
a lot of pressure on our pitchers.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the best pitchers of all time takes the mound for New
York Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens knows. He knows that this is only one game, but he also
knows that it'll be smothered in symbolism. He knows that a Boston
victory over Roger Clemens in Yankee Stadium would be a major boost
to the fragile psyche of Red Sox Nation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
