<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fortune looks at Internet stock boom
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Internet dominates more than the stock market
these days. It's beginning to dominate the nation's business press
as well.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fortune (June 7) says these new Internet stocks are more than
the latest incarnation of Dutch tulips, items of an earlier buying
mania.
</P>
<P>
   These companies are in a ``parallel universe'' where earnings
are less important than grabbing market share by acquiring other
companies and following the lead of CEOs who make the rules. ``I
think our valuation is a sign that investors are actually rewarding
us for being aggressive,'' iVillage CEO Candice Carpenter says.
</P>
<P>
   Fortune lists nine stocks for investors willing to take a
chance: America Online, Cisco Systems and Microsoft are ``risky'';
eBay, Yahoo! and At Home are ``riskier''; and Amazon, CMGI and
Exodus are ``riskiest.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Meanwhile, Smart Money (June), The Wall Street Journal's
personal finance magazine, points out that the Internet frenzy has
already created a new class of investors: ``the Internet
have-nots,'' who know what it feels like ``to be road kill on the
information highway.''
</P>
<P>
   These ``prudent investors'' sat out the Internet boom while
friends and family ``struck it rich'' and therefore are in a highly
irritable state. Missing an opportunity to make big money was bad
enough, but they chafe at the boasting of successful Internet
investors.
</P>
<P>
   One investor laments the loss of a chance to own $5 million
worth of America Online stock because he listened to his banker's
advice. ``We no longer speak,'' he told Smart Money. ``I struck him
from my life.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Business Week (May 31) profiles the two titans of the Web _
Amazon.com, which helps people find almost anything they want to
buy online, and eBay, which runs the biggest person-to-person
auction Web site. The question is which of the two techniques will
shoppers prefer, fixed prices or dynamic pricing? The outcome, says
Business Week, will decide which of the two becomes ``the Wal-Mart
of the New Economy.''
</P>
<P>
   A time to celebrate
</P>
<P>
   Two magazines aimed at entrepreneurs and women celebrate their
20th anniversaries with their June editions: Inc., the magazine for
growing companies, and Working Mother.
</P>
<P>
   Inc. calls the period since 1979 ``the entrepreneurial
decades,'' during which we learned ``everything necessary to create
businesses that grow.'' The magazine pays tribute to John D.
Rockefeller Sr. as ``entrepreneur of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Working Mother finds one of the biggest social
changes in the attitudes of the husbands of women who work. ``Wives
of the 1970s really felt they needed a husband's permission to
leave the home. ... A contemporary husband says, `It might be ideal
for one of us to stay home with the kids, but it's not financially
realistic,''' the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
