</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KASHMIR-GUERRILLAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA LAUNCHES AIRSTRIKES IN KASHMIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAHUL BEDI AND INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI _ Heightening a simmering conflict between the world's
two newest nuclear powers, India launched air raids Wednesday in
the disputed state of Kashmir on more than 600 Muslim mercenaries
allegedly backed by Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan vowed to retaliate for the first border air attack in
years in a dispute that has raged intermittently for more than half
a century.
</P>
<P>
   India said it resorted to air attacks after the separatists,
armed with assault rifles and mortars and riding snowmobiles,
pushed through before winter snows melted to occupy dozens of
vantage points abandoned before winter by Indian troops. Despite
artillery backing, Indian troops had made little progress
dislodging the separatists in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Indian military officials said fighter aircraft and helicopter
sorties from the airfield in Kashmir's capital of Srinagar would
continue until the Indian army reoccupied the wide swath of Indian
territory held by the separatist insurgents.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan charged that Indian aircraft bombed
Pakistani-controlled Kashmir, a report that India denies.
Pakistan's military has been placed on high alert, and a Pakistani
army spokesman said the country was ready for ``all
eventualities.''
</P>
<P>
   Pakistani Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz also denied reports from
India and Western intelligence sources that Pakistan was backing
the mercenaries, saying ``no one knows where they come from or who
they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee said he had warned
Pakistani leader Nawaz Sharif in a telephone call Monday to pull
back the invaders, or India would take all steps to dislodge them.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's airstrikes mark the first major showdown since the
two sides declared themselves to be nuclear powers a year ago, and
began stockpiling missiles capable of striking deep into each
other's territories. It was also the first time that New Delhi used
air force against insurgents since a Muslim uprising erupted in
Indian-controlled Kashmir in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   India last used fighter aircraft against Pakistan since they
fought a war over the secession of East Pakistan, or Bangladesh, in
1971. The rival nations, which were created with the partition of
British India in 1947, fought two earlier wars over Kashmir _ in
1947 and 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Kashmir is divided along a UN-designated cease-fire line.
Two-thirds of the mainly Muslim state is controlled by
majority-Hindu India; one-third by Muslim Pakistan. Both nations
want to control the entire Himalayan state, which strategically
borders China and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Indian officials say the invaders include Taliban guerrilla
fighters from Afghanistan and other Muslim mercenaries who had
taken control of Kashmir's decade-old civil war for an independent
Muslim homeland _ a battle that has claimed at least 15,000, and
perhaps as many as 20,000 lives.
</P>
<P>
   India insisted that the air attacks occurred solely within its
part of Kashmir, and were aimed at Afghan mercenaries supported by
Pakistan. Officials said the invaders had moved into the
Indian-controlled part of the Himalayan region this month and posed
a threat to Indian supply lines.
</P>
<P>
   The enmity between the two enemy neighbors flares daily along
the 450-mile-long line of control. Thousands of troops on either
side of the line, sheltering in bunkers, have exchanged thousands
of rounds of artillery, machine gun, and mortar fire daily.
</P>
<P>
   India claims firing by Pakistan along the line covers the
infiltration of armed Islamic militants into Kashmir. ``We are tied
down all the time by the influx of militants,'' said an Indian
officer interviewed at the border. He said the rough local terrain
makes it impossible to seal the border, and even if soldiers stood
shoulder to shoulder along the line, infiltration could not be
stopped.
</P>
<P>
   The Kashmir dispute has turned the region into one of the
world's most volatile flashpoints, especially since the two sides
became nuclear powers. Kashmir remains the core issue between the
two nations, scuttling all efforts at peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan declared last year that it would not sign the nuclear
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty unless the Kashmir dispute was
resolved. Last year, Pakistan's then-Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub
Khan said the quarrel over Kashmir could trigger a nuclear war. He
called Kashmir was an ``open wound.''
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan has also refused India's offer not to fire the first
nuclear strike, pending a settlement over the disputed state.
Pakistan has long demanded a plebiscite that would allow Kashmir's
residents to decide whether to join Pakistan or India _ a vote
India has resisted for the last 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   India says Pakistan has never forgiven India for helping East
Pakistan break away to form Bangladesh in 1971, and has armed and
trained insurgents to fight the civil war in Indian-held Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Indian Major General J.J. Singh acknowledged Wednesday that it
would take at least two months to push the invaders back. He said
17 Indian soldiers had died and 70 were injured, 20 of them
seriously in the fire fighting over the past two weeks on terrain
that offered no cover. He said more than 160 of the infiltrators
had been killed.
</P>
<P>
   (Indira A.R. Lakshmanan of the Globe staff contributed to this
report from Hong Kong.)
</P>
</TEXT>
