<SLUG> BC-PARSONS-DANCE-STUDIO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCE REVIEW: 2 DIRECTORS, 2 STYLES _ DREAMINESS AND VIGOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JENNIFER DUNNING  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It isn't every choreographer and company director who
invites his dancers to contribute new repertory. David Parsons has
done that, however, and the results were presented Tuesday night at
the Joyce Theater. The program of dances by Parsons and Robert
Battle will be performed with changing casts through Sunday
afternoon at the Joyce.
</P>
<P>
   Battle is developing a personal style after only a few years of
choreographing. The sleek, jazzy hyperactivity of several of the
six pieces he presented nicely complements Parsons' more relaxed,
dreamier way with movement.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Takademe,'' Battle deconstructs the complex, tightly woven
rhythms of Indian Kathak dance, sprinkling the solo with allusions
to other dance forms that fit with impressive ease. Abstracted and
rooted to a circumscribed area of the stage, the dance incorporates
spurting aerobic jumps, for example, and even a hint or two of
classical ballet mime.
</P>
<P>
   The jazzily percussive score by Sheila Chandra takes as its
departure point the vocalized rhythmic syllables _ a kind of
traditional Indian scat-singing _ that accompany Kathak dance. And
Jaime Martinez was excitingly propulsive without losing the clear
shapes and shifts of this fast-moving excursion into rhythmic
exotica.
</P>
<P>
   Battle's new ``Rush Hour,'' danced to music composed by Robert
Mackey and performed live by his ensemble, was the crisply surging
jazz dance equivalent of a precision drill for seven
militaristic-looking near-robots. But the choreographer's point of
view or purpose was unclear in his four other new pieces on the
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Variation,'' danced to music by Mackey, might simply have been
a showcase for Mia McSwain in a deftly physical mood. But it was
hard to detect a heart beating beneath the sleek surfaces of
``Two,'' ``Strange Humors'' and ``Damn,'' despite the accomplished
performances they received from Martinez and Battle, Jason McDole
and Henry Jackson, and Elizabeth Koeppen.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons was best represented by ``Sleep Study,'' an endearingly
tender look at pajama-clad sleepers that is full of small, witty
movement jokes, and by ``Closure,'' a smooth-flowing, majestic
ritual for a community of eight dancers. Ms. Koeppen gave his
``Caught'' an interestingly sultry spin in a program completed by
Parsons' ``Union'' and an improvisational quartet.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth-Ellen Kroll's fearless, imaginative star turn in the
improvisation was a high point of the evening. May she be Parsons'
next choice _ and soon _ for guest choreographer.
</P>
</TEXT>
