<SLUG> BC-PALESTINIANS-JORDAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARAFAT MEETS WITH JORDAN'S KING ON PEACE AGENDA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip _ Anticipating renewed peace efforts after
the election of Ehud Barak as Israel's prime minister, Yasser
Arafat, the Palestinian leader, met here Wednesday with King
Abdullah of Jordan to set a common agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, at Arafat's office, was part of a flurry of
contacts among the Palestinian Authority, Egypt and Jordan after
the Israeli election on May 17. It was Abdullah's first visit to
Palestinian-ruled territory since he succeeded his father, King
Hussein, who died in February.
</P>
<P>
   After a two-hour discussion, Arafat and Abdullah issued a joint
statement stressing the need for ``Arab coordination,''
specifically among the Palestinians, Jordan and Egypt, before
resumption of Israeli-Palestinian talks on a final peace agreement.
Those talks were supposed to have ended on May 4, but they have
barely begun.
</P>
<P>
   Following a meeting with Arafat in Cairo this week, President
Hosni Mubarak of Egypt said plans were under way to hold a summit
meeting among leaders of the Palestinians and the four Arab
countries bordering Israel. Nabil Shaath, a senior aide to Arafat,
said Wednesday that no date had been set.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding peace efforts with Israel, Arafat and Abdullah said
they had ``agreed on the need to fully implement all agreements,
including the Wye River agreement, to stop all settlement
activities and to resume final-status negotiations with good
will.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wye accord, signed in Washington last October by Arafat and
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of Israel, was in effect frozen
after Netanyahu stopped troop withdrawals in the West Bank,
asserting that the Palestinians had failed to keep their security
commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Reviving that agreement would be a test of Barak's willingness
to move ahead, Shaath said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to wait and see what he does when he takes over on the
ground,'' he said at a news conference. ``Stopping settlement
activity and implementing the Wye River agreement _ I think these
would be the two signals we are waiting for to see how much good
will he has in making the peace process work.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Barak has promised to move peace efforts forward, he
has said little yet about his concrete plans. Palestinians have
expressed concern over policy guidelines that appeared in Barak's
victory speech last week and in his campaign messages.
</P>
<P>
   They included a rejection of a withdrawal from the West Bank to
Israel's boundaries before the 1967 Arab-Israel war and a pledge to
maintain Israeli control over all of Jerusalem. Palestinians claim
East Jerusalem as the capital of their hoped-for state in the West
Bank and the Gaza Strip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
