<HEADER>
A2403 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISLAND-RECIPES-LADN     05-26 1678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISLAND-RECIPES-LADN </SLUG>
 
(Recipes with ISLAND-CUISINE, CHOY-PROFILE) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOK-BARBECUED SHRIMP WITH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PEPPER-PAPAYA-PINEAPPLE CHUTNEY
</P>
<P>
   I ``fire up'' my wok-cooked shrimp by marinating them in the
zesty flavors of fresh ginger and Asian chiles. Pour stir-fried
shrimp over a bed of hot rice with the spicy chutney on the side
for dipping. You can also skip the rice and serve as appetizers.
</P>
<P>
   1 pound jumbo shrimp (16 to 20 count) &QL; 
Wok Barbecue Marinade (recipe follows) &QL; 
1 1/2 tablespoons canola oil &QL; 
Pepper-Papaya-Pineapple Chutney (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   To prepare shrimp, shell and devein, but leave tails attached.
Marinate in Wok Barbecue Marinade 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In a wok, heat oil and stir-fry shrimp over high heat 4 to 5
minutes. Do not overcook. Serve with Pepper-Papaya-Pineapple
Chutney. Makes 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WOK BARBECUE MARINADE
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup canola oil &QL; 
2 tablespoons soy sauce &QL; 
2 tablespoons peeled and minced fresh ginger &QL; 
2 tablespoons chopped fresh cilantro &QL; 
1 tablespoon minced fresh garlic &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon granulated sugar &QL; 
1 chile, seeded and chopped (OR 1/8 teaspoon red chile pepper
flakes)
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients and mix well. Makes 1 cup. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
PEPPER-PAPAYA-PINEAPPLE CHUTNEY
</P>
<P>
   1 small fresh pineapple, peeled, cored and chopped &QL; 
1 medium fresh papaya, seeded, peeled and chopped &QL; 
1 tablespoon peeled and minced fresh ginger &QL; 
6 tablespoons granulated sugar &QL; 
1 tablespoon hot Asian chile paste, such as sambal oelek
</P>
<P>
   In a medium saucepan, combine all ingredients except chile
paste. Cook, uncovered, over medium heat 1 hour or until mixture
has a syrupy consistency. Fold in chile paste. Makes 1 1/2 cups. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
O'AHU-STYLE POTATO SALAD
</P>
<P>
   There are all different things in this salad _ crab, uncooked
corn kernels that add a little crunchiness. Whew, `ono (delicious).
It's great to take to the beach or a tailgate party.
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds new red potatoes &QL; 
Water &QL; 
2 cups crab meat, picked over well &QL; 
1/2 cup shelled, cooked small shrimp &QL; 
4 hard-cooked eggs, chopped &QL; 
1 cup fresh corn kernels &QL; 
1/2 cup pitted medium ripe olives &QL; 
1/4 cup sliced water chestnuts &QL; 
1 1/2 cups cleaned and chopped fresh spinach &QL; 
1/2 cup minced sweet onion &QL; 
1/2 cup minced celery &QL; 
1/2 grated carrots &QL; 
2 1/2 cups mayonnaise &QL; 
Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Cook potatoes in lightly salted boiling water until fork-tender.
Cool, peel if desired, then cut into eighths.
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl, toss potatoes with remaining ingredients
lightly to combine. Adjust seasoning with salt and pepper if
necessary. Makes 8 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
HALE'IWA BARBECUED PORK RIBS
</P>
<P>
   The reason I call this Hale'iwa barbecued pork ribs, is that we
used to go to Hale'iwa Beach Park on Sunday drives and have
barbecues. It was important that we had the ribs marinated and
cooked ahead of time so we didn't have to spend all day over the
coals. We'd just throw them on the grill, brush them with sauce and
as soon as they heated through, we'd have a delicious, quick meal.
</P>
<P>
   2 whole slabs pork ribs, cut into sections of 3 ribs EACH &QL; 
Water &QL; 
1/2 cup sea salt OR kosher salt &QL; 
4 cloves fresh garlic &QL; 
1 finger fresh ginger, peeled &QL; 
2 green onions &QL; 
Hale'iwa Barbecue Sauce (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   Place ribs in a stockpot and cover with water. Start with 1/2
cup sea salt and keep adding until water tastes salty, then add
garlic, ginger and green onions. Bring to a boil. Reduce heat and
let simmer 45 minutes to 1 hour or until ribs are tender.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, prepare Hale'iwa Barbecue Sauce. When ribs are
tender, remove from stockpot and let cool. Cover tightly and store
in refrigerator until ready to barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   Brush with Hale'iwa Barbecue Sauce and grill over hot coals on a
hibachi until heated through. Continue to baste ribs with barbecue
sauce as they cook. Makes 4 to 6 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
HALE'IWA BARBECUE SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon red chile pepper flakes &QL; 
2 cans (15 ounces EACH) tomato sauce &QL; 
2 cups packed brown sugar &QL; 
1/2 cup vinegar &QL; 
1/2 cup honey &QL; 
2 cups minced onions &QL; 
2 teaspoons liquid smoke &QL; 
2 teaspoons chili powder &QL; 
1 teaspoon coarsely cracked black pepper &QL; 
2 tablespoons steak sauce &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon dry mustard &QL; 
1 cinnamon stick &QL; 
1 cup canned crushed pineapple &QL; 
1 tablespoon mixed fresh garlic
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients in a saucepan, bring to a boil, reduce
heat and simmer 1 hour. Strain. Makes 3 to 3 1/2 cups. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SWEET-AND-SOUR CHICKEN BREASTS &QL; 
WITH TROPICAL FRUITS
</P>
<P>
   I really like making this dish because it gives a whole new
twist to sweet-and-sour-sauce. Adding fresh tropical fruit makes it
different. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
4 boneless, skinless chicken breast halves, 6 to 8 ounces EACH &QL; 
Maui Moa Marinade (recipe follows) &QL; 
1/2 cup all-pupose flour &QL; 
3 tablespoons vegetable oil &QL; 
1 cup diced fresh pineapple &QL; 
1 cup chopped fresh papaya &QL; 
1 cup chopped mangos OR tropical fruit of your choice &QL; 
Sweet-and-Sour Sauce (recipe follows) &QL; 
Green onion strips and sprigs of fresh cilantro for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Cover chicken with Maui Moa Marinade and let stand 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove chicken from marinade and blot off excess liquid. Dust
chicken with flour to coat. Pan-fry in oil until golden brown,
about 4 minutes per side on medium heat. Remove chicken, set aside
and tent with foil to keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Discard most oil in pan, leaving about 1 tablespoon. Stir-fry
fruit 2 minutes. Add Sweet-and-Sour Sauce and heat through.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange chicken breasts on a serving platter, pour some sauce
over them and garnish with green onion strips and cilantro. Pass
remaining sauce separately. Makes 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MAUI MOA MARINADE
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup soy sauce &QL; 
1/2 cup canola oil &QL; 
2 tablespoons mirin (Japanese sweet rice wine) &QL; 
1 tablespoon minced fresh garlic &QL; 
1 tablespoon peeled and minced fresh ginger &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon salt &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon white pepper &QL; 
2 tablespoons cornstarch mixed with 1 1/2 tablespoons water &QL; 
1 1/2 teaspoons brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients. Makes 1 1/2 cups. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SWEET-AND-SOUR SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup ketchup &QL; 
1/2 cup vinegar &QL; 
1/2 cup water &QL; 
2 teaspoons soy sauce &QL; 
1 cup granulated sugar &QL; 
1/4 cup orange marmalade &QL; 
1 1/2 teaspoons peeled and minced fresh ginger &QL; 
1 teaspoon minced fresh garlic &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon hot pepper sauce &QL; 
2 tablespoons pineapple juice &QL; 
2 tablespoons cornstarch blended with 1 1/2 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients except cornstarch mixture in a medium
saucepan. Bring to a boil. Stir in cornstarch mixture, reduce heat
and simmer, stirring frequently, 1 to 2 minutes or until thickened,
stirring constantly. Makes about 4 cups. &QL; 
EASY FRUIT SALAD FOR THE BEACH
</P>
<P>
   Cut the fruit and mix the dressing and keep them separate until
you're ready to eat, then mix them together in a large bowl and
have at it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
FRUITS: &QL; 
1/2 honeydew melon, sliced into 1/2-inch chunks &QL; 
1/2 cantaloupe, sliced into 1/2-inch chunks &QL; 
1 papaya, sliced into 1/2-inch chunks &QL; 
1 pineapple, sliced into 1/2-inch chunks &QL; 
6 strawberries &QL; 
1/2 bunch of grapes &QL; 
DRESSING: &QL; 
2 tablespoons dairy sour cream &QL; 
2 tablespoons mayonnaise &QL; 
Salt and pepper to taste &QL; 
1 tablespoon pineapple jam OR papaya-pineapple marmalade
</P>
<P>
   Mix fruits together just before serving. Combine dressing
ingredients and serve with fruit salad. Makes 4 to 6 servings. &QL; 
ISLAND-STYLE COLESLAW
</P>
<P>
   This is a very tangy slaw, made with won bok (a Chinese
cabbage). You can substitute celery cabbage or head cabbage. For
crunchy coleslaw, cut the cabbage in half and soak it in salted ice
water for about 1 hour; drain well. Chill cabbage and slice into
thin strips. This is a great side dish for barbecues or picnics. It
travels well. &QL; 
1/4 cup chopped green bell pepper &QL; 
4 cups shredded won bok (OR other cabbage) &QL; 
1/4 bunch watercress, chopped &QL; 
8 stuffed olives, sliced &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon dry mustard &QL; 
1 teaspoon celery seeds &QL; 
2 tablespoons granulated sugar &QL; 
3 tablespoons vegetable oil &QL; 
1/3 cup vinegar &QL; 
1 tablespoon chopped pimiento &QL; 
Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Place green pepper, won bok, watercress and olives in a large
bowl. Cover and chill. Combine remaining ingredients in a jar.
Cover.
</P>
<P>
   Before serving, shake jar and pour dressing over vegetables.
Toss until combined. Makes 6 to 8 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MACADAMIA NUT PIE
</P>
<P>
   This is a rich dessert _ macadamia nuts suspended in a sweet,
creamy pie filling and topped with fluffy whipped cream. Serve it
with a good hot cup of Kona-blend coffee. &QL; 
3 eggs &QL; 
2/3 cup granulated sugar &QL; 
1 cup light corn syrup &QL; 
2 cups coarsely chopped macadamia nuts &QL; 
2 tablespoons butter, melted &QL; 
1 teaspoon vanilla &QL; 
1 unbaked 9-inch pie shell &QL; 
Whipped cream (optional) and 2 tablespoons chopped macadamia nuts
for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Beat eggs with sugar and corn syrup. Stir in 2 cups macadamia
nuts. Add butter and vanilla and blend well.
</P>
<P>
   Pour mixture into pie shell. Bake in preheated 325-degree oven
50 minutes or until crust is golden and center is somewhat set.
Test by shaking gently. Let cool, then chill.
</P>
<P>
   Garnish with a swirl of whipped cream and a sprinkling of
remaining 2 tablespoons chopped macadamia nuts. Makes 8 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MINAKA'S MACNUT BROWNIE
</P>
<P>
   I really enjoy a good, crunchy-crusted, gooey brownie. So, when
my friend Minaka brought these brownies to a Christmas party, I
asked her for the recipe. In my restaurants I top the brownies with
two scoops of vanilla ice cream and a thin stream of chocolate
syrup. It's a real treat. &QL; 
4 ounces dark OR semisweet chocolate &QL; 
8 tablespoons (1 stick) butter &QL; 
3 eggs &QL; 
1 1/4 cups granulated sugar &QL; 
1 teaspoon vanilla &QL; 
1 cup sifted all-purpose flour &QL; 
1/4 cup diced macadamia nuts
</P>
<P>
   Butter an 8-inch square baking pan.
</P>
<P>
   Melt chocolate and butter in a double boiler over simmering
water. Whip eggs with sugar and vanilla 5 to 10 minutes until thick
and pale yellow in color. Gradually stream melted chocolate into
egg mixture, whipping constantly. Fold flour into batter, then turn
into prepared pan. Sprinkle macadamia nuts on top.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 325-degree oven 20 to 25 minutes or until an
inserted toothpick comes out almost clean. Cool. Cut into 12 bars.
Top with vanilla ice cream before serving. Makes 6 servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
