<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Thursday, May
27, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Veronica
Villarreal at (206) 448-8342.
</P>
<P>
   SETTLEMENT-REFINERY (ANACORTES, Wash.) _ The company that owns
the refinery in Anacortes, Wash., where six workers died in an
explosion last year agreed to a record $4.4 million settlement that
includes a fine, a contribution to a scholarship fund and money for
a new fire truck in Anacortes, state labor officials said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   By Scott Sunde. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   MULTIPLE-PERSONALITY (Seattle) _ Tyrone attacked his therapist
when she came to check on him at his Everett home. Sam tried to
save the woman, but couldn't get Tyrone to stop. Now Tyrone and Sam
are jailed for life -- along with the 22 other personalities said
to occupy the head of the therapist's client, William B. Greene.
The Washington Supreme Court will hear arguments Thursday on the
unusual multiple-personalities case, deciding whether Greene should
have been allowed to argue he was not guilty by reason of insanity
when he tied up and molested his therapist in 1994. A Snohomish
County judge had ruled that there wasn't enough acceptance of
multiple-personality disorder's existence to allow it at trial, but
a state Appeals Court disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   By Rebekah Denn. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-DISCRIMINATION (Seattle) _ A federal court judge on
Wednesday delayed the distribution of money in the settlement of a
discrimination lawsuit against The Boeing Co. so that a group
objecting to the deal can state its case. U.S. District Judge John
Coughenour scheduled another hearing in the matter Sept. 23 after
attorneys take depositions. Among those who could be deposed is
Boeing Chairman Phil Condit.
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Nyhan. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   CAPTAIN-WOMAN (Seattle) _ Feature on Linda Greenlaw, the only
woman swordfish captain on the East Coast and the gritty star of
Sebastian Junger's best seller ``The Perfect Storm.'' Greenlaw has
written her own book, ``The Hungry Ocean,'' about surviving rough
seas, and surviving in a world dominated by men.
</P>
<P>
   By M.L. Lyke. (Story will move in the ``l'' and ``a''
categories.)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-BECKER-FEAR (Undated) _ Having already written a book on
appreciating the role of fear in survival, ``The Gift of Fear,''
Gavin de Becker's new book, ``Protecting the Gift: Keeping Children
and Teenagers Safe (and Parents Sane),'' focuses on how to use that
intuitive fear to protect your children as well as yourself from
danger.
</P>
<P>
   By D. Parvaz. (Story will move in the ``l'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (Minneapolis) _ Seattle Mariners defeat the
Minnesota Twins as Ken Griffey Jr. belts his 19th home run.
