<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2413 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPTAIN-WOMAN-SPI &LR;      05-26 1361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPTAIN-WOMAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRITTY SKIPPER STEERS THROUGH UNFAMILIAR SEA OF BOOK PUBLICITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By M.L. LYKE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ ``Ma'' would rather be fishing. She would rather be
1,500 miles out to sea, staring down the eye of a hurricane. She
would rather be jerry-rigging a circulating pump with a garden
hose, planting the gaff hook in a bulbous swordfish eye, or yanking
the chain on a rebellious crewmember.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Linda Greenlaw _ called ``Ma'' by her seagoing staff _
would rather be doing almost anything than writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't enjoy it at all,'' says the plain-talking author of
``The Hungry Ocean'' (Hyperion, 265 pages, $22.95), an account of
Greenlaw's experiences as a swordfish captain working the
treacherous waters of Grand Banks, southeast of Newfoundland.
</P>
<P>
   Greenlaw, the gritty, high-catch skipper made famous in
Sebastian Junger's 1997 best seller ``The Perfect Storm,'' calls
her book ``265 pages of sustained effort.''
</P>
<P>
   She admits she's in it for the money.
</P>
<P>
   That begins with the $150,000 advance she received from
Hyperion. Hyperion was top fish in a bidding war with eight other
publishing houses for rights to the story of Greenlaw's life aboard
the 100-foot Hannah Boden, sister ship to the Andrea Gail, the
doomed swordfish boat in ``The Perfect Storm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing,'' says the reluctant author, stopping in Seattle
on a 35-city, three-month promotion tour earlier this week. ``You
get paid before you ever do any work.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenlaw's agent has already sold foreign rights to the book,
and she has recorded a taped version for Brilliance Audio.
</P>
<P>
   Greenlaw, whose previous writing experience consists mainly of
college term papers and the occasional letter, will be meeting on
Thursday with a Los Angeles movie agent, who has producers lined up
to talk about putting ``The Hungry Ocean'' on the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   The hoopla doesn't end there.
</P>
<P>
   She's been named to Vanity Fair's ``Hall of Fame,'' been
interviewed for People magazine, appeared on the Discovery Channel
and ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Boston magazine named her one of the most ``intriguing women of
1997'' after Junger's book hit best-seller lists.
</P>
<P>
   He described her as one of ``the best captains, period, on the
entire East Coast.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he's calling her book ``the best book, period, I've ever
read on fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   The book is not the riveting disaster-at-sea some readers may
expect. Nor is it a sequel to ``The Perfect Storm'' _ in fact,
Greenwall barely touches on the disappearance of the Andrea Gail in
the brutal Halloween storm of 1991.
</P>
<P>
   It is also not a manifesto of feminist triumph. Greenwall, who
insists she's no feminist, maintains being a woman in this
male-dominated world has been ``no big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor, she says, has she ever been hit on by her crew. ``When I
first started hearing about sexual harassment, I felt bad,'' she
says with a wry smile. ``I kept wondering, `What's the matter with
me?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The book is, simply, a thorough, matter-of-fact look at everyday
life aboard a 100-foot swordfish boat, from the intricacies of
Doppler radar in the wheelhouse to the frictions between captain
and crew on deck.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times called it less dramatic, but saltier than
``The Perfect Storm.'' ``The Hungry Ocean'' is a beautiful book for
what it says about the love of the sea,'' writes Douglas Whynott.
</P>
<P>
   The incoming tide of hype surrounding it is strange waters for a
38-year-old woman who rolls up her sleeves and tells it like it is,
whether she's on the deck of a boat or at the keyboard of a
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she's determined to enjoy it _ while it lasts. ``I know
all this attention I'm getting is going to be short-lived. It's my
15 minutes of fame, and I'm going to enjoy every last second of
it,'' says the high-energy woman, who stands 5-foot-3 in her size 6
rubber boots and has to buy women's flowered gardening gloves to
haul in longlines.
</P>
<P>
   Men's work gloves are too big.
</P>
<P>
   The pants, however, fit just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The woman thing is not a problem. If the crew didn't want to
go to sea with a woman, they wouldn't ask to work with me,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Greenlaw hates the term fisherwoman. ``It's not even in the
dictionary.''
</P>
<P>
   No one's likely to call her a lady, either.
</P>
<P>
   Ladies don't stand on the decks of their boats yelling
obscenities and giving the finger to a monster $2,000 swordfish
that has slipped its hook.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do they relate with relish the slow torture of a blue shark,
hung by a noose from the Hannah Boden's rigging, thrashing wildly
as it is swaddled in rags saturated in lighter fluid, slashed with
knifes, and set ablaze, producing a ``strangely satisfying
stench.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenlaw wears no makeup, no jewelry and pulls her brown hair
back in a no-fuss ponytail. Her wind-weathered face is a map of
fine lines that appear and disappear as she talks at fast-forward
speed, her tiny hands tapping at the table, her big brown eyes
moving out the window to Elliott Bay, and Puget Sound and back
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has eyes like an eagle,'' says Eric Maxcy, one of the
crewmembers who has worked with Greenlaw fishing the waters off
Gloucester, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Greenlaw's crew describe her as big-hearted, tough-skinned,
pushy, smart, funny and, on occasion, temperamental.
</P>
<P>
   One boat captain said that when Greenlaw sticks out her lower
lip, it's time to back off. She's famed for throwing a fire ax at a
television set to get her crew's attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen her mad a couple of times, and it wasn't good,''
says Eric's nephew Michael ``Carl'' Maxcy, one of the crewmen
featured in the book.
</P>
<P>
   He calls ``The Hungry Ocean'' ``accurate to a fault.'' That
includes his own blowouts with a hated crewmember.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets pretty tense at times. You're out on a boat for 30
days, people get to wearing at you, stressing you out bad,'' says
Maxcy. ``Some trips you love them to pieces, other trips you want
to kill them. One wrong word will set you off.''
</P>
<P>
   Swordfish boats fishing the Grand Banks generally work on the
lunar cycle, spending 30 days at sea, baiting 40 miles of longline
with whole squid. Captains, who can make up to $200,000 in three
months of fishing, search for warm Gulf Stream currents to make
their sets, and work alongside the crew when the fish are hauled
in, sometimes going days without sleep.
</P>
<P>
   It's a life of bone-wearying fatigue, and Greenlaw captures that
unerringly. ``At some point in every trip, everyone reaches a stage
of exhaustion unimaginable to anyone who has never quite been
there. It is a state beyond dead tired, a fatigue that goes all the
way to the bitter end of each and every hair on your head.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenlaw grew up in Maine, spending summers on the Isle au Haut,
a remote island with a year-round population of 65 to 70 that has
been home to generations of Greenlaws.
</P>
<P>
   She was _ and still is, she says with a laugh _ a tomboy. ``My
hero was Daniel Boone. I had a plastic musket and a coonskin hat. I
played all day in the woods, building forts and shooting my
slingshot.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 12, she had her first taste of what she calls
``sea-fever,'' and soon, while her sister was out stealing the
family car, Greenwall was out stealing the family boat.
</P>
<P>
   By 19, the young college English major was fishing to earn extra
money. And by her 20s, the hard-working college girl was giving up
dreams of law school to captain her first swordfish boat.
</P>
<P>
   She switched from swordfishing to running her own inshore
lobster boat out of Isle au Haut last year _ operating a 35-footer
called the Mattie Belle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been at sea so long, I felt I was missing out on a lot. I
figured I could do the lobster boat while figuring out what to do
with the rest of my life. I wanted to marry and have kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenwall, who has had a long string of fisherman boyfriends, is
reconsidering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a real flip-flopper on the marriage thing,'' she says, her
fingers tapping. ``I just don't know about this rest-of-the-life
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   She turns her eagle eyes back to the bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, what kind of guy could put up with my lifestyle?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
