A2414 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-CHINA-BOS &LR;      05-26 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-CHINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPLICATION OF PLEA BARGAINS WORRIES GOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When a Senate panel two years ago investigated
allegations that foreign money was given to the Democratic Party,
it hoped to nail down the specifics with testimony from three
fund-raisers with connections to the Chinese government. But all
three men refused to testify without being granted immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the same three men, John Huang, Yah Lin ``Charlie'' Trie
and Johnny Chung, are secretly telling what they know to the
Justice Department in exchange for guilty pleas to relatively minor
offenses.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans worry that the plea bargains, rather than
helping the government get to the bottom of the campaign finance
scandal, are an effort by the Clinton administration to end the
investigation quietly and avoid the publicity of a trial and
possible implications toward the president and vice president or
other officials.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign finance cases have extra significance in the wake
of this week's House select committee report that China has
systematically been stealing US nuclear secrets. From the start of
the campaign finance probe, Republicans have tried to investigate
whether Chinese authorities plowed money into the Democratic Party
in exchange for some kind of favor, such as access to satellite
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks bad,'' said Senator Fred Thompson, the Tennessee
Republican who headed the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee
investigation in 1997. He noted Huang reportedly has not implicated
``higher-ups.'' ``If this is the kind of cooperation they are
getting for a probation sentence, it heightens our concern,'' he
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said he plans to launch a new investigation focusing on
why the Justice Department decided to plea bargain. Thompson often
has said an independent counsel should be appointed to examine the
campaign finance matter because the administration has a vested
interest in closing the probe.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest matter, Huang is expected to plead guilty on
Monday in Los Angeles to a felony charge involving $7,500 in
donations. The plea does not deal directly with some $1.6 million
in contributions Huang raised for the Democrats that were later
returned amid questions about the source of the funds. Huang's
lawyer, Ty Cobb, did not respond to a request for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department spokesman Myron L. Marlin said Wednesday that
it would be a mistake to presume the plea bargains signal an end to
the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is actually a sign that our investigation is continuing
and that we are making progress,'' Marlin said. Another senior
Justice Department official stressed that the agency is dealing
with laws that are often confusing and poorly written, making
prosecutions difficult, but he said all leads are being followed.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Madigan, the Republican counsel for the Senate
campaign finance probe, said the plea bargains look like an effort
to end the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has all the earmarks of something being swept under the
rug,'' Madigan said. He said it was troubling that Huang is
pleading guilty to ``one of the most minor things he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Huang is expected to be charged with making an
illegal $2,500 donation to a candidate for Los Angeles mayor and a
$5,000 contribution to the 1994 California Victory Fund. Thompson
said he wants to know why Huang isn't being charged in connection
with a $100,000 fund-raiser at Buddhist temple in California that
Vice President Al Gore attended.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson noted that the House committee that released the
Chinese espionage report on Tuesday was unable to get testimony
from Huang, and he said the Justice Department did not cooperate
fully with the spy probe.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the plea agreement, Huang, a former Commerce
Department official who then went to work at the Democratic
National Committee, was portrayed by some Republicans as the
possible mastermind of an illegal foreign fund-raising operation.
He is slated to be given probation without any jail time. He also
will receive a statement that the Justice Department found no
evidence Huang was involved in espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Trie, a former Arkansas restauranteur who has known
President Clinton for years, agreed to cooperate with the campaign
finance probe in exchange for pleading guilty to a felony count of
making false statements to the Federal Election Commission. Many of
Trie's contributions came from Asia, prompting the DNC to return
$645,000 solicited by him. In addition, Clinton's legal fund
returned returned $639,000 raised by Trie.
</P>
<P>
   The third fund-raiser, Chung, who brought numerous Chinese
guests to the White House for photos with Clinton, pleaded guilty
last year to charges that he gave about $28,000 in illegal campaign
contributions to Democrats. He was sentenced to five years
probation. Chung had given about $400,000 to Democrats, all being
returned when questions were raised about the source of the money.
Earlier this month, Chung testified before a House committee that
he met in 1996 with a high-ranking Chinese intelligence official
who said he would provide $300,000 for the Clinton campaign.
</P>
<P>
   This week's House report on Chinese espionage also referred to
Chung, saying he was given $300,000 by two Chinese military
officials. Chung was supposed to use the money to establish the
daughter of a Chinese general as a businessperson who would be in
position to purchase US technology, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Chung formed Marswell Investments Inc., with Colonel Liu
Chaoying, daughter of the Chinese General Liu Huaqing, as president
of the company. In July 1996, Chung took Liu to a DNC fund-raiser
and she met Clinton, according to the House panel report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Select Committee determined that Col. Liu's payment to
Johnny Chung was an attempt to better position her in the United
States to acquire computer, missile, and satellite technologies,''
the report said. The report did not say, however, whether any of
the $300,000 was given to the Democratic Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
