<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE PASSES SOCIAL SECURITY 'LOCK BOX' BILL
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With prospects for Social Security and Medicare
reform in this Congress doubtful, the House passed a largely
symbolic measure Wednesday that declares the surplus from those
programs off limits for federal spending.
</P>
<P>
   The 416-12 vote came on a Republican bill that would impose a
new parliamentary hurdle _ requiring a majority vote of the House
and 60 votes in the Senate _ before Congress could use any part of
the projected $1.8 trillion in Social Security and Medicare
surpluses over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1969, Social Security and Medicare have been included in
the federal budget. Money from payroll taxes for those programs is
collected and then spent in other ways, in exchange for special
Treasury bonds that will finance the programs in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 30 years, federal budgeteers have included Social Security
surpluses in their reporting to cover up what what's really going
on in the rest of the federal budget,'' said Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr.,
R-Fla., who co-sponsored the bill. ``This safe deposit box stops
the federal government from hiding behind Social Security surpluses
to claim that its budget is balanced.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats complained the bill was unnecessary and did not
resolve Social Security's long-term financial problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans have offered a 'lock box' that has nothing in
it, except money that already belongs to Social Security,'' said
Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y. ``It's an empty gesture designed to
fool the American people into thinking something has been done for
Social Security. In reality, the Republican leadership has no plans
to push through any legislation to preserve Social Security and
Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, who chairs the House Social Security subcommittee and has
cosponsored a reform bill, said he believes the program will be
reformed during this Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
