<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRILLS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Casual living has folks firing up the barbecue with charcoal,
gas
 &HT;    By Sabine Morrow
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Memorial Day kicks off the summer cookout season _
although, according to the Barbecue Industry Association, more than
half of Americans are cooking out year-round. That's easy to do in
Atlanta, with its fairly mild winters, outdoor-friendly summer
evenings and glorious autumns and springs.
</P>
<P>
   When and what to plan for a meal outdoors is simple. What's a
bit tougher is deciding on the kind of grill to buy.
</P>
<P>
   With all the options at our disposal _ from side burners and
infrared rotisseries to woks and griddles _ it's hard to imagine
that many of us cut our grilling teeth on a hibachi. That puny
barbecue held a handful of charcoal, and the cooking surface was
hardly large enough for a couple of burgers, much less a pair of
hefty steaks.
</P>
<P>
   These days, says the BIA, which tracks barbecue trends, people
are investing in higher quality and bigger grills.
</P>
<P>
   And increasingly they're opting for gas grills. According to the
BIA's latest survey, consumers purchased 7.9 million gas grills and
5 million charcoal models in 1998. Donna Myers, BIA spokeswoman,
says grill sales have shown the most increase in the $400-$800
price range.
</P>
<P>
   One reason consumers are willing to spend more is because they
lead a more casual lifestyle. ``They don't want to entertain with
white linens as much these days,'' she said. ``What began as casual
Fridays has extended throughout the week. Now people want to invite
friends over in jeans. It's less formal and grilling lends itself
perfectly to that.''
</P>
<P>
   John Miniutti, manager of Barbeques Galore Atlanta _ which sells
more gas grills than charcoal grills _ says what attracts many of
his customers to high-end gas models are larger cooking surfaces
and higher Btu (or British thermal units, which measure the heat
generated). ``The big factor in grilling is high heat. The faster
you can sear the meat and get those grill marks on the better. That
ensures that it retains flavor and doesn't get dried out. And the
two things that allow for that in a gas grill are heavy cooking
surfaces and high Btu. With those in place you can come close to
getting the same flavor as you get with a charcoal grill,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Miniutti also sees a growing number of buyers who want grills
that can be connected to a direct natural gas line.
</P>
<P>
   ``In time, they end up saving money over using the liquid
propane tanks, and it's so convenient,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barbecue fanatic Dana Shelton in Decatur agrees. ``It's
absolutely wonderful for the sheer convenience. It's always
there,'' she said. ``There are no tanks to disengage, and you never
have to walk up to your grill and find an empty propane tank while
a houseful of company waits for supper.''
</P>
<P>
   But some aren't sold on gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a gas grill, but I'll never use it again,'' says Jim
Smith of Conyers, who's owned a Big Green Egg ceramic charcoal
grill for six months. ``I love my Egg. It makes the best grilled
food I've ever cooked.''
</P>
<P>
   And while it's hardly a war between owners of gas grills and
those who favor charcoal, each has definite ideas about what he or
she prefers.
</P>
<P>
   For Gerry Klaskala, co-owner of We're Cookin', the group that
owns Canoe, Fishbone and Hedgerose restaurants, there's nothing
like a traditional Weber Kettle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the intensity of the heat and the flavor I get from my
grill,'' he said. Klaskala doesn't feel the need to upgrade to a
high-tech model since he manages to successfully cook a wide
variety on his basic, charcoal-fueled Weber. ``I've cooked
everything from lobsters and scallops to vegetables on my grill,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another trend on the upswing is built-in grills. Some
manufacturers offer drop-in grill tops that fit into self-contained
islands that come in a variety of materials and colors. These
custom units are more expensive, but they allow for greater
flexibility and virtually turn that deck or patio into an outdoor
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   DCS Stainless Steel Gas Grill
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Price: $3,995.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Features: Looking very much like a restaurant-style range,
this sleek grill boasts a heavy-duty 693-square-inch cooking
surface and a spacious double-door cart. The four-burner power
horse fires up with 20,000 Btu per burner and also comes with a
15,000 Btu side burner and a rear rotisserie. Accessories include a
range-top wok and griddle plate.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Comments: While car buffs may fantasize about a sleek Italian
sports car, grilling fans no doubt dream of the DCS stainless steel
professional gas grill. With one of these on your deck, you might
never feel the need to use your kitchen range again. Definitely for
serious entertainers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Retailers: Available at Barbeques Galore at 6550 Roswell Road,
Sandy Springs (Ga.), and 3885 Venture Drive, Duluth (Ga.); Home
Depot Expo at Perimeter Mall.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
