<SLUG> BC-U.N.-AID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. PRESSES FOR MORE AID TO POOR COUNTRIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Reflecting concern that the war in Kosovo is
diverting political energy and scarce resources from other
conflicts, Secretary-General Kofi Annan appealed on Wednesday to
world leaders to do more next month at the meeting of major
industrialized nations to help the developing world.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the heads of the Group of Seven industrialized
countries and Russia, Annan pressed for increased development aid
and greater debt relief for debt-ridden Third World countries and
additional steps to shore up the international financial system,
whose stability he said is key to preventing global recession.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, diplomats are quietly complaining that the
international community, preoccupied with Kosovo, is paying too
little attention to conflicts in Angola, Ethiopia and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday morning, for instance, the Security Council
expressed ``deep concern'' at the deteriorating situation in
Angola, where until a few months ago the United Nations thought it
had settled a long, bloody civil war, only to see fighting erupt
again this year.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing a description of the conflict and an impassioned
plea for emergency assistance, from Francesco Strippoli, the U.N.
humanitarian coordinator for Angola, the council expressed
``particular concern'' about the relief groups' lack of access to
hundreds of thousands of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   They have been displaced within Angola by the fighting between
the government and Unita, its rebel opponents who control many of
the roads leading to the now besieged provincial cities to which
thousands have fled.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Strippoli said that $110 million in food and
other assistance was desperately needed just to sustain the 1.6
million internally displaced Angolans, 950,000 of whom have lost
their homes and possessions since December.
</P>
<P>
   There was little doubt, he said, that the crisis in Kosovo was
preoccupying the international community. While refusing to
``compare human misery'' and acknowledging that the situation in
the Balkans was also horrendous, he said that the conflict in the
Balkans was making it even harder for diplomats and donors to focus
on the plight of Angolans.
</P>
<P>
   Another war that seems to be escalating is that between Ethiopia
and Eritrea, now Africa's _ and perhaps the world's _ largest.
``The Security Council is doing practically nothing,'' Fesseha
Tessema, Ethiopia's minister counselor, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council took no action last Wednesday after hearing
a briefing on U.N. efforts to end a conflict that has killed
thousands and, according to UNICEF, displaced more than 550,000
people.
</P>
<P>
   A U.N. special envoy has been trying to mediate an end to the
conflict, but the council decided to wait for further action by the
Organization of African Unity, which has brokered a peace
agreement, before taking any formal action.
</P>
<P>
   Tessema blamed what he called a lack of concern about a conflict
in poor, remote Africa for the lack of response. ``If this war were
in Europe, or close to the United States, there would more council
intervention,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Louise Frechette, the deputy secretary-general, did not agree
that the council or the United Nations was focusing solely on
Kosovo at the expense of other conflicts. The United Nations, she
said in an interview, was ``extremely active'' in trying to
alleviate human misery and find political solutions to numerous
conflicts throughout the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 2009EDT &QL; 
