<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASINO27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Faulty odds kill casino
 &HT;    By Ralph Ellis
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Kialegee Indians are giving up on Carroll County,
but not on Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The Oklahoma-based tribe will drop all plans to build a casino
in Carroll County, according to Ken Baldwin, the businessman who
represents the tribe.
</P>
<P>
   However, the tribe may try its luck at other locations in the
Kialegee's ancestral homeland, which includes all of Georgia and
most of Alabama. Baldwin said he'll talk to tribal leaders within a
week to determine their wishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless there's some significant change, we won't exercise any
energy or money in pursuit of anything in Carroll County,'' Baldwin
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin formed an investment group that joined with the Kialegee
Indians in proposing a 150,000-square-foot casino, a 350-room hotel
and a golf course off I-20 near the Alabama line.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin stressed the economic benefits of a casino, saying one
would pump up the local economy. The tribe offered to pay state and
local government $1 billion over 10 years from machine game
winnings.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was slapped down twice on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, Gov. Roy Barnes strongly repeated his opposition
to all kinds of gambling and to the casino proposal in particular.
That night, the Carroll County Commission unanimously voted against
the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll County Commission Chairman Jack Bell said the board
initially liked the casino idea, but support disappeared as
religious groups and state legislators came out in opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Bell said Barnes's comments on Tuesday finally killed the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the tribe could keep pushing the casino plan in
Carroll County through a complicated federal appeals process,
according to the National Indian Gaming Association, a Washington
lobbying group.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian Gaming Regulatory Act requires states to negotiate
with tribes that want to operate casino-style gambling. The tribe
and state must reach an agreement that outlines the kind of games
offered, the size of the facility, betting limits, security and
other issues.
</P>
<P>
   If a tribe thinks a state is not negotiating in good faith, it
can ask the federal courts to appoint a mediator. The U.S.
secretary of the Interior has the final authority to set conditions
and procedures for tribes to offer casino gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin said the Kialegee tribe won't pursue that option. ``Even
thought the law is written in our favor, we do not intend to push
this in a hostile way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   June Fixico, the Kialegee chief in Wetumka, Okla., said
Wednesday she didn't know what the tribe would do next. She said
the tribe wanted to set up a reservation in Georgia because it has
no reservation of its own in Oklahoma and occupies a tribal town on
a Creek reservation.
</P>
<P>
   She said the tribe has about 450 members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going back to our ancestral homeland for economic
development for the people,'' Fixico said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
