<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2427 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-RECORDS27-COX     05-26 0363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-RECORDS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Games officials due to reply to Congress query next week
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Olympic officials said they will respond to a
congressional inquiry into the city's bid for the 1996 Summer Games
early next week.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation will provide a thorough
response to questions about excessive gifts, favors and visits by
International Olympic Committee members, according to spokesman Lee
Echols.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good opportunity to start clearing the air on some of
these issues,'' said Echols.
</P>
<P>
   Echols said the response will be far more detailed than the one
prepared for an IOC investigation of the bid cities from 1996
through 2004 in the wake of a bribery scandal that has tarnished
Salt Lake City's winning effort for the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta organizers have admitted to exceeding spending limits on
gifts for IOC members, but told the IOC in March that they did
nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta won the games `fair and square' in an honorable
manner,'' bid chairman Billy Payne wrote in a letter to IOC
President Juan Antonio Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   A congressional committee that has looked into the Salt Lake
City matter announced earlier this month that it now is seeking
evidence to determine whether Atlanta bidders bribed IOC delegates
in return for votes.
</P>
<P>
   A House subcommittee is trying to determine if the Foreign
Corrupt Practices Act should extend to the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC is undergoing massive reforms because of the corruption
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee asked the GAAF to document cash payments or
other inducements for IOC members, such as medical services,
employment help, athletic training services, sports equipment,
scholarships and shopping sprees.
</P>
<P>
   After reviewing the written report, the subcommittee said it
likely will send investigators to dig through the 1,400 boxes of
Olympic records stored at the Atlanta History Center.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation is embroiled in a legal fight with Atlanta media
organizations to keep some of the bid records sealed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
