<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2428 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONET-GIVERNY-2TAKES-     05-26 1356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONET-GIVERNY-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LASTING IMPRESSIONS FROM PAINTER'S FARHOUSE STUDIO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
EDS: MOVING WITH ART 
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; GIVERNY, France _ The azalea bush, in riotous bloom at water's
edge, offers a splash of pink against a backdrop of green
shrubbery. The contrast is gently muted as the sun ducks
momentarily behind a cloud. Then a breeze ripples the surface of
the pond, reducing the reflected image of this scene to an
indistinct smudge.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Claude Monet spent so much time here, enchanted by the
interplay of color, light and form. No wonder he planted his easel
here _ on this very spot _ and dabbed furiously at his canvas in
order to capture the subtleties of various scenes before nature
irretrievably altered them.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Monet grew so comfortable in his two-story farmhouse at
Giverny, and derived so much inspiration from the sprawling gardens
that adjoined it, that he called it home for the final 43 years of
his life. He'd often carry his palette outdoors, where he would
stand transfixed by willows, water lilies, poplars and flowers of
every hue.
</P>
<P>
   That's probably why the gardens are such a popular day trip for
tourists who are staying in Paris. One day, you can stand in the
Musee Marmottan, surveying a Monet oil that hangs on a wall in the
basement. The next, after a one-hour train ride to the west, it is
as if that static painting has become a window, opened onto
reality.
</P>
<P>
   For lovers of art, it is a unique opportunity. Impressionism was
far out of step with the mainstream when it began to develop as a
discipline in the 1870s, such that many of its masters labored in
obscurity and poverty. For Monet's paintings, however, a receptive
audience was found in America, and he was actually able to make
some money at it.
</P>
<P>
   In 1891, impressionist painter Camille Pissarro wrote to his
son, Lucien: ``People want only Monets, it seems he can't paint
enough to go round. ... Everything he does goes straight to America
at prices of 4,000, 5,000 and 6,000 francs.''
</P>
<P>
   The uncommon prosperity enabled Monet to purchase a former cider
farm in the Normandy countryside that he had been renting since
1883. It also gave him the capital to acquire adjacent land, saving
some of his beloved poplars from the lumber mill.
</P>
<P>
   And then Monet got comfortable, designing and nurturing the
gardens on his five-acre property as lovingly as he created his
oils.
</P>
<P>
   It's all meticulously preserved today, creating kind of a
turn-of-the-century time warp for art pilgrims: the water lily
pond, the Japanese bridge, the stately willows at water's edge, the
archways of wisteria and carpets of rhododendron in the garden
nearer the house.
</P>
<P>
   It is such a natural lure for tourists that the grounds can get
oppressively crowded, obliterating any sense of the serenity that
Monet knew while living there with his mistress and future wife,
Alice Hoschede, and their children. The line out front of the house
has been known to result in waits of up to 1{ hours, and at times
visitors must be confined to the gardens when the house itself gets
crammed full.
</P>
<P>
   But there are ways to avoid the peak periods.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; Groups of French schoolchildren tend to make their field
trips on Tuesdays and Thursdays; Wednesdays, which are off days in
French schools, are often much quieter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; Be alert for cloudy, cold or even wet days. Many tourists
will be chased off by these conditions. A heavy coat and an
umbrella will likely be the only fortification you'll need against
the elements.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; Another opportune time to visit is just after the gardens'
10 a.m. opening on Saturdays and Sundays. France's inveterate night
owls seem to stir a bit more slowly on those days.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; And although Giverny is at the zenith of its tourist
popularity _ May and June, when the irises and roses are in full
cry _ other times of its April-through-October season should not be
ignored. On a chilly, damp day in the middle of April, the tulips
were nonetheless glorious. In July and into August, the water
lilies burst into bloom. And in the fall, the garden is a wild,
junglelike place, with nasturtiums holding forth.
</P>
<P>
   Most visitors roam the grounds with their cameras at the ready,
hopeful of finding Monet's exact vantage point for one of his
paintings _ perhaps that of ``Le Bassin aux Nympheas,'' from 1899,
which they might have seen earlier in the Musee d'Orsay. In doing
so, most search in vain for the holy grail of the Giverny tourist:
a famous Monet inspiration ... with no gaggle of sweatsuit-clad
tourists mucking up the very center of it.
</P>
<P>
   But even if that photograph is utterly unachievable, the visit
is no less rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to Giverny is simple enough _ and doesn't require the
prohibitively expensive rental of a car or the confounding
negotiation of France's country roads.
</P>
<P>
   Northwestbound trains from Paris' Gare St.-Lazare reach Vernon
in just under an hour; round-trip fare about $23 for second class,
$33 for first. At the train station, don't expect ticket-sellers to
be fluent in English. But if you have difficulty acquiring a ticket
_ key words: ouest (west) and Normandy _ seek out the information
kiosk near the train platforms, under the ``Accueil'' sign. They
have a bottomless supply of one-page, English-language fliers that
provide all the information needed for a Giverny excursion.
</P>
<P>
   After stepping down from the train in Vernon, you'll find
shuttle buses lining up less than a block from the station's front
door. They cover the 15-minute ride to Giverny for a round-trip
fare of just under $7.
</P>
<P>
   Taxis also queue up to meet the trains. For a one-way ride, the
meter will run to about $11 with tip, but this mode has the added
advantage of beating the buses, which means less time in line at
the other end. And the drivers definitely know the drill. A few
years ago, a cabbie collected a party of five and sped off without
even receiving a word as to the intended destination. Minutes
later, still with no exchange whatsoever, he pulled to a stop in
front of Monet's door.
</P>
<P>
   Admission to the house and gardens is about $6 for adults, $3.50
for children, but if you don't immediately relish standing in a
long, shuttle-fed line to pay it, one option is to fortify yourself
with lunch at Les Nympheas, just across the street. For an
establishment that does not have to worry about repeat business, it
is surprisingly good.
</P>
<P>
   Its offerings recently included intriguing salads (one featured
chicken gizzards and livers), vegetables that tasted as if they'd
just been plucked from the garden, and such tasty standards as
roast chicken and quiche. An added benefit: The proprietors realize
that their patrons are anxious to get to the house and flower
gardens across the street, so you won't be subjected to the
interminable waits between courses (and for the bill) that
characterize the languorous experience of most French cafes.
</P>
<P>
   The art world may have gotten lucky with Monet's house and
gardens, in that the painter's youngest son, Michel, spent the
1950s selling off the paintings he'd inherited and traipsing the
world, rather than fathering heirs.
</P>
<P>
   Michel bequeathed the house and grounds to France's Academie des
Beaux-Arts, which ensured that the property _ which had fallen into
a terrible state of disrepair _ was restored and maintained as a
kind of national treasure.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, Giverny will celebrate its 20th year since an
extensive restoration. Throughout those two decades, a painstaking
effort has been made to achieve as much authenticity as possible in
re-creating the gardens as Monet knew them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like archeology,'' said Claudette Lindsey,
assistant director of the Claude Monet Foundation, which
administers the property. ``You have to find out what was planted
here, what was planted here. We tried to look at some paintings,
and many old photographs of that time. There were letters that
people had written about the paintings (after visiting Monet at his
home), and they made references to the gardens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
