<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0342 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2429 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-CRIME27-COX     05-26 1603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-CRIME27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crime mars ANC's political record
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ First, the African National
Congress defeated apartheid. Then, five years ago, the party
defeated all others in an election and formed South Africa's first
black-led government.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one enemy the ANC has not been able to defeat, the
only foe that seems to pose any threat at all to the party's drive
to win re-election Wednesday and install Thabo Mbeki, Nelson
Mandela's personally selected successor, as president.
</P>
<P>
   The enemy is crime. It is rampant.
</P>
<P>
   People _ black, white, Indian and colored _ are scared,
particularly in urban areas such as Johannesburg and Cape Town.
Some lifelong residents are fleeing the country, taking with them
their business knowledge, capital and ability to employ people.
Rates for some violent crimes are higher than anywhere else in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   And each edition of the daily paper seems to bring news of
crimes more horrifying than those of the day before.
</P>
<P>
   Consider these stories from several days of recent newspapers in
Johannesburg:
</P>
<P>
   _ Paramedic Bongani David Khumalo was shot and killed in Soweto.
The goal of the killers: to hijack his ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   _ Six people posing as police officers flagged down Johannesburg
businessman Zunaid Tayob, kidnapped him and held him for $300,000
in ransom. Tayob was eventually freed by police.
</P>
<P>
   _ Police Sgt. Jetro Jabulani Mbatha was ambushed in Soweto and
shot dead. The same day, Inspector Jacques Joubert, with the
highway patrol in Gauteng province, which includes Johannesburg,
was killed in a running gun battle with about 15 men who were
trying to steal money from private security guards at a mall. One
of the robbers was also killed.
</P>
<P>
   _ In KwaZulu-Natal, where Durban is located, five youths ages 12
to 18 were arrested for shooting to death an 83-year-old farmer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Police in Johannesburg were searching for four Zimbabwean men
believed to have committed five robberies around Johannesburg _
home invasions in which they tortured people with hot irons.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mayor Kabelo Mashi of Ventersdorp, a town west of
Johannesburg, was found dead in a sunflower field, apparently
stabbed to death by a man to whom he had given a ride. The man,
police said, had forced the mayor to withdraw the equivalent of
$666 from his bank account, then killed him.
</P>
<P>
   Interspersed with all those were crimes given lesser amounts of
newspaper space _ a horrendous spate of rapes, murders, carjackings
and other crimes that have become commonplace in South Africa
today. Carjackers are known to spread debris across roads to cause
flat tires, then murder the driver when he or she gets out to put
on the spare.
</P>
<P>
   Even police are not immune from South Africa's crime wave. The
Mail &AMP; Guardian newspaper in Johannesburg reported that from 1994
to 1998, 240 police officers, on average, were murdered every year.
In the United States, which has a population more than six times
that of South Africa, the average was 70 police officers murdered
each year. In England and Wales, with a combined population 20
percent higher than that of South Africa, the average is fewer than
two officers killed per year.
</P>
<P>
   The crime wave has a lot of South Africans frightened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting a bloody hell of a lot worse,'' said Franie
Terblanche, a 68-year-old retired train engineer who lives in an
Afrikaner neighborhood in Pretoria. ``Theft, housebreaking, rape,
hijacking. And, goodness me, murders!''
</P>
<P>
   That's not just his opinion. South Africa's murder rate is one
of the highest in the world _ 15.9 murders per 100,000 people in
1997, more than twice the U.S. rate of 6.8 per 100,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Terblanche and many others blame the ANC _ even though, he said,
the ANC declines to accept responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that's gone wrong, they pronounce apartheid,'' he
said. ``That's wrong. They can't accept their own wrongcomings.''
</P>
<P>
   Des Naude, an Afrikaner warehouse manager who lives in Pretoria,
said he plans to move himself and his five children to Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   He won't be the first to leave. Last year, 6,770 South Africans
emigrated, according to the government. A survey of South Africans
living in the United States shows that most were engineers,
professors, scientists and lawyers _ and crime was a major reason
they left their native land.
</P>
<P>
   They are people like Benjiy Dubovsky, 51, who gave up his career
as a lawyer in Cape Town in 1995 to live in Dunwoody and sell
residential real estate.
</P>
<P>
   His primary reason, he said, was to get better educational and
job opportunities for his four children. But crime was also a
factor _ and it has gotten a lot worse since he left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I miss the people, and it's a great country,''
Dubovsky said. ``But I have no regrets.''
</P>
<P>
   His father, Gerald Kleinman, who is 73, stayed behind in Cape
Town. But he worries about crime.
</P>
<P>
   Kleinman believes the country has ``blossomed'' as a result of
the end of apartheid and the shedding of its status as an
international pariah.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand,'' he said, ``there's a tremendous
difference, in my opinion, between being freedom fighters and
running a government. They've hit a few snags; the most serious is
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Crime, Kleinman said, has always existed in the black townships.
But when apartheid ended and the crimes spread into the white
areas, it was a surprise, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The struggle for life in the townships was unknown to us,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the rising crime rate has affected blacks as well as whites.
Razor wire spirals atop the walls surrounding mansions in the rich,
predominantly white areas north of Johannesburg. But it swirls,
too, around most homes in Soweto and also around the dirt yards and
corrugated metal shacks of squatter camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot go to my neighbor's without locking my house,'' said
Hlamalani Shemane, 44, who lives in the brick house in Soweto in
which she was born. Glancing through the window at her outhouse,
she added sadly, ``I can't even go to the loo, I have to lock my
house.
</P>
<P>
   The signs of crime are evident throughout downtown Johannesburg,
too. Private guards hired by the city warn visitors not to venture
beyond a small, well-patrolled area. Security guards tote shotguns
in front of storefronts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dangerous just to walk around down here,'' said David
Delange, 27, a white guard hired to protect a clothing shop.
</P>
<P>
   Two prominent downtown hotels have closed _ including,
embarrassingly enough, the Carlton Hotel, where Nelson Mandela made
his victory speech five years ago after winning the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Hillbrow, once a fashionable Johannesburg neighborhood, is now
the home of drug dealers, addicted hookers and hollowed-out hotels.
Police can frisk people at random and quickly come up with
marijuana or crack cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Police also routinely seize heroin, LSD, Ecstacy and other
drugs, said police Sgt. Kriban Naidoo.
</P>
<P>
   These are streets outsiders cannot walk, Naidoo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within seconds, they will grab not only your camera but your
clothes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Police can do little to alleviate the problem. They are
undermanned, undertrained and underpaid. And those, Naidoo said,
are not the only problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our justice system stinks,'' he said. ``What's the use in
arresting a man for a crime when he has enough money to hire a
fancy lawyer, walk out of court and laugh in your face the next
day? What do you do _ arrest him, or take his bribe and let him
go?''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Hillbrow police station, businessman Imraan Hussain,
30, was not happy with the crime in the area or with police efforts
to control it. He had been mugged 20 minutes earlier, in broad
daylight, by a man who waved a knife and wanted Hussain's cell
phone.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time Hussain had been mugged in a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police are pathetically underpaid,'' he said. ``If you pay
people peanuts, you get monkeys working for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Constables patrolling the streets get paid 37,000 rands a year,
Naidoo said _ less than $6,100.
</P>
<P>
   With a national election looming Wednesday, the crime rate has,
naturally, become a political issue. Inkatha Freedom Party posters
taped to power poles, storefronts and the portable toilets that
line the roads of squatter camps bear the slogan ``Make South
Africa Governable'' _ implying that, under the ANC, the country is
descending into chaos.
</P>
<P>
   And the New National Party, the descendant of the party of
apartheid, has harshly criticized the ANC government for having
abolished the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   But ANC spokesman Thabo Masebe said the government is not to
blame for the high crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1994, we took over a police force whose main focus was
hunting down members of the ANC and patrolling townships against
demonstrations,'' Masebe said. ``There was no force dedicated to
bringing down crime.''
</P>
<P>
   When the ANC turned the focus of the department to fighting
crime rather than harassing political enemies, new training was
needed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now on top of the situation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But even some hard-core ANC supporters are not so sure. Bennie
Makololo, 34, who lives in the Alexandra section of Johannesburg
and makes security fences for a living, is black and will vote for
the ANC _ just as he did five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But given the choice, he would take the pre-liberation police
force over the current one.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should have changed everything,'' he said, ``but left the
police alone.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
