<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2430 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONET-GIVERNY-2ndTAKE     05-26 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONET-GIVERNY-2ndTAKE-LADN </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Giverny:  they made references to the gardens.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   The foundation also consulted with Jean-Marie Toulgouat, Monet's
step-great-grandson. Gerald van der Kamp, the head gardener who
oversaw the restoration, even huddled with an elderly man (now
deceased) who was once the apprentice to the nurseryman who sold
Monet many of his plants.
</P>
<P>
   Today, eight gardeners and their assistants tend to the grounds
(Monet employed seven gardeners), and they've had to make several
concessions to the crush of visitors. Most walkways through the
main garden are chained off to prevent the edges of flower beds
from being trampled. Other walkways have been widened and covered
with paving materials.
</P>
<P>
   And the gardens are more orderly and neatly manicured, not the
overgrown jungles that are evident in the black-and-white
photographs of Giverny that remain from Monet's time there.
</P>
<P>
   But Monet, even as his plants overran their beds, had a keen
sense of combining floral varieties to achieve optimal blends of
compatible colors. And that objective is still high on the
foundation's priority list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even people who don't know too much about painting are
interested by the garden side,'' Lindsey said. ``It gives ideas to
people who garden _ the way the colors are organized. It's a very
rich place.''
</P>
<P>
   The house is every bit as intriguing. It has a pink, roughcast
facade, and the shutters are painted the exact shade of green
specified by Monet.
</P>
<P>
   The salon has a large window facing west, such that sunlight
streams in during the late afternoon. Monet used to adorn the walls
with his paintings, studying them in this light; today,
reproductions hang in their place.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen, which looks as if it would seat 50, is done in
gleaming hues of yellow. It overlooks the garden _ and in fact
feels like an extension of it.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the real charms of the dwelling is its huge studio,
where Monet worked beneath the skylights on his enormous canvases
of water lilies and other subjects. The walls of the studio, which
now doubles as a gift shop, are hung with large photographic prints
of the artist at work in his gardens and in this very room. The
studio still holds one of his couches, on which he used to flop for
a nap when his struggles with light and color got to be
particularly vexing.
</P>
<P>
   These gardens, this house, this studio clearly provided
reassurance for Monet. He roamed Normandy, Norway and London
looking for subject matter late in his career, but his letters
suggest he was always anxious to return home.
</P>
<P>
   In 1908, just before the onset of cataracts that began to rob
him of his sight, he wrote to Gustave Geffroy, an art critic,
advocate and friend: ``You should know I am immersed in work. These
landscapes of water and reflection have become my obsession. It is
beyond my old man's strength, yet I still want to convey what I
feel.''
</P>
<P>
   After only a few minutes strolling the Giverny grounds today,
even amid the mob, it isn't difficult to appreciate the
compulsion. &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
