<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2432 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IPO-MARKETPLACE-NYT &LR;      05-26 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IPO-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET INITIAL PUBLIC OFFERINGS NOT ALWAYS GOLDEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Mass.) (rk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks generally rebounded Wednesday from a
four-session losing streak, but not all Internet stocks caught the
wave.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, three Internet issues fell below their offering price
during their first day of trading, and two others posted gains that
were handsome _ but less spectacular than those of their peers in
recent months.
</P>
<P>
   The automatic doubling or tripling of a new Internet stock is
history, investors seemed to be saying as they made clear
distinctions among the various offerings. The stocks of Ziplink
Inc. and Juno Online Services finished below their initial offering
prices, and that of Edgar Online bobbed up from underwater to a
gain of pennies.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, underwriters of an upcoming deal, for Private
Business Inc., responded to the softening market by cutting the
price and reducing the number of shares to be issued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't recall an Internet IPO that fell below its offering
price on the day of offering,'' said Neil Barsky, co-founder of
Midtown Research Group, a hedge fund that specializes in these
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Internet stocks are down sharply from their highs,
Barsky predicted that the tailspin would worsen. Though, ``I don't
think this is the big one,'' he said, resorting to the language of
earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   Pessimism also emerged from Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, whose
highly regarded Internet analyst, Mary Meeker, told the firm's
brokers and strategists that Internet stock prices, already down 46
percent from their highs of last year, could well skid 20 percent
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't uncommon at this time of year for prices of
technology stocks to contract when catalysts are insufficient,''
the firm stated in summarizing her morning comments. ``Also, as the
number of Internet initial public offerings has increased sharply,
it seems the deal quality has declined markedly and we wouldn't be
surprised to see investor resistance.''
</P>
<P>
   Market demand was underwhelming for Ziplink, a Lowell,
Mass.-based company that provides Internet access, which sold 3.5
million shares at $14. The stock closed at $12.375. Another laggard
was Juno Online Services, which provides free e-mail and is
controlled by hedge fund manager David E. Shaw. It was priced at
$13 and sank to $11.625.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Online Inc. of Norwalk, Conn., whose business is helping
investors extract information from documents filed with the
Securities and Exchange Commission, offered 3.6 million shares at
$9.50. After opening at $8.75 and trading as low as $8.50, Edgar
edged up to close at $9.5625.
</P>
<P>
   Although Internet euphoria has been on the wane for much of the
year, it is only this month that Internet initial public offerings
as a group have failed to double from their offering prices.
</P>
<P>
   Through Tuesday, according to a tabulation by Thomson Financial
Securities Data, 22 deals in May averaged first-day gains of 79
percent, just over half the March gain and less than one-third the
gains of a much less active January.
</P>
<P>
   The figures also show that price increases after four weeks of
trading shrank in April to about one-quarter as great as at the
peak in February.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are some Internet analysts who remain bullish, at
least on the higher-quality companies that will be the industry's
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, analysts noted a clear pattern in which these
stocks have tended to suffer immediately after the earnings season
ends _ that is, the middle month of a given quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without any news there isn't any catalyst for these stocks to
go up,'' said Keith Benjamin, senior Internet analyst at BancBoston
Robertson Stephens in San Francisco. He added that ``anybody who
wasn't expecting this wasn't paying attention.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Benjamin said there are too many companies that don't
deserve their high valuations and too many others going public
these days, the group's recovery is only a few weeks away when the
focus moves to second-quarter earnings, which, he said, will once
again surpass expectations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
