<HEADLINE>
THE EXPLORATION OF SPACE AND SMELLING GOOD
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Astronaut &UR; Buzz Aldrin &LR;  was on hand in London this week for the
unveiling of p, which is pronounced ``pi'' and is a new Givenchy
perfume for men.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech quoted in the Telegraph, Aldrin, who has walked on
the moon, said it had a ``stark beauty all its own,'' describing it
as ``a place where I could cover with my thumb the site of all
history. ... Apollo was inevitable in the first gleam in the eye of
the hunter-gatherer. ... We are alive at the morning of a new
renaissance.''
</P>
<P>
   A Givenchy publicist told the Telegraph that Aldrin's role at
the unveiling of the scent _ purported to smell like the ``light,
sunny tempo of tangerine ... the familiar accents of rosemary,
basil and tarragon ... powerfully wild balsamic chords ... cosmic
woody notes'' _ was to serve as ``ambassador for Givenchy.'' Aldrin
himself explained it as ``tying in with exploration and the
specificity of the term `p' and how it has opened up so much for
our understanding of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONSUMING INTERESTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Every chic restaurant has a secret telephone number to enable
preferred customers to get reservations while the common folk are
turned away. Vogue magazine food writer  &UR; Jeffrey &LR; 
 &UR; Steingarten &LR;  tells a tale of Balthazar, New York's hottest spot:
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, Vogue's publication of the secret number
infuriated the restaurant's management, which was forced to change
it and telephone 3,000 customers to give them the new one.
Whereupon the New York Times ran a story about it, and printed the
new number. ``According to reliable reports,'' writes Steingarten,
the restaurant's owner thereupon told people who called that number
that it had been changed, and gave them the home phone number of
the Times reporter.
</P>
<P>
   The owner ``vehemently denied that he had done this,'' writes
Steingarten, ``describing it as an act of extreme immaturity but
saying that if he did do it, he will never do it again, and if he
does do it again, he apologizes profusely in advance.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Having surveyed their readers and voters, the creators of the
Zagat guides to dining have created a 10-point diners' bill of
rights that includes: the rights &LR;  to ``courteous, hospitable,
informative service''; the rights &LR;  to clean bathrooms; the right to
cellular phone-free seating; the right to complain; and No. 10,
``write in your own.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 10: The right to begin the meal with a piece of chocolate
cake and to use one's fork to stab a fellow diner who attempts to
take even the tiniest morsel for him- or herself.
</P>
<P>
   _ Homies, small plastic figurines that come in eight models _
featuring tattoos, baggy clothes and bandannas _ have aroused the
wrath of the Los Angeles Police Department, which thinks they
glorify gangs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; David Gonzales &LR; , creator of the made-in-Taiwan figures, says
they represent a segment of Chicano culture. Los Angeles County
prosecutor  &UR; Michael Jesic &LR;  said he is ``thinking of putting them up
in court and saying, `If you're dressed like these guys, you're
violating probation.' ''
</P>
<P>
   _ Gucci pool toys are ``made of durable rubber,'' says GQ,
``resist burns from Gitanes and promise to keep the biggest fashion
swells afloat. The inner tube costs $190, and the beach ball costs
$290.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Polish TV is reporting that posters advertising lingerie will
be removed from billboards during next month's visit by  &UR; Pope &LR; 
 &UR; John Paul II &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Ted Turner  &LR; said at the University of Montana this week that
he won't run for president because &UR; Jane Fonda &LR;  objects. ``I thought
about it a number of times,'' he said, ``but my wife, who was
married to a politician before, said she would leave me.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Spin magazine asked  &UR; Mike Myers &LR; , who plays Dr. Evil in the
new Austin Powers movie, why his head is shaven. ``I prefer the
smooth look,'' he says. ``There's a lot of anti-hirsute prejudice.
I mean, name one very hairy person in a position of power _ besides
 &UR; Robin Williams &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   _ Random House is rumored to have shelled out a $750,000 advance
for ``Big Stone Gap,'' a first novel by TV writer  &UR; Adriana &LR; 
 &UR; Trigiani &LR; , whose agent told Entertainment Weekly the book is ``
`Fried Green Tomatoes' meets Lake Wobegon.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``One reason why cats are becoming more popular with, or at
least more acceptable to, men is the women's movement of the 1970s.
... More men feel free to like cats.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Cats magazine.
</P>
