<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2434 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EURO-CURRENCY-ART-NYT     05-26 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-CURRENCY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EURO DROPS BELOW $1.05 FOR FIRST TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Where's the bottom for the euro?
</P>
<P>
   That was the question Wednesday as Europe's single currency
plunged below $1.05 for the first time. The euro is now down 10
percent since it began trading at the beginning of the year at
$1.17.
</P>
<P>
   While some currency strategists expect the euro to stabilize
near its current level, they are warning that it could break
through the one dollar barrier. ``Ninety-nine in '99 remains a
possibility,'' said Michael Rosenberg, head of global foreign
exchange research at Deutsche Bank.
</P>
<P>
   For American tourists preparing for European trips this summer,
the decline could not be better timed. The euro's fall is mirrored
in the value of the 11 currencies it represents, including the
German mark, the French franc and the Italian lira. Credit card
charges for tourists are in euros, and there are euro travelers
checks. But cash is still in the old local currencies. Paper euros
and coins will be introduced in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The news is not so good for American exporters, however, whose
products are becoming more expensive in Continental Europe as the
dollar rises in value. (Britain and three other nations in the
European Union _ Greece, Denmark and Sweden _ are not part of the
euro.)
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the euro settled at $1.0455 Wednesday, down 1.4
percent from $1.0601 on Wednesday. The dollar slipped slightly
against the Japanese yen, to 122.17 from 122.70.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the euro's weakness is simple: The American
economy is continuing to grow briskly while the economies of the
euro members, especially Germany and Italy, remain sluggish at
best. Vibrant worker productivity in the United States and the
belief that the potential for growth here is much better than in
Europe also helps the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Those advantages for the dollar have been heightened by the
widening of the differential in interest rates here and in Europe,
which also attracts investors. Since last fall, for example, the
spread between rates on two-year Treasury notes here and in Europe
has gone from six-tenths of a percentage point to 2.7 percentage
points, Rosenberg said. The recent move by the Federal Reserve to
lean toward higher interest rates helped widen that spread.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Wednesday, investors traded with a new worry about the
euro. Late Tuesday, the European Commission approved an increase in
the size of the 1999 Italian budget deficit to 2.4 percent of gross
domestic product from 2 percent. That move was seen by some
strategists as a weakening of the fiscal discipline that is
supposed to be one of the pillars of Euroland, the nickname for the
countries behind the euro.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a sign of fiscal imprudence,'' said Jeremy Fand,
senior foreign exchange strategist at BankBoston. He is forecasting
that the euro will fall to 90 cents by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Sinche, the senior currency strategist at Citibank, is
not as harsh in his interpretation, noting that the stability
agreement for the euro restricts government budget deficits to 3
percent of gross domestic product, and Italy is still below that
key level.
</P>
<P>
   But he says that this restriction on government spending means
there is little hope European governments can put together a
stimulus program to jump-start their economies. This means the only
lift can come from another interest rate cut by the new European
Central Bank, which reduced its benchmark rate by a half-percentage
point in April. And the anticipation of such a move, which would
just widen the gap between interest rates in United States and
Europe, is weighing down the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Sinche and other analysts also said that the NATO campaign
against Yugoslavia was also undermining the euro. The threat of a
land war is one negative. Paying for it, and the rebuilding of
Kosovo and Yugoslavia, given Euroland's tight fiscal restrictions,
is another.
</P>
<P>
   Sinche, however, is forecasting that the American economy will
slow in the second half of the year, while Europe should begin to
rebound. Because of this, he is forecasting that the euro will end
the year in the $1.05 to $1.10 range, above where it is now.
</P>
<P>
   The decline of the euro can be nothing but an embarrassment for
the leaders of its 11 constituents and the European Central Bank,
which is overseeing the currency. Still, several officials said
they were not worried about the decline.
</P>
<P>
   Wim Duisenberg, the president of the European Central Bank, said
the euro's decline was ``not at all unnatural, also not at all
unexpected'' given the sluggish economic growth in Europe,
according to Bloomberg News. But he added that ``recovery is under
way, be it very slowly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
