<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2438 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-RYSHER27-COX     05-26 0391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-RYSHER27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cox unit will stop making TV shows
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a major strategic shift, Cox Broadcasting is
pulling out of the business of making TV shows in a deal with
Paramount valued at more than $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   It's a complex deal in which Cox Broadcasting will shut down its
Rysher Entertainment production unit but continue to own the
library of shows it has produced.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount, the TV unit of one of Hollywood's biggest studios,
will buy the U.S. and international rights to distribute TV shows
and movies from Rysher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that this is a good deal for Cox and for Paramount,''
said Cox Broadcasting President Nick Trigony.
</P>
<P>
   The closing of Rysher is the second step in Cox's withdrawal
from making filmed content.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Rysher shut down its money-losing movie studio and took
a $170 million write-off.
</P>
<P>
   Rysher's closing also marks an about turn from a strategy five
years ago, when Cox Broadcasting and its parent, Atlanta-based Cox
Enterprises, decided it had to make movies and TV shows.
</P>
<P>
   But Cox entered the film production business at the cusp of huge
industry consolidations.
</P>
<P>
   It soon became a player too small to compete with the likes of
industry giants such as Paramount, Warner Bros. and Universal.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Rysher's shows did not do well enough to propel the
company into the big time.
</P>
<P>
   Some of its TV shows, however, have fared well. It co-produced
with Paramount, for example, ``Entertainment Tonight,'' one of the
most watched shows on TV. It was a major moneymaker for Cox
Broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the deal announced Wednesday, Paramount will now
own all of ``Entertainment Tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Paramount will also assume production of Rysher's current shows,
which include CBS' ``Nash Bridges,'' and HBO's ``Sex and the City''
and ``Arli$$.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox Broadcasting will remain in the broadcast business, owning
11 stations.
</P>
<P>
   It also owns or operates, through Cox Radio, 59 radio stations.
Cox Enterprises also owns The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   RYSHER'S TV SHOWS
</P>
<P>
   ``Saved by the Bell''
</P>
<P>
   ``OZ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Highlander''
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Mills Lane''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex and the City''
</P>
<P>
   ``Arli$$''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nash Bridges''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0349 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2439 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCOMPANY27-COX     05-26 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCOMPANY27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern set to tap big U.S. markets
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ Southern Co. is on its way to becoming a
major electric power supplier to Boston, New York, Chicago,
Dallas/Fort Worth and Los Angeles, the company told shareholders
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are standing on the doorstep of some of America's largest
markets,'' Chairman and CEO A.W. ``Bill'' Dahlberg said at the
annual shareholders meeting. Dahlberg noted that six top U.S.
metropolitan areas are within reach of electricity grids supplied
by Southern plants serving its growing wholesale energy market.
</P>
<P>
   Southern last year spent $1.3 billion to acquire power plants
divested by California and New England utilities and will soon
close a $480 million deal in New York. Other plants have been
acquired or are being built in Texas, Wisconsin and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Southern has mapped plans to operate 24,000 megawatts of
generating capacity outside its service territory, Dahlberg told
shareholders. That's more than the company currently operates to
supply its five utilities in the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Dahlberg said the expansion is part of an effort to diversify in
advance of deregulation and competition, which he doesn't foresee
reaching the Southeast until at least 2003.
</P>
<P>
   He said the new businesses will allow Southern to increase its
earnings-per-share growth after 2000 to between 6 percent and 8
percent, compared with an earlier target of 5 percent to 6 percent.
Since 1997, average per-share growth has been 6.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   He also said Southern wants to expand into wholesale and
industrial natural gas sales, but has ``not found the right fit at
the right price'' to acquire a gas company.
</P>
<P>
   Dahlberg also said Southern will ``sharpen our focus
internationally and concentrate on fewer countries.''
</P>
<P>
   The company said it has received approval from the U.S.
Securities and Exchange Commission to sell power and natural gas in
Canada, which is opening its electricity market to competition.
Southern, however, doesn't have any specific plans to do so, said
spokesman Chuck Griffin. He said the company is waiting to see how
the electricity market there develops.
</P>
<P>
   One of the 1,000 shareholders who attended the meeting in
Birmingham questioned the wisdom of Southern's investments to date
in Asia and South America.
</P>
<P>
   The company ``just got burned real good'' in South America,
Herman Falk, a retiree from nearby Pelham, Ala., told Dahlberg
during a question-and-answer session. He was referring to a $200
million writedown taken by Southern last year to reflect declining
value of investments in Chile and Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   Falk also questioned Southern's plans to focus on Brazil and
said China ``just doesn't sound good at all. I wonder where the
wisdom comes from.''
</P>
<P>
   Dahlberg countered that Southern does not have a ``substantial
commitment'' in Brazil and does not anticipate expanding there this
year. He also noted that the Chinese power plants were profitable
last year and a major plant will begin operations during the next
few months in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand the concern about our investments there,'' he
said. ``But despite major turmoil in Asia, there should still be
major opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Falk, however, was not mollified. Southern stock ``used to be
for widows and orphans,'' said Falk, 72, a shareholder for two
decades who relies on Southern dividends for retirement income.
Given the new risks, ``I think I'll sell my Southern stock and buy
Internet shares,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
