<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2440 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT     05-26 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE WAY THE KNICKS CAN WIN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Latrell Sprewell says that the New York Knicks'
second team regularly beats the Knicks' first team in practice so
decisively that ``the first team doesn't want to play us anymore.''
And no one on the Knicks disputes this.
</P>
<P>
   So if the Knicks' second team can do this, is not the second
team better than the first team? Well, you say, that's just in
practice.
</P>
<P>
   OK. But it is also a matter of record, particularly down the
stretch in the regular season and now in both playoff series
against the Heat and the Hawks, that the Knicks are better in real
games when the second team is on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks are better when they run as opposed to setting up in
a half-court offense and allowing the old and ailing Patrick Ewing
and Larry Johnson to pound, pound, pound the ball in post-ups as
they struggle for shots while their teammates become mere
bystanders, albeit with a courtside location that even the
introverted Spike Lee might envy.
</P>
<P>
   No one would argue that it will take the best players the Knicks
have to beat the puissant Pacers. And it follows as night does to
day that the best players should be on the court for the longest
periods of time.
</P>
<P>
   Which leads to the inevitable conclusion: the second team should
start, with one holdover from Team One, and that is Allan Houston.
If I were advising Jeff Van Gundy, the Knicks head coach, as, in
all fake humility I am now, I would try to bring him to his senses.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell, the team's best player, should unquestionably be
starting. Chris Childs is playing better than Charlie Ward, and in
the uptempo style Ernie Grunfeld saw him play for the Nets and
thereafter bought him for a pretty penny. Marcus Camby at 25 does
things in the air that Ewing and Johnson _ and the correctly
traded, 35-year-old Charles Oakley _ could only dream about, even
in, unconscionably, 20 minutes a game.
</P>
<P>
   And Chris Dudley for Ewing. Hold on to the bricks you're tempted
to heave in this direction, Ewing fans. Ewing remains a valuable
asset _ along with Houston the team's best pure shooter _ but the
team moves considerably better than when he's always looking for
his shot.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing is playing the best team ball of his career because he
can't do all the things he once did because of age and infirmity.
It is a blessing in disguise for the Knicks. He now may pass to the
open man.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a little-observed but revealing moment at the end
of Game 5 in Miami. When Houston shot that last shot, he followed
it to, as he said, ``get in position for a rebound.'' Sprewell
darted in for the same. Ewing was at the top of the key, watching
and rooting. He made no move to the basket. Dudley invariably does.
</P>
<P>
   When Ewing was injured and out of the lineup at the end of the
regular season, Houston said that Ewing would have to adjust to the
new style of play. And more or less he has. But he still has the
tendency to be the old Patrick. Dudley doesn't clog up the middle,
which happily frees Sprewell and Childs and Houston and Camby to do
more damage than they ever have collectively before.
</P>
<P>
   The whole business with Sprewell not starting is ludicrous, and
Van Gundy gets no blue ribbons for it. Yes, Sprewell creates a
spark and lift for the team off the bench. But he would be equally
dynamic at the opening tipoff. Sprewell is the team's leading
scorer in the playoffs, at 19 points a game, but is third in
minutes played, at 32.8 to Houston's 34.2 and Johnson's 33.7.
</P>
<P>
   The classic sixth man in this generation was John Havlicek, who
in that role still played more minutes than anyone on the Celtics
except Bill Russell. And Havlicek was a starter by the time he was
28 years old, Sprewell's age. And Sprewell, like Havlicek, never
seems to tire.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Bulls' best player didn't come off the bench to
create a spark. Didn't have to. And even in the grueling six-game
NBA finals against Utah, he managed to play 42 minutes a game and
average 33.5 points. While no one is pretending Sprewell is Jordan,
Sprewell is a superbly conditioned 28-year-old. Jordan was a
superbly conditioned 35-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   If, as Ewing and Johnson say, they are all team and no ego, then
they along with Kurt Thomas might agree wholeheartedly at coming
off the bench _ creating, surely, a spark of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the man who put this team together, the man Lenny
Wilkens, among others, has credited with making the astute trades
for Sprewell and Camby that transformed the team into the current
contender, should not be forgotten. The vote here for the NBA's
executive of the year is Ernie Grunfeld. Should be unanimous.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
