<HEADER>
A2442 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALBANIA-REFUGEES-BOS &LR;      05-26 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANIA-REFUGEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY KOSOVARS BALK AT MOVING TO ALBANIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CEGRANE, Macedonia _ Father and son have heard the buzz. They've
read the flier. All that's left are the one-on-one pitch and maybe
a sneak peak at what they're being offered.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hetemis have no intention of falling for the hard sell.
After a month in Macedonia, they say they're not budging, certainly
not to move to southern Albania. Germany maybe, since they have
family there. Kosovo, sure. Albania, no way, even if it is their
ancestral home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard about people who left, we know they want us to
leave, but we are not leaving this place,'' Lutfi Hetemi, 52, said
as his 22-year-old son, Lulzim, trimmed his hair at one of the
outdoor barber shops that have sprung up in the refugee camp.
``They can try all they want, but we are staying if we are not
accepted to go to Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   UN officials hope to persuade him otherwise. In a campaign
befitting time-share condominiums in Florida or Arizona retirement
communities, southern Albania is being pitched to Kosovo refugees
as the place to be. Open spaces, warmer winters, and better
security all figure into the campaign aimed at the earliest
arrivals, who have settled into their second homes and are loathe
to leave for a third.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Kosovo community leaders and elders have been
flown to Cegrane from overcrowded Kukes, located along Albania's
northern border with Yugoslavia, to tour the camps and try to
persuade their inhabitants. Brochures touting the merits of
southern and central Albania are being distributed. The United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees is preparing a video to show
in Cegrane and other Macedonian tent cities, where refugees are not
in danger of shelling by Serb-led Yugoslav forces but of being
evicted by Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the campaign has fallen on stubborn ears.
</P>
<P>
   The commission hopes to relocate at least 33,000 Kosovars who
were forced to flee their homes when Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic launched his ``ethnic cleansing'' campaign and NATO
responded with airstrikes. But barely 500 refugees have accepted
the UN agency's offer in Kukes, according to figures released
Wednesday. The first group of 204 headed south on Monday onmilitary
trucks; Tuesday's convoy carried 301 on the 24-hour journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are still very much undecided,'' said Melita Sunjic,
the spokeswoman for the UN High Commissioner for Refugees in the
Albanian capital of Tirana. ``They sign up and change their minds
and don't go. We understand that they're sick and tired of moving,
so we're doing everything we can to convince them it's for the
best.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Kosovars say they feel otherwise, especially those in
Macedonia, where the sound of distant shelling does not regularly
interrupt sleep. Refugees there can also apply to emigrate to other
countries, including the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking through interpreters, refugees in Kukes say they want
to stay where they are, too _ close to home and on hand for family
members still making their way into Albania. Even the ethnic
Albanians living in the relatively pristine camps in southwest
Albania sound unhappy to be so far from the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to stay in Kukes, even though it was dirty and they
said it was dangerous,'' said Lumturije Benisha, 33, who was
separated from her husband and 12-year-old son by Serb police and
was forced to turn over most of her money and jewelry in exchange
for safe passage for her and her 6-year-old daughter. ``I wanted to
stay until my family came over. I haven't heard anything from them
and I'm afraid I never will if I'm here.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Benisha, Mustaf and Nazife Maksutaj could not quite explain
who made them leave Kukes and why. As they tell it, they were
ordered onto a bus headed to the southern Albania city of Fier,
where the United States recently opened Camp Hope and will soon
open Camp Eagle. UNHCR officials explained that newcomers _ and all
three were _ are being spread throughout Albania. Only those
already settled into camps are being given a choice.
</P>
<P>
   On the Kosovo-Albania border ``the police said we must go to
Albania; in Albania someone said we must go here,'' said Nazife
Maksutaj, 62, who is sharing a spotless, spacious tent with eight
relatives and four members of another family who were strangers
until a week ago. ``They did not say please. They said go. But we
don't want to be in this camp. I want to be in our home.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Mustaf Maksutaj, 70, who each day dons a knit vest, pocket
watch, and traditional cream-colored Kosovo hat known as a plis,
``They burned our house. . . . But we will get back to Kosovo even
from here. We have money for the bus.''
</P>
<P>
   Colonel Carol A. Miller, an Army reservist who is Camp Hope's
spokeswoman, said refugees continually ask when _ and how _ they
will get home to their farms and apartments in Kosovo. Yet new
arrivals keep coming, most from Kukes, some from nearby Fier where
they had been sleeping in city parks and on front lawns, still
others from camps in bordering Greece. Among refugees, there are
good words on the $40 million camp that will eventually hold almost
20,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are coming officially and unofficially, some in
mini-vans on their own, other in buses from the border,'' said Paul
J. Giannone, deputy director of the emergency group at
Atlanta-based CARE, the relief agency running Camp Hope. ``People
don't even have directions, but somehow they know to get here.
People just show up at the gate.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the camp in Fier never fills up, the UN High
Commissioner for Refugees says its policy is to ask, not force,
ethnic Albanians to relocate. Still, the tent camps in Kukes will
eventually be closed and those in Macedonia could be closed if that
country ever makes good on its since-rescinded threat to ship at
least some of the 96,000 refugees now living in tent camps to
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not like to use the word forcing and at the same time we
intend to step up the movement of people,'' Sunjic said. ``We are
against involuntary movement, because refugees are refugees by
definition because they were involuntarily moved. We don't want to
do that to them again.''
</P>
<P>
   That means the UNHCR must persuade them to move. So relief
workers talk up water shortages in Kukes, overcrowding in Cegrane.
Refugees who relocate may also get free daytrips back to the
border: at least some are expected to be asked to return to tell
others how much better life is in southern Albania.
</P>
<P>
   At Camp Hope, Hava Hajrizi said she would be happy to testify on
her new home's behalf. After learning her brother had been killed,
after watching her house burned, after walking a week to the
border, after being robbed by Serb police, after spending two
nights in a park in Kukes, she said she gladly climbed aboard a bus
headed south.
</P>
<P>
   ``The place has got some problems, but we're happy here, as
happy as we can be,'' said Hajrizi, 50, who shares a 20-person tent
with relatives. ``It's better here. It's risky near the border. I
feel bad saying so, but conditions up there are so much worse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
