<HEADER>
A2445 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-HEART-ATTACK-670&AMP;     05-26 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HEART-ATTACK-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHT HOSPITAL IS MORE IMPORTANT THAN NEAREST HOSPITAL FOR HEART
VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For someone who is having a heart attack, getting to the right
hospital _ one that treats many heart attack victims _ is more
important than getting to the closest one, and may mean the
difference between life and death, researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   The findings appear in a new report that also calls for
emergency medical systems to consider identifying certain hospitals
as heart attack centers, just as they now designate trauma centers.
Then, heart attack victims, who are now rushed to the nearest
hospital, could instead be taken straight to the one most likely to
save their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Making such changes nationwide could save 5,000 lives a year,
said Dr. David Thiemann, a cardiologist at Johns Hopkins University
and lead author of the report, which is being published on Thursday
in the New England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The study is the first to show a connection between surviving a
heart attack and the type of hospital where a patient is treated,
though earlier research had shown that patients having various
types of surgery fared better at certain hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The findings were based on the records of nearly 100,000 people
65 and older who were treated for heart attacks at more than 4,000
hospitals in the United States from February 1994 to July 1995.
Although they were several years old, Thiemann said the cases were
still relevant because the treatment of heart attacks has not
changed.
</P>
<P>
   Thiemann and his research team found that within 30 days of
being admitted, patients were 15 percent more likely to survive at
a ``high-volume'' hospital that treated many heart attacks, as
opposed to a ``low-volume'' hospital that treated few. High-volume
hospitals averaged at least 4.4 heart attack patients a week, and
low-volume sites treated 1.4 or fewer.
</P>
<P>
   At low-volume hospitals, 16.7 percent of patients died within 30
days, and 14.4 percent died at high-volume hospitals. For every 100
patients treated, the researchers calculated, 2.3 more were likely
to die at low-volume hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The younger the patient, the larger the difference in survival
between hospitals: among patients 65 to 69, for example, those
treated at a low volume center were 38 percent more likely to die
than those taken to a high-volume hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Thiemann said he did not know why this was but added that he
thought the findings would also apply to people younger than 65 and
that the difference might be even bigger.
</P>
<P>
   The team also found that city-dwellers were more likely to
survive heart attacks than people in rural areas, who were 11
percent more likely to die. The reason was not known, Thiemann
said, but he said it might be partly because it takes longer to get
to a hospital in a rural area.
</P>
<P>
   When Thiemann and his colleagues tried to determine why survival
was better at high-volume centers, they found that specific
treatments _ including aspirin and other drugs and procedures to
dissolve blood clots and open blocked arteries _ accounted for only
about a third of the benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rest,'' Thiemann said, ``is in the intangible that you
call experience. And experience matters. A lot of clinical practice
is still more art than science.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not merely doctors' experience that counted, he said, but
also that of nurses and lab technicians and everyone on the team
that takes care of the patient.
</P>
<P>
   Thiemann said he and his colleagues recommended that policy
changes be considered, but not put into effect immediately. One
reason, he said, is that ``we're not terribly good at identifying
heart attack patients in the field.'' There are false alarms, and
if emergency crews were suddenly to start transporting everyone
with chest or abdominal pains to one center, that center would be
overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``I think some changes are probably appropriate
even now.'' Some heart attacks are easily diagnosed by paramedics,
and if a high volume center is only a few minutes beyond the
nearest one, Thiemann said those patients should be taken to the
high-volume center.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Dr. Edward L. Hannan, of the University of Albany School of
Public Health in Rensselaer, N.Y., expressed reservations about the
study in an editorial in the same issue of the journal.
</P>
<P>
   Hannan said the reasons for the differences in survival needed
to be explained better, and he cautioned that findings on the
relation between volume and survival tended to be true only on
average, and could not be applied to any one hospital. Some
high-volume centers would perform poorly and some low-volume ones
would be excellent, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Thiemann also said it was important for people not to assume
that they could use the findings to pick and choose among hospitals
in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Individual patients should not be trying to drive themselves
across town or directly to a high-volume hospital,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
