<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2449 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USCHINA27-COX     05-26 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USCHINA27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Campaign fund-raisers, espionage players may be linked
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Some of the key players in the congressional
investigations into campaign fund-raising abuses surfaced in the
House committee report released earlier this week documenting
China's extensive espionage campaign in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The cross-fertilization between the two investigations suggests
that some of the people accused of funneling illegal contributions
into the Democratic Party could also be connected to what Democrats
and Republicans say is one of the most pervasive spying operations
ever undertaken in this country.
</P>
<P>
   The 907-page report from the special House committee headed by
Rep. Christopher Cox (R-Calif.) raises questions about the
activities of former top Democratic fund-raisers John Huang,
Charles Yah Lin Trie and Johnny Chung.
</P>
<P>
   All three have pleaded guilty to campaign finance violations
stemming from the congressional and Justice Department
investigations of fund-raising practices during the 1996
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   The Cox report links Trie to Chinese arms dealer Wang Jun, the
son of the late Chinese President Wang Zhen. It also traces
connections between Chung and Chinese Lt. Col. Liu Chaoying, the
daughter of Chinese General Liu Huaqing. Huang is linked to a
company owned by the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
   Those associations have some lawmakers on Capitol Hill calling
for an investigation. Already, the House Government Reform and
Oversight Committee said it will issue Huang a subpoena this week
to answer questions. Trie has already been subpoenaed to appear
June 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all part of the same spider's web,'' said Rep. Bob Barr
(R-Ga.), a member of the main House committee investigating
campaign finance abuses. ``We are talking about the integrity of
our political system and our national security.''
</P>
<P>
   The report calls Wang and Liu ``princelings'' because of their
family connections to the Chinese Communist Party. ``Princelings
such as Wang and Liu present a unique technology transfer threat
because their multiple connections enable them to move freely
around the world and among the different bureaucracies in the
PRC,'' the report states.
</P>
<P>
   The report says that Chung, a Chinese-American, was given
$300,000 by two high-ranking Chinese military officials with the
purpose of putting Liu in the position of acquiring sensitive
American technology.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's report found that in the summer of 1996, Chung,
a California businessman, went to Hong Kong to meet with Lt. Col.
Liu and Gen. Ji Shengde, director of military intelligence. Soon
after, the money was sent to Chung.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of that money was to make contacts that would be
useful in setting up one or more front companies in the United
States,'' Cox said Wednesday. ``Those companies in time would be
used for the acquisition of military technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Chung's attorney denies that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Chung had no discussions with these two figures about
gathering sensitive technology or anything remotely close to
spying,'' said Brian Sun, Chung's attorney. ``It would be
inappropriate to take Chung's dealings with these people and
suggest connections (to spying).''
</P>
<P>
   The report also singles out Wang for seeking military
information from American companies and says he may be linked to
Trie.
</P>
<P>
   Wang is chairman of China International Trade and Investment
Co., considered the most powerful company in China. He is also the
president of Polytechnologies Corp., an arms trading company owned
by the People's Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1996, Wang attended one of the Democratic Party's
``fund-raising'' coffees at the White House where President Clinton
was present. The next day, he met with Commerce Secretary Ron
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The report states that Wang is suspected of funneling
contributions to the DNC through Trie. Trie gave the party over
$600,000 in illegal campaign contributions during the 1996
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The report states that Huang ``was provided with a wealth of
classified material pertaining to China, Taiwan and other parts of
Asia'' when he worked for the Department of Commerce from late 1993
through 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Before working for the Commerce Department, Huang had worked for
the Lippo Group. Lippo's principal partner in China is China
Resources Co., a Hong Kong-based company owned by the Chinese
government.
</P>
<P>
   China Resources is one of several companies owned by the Chinese
government that shares a controlling interest in Asia Pacific
Mobile Telecommunications Satellite Co. Ltd. The company is
preparing to use China Great Wall Industry Corp. to launch a
constellation of American-made satellites on Chinese rockets, the
report states.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is examining that connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this shows that the Chinese have waged a systematic
campaign on several parallel courses, the two most obvious being an
attempt to gain our nuclear an military technology, the other to
influence our political system,'' said Mark Corallo, press
secretary to the Government Reform and Oversight Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Bureau reporter Julia Malone contributed to this
story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
