<SLUG> BC-REFUGEE-WORKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BITTEN BY THE HUMANITARIAN `BUG' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FIER, Albania _ The Kosovar teenager acting as Lisa Woodbury's
interpreter had a puzzled look on his face.
</P>
<P>
   His English was tentative, hers was Bostonian, and in the dust
and heat of the new US refugee camp she had to communicate through
him. Woodbury, he knew, worked for an international relief agency
called CARE and this week was posted to Fier, even if she
pronounced them without the r's. Other words were touch and go.
</P>
<P>
   But Woodbury, 35, wasn't worried. Covered in grime after just 24
hours in southern Albania, she said she has learned to work with
whatever she's handed. That is, after all, the nature of the job.
And that's why she has turned the black bag she carries into a
``mobile office.''
</P>
<P>
   A partial inventory: flashlight, stapler, business cards, brush,
prescription medicines, decongestants, sunscreen, pens, pads of
paper, candy for the kids and, less obviously, ``Save Fenway''
bumper stickers. The duffle bag and backpack she hauled with her
from North Attleboro, Mass., were equally crammed, with, among
other items, a portable CD player on which she listens to the
Chieftains, and a laptop computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn to come prepared,'' said Woodbury, who has done
relief work in Tanzania, Bosnia, and a half-dozen other countries.
``I could live in one place, with all my things. But I haven't
found out where it is. It's a bug, and I've got it.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodbury, the youngest of seven children and the lone nomad in
the clan, first caught the bug in the Army, where she rose to
captain and was sent to Somalia in 1993 to work as the medical
liaison to relief agencies. The posting changed her perspective.
She recalled thinking ``this is something I want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   So nine years after joining the Army as a way to pay for
college, and after earning undergraduate and graduate degrees in
business, she signed on with the International Rescue Committee and
headed to Africa. In the Army she had specialized first in nuclear,
biological, and chemical defense, then in civil affairs. Now she
does whatever needs to be done for whatever relief agency she is
working for at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just so rewarding, not financially, but the human contact
of it,'' Woodbury said. ``You're dealing with people at the bottom
who have nowhere to go but up with your help.''
</P>
<P>
   She does, at times, miss home, miss friends, miss family. But
she's been away so long that she can't even explain the term
``personal life'' anymore. She's happy enough to have her fellow
relief workers, who tend to form fast and intense bonds that can
last a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go home and see my friends from kindergarten and they have
houses and kids and I think, `What is a personal life?' '' she
said. ``Is it dating and friends in one place and that stuff. ... I
really don't feel as though I'm missing out on anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodbury, who as an Army reservist had been concerned about
being called up for active duty, has a one-month contract with
CARE, the agency running just-opened Camp Hope and Camp Eagle,
which is under construction. But she expects to be in Fier much
longer, maybe long enough to pronounce it like an Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pray every night there will be peace and that I'll be out of
a job,'' she said. ``But the way things are going, there's going to
be plenty of work for me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
