<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-PHONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
11TH-HOUR RESCUE OF MEXICO'S UNEFON 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Ricardo Salinas Pliego, the chairman of Mexico's
second-largest television network, summoned all his showmanship
Wednesday to portray an 11th-hour rescue of his fledgling wireless
telephone business as a bold foray into the interactive Mexico of
the future.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas announced that he was turning over the business, Unefon
SA de CV, to a joint venture formed by his network, TV Azteca SA de
CV, and two members of an investor family, Alberto Saba Raffoul and
Moises Saba Masri. TV Azteca and the Saba family will each put up
$180 million to capitalize the company. Salinas controls about 70
percent of TV Azteca.
</P>
<P>
   He said the new wireless company, which has not been named,
would provide much more than the low-cost local telephone service
that had been Unefon's focus. He said the new company would use a
part of the frequencies it bought from the Mexican government to
deliver television programming to working-class Mexicans, allow
them to cruise the Internet and shop from home.
</P>
<P>
   Those services, which are still on the drawing board, will be
sold along with the phone services through the retail stores of
Elektra, Salinas' thriving bargain-appliances chain, he said. He
made no secret that TV Azteca air time would be used to promote the
venture.
</P>
<P>
   TV Azteca shareholders have worried for months that Salinas
would reach into the network to save Unefon. An effort to raise
bank financing for it failed in March, and Salinas is facing a June
15 deadline to pay the federal government for the frequencies
Unefon won the right to buy in bidding last year. TV Azteca has
struggled for the last year against a strong comeback by its chief
competitor, Televisa.
</P>
<P>
   But Salinas dismissed those concerns Wednesday, describing the
new wireless enterprise as ``a strategic opportunity that TV Azteca
will not have again.'' In practice, though, the only thing about
Unefon that has changed so far is the breadth of Salinas' ambitions
for the services its new incarnation will provide.
</P>
<P>
   On June 10, shareholders will be asked to add to their
investments in TV Azteca so as to increase its capital by as much
as $125 million. Salinas said he had a group of Mexican investors
ready to fill the gap if current shareholders balked.
</P>
<P>
   He said he gave up Unefon at cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricardo Salinas Pliego didn't make anything,'' he said of
himself. He also said that he would be reimbursed for $80 million
he had already paid the government for the frequencies and that a
remaining payment of about $270 million would be made by the June
15 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   TV Azteca shares fell 5.9 percent, to 3.06 pesos, in Mexico
City. Its American depository receipts fell 25 cents, or 4.7
percent, to $5.125, in New York. Salomon Smith Barney downgraded
its recommendation on the stock from ``buy'' to ``neutral.''
</P>
<P>
   Salinas bridled at the market's skepticism. ``I'm a businessman
because I see a good investment decision and I take it,'' he said.
``If I didn't, I would be an analyst.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
