<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-NOMAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURY KEEPS GARCIAPARRA ON BENCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ His finger was bleeding when he hit his first home
run in Yankee Stadium Tuesday night, and he came to the ballpark
Wednesday expecting to play.
</P>
<P>
   But Nomar Garciaparra decided otherwise Wednesday morning when
he realized that the bruise on the tip of his right index finger
would not allow him to grip a bat or ball properly.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox shortstop was a late scratch from Wednesday
afternoon's 8-3 loss to the New York Yankees, and while he said he
was hopeful of playing Thursday night against Roger Clemens, his
status remains in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra was injured while taking groundballs from Sox
manager Jimy Williams during batting practice Tuesday. The flesh
behind the fingernail on the finger was pulled away from the nail.
``It was bleeding underneath the nail, and bleeding during the
game, but I didn't think much of it,'' Garciaparra said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But today, it was throbbing. When I tried to throw the ball,
it kept slipping off one finger. I said, `This isn't working.' What
scared me is when I threw the ball, it acted like a cutter, or a
slider. I didn't want to change my mechanics. It wasn't worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Garciaparra's place, Jeff Frye made his first career start at
shortstop and handled seven chances cleanly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nomar's a tough kid,'' Frye said. ``He knows how important he
is to this team. But I don't think I'm going to hurt the team at
short, even though I know I can't replace him.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said that for now he has no intention of summoning
another infielder, but all that could change if Garciaparra can't
play the next couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking, `I've got a guy at second base (Jose Offerman)
who's probably played 500 games at short, and a guy at third base
(John Valentin) who's probably played 500 games at short,''
Williams said. ``But I thought this was the best way for us to go,
because those guys have played now in those slots.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said it was possible Garciaparra could be the
designated hitter, though it's unlikely the Sox manager would use a
subpar Garciaparra, especially against Clemens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 2033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2468 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES27-COX     05-26 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Far from Kosovo chaos, refugee family faces press
 &HT;    By Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COMER, Ga. _ Teuta Hoxha, a 15-year-old who fled the horror and
war of Kosovo, spent Wednesday morning in a far more peaceful
setting _ walking through the woods and fields of Jubilee Partner's
258 acres in Comer. The refugee center, she said, reminds her of a
park near Pristina she liked to frequent with her friends in the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'd like to finish school here, in the United States,
then go back to Kosova,'' said Teuta, using the Albanian
pronunciation of the province's name. She wants to study
architecture, she said, ``to build back everything in Kosova the
Serbs destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, Teuta, along with the rest of her family _
her father, Ilir; her mother, Hysnije; her sister Arbreshe; and her
brother, Arben _ sat on the porch of the cabin that will be their
home for the next two months at the Christian refugee center,
answering questions about their journey from Kosovo to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   They cried as they recalled their anxiety and fear at having to
vacate, at gunpoint, the home in Pristina they had built 10 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking through an interpreter, Mrs. Hoxha said that at 4:30 on
the afternoon of March 31 _ exactly a week after NATO began bombing
_ masked soldiers came to their house and told her and her
daughters to leave immediately. Once the women were outside, the
men detained her 45-year-old husband, and their son, who is 20. The
soldiers took the pair to another part of the house, pressed
machine guns against their throats and demanded money _ either
German marks or American dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Hoxha said he told the soldiers to kill him if they wanted,
because he had only money from Kosovo, having spent his career
there. He had worked as a musical producer for a television
station, and his wife had been with the Kosovar Bureau of Health,
until both were forced out of their jobs. That kind of persecution
had begun years ago, they said, as Serbian government officials
began to make life harder for Kosovo's ethnic Albanians, people
like the Hoxhas.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Hoxha broke into tears when he tried to express his feelings
at having to abandon his home and all his family's belongings _ the
toys and dishes, the photographs and souvenirs, the clothes and
books.
</P>
<P>
   The only sound for a few seconds was the call of a mockingbird.
Mr. Hoxha gazed at the stand of trees across the gravel road in
front of the cabin, not bothering to wipe the tears from his face.
</P>
<P>
   Arbreshe, who is 17, rose from the table and went inside the
cabin, returning with with paper napkins for her parents and her
brother and sister. After a minute or so, the Hoxhas regained their
composure.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hoxha said she had been wearing slippers when the Serbian
soldiers and police forced them from their house for the three-mile
walk to the train station. They were her only shoes for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Family members didn't know what was going to happen to them,
where they would be sent _ or whether they would face the fate Mrs.
Hoxha's cousins, who were executed. The Hoxhas were kicked off the
train near the Macedonian border and warned to walk only on the
railroad bed, because the adjacent land was mined.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hoxha said the Macedonian government did not treat them
well. They spent days out in the open, often in the rain, with no
shelter and no provisions.
</P>
<P>
   The Hoxhas were asked by refugee workers where they wanted to
go. Norway, where Mr. Hoxha's brother had been sent? Or perhaps
Germany, where other relatives were staying. In the end, however,
they chose the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Family members have not really thought about whether they will
stay in the United States permanently, Mr. Hoxha said. They hope to
relax for the next couple of months, and work on their English.
</P>
<P>
   Today, they will be interviewed by television news crews. This
weekend, they will unwind in the North Georgia mountains. Next
week, they will begin taking English classes and making excursions
into Comer and Athens, about 10 miles to the southwest, to start to
become acclimated to American customs and culture.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
