u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-YANKEES-BO     05-26 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-YANKEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERNANDEZ OVERPOWERS BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It sounds like a qualifying match in World Cup
soccer: Cuba vs. Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   But as a subtext to the Yankees-Red Sox rivalry, so far it has
been no contest, as Cuban defector Orlando Hernandez claimed his
second win in six days over Red Sox roustabout Mark Portugal, 8-3,
before a matinee crowd of 45,800 in Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Minus their crown prince, Nomar Garciaparra, a late scratch
because of a bruised and bloodied right index finger, the Sox were
once again no match for El Duque, who shut them out on three hits
in seven innings and has allowed the Sox just a run on five hits in
15 innings over two starts.
</P>
<P>
   In five games between the teams in the last eight days, it now
stands: Sox 3, El Duque 2, with that marquee showdown, loose cannon
Pat Rapp vs. Rocket Roger Clemens, still to come Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to battle as long as I could,'' said Portugal, who was
hurt most by the collateral damage inflicted by Tino Martinez's
grand slam off reliever John Wasdin in the Yankees' five-run fifth,
``but El Duque pitched another wonderful game against us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, who did not advance a runner to third base in the first
eight innings Wednesday, scored three times in the ninth against
reliever Ramiro Mendoza, on a two-run home run by Brian Daubach and
three consecutive singles, before closer Mariano Rivera snuffed out
the belated uprising.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal, who has won just once in seven starts after opening
the season with two victories, had already pitched out of one
bases-loaded jam and was attempting to extract himself from another
in the fifth inning when he bounced into the backstop retrieving
Trot Nixon's overthrow from right field on Paul O'Neill's single.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that wall was padded,'' said Portugal, whose
momentum carried him into the low retaining wall when he spun and
threw to catcher Jason Varitek. ``It's not. I jammed my thigh. And
it didn't make me feel any better to have a lady standing over me,
laughing at me.''
</P>
<P>
   His humor didn't improve any when he walked the next batter,
Bernie Williams, on four pitches to force in a run that made it
2-0, Yankees, and compelled Sox manager Jimy Williams to call for
Wasdin.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not an excuse for throwing the ball all over the strike
zone,'' said Portugal, who issued a season-high four walks. ``You
walk guys against this club, you put yourself in position to have
the (stuffing) kicked out of you. That's what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasdin took the brunt of the punishment, grooving an 0-and-2
fastball to Martinez that landed in the third deck in right field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to make a quality pitch inside to him,'' Wasdin
said.
</P>
<P>
   That pitch had as much chance of getting past the
quality-control inspectors as it did Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had two chances there to make him chase a bad pitch,''
pitching coach Joe Kerrigan said. ``You can go bad high with a
fastball, or bad low with a splitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he didn't physically execute the pitch. He wanted to throw
a bad high fastball and threw it right down the middle. You can't
make that type of mistake against that type of hitter, because
there's no forgiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's seventh career slam, which doesn't count his epic
World Series slam last October, made it 6-0, and the Yankees added
a pair in the seventh against short-timer Tim Harikkala.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, meanwhile, were putty for Hernandez, who gave up a
two-out single in the first to Daubach, a leadoff double in the
fifth to Troy O'Leary, and a one-out single to Reggie Jefferson in
the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the key to the game was the pitcher for the Yankees,''
Jimy Williams said. ``He's tough. He's really tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez left the Sox admiring not only his moundwork, but his
instincts after he seized Jeff Frye's sharp comebacker following
O'Leary's double and turned it into an unusual double play.
Hernandez spun and nabbed O'Leary diving back into second, where
shortstop Derek Jeter applied the tag, then threw a bullet to first
to nail Frye.
</P>
<P>
   It was still a one-run game at the time, the Yankees having
taken the lead in the second on a walk to Martinez and a double by
Chili Davis, but not for long.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of shocked me,'' said Frye, making his first career
start at short after Garciaparra discovered he couldn't grip ball
or bat the morning after taking a batting-practice grounder off his
finger.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I hit it, I saw O'Leary breaking back, so I put my
head down and ran. Next time I looked, Jeter was whirling and
firing to first. I probably broke stride, but it's not as if I
slowed down. It was an unusual play.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Yankees, who ended the Sox' four-game winning streak and
handed them just their fourth loss in the last 19 games, this was
business as usual, at least the way they've always conceived it.
</P>
<P>
   And now comes Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't look good in pinstripes,'' John Valentin said with
a smile.
</P>
<P>
   A fashion statement, or wishful thinking? Tune in Thursday night
for the answer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
