u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARPENTERS-PETITION-B     05-26 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARPENTERS-PETITION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGIONAL UNION MEMBERS ASSAIL CHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Nearly three years after the national carpenters' union
promised reforms and an end to cronyism, some New England members
are joining others around the country who claim the changes
stripped them of power and voting rights.
</P>
<P>
   The issue: A plan by the 500,000-member United Brotherhood of
Carpenters and Joiners of America that gives 65 regional councils
across the United States tighter control over the union's 1,000
locals.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, angry carpenters have reacted by peppering the city
with signs that say, ``Union Carpenters Demand the Right to Vote,''
and by collecting 3,000 signatures this month on a petition
demanding the right to elect business agents and organizers for the
22,000-member New England Regional Council of Carpenters.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters, who have formed an ad-hoc group called
Carpenters for a Democratic Union (CDU), say the plan launched by
national president Douglas McCarron three years ago directs what
was once rank-and-file power into the hands of regional councils
and, ultimately, McCarron.
</P>
<P>
   ``The council is now the governing body for all of New England,
which means it sets budgets for the locals, assigns employees to
the locals, assigns work to the locals,'' said Tom Jones, president
of Local 218 and a council representative.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is also a former business agent. Under the new plan, 10
business agents were either fired or took early retirement during
what sources describe as internal housecleaning by David Bergeron,
executive secretary treasurer of the New England Regional Council
of Carpenters. Jones and other business agents who remained after
those changes became council representatives, and are no longer
elected by the membership.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is driving this movement is that people feel there is no
more accountability,'' said Jones. ``Rank-and-file members feel
they are being left out. People can vote for constitutional
officers like president, but not for business agents, business
managers, or organizers.''
</P>
<P>
   In most locals, the business manager or agent was the second or
third most powerful officer in the union, responsible for contract
negotiations and business operations.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Bergeron is widely known as an elected reformist who
took a bankrupt local in western Massachusetts and turned it
around, making it the second largest local in the state's old
district council.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Bergeron defended the new plan. He maintained
that the changes now being instituted became part of the union's
constitution in 1993 at a constitutional convention, some two years
before McCarron's election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have I ruffled feathers?'' he asked. ``Yes, I terminated some
business agents and there is now progressive discipline. If they
don't perform, they're out.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he argued, there is also due process: ``We have 13
executive board members elected by their own union locals who vote
on (whether to discipline or fire a representative or agent).''
</P>
<P>
   Bert Durand, a spokesman for the regional council, said the
changes went into effect because the union needed to bring its
structure in line with a construction market that now crosses state
lines and is no longer local in nature.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some members are fighting mad.
</P>
<P>
   In a May 24 letter to McCarron, the chairman of the newly
organized CDU made the group's displeasure clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the council was established, thousands of members in New
England have been allowed to cast only one real ballot _ to elect
fewer than 120 delegates who make all decisions for them, including
who their leaders will be,'' wrote CDU chairman Tom Harrington of
Local 33 in Boston. ``That's not fair!''
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the grass-roots protest is not unlike others staged
by union locals in California and New York, where McCarron pledged
to clean up the old mob-ridden district council and where reformers
from the national union took over the council's luxurious
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   But while McCarron instituted notable reforms such as booting a
corrupt officials and developing an equitable hiring system, he has
also been criticized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, in wide sections of the construction trades and,
especially in the carpenters' union, there is now a tendency to
turn the locals into powerless administrative units with no
authority,'' said Herman Henson, secretary treasurer of the
Association for Union Democracy in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
