<HEADLINE>
ATTN:WACO 
75 ADOPTED CHILDREN TAKE CITIZENSHIP OATH AT ZOO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL BOURGEOIS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The normal zoo sounds of elephants
trumpeting and lions roaring were replaced Wednesday by little
unsure voices pledging allegiance to the Red, White and Blue.
</P>
<P>
   At the Fort Worth Zoo, America gained 75 new citizens _ children
who started their lives in Europe, Asia and South America.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign adoptions have risen sharply, according to the
Immigration and Naturalization Service, which might be shedding its
hard and foreboding image by staging a mass swearing-in at the
child-friendly zoo rather than at a cold office.
</P>
<P>
   The children, ranging from 1 to 17 years old, represent 17
countries. More than half of them _ 41 _ are from China and Russia,
said Lynn Ligon, a spokesman for the INS in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very rarely do we do a mass ceremony like this, but we have
had such an influx of adoptions,'' Ligon said. ``Then we looked for
a venue that would be special, and what better than the zoo for a
group of kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Ligon said that for those who are too young to know what's going
on and for those whose English is still shaky, parents take the
oath for the children.
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't realize what any of this is,'' said Sherry
Thompson, mother to 4-year-old Alden, formerly Qi, who came to the
Thompson home in Haltom City as an infant from China.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had never been able to have children of our own, and I
always wanted an Asian child. There are so many abandoned,
especially girls. These children are truly orphans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just so excited,'' said Thompson, a flight attendant.
``Why? It's just a great thing to become a United States citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Dean of Bedford said she and her husband, Robert, welcomed
their new daughters, Megan and Paige, only about a month ago. She
said the girls might not be exactly sure about what this is all
about, but they know it's very special.
</P>
<P>
   The Deans said 8-year-old Megan, formerly Oksana, and Paige,
Olga, 4, are still dealing with the language. They have a firm
grasp on just a few things such as ``hot dogs,'' ``dollar'' and
``swim,'' which they more than eager to do in the backyard pool,
something unheard of in their former hometown of Penza, about 400
miles southeast of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been thinking about it for a long time,'' said Cindy
Dean, a program analyst for the INS. She said she and her husband
felt that their son, Trevor, 6, was lonely and was missing
something by not having siblings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just needed more kids in the house. Big families are kind
of nice,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, I grew up an only child,'' said Robert Dean, an
electrical engineer, ``and it wasn't much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The Deans said adopting overseas is often easier.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Dean said in-country adoptions have more stringent
standards for marital status, age and income.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another good thing is we won't have any parents coming back
saying they want their child back,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a neat way for them to be naturalized,'' said Janie
Hermosillo, director of immigration services for Catholic
Charities, which helped organize the event. ``Most of the time,
they do it in some office and that's that. This will make it a
memorable day for the children and the parents.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   .MDBR/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
