<HEADER>
A2485 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAYA-AD-COLUMN-480&AMP;AD     05-26 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAYA-AD-COLUMN-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: NAYA LEARNS A HARD LESSON 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Naya Inc., a Canadian bottled-water company that has watched its
sales surge in the last five years, now finds itself paddling hard.
</P>
<P>
   Naya was a success story. It had a trendy product _ bottled
water in small containers is the fastest-growing beverage in the
United States _ a snappy advertising slogan (``hungry for life,
thirsty for Naya'') and about 65 percent of its volume distributed
by Coca-Cola Enterprises, one of the most powerful networks in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Sales have grown every year by at least 30 percent, said Steven
Wasik, the company's vice president for marketing. Things were
going so well that about two years ago the bottler made a bid to
acquire the privately held Naya, though the two sides never
completed the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a key part of the picture has changed. Coca-Cola Co., which
owns 39 percent of Coca-Cola Enterprises, its largest bottler,
decided to introduce a bottled-water brand of its own called
Dasani, and Naya executives were told that they would have to start
looking for a new distributor.
</P>
<P>
   While Coca-Cola Enterprises handles other companies' products,
and such products accounted for 12 percent of the bottler's 3.8
billion case volume last year, there apparently isn't room on its
trucks for more than one spring water in Naya's markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This came as a great surprise,'' Wasik said. ``We had fully
expected to be able to coexist with Dasani.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dasani brand is purified tap water with added minerals. Naya
is bottled from a pair of Canadian springs and is priced higher
than Dasani, Wasik said, though not as high as Danone SA's Evian, a
spring water imported from the French Alps, which Coca-Cola
Enterprises has also distributed.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Asman, a spokeswoman for the bottler, said: ``We believe a
purified water such as Dasani provides Coca-Cola Enterprises with a
high-growth, high-profit product that will capture a significant
share of the bottled-water category. For consumers who are only
interested in a natural spring water, we will continue to offer
Evian.''
</P>
<P>
   Notice of the change came to Naya in November and went into
effect last week. Wasik said the company has switched to a
distribution method that uses brokers to provide its products to
stores. Several other beverage companies, including Triarc Cos.,
the owner of Snapple and RC Cola, rely on the method. But it has
its drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the convenience store, the gas stations and other
smaller accounts are a greater challenge for us,'' Wasik said.
</P>
<P>
   Others were blunter. ``This is going to be a substantial body
blow for Naya,'' said John Sicher, publisher of Beverage Digest, an
industry newsletter. ``They are probably going to lose somewhere in
the range of 30 percent of their volume. The reason is, when a
product is distributed in the Coke bottling system, it's in every
vending machine, nook and cranny in the U.S.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Naya is not the only brand left bobbing in Dasani's wake.
Coca-Cola Consolidated, a large Coke bottler based in Charlotte,
N.C., which last month oversaw the introduction of Dasani, no
longer distributes Le Bleu, a privately owned distilled water. ``It
was doing fine,'' said Lauren Steele, a spokesman for Consolidated.
``But Dasani sales are eclipsing it dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   To counteract the loss of Coca-Cola Enterprises, Naya executives
have been working the public relations machines overtime. First
came a large ad in the April issue of Beverage World, a trade
publication, thanking the bottler for the memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great relationship,'' the ad reads in part.
``While you supplied the distribution strength, we supplied the
finest-quality product and a commitment to invest in marketing
through advertising, promotions and sponsorships. Together, we took
an already successful brand and made it better.''
</P>
<P>
   The point, Wasik said, was to let retailers know that Naya _ and
not Coca-Cola, as some believed _ had been the promotional force
behind the brand. ``It was our way, and we hope a classy way, of
saying here's the real deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Monday it issued a release titled ``How Naya Kicked the
Coke Habit.'' In it, Naya all but lambasted the Coca-Cola system
for dropping it and even took a shot at Dasani. ``In our opinion,
by replacing Naya natural spring water with a purified bottled
water, Coke is emphasizing cost savings over quality,'' Naya's
president, Stu Levitan, said in the release.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps Naya executives have only themselves to blame. Some
analysts say they should not have depended so heavily on one
distributor. ``They were riding the tiger,'' said one analyst,
adding that the possibility always existed that Coke might get into
the water business, as Pepsico did in 1995 with Aquafina.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a two-edged sword, as Naya found out,'' said Emanuel
Goldman, an analyst for Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. ``Ideally, what you
want is to have your business spread out, like Dr Pepper.'' That
soft-drink brand, owned by Cadbury Schweppes, is handled by
Coca-Cola and Pepsi bottlers as well as independent bottlers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, another factor in Dr Pepper's success is that no other
brand has emerged as a true alternative to it. The same cannot be
said about water, which American consumers tend to select based on
price and purity, not on subtle differences in taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty easy category to get into,'' said Henry
Schimberg, the president and chief executive of Coca-Cola
Enterprises, speaking at a beverage-industry conference in New York
earlier this month. ``If you don't have a faucet, you can't get
in.''
</P>
<P>
   For soft-drink companies, entering the bottled-water arena is a
somewhat conflicted business move. Certainly, consumer demand
exists, but the segment offers lower profit margins for a
concentrate maker like Coke or Pepsi. After all, Goldman said,
``it's hard to come up with a water concentrate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
