<HEADER>
A2486 &Cx1f; tth-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-DEBECKER-SPI &LR;      05-26 1497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-DEBECKER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USE INTUITIVE FEAR TO PROTECT YOUR CHILDREN, YOURSELF, AUTHOR
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By D. PARVAZ  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ You have no idea how many disasters you avoid with
help from your inner voice _ the one that tells you not to walk to
your car alone at night, or to chose one baby sitter over another.
</P>
<P>
   Nature has equipped you with the instinct to realize threats and
the ability to protect yourself from them.
</P>
<P>
   That's the assertion Los Angeles writer Gavin de Becker makes in
his second book, ``Protecting the Gift: Keeping Children and
Teenagers Safe (and Parents Sane)'' (The Dial Press, 325 pages,
$22.95).
</P>
<P>
   Having already written a book on appreciating the role of fear
in survival, ``The Gift of Fear,'' de Becker's new book focuses on
how to use that intuitive fear to protect your children as well as
yourself from danger.
</P>
<P>
   De Becker advises parents on ways to listen more acutely to
their ``wild brain'' _ the little voice that tells you something
just isn't right _ as opposed to the logical brain, the one that
tells you that nothing could go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your wild brain is the protective tool,'' de Becker said in a
recent phone interview. ``Our defense mechanisms are our minds and
our hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   While de Becker is not a parent, he is an expert in studying and
predicting violent behavior. (A threat-assessment system designed
by de Becker is used by the CIA).
</P>
<P>
   His goal, he said, is to impress upon people the fact that no
one is just ``a victim in waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the resource (to not be a victim) _ it might be
fighting, it might be trickery, it might be guile, it might be
submission, it might be negotiation, it might be resistance, but
whatever the resource _ you've got it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   De Becker writes, ``Human beings didn't get the sharpest claws
or strongest jaws or fastest legs. We got the biggest brains _ and
the best parents to show us how to use them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it all starts with knowing what true fear is, as opposed
to paranoid panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``True fear ... is something you want _ if there's a reason for
it,'' he explained. ``Like a signal in the presence of danger, it's
the thing that gets your body ready for danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want unwarranted fear, and here's how to tell the
difference: True fear is always based on something you perceive, or
on something in your circumstance. You hear it, you see it, you
smell it, you touch it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unwarranted fear is always based on something in your memory
or imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   He gave the following example: You're at the airport and you
suddenly get a feeling you shouldn't board a plane for fear of
crashing.
</P>
<P>
   If that fear is a result of something you saw in the news two
weeks ago, then you're not experiencing true fear.
</P>
<P>
   If, however, your apprehension is based on seeing the pilot
stumble out of an airport bar and toward the plane, then that is
based on something you've seen. That is real fear and it's
something you should value.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reality is the highest ground you can get onto, and from
there, you can see what's coming,'' said de Becker.
</P>
<P>
   This is handy for parents who find themselves in a constant
state of worry over their teens. De Becker said there is a way to
keep things in check and not overreact.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the absence of being informed, you would have a million
unnamed fears that become abstract fears,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit like if you have cancer you want to learn
all about it, but if you don't have it, about the last thing you
want to do is pick up a book called `All About Cancer.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He said that's why parents often resist learning about what they
need to fear, opting instead to worry about absolutely everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``If parents ask the question `Could this happen to my child?'
about some particular thing, the answer will always be, `Yes,
anything could happen,' '' said de Becker.
</P>
<P>
   ``The better question to ask is, `Is this happening to my child?
Is this process under way?'''
</P>
<P>
   This advice might offer parents some sanity, given the long list
of things that could happen to children (sexual abuse, drugs,
gangs, etc.).
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, denying that there is a problem is just as
harmful as misguided worrying.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other productive question _ to get around denial _ and
what I consider one of the most powerful questions you or I could
ask in our lives, is: `What am I choosing not to see here?'''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, the scenarios in ``Protecting the Gift'' are ones
most parents would rather not think about. While de Becker aims to
reassure and inform parents, he also describes cases that sum up
every parent's nightmare: A child abducted from a shopping mall,
never to be seen again; a teenage girl molested by a family friend;
an abusive baby sitter.
</P>
<P>
   In some of the cases, a parent's instinct kicks in and saves a
child. In others, the parent's inability to accept that something
horrible is around the corner leads to disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The Littleton, Colo., shootings can be seen as a tragic case of
denial at work. ``If you ask questions like `Oh my God, how could
these boys ever shoot other boys in school so heartlessly?' Well
doesn't that deny that teenage boys in every culture in human
history have been the ones we used to fight wars ... to do its
killing and be its killed?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, Littleton didn't happen without warning,'' de Becker
said. ``If shooter Eric Harris had gone on `The Tonight Show' the
night before, I don't suspect the people there would have listened.
Already, (Harris and Dylan Klebold) had given a presentation to
their school, they'd done a videotape of a shooting, they had a Web
site with direct death threats on it to specific people, they'd set
off three pipe bombs, they'd talked about acts of violence ... so
you can't call that an act that comes out of nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   De Becker does not believe there is such a thing as a ``random''
act of violence. He's a big believer in ``pre-incident
indicators.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You see on the news that somebody `just snapped' and went on a
shooting spree. That never, ever happens. Human beings do not `just
snap' and go on shooting sprees. There's always a process under
way, just like water coming to a boil,'' he said, adding that as a
society, we find it easier to believe that bad things happen
randomly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to believe that these things happen without warning,
because if there's no warning, then there's no responsibility to
predict.
</P>
<P>
   ``The solution to the violence in America is not more guns or
more cops or more laws or more prisons. The solution to violence in
America is acceptance of reality.''
</P>
<P>
   He calls the reality of life for American teenage boys ``Camp
USA.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If Camp USA knocked on your door and said, `We want to take
your teenaged sons for three years off to our camp,' you'd say,
`What kind of camp is it?'
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd say, `Well, we spend about six or seven hours a day
showing them violent images of various sorts _ movies, news, video
games _ whatever it may be. Then we put them on simulators that
teach them how to kill people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we have a lot of guns and ammunition around, in case they
want to go shooting, and we don't listen to the little cues they
give us and the little hints they give us about what they're
feeling. We intentionally don't listen to those.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's the good news: The camp is free. And here's the really
good news: Your boy wants to go, because he's not getting
everything he needs at home.'''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine a parent who would say, ``Yes, sign me
up.'' But de Becker said millions of parents are, in essence,
sending their children to just that camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``These boys live in a culture where ... the leading cause of
death to teenage boys is gunfire.''
</P>
<P>
   De Becker also considers glamorizing violence a factor in teen
violence. ``You want to be cool? Be like Keanu Reeves. ... The most
promoted image in the United States in the two weeks prior to the
Littleton shooting was a single picture _ you saw it 500 times _ of
Keanu Reeves in a black trenchcoat, automatic weapons around his
waist (ads for the film ``The Martix'').
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what was on bus benches, billboards, and of course, all
over newspapers and movie theaters. That was the No. 1 movie.''
</P>
<P>
   He says that boys like Harris and Klebold are trying to
establish an identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them have tried to have an identity of meanness and
violence and hostility and anger and vicious games and that's their
identity. ... They lose that persona when they get rejected,
humiliated, insulted.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there is no faster way (than a violent act) to establish
an identity, which is what every human being wants. Our identity is
our reason for being included in the tribe, otherwise we're thrown
out,'' de Becker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When their identity is at risk. ... They will kill for it _
they do it all the time _ and they will die for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 2048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
