<SLUG> BC-BASE-CLOSINGS-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE REJECTS CLOSING OF MORE MILITARY BASES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Maine, Ariz., Va., Mich., S.D., Miss.)  (lb) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A week after Congress approved a $15 billion
package to finance the war in Kosovo and other Pentagon programs,
the Senate on Wednesday rejected the administration's request to
close more military bases and save money.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate blocked the initiative for the third straight year in
a bipartisan vote of 60-40, brushing aside the pleas from Secretary
of Defense William Cohen that closing more bases would improve the
military's readiness at a time when the Kosovo conflict has
strained resources.
</P>
<P>
   Closing military bases has never been popular in Congress, as
members are loath to lose the jobs and payrolls of the bases in
their districts. And the issue became even more politically charged
after the last round of closings in 1995 and 1996 when Republicans
accused President Clinton of manipulating the base closings in
California to help ensure his electoral victory.
</P>
<P>
   This year Cohen said he had hoped that with both Congress and
the White House committed to increasing the Pentagon budget he
could convince the lawmakers that the efficient spending of those
additional dollars would help improve the military's readiness.
While there was little hope that Congress would approve base
closings this year, administration officials nonetheless said they
were disappointed by the size of the defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously this is a disappointment at a time we need to
channel every available dollar into readiness, procurement of more
modern weapons and training,'' said the Pentagon spokesman, Kenneth
Bacon. ``It's a disappointment to learn that we have to support
unnecessary infrastructure well into the future.''
</P>
<P>
   In rejecting that argument, several lawmakers said the war in
Kosovo persuaded them that the bases were necessary to ensure that
the military was ready to fight in a modern war.
</P>
<P>
   ``The example of Kosovo reminds us that warfare in the 21st
century will demand the deployment over greater distances from
airfields and ports at home,'' said Sen. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine.
``We cannot escape from the fact that alternative savings sources
provide more reliable long-term relief for readiness and
modernization programs.``
</P>
<P>
   Other senators questioned whether the Pentagon had sufficient
proof that closing bases would bring about annual savings of $2
billion to $3 billion. In the past year, however, the General
Accounting Office, an investigative arm of Congress, issued two
reports agreeing with that estimate by the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., along with Sens. Charles Robb of
Virginia and Carl Levin of Michigan, both Democrats, introduced the
legislation calling for the base closings. A candidate for
president, McCain has stood out in the national debate for his
strong advocacy of the military and national security, including
supporting the dispatch of ground troops to fight in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has the support of military and business officials who
argue that the military does not need all of the bases from the
Cold War era. Several critics of the vote on Wednesday dismissed
members who opposed the closings as shortsighted, with little
interest in efficiency.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``It's just symbolic of how Congress is not willing to make the
tough choices on defense,'' said Erik Pages, vice president of the
Business Executives for National Security, a nonpartisan group.
``You can't buy your way out of the current defense problems _
you've got to cut things as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Pages said the vote was a stiff public rebuke of Cohen and the
military chiefs, who had made base closings a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   But many Democrats also opposed the base closings, including
Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the minority leader. He joined
the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott of Mississippi, who said
Wednesday that ``the timing could not be worse.'' Lott said the
action in Kosovo was proving to him that the military had become
stretched and that no military base should be closed.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Warner, R-Va., the chairman of the Armed Services
Committee, supported two earlier rounds of base closings but since
those in 1996 he has voted against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``As secretary of the Navy, I closed bases in Boston and
Newport, Rhode Island, and I recognize there exists excess property
today,'' Warner said. ``I opposed this bill because politics have
destroyed the credibility of the process for closing bases.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
