<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-HOUSING-CODE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANNED WEAKENING OF BUILDING CODE ANGERS HURRICANE-PRONE
FLORIDIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Hurricane Andrew blew the roof off decades of shoddy
building practices in South Florida, exposing support columns
filled with wadded-up newspapers instead of concrete, and knocking
down walls made with cheap particle board that crumpled like
cardboard in the driving wind and rain. Roof beams that should have
been tied down with steel straps were found, after Andrew lifted
them up, up and away, to have been tied down by nothing.
</P>
<P>
   There were more extreme examples, like Styrofoam used as the
most substantial material in porch pillars and cement that
dissolved in the rain, as mile after mile of devastation from the
hurricane revealed a standard of construction and inspections that
people would have laughed at if they had not been standing in the
ruins of their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not until you have 11 people standing in one bathroom, three
of those your children, and your life is threatened do you realize
how important the building code is,'' said Julie Romero, whose home
came apart around her and her family as Andrew roared through
Homestead, Florida City and other communities south of Miami on
Aug. 23, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers and state officials have estimated that as much as 40
percent of the $16 billion in damage caused by the storm was
attributable to the region's legacy of lax codes, slipshod and
sometimes illegal construction, and inspections that residents
derisively referred to as ``drive-bys.'' To try to make sure it
never happens again, South Florida officials changed the building
codes, resulting in stronger, safer buildings, people here say.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in a move that has many people shaking their heads in
bewilderment, the state is proposing to supersede South Florida's
higher standards and allow builders to operate under a new, weaker
statewide code that would undo much of what was accomplished in the
wake of Andrew, the most expensive natural disaster in the nation's
history.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Building Commission, a state agency formed after the
hurricane rearranged the face of South Florida, is drafting the
code, which will be presented to the state Legislature next year.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the plan fear that it has a good chance of going into
effect because builders are a big part of the Republican Party's
base here, and Gov. Jeb Bush is a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor is not in favor of anything that's going to leave
structures in South Florida vulnerable to hurricanes,'' said Corey
Tilley, a spokeswoman for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   `'He's reviewing it and it's only a draft right now,'' Ms.
Tilley said of the proposed statewide code.
</P>
<P>
   State officials have recently unveiled a first draft of their
proposal that would install ``a weak code for the whole state,''
said Jerry Jarrell, director of the National Hurricane Center in
Miami. ``And they're forcing South Florida to use it.''
</P>
<P>
   It would supersede a building standard in South Florida that has
become a model for coastal construction elsewhere in the state, the
Caribbean and as far away as Australia, county officials and
homeowners said.
</P>
<P>
   If the proposed plan passes the Legislature with its current
watered-down codes, ``that's a crime,'' Jarrell said.
</P>
<P>
   It is, residents say, one of those ``only in Florida'' stories,
where land developers and their powerful political lobbies have
long influenced the fate and future of the state.
</P>
<P>
   State officials have said the statewide system would give
Florida a solid, uniform code that could be more easily enforced,
and would help hold down housing costs that have been driven up by
excessive requirements.
</P>
<P>
   But in South Florida, residents have learned that less stringent
codes allow cheaper construction, which increases profit margins.
And people who are protesting the change, as well as experts on
what the hurricanes that menace South Florida can do, contend that
profits are the real reason behind the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The building codes in Florida should have always been a lot
stronger,'' said Charles Glagola, a professor of civil engineering
at the University of Florida. Hurricane Andrew, he said, should
have taught the state a lesson.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Pfeiffer, chairman of the Florida Building Commission,
acknowledged that the proposed code has become an emotional issue,
but said it should not be.
</P>
<P>
   The code is still being shaped as the commission ``comes to a
conclusion that balances safety issues with affordability issues,''
Pfeiffer said.
</P>
<P>
   Counties like Miami-Dade and Broward, which have installed
similar, tough building codes, can amend the state code by a vote
of their county commissions to make it stronger, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can do better, in my opinion,'' said Pfeiffer,
referring to the Florida Building Commission's efforts to put in
place a code that adequately protects people in high-risk areas
like South Florida. ``My opinion is also that folks in Dade County
have elevated this issue to political heights that it does not
deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not true, said commissioner Miguel Diaz de la Portilla
of Miami-Dade County, who is fighting the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say, `You can amend this,' but they've created too many
bureaucratic hurdles to make that viable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a part of the country where prefabricated homes and small
apartment buildings seem to appear overnight, residents say, any
loophole will be exploited. And homeowners fear that with a weaker,
statewide code in place, it will be harder to challenge shoddy
construction in the courts, the last resort for many South
Floridians in the past. Even after the county amends it, as some
commissioners have promised to do, builders will use that statewide
code as a legal standard, contending that the local codes are
excessive, homeowners say.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Residents fear a mess, legal and otherwise, for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to fight substandard work, but as long as we have
good codes we can do something'' to protect against builders who
try to cut corners on construction, said John Sykes, a 55-year-old
real estate investor whose home in Cutler Ridge was destroyed by
Hurricane Andrew.
</P>
<P>
   The latest draft of the proposed code would, if adopted, require
less reinforcing steel in construction, remove mandates for
hurricane shutters and lessen other construction requirements
designed to guard against high winds.
</P>
<P>
   And, in a move that seems to concern residents most, it would
reduce the number of inspections during construction from eight to
three.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great deal of the damage to the homes was due to inadequate
inspections,'' said Glagola, the engineering professor. ``You have
to be out there in the field making sure the code requirements are
in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Insurers have sided with homeowners in the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make any sense to lessen the building codes,'' said
Jane Wahl, public affairs manager for State Farm Insurance,
Florida's largest insurer.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance writers have predicted that lessened standards and
inevitable shoddy building will only drive up insurance rates.
</P>
<P>
   Homeowners, Ms. Wahl said, are willing to pay more for quality
construction if it means a safer, better-built home.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the stringent codes, insurance rates have climbed
steadily since Hurricane Andrew.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lower the building standards, the insurance companies
will continue to increase the premiums,'' said Sykes, whose own
insurance has tripled in cost since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Builders in South Florida, who make up one of Florida's most
powerful lobbies, are behind the statewide code.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Maxwell, executive director of the Builders Association of
South Florida, said the uniform code would make doing business
easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before this, there were hundreds of building codes around the
state of Florida,'' she said. ``These codes were running up
costs.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also misleading, Ms. Maxwell said, to believe that tougher
building codes will protect people in a storm like Andrew. ``The
building code can help minimize damage, but people need to realize
that when there's a Category 4 or 5 hurricane, like Andrew, there's
going to be significant damage and loss of life. You're not safe in
250 mile-per-hour wind gusts.''
</P>
<P>
   Homeowners in South Florida say they do not believe that the
money builders save will be passed on to them.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Romero, whose home was destroyed by Andrew, was one of about
40 or 50 protesters who picketed one of the state building
commission's public hearings on the proposal last week in
Hollywood, north of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Florida wants to go with a new code,'' she said, ``accept
our code and let counties that want an inferior code apply for an
inferior code.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
