<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS NO. 1 HINGIS PERSEVERES, KAFELNIKOV DISAPPEARS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The No. 1 player in the world fell in an upset Wednesday
at the French Open, but not the No. 1 whose match against the
fourth-most popular athlete in France had been infused with the
hype of a heavyweight prizefight and the gravity befitting a moral
debate.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1-seeded Martina Hingis admitted that she felt as if ``a
heavy rucksack of stones'' had been lifted off her shoulders after
she sent an outclassed Amelie Mauresmo packing, 6-3, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss player performed with more wit and composure than her
popular rival did, and she advanced toward the only Grand Slam
title she has not won. ``I think if I will win this tournament on
this red stuff here in Paris, I really deserve it,'' Hingis said.
</P>
<P>
   But top-seeded Yevgeny Kafelnikov, who became a Grand Slam
champion here at Roland Garros in 1996 and swore he could do it
again if he could just clear his second-round hurdle, instead made
a premature but somewhat predictable exit.
</P>
<P>
   Kafelnikov's top ranking fell into jeopardy once Dominik Hrbaty,
a 30th-ranked spoiler who has defeated him all four times the
Russian has faced him, chased him out of Roland Garros, 6-4, 6-1,
6-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to ask him if he has a complex about me,'' said
Hrbaty, who made a memorable Grand Slam debut at the 1996
Australian Open, where he was a point away from taking a 5-2
fifth-set lead against another No. 1, Pete Sampras, in the fourth
round.
</P>
<P>
   This was Kafelnikov's first time trying to uphold the top
seeding at a Grand Slam event. And despite his best intentions, he
reverted to the form that brought him six consecutive first-round
losses this spring _ a slump that made his ascension to the top
ranking on May 3 a bit of a paradox. Now 6-4 since becoming No. 1,
Kafelnikov called his clay-court preparation ``very poor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm not 100 percent in my game, it's pretty obvious that
I'm going to have a tough day in the office, and that's basically
what happened,'' said Kafelnikov, whose ranking rose on the
strength of his 1999 Australian Open victory. ``For the fans to see
the No. 1 player in the world losing in the early stages of a
tournament is really frustrating; all I can see is being No. 1 is a
great responsibility, because everybody wants to get a piece of
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis knew that the 18th-ranked Mauresmo had that attitude, as
well as a desire for further revenge against Hingis for off-court
remarks regarding the French teen-ager's homosexuality. And she
knew the Roland Garros crowd, which booed her entrance and booed
her again the moment she touched the ball as she and Mauresmo
started a nervous warm-up session on Center Court, was dying for
her loss. But Hingis was determined not to give them, or Mauresmo,
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I knew what to expect,'' said Hingis, who was hissed like
a villain when she fell to a vengeful Mauresmo, 2-6, 6-1, 6-3, at
their last meeting in February in the quarterfinals of the Paris
Indoors.
</P>
<P>
   Of her plans to keep Pandemonium, and Mauresmo's home-court
advantage, at bay Wednesday, Hingis said, ``I didn't let it go that
far that they could scream and do something really big.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 18-year-old Hingis, who handled the pressure with her usual
grin-and-bear-it aplomb and let Mauresmo cave in with 51 unforced
errors, added: ``It wasn't such a great match. It depended a lot on
mental things, how we both were dealing with the crowd, the
pressure, and everything. I think I am a better player, if I play
well, than her. Everybody was putting pressure on her. Maybe if she
would have played someone else, she would go further.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis has been treated like public enemy No. 1 in France, and
Mauresmo has been hailed as a heroine, ever since Hingis made
disparaging remarks about her opponent's sexual preference at the
Australian Open. During that event, Mauresmo announced she was a
lesbian after advancing to the final, where Hingis trampled her,
6-2, 6-3, to win the title.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis reportedly referred to Mauresmo as ``half a man,'' a
remark that she has never completed retracted but has repeatedly
insisted was blown out of proportion. Wednesday Hingis acknowledged
their relationship remained chilly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't love each other; we're not best friends on the
tour,'' Hingis said. ``But I think it's a professional
relationship. She has her own people around her. I have mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauresmo insisted she wasn't overwhelmed by the pressure of the
situation, but she did confess that she perhaps ``overdid it'' in
her quest to spoil Hingis' French Open bid and satisfy her public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to push it,'' said the Frenchwoman, who had
her backhand exploited by Hingis. ``She is No. 1. I'm still far
behind. She adjusts her game to the surface. At the crucial moments
of the match, she does the exact shots that need to be played.''
</P>
<P>
   At the most crucial moment of 13th-seeded Andre Agassi's
3-hour-20-minute entanglement with 82nd-ranked Arnaud Clement of
France, the Las Vegan buckled down and refused to submit.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he found himself two points away from being upset in
the 10th game of the fourth set, Agassi pulled off a 6-2, 4-6, 2-6,
7-5, 6-0 victory. After clawing his way to 30-30 from a 30-0
deficit in that service game at 4-5, Agassi used a pair of
blistering cross-court backhanders to hold for 5-5, broke Clement
with a backhand drop shot after a 19-stroke exchange, and escaped a
40-0 deficit in the course of serving out the set. In the 20-minute
fifth set, a cramping Clement was virtually invisible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I managed to hang in there long enough to make something good
happen,'' said Agassi, who will see a more familiar face,
Knoxville's Chris Woodruff, in the next round. Woodruff beat Agassi
here in the second round in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
