u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-SPENDING-NYT &LR;      05-26 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-SPENDING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUERRILLA TACTICS STOP SPENDING BILL IN HOUSE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a challenge to Speaker Dennis Hastert and a
harbinger of chaos to come, conservatives Wednesday tried to derail
the year's first spending bill on the floor of the House.
</P>
<P>
   The House was tied in knots as Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., used
legislative guerrilla tactics that stopped a Republican-approved
$60.8 billion agriculture bill cold.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, the first of 13 spending measures that will come to
the House floor this year, was supposed to be easy to pass. But it
was threatened with death by a thousand cuts _ or 119, to be
precise.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn vowed to submit 119 amendments, one by one, until a
quarter-billion dollars is cut from the agriculture bill, bringing
it down to last year's level. He and his allies intend to force
Hastert to devise a grand strategy for financing the government
without dipping into surplus Social Security money.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn has solid backing from many House conservatives. The two
Texas Republicans who lead them _ the majority leader, Dick Armey,
and the majority whip, Tom DeLay _ voted for some of his
amendments, signaling their support.
</P>
<P>
   The ranking Democrat on the House Appropriations Committee, Rep.
David R. Obey of Wisconsin, said those votes showed that ``the
leadership of the House on the Republican side is cooperating in
the destruction of its own ability to produce any progress on
appropriation bills for the rest of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   What is happening here has little to do with whether the
Agriculture Department spends an extra $300,000 on wool research,
money that would be cut by one of Coburn's myriad of amendments. It
will directly affect Republican plans to cut billions of dollars of
social programs, Democratic efforts to thwart them, and both
parties' vows to hold down federal spending.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn, an obstetrician by trade, is delivering a harsh message.
He says Hastert has ``no appropriations strategy'' and ``no plan to
control spending'' _ and no way to avoid repeating last year's
spectacle of a last-minute spending bill that included $21 billion
in extras.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert ``respects Coburn's resolve'' and did not oppose his
amendments, one of the speaker's spokesmen said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Coburn said he was not attacking Hastert's
leadership. But, he said, ``my team's got to have a game plan, and
we don't have one right now. The speaker doesn't feel he has a
strategy yet that'll work.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon, debate on the agriculture spending ceased.
Instead, the House began debating Republican legislation aimed at
locking away surplus Social Security and Medicaid funds. Only last
week, Congress approved and President Clinton signed an emergency
spending bill financed with nearly $13 billion in excess Social
Security revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn said Wednesday that he intended to keep trying to talk
the agriculture bill to death. ``My intent is to re-establish the
integrity of the House, to make them do what they said they were
going to do,'' namely, ensure the sanctity of Social Security
surpluses, said Coburn, who will retire next year.
</P>
<P>
   Though Democrats on the House floor called the parade of
amendments ``a spectacle'' and ``a circus,'' Coburn said, ``I think
the American people benefit from seeing the debates on how we spend
money, and the closer that we put the magnifying glass to it, the
better we are as a country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
