<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN TO SEND ANOTHER 12,000 TROOPS TO BALKANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Signaling its strong backing for the
deployment of ground troops, Britain on Wednesday ordered 12,000
soldiers to prepare to join an expanded NATO peacekeeping force for
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The move came as NATO announced it would hold a meeting on
Monday to decide how many troops each member would contribute to a
heavily armed peacekeeping force of 50,000 soldiers that is to
deploy mainly in Macedonia over the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   NATO decided on Tuesday to add to the pressure on the Yugoslav
president, Slobodan Milosevic, by increasing the number of troops
planned for a peacekeeping force from 28,000 to 50,000. Under
present plans, the troops would not enter Kosovo until Yugoslav
forces had been withdrawn from the province.
</P>
<P>
   George Robertson, the British defense secretary, told the House
of Commons that Britain had decided it would make ``a substantial
contribution'' to the planned force. ``This is consistent with the
role we have taken so far in the campaign and with our
determination that it be brought to a quick and successful
conclusion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Britain already has about 5,000 troops in the region, so the
eventual dispatch of another 12,000 would mean that British
soldiers would account for about one third of the NATO force. The
United States has indicated it will send about 7,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said the aim was to have at least 30,000 troops
on Kosovo's southern border within the next month, and then add to
those progressively. About 14,000 NATO troops for the peacekeeping
mission are already in the region.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-nation Western alliance wants to be in a position to
deploy well-armed forces in Kosovo simultaneously with any peace
agreement. With diplomacy moving slowly, Western officials say no
accord is now expected before a meeting of the Group of Seven
wealthiest nations and Russia in mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   Britain has been arguing for several weeks that at least the
threat of the use of ground troops may be essential to enable NATO
to achieve its aim of bringing more than 1 million ethnic Albanian
refugees back to their homes in a Kosovo that all Yugoslav forces
will have left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is essential that we create a troop presence that will
ensure that the refugees are able to return safely to their
homes,'' Tony Blair, the British prime minister, said Wednesday.
The NATO troop buildup is also clearly intended to foster ambiguity
about the alliance's eventual intentions. Earlier statements from
Western leaders that a ground attack was not under consideration
have given way to more ambiguous remarks from some that suggest
that an eventual invasion by a force of about 150,000 troops is
possible if all other measures fail.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting on Monday to discuss the participation in the
50,000-strong force will be organized by the deputy commander of
NATO forces, Gen. Rupert Smith, a British general who commanded
U.N. troops in Bosnia during the last year of the war there and
took a generally tough line with the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said the British forces being prepared for deployment
included three infantry battalion groups already in training for
action in Kosovo, a commando brigade and air force support
helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are serious steps and they will place great demands upon
all three services, individual servicemen and their families,'' he
said. ``But they are steps which measure up to the seriousness of
the situation confronting us in Kosovo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 2112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
