<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-TABLOIDS-ART-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALACE CALLS PUBLICATION OF REVEALING PHOTO OF ROYAL FIANCEE
`CRUELTY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In a rambunctious renewal of the war between Britain's
tabloids and the royal family, The Sun Wednesday published a
decade-old private snapshot of Prince Edward's fiancee, Sophie
Rhys-Jones, with a breast bared.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rhys-Jones, a 34-year-old London press agent, is to wed
Edward, the 35-year-old son of Queen Elizabeth, in a glittering
ceremony at Windsor Castle in three weeks, and Buckingham Palace
issued a statement condemning the newspaper's action and its timing
as ``premeditated cruelty.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Sophie Topless'' headline appeared on newsstands during a
week in which the behavior of Britain's notorious tabloid press was
once again in dispute because of a series of disclosures of sex and
drug scandals uncovered by the use of hidden cameras, secret tape
recordings and reporters faking their identities.
</P>
<P>
   Editors had pledged to abandon such techniques in the earnest,
furrowed-brow re-evaluations of individuals' rights to bar
intrusions into their private lives that followed the death of
Diana, the Princess of Wales, in a car crash in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Challenging The Sun, Chris Tarrant, a broadcaster who appeared
in the picture with Ms. Rhys-Jones, said, ``Haven't you learned
anything from the death of Diana?''
</P>
<P>
   The shot was taken on a business trip to Spain in 1988, at a
time when Ms. Rhys-Jones was handling public relations for Capital
Radio, and the breakfast show Tarrant presented was originating
from Malaga, a favorite British vacation spot.
</P>
<P>
   The picture was taken by the show's co-host at the time, Kara
Noble, at a moment when Tarrant had taken a playful tug at Ms.
Rhys-Jones' bikini top. Both of them are laughing in the snapshot,
which was considered so harmless at the time that it was posted on
a bulletin board at the station's London offices.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Noble, who in 1995 moved to a rival morning broadcast,
received as much as $400,000 from The Sun for the picture, Reuters
reported. She may need the money since her employer, Heart FM,
dismissed her Wednesday ``with immediate effect'' on learning of
her involvement in the story.
</P>
<P>
   Brian MacLaurin, a public relations executive who first
introduced Ms. Rhys-Jones to Prince Edward, said that the couple
had known of the existence of the photograph and that Ms. Noble had
as recently as two months ago given assurances that ``this picture,
taken in private among friends, would not find its way into the
public domain.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he had spoken to Ms. Rhys-Jones Wednesday and that
she was ``furious, angry, upset and feels betrayed.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckingham Palace said it would formally seek action from the
Press Complaints Commission, and David Yelland, editor of The Sun,
said he would apologize to Ms. Rhys-Jones and to the palace.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a busy week for the tabloids, and for three straight
days The Mirror, with a readership of 2.2 million, has been beaten
to the punch by The Sun, with its readership of 3.5 million. It
retaliated Wednesday in creative style.
</P>
<P>
   Portraying itself as concerned with good manners _ something no
one has thus far ever suspected it of _ it criticized its rival for
exercising bad taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shame on You,'' it scolded The Sun on its front page. ``How
Many More Will They Smear?'' it asked on an inside page reproducing
Sun headlines earlier this week describing adulterous romps by a
well-known comedian (``Lenny Henry's Night With a Blonde'') and a
onetime cricket hero (``Botham's Secret Lover'').
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The latest skirmish in the tabloid wars began on Sunday when the
News of the World, whose circulation, four million, is Britain's
largest, published admissions of drug abuse and frolics with
prostitutes in Amsterdam by the captain of the English national
rugby team, Lawrence Dallaglio.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old athlete denied the charges but immediately
resigned his position and said he would not accompany the team on a
coming World Cup warm-up tour of Australia. Attention focused as
much on the methods used to extract his confessions as the
admissions themselves.
</P>
<P>
   A meeting with Dallaglio in a London hotel had been set up by
people who said they represented the Gillette toiletries company
and were interested in signing him up to an $800,000 sponsorship
deal. They had business cards and letterheads that identified them
as members of the CSR Partnership in the North London neighborhood
of Islington. In fact no such advertising agency existed, and they
were reporters for the News of the World.
</P>
<P>
   The room was wired for recording and a hidden video camera
before Dallaglio's arrival, with monitors stationed in the
adjoining room. Dallaglio said that he was interviewed for five
hours over bottles of champagne and that a woman asked leading
questions about his sexual and drug-taking past.
</P>
<P>
   The Press Complaints Commission permits ``legitimate
subterfuge'' where uncovering criminal activity is the purpose. In
the last year, reporters disguising their identities have exposed
the drug habits of a number of minor British celebrities and of the
sons of Camilla Parker Bowles, the mistress of Prince Charles, and
Home Secretary Jack Straw, who is in charge of law enforcement in
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   In a case that resulted in a nine-month jail sentence by a
London judge Wednesday, John Alford, a 27-year-old television
actor, was caught supplying cocaine and cannabis in an arranged
meeting at the Savoy Hotel with a man who said he was seeking drugs
and gave his name as Sheik Mohammed al-Kardeem. In fact, he was
Mazher Mahmoud, the newspaper's investigations editor.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on Tuesday, Dallaglio admitted making the
admissions but said he had been lying, bragging in an effort to
impress the woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played along with that game,'' he said, ``totally stupidly
and foolishly and created stories which simply weren't true in an
attempt to fit in with them and obviously to try to impress them in
some way.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper dismissed the explanation as ``frankly
astonishing'' and said it would furnish tapes to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Hall, the editor of the paper, has assigned a number of
young women to the scandal beat, and the BBC accused him of
springing ``honey traps'' on victims. Hall replied that his purpose
was to ``redress the balance in an office which is
male-dominated.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``The best cover on an investigative story can
sometimes be a couple. You cannot send two blokes to an orgy. The
girl will often play a softer part, flirting with a drugs dealer
perhaps, while the man plays the hard buyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Sophie Goodchild, a former News of the World staffer who now
works at The Independent on Sunday, said she would deliberately
dress in leather miniskirt, thigh-high boots and tight tops and
that ``flirting was definitely the name of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``The idea was to lull people into a false sense of
security and it did work.''
</P>
<P>
   Aylia Fox, who worked ``undercover'' for the News of the World
for eight years, said she had posed as a nurse, prostitute, spouse
swapper, swinger, hospital well-wisher and a nun to get stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it,'' she said, ``nobody wants to talk to a News of
the World reporter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
