<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PENTAGON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESSED BY WAR IN KOSOVO, PENTAGON POSTPONES AIR FORCE
RETIREMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: 2nd take is new)  (rm) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon ordered a sweeping suspension of
retirements from the Air Force Wednesday to ensure that enough
pilots and other personnel are available to continue waging NATO's
air war in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The order, another sign of the strain the war is putting on the
U.S. military, immediately affects more than 6,000 officers and
flyers who have indicated plans to retire by December.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, it will postpone any new retirements by about
120,000 Air Force personnel with particular job skills, including
virtually all pilots, as well as navigators, air-traffic
controllers, weather forecasters and intelligence analysts.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the order affects 40 percent of the Air Force's 363,000
personnel; the other services, which have provided comparatively
fewer forces to the campaign, are not affected.
</P>
<P>
   The order underscored the depth of the American commitment to
the war, which appears no closer to an end than when it began more
than two months ago. It also made clear that the Pentagon, like the
NATO allies, is preparing to conduct its military campaign well
into the summer or fall, with consequences that will ripple across
the armed services.
</P>
<P>
   Wielding the same authority that allows him to activate
reservists and National Guard members, President Clinton can in
effect make military service obligatory, forcing personnel to stay
on active duty beyond the tours they signed up for. The Air Force,
which was struggling to stop pilots from quitting to join
commercial airlines even before the war began, took pains to
acknowledge the hardship such a step would cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are acutely aware that ours is a volunteer force and that
this action, while essential to meeting our worldwide obligations,
is inconsistent with fundamental principles of voluntary service,''
the acting secretary of the Air Force, F. Whitten Peters, said in a
statement Wednesday. ``We also know that this action will adversely
affect the lives of airmen and their families.''
</P>
<P>
   The suspension is the first since August 1990, when the United
States began to build up the force of more than 500,000 troops that
ultimately repelled Iraq's invasion of Kuwait. President Clinton
has already activated more than 5,000 reserves and Guard members
and authorized the call up of as many as 33,000.
</P>
<P>
   The action came as the alliance pressed its air war with a
withering new wave of strikes. At NATO's headquarters, spokesmen
said that allied warplanes took advantage of clear weather and
launched the heaviest night of raids so far, including 358 strike
missions.
</P>
<P>
   Over the 24 hours leading up to Wednesday afternoon, NATO
warplanes hit 58 targets, including, for the second night in a row,
a bunker beneath one of the villas of the Yugoslav president,
Slobodan Milosevic, outside of Belgrade. NATO also hit army
barracks and armored forces operating in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Brussels and here in Washington have vowed to
intensify the attacks. They said they want to put still more
military pressure on Milosevic, even as he faces international
diplomatic pressure, with the news that the war crimes tribunal in
The Hague, Netherlands, has issued an indictment against him.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its successes in hitting Yugoslavia's forces, however,
there is still little indication that the air war has brought
Milosevic any closer to accepting NATO's demands that he withdraw
his forces from Kosovo and allow the province's ethnic Albanians to
return to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring misgivings within the Pentagon about NATO's
strategy, the Army's senior general said Wednesday that he had
concerns whether air power alone would force Milosevic to back
down.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Dennis Reimer, the Army's chief of staff, said that NATO's
air campaign had inflicted enormous damage on the Yugoslav military
and paramilitary forces but could not, even after more than two
months of bombing, guarantee Milosevic's capitulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it has been disruptive to him,'' Reimer said in a
breakfast interview with reporters. ``I think it has been highly
effective, the air campaign, in terms of not losing any airmen.
Whether it will actually succeed in bringing him to his knees and
the five points that we have said are critical, or not, I just
don't know yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the hard part about it,'' he added. ``You just don't
know whether you're an hour away from him capitulating or whether
you're months away.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   From the start, NATO's campaign has been met with reservations
within the U.S. military _ at least in private. Some senior
officers, notably Gen. Charles C. Krulak, the commandant of the
Marine Corps, openly questioned the strategy before the bombing
started, but Reimer, who is stepping down as the Army's chief next
June, was the first to detail his concerns so publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ``My view, in general terms, is that if you're going to use
military force, using the total military force available to you is
the right way to go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   An ideal campaign, he said, combines air power with large, heavy
ground forces. The Clinton administration, like many NATO allies,
has adamantly ruled out the use of ground troops to finish off the
campaign against Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had had ``adequate opportunity'' to express his views
in the internal debates that took place before the bombing began on
March 24. He also said the decision to rely on an air war had to be
understood in the context of NATO's consensus approach to making
war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was Napoleon who said, if you want to fight a war,
make sure it's against a coalition,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
