<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-ART-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE, IN TEXAS, SIDESTEPS OPPONENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The governor down here is thinking of running for
president. You might have heard something about it.
</P>
<P>
   But Vice President Al Gore, the presumptive front-runner for the
Democratic nomination, finished almost two days of hopscotching
across Texas without once allowing the name of George W. Bush, the
presumptive Republican front-runner, to cross his lips in public.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president walked along a dusty, sun-hardened street in
the small Rio Grande Valley town of Sebastian, chatting amiably
with camera-flashing residents; appeared at a White House
Empowerment Conference alongside President Clinton, who struggled
to spark a fledgling presidential effort that even the president
has declared energy deficient; pumped his fist in the air shouting
``Fiesta!'' a couple of times before attending a
mariachi-and-maraca picnic at a community college; raised some
money for Democrats around the palm-lined pool of a border
construction magnate; raised some more money at a fancy hotel in
downtown Dallas; talked to some students and parents about school
violence, and then was off to raise even more money at an evening
fund-raiser in another fancy hotel in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   And even though he was here in the enemy's lair, as if an
Achilles inside the walls of Troy, he never once brought up the
apparent, impending struggle between the two political scions to
take the world's superpower into the new century.
</P>
<P>
   It was on a few other people's minds, though.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Ortiz had been standing in the blistering late afternoon
sun in McAllen for almost an hour to get a glimpse of the vice
president's arrival at the community college fiesta. ``I think I
like Gore,'' Ortiz said. ``But he will have a very difficult time
defeating our governor in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Garry Mauro, the former land commissioner who lost a landslide
election to Bush last year, and who had been the state director of
the Clinton campaigns in 1992 and 1996, was working the crowds at
all three fund-raisers, one for the party's Hispanic Unity
political action committee and two for Gore's campaign. Mauro said
he expected the three events to raise a million dollars, most of it
for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro acknowledged that the vice president had not been getting
good reviews for some of his recent public appearances, reigniting
old concerns that he was too stiff and dull to connect to national
voters. But this would change, he said, as soon as more people got
to know Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it puts us in a good position,'' Mauro said. ``The
thing is, Gore's expectations, as a result, are way down here,
while Bush's are way up here. He's got nowhere to go but down. I'd
rather be where we are than where he is.''
</P>
<P>
   The closest Gore got to uttering the B word was during the forum
on Wednesday afternoon with his wife, Tipper, at W.E. Griener
Middle School (``no school finer'') in Dallas when he talked about
the need to ``take a stand against efforts to make concealed
weapons more commonplace in our society.'' Gore called on ``all
leaders everywhere to reconsider'' whether concealed-weapons laws
were such a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   This was widely seen, at least in Texas, as a first, tentative
nudge at Bush, who saw such a concealed-weapons law pass in his
first legislative session and has defended it repeatedly ever
since. Aides to the vice president said he was not trying to single
out Bush or any particular leader, but if the shoe fit ....
</P>
<P>
   Gore also questioned those who support state laws that prohibit
cities from filing suit against gun manufacturers. Such a law has
passed both houses of the Texas Legislature and, while the governor
has not yet signed it, he has signaled his intention of doing so.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bush, who is in the final week of the last Texas
legislative session before the 2000 presidential race, has shown an
increasing appetite for offering criticism of the way Clinton and
Gore have managed the administration.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said on Tuesday in Austin that the congressional
report on Chinese nuclear spying in the last 20 years ``also shines
a glaring light on the current administration's failed policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that while he understood that some of the nuclear
espionage had supposedly occurred during administrations when his
father was either vice president or president, he believed that
this was the first administration to know about it and should have
done more to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the balance of power is going to shift as a result of
this,'' Bush said. ``I think it's going to accelerate China's
emergence as a nuclear power. And the next president and presidents
after that are going to have to deal with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas became, for a couple of days this week, the epicenter of
the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush was holding forth on Chinese espionage in Austin, and
Clinton and Gore were in the Rio Grande Valley, former Sen. Bill
Bradley, Gore's only announced opponent in the Democratic race, was
appearing at fund-raisers in Houston and El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Not able to cushion himself from reporters' questions as easily
as the vice president, Bradley was forced to utter the governor's
name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really know much about George W. Bush, frankly,''
Bradley told reporters in El Paso. But Bradley, too, was reluctant
to cast stones too early.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in playing one game at a time, and this game is the
primary election,'' Bradley said. ``When I have the nomination,
then we'll focus on whoever is the Republican nominee.''
</P>
</TEXT>
