u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NELLIE-MAE-BOS &LR;      05-26 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NELLIE-MAE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NELLIE MAE TO SELL STUDENT LOAN SUBSIDIARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In a transaction that will put more loans in students'
hands and more grants in educational coffers, Nellie Mae Foundation
Inc., the Braintree-based educational lender and grantmaker, agreed
Wednesday to sell its student loan subsidiary to the nation's
largest buyer of such loans for $320 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The deal between Nellie Mae and SLM Holding Corp., known as
Sallie Mae, marks the final step in Nellie Mae's transformation
into a fully nonprofit entity focused on improving adult literacy,
high school graduation rates, and other educational issues.
</P>
<P>
   Nellie Mae will have $395 million in assets after the sale and
will become New England's largest educational grant source. Among
its recent projects are a $1 million award to the Boston Annenberg
Challenge to improve the city's public schools and a $1 million
subsidy to a New Hampshire program to foster leadership among high
school students.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also helps Sallie Mae's plans to ramp up its student
lending to $1 billion by 2000 from barely $5 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Nellie Mae had been among the nation's 10 biggest student loan
holders, with $2.6 billion in high-quality loans to students on 250
campuses throughout the country. It made most of the loans itself
but also bought some loans from other companies.
</P>
<P>
   The company began life as the New England Education Loan
Marketing Corp., and was originally a buyer and seller of other
outfits' loans, not a lender. It changed its focus to lending in
recent years and spun off its loan operations into a for-profit
unit in 1997. Nellie Mae executives had come to see a sale of their
lucrative loan making business as a good way to fully endow the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Sallie Mae, a quasiprivate firm with publicly
traded stock but government-guaranteed debt, services $47 billion
in over 5 million student loans it buys from other firms. The
company, based in Reston, Va., only recently dipped its toes into
the lending business.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Nellie Mae, the deal simply gives the foundation more
money,'' said analyst Howard Shapiro of Prudential Securities.
``For Sallie Mae, it boosts their share of the student loan market
by 5 percent to 25 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Student loans are highly lucrative for their makers and
handlers. Because its debt is backed by the government, Sallie Mae
can buy repackaged loans at below-market interest rates. In an
industry rife with default, Sallie Mae and Nellie Mae make money by
originating or servicing loans, either with federal or private
money, and later offering interest discounts to students to get
them to pay the loans back on time. In a market in which $35
billion in student loans is made each year, competition for lending
arrangements with colleges and universities is fierce.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's transaction, in which Sallie Mae is acquiring the
outstanding stock of Nellie Mae, is subject to regulatory approval
and is expected to close by June 30. Nellie Mae's loan unit will be
a wholly owned subsidiary of its parent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
