<SLUG> BC-BKN-WHITT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ RALLY RINGS A FAMILIAR TUNE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
Like corns, the Utah Jazz are old, irritating and almost impossible
to get rid of.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rest of the NBA's conference semifinals were May Sweeps, but
the Jazz is producing dramatic television by pushing the Trail
Blazers. Just when it seemed that Portland's youth, energy and
depth would shove them out of the series, the Jazz dominated Game 5
and forced tonight's Game 6 in Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played too hard for too long to just give up,'' Utah
guard Jeff Hornacek said. ``If Portland thought we were going to
roll over and die, they were wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by John Stockton's determination, Karl Malone's elbows and
Jerry Sloan's gritty leadership, the Jazz are 6-1 when facing
elimination the past two seasons, including 3-0 in these playoffs.
Only six teams in league history have rallied from a 3-1 deficit to
win a series. With a victory tonight and in Game 7 on Saturday in
Salt Lake City, the Jazz would become the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at our best when it's all on the line,'' Stockton said.
``We're forced to be now.''
</P>
<P>
   The other three series were over almost before they started, but
this one has turned attractively ugly. Malone has sent Brian Grant
to the floor twice with accidental (yeah, right) elbows, Sloan and
Mike Dunleavy have traded on-court tirades the past two games, and
Portland's Walt Williams agitated the veteran Jazz by pounding his
chest and screaming ``You can't do nothing with us!'' after Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz are surviving despite horrid play from center Greg
Ostertag and an uncharacteristic 31 missed free throws the past
three games. Portland, the fourth-youngest team in the league, has
a chance to win tonight despite Grant scoring only 15 points the
past two games while clearly bamboozled by Malone's baiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he doesn't like me and wants to talk trash to me, tell him
to get in line,'' Malone said. ``A lot of people don't like me
these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Whichever team survives the bloodbath, it's the
resting-and-waiting San Antonio Spurs who are truly benefiting.
\Nsubheds:Offbeat beat In this year of small-market success, NBC
must be rooting more than ever for the New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Already assured of a Western Conference team from the nation's
bottom third of markets: San Antonio (Spurs), Portland (Blazers) or
Salt Lake City (Jazz) _ the network couldn't afford a matchup
including Indianapolis (Pacers). Playoff ratings are already down
around 12 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a big believer that for the Finals to work, you have to
have stories,'' NBC Sports president Dick Ebersol said. ``With
Reggie Miller and Larry Bird, you have ready-made stars. Same with
Tim Duncan. The two most important factors _ in order _ are story
line and length of series. Market size is gravy.''
\Nsubheds:Numbers game 47.5: Shaquille O'Neal's free-throw
percentage in four games against the Spurs, compared with Tim
Duncan's 81 percent. Shaq has been swept out of the playoffs five
times in six years.
</P>
<P>
   31.6: The Hawks' shooting percentage against the Knicks,
managing a pitiful 306 points while being swept in four games.
\Nsubheds:24 seconds Sad sight at last week's exhibition pitting
the Globetrotters vs. college All-Stars: on one bench, former
Wizards coach Bernie Bickerstaff; on the other, former Mavericks
coach Jim Cleamons and top assistant Butch Beard. Surprise,
Cleamons' All-Stars weren't running the triangle offense. ... If
the Spurs advance to the NBA Finals, they'll be the first _ and
hopefully last _ to do so with a home-court splashed in pink. ...
Magic Johnson is at it again, not only dropping more hints that
he'd like to coach the Lakers, but even someday follow David Stern
as NBA commissioner. ... It's more than just a coincidence that the
Nets acquired point guard Stephon Marbury, quickly signed him to a
long-term contract, and now this week are interviewing former
Georgetown coach John Thompson for their vacancy. Marbury and
Thompson are David Falk clients. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
