<HEADLINE>
SPORTSLINE, BASEBALL HIT A WINNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In this dog-eat-dog world of sports cyberspace, another big dog
has taken a bite and gained some ground on its rival.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, SportsLine USA, the Fort Lauderdale, Fla.-based
sports Internet company known best for its CBS SportsLine site,
signed a three-year contract to produce Major League Baseball's
official site.
</P>
<P>
   SportsLine and baseball plans to relaunch the site next month
with an updated look and live audio broadcasts of each game in
addition to other snazzy features.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal will combine the access that baseball fans have with
the official site with some great new features on SportsLine,''
said Jerry Milani, spokesman for SportsLine USA.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is big news because it's another big-time consolidation
in the sports Internet industry. Big-media companies are aligning
their resources with professional leagues, and baseball was one of
the last holdouts.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the cyber big dogs, SportsLine has had the biggest growl
lately and seems to be closing the gap on rival ESPN Internet
Group, which has a near 2-to-1 advantage in Internet traffic. In
the past two months, SportsLine has been on a tear, acquiring
official sites for the PGA Tour and NFL Europe and announcing the
launch of SportsLine Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN Internet Group, which produces the official sites for the
NFL and NBA in addition to NASCAR, attracted 6.2 million unique
visitors to its sites, compared with 3.4 million for SportsLine
during April, according to Media Matrix, a company that measures
Internet use. ESPN Internet Group also gained an ally in the NHL
with a content-sharing agreement.
</P>
<P>
   SportsLine, which produces official sites for Tiger Woods,
Shaquille O'Neal and Michael Jordan, has its eye on toppling the
ESPN empire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be after them in a big way,'' said Michael
Levy, SportsLine president. ``If we had the NFL and NBA, we would
be solidly No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   With baseball's official site, SportsLine will be working with a
site that has few bells and whistles but has exclusive content.
SportsLine plans to add Baseball Live, a feature that animates live
pitch-by-pitch action from a game onto a Web page. SportsLine also
plans to post interactive games, historical sections and fantasy
competitions.
</P>
<P>
   Users will be able to access the baseball sites through
SportsLine's main page.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball put up its site for bid. SportsLine got
the inside track because of its experience with producing the
official site of the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, SportsLine will split advertising and
business revenue with baseball after the company gets a guaranteed
amount of revenue. Terms were not disclosed during yesterday's
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``SportsLine was very aggressive in their sales plan and that
impressed us,'' said Alex Kam, director of New Media for Major
League Baseball told Bloomberg News. ``It also helped that they
have done some things with us in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Milani: ``It was kind of like a test run to see how we'd
handle a big official site.''
BYTES
</P>
<P>
   Poll of the week: Stars goalie Ed Belfour isn't scoring high in
an ESPN.com poll that asks, ``Which of the remaining goalies would
you feel more comfortable playing in front of?'' Of 11,525
respondents, only 9.8 percent selected Belfour. Patrick Roy of the
Colorado Avalanche collected a poll-leading 40.9 percent of the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   New season, new design: WNBA.com, the official site of the WNBA
and its 12 teams, unveiled its redesign and new features Monday.
The site has streaming video, behind-the-scenes highlights and live
game radio broadcasts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
