<P>
   (NYT31) UNDATED -- May 26, 1999 -- Y2K-CONTINGENCY, 5-26 --
After months of weighing options, businesses and governments are
now being forced to decide how much they will invest in preparing
for year 2000 computer problems, and suddenly contingency planning
has moved to the top of many companies' agendas. Preparations are
likely to include the scheduling of more employees than normal to
be on duty in the weeks before and after New Year's, so that a
company can fall back on nonelectronic methods of business. (Tony
Cenicola/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) UNDATED -- May 26, 1999 -- GORE-CAMPAIGN, 5-26 -- Former
Gov. Mario Cuomo of New York, right, says the best thing for Vice
Presi dent Al Gore, center, in his campaign for president, would be
if Hillary Rodham Clinton stays put and does not run for the Senate
from New York. But his son Andrew Cuomo, left, the Secretary of
Housing and Urban Development, says the best thing for Gore's
campaign would be if Mrs. Clinton runs for the Senate. The dueling
Cuomos mirror a larger, public quarrel that is increasingly
consuming prominent Democrats. (Paul Hosefros, left, Bita Honarvar,
Cox News Service, center, Frances Roberts/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) MILAN, Italy -- May 26, 1999 -- LAST-SUPPER-2, 5-26 --
Reporters and art experts gather around the unveiling of Leonardo
da Vinci's 1498 masterpiece ``The Last Supper'' in Santa Maria
delle Grazie church after a major restoration which lasted over 20
years. Friday will be the public's first chance to see the painting
unencumbered by scaffolding, easels and equipment. (James Hill/New
York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) PORTLAND, Maine -- May 26, 1999 -- FOOD-GRILL-BOS, 5-26
-- Chef/owner Sam Hayward grilling a rabbit in his Fore Street
restaurant. Tomorrow, the room and even the street outside will
carry traces of the wood's irresistible smoky essence. (Tom
Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- May 26, 1999 -- AUTHOR-PIPES-BOS,
5-26 -- Richard Pipes' new book, ``Freedom and Property,'' is a
departure for the Harvard historian and one of the West's foremost
authorities on the Kremlin. A study of the connection between
political liberty and private ownership, it devotes only one of its
five sections to Russian history. ``In general, almost everything
that has been written in the field (of Soviet history) since the
'60s has been quite wrong,'' says Pipes, 75. (Wendy Maeda/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) MORINI, Albania -- May 26, 1999 -- KOSOVO-ALBANIA, 5-26
-- An exhausted and dehydrated ethnic Albanian refugee, who had
just crossed into Albania from neighboring Kosovo, is comforted on
a bus taking the refugees to a nearby camp on Wednesday. More than
300 refugees crossed into Albania Wednesday. (Tyler Hicks/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- May 26, 1999 -- ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS,
5-26 -- Wendell J. Knox, president and chief executive of Abt
Associates Inc., a public policy research firm in Cambridge. Knox,
50, controls $140 million in assets and employs 900 workers
worldwide. (Janet Knott/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) SPARTANBURG, S.C. -- May 26, 1999 -- SC-HOMEMADE-CD,
5-26 -- Baker Maultsby in a Wal-Mart parking lot in Spartanburg. If
there is anything to be gleaned from Maultsby's homemade CD,
``Bingo  &QC;  Sin,'' which boasts songs about
Wal-Marts, high school delinquents and greasy-food joints, it is
how permeable the line can be these days between brand-name culture
and semi-professional culture. ``People don't know it's not a real
record,'' he says. (Wade Spees/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- May 26, 1999 -- BOOK-TALK, 5-26 -- Elisabeth
Schmitz, editor and success story at Grove/Atlantic. She edits 8 to
10 books a year, and besides being a senior editor is the director
of subsidiary rights. ``At a bigger house I'd probably dump
rights,'' says Ms. Schmitz, 35. ``But everyone wears another hat
here, and anyway rights keeps me in touch with what's going on with
other publishers, and lets me deal with other editors.'' (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) BOSTON -- May 26, 1999 -- BKO-RUSSELL-B&AMP;W-BOS, 5-26 --
Boston Celtics star Bill Russell hugging coach Red Auerbach after
Russell scored his 10,000th point in an NBA game at the Boston
Garden, Dec. 12, 1964. The Celtics play their last regular season
game in the Garden - the scene of many special moments for
Auerbach, Russell and the team - Friday night. Next season, the
Celtics will be moving to a new facility and the Garden is set to
be demolished. (Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NORTH ADAMS, Mass. -- May 26, 1999 -- MASS-MOCA-2, 5-26
-- Joseph C. Thompson, the director of the Massachusetts Museum of
Contemporary Art, getting ready for the opening on Sunday in North
Adams. ``These buildings have a heft that invites large gestures,''
he says. After 13 roller-coaster years and a last-minute scramble
to install the giant artworks it was designed to display, the $37
million museum is finally ready. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NORTH ADAMS, Mass. -- May 26, 1999 -- MASS-MOCA-1, 5-26
-- The Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art opens on Sunday in
renovated 19th century industrial buildings in North Adams. After
13 roller-coaster years and a last-minute scramble to install the
giant artworks it was designed to display, the $37 million museum
is finally ready. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- May 26, 1999 -- NY-POLICE-BRUTALITY, 5-26 --
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York is sworn in before testifying
before the U.S. Civil Rights Commission on Wednesday. Giuliani and
his police commissioner, Howard Safir, took part the broad-ranging
hearing to determine if police routinely violate citizens' civil
rights. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- May 26, 1999 -- REPUBS-CAMPAIGN, 5-26 --
Rep. Christopher Shays, right, huddles with his Rep. Greg Ganske
before a press conference on campaign finance reform, Wednesday. A
small group of Republicans broke with their party and signed a
petition to force a vote on campaign finance overhaul. Shays made a
frontal assault on Rep. Tom DeLay, the Republican whip, calling it
a struggle for the soul of the Republican party. Shays accused
Delay of threatening to fund a primary challenge in his district.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- May 26, 1999 -- PORCELAIN-TUB, 5-26 --
Rather than trying to match Donna Paul's old tile, David Mullman,
an architect, created a contrasting grid with new fittings.
Renovating a down-at-the-heels bathroom to its prewar glory can be
a stone-cold sobering experience, as thousands of New York co-op
owners have learned. (Donna Paul/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- May 26, 1999 -- BATHROOM-SINK, 5-26 --
Vitraform's glassyslot-nat/el con ca bath sink. The old-fashioned,
large-ledged lavatory sink is being pulled down its own drain by
fashion and the plumbing fixtures industry, which has been steadily
flooding the market with novel product introductions it hopes will
create a thirst for new types of bathroom sinks. (Tony Cenicola/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEWTON, Mass. -- May 26, 1999 -- URBAN-BEAUTIFICATION,
5-26 -- Martia Branch, left, and Olivia Swomley, proud of the
woods. Since the Newton Pride Committee was started more than a
decade ago, hundreds of volunteers have planted more than a million
bulbs, annuals and trees in public places around town - at no cost
to the city. (Evan Richman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- May 26, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 30 --
ANASTASIA-BALLET-2-B&AMP;W, 5-26 -- Lynn Seymour rehearsing
``Anastasia'' at the Metropolitan Opera House in 1989. On Thursday,
``Anastasia'' returns to New York in the first of eight
performances to be presented by American Ballet Theater at the
Metropolitan Opera House. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- May 26, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 30 --
ANASTASIA-BALLET-1, 5-26 -- Viviana Durante, who will dance the
title role in ``Anastasia'' this week with American Ballet Theater.
The ballet - set to music by Tchaikovsky - depicts some of the
dramatic, often harshly contrasting events that the woman who
claimed she was Anastasia might have lived through in the days
before and after the Czar's family was executed in 1918. (Nicole
Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- May 26, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 30 --
JAZZ-IMPRESSARIOS, 5-26 -- George Wein, seated, and Michael Dorf at
the New York Times recently. Wein and Dorf - impresarios of this
year's JVC Jazz Festival and the Bell Atlantic Jazz Festival,
respectively - have been butting heads for 11 years. ``I can't
understand the new technology and things like that,'' says Wein,
73, who produced 37 music festivals around the world in 1998.
``Jazz is perfectly suited for the Internet because it is a little
more intelligent,'' says Dorf, 37, who runs a club and a record
label. (Jeffrey A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) VENICE, Italy -- May 26, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 30
-- INSTALLATION-ARTIST, 5-26 -- The artist Ann Hamilton in front of
the American Pavilion in Venice, where she is representing the
United States at the 48th Biennale with an installation called
``Myein'': stepping into a temporary world. ``I'm thinking that I
am the American representative, and it's the eve of the
millennium,'' she says. ``I want to bring to the surface the
questions we should be asking.'' (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) MILAN, Italy -- May 26, 1999 -- LAST-SUPPER, 5-26 --
Crowds gather around the unveiling of Leonardo da Vinci's 1498
masterpiece ``The Last Supper'' in Santa Maria delle Grazie church
after a major restoration which lasted over 20 years. (James
Hill/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) LONDON -- May 26, 1999 -- BRITAIN-TABLOIDS, 5-26 -- A man
walks past a newstand on Wednesday. There is an uproar as The Sun
prints a topless picture of Prince Edward's finance, just weeks
before the wedding. She says her engagement is ``ruined.'' Even
another tabloid says ``SHAME ON YOU'' to The Sun. All this comes
during a week of tabloid frenzy and criticism over tabloid
reporters who pose as non-journalists to trick famous people into
revealing secrets. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- May 26, 1999 -- CHINA-COX-NUKE-2, 5-26 --
Reps. Norman Dicks, foreground, and Christopher Cox, testify about
Chinese espionage before the House International Relations Asia and
the Pacific subcommittee on Wednesday. Projected on the wall is a
copy of a Chinese document from their report that reads: Combine
the military and civil, combine peace and war, give priority to
military products, let the civil support the military. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- May 26, 1999 -- CHINA-COX-NUKE-1, 5-26 --
Sen. Joe Biden, D-Del., standing, gives a speech about nuclear
warfare and the latest developments on alleged Chinese espionage on
the steps of the U.S. Capitol to a group of visiting high school
students from Neward, Del., on Wednesday. Biden is the ranking
member on the Senate Foreign Affairs committee. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- May 26, 1999 -- URINAL-2, 5-26 -- Philippe
Starck, progenitor of chic hotel bathrooms, has designed a urinal
for the home that is a porcelain horn of plenty. The last time a
urinal was the center of attention, it was signed by Marcel Duchamp
and hanging upside down in a show of avant-garde art. Today, the
urinal has taken its stand alongside the bidet and the working
fireplace as the latest must-have in the well-ap pointed bathroom
suite. (New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- May 26, 1999 -- URINAL-1, 5-26 -- The Porsche
of urinals, made by J. L. Mott between 1900 and 1920. With the look
of a bidet bulked up on steroids, the Mott urinal is topped off
with an ornamental steel cap that resembles a shiny fire hydrant.
Such urinals can sell for as much as $5,000. The last time a urinal
was the center of attention, it was signed by Marcel Duchamp and
hanging upside down in a show of avant-garde art. Today, the urinal
has taken its stand alongside the bidet and the working fireplace
as the latest must-have in the well-ap pointed bathroom suite.
(Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- May 26, 1999 -- OBIT-LORTEL, 4-05 -- Jo
Sullivan Loesser performs on Monday during a memorial tribute for
the Off Broadway producer Lucille Lortel who died in April. Lortel,
the longtime theater producer known as the Queen of Off Broadway,
was remembered at the memorial tribute as a benefactor of the arts
whose stubborn devotion to the playwrights she loved helped foster
some of the most celebrated theater of the 20th century. (Chester
Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- May 26, 1999 --CIR-HIDDEN-CHIPS, 5-26 -- The
average middle-class American household has about 40
microprocessors in it. If you own a PC, with all the paraphernalia
that goes with it, that number increases to about 50. However the
combined amount of microchips found in dishwashers, irons and other
appliances, known as embedded microprocessors, are far more
numerous than those that drive desktop or portable computers. (
Cenicola/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BERGENFIELD, N.J. -- May 26, 1999 -- CIR-WEB-MAIL, 5-26
-- How do you communicate with those who do not email? Go to
Letterpost.com, type a letter, and the folks at the other end will
print it out, put it in an envelope and plop it in a mailbox for
delivery by an old fashioned mailman. ``A substantial number of
people, like my parents' generation, will never get E-mail,'' says
the website's founder, Donal O'Mahony, a computer scientist on
sabbatical from Trinity College in Dublin who is now a visiting
scholar at Stanford University. (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- May 26, 1999 -- COLLEGE, 5-26 -- Barry Mason
on campus at Columbia University. Mason uses a high-speed Internet
connection in his dormitory which he misses greatly when returning
home on vacations. His parents use a dial-up connection which is
about 200 times slower then what Mason is accustomed. (Frances
Roberts/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
