<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2538 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASDAQ-TRADING-HOURS-     05-26 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASDAQ-TRADING-HOURS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVENING SESSION FOR NASDAQ MAY WIN APPROVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Directors of Nasdaq, the United States'
second-largest equity market after the New York Stock Exchange,
forwarded to its parent regulatory group on Wednesday a
recommendation that trading hours be extended to encompass an
evening session. That set the stage for possible adoption of the
proposal on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The board of the National Association of Securities Dealers, or
NASD, the self-regulatory group that oversees Nasdaq, will consider
the proposal at a meeting in Manhattan on Thursday. Though the
recommendation is not binding, several directors expect the measure
to be approved. Under the plan, Nasdaq, which is now open for
trading from 9:30 a.m. to 4 p.m., would close until 5:30 and then
extend trading in a session lasting to 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The evening trading session would begin, maybe as early as
September, after approval by the Securities and Exchange Commission
and a period allowing for comments by members of the association.
Trading would initially encompass a subset of the most actively
traded stocks on Nasdaq, perhaps as few as 100 of the market's more
than 6,000 stocks.
</P>
<P>
   A Nasdaq spokesman declined to comment on the action by the
Nasdaq board on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Levitt, chairman of the SEC, has said that he will not
stand in the way of such a proposal to extend trading hours, but he
has expressed concern that securities firms be adequately prepared
to deal with year 2000 computer issues before trying to take on an
added trading session.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Nasdaq officials said they expected to extend trading
hours beginning this summer. But the starting date was pushed back,
apparently in reaction to questions from traders, brokerage firms
and other market participants about how they would cope with a
longer trading day.
</P>
<P>
   At least two electronic trading services, operated by Eclipse
Trading and Wit Capital, have also said they intend to offer
after-hours trading beginning this summer.
</P>
<P>
   After the announcement by Nasdaq, the New York Stock Exchange
said that it, too, would consider offering a late trading session
beginning this year. Previously, the Big Board had expected to
adopt a late session starting in 2000. But Richard Grasso, chairman
of the exchange, said that if Nasdaq went ahead with its plan this
year, the New York Stock Exchange would be forced to move its
schedule up for competitive reasons.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting of financial executives on Thursday, Grasso is
expected to urge market officials to ``consider the public
interest'' before rushing to adopt extended trading hours, a
spokesman for the New York Stock Exchange said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Richard Ketchum, president of the NASD, told
representatives of the Independent Broker-Dealers Association, a
trade group representing small brokerage firms, that Nasdaq had
heard enough misgivings expressed by industry executives to decide
that extended trading hours should not be rushed into effect this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Davidson, president of the trade group, said small firms
were concerned that the comparatively higher costs they would face
for operating during an evening session would not be covered by
potential revenue. Davidson, who is also a member of the NASD board
that will consider the measure on Thursday, said he would oppose
extending trading hours unless small firms received guarantees that
their interests would be protected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
