<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GUN-SUITS-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUITS PUT GUN MAKERS UNDER SCRUTINY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Mass., N.Y., Pa.)  (rk) 
 By FOX BUTTERFIELD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Los Angeles and San Francisco filed lawsuits against the
gun industry on Tuesday, the growing legal assault on gun makers
gained its best opportunity to subject the industry to a
wide-ranging investigation that might reveal damaging internal
documents similar to those that led tobacco companies to settle
with the states, lawyers familiar with the gun cases say.
</P>
<P>
   The California suits have several advantages over those filed
earlier by other cities across the country, starting with the sheer
size of the populations involved, which gives them more financial
resources to litigate and more basis to win damages from the gun
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles is the most populous city yet to take on the gun
industry, and the nation's biggest gun market, and it was joined by
Compton and West Hollywood in its suit, while San Francisco's suit
was joined by Oakland, Sacramento and Berkeley and two counties,
Alameda and San Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles and San Francisco both hired the same two prominent
law firms that had won suits against tobacco companies, so that
their efforts to depose gun officials and learn about company
practices can be coordinated.
</P>
<P>
   Another advantage, lawyers said, is the California unfair
business practices law under which the cities are suing, a potent
tool that has been broadly interpreted by California courts. In
essence, all the cities need to prove is that the gun makers have
engaged in an unfair or reckless practice _ for example, by
marketing guns in a way that put them in the hands of criminals or
juveniles causing accidents or deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, a judge could order the gun companies to change
their distribution practices or to stop advertising in certain
magazines. A judge could also award penalties of $2,500 per count
for each gun sold improperly and order the companies to repay part
of their profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is fair to say that when the California cities
stepped into the litigation, the earth moved,'' said Dennis
Henigan, legal director for the Center to Prevent Handgun Violence
in Washington and a co-counsel to the California cities in their
suits.
</P>
<P>
   David Kairys, a professor at Temple University Law School who
helped devise the theory behind the California suits, said, ``I
think the smoking gun that we are looking for and that happened in
tobacco may come from the left coast, and these cities are likely
to bring it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for three of the major gun makers, Sturm, Ruger &AMP; Co.
Inc., Glock Inc. and OF Mossberg &AMP; Sons Inc, did not return
telephone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits accuse the manufacturers of providing weapons to
disreputable dealers, and to dealers in areas with lax controls,
knowing that these people were likely to sell guns to criminals.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Though suits like these can take years to get to trial, they
immediately put the gun industry under pressures that it has not
faced before, lawyers familiar with the cases said.
</P>
<P>
   Kairys noted that a key turning point in the battle against the
tobacco industry was when cigarette company executives told a
congressional hearing that cigarettes were not addictive. When they
were contradicted by revelations in company documents that nicotine
was addictive, their legal defenses were severely compromised.
</P>
<P>
   The gun companies, ``even after years of concern about violence,
have never been asked questions in front of a congressional
committee,'' or put through prolonged depositions, Kairys said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt in my mind,'' he said, that the gun makers
know the connection between the way they distribute guns and the
way guns get into the hands of criminals. The gun makers have tried
to insulate themselves from responsibility by selling guns only to
wholesalers who then sell to retail dealers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A consciousness that there is a problem here'' could show up
in internal company documents in the fact-finding process,
especially when the gun companies are pressed by experienced
lawyers from large firms with unlimited budgets, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The law firms representing Los Angeles and San Francisco are
Milberg Weiss Bershad Hynes &AMP; Lerach of New York and San Diego, and
Lieff, Cabraser, Heimmann &AMP; Bernstein of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Another line of inquiry is the tracing of guns used in crimes,
in which federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms agents go
to the manufacturer to ask to whom the gun was sold. This is bound
to tip off the gun makers about what is happening to their guns,
Kairys said.
</P>
<P>
   That gun industry officials are aware of this was indicated in a
deposition by Robert Haas, a former senior vice president of
marketing and sales for Smith &AMP; Wesson, in a lawsuit against 25 gun
makers in federal court in Brooklyn last winter. Haas' deposition
is included in the California suits.
</P>
<P>
   Haas said Smith &AMP; Wesson ``and the industry as a whole are fully
aware of the extent of the criminal misuse of handguns.''
</P>
<P>
   Another danger to the industry is the sheer number of lawsuits
filed against it in the past seven months. Since New Orleans became
the first city to sue in November, a total 16 cities and three
counties have filed suits. Newark, N.J., Boston and New York state
are preparing suits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
