<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, MAY 27
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-GM-DELPHI-NYT (moved on Monday, May 24)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, May 24,
about the spinoff of Delphi Automotive Systems by General Motors,
which owns 82.3 percent of it, misstated the distribution of
shares. G.M. shareholders will receive 80.1 percent of Delphi; 2.2
percent will go to a nonpension retirement plan. The remaining 17.7
percent of Delphi is already publicly held.
</P>
<P>
   BC-PARADISE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT (moved on Tuesday, May 25)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, May 25,
about ``Inventing Paradise: The Greek Journey, 1937-1947,'' by
Edmund Keeley, misstated the involvement of the writers Lawrence
Durrell and Henry Miller with the Elgin marbles. The passage should
have read, ``Durrell and Miller were the first generation of those
who, literarily at least, restored the marbles'' (not ``literally
at least'').
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-MUSEUM-GUIDES-NYT (moved on Wednesday, May 5)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, May 5,
about hand-held electronic guides misidentified the developer of a
device used in a Kuala Lumpur museum. The device was developed by
employees of DMCD Inc. and Anway &AMP; Company. They included Paul
Trapido, who was not an independent exhibition designer at the time
and was not the sole developer.
</P>
</TEXT>
