<HEADER>
A2555 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-HIGHWAY-INQUIRY-BO     05-26 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-HIGHWAY-INQUIRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON ROAD PROJECT UNDER FIRE FOR INVESTING US AID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ &UR;  &LR; A massive Central Artery project is under fire from
the US Department of Transportation for what it calls the improper
diversion of scarce federal highway money to a $260 million trust
fund that helps distort the actual cost of the work.
</P>
<P>
   In a report to the Federal Highway Administration to be released
Thursday, the transportation department's inspector general asks
the agency to take back at least $150 million from the project,
also known as the Big Dig, because the funds should not have been
allocated to the account. The funds were invested in corporate
bonds, such as those issued by Walt Disney Co., Wal-Mart, and
General Electric, and not spent on highway projects as intended,
the audit says.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick J. Moynihan, the Central Artery project director, said
Wednesday that the state would strongly resist giving back the
money, saying the funds support an innovative self-insurance
program to cover potential catastrophic incidents and will save the
project $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we think is cutting edge and will be
followed by similar major public works programs in the future,''
Moynihan said.
</P>
<P>
   The highway administration, which approved use of the money for
the insurance plan, strongly disagreed with the report, saying the
inspector general's office had misunderstood the use of the trust
fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our primary concern is that this largest highway project in
the United States should not risk a loss of the billions of dollars
that have been invested and will be invested,'' Anthony Kane, the
FHA's executive director, told the auditors.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts congressional delegation seized news of the
report to resume its attack on Governor Paul Cellucci's handling of
federal highway funds, saying the administration is holding back
money for much-needed local projects in order to pay for the Big
Dig.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fight hard for this money, but we don't fight hard so it
can be invested in a trust fund to help Mickey Mouse or Donald
Duck,'' said US Representative James P. McGovern, a Worcester
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The delegation, all Democrats, has sharply criticized Cellucci,
a Republican, for blaming it for the shortage of federal funds.
Last year, the GOP-controlled Congress sharply cut back the state's
share of highway money.
</P>
<P>
   Project officials say the trust fund _ into which $150 million
in federal money has been placed _ is part of an insurance program
that allows them to negotiate a so-called pooled umbrella system.
Besides the lower rates, this approach can also control the payout
on the claims, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that we are saving $1 billion is never mentioned in
this report,'' said Andrew Paven, a Big Dig spokesman. ``We think
those savings are good public policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the auditors said the state uses the trust fund to
underplay the actual cost of the project. Project officials contend
that the potential rebates of unused portions of the fund,
estimated at $817 million, will be available to Massachusetts in
2017.
</P>
<P>
   According to the audit, those funds are calculated into the
state's predictions that the project will cost $10.8 billion,
rather than almost $12 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Claiming excess funds are needed to cover future liabilities
while at the same time citing these funds as a credit against
ultimate project costs is inherently inconsistent,'' the report
said. ``Project management cannot have it both ways.''
</P>
<P>
   But Paven disputed the charge. ``That shows a lack of
understanding of the finance plan,'' he said. ``That plan
identifies every dollar needed to complete this project.''
</P>
<P>
   James Kerasiotes, chairman of the Massachusetts Turnpike
Authority, which oversees the project, said he found the audit
``amusing'' but ``wasteful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've reduced this to the ridiculous in terms of criticizing
this project,'' Kerasiotes said. ``People have been trying to find
something wrong with the Big Dig since Day One. Now we are down to
criticizing innovative management.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
