A2556 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REPUBS-CAMPAIGN-1STLD     05-26 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-CAMPAIGN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP CONGRESSMAN ACCUSES DELAY OF WORKING AGAINST HIM 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Fixes lead to say that DeLay is accused of offering to donate
to a challenge, not finance it; fixes 2nd graph to change numbers
of Republicans signing petition and total number of signatures;
fixes 4th graph to change spending limits to contribution limits;
subs 7th graph to clarify why votes would be necessary soon after
Memorial Day; subs 10th graph to add name of sixth Republican
signator.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(rm) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chief House Republican proponent of overhauling
the nation's campaign finance laws defied his party Wednesday by
signing a Democratic petition designed to force the issue to the
House floor. He accused Tom DeLay, the powerful House Majority
Whip, of offering to donate money to a primary challenge against
him and cast the issue as a struggle with DeLay over the soul of
the party.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Shays of Connecticut was one of six Republicans
who broke with the Republican leadership Wednesday to sign the
petition. That brought the number of signatures to 202, still 16
short of the 218 majority needed to force action.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the nearly three dozen Republicans who support the
bipartisan bill that Shays sponsors with Rep. Martin Meehan,
D-Mass., remained deeply reluctant to cross their House leaders,
who have cast a decision to work with the Democrats on the campaign
issue as a vote of no confidence in the new speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis Hastert is their speaker,'' DeLay, R-Texas, said
Tuesday as he put his weight behind a separate bill to eliminate
public financing of campaigns and eliminate all contribution
limits. ``He's been working with them. He's been very helpful to
them and, frankly, I think they ought to show him the respect to
work through the regular order.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Scanlon, a spokesman for DeLay, denied Shays' charge
that the whip had offered a contribution if someone ran against
him. ``We have a long standing policy to support incumbents and we
won't break that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although majorities in both the House and Senate have voted for
the legislation to ban the unlimited, unregulated donations to
political parties at the heart of the 1996 campaign finance
scandals, leading Republicans have managed to bottle up the measure
since their party took control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert has scheduled the issue for September, which its
proponents say will guarantee that it once again dies in a Senate
filibuster since that will be too close to session's end. Unless
another, larger group of Republicans signs the Democrats' petition
to bring the number to 218, the petition drive will fail. And,
those signatures would have to be gathered immediately after the
Memorial Day recess, because there is a lengthy and complicated
process for bringing an issue to the floor for a vote, and there
might not be time to push the bill to the floor before the summer
recess.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 195 Democrats and one independent have also signed the
petition. Meehan said he thought two more Democrats might sign. He
predicted the measure would pass decisively whenever it gets to the
floor. But opponents of the bill expressed confidence that the
petition would not succeed, in part because many Republicans had
voted against the Shays-Meehan measure last year and still won
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sky didn't fall,'' said Rep. John Doolittle, R-Calif., who
opposes the bill as an infringement on free speech. ``They all came
back and discovered they could be a little more bold on this
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Shays, the Republicans who broke with their leaders were
Michael Forbes of New York, Michael Castle of Delaware, Greg Ganske
of Iowa, Constance Morella of Maryland and Nancy Johnson of
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The ferment over campaign finance legislation came amid other
signs that the unity House Republicans have maintained all year is
starting to fray. Conservatives on Wednesday slowed down the first
spending bill of the year for agriculture by offering amendment
after amendment in a floor protest.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert has staked his reputation on being able to pass the
year's 13 spending bills on time.
</P>
<P>
   Shays had little to say Wednesday about Hastert. But time and
again, echoing charges usually made by Democrats, he focused on
DeLay, the passionate conservative who was the hard-charging leader
driving impeachment of President Clinton through the House.
</P>
<P>
   At a breakfast with reporters, he called DeLay the ``most
powerful person in Congress.'' He said that DeLay, among other
Republicans, was using a leadership political action committee _ a
vehicle that allows individual power brokers in Congress to curry
favor with candidates _ to raise ``unlimited sums from
corporations.''
</P>
<P>
   He said ``leadership controls the money and they like to control
the money because they control the members.''
</P>
<P>
   Shays also said that DeLay had offered in meetings with
activists to contribute to any primary challenger to Shays, who
angered some Connecticut Republicans by voting against Clinton's
impeachment. ``This Republican Party has to decide _ particularly
in Connecticut _ whether it wants to be the party of Tom DeLay or
the party that I represent,'' Shays said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that Scott Hatch, a former high ranking DeLay aide
who now is executive director of the House Republicans' re-election
effort, had ``actively advocated that someone run against me''
before he had assumed his new position at the National Republican
Congressional Committee. He said Hatch has since said that he would
remain neutral because of his new position. But in another warning,
Shays said a staff member of the election committee had called to
tell him not to sign the petition.
</P>
<P>
   It would be highly unusual for Republicans to endanger a seat by
pushing for a primary against an incumbent. Michael Scanlon, a
spokesman for Delay, said the whip ``had never done anything like
that.'' He said DeLay would be glad to talk personally to Shays to
tell him that.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Thomas Davis of Virginia, the new chairman of the National
Republican Congressional Committee, said that ``this committee
traditionally supports incumbents and will support Shays.'' He said
that when he took over the committee he had told Hatch to iron out
differences with Shays, saying, ``'there's some perception you guys
need to sit down. My impression is everything is fine with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Shays was less pointed about DeLay later in the day when he
stood with three of his four co-signers to announce that they would
join the Democrats. This time, he, like the rest of the group, put
the emphasis on reducing the influence of money on politics.
</P>
<P>
   Ganske said he had ``seen the power of soft money on influencing
political decisions.'' A strong proponent of regulating health
maintenance organizations, Ganske blamed contributions from the
insurance industry for the failure of Congress to enact legislation
to strengthen the rights of patients.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 2147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0405 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2557 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      05-26 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSING SURGE CONTINUES IN SPITE OF EXPECTATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Against all expectations, the housing market is continuing to
boom. Across the United States, home construction and sales of
existing homes from January through April are running well ahead of
the same period in 1998, itself a strong year. Home prices are
rising, too, and home ownership has reached its highest level in
history: 66.7 percent of U.S. households.
</P>
<P>
   All this flies in the face of forecasts that housing would begin
a long decline in the mid- to late '90s, once the baby boomers were
past their big home-buying years. The succeeding generation,
experts predicted, would buy or build far fewer homes, and prices
would fall. But the opposite has happened.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS REBOUND AFTER FOUR-DAY SLIDE
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rebounded from a four-day slump as the banking and
Internet shares that faltered earlier this week roared back. The
Dow Jones industrial average rose 171.07 points, or 1.62 percent,
to 10,702.16, led by a surge in IBM. Shares of the computer giant
soared $15.0625, to $236.25, before a 2-for-1 split took effect
after the market closed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
gained 20.36 points, or 1.59 percent, to 1,304.76, and the
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 46.28 points, or 1.94
percent, to 2,427.18.
</P>
<P>
   Directors of the Nasdaq stock market forwarded a recommendation
to its parent for an evening trading session that could begin as
early as September, setting the stage for possible adoption on
Thursday of the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC GIANTS IN ONLINE SCRAMBLE
</P>
<P>
   Two music-industry giants, Universal Music and BMG
Entertainment, said they would team up with AT&AMP;T and Matshushita to
create technology to sell, store and distribute music over the
Internet. Because both companies had already announced similar
initiatives with other companies, the deal underscored the
desperation of the major record labels to establish a foothold in
electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   25 CHARGED IN INSIDER-TRADING CASE
</P>
<P>
   A former IBM secretary who knew of the company's plans to buy
Lotus tipped off her husband, leading 25 people to pocket more than
$1.3 million from insider trading, the Securities and Exchange
Commission charged.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN SCRUTINIZES U.S. COMPANIES
</P>
<P>
   For years, U.S. officials have called on regulators to be
tougher on the financial-services industry in Japan, but they
hardly expected that the result would be raids on U.S. companies.
But that is what has happened, with Japanese officials stepping up
the intensity of their inspections to show that they are cracking
down on financial misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   TV CHIEF TURNS OVER WIRELESS UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Salinas Pliego, the chairman of Mexico's second-largest
TV network, said that he was turning over his wireless telephone
business, Unefon, to a joint venture formed by his network and two
members of the Saba investor family. He said the new company would
also deliver television programming to working-class Mexicans,
allowing them to cruise the Internet and shop from home.
</P>
<P>
   PANASONIC TO LEND HDTV GEAR
</P>
<P>
   Panasonic has agreed to lend the ABC television network millions
of dollars' worth of new equipment so that ABC can broadcast its
Monday night football games and the Super Bowl in high definition
starting this fall.
</P>
<P>
   DISPUTE OVER MAGAZINES IS SETTLED
</P>
<P>
   Canada and the United States averted a trade war with an
agreement that resolves a protracted dispute over Canadian barriers
to American magazines.
</P>
<P>
   NAYA TOLD TO FIND NEW DISTRIBUTOR
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, which owns 39 percent of the largest bottler of Naya,
a Canadian bottled-water company, has decided to introduce its own
bottled-water brand, and Naya executives were told that they would
have to start looking for a new distributor.
</P>
<P>
   DURABLE GOODS ORDERS ROSE IN APRIL
</P>
<P>
   Factory orders for durable goods other than aircraft and cars
rose in April for the second straight month, suggesting that
manufacturing is on the mend, new figures showed.
</P>
</TEXT>
