<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Add-ons threaten juvenile justice bill
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two days after the deadly shootings at Columbine
High, the House Judiciary subcommittee on crime adopted a
far-reaching juvenile justice bill that would pump more than $1.5
billion into the nation's understaffed and overwhelmed youth
justice system.
</P>
<P>
   Three years in the making, the legislation blended a measure of
prevention with a strong dose of punishment, attracting support
from every member of the committee _ no small feat in one of the
House's most ideologically polarized committees.
</P>
<P>
   But the recent decision by House Republican leaders to
incorporate new gun control measures and a laundry list of tough
new punishments into the bill is now threatening to unravel the
compromise that produced it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This clearly, in my opinion, is an effort to kill the
legislation and sabotage the will of the public,'' said Rep.
William Delahunt (D-Mass.), one of the original sponsors of the
so-called Consequences for Juvenile Offenders Act of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Delahunt and other Democrats support new gun control measures.
But they object to many of the more stringent provisions that
Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde (R-Ill.) now plans to add to the
juvenile crime bill, such as mandatory minimum sentences and
greater freedom for prosecutors to try juveniles as adults.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde acknowledged Wednesday that the revised juvenile crime bill
will ``raise the hackles of the Democrats.'' But he denied that he
was seeking to kill the bill and any accompanying gun control
provisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want that,'' Hyde said. ``The charge that we are a
do-nothing Congress is something we want to offset by having solid
legislative achievements. This is an area that cries out for proper
legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the House juvenile crime bill is fast becoming a
vehicle for a sweeping and potentially controversial proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Under a draft outline of the new bill obtained by the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, House Republicans propose authorizing the
Federal Trade Commission and the Department of Justice to
investigate whether Hollywood is ``marketing violent shows and
games to children.''
</P>
<P>
   Also under the heading of ``changing the culture of violence,''
the legislation would require federal agencies to consider a
movie's violent content before authorizing any filming on
government property.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Scott (D-Va.), the ranking Democrat on the crime
committee, said he is concerned that the new juvenile crime bill
will be so loaded down with controversial provisions that it won't
win support from either party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with juvenile crime legislation is that when it is
not done in a thoughtful manner we end up slinging sound bites at
each other,'' Scott said. ``If you have guns on one end and a bunch
of constitutionally dubious provisions on the other ... you may end
up with a product that isn't worth supporting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
