<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR CRIMES TRIBUNAL EXPECTED TO INDICT MILOSEVIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN AND KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST _ Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic will be
indicted Thursday by the United Nations War Crimes Tribunal in The
Hague, sources said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the imminent indictment was met with elation by human
rights workers and Milosevic foes who have long insisted that the
man dubbed ``the butcher of the Balkans'' by his detractors has
gotten away with murder in Kosovo, Bosnia, and Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   However, the move will greatly complicate already-feeble
negotiations to end the two-month-long war in which hundreds of
thousands of Albanians have been forced from Kosovo and an unknown
number Serbs and Albanians have been killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who can meet with him if he's an indicted war criminal?''
asked Colin Soloway, an analyst with the International Crisis Group
in Sarajevo. ``The fear the Americans have is that the Serbs will
not deal'' after Milosevic is indicted, Soloway said. ``It could
mean Milosevic is just going to put his back up to the wall and
fight until the end.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came as some members of Congress expressed
serious concern about the way Washington has handled Milosevic to
date, and as several issued a letter to President Clinton urging
much tougher action against the Yugoslav leader, who has been
suspected of war crimes for nearly half a decade and who was last
year found guilty of ``crimes against humanity'' in an overwhelming
congressional vote.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear Wednesday whether the war crimes accusation was
based on evidence from the 1992-95 wars in Bosnia and Croatia, or
from the ongoing conflict in Kosovo, Serbia's southern province.
</P>
<P>
   But human rights workers said an indictment based on deportment
and executions in Kosovo was more likely, since it is easier to
establish a chain of command from Serbian police and paramilitary
to Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   During the Bosnian and Croatian wars, Milosevic was president of
Serbia only, and it is more difficult to connect him directly to
atrocities committed in other countries by forces not under his
direct command.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
   --NATO announced it had conducted the busiest day of air attacks
on Serbia since the strikes began March 24. NATO pilots flew 284
attack sorties, most of them directed at Kosovo and southern
Serbia. Among the targets was Milosevic's private villa just west
of Belgrade. Yugoslav officials said the president was not there.
It was the fourth time the villa was hit.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian-run Media Center in Pristina, the Kosovo capital,
said two children were killed and one seriously hurt during NATO's
bombing of Radoste, a village about 40 miles southwest of Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   --NATO military commanders won political approval Wednesday to
attack some of Yugoslavia's most sensitive sites, including
leadership residences, police and ministerial headquarters and the
country's basic infrastructure networks in a bid to cut
communications between Belgrade and armed forces in Kosovo, senior
NATO sources said.
</P>
<P>
   --A trial began in Belgrade of three workers for the aid group
CARE, including two Australians and one Yugoslav national. The
three were arrested for allegedly spying and have been in custody
since March 31. The Serbs refused to allow international observers
or journalists into the courtroom, fueling fears that the trial
will not be fair.
</P>
<P>
   _ Russian Foreign Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin met with US
Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott and Finnish President
Martii Ahtisaari in Moscow. The three are trying to work out a plan
for ending the crisis, including the makeup of a peace-keeping
force in Kosovo. Chernomyrdin is scheduled to go to Belgrade for
talks Thursday. However, one diplomat in Brussels said Milosevic's
indictment makes Chernomyrdin's trip highly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   --Russia called for an immediate end to the airstrikes, and NATO
member Greece called for a pause in the air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   --Sergio Vieira de Mello, the UN's deputy for humanitarian
affairs, told reporters in Belgrade that while the ethnic cleansing
in Kosovo is ``deeply disturbing,'' Serbs also have suffered from
``a combination of anxiety, humiliation, lack of understanding, and
immense stress'' because they are being bombed by ``an invisible
enemy that can strike at any time.'' The 500,000 Serbs who fled
Croatia and Bosnia also ``deserve equal attention and have equal
rights, particularly the right to return,'' said de Mello, who is
preparing a report on his recent tour of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   --The newly appointed Yugoslav minister responsible for
refugees, Bratislava Morina, said the refugees living in Albania
and Macedonia should be allowed to return to Kosovo. The details,
she acknowledged to Serb TV, are a long way off.
</P>
<P>
   The planned indictment of Milosevic would be the first time a
sitting head of state has been accused of war crimes by the
tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   An eventual conviction could force Milosevic out of power,
something Balkan observers say is critical to long-term stability
in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic lost the war in Bosnia, but kept his political power
when he signed the peace agreement in Dayton, Ohio, in 1995. If
Milosevic stays in control after the Kosovo conflict is over, his
enemies fear, he will simply provoke another fight in another part
of the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty of this'' indictment ``is that it will foreclose a
diplomatic low-road way out,'' said Kurt Bassuener of the Balkan
Action Council in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment alone probably would not topple Milosevic. Many
indicted war criminals from the Bosnian and Croatian wars _
including two of the most notorious accused criminals, Bosnian
Serbs Radovan Karadzic and Ratko Mladic _ are still at large.
</P>
<P>
   Hague officials, as is their custom, would not discuss the
reported indictment. But sources close to The Hague say tribunal
officials have been readying the evidence _ and announcement _ for
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Risley, a spokesman for War Crimes Tribunal chief Louise
Arbour, said investigators had ``evidence of war crimes on a
massive scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright and Joe Lockhart,
the White House spokesman, declined to comment on the reported
indictment.
</P>
<P>
   But State Department spokesman James Rubin said, ``Our line (to
the tribunal) is you should follow the evidence wherever it leads
and we will back you.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Benjamin L. Cardin, the Maryland Democrat who
authored the letter sent to Clinton Wednesday, said he was worried
that US intelligence and military agencies have been willing only
to send vague synopses of war crimes material to The Hague, instead
of turning over hard data that could be used against Milosevic in a
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's letter was signed by members of both parties,
including Massachusetts Representatives Edward J. Markey, John W.
Olver, and James P. McGovern, all Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   An indictment of Milosevic would box in both him and the West,
analysts say, since both would lose some diplomatic negotiating
room. Neither side could cut a deal under which Milosevic is
protected from prosecution if he agrees to NATO's demands.
</P>
<P>
   Still, isolating Milosevic as an accused war criminal could help
the United States with its less-committed allies in the war effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it a bit easier, in some ways,'' Hill said. ``We
(Americans) don't have to convince the Europeans that he isn't
someone you can trust anymore. In the long term, it's going to be
useful.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Anne Kornblut of the Globe staff contributed to this report from
Washington. Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
