<SLUG> BC-COMPUTING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Translation Programs Make It Easy to Speak in Tongues  &HT;       
 By David Einstein  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  Is there a way I can type an e-mail message to my cousin
in Italy and have it immediately translated into Italian? I am
aware of translation services for a fee, but is there a free
option?
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; Answer &LR; : You know the old saying, there's no such thing as a
free translation. Translation services can cost up to 25 cents per
word. If you plan to do a lot of corresponding with your cousin,
you might consider translation software, which automatically can
change your English prose into Italian (or German, French, Spanish,
etc.). Three such programs are Power Translator Pro from Lernout &AMP;
Hauspie ($130), Universal Translator from Language Force ($40) and
Easy Translator from Transparent Language ($42). Of those, the only
one I've used is Power Translator Pro, which seems to work pretty
well though it's not great with grammar and syntax. My hunch is
that if you use one of these programs, you'll sound like a tourist
but your cousin will get the picture. By the way, to use this kind
of software, you have to create your message in a word processor
such as Microsoft Word, then copy and paste it into an e-mail
window.
</P>
<P>
   Q: my sister-in-law's Compaq Presario has a ``sleep'' button
right on the keyboard, which instantly switches the computer into a
low-energy idle mode. She leaves the computer on 24 hours a day and
uses only the snooze button to toggle her system on and off. She
claims that this is better for the computer than shutting it down
and rebooting every day. Do you agree? Also, my computer doesn't
have a sleep button, but I can program the system to automatically
switch the monitor into low-energy standby. Is this essentially the
same action performed by the Compaq's sleep button?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sleep mode (also called ``standby'' or ``suspend'') is really
designed for someone who works at the computer periodically
throughout the day but also spends time doing other things. When
you put the computer to sleep, the hard drive and monitor both
power down, and the system uses about one-third as much energy.
When you wake the computer up, the system instantly returns to
whatever you were doing before it went to sleep. So you avoid the
regular reboot sequence.
</P>
<P>
   Your sister-in-law is right _ using sleep mode all the time is
easier on the system than shutting it down and restarting it every
time you want to use the computer. But if saving energy is a
priority, then it's better to simply turn the computer off at the
end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   As for your computer, setting the monitor to go into standby is
really just half the battle. Your hard drive is still going to
spin, which means that it'll eat up energy and make that humming
noise of which we're all so fond. You might check the energy-saving
features of your PC just to see if you can power down the hard
drive when the system is idle. Many newer computers let you do
that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I find that when surfing the Web, I lose humongous amounts of
time while the system loads graphics and pretty color photos. All I
want is text. I'm told there is a way to disable graphics in
Netscape Navigator. How?
</P>
<P>
   A: Here's how, using Navigator 4.5: Choose Preferences from the
Edit menu. On the left side of the Preferences dialog box, click
Advanced. Then, uncheck the box labeled Automatically load images.
Web documents henceforth will be displayed sans graphics and
photos.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a 56K modem, but the connection with my ISP is only
50,660 Kbps. How can I get the maximum speed?
</P>
<P>
   A:  &LR; Only 50,660?  &LR; I'd say that's pretty good. My connection at
home tops out at about 46 Kbps. You're never going to see true 56K
speeds because federal regulations limit downloads to 53 Kbps.
Other factors also can conspire to slow you down. They include your
Internet service provider's system, your modem and the quality of
your telephone line. If you consistently can hit the 50s, you
should consider yourself lucky.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TIP OF THE WEEK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; You're in the market for a free e-mail account, but you're not
sure which one is best for you. Check out the Free Email Address
Directory at &LR;  www.emailaddresses.com. &LR;  This Web site has
information on more than 500 free e-mail services, as well as a
guide to choosing a service. And of course, it's free.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Einstein is West Coast bureau chief of Forbes Digital Tool.
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to computers(AT
SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
