<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2572 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-SFCHRON &LR;      05-26 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: CMP Media Shares the Wealth With Workers  &HT;       
 By Dan Fost  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
It seems to be the rule of the takeover: Executives fatten their
wallets in a merger while employees feel the layoff ax.
<P>
   How refreshing, then, to see CMP Media _ the venerable high-tech
publisher that was just bought by United News &AMP; Media _ share the
wealth with the journalists and other workers who helped create the
company's value.
</P>
<P>
   CMP is giving $50 million away to its 1,800 employees (including
about 300 in the Bay Area) during the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're grateful for all of the effort that a lot of people put
into building the company, and we wanted them to share in how well
we've all done,'' said Michael Leeds, the outgoing chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Leeds' parents founded the company, launching their first
magazine, Electronic Buyers News, 28 years ago on Long Island, N.Y.
It grew to 12 print and two online publications, all tech fare like
Information Week, Windows Magazine and Electronic Engineering
Times, and last year, it earned $10 million on sales of $478
million.
</P>
<P>
   The family run concern hit the public marketplace in 1997 and
earlier this year announced that it was up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   While that's often cause for concern, Leeds tried to allay
employees' fears by promising a payoff.
</P>
<P>
   Then he delivered _ double.
</P>
<P>
   Leeds initially expected to offer every employee $2,000 for each
year they worked at CMP, plus 20 percent of their salary.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before United News &AMP; Media, the London parent of
San Francisco's Miller Freeman, announced last month that it won
the bidding war for CMP with an offer of $920 million cash. You
read that right: almost $1 billion &LR;  cash &LR; , not the ``funny money''
stock so typical of today's transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Leeds then upped the bonus to $4,000 for every year with the
company, still including the original 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The average payout per employee: $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Ten old salts who've been with the company 20 years or more will
get more than $100,000 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Hayes, 35, a senior editor at Information Week in San
Francisco, has been with CMP for five years, so her payout will be
well over $20,000. (If she told us the exact amount, we'd be able
to figure out her salary, so mum's the word on that.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice chunk of change,'' she said. ``I plan to invest
it. Hopefully, one day I can afford an overpriced home in San
Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Aragon, 35, of Fremont, who has worked for the past year
and a half in the San Mateo office of CMP's VAR Business magazine
(VAR stands for value-added reseller, which doesn't really explain
anything but is nice to know), has already spent $500. He's finally
able to deliver on his promise of a jungle gym for his 3-year-old
son, Sam.
</P>
<P>
   He's not done spending. ``My wife said, `Now you can buy me that
anniversary ring you promised me for our 10th anniversary,'''
coming up in August 2000, he said. You might call that Aragon's Y2K
problem.
</P>
<P>
   In the overheated market for technology journalists, in which
the demand for writers exceeds supply and once-humble scribes now
are raking in stock options worth millions, CMP workers suddenly
have placed their career jumps on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Although no one would talk about it for the record, some
reporters confirmed that they're mulling moves _ after the check
arrives in mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some employees didn't time things exactly right.
Barry Zusman is leaving his job in corporate communications  &LR; Friday
 &LR; before the payoff comes. ``How's that for timing?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THE CABLE GUYS: &LR;  The deal that CNN and International Data Group
announced this week in San Francisco _ to launch a weekly consumer
technology show on CNN _ is the second Web partnership for Ted
Turner's brainchild.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, CNN announced that it would produce a show
with WebMD, the Atlanta online health company that just merged with
Healtheon.
</P>
<P>
   In such media partnerships, CNN maintained that it does not
surrender any editorial control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought about that a great deal,'' said Tom Johnson, the
chief executive of the all-news channel. ``CNN will have
responsibility for anything that goes out on any CNN-branded
services.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, IDG piped up that it, too, will maintain control over
the content that appears on its Web sites, even when that content
is created at CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Any doubts about the partners' common commitment, however, could
be allayed by realizing that IDG President and CEO Kelly Conlin
began his career as CNN's New York assignment editor in the
network's early days.
</P>
<P>
   Even though CNN is a unit of a pretty fair magazine publisher,
Time Warner, the company chose to go with IDG, which has vastly
more experience in technology publishing.
</P>
<P>
   The companies are following a trail blazed in San Francisco by
Cnet, which produces programming for USA Networks and the Sci-Fi
Channel; New Media News, a technology show that airs on cable
locally on KRON (Channel 4) and BayTV and nationally on Knowledge
TV; and ZDTV, the Ziff-Davis 24-hour cable channel. Earlier this
month, Cnet said it would produce a show to air Sunday afternoons
on NBC's cable network CNBC starting in October.
</P>
<P>
   If Cnet execs were miffed about CNN entering the fray, they
didn't let on. ``It's flattering that someone else is copying our
format,'' said Cnet Vice President Dan Sexton. ``It's flattering,
and it also validates what we do. Hey, it's great.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THE STANDARD WAY: &LR;  After the press conference at the San Francisco
Park Hyatt, Conlin spoke about IDG's latest tech publication, The
Industry Standard. It's a sharp magazine, not as geeky as some of
the company's offerings, but it's still far from profitable after
only one year in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Conlin said the magazine is above budget, ahead of projections
with a 100-page issue and is showing strong growth on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   But what's really encouraging, he said, is an ``Internet
Summit'' conference planned for this summer in Laguna Niguel in
Orange County. Admission is a pricey $3,900 a person, and they've
got 550 people signed up to attend, with more than 100 on the
waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``The way to make money on the Internet,'' Conlin said with a
grin, ``is to do conferences on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Media Bytes appears every Thursday in The San Francisco Chronicle.
Send buzz, dirt, tips and comments to fostd(AT SIGN)sfgate.com,
call (415) 777-6004 or fax (415) 543-2482. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
