<SLUG> BC-APPLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Apple Adds Gap's CEO To Its Board  &HT;       
 By Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Apple Computer named Millard ``Mickey'' Drexler, president and
chief executive of Gap Inc., to its board of directors yesterday.
<P>
   In appointing the head of one of the world's leading specialty
retailers, the computer-maker appears determined to reestablish
itself as a major brand name for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Drexler's) expertise in marketing and retail will be a
tremendous resource as Apple continues to grow in the consumer
market,'' Steve Jobs, Apple's interim chief executive, said in a
statement. ``He will add a completely new dimension to Apple's
board.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cupertino company is in the midst of cranking up sales to
first-time computer users. Last year, it introduced the curvy,
space-age iMac computer for novice users, and last month, it inked
a distribution deal with Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. to carry iMacs. The
company also has hired former Volkswagen executive Steve Wilhite to
spearhead marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Drexler, 54, is the seventh member of Apple's board, which has
been overhauled since mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
   The New York native joined Gap in 1983 from apparel retailer Ann
Taylor. He was promoted to president in 1987 and CEO in 1995. The
San Francisco chain has 2,500 stores in the United States, the
United Kingdom, Canada, France, Germany and Japan under the Gap,
GapKids, babyGap, Banana Republic and Old Navy brand names.
</P>
<P>
   The computer-maker's current board includes Jobs, who also is
chairman of Pixar Animation Studios; Oracle CEO Larry Ellison;
Intuit Chairman Bill Campbell, a former Apple marketing executive;
Ed Woolard, chairman of E.I. DuPont de Nemours; Jerry York, former
chief financial officer of IBM and Chrysler, now DaimlerChrysler
AG; and Gareth C.C. Chang, executive chairman of Star TV, the Asian
satellite TV unit of News Corp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
