r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROVIDIAN-SFCHRON &LR;      05-26 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROVIDIAN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Providian Tries to Assuage Customers  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
As Providian Financial stock slid an additional 13 percent
yesterday on rumors that it's about to be charged with fraud, the
San Francisco credit card issuer said it is taking steps to restore
consumer confidence.
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Providian said it will cancel late fees if customers feel they
were wrongly charged, and discontinue services such as credit
protection if customers believe they were misled into signing up.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which targets customers with flawed credit records,
is under investigation by the San Francisco district attorney's
office for a range of practices involving credit card sales and
debt collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always been committed to customer satisfaction;
however, we are human,'' said Providian Chairman and chief
executive Shailesh Mehta.
</P>
<P>
   In a press release, Providian said it is taking ``special
actions to reinforce'' its ``100 percent satisfaction guarantee''
in response to concerns ``expressed in the media and by others.''
</P>
<P>
   Providian stock fell $12.63 to $83.38 yesterday, and volume was
8.3 million shares, about eight times average for the past six
months.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said rumors were circulating that the California
attorney general or San Francisco district attorney soon will
indict Providian for defrauding consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The analysts said the rumors almost certainly were false. But
the buzz still worried investors spooked by reports last week that
the San Francisco district attorney's office is investigating
Providian's sales and debt-collection practices.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock has plunged 33 percent since May 18, when
the D.A.'s office confirmed its investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are really panicking about the news,'' said Bear
Stearns analyst David Hochstim.
</P>
<P>
   Providian said it didn't know anything about yesterday's rumors.
``We have no new information,'' said spokeswoman Laurie Cole. The
company has said it will cooperate with any investigation.
</P>
<P>
   David Pfeifer, chief of special investigations in the San
Francisco district &UR;  &LR; attorney's office, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the San Francisco district attorney's office
said last week that prosecutors are ``miles away'' from deciding
whether to take criminal or civil action against the company.
</P>
<P>
   Market watchers said the rumors about Providian appeared to be
based on comments by Todd Pitsinger, an analyst for Friedman,
Billings, Ramsey, a brokerage firm near Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Pitsinger said he has told clients he considers it ``more likely
than less likely'' that the San Francisco district attorney's
office will take action against Providian.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've not had any indication that anything from the D.A.'s
office is imminent, nor have we spoken with anybody in the D.A.'s
office,'' Pitsinger said.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney's office hasn't said what issues it is
probing. But consumer agencies say they've been inundated with
complaints about Providian.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the those complaints allege that consumers were misled
into buying products such as credit protection or that the company
failed to post payments when they were received, triggering
late-payment fees. Providian says it obeys all laws and
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   In its announcement yesterday, Providian said it will cancel any
add-on products, such as credit protection, and refund the fees for
up to a year if customers are unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to reversing late fees on customer request, the
company said it will give customers two extra days beyond their due
date to make payments without incurring a late fee. It also has
hired the accounting firm Ernst &AMP; Young to review its
payment-crediting processes.
</P>
<P>
   Providian also said it is checking direct-mail and telephone
solicitations to ensure that customers aren't misled. And it said
it will set up a special 800 customer service number by the end of
the week for customers unsatisfied by normal procedures.
</P>
<P>
   The company said there will be costs associated with the new
measures but that it doesn't expect them to hurt profits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
