<SLUG> BC-CALL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Editors: Note `TILDE SIGN' should be replaced by actual mark
in  web address)   Call Waiting Comes to the Internet 
 &HT;       
 By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
It's enough to drive a person crazy.
<P>
   You want to surf the Web but are expecting a phone call. Unless
you've got a second phone line, you have no choice but to wait by
the phone or risk missing the call if you go online.
</P>
<P>
   Until now.
</P>
<P>
   A technology called Internet call waiting allows consumers to
stay online and still know when they've got an incoming call.
</P>
<P>
   Several large phone companies are testing the technology and
plan to roll it out to customers over the next year. Pacific Bell
said it will decide within the next couple of months how to deploy
it. And some smaller businesses are already selling devices for
well under $100 that let customers check their e-mail and still get
that call from Mom.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay Area, consumers will soon be able to get Internet
call waiting from a few Internet service providers. Two ISPs are
expected to announce the service within the next month.
</P>
<P>
   The service usually costs less than the price of a second phone
line _ between $4.95 and $9.95 a month, plus an activation fee. In
the Bay Area, a second phone line is $11.25 per month through
Pacific Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Like traditional call waiting, Internet call waiting works by
informing a person who is online that there is someone on the
phone.
</P>
<P>
   The service alerts a user to an incoming call with a box that
pops up on the computer screen. If a customer has Caller ID, the
box can also display the name and number of the person calling.
</P>
<P>
   A computer user then has three choices:
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  _Pick up the telephone and take the call, but drop the
Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   _Click on the box that appears on-screen and take the call
online using a technology called Internet telephony. The software
turns the computer into a speakerphone of sorts, allowing the user
to talk through the PC's microphone and hear through its speakers.
This does not drop the Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   _Ignore the call and send it to voice mail.
</P>
<P>
   Customers may need to download software from the Internet to use
Internet call &LR;   &LR; waiting, but they don't need to install any
hardware on their computer. Those who want to talk online using
Internet telephony must have a multimedia computer for the service
to work.
</P>
<P>
   Another alternative is to get an Internet call waiting device
that connects to your phone line between your modem and telephone
wall jack. Two such devices are available now: HotCall from Command
Communications of Aurora, Colo., and WEBS Call Waiting Detector
from Fireball 7, a San Anselmo company.
</P>
<P>
   HotCall, which costs about $70 and is available at CompUSA,
connects to a PC and can sense when the user has an incoming call.
It beeps and flashes to alert the computer user, who can take the
call and end the Internet connection. The user can also send the
call to voice mail or pick up the phone and keep the Internet
connection if they talk for less than 10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   There is no software and the device works with both PCs and
Macs. A slightly more expensive model that displays the caller's
name and number is also available to customers who have Caller ID.
</P>
<P>
   The WEBS call waiting detector, which works in much the same
way, is about $60 and can be ordered at  &LR; mbay.net/(TILDE &LR; 
 &LR; SIGN)rsb/ &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Neither device requires a monthly fee.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet call waiting services and devices are alternatives
to getting a second phone line, which many people can't afford or
don't want to pay for. Since about 75 percent of Internet access
comes from the home, industry watchers say a line that can do
double-duty as a telephone and Internet pipe should have broad
appeal. The technology is aimed at residential customers who use
the Internet for a couple of hours each day.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will appeal to big online users and those who are on just
a couple of hours a day,'' said Dana Thorat, a research analyst
with Internet Data Corp. According to IDC, about 26 percent of
online households will use Internet call waiting by the end of 2000
and by 2003, that number could reach 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The technology is being developed by companies like Lucent
Technologies, Nortel Networks and eFusion of Oregon. They have
created software and hardware that phone companies and ISPs can
install in their networks to offer Internet call waiting.
</P>
<P>
   The companies developing the technology also think it has broad
consumer appeal. Most of the developers said they were responding
to complaints from consumers, who said they were frustrated by not
being able to get through to their home phone because their kids or
spouses were on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is for cost-conscious customers who got on the Internet
because they've got kids at home and wanted e-mail,'' said Ajit
Pendse, CEO of eFusion. ``These are people who are not going to buy
a second phone. They just want to be able to use the same line for
all their needs.''
</P>
<P>
   As companies begin deploying Internet call waiting, Thorat says
customers are going to begin demanding it as a standard service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is trialing it in anticipation,'' Thorat said. She
added that all the major local phone companies are testing Internet
call waiting, except for Pac Bell and Ameritech.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Dimmitt, vice president of consumer marketing at Pac Bell,
said the company is interested in Internet call waiting, but hasn't
decided how it wants to deploy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think Internet call waiting is a good product and we think
it makes a whole lot of sense for people with a single phone
line,'' Dimmitt said. ``We're looking at what's the right
technology and whether it makes more sense for Pac Bell to deploy
it or Pac Bell Internet. We should have a decision within the next
couple of months.''
</P>
<P>
   Phone companies in other parts of the country, including US West
and GTE Corp., have announced plans to offer Internet call waiting.
Both companies are testing the service now and plan to roll it out
within the next few months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 2202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
