<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2579 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PORSCHE-SFCHRON &LR;      05-26 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORSCHE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Court Case Could Stop Cybersquatters  &HT;       
 By Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Corporate America is closely watching an obscure case in a Virginia
federal courthouse tomorrow that could effectively quash
``cybersquatters'' _ individuals whose Web site addresses contain
the names of well-known companies to ensnare unwitting Web surfers.
<P>
   Porsche Cars North America Inc. filed an umbrella suit earlier
this year against 138 online addresses that illegally used the
Porsche name or variations on it, such as ``porsch.'' Porsche
attorneys have developed a legal strategy in which they are suing
domain names _ not the individual Web registrants.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called in rem tactic (Latin for ``against the thing'')
allowed the Atlanta-based automaker to sidestep having to serve
individuals with a summons. Finding individual registrants has
deterred some past cases as many cybersquatter registrants use
phony names and addresses, and often live outside the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This seems to be the easiest way to stop trademark dilution
without having to hunt down people with fictitious names or
offshore offices in Iran and Belarus,'' said Gregory Phillips, a
Salt Lake City lawyer who represents Porsche.
</P>
<P>
   Copycat Web domain names are a rampant problem for many
corporations. ``A guy in Libya, in just five minutes, can register
for $70 a site called CokeSucks that is filled with offensive
material,'' Phillips said. ``It is the functional equivalent of
constructing misleading road signs on a highway to divert people.
You'll see a Chevron sign but when you turn off the exit, you pull
into a Podunk gas station.''
</P>
<P>
   But in its zeal to stop trademark infringement online, Porsche's
legal gambit may unfairly include innocent Web site operators,
contends an attorney for one of the defendants who is challenging
the suit in court tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're using a sweeping suit that is like a tuna net. It
catches tuna but it also catches dolphins,'' said Paul DeCicco,
whose client, Christian Holmgreen of Kent, England, owns two
Porsche addresses without Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a suit of convenience that when you really examine it,
falls apart,'' DeCicco said.
</P>
<P>
   In its haste to round up the offending URLs, in fact, Phillips
admits accidentally including several Porsche dealerships in
California and Flordia on the original list of defendants. They
were later dropped from the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the misstep, Porsche's unconventional strategy seems to
be working.
</P>
<P>
   Since it filed suit in U.S. District Court in Alexandria, Va.,
in January, about half of the 138 sites using the automaker's name
have withdrawn their Web addresses. The suit specifically applies
to Web addresses invoking the Porsche name without the automaker's
permission _ but not to sites containing content on Porsche.
</P>
<P>
   The suit is being brought in Virginia because that's where the
URL addresses were issued by online registrar Network Solutions
Inc., which is based in Herndon, Va. NSI is not named in Porsche's
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the first case of its kind, and every company with a
well-known name is interested in the outcome,'' said Philip Green,
a law partner at Green &AMP; Green in San Rafael. ``If Porsche is
successful, this could start a flurry of copycat suits.''
</P>
<P>
   It already has. Bell Atlantic filed an in rem suit a few weeks
ago in the same Virginia federal court, nicknamed the ``rocket
docket'' for its speedy judicial process. The court features a
statue of Lady Justice with the inscription, ``Justice delayed is
justice denied.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys at some other frequent cybersquatter targets _ Chanel
and Nissan _ are considering the same tactic, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Like dozens of previous infringement cases filed by the likes of
Microsoft, Playboy and others, Porsche's lawsuit was prompted by
Web sites that flaunt the carmaker's name. Most of the commercial
Web pages are fronts for pornography.
</P>
<P>
   One Porsche.com porno proprietor, Yom Tobian of Sherman Oaks,
has also registered X-rated sites under the online monikers of the
New York Times, Infinity and Nissan. He has 17 sites containing
``Chanel'' in their title, and faces legal action from all those
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Tobian and other cybersquatters evidently find the risk to be
worthwhile. By 2003, consumers will plunk down an estimated $3.2
trillion to buy products and services over the Internet, e-commerce
experts said. Budding Net entrepreneurs hope to grab some of that
revenue stream by carjacking traffic headed for the Web sites of
major brand names.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, a corporation's only defense was to sue each
offender _ if one could be found and served with court papers. Many
companies found that option costly, and instead bought the Web
address from domain-name raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations won't have to cave in to the cyber extortion,
however, if Porsche attorneys win their court battle tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we can clean up this (cybersquatting) mess with an in
rem strategy,'' said Neil Smith, a San Francisco trademark attorney
who is discussing similar suits with his clients. ``You don't have
to go around the world to find defendants, and you can consolidate
your case in one spot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 2203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0416 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2580 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIGAR-POLITICS-TEX     05-26 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIGAR-POLITICS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBAN TRADE EMBARGO IS TARGET OF CIGAR FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAN PILLER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cigar smokers used to gather in smoke-filled rooms and talk
mainstream politics, involving such things as nominating and
electing presidents and other candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, cigar smokers are talking about the politics of
cigars. The issue of the Cuban trade embargo, close to the heart of
U.S. cigar smokers, is as hazy as the smoke from a full-bodied
robusto.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible to attend one of the popular ``Big Smoke''
dinners and hear cigar-puffing conservatives in good standing argue
that the U.S. trade embargo against communist leader Fidel Castro
be liberalized.
</P>
<P>
   But then comes Cuban-born Ernesto Carillo, owner of El Credito
Cigar Co. of Miami and the Dominican Republic, who argues that,
``The embargo should not be lifted until Castro is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Lest this matter be considered trivial, note that the Miami
International Airport recently banned the sale of the popular and
influential ``Cigar Aficionado'' magazine's special issue
advocating an end to the 37-year-old embargo of Cuban products.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually had the American Civil Liberties Union involved,''
said Gordon Mott, editor of CA, who appreciates the irony of the
slick, upscale magazine being joined on the issue with the liberal
ACLU.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could go on for hours about the philosophy of this, but the
issue is very complex,'' Mott said.
</P>
<P>
   The matter of the Cuban embargo, imposed in 1962 by President
John F. Kennedy, (one of a long line of cigar-smoking presidents)
has been roused recently by not only the CA issue, but also by the
first post-Castro baseball games between the Baltimore Orioles and
a Cuban national team.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of the embargo is important because the much-heralded
cigar boom seems to have hit a pause after becoming a noted 1990s
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Consumption of large cigars held steady in the United States in
the 6 billion to 8 billion annual range from 1920 to 1970. Then
baby boomers, with their health and anti-smoking zeal, put cigars
on the dreaded unhip list. Sales plunged to scarcely more than 2
billion through 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But with a huge assist from CA magazine and prominent and
diverse smokers such as Michael Jordan, Jack Nicholson, Bryant
Gumbel, Claudia Schiffer and Rush Limbaugh, (not to mention the
first baby boomer president, Bill Clinton), cigars have been
restored to hipness. Schiffer and other women now make up 25
percent of cigar smokers.
</P>
<P>
   Although premium cigar sales have flattened nationally,
producers and retailers say that the market is steadier and more
profitable now than in the mid-1990s, when the boom began.
</P>
<P>
   ``Premium cigar sales still are strong, but now the supply is
better because the producers have expanded capacity,'' said Glen
Elliot, owner of Tobacco Lane on the Square in downtown Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Because supplies are no longer so tight, Elliot says, retailers
have begun to offer discounts on certain brands. This comes as a
welcome relief to newly enrolled cigar lovers who were turning
green at prices of $10 to $15 per cigar for some premium brands.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, premium cigar sales have been flat for the past
couple of years. Norman Sharp, director of the Cigar Association of
America, says ``the bloom is off the rose.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharp said the boom, which began in 1994, caught Caribbean
producers off guard. Because good cigar rollers are rare and hard
to train, and because premium cigars should be aged up to three
years after rolling and before being sold, the sudden surge in U.S.
cigar sales threatened to eat the industry from within.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had a serious supply problem, which translated into a
price issue,'' Sharp said.
</P>
<P>
   As premium cigars became harder to get and more expensive when
available, some enthusiasts argued that lifting the Cuban embargo
would not only weaken Castro internally but would also ease the
supply crunch in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But producers such as Carillo, whose Miami-based company makes
La Gloriana Cubana and other brands in the Dominican Republic have
joined in the anti-Castro Cuban expatriate community of south
Florida to argue against a hasty lifting of the embargo.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the companies offering premium hand-rolled brands,
Carillo's family has been in the business for generations and fled
Cuba after Castro's revolution in 1959. Castro's government seized
the properties of those producers and since the early 1960s has
produced Cuban brands for most of the rest of the world under the
original names.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Cuban expatriates such as Carillo have moved to
various Caribbean nations to grow their tobacco and roll the
cigars, also using their own names.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the lifting of a U.S. trade embargo would raise the specter
of two kinds of various premium brands flooding the U.S. market,
setting off a trademark war. Expatriate producers such as Carillo
fear that U.S. consumers would suddenly be faced with competing
versions of the same premium brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Cuban embargo were to be lifted, there would be a
serious trademark issue,'' Carillo said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp says his association would want what he calls
``nondiscriminatory access to Cuban tobacco, which was always
highly prized.''
</P>
<P>
   He says the real issue isn't where the cigar is rolled. Most
pre-Castro ``Cubans'' were rolled in the United States but with
Cuban-grown tobacco. But Castro, Sharp said, shouldn't be allowed
to monopolize the tobacco in his country.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the argument and smoke about the embargo, an unanswered
question is how strong the U.S. demand would be for genuine
Cuban-grown cigars.
</P>
<P>
   Elliot says Cuban cigars are more full-bodied, or stronger, than
their Caribbean cousins. He therefore isn't sure that the U.S.
market would instantly gravitate to the Cuban products.
</P>
<P>
   Mott says the newer cigar smokers who have fueled the increase
in sales during the 1990s could be expected to prefer the milder,
non-Cuban brands.
</P>
<P>
   ``A genuine Cuban cigar can be twice as strong a smoke as the
Caribbean,'' he said. ``Experience shows that the newer smokers
generally don't get into the stronger blends for quite a while.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
