<SLUG> BC-CAR-DALEJR27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dale Jr. qualifies for 1st Cup race
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.C. _ A streak ended Wednesday night at Lowe's Motor
Speedway, but an era began.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt, Jr., attempting to make his first Winston Cup
race, qualified for Sunday's Coca-Cola 600 in dramatic fashion.
Earnhardt Jr., the 24-year-old son of the seven-time Winston Cup
champion, will start eighth after covering the 1.5-mile oval in
29.283 seconds, an average speed of 184.407 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt Jr., the 1998 Busch Grand National champion who will
move to Winston Cup full-time next year, said he was relieved after
anticipation surrounding his debut had been building for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't never been that nervous in my life,'' he said. ``I
wasn't worried about my ability to run a fast lap. I just knew
there were a lot of people looking at me. I couldn't wait to get
the motor cranked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I did and rolled out on the track, I just forgot about
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Labonte won the pole at Lowe's for the second straight
week, after starting first in Saturday's The Winston all-star race.
Labonte's average speed of 185.230 mph broke Jeff Gordon's
Coca-Cola 600 qualifying record of 184.300 mph, set in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Burton will start second, followed by an unlikely group
that includes Kenny Wallace, rookie Elliott Sadler and Steve Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six hundred miles is a long race,'' said Labonte, who won his
third pole in 12 events this year. ``But it's important to start up
front everywhere. In a 600-mile race, we've got to make sure we're
patient and finish up front, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Two-time defending race winner Gordon, who was trying to become
the first driver to win six poles in a row in the spring race here,
will start 10th. Gordon, the fifth of 52 drivers attempting to
qualify, had an average speed of 184.162 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Charlotte, you've got to draw a late number to qualify on
the pole,'' Gordon said. ``I believe we put a good number up there,
but this place gets faster as it gets darker and cools down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had fast race cars here in the past, but we've also had
some good late draws.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon remains tied with David Pearson with five straight poles.
Pearson won 11 straight poles from October 1973 until October 1978,
including five straight poles in the spring race.
</P>
<P>
   The night still belonged to Earnhardt Jr., who will start seven
spots ahead of his father, who has won five times in 44 starts
here.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
