<HEADER>
A2584 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES27-CO     05-26 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rare homer adds to fun Weiss having in leadoff
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ This has been a memorable trip for Braves shortstop
Walt Weiss, who hit his first home run as an Atlanta Brave on
Tuesday night to extend his career-high hitting streak to a dozen
games. It was his first home run since Sept. 15, 1997 in Florida
when he was a Rockie.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss' wife Terri told him after the game their 4-year-old son
Brody got a special kick out of it watching from home in Colorado,
cheering for his dad in front of the TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I hit more of them,'' Weiss said. ``It was fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss' hot bat corresponds with his move from No. 8 to the top
of the order, where he's hit .364 in the eight games since Bobby
Cox replaced Otis Nixon with Gerald Williams in left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have a better game plan at the plate since I've been
leading off,'' Weiss said. ``When I was hitting in the eighth spot,
I was expanding my strike zone a lot, especially with guys on base.
I'm not a good bad-ball hitter. I've hit a lot in the eighth spot
in the National League and I can do the job if you're looking for a
guy to get on base and turn the lineup over, but if you're looking
for a guy to expand the strike zone and hit bad pitches, I'm not
your guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss had two errors on Tuesday night game for the second time
this season. He threw past first base attempting to turn a
first-to-second-to-first double play, Weiss said he never should
have thrown the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was too much daylight between (Greg Maddux) and the base
when I made the throw,'' Weiss said. ``That's a tough play to
make.''
</P>
<P>
   The popup he dropped four innings later was more perplexing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the first popup I've ever dropped,'' Weiss
said. ``I don't think I ever got set up underneath it.''
</P>
<P>
   Boone's bat
</P>
<P>
   The four hits Bret Boone got on Tuesday night matched a
career-high, something he's hit 10 other times, including four
times last season. He used these four hits to raise his batting
average back up to .299, matching the highest it's been this
season. Heading into Wednesday night's game, Boone had hit in 24 of
his last 26 games.
</P>
<P>
   Boone has hit .300 once in his major league career, when he hit
.320 in 1994, his first year with the Reds. The career .256 hitter,
known more for having good power for a second baseman, keeps .300
as a reasonable goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm a better hitter now than I was when I hit .320,''
Boone said. Hunter hero
</P>
<P>
   Brian Hunter's two-run home run on Tuesday got the Braves off to
a good start as the 2-0 lead held up until the eighth inning.
Hunter, who was making his seventh start of the year at first base,
got his first hit since May 8 in San Diego. He's made three starts
since then, including Tuesday night when he served a Jim Abbott
curveball into the left field seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fortunate that pitch didn't get down in the dirt,''
Hunter said. ``That's the pitch I've been striking out on. It gives
me some confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga change of plans
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Eddie Perez said Andres Galarraga has changed his mind
and won't join the Braves on their trip to Boston next week but
would like to join the team later.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just had a treatment and he's been taking pills and shots
and he doesn't feel real good,'' Perez said.
</P>
<P>
   Hudek's progress
</P>
<P>
   Reliever John Hudek said he expects to throw to hitters for the
second time today or Friday and then head off on a rehabilitation
assignment in the minor leagues soon afterward. Hudek threw to
hitters without a bandage for the first time since first rubbing a
blister in a game in Chicago less than two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hudek threw breaking balls for the first time, the toughest
pitch for him to grip with the blister on his third finger. Hudek
said he was throwing at about 75 percent effort and felt good doing
it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
