<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2585 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HAWKS27-COX     05-26 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No overhaul for Hawks
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hawks president Stan Kasten was stung by the Hawks'
playoff collapse, but he said Wednesday that he still believes the
team is on the right track as it heads into ``the most important
year in the history of our franchise and therefore the most
important summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasten said the Hawks have the tools to strengthen their team
and the organization is in a position it carefully sought while
preparing for the move into the new Philips Arena.
</P>
<P>
   He cautioned that no major changes are being considered _ not
with current players nor with coach Lenny Wilkens and general
manager Pete Babcock, both of whom are under fire from some critics
and fans.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, Kasten indicated that no player can
feel fully secure if the right offer comes along.
</P>
<P>
   ``The upside of not having a big media star means that we have
no one who is untouchable here,'' he said. ``The day we can improve
at any position, we will do it. And let me say that our players
understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasten referred to the program that started with the free-agent
signing of Dikembe Mutombo and the retention of leading scorer
Steve Smith. ``This is what we've been planning for three years,
and that's what we've got our (salary )cap exception and our four
draft picks for,'' he said. ``And we already have a very good
roster.''
</P>
<P>
   Major roster changes are unlikely, Kasten said. ``I told myself
before the year started that I would not indulge in major changes
because of the nature of how disruptive the whole season was,
because of the lockout and the way we had to all come together and
get the season behind us. I don't think it's a fair year to draw
any conclusions from, and that's how I feel today.''
</P>
<P>
   However, change clearly is in the offing, Kasten said, by the
way the Hawks very nature of having stockpiled draft picks and the
team's $4.4 million trade exception, which that will allow him to
bring in an additional established player. , Kasten said change
clearly is in the offing. We always make changes in the off-season,
both franchises (Hawks and Braves). I would say
</P>
<P>
   The basic goals are He said the basic goals were to improve the
team's depth and its offense, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, this year was a disastrous offensive year for the whole
league,'' Kasten said. ``There and there are lot of reasons for
that, much of which has to do with the screwy nature of this
particular season, the short time to put teams together, short time
to train guys and then, of course, the compressed schedule. You
never had time to construct an offense.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the Hawks were more guilty than most. Despite a 31-19
record in over the regular season, they ranked 28th in the league
in scoring at 86.3 a game. Against New York, they set records for
gruesome four-game playoff series records for fewest points (306),
fewest field goals (101) and worst shooting percentage (.316).
</P>
<P>
   ``We clearly need to improve . . . ours as the next thing, and
one of the ways you do that is adding scoring, whether it's
starters or off the bench,'' Kasten said. ``I will say this: If
we're healthy, we should have a deep enough and good enough team
where we're getting nine or 10 players on our 12-man roster into
our games. If a year from now we don't, that would concern me.'' It
doesn't concern me now because of the screwy nature of our season,
but if it were true next year again, that would be a real red flag
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasten said he is ``saatisfied with our leadership'' from
Wilkens and Babcock. Regarding Wilkens and Babock, Kasten said,
``I'm satisfied with our leadership. ``We put this roster together
with trades and free-agent signings and when we're healthy,
everyone acknowledges we have a good, deep roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're poised on being the kind of team we planned on being,
and you know that doesn't happen by itself,'' Kasten said. ``That's
not an accident. So it's one thing to be down today, which I assure
you I am, but in terms of where we have to be as we move into a
great new building, I think we're exactly where we need to be, and
next year we will be at or near the top of the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
