<SLUG> BC-FBN-OWNERS-NOTES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coaches still feel owners aren't addressing worries
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just a few miles from where the owners adjourned their
two-day meeting Wednesday afternoon, NFL assistants completed their
second annual coaching symposium. A session designed by senior vice
president George Young featured speakers who covered such topics as
dealing with agents, media relationships and benefits and
retirement packages.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike last year, when Denver offensive line coach Alex Gibbs
delivered a fiery speech, the NFL Coaches Association, a group
attempting to improve working conditions for assistants, made no
public display. But some assistants said privately that
commissioner Paul Tagliabue and prominent owners missed another
opportunity to address the coaches' concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made myself available,'' said Larry Kennan, executive
director of the group. ``My belief is that the NFL wants to get
something done but just doesn't know how to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Three league owners _ Mike Brown (Cincinnati), Tom Benson (New
Orleans) and Jerry Jones (Dallas) _ prohibit assistants from
joining the association.
</P>
<P>
   Baggy suit
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit brought against former Washington owner John Kent
Cooke and general manager Charley Casserly by failed Redskins
suitor Howard Milstein was criticized by Tagliabue and several
owners. ``I told him his contentions were misguided and terribly
wrong,'' Tagliabue said. Milstein failed to generate support for
his purchase of the team, and the Redskins were sold on Tuesday to
his onetime partner, Daniel Snyder. Most owners felt they had an
agreement with Milstein that he would not sue if he didn't get the
team. ``I think it's disgraceful,'' Pittsburgh owner Dan Rooney
said.
</P>
<P>
   Champ talks begin
</P>
<P>
   Casserly took advantage of his trip here to huddle for several
hours early in the week with Jack Reale, agent for Champ Bailey,
the Redskins' first-round pick from Georgia. ``It was just a first
meeting, a chance for us to get a little more familiar with each
other,'' Casserly said. Reale also represents two other Redskins
draft choices, former Georgia Tech linebacker Nate Stimson (No. 4)
and wide receiver Tim Alexander of Oregon State (No. 7).
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl awarded
</P>
<P>
   League owners on Wednesday formally awarded Super Bowl XXXVII in
2003 to San Diego. The game had been scheduled for San Francisco
but had to be moved because prospects for a new stadium in the Bay
Area are in peril, in part because of the feud between 49ers owners
Ed DeBartolo Jr. and Denise DeBartolo York.
</P>
<P>
   If the 'Shu' fits ...
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Fame coach Don Shula is interested in the presidency of
the Redskins, but Snyder insisted he's ``still a long way'' from
naming a chief executive for the club. Early word is that Shula
probably won't get the job. Likely candidates are Thomas McCormack,
attorney for Snyder, and former Carolina Panthers president Mike
McCormack.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Free-agent defensive end Marco Coleman has reached an agreement
in principle with the Redskins. The deal for the former Georgia
Tech star probably won't be announced for a few weeks, until Snyder
assumes control. ... The Falcons re-signed reserve linebacker Ben
Talley to the one-year tender of $429,000. ... Former Georgia
defensive tackle Emarlos Leroy, a sixth-round pick in Jacksonville,
agreed to a two-year contract worth $445,000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
