<SLUG> BC-FBN-OWNERS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Replay improved, but still has flaws
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Somewhere, former Seahawks coach Dennis Erickson
probably is wondering what took the NFL so long to implement the
instant-replay technology unveiled at Wednesday's owner meetings at
the Buckhead Ritz-Carlton.
</P>
<P>
   The new system, to be used this fall, might have saved
Erickson's job last season.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, officials awarded Jets quarterback Vinny Testaverde a
phantom touchdown in the waning seconds of a December game, giving
New York a victory and eliminating Seattle from playoff contention.
Erickson was fired less than a month later.
</P>
<P>
   In a mock demonstration Wednesday, the NFL used replay
technology that provided six angles of the play _ and proved that
Testaverde did not score.
</P>
<P>
   A replay official in the mock booth sent the best angle of the
play to Jerry Seeman, the NFL's senior director of officiating, as
Seeman stood in front of a monitor like the two that will be on the
sidelines of every game this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Seeman reviewed the play on his monitor, as referees will, and
ruled the touchdown was awarded in error.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely a more efficient system,'' said Redskins
general manager Charley Casserly, long a proponent of instant
replay.
</P>
<P>
   The system allows technicians to pick quickly one of six angles
displayed on the same monitor _ all from the network TV feed.
</P>
<P>
   But not everybody is convinced it will work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a skeptic,'' Bengals president Mike Brown said. ``The
technology is tremendously improved, but we won't know until it is
implemented.''
</P>
<P>
   Each team is allowed to challenge two plays per game, although
in the final two minutes of each half, only the replay assistant
can stop the game for a review. If a challenge does not result in a
reversal of a call, that team loses a timeout. A team without a
timeout cannot issue a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We run the risk in the last two minutes of stopping a game and
not reversing, thereby giving a (trailing) team an edge,'' said
Mike Pereira, one of the league's 16 replay assistants.
</P>
<P>
   The system has another flaw. Nothing after the ball is whistled
dead is open to review. That means the play in the Green Bay-San
Francisco playoff game, in which 49ers receiver Jerry Rice fumbled
before he was down, wouldn't have been reversed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
