<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2588 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-THRASH27-COX     05-26 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASH27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Selection of head coach still getting thrashed out
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the Thrashers' management and scouting staffs
congregate in Boston in four weeks to assemble the nucleus of the
team's original roster, there is a good chance one seat at the
conference table will be empty.
</P>
<P>
   It's the one reserved for a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Thrashers general manager Don Waddell, who has eliminated as
many potential head coaches from his prospect list as he has added,
acknowledges for the first time the strong possibility that a coach
will not be in place in time for the team's expansion draft June
25.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be reactive to a date,'' Waddell said.
``Everybody says, `It's an expansion team. You can hire someone and
fire him in two years.' But I want to hire someone for the long
term. Believe me, if there was somebody out there right now we
wanted to hire, I would. It would be a lot easier to sleep, and I'd
be getting a lot fewer phone calls every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Waddell has two reasons to delay hiring a coach. His priority
has been to put together a scouting staff and to evaluate players.
And he has not had an overwhelming candidate to pursue. When former
Colorado coach Marc Crawford was available, Waddell showed no great
urgency to interview a coach who had won a Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in situations where I could've hired some
high-profile people as coaches,'' Waddell said. ``My line on that
is, if you hire a big-name coach, it's only good until you drop the
puck. It doesn't matter who the coach or the general manager is.
You're based on your performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Waddell has been doing background checks on ``30-some'' coaching
candidates. He estimates that only seven to 10 will be interviewed,
with two to four brought back to Atlanta for extensive interviews.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledges the potential disadvantages of not having a head
coach to give any input on the Thrashers' 26 expansion picks _ one
from each team, excluding Nashville. ``I realize there's a
possibility of a head coach going to war with a guy he doesn't
like,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the GM reiterated that he is fully responsible for the team.
Avoiding a potential conflict on draft day ``could actually be
viewed as a positive,'' he said. If Waddell, assistant GM Les
Jackson and NHL scout Murray Oliver agree on a player, but the
coach cast an opposing vote, which way would Waddell go?
</P>
<P>
   ``You could make the point that it's better to go to a (coaching
candidate) and say, `Here's the players we drafted. What can you do
for us?' The bottom line is it would be unfair to have a coach in
the room if we didn't allow him any input. But if he had input and
there's a problem, what do you do?''
</P>
<P>
   Waddell often has joked that he might just name himself as
coach, as he once did in San Diego (IHL). ``Then I can always say,
`I've got lousy players. Fire the GM.'''
</P>
<P>
   It won't happen, but his prerequisites have changed. Waddell
once mandated that his head coach have NHL head-coaching
experience, but he is backing away from that requirement and saying
that a top flight assistant is a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no shortage of names mentioned, some legitimate
candidates, many not. Waddell has been contacted by approximately
25 job hunters or their agents in the last three weeks alone, and
some are finding their way into media rumor mills.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who won't make it to an interview are former Ottawa
coach Rick Bowness, now a Nashville scout; Ottawa general manager
Rick Dudley, who is on the verge of becoming GM in Tampa Bay; Tampa
GM/coach Jacques Demers, who might lose both jobs; Phoenix
assistant coach John Tortorella, a walking rumor these days; former
Los Angeles coach and ESPN commentator Barry Melrose; multi-team
coach Mike Keenan; Calgary coach Brian Sutter, who is seeking a new
contract; Orlando (IHL) coach Curt Fraser; and Providence (AHL)
coach Peter Laviolette.
</P>
<P>
   The legitimate candidate list includes three former NHL head
coaches: former Buffalo coach Ted Nolan (who may be close to
getting the Los Angeles job); former Calgary coach Dave King, a
Montreal assistant; and former Phoenix coach and Anaheim assistant
Don Hay, coaching the Tri-Cities (Wash.) junior team in the Western
Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Several other NHL assistants aspire to be a head coach,
including Detroit's Dave Lewis, likely headed to replace Scotty
Bowman; Colorado's Brian Trottier; Toronto's Rick Ley, who coached
parts of two seasons in Vancouver; Ottawa's Mike Murphy, who had
two last-place finishes in Toronto; Buffalo's Don Lever; and
Dallas's Doug Jarvis.
</P>
<P>
   Former Anaheim assistant Walt Kyle, who coaches Hamilton of the
AHL and worked with Waddell in San Diego, also is a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell is seeking a coach who excels in teaching and
communicating and has the patience to bring along an expansion
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all want to win today, but that doesn't mean we will win
today, and it doesn't mean we're going to mortgage the future,'' he
said. ``Coaches get paid to win hockey games. But whoever we hire
is going to have to deal with certain player personnel issues of
being an expansion team.''
</P>
<P>
   Waddell will make one guarantee: ``I'll have a coach in place by
training camp.'' Which, by the way, isn't until September.
</P>
<P>
   BRIEFLY: Waddell will be in Toronto this weekend for testing and
interviews of draft prospects, followed by four days of pre-draft
meetings with his scouting staff. The likely first four picks in
the entry draft _ Patrik Stefan, Pavel Brendl, Daniel and Henrik
Sedin _ will not attend the scouting combine. ``The big boys won't
be there, but that doesn't bother me,'' Waddell said. ``We know all
those guys real well. We've watched them, we've met them all, we've
been to their house and had dinner with them. This gives us more
time to spend with the other players. I've said it before _ the
first pick is easy; picks two through nine are hard.'' . . .
Waddell said director of player evaluation Bob Owen, who has been
resting after recent heart surgery, will attend the pre-draft
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
