<SLUG> BC-TEN-HALLOFFAME27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gulliksons, Purcells in college Hall of Fame
 &HT;    By Plott Brice
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ The Intercollegiate Tennis Association inducted
eight new members into the Collegiate Hall of Fame on Wednesday,
including twins Tim and Tom Gullikson and father-and-son
combination Bennie and Mel Purcell.
</P>
<P>
   The Gulliksons played at Northern Illinois and put that school
on the tennis map as one of the nation's top doubles teams. They
had success on the pro tour, reaching the finals at Wimbledon. Tim,
who had an outstanding career as a tennis coach and is credited
with the rise of Pete Sampras, died of a brain tumor in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Tom is captain of the U.S. Davis Cup team, which will host
Australia in July in the Centennial Davis Cup tie. He also coached
the 1996 Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   Bennie Purcell, an outstanding basketball player at Murray
State, didn't take up tennis until he was 35, but took over the
Murray State tennis program and won 11 Ohio Valley Conference
titles. His son, Mel, was a star at Memphis State and Tennessee.
With partner Rodney Harmon, he won the NCAA doubles title in 1980
and also won the indoor singles title. As a pro, the younger
Purcell had wins over Ivan Lendl and Boris Becker. He took over the
program at Murray State, but also still plays on the Legends Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Also inducted were Bill Scanlon of Trinity University, Wallace
Johnson of Pennsylvania, John Whitlinger of Stanford and Baylor
coach Charles Mapes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
