<SLUG> BC-CHINA-COX-RENO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF LAWMAKERS CALL FOR BLOOD, THEY MAY GET RENO'S 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Ala.)  (Eds: See also CHINA-COX-NUKE) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A congressional committee's conclusion that China
systematically stole nuclear secrets has prompted angry lawmakers
in both parties to look for a high profile official to blame, and
increasingly they are taking aim at Attorney General Janet Reno,
for failing to respond aggressively to the threat.
</P>
<P>
   Reno is not alone in the cross hairs; other officials, like
Sandy Berger, the national security adviser, have also come under
attack. But it is Reno who appears to be most vulnerable after the
congressional report, made public on Tuesday, found that Beijing
stole crucial data related to the most advanced thermonuclear
weapons of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Justice Department has shown little progress in
prosecuting anyone in the case. The chief suspect remains free
following admissions by Justice Department officials that they
declined to allow the FBI to investigate more aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, Reno's aides acknowledge that she has already been
wounded by the attacks, and they are growing more worried because
the calls for her resignation are coming not just from Republicans
in Congress, but also from Democrats usually allied with the
Clinton administration, like Sen. Robert Torricelli of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, Reno appears to be losing her once solid backing
among some key midlevel and senior managers at the Justice
Department. They blame her for mishandling the FBI investigation of
Wen Ho Lee, the Los Alamos scientist under suspicion of passing
secrets to Beijing, and for failing to set clear priorities in
espionage cases. They also say she did not stand by her
subordinates when the Justice Department was attacked.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials have publicly expressed support for Reno,
but they have not rallied to defend her. At times, Reno's
independence has annoyed presidential aides, and they have
occasionally expressed the hope that she would step aside. One
Democratic congressional official said that White House officials
might soon say publicly what some have said privately: that they
have lost confidence in her.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli raised the question of Reno's tenure at a Senate
Democratic leadership meeting on Capitol Hill on Tuesday, according
to congressional officials, but several senators _ all women _
responded that the criticism of her was unfair.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, a move to dislodge Reno could be seen as an
attempt to deflect criticism from the White House and divert
Congress from accusations that officials like Berger, who is much
closer to Clinton, failed to make the president aware of the
magnitude of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism of Reno appears founded in part on a weariness
with her stewardship. After more than six years, she has forged few
close friendships with lawmakers from either political party.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, furious over Reno's refusal to refer any aspect of
the campaign finance case to an independent prosecutor, have seemed
to relish piling on. Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., who heads the
Senate Intelligence Committee, has said that the Justice Department
is adrift and that Reno should resign and take her top aides with
her.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's support, congressional aides said, is eroding among
Democrats, who were already worn down by Clinton's impeachment and
have shown few signs that they are willing to defend another
administration official. Some have grown impatient with Reno, whose
taciturn appearances at hearings have led them to question her
command of issues.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli urged Reno to consider resigning based on what he
said was the ``almost inexplicable refusal'' of the Justice
Department to authorize the electronic monitoring of Lee, who has
issued a detailed rebuttal denying that he spied for any foreign
power.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said Reno's aides argued for nearly
two days about the language of a statement she issued Monday
evening. In it she defended the decision of the Office of
Intelligence Policy Review to reject an FBI request to use more
aggressive surveillance techniques in the Wen Ho Lee case.
</P>
<P>
   But even this irritated some department officials, who viewed it
as an awkward effort by Reno to distance herself from the decision.
``Although I was not apprised of the details of the case at the
time the decision was made, I have reviewed the decision of the
OIPR and fully support it,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Justice Department, officials said that Reno's policy
edicts and management style created a rigidly bureaucratic climate
that hamstrung the FBI investigation. One policy change meant that
spy-hunters at the internal security section of the Justice
Department's criminal division did not even know about the Wen Ho
Lee case until it was the subject of news reports, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The internal security unit, staffed by the government's most
experienced espionage prosecutors, was barred from even knowing
about such cases under a rule adopted after the prosecution of
Aldrich Ames, the CIA officer who pleaded guilty to spying for the
former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   That rule was designed to prevent the intermingling of
intelligence with criminal evidence, so that any case the
department ultimately brought would not be tainted by evidence
collected solely for intelligence purposes. Under the rule, the FBI
cannot discuss counterintelligence cases with criminal prosecutors
until investigators have enough evidence of their own to bring a
case. In the Wen Ho Lee case, the rule meant that investigators and
prosecutors did not consult each other.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
