<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-MAGAZINES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND CANADA REACH AGREEMENT ON MAGAZINES, AVERTING TRADE
CONFLICT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KALYANI VITTALA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Canada and the United States averted a trade war
Wednesday with an agreement that resolves a protracted dispute over
Canadian barriers to U.S. magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, U.S. or foreign magazines exported to
Canada can aim up to 12 percent of their total advertising space at
the Canadian market place during the first year, 15 percent within
18 months and a maximum of 18 percent over three years. If foreign
magazines wish to increase their amount of Canadian advertising
share, they will have to substantially increase the content level
in the magazines that is specifically aimed at Canadian readers.
</P>
<P>
   Canada would also make changes to income tax law so that
advertising in a foreign publication becomes a standard business
deduction.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Canada pledged to liberalize its investment
regulations to permit 51 percent foreign ownership within the next
90 days and 100 percent ownership within the year. The current
maximum is 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased that we have negotiated a settlement to this
long-standing dispute with our largest trading partner,'' said U.S.
Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky. ``It will increase market
access in clear and predictable ways, address anti-competitive
regulatory concerns, and provide tax and investment benefits and
opportunities for foreign publishers in Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   The Canadians said the deal would protect their country's
magazines. ``The Americans wanted unfettered access,'' said
Canadian Heritage Minister Sheila Copps. ``What they are getting is
18 percent of the pie and we are protecting the 82 percent for
those who provide Canadian content.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute arose over what are known as ``split-run'' magazines
_ Canadian editions of foreign publications that carry little or no
Canadian content. The dispute has been simmering between the two
countries for years.
</P>
<P>
   Canadians argue that split-run versions of such publications as
People or Sports Illustrated would have an unfair advantage over
Canadian magazines because their production costs are underwritten
by sales in their own country, allowing them to slash advertising
rates in the Canadian market. If Canadian magazines are unable to
compete financially, the argument goes, there would be damage to
Canadian culture because its own perspective would be lost.
</P>
<P>
   The United States had maintained that culture had never been the
issue and that Canada was simply trying to eliminate foreign
competition to its magazine industry.
</P>
<P>
   A Canadian law that prohibited split runs through a complicated
set of taxes was struck down as an unfair trading practice by the
World Trade Organization in 1997. But Canada resisted making
changes that would increase foreign access to its magazine market.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the United States threatened to impose $2.5 billion
in punitive tariffs on Canadian goods unless the law was amended.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from both countries have been in intense negotiations
since then.
</P>
<P>
   Two-way trade between Canada and the United States is estimated
at $1 billion a day.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian International Trade Minister Sergio Marchi said the
compromise between the two countries proves ``there is nothing
inconsistent or incompatible about a vigorous and open trade policy
and an equally strong promotion of one's own culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Resolution of the magazine dispute with Canada still leaves the
United States engrossed in major trade battles with the European
Union over bananas and hormone-treated beef. In both of those
cases, the United States has won favorable rulings from the World
Trade Organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
