<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NO CONTEST SHOULD EQUAL NO SYMPATHY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like everybody else at Yankee Stadium on Wednesday,
Joe Torre was talking about the Yankee who wasn't there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darryl has always been a plus here,'' the Yankee manager was
saying, ``but now there's another hurdle he's got to get over.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, another hurdle, if not two or three.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Darryl Strawberry arrived as a Mets rookie in 1983,
he has had to get over more hurdles than Edwin Moses, the great
Olympic hurdler. But in an Olympic race, the hurdles are the same
height, they're only there for a minute or two and even if you trip
over one, life goes on.
</P>
<P>
   For the man-child known as Straw, the hurdles not only keep
getting higher, but he also somehow creates more and more of them.
And this time he doesn't deserve to go on with his baseball life.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's on 18 months probation for his no-contest plea in
Florida for solicitation of a undercover police officer posing as a
prostitute, and possession of cocaine, Strawberry should be
suspended by Commissioner Bud Selig for violating its
substance-abuse policy.
</P>
<P>
   After all his mistakes in life, no contest should equal no
sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   If he's not suspended, the Yankees should consider his plea a
breach of his one-year, $2.5 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he somehow gets over those hurdles, others are out
there.
</P>
<P>
   He's now 37 with an arthritic knee that hobbles his range as an
outfielder. He's also still recuperating from colon-cancer surgery
and follow-up chemotherapy treatments. In addition to the two drug
tests administered to him by Major League Baseball each week, he is
now subject to two additional drug tests by the state of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows just how healthy he really is, or if he still has
that home-run swing that labeled him the black Ted Williams when he
was a Mets rookie _ his first hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   He has never been another Ted Williams, but he hit 39 home runs
for the Mets in both 1987 and 1988, then he hit 37 in 1990 before
deserting to the Los Angeles Dodgers as a free agent for a
four-year, $20 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   But that's when Strawberry's hurdles kept multiplying. Alcohol
abuse. Drug abuse. Spousal abuse. Conviction for income-tax
evasion. Debt. And now the no-contest plea.
</P>
<P>
   After the preaching that Strawberry has sometimes done during
his career, you would think that his teammates might feel betrayed
by his recent Florida fall from grace. Maybe some do, but Derek
Jeter, Andy Pettitte and Chili Davis, who care enough for him to
have phoned him recently, still consider him a teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to him a couple of days ago,'' Jeter said. ``His
spirits were high. He just wants to put this all behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel betrayed,'' Pettitte said. ``We all make
mistakes. He happens to be a professional athlete, so it gets
magnified.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't be worried about being betrayed,'' Davis said. ``I'm
more worried about him than I am about how it affects me.''
</P>
<P>
   Their reaction is commendable. Once a teammate, always a
teammate. But as the Yankees struggle to hit, even in Wednesday's
8-3 victory over the Red Sox, at least some of his teammates must
be wondering if their record would be better than 25-19 if
Strawberry were in their dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been lacking a left-handed bat to come off the bench,''
Torre acknowledged. ``Strawberry is an imposing figure. He
intimidates the opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   In last season's roll to 125 victories, Strawberry hit two
grand-slam pinch-hit homers, notably the one in Oakland that Torre
considered symbolic of the Yankees' domination. In only 295
at-bats, he hit 24 homers and drove in 57 runs in 101 games.
</P>
<P>
   But his bat isn't in the Yankee bat-rack now. And maybe it never
will be.
</P>
<P>
   To anyone familiar with Strawberry's earlier hurdles, his fall
from grace in Florida was something that had to happen sooner or
later. If for no other reason than, to use Pettitte's phrase, he
happens to be a professional athlete and considering all his
mistakes in life, a professional athlete who has somehow been able
to generate public sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   Because he has been able to hit home runs, Darryl Strawberry has
been allowed to run around most of those hurdles instead of having
to jump over them. That's why his new hurdles are higher now. But
after all those mistakes, he shouldn't be allowed to go around the
new hurdles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
