<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MUSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSAL MUSIC AND BMG FORM TEAM FOR WEB VENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., N.Y.)   (af)  
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The frantic push by record companies to sell copyrighted music
over the Internet is making for a kind of technological polygamy.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest example, two music industry titans, Universal
Music and BMG Entertainment, said Wednesday that they would team up
with AT&AMP;T Corp. and Matsushita Electric Industrial Co. of Japan, to
create technology to sell, store and distribute music over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Since both Universal and BMG had already announced similar
initiatives with other companies, the deal underscored the
desperation of the major record labels to establish a foothold in
electronic commerce _ even if it means pursuing multiple solutions
simultaneously and forging uneasy alliances with their own
competitors and with competing technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   Universal, the largest record company, is already committed to
an alliance announced earlier this month with Intertrust
Technologies Corp. of Sunnyvale, Calif., to create a secure digital
music technology _ that is, a way of delivering music to consumers
online while at the same time protecting copyrighted recordings
from electronic piracy.
</P>
<P>
   Universal, a unit of the Seagram Co., and BMG, which is the
music division of Bertelsmann AG, are also part of the Madison
Project, an initiative sponsored by the International Business
Machines Corp., to distribute music online.
</P>
<P>
   Some record companies are parts of larger conglomerates yet find
themselves aligning with manufacturers and developers that compete
with the technology arms of their mother corporations. For example,
Sony Music's own Magicgate software is designed to deliver music in
a secure format, but Sony Music is also part of the Madison
project, and has signed an agreement to use Microsoft's MS Audio
4.0 technology to distribute music online.
</P>
<P>
   After long ignoring the Internet, the recording industry is now
frantically seeking to establish a consumer alternative to MP3, the
technology that has become the de facto standard for distributing
music online.
</P>
<P>
   The record companies dread MP3, which compresses digital sound
into relatively small files that can be easily sent over the
Internet with no way for the record labels to trace the
distribution or prevent near CD-quality recordings. The major
labels fear that they are already losing millions of dollars
annually in revenues to MP3 recordings traded freely online.
</P>
<P>
   In their search for a standard that will enable secure sales of
music delivered online, the record companies are ``casting their
lots with a lot of players,'' said Mark Mooradian, senior analyst
with Jupiter Communications, a New York-based research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Mooradian said they were dealing from a position of
strength. The rush of deals, he said, demonstrated the power of the
record labels ultimately to determine what standard will be used,
and thus to dictate terms to technology companies, which are all
vying to establish their protection schemes as the industry
standard.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in attempting to analyze the apparently conflicting
deals announced by Universal, Mooradian said: ``When I talked to
AT&AMP;T, they said, `Intertrust is out and we're in.' Universal said,
`No, no, no, they're not out.'''
</P>
<P>
   Intertust declined comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the record labels said they had no intention of
signing exclusive agreements with individual technology partners.
Larry Kenswil, president of electronic commerce and advanced
technology for Universal Music, called the present scramble ``the
Wild West'' and said his company intended to embrace whatever
technology ``people want to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Universal, he said, does not necessarily favor any single
solution from AT&AMP;T or Intertrust; both technologies could wind up
being part of a group of solutions eventually embraced by Universal
Music.
</P>
<P>
   Fred R. Ehrlich, Sony Music's senior vice president for new
technology, said of his company's tango with multiple partners:
``Sony Music has made no exclusive relationships. I won't be
surprised if record companies make many, if not multiple,
alliances.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology companies do not seem surprised or disturbed by the
fact they are being courted by the already betrothed. Ronald J.
Brachman, research vice president at AT&AMP;T Labs, said not just
record labels but hardware and software developers were engaged in
this evolving form of corporate polygamy, often referred to as
``coopetition.''
</P>
<P>
   All this is taking place against the backdrop of an
international rush by an ad-hoc recording industry committee, the
Secure Digital Music Initiative, to negotiate an industry standard
by June from among the conflicting priorities of record labels and
the makers of consumer music devices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
