</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Risky business: Patience pulls drivers to top of Indy race
 &HT;    By Dave Lance
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Mark Dismore, who qualified for Sunday's
Indianapolis 500 in the fifth starting position, sounded like he'd
almost be disappointed if he led the race early on.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Leading early) is immaterial,'' Dismore said. ``I'm going to
line up behind (the front-row) guys like a baby duck behind his
mother. I have no intentions of winning the Indianapolis 100 .''
</P>
<P>
   It was a sentiment expressed by the other drivers in the first
two rows. The front row consists of pole-sitter Arie Luyendyk
(225.179 mph), Greg Ray (225.073) and Billy Boat (223.469), while
the second row includes Robby Gordon (223.066), Dismore (222.963)
and Scott Sharp (222.771).
</P>
<P>
   They were asked if they'd let Luyendyk lead the first lap as a
going-away present for the retiring two-time Indy 500 winner. After
unanimously vetoing that idea, they admitted the first few laps
have little impact on who wins the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the green flag falls and we're past the first corner,
we're all in it for ourselves,'' Boat said. ``But I have to be
patient. I'm not going to try to win on the first lap.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason the front-row drivers are so concerned with starting
fast is because they know they don't have to do as much work to get
to the front as the drivers in the last few rows. Still, Ray vows
to keep an eye on the back-row starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a heck of a lot easier starting in the front than in the
back,'' Ray said. ``But the last-place driver can win here and I
hold everyone in the field with the highest regard.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cruise and you go from first to 10th in a hurry. I think
you have to be aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Boat's style and he promises not to change it come Race
Day. Boat's trip to the 500 has been a rough one: He crashed two
cars during practice and another during his first qualification
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've have enough laps around here where I feel I can drive it
in my sleep,'' said Boat, the pole sitter last year. ``Then we got
behind right off the back with the (crashes).
</P>
<P>
   ``Toward the end of the week I felt comfortable again, then I
make the big mistake qualifying. It was devastating to me. It was
A.J. Foyt (car owner) and the rest of the team who picked me up.''
</P>
<P>
   Boat hopes practice goes smoothly today (Carburetion Day), the
last time the drivers are allowed on the track until the race.
Practice runs from noon to 2 p.m., followed by the pit-stop
competition (2:30-4:30 p.m.).
</P>
<P>
   Each driver's car will be equipped with the Suspension &AMP; Wheel
Energy Management System once practice begins. The Indy Racing
League made SWEMS, which is designed to minimize the chances of
wheel assemblies becoming detached during accidents, a requirement
on all IRL cars in light of the fatalities at Lowes Motor Speedway
May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Three spectators were killed at Lowes when debris from a wreck
flew into the grandstand.
</P>
<P>
   Dismore thinks SWEMS is a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no choice,'' he said. ``You can't hurt people and
that's the bottom line. You've got to do this and hope there's no
repercussions on the drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We assume a risk anyways. People are here to entertain their
families, so you've got to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
