</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Workers using sprinkler system to douse troublesome muck fires
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Workers fighting a vast, 10,000-acre
underground muck fire in the Florida Everglades began laying a
giant sprinkler system Wednesday to extinguish it.
</P>
<P>
   Using a crane and flatbed trucks, state rangers and South
Florida Water Management District workers brought in pumps capable
of pumping 25,000 gallons of water a minute through 150-foot
lengths of 30-inch pipe. Once up and running, the pumps will dump
about 144 million gallons a day on the week-old fire in the
Rotenberger Wildlife Management Area in southwestern Palm Beach
County.
</P>
<P>
   It could take another week to put out the smoldering fire that
has sent clouds of acrid smoke as far south as Miami and north to
Fort Pierce since Monday.
</P>
<P>
   When a muck fire broke out last month after a fire devoured
170,000 acres of saw grass in Broward County, rangers used similar
pumps. The muck burned for nearly a month after the initial fire,
and grew to only 2,500 acres.
</P>
<P>
   During the week, mostly in the morning and late afternoon when
sea breezes die down, the fire has pumped smoke into the air. Boca
Raton Middle School principal Dick Reed wore a mask during his
morning workout Wednesday: more than a dozen golfers at the
Sandalfoot Country Club cancelled morning rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't use air-conditioning so our windows were open and boy
it woke me up,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   Lightning ignited the fire Friday. But it went unnoticed as
winds blew from the east, fanning smoke into the unpopulated wilds.
Suddenly Monday, the wind shifted west and the fire spread to more
than 12,000 acres. Smoke hugged the coast. Or, more accurately, put
it in a choke hold. Ash fell like light snow in places. And schools
moved PE classes into the gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so thick our kids stayed indoors,'' said Jim Riley,
assistant principal at Wellington Landings Middle School.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, when winds shifted back to the east, rangers dropped
plastic balls packed with explosives on the fire's northern edge,
setting back fires. By afternoon, the surface fire was out, but the
muck fire continued to spread and proved more problematic. Unlike
surface fires that can be stopped by digging trenches or
back-burning, only water can extinguish fire in muck. And that
means big pumps.
</P>
<P>
   Muck fires also put out thicker smoke than mere brush fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's heavy and puts a lot of particulate matter in the air and
when plants burn on the surface, they burn cleaner,'' said forestry
spokeswoman Sue Congelosi. ``The muck fire is just continuously
puffing out smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers expect to get at least two pumps running today and will
lay lines in a horseshoe shape around the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Sea breezes that normally pick up by midmorning should lift
smoke on the coast during the day today and by tonight, winds
should shift to the northwest, ``so Palm Beach should be spared,''
National Weather Service meteorologist Tom Warner said. A 40
percent chance of rain is forecast for Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
