<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANCE-ARMSTRONG27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Armstrong, focus is off cancer and on cycling
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ This time two years ago, Lance Armstrong was
most worried about whether his monthly blood tests would show that
the chemotherapy had successfully rid his body of the malignant
tumors that had spread from his testicles to his stomach, lungs and
brain.
</P>
<P>
   Competitive cycling was out of the question, and he worried
whether he'd ever return to the elite level where he'd been only
months before. Still, he hosted the inaugural Ride for the Roses, a
noncompetitive cycling event, and invited some of the participants
to a casual gathering at his home on Lake Austin the night before.
Armstrong rode the full 100 miles, but physically, he wasn't close
to where he needed to be to return to competitive cycling.
</P>
<P>
   This time a year ago, the party had evolved into a fund-raiser
at a downtown hotel and Armstrong, whose cancer was in remission,
used his win in the first-ever Sprint 56-K Criterium through
downtown Austin to kick off what would be his abbreviated, but
successful cycling season.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the pre-event party, now called the Live to Ride
Gala, has grown so large that the Austin Convention Center is
needed for the expected 600 guests.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's goals have swelled as well.
</P>
<P>
   He has geared his entire season to participating in and possibly
winning the prestigious Tour de France, the three-week, almost
2,400-mile long stage race in July. And given that he had such a
successful 1998 season _ his highlight was an unexpected
fourth-place finish in the Tour of Spain, which is comparable to
the French tour _ most cycling experts think Armstrong has a
legitimate chance at faring well during the grueling French race.
</P>
<P>
   He'll race and probably win Friday's BMC Software Downtown
Criterium, a one-hour sprint event, and will play host to thousands
of riders who will participate in Sunday's Ride for the Roses.
He'll have an extra day to enjoy Austin before he and his pregnant
wife fly back to southern France, which will be their home for
eight months this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never really tried (to win) the tour,'' said the two-time
Olympian and former world champion who last competed in the world's
most prestigious cycling event in 1996, two months before he was
diagnosed with advanced testicular cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just always been focused on the spring races, the one-day
races. I started cycling after coming from swimming and triathlons.
Even the classics I won weren't a big goal for me at the time. And
riding (the tour) was never like a childhood dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, 28, has changed the focus of his training so that he
can maneuver the steeper stages of the tour that will take racers
through the Pyrenees and Alps. He has whittled his body fat to 6
percent on his way down to 4 percent, banking on the theory that
less weight will make it easier to pump through the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   He already has participated in two minicamps, a five-day one in
the Pyrenees and a weeklong stretch in the Alps, to prepare him for
the stages in the tour that often have cyclists climbing steep
slopes for 25-mile stretches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best descriptions of the climbs _ they're long,''
Armstrong said. ``Here in Austin, you might find a hill where you
climb for 1 mile. Over there, their climbs go up for 20 to 25
miles. It's a difficult effort, because hills in Austin, you can
sprint over.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong has won three stages on the Tour de France, but has
never finished in the top 30. His contract with the U.S. Postal
Service team will pay him up to $150,000 per stage win. His
contract, coupled with his product endorsement deals, will pay him
an extra $1 million if he wins the tour.
</P>
<P>
   And a stage win or victory overall would complete his cancer
comeback and make him bankable across the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he won the tour, his popularity would increase by a factor
of 100,'' said Bill Stapleton, Armstrong's agent and attorney. ``A
win would just broaden and deepen the Lance Armstrong brand. And it
will make him more marketable. Plus, if he wins the tour, I
guarantee you'll see him on the cover of Sports Illustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the publicity surrounding his illness, most of
Armstrong's teammates and competitors don't bring up his cancer
anymore, mainly because he has returned to such a high level in his
sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're to the point now where we forget about the cancer,''
Chris Vande Velde, a U.S. Postal teammate, said in Chicago earlier
this month. ``He never brings it up.''
</P>
<P>
   But Armstrong doesn't want people to forget how ill he was and
how far he has come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of my situation with cancer,'' Armstrong said. ``I
don't want to lose that relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
