<SLUG> BC-BBA-STRAWBERRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERRY GETS 18 MONTHS PROBATION FOR SOLICITING AND DRUG
POSSESSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a county courthouse in Tampa, Fla., Wednesday, Darryl
Strawberry offered a plea of no contest to charges of drug
possession and solicitation of prostitution and was given 18 months
probation as part of his sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Now his future as a baseball player rests with Major League
Baseball, which is expected to suspend Strawberry as a repeat
offender of its drug-aftercare program.
</P>
<P>
   A suspension of 90 days or more would all but end any chance of
the 37-year-old Strawberry's playing for the New York Yankees this
season, and in years to come there is no guarantee any team will
risk signing an aging slugger with a bad knee and a dubious history
of off-field incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry has been on administrative leave since April 24, and
should he be suspended for 60 days or less and be credited with
time served for his first month away from baseball, he could come
back to the Yankees in July or August. But the Yankees would have
to need him _ they currently have four other left-field candidates
and a full-time designated hitter _ and the calendar is working
against him.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, estimated that Strawberry would
need at least two to three weeks in the minors before being in
shape to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always welcomed back, as far as I'm concerned and the
rest of the team is concerned,'' said Chili Davis, the Yankees'
designated hitter. ``But it's not up to us. It's up to Major League
Baseball and the Yankees as to what is going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   And when baseball will act remains to be seen. Following
Strawberry's plea Wednesday, Commissioner Bud Selig issued a
statement, saying: ``Now that Darryl Strawberry's legal proceeding
has been resolved, I will promptly review all of the facts and
circumstances surrounding this matter in order to determine what
action is appropriate under baseball's drug policy. Prior to making
a determination I will consult with the medical advisers to Major
League Baseball and to the Major League Baseball Players
Association who recently evaluated Strawberry.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankee officials believe that the language in Strawberry's $2.5
million contract is so strong that his contract could have been
voided when he was arrested, and that Wednesday's sentencing
provides another chance for club officials to explore this
possibility, if they so choose.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager, said there were no
discussions Wednesday about voiding Strawberry's contract in the
wake of his sentencing. Like Strawberry, the Yankees and their
principal owner, George Steinbrenner, are waiting for Major League
Baseball to render a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry was charged April 14 after offering an undercover
police officer $50 for sex. During an ensuing search, 0.03 grams of
cocaine were found in his wallet. After being arrested, Strawberry
said that he was only joking with the undercover officer and that
the drugs belonged to an uncle of his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry ultimately pleaded no contest, however, and along
with his probation, Strawberry must provide 100 hours of community
service, pay $458 in court costs, continue to receive drug
treatment and submit to two drug tests a week (Strawberry already
undergoes multiple random tests every week from Major League
Baseball).
</P>
<P>
   Jack Espinosa Jr., a Florida circuit court judge, also told
Strawberry to stay out of bars, and asked prosecutors to provide
him with a map of places in the Tampa area that Strawberry should
avoid. If Strawberry meets the sentencing guidelines, the charges
will not be part of his permanent record.
</P>
<P>
   The judge lectured Strawberry. ``This isn't really about
baseball,'' Espinosa said. ``It isn't about your job, but about
you.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you stop producing, nobody will care about you. If this
is a picture of life after baseball, it's not pretty. This is only
an opportunity. I hope you make the best of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry at first declined to address the court, but then
expressed remorse. ``I'd just like to say I'm truly sorry,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
