</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAT-MANHEIM27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Confident Manheim caters to her crowd
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This only sounds like a real cheap shot, because, in
fact, it's meant as the ultimate compliment:
</P>
<P>
   That Camryn Manheim sure does fill up a room.
</P>
<P>
   It has absolutely nothing to do with her physical stature.
Although, let's face it, the 5-foot-10, size-22 actress didn't just
raise the issue, she smacked us over the head with it by entitling
her autobiography, ``Wake Up, I'm Fat!'' (Broadway Books, $23). No,
from the moment the Emmy-winning star of ABC's ``The Practice''
emerged from a back office in the Town Center Mall Lane Bryant
store Wednesday evening, looked left, then right at racks of
lingerie, and finally called out exuberantly to her public, ``OK,
where are you?!'' the place practically wasn't big enough to
contain all of her personality.
</P>
<P>
   Manheim, crowing to a crowd of about 75 people, who had begun
gathering some two hours early: ``I was going to have a chapter
called `Revenge _ The Following People I Hate.' Then I won the Emmy
and I thought `I don't know if I need a revenge chapter anymore!'''
Calling out to a fussy baby, just before she started to read an
excerpt aloud: ``This should take about eight minutes. Can you
handle that, sweet pea?'' And interrupting it all to loudly
instruct a certain newspaper's photographer, who'd thought he'd
kneel down and shoot up at her: ``You have to get up from the
floor, because that is a very unflattering position for me to be
in. In fact, I might even have you get up on an apple crate!''
</P>
<P>
   All of it delivered with the perfect blend of good humor and
self-assuredness her fans clearly were expecting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had her confidence,'' confessed Debbie Gibbons, 34,
who was first in line for Manheim's autographs on two copies of
``Wake Up.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Gibbons was doing fine on her own. She'd started out
second in line, but soon convinced her new best friend, Randall
Garrison of Acworth, to cede the top spot to her by promising to
try and get him a date with Manheim. Garrison, 34, came away with a
personalized copy of ``Wake Up,'' suggesting he fill out the _ we
kid you not _ ``Official Boyfriend Form'' on page 117.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was Garrison the only man in a crowd that eventually swelled
to several hundred people of all sizes, ages and races. All they
had in common, it seemed, was an appreciation for Manheim's
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to fight really hard for what you want,'' Manheim
said in an interview, just before heading out to inscribe ``Raise
some hell!'' in many fans' books. ``There aren't that many brass
rings to be had, and the person with the most confidence wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Can you handle that, sweet pea?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
