<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MEDICAID-HMOS-695&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. LETS STATE SHIFT POOR INTO MANAGED-CARE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Federal officials said Wednesday that New York
can begin moving more than 1 million poor people in New York City
into managed-care health plans as early as July in one of the most
ambitious efforts of its kind in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The state and the city have for two years been seeking approval
from Washington to begin the mandatory managed-care program in New
York City, where most people on Medicaid receive medical coverage
under the traditional fee-for-service system in which medical
providers are paid every time a patient is treated.
</P>
<P>
   Under a waiver approved Wednesday by the U.S. Department of
Health and Human Services, the state would be allowed to place as
many as 1.1 million Medicaid recipients in New York City into
managed-care programs during the next two years, according to state
and federal officials. People with chronic illnesses like AIDS or
diabetes would be exempt from the program. The federal government
has approved similar waivers in about a dozen other states.
</P>
<P>
   The administrations of both Gov. George Pataki and Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani have repeatedly touted managed care as a way to save
taxpayer dollars, largely because managed-care companies are paid a
set rate for each patient and, in turn, hold down costs by limiting
access to specialists and emphasizing preventive care.
</P>
<P>
   They also say care would be improved for the poor because they
would be assigned a regular doctor and would rely less on
emergency-room visits for basic care.
</P>
<P>
   But the effort has faced resistance by advocates for the poor
and Democratic lawmakers who are concerned that it would reduce
services to welfare recipients. Hospitals have also expressed
concern that the program could shortchange them on the cost of
services, because health-maintenance organizations will try to
negotiate low rates.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of Medicaid in New York state has grown to about $28
billion a year, the most expensive Medicaid program in the nation.
The state and local governments, primarily New York City, pay
roughly half of the program's cost, with the rest covered by the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government two years ago gave the state the
authority to begin placing Medicaid recipients into managed-care
programs, but has required it to do so gradually. Wednesday's
ruling affects only New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The state has already been requiring Medicaid recipients in a
dozen upstate counties to enroll in managed-care plans.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, where the bulk of the state's Medicaid
population lives, poor people have been given the option of
enrolling in managed-care plans.
</P>
<P>
   There are currently 620,000 Medicaid recipients in managed-care
plans throughout the state; nearly 400,000 of them living in New
York City, where recipients, until now, had the option to enroll
voluntarily in managed-care plans, according to state officials.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the federal government was warmly praised by
officials in the Giuliani and the Pataki administrations, which
have made managed care for Medicaid recipients one of the keys to
their health-care initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great victory for the governor and for New York
City,'' said Dennis Whalen, the acting state health commissioner.
``This waiver will give millions of medically needy New Yorkers the
medical homes and the quality health care they need to live long
healthy lives.''
</P>
<P>
   However, city and state officials said they needed to review
some of the conditions that the federal government included in the
approval. Federal officials said they would allow the state to move
ahead with the managed-care program in the city only after it
established certain protections for recipients, like establishing
an appeals process for decisions made by their managed-care plans.
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid recipients have a choice of managed-care plans in which
they can choose to enroll.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government is also requiring the state and the city
to undertake an extensive public information campaign intended to
alert people with AIDS or chronic illnesses that they are exempt
from being placed into managed care, because of the gravity of
their illnesses.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Wednesday's decision came after federal investigators spent
months reviewing whether the city had a sufficiently extensive
network of health plans and doctors to absorb the hundreds of
thousands of Medicaid recipients who will be sent into managed
care.
</P>
<P>
   The extensive federal review was in part prompted by concerns
among advocates for the poor and the disabled, who worried that
many managed-care companies would try to cut corners and reduce
services, particularly given the high cost of treating Medicaid
patients, who on average are sicker than others.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for the poor and the disabled said Wednesday they were
pleased that the federal government had placed conditions on the
program. ``The federal government isn't taking an `anything goes'
attitude,'' said Michael Kink, legislative counsel for Housing
Works, a group serving people with AIDS. ``They are being careful.
And there are plenty of good reasons to be careful when the health
care of more than a million poor and disabled New Yorkers is at
stake.''
</P>
<P>
   The government's decision comes as many of the city's
economically beleaguered hospitals are raising concerns that the
advent of managed care among the state's Medicaid population,
particularly in New York City, will cause them greater financial
distress and potential ruin.
</P>
<P>
   Many hospital officials contend they are already facing huge
financial headaches as they find themselves caught between
increasingly powerful HMOs that demand reduced rates for their
private customers, and state and federal officials who are cutting
billions of dollars in hospital payments.
</P>
<P>
   The hospitals are concerned that health-maintenance plans will
also demand reduced rates for their Medicaid customers,
particularly since the plans themselves have been complaining that
the state is not adequately reimbursing them for the services they
provide recipients.
</P>
</TEXT>
