<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-BOSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNOBLAUCH AND O'NEILL GIVE YANKS SIGNS OF LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Paul O'Neill will be the cover boy of any New York
Yankees slump, for helmet-launching and bat-throwing translate
easily into signs of frustration. When O'Neill and the Yankees are
losing, anybody who can identify a flying water bottle will know
it.
</P>
<P>
   When Chuck Knoblauch is struggling, when he is totally consumed
by his failures and he is finally unable to repress his emotion,
Knoblauch shakes his head ever so slightly on his way back to the
dugout _ a more subtle but no less important barometer of how the
Yankees' offense is doing.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch is the leadoff hitter and O'Neill bats third, and each
must hit for the Yankees to win, and there are signs that both are
emerging from their respective slumps. Each had two hits Wednesday
and contributed to a five-run rally that was highlighted by Tino
Martinez's grand slam in the Yankees' 8-3 thumping of the Boston
Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez (5-4) pitched seven shutout innings and beat
Boston for the second time in a week. The Yankees are within one
and a half games of the Red Sox in the American League East. ``We
won a good game today,'' O'Neill said, ``and that makes everybody
feel better.''
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra of Boston, who split his finger underneath the
fingernail fielding a ball on Tuesday, sat out Wednesday's game and
may also miss Thursday night's matchup, in which Roger Clemens will
pitch against the Red Sox for the first time since joining the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   On May 1 Knoblauch was batting .381 and O'Neill .304 and the
Yankees' record was 15-7. Each fell into a horrible slump, and the
Yankees lost 11 of their next 19 games. Cause and effect: O'Neill
was 1-for-25 (.040) with runners in scoring position from May 1
through May 23, and Knoblauch was 6-for-62, attempting a stolen
base once in 22 games.
</P>
<P>
   Slumps gnaw at both players, but the symptoms manifest
themselves differently. O'Neill lingers at his locker after a bad
game and engages teammates, telling them he has never felt so
awful, almost inviting others to reassure him. Knoblauch can be
introverted, silently moving through the clubhouse with a blank
expression as he proceeds to his next workout station; nobody
trains harder, a club official noted Wednesday. Intensity can
consume them.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday and Tuesday, O'Neill sat and chatted in Manager Joe
Torre's office, talking about hitting, talking about slumps.
Knoblauch made an internal decision to alter his approach at the
plate: forget about mechanics, forget about where his hands are
supposed to be. Just see the ball and hit the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you can get too caught up in focusing on the way you
think you should hit,'' Knoblauch said. ``Your mind has to be on
the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch smashed a home run leading off Tuesday's game, and two
batters later O'Neill laced a triple _ only the second time since
May 2 that Knoblauch and O'Neill had reached base in the same
inning on a hit or walk. With excellent control of his fastball and
curve, Hernandez protected a 1-0 lead into the fifth inning, a
frighteningly thin margin of error for a struggling team.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch led off the Yankees' half of the fifth by rolling a
single through the middle, and Derek Jeter followed with a single
of his own against Mark Portugal of Boston. This is what the
Yankees did so well in 1998, getting a couple runners on base and
pressuring the opposing pitcher and forcing them into mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill leaned over the plate to line a changeup to right field,
Knoblauch stopping at third. Bases loaded, nobody out, and Portugal
limped to the mound after backing up the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams fouled off two pitches before waiting for
Portugal to throw him a strike, and with a 3-2 count, he drew a
walk, forcing Knoblauch home with the Yankees' second run. John
Wasdin relieved Portugal to pitch to Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' first baseman had popped out with the bases loaded
in his previous at-bat, but in this situation, he said, ``I was
obviously in the driver's seat.'' Martinez knew Wasdin had to be
aggressive and throw strikes. Even when Martinez fell behind by
0-2, he figured Wasdin would attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston right-hander tried blistering the corner with a
fastball, but it drifted over the middle of the plate and Martinez
pounced. The ball soared into the third upper deck in right field,
and, his teammate David Cone said later, it was if all the Yankees
were relieved, finally having all the hits and pitching and defense
they needed, for one day.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 45,800 called for Martinez to take a bow, the
culmination of a good day. Knoblauch grinned and looked relaxed,
O'Neill slammed his bat just once; in the span of 48 hours, Torre
said, it was nice to see O'Neill's mood improve.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
