<SLUG> BC-BOEING-DISCRIMINATION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPONENTS OF BOEING BIAS SUIT SETTLEMENT WIN RIGHT TO REVIEW PACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Minority employees at The Boeing Co. will have to wait
at least four months for their share of a $15 million settlement of
charges of discrimination because a federal judge has allowed
opponents of the pact to investigate allegations that it doesn't go
far enough.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 22, Boeing announced it was settling two class-action
lawsuits brought by a group of African American employees who
charged they were discriminated against at the aerospace giant.
U.S. District Court Judge John Coughenour weighed the fairness of
the proposal at a hearing Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Coughenour has given opponents of the pact four months to
investigate concerns about how the settlement was structured,
including the involvement of civil rights leader Jesse Jackson in
settling the case, according to lawyers familiar with the case. The
federal judge has scheduled another hearing for Sept. 23, after
lawyers depose a handful of witnesses, which could include Boeing's
chairman and chief executive officer, Phil Condit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allows us the opportunity to get to the bottom of some of
the suspicions the objectors have,'' said Mary Roberts, a lawyer at
the firm of Frank Rosen Freed Garfinkel &AMP; Roberts, who is
representing opponents of the settlement along with Philadelphia
lawyer Alan Epstein.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the $15 million in payments, Boeing promised in
the settlement to improve the way it selects and promotes workers,
adopt a new system for handling complaints about discrimination,
harassment or retaliation, and hire a consultant to assess how well
the changes work.
</P>
<P>
   Some employees, led by Epstein and Roberts, say the proposal
doesn't go far enough, charging it lacks the teeth to enforce the
changes. They also questioned whether the monetary award is large
enough, Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, lawyers also won the right to question Condit, or his
representative, about the possibility that money was sent to an
associate of Jackson who could have a role in overseeing the
agreement, and a possible meeting between Condit and one of the
class representatives, Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Boeing denied the company ever paid Jackson
to visit its plants. Jackson could not be reached for comment on
the claim.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing said it committed _ before crafting the settlement _ to
contribute $50,000 to a Jackson-sponsored project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the accusations as put forward by Alan Epstein are
based on heresay and have no bearing in the fairness and
reasonableness of the proposed settlement,''said Peter Conte, a
Boeing spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Conte added that Boeing already has begun implementing some of
the changes called for in the agreement. Under terms of the 35-page
consent degree, Boeing denied it ever engaged in any pattern of
racial discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the original plaintiffs praised the ruling because
it limited the scope of the hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was a good ruling,'' said Oscar Desper III, one
of the lead attorneys for the employees.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits were filed last year. The initial suit was brought
by 43 black workers who said discrimination was common at Boeing
plants in the Puget Sound area.
</P>
<P>
   Later, black workers for Boeing in Philadelphia and in Wichita,
Kan., joined the suit. A second suit also was started.
</P>
<P>
   The suits complained of a racially hostile work environment in
which blacks were the object of slurs, crude drawings and
intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 13,000 blacks worked for Boeing around the country as of
January. The total work force is currently about 217,000.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed settlement, 20,000 current and former
employees of Boeing and its subsidiary companies would be eligible
to share in $7.3 million in payments.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing also agreed to spend $3.65 million on improved training
and changes in the way it selects managers and makes other
promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Epstein is expected to receive $200,000. Lawyers for the
original plaintiffs, spread among three law firms, will likely
receive $3 million in legal fees, according to Desper.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing must also pay $750,000 over three years to finance the
monitoring of the settlement, Desper said.
</P>
<P>
   Material from The Associated Press and Post-Intelligencer
reporter James Wallace is included in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
