<SLUG> BC-SUMO-AMERICANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND AMERICAN IN TOP RANK AS DIVERSITY HITS SUMO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Hawaii)   (bl)  
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ A second American muscled his way into the top ranks of
sumo Wednesday. The Musashimaru, a Hawaiian whose given name is
Fiamalu Penitani, became the 67th yokozuna, or grand champion, in
the 300-year modern history of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   But his promotion had a larger significance. To gain his title,
he had to beat another American, Akebono, the shy giant, also from
Hawaii, who became Japan's first non-Japanese yokozuna in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four yokozunas fighting, two are the Americans and the
others are brothers from a family with a long history in sumo, a
lineup that reflects the growing diversity of the sport. Argentina,
Brazil, Korea and Mongolia are represented among the sumo ranks,
despite persistent debate over whether the inclusion of
non-Japanese in this most Japanese of sports has cheapened the
contest.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts say they believe that the Americans' arrival, in
particular, many of whom have the size and girth of their
Polynesian and Samoan ancestors, has given weight too much of a
role in winning. The complaints say that increases injuries and
lessens the importance of agility and strength, the traditional
determinants of skill.
</P>
<P>
   The two Japanese grand champions, Takanohana and Wakanohana,
retired early from the tournament that ended Sunday because of
injuries. Akebono sat on the sidelines of the two previous
tournaments because of a bad back.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, however, sentiment seems to be changing, as
Musashimaru's promotion demonstrates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little by little, the Japanese public has become accustomed to
foreign rikishi,'' or wrestlers, said Andy Adams, publisher and
editor of Sumo World, a magazine that follows the sport. ``Some of
the foreigners have become quite popular.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside Musashimaru's stable _ that is, the place where a
collection of wrestlers allied to the same coach eat, sleep and
practice _ the neighbors seemed more than ready to embrace him as
one of their own, even though the lei around his neck was clearly a
nod to his origins.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really looks like a statue of Saigo Takamori,'' said
Ogiwara Mitsuo, referring to a hero who played a role in the
overthrow of the Tokugawa shogunate that led to the establishment
of modern Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Konishiki, another Hawaiian and the first foreigner to achieve
the big time in sumo, is the star of series of popular television
commercials for the beverage company Suntory and is a frequent
guest on talk shows. He retired from sumo last year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another Hawaiian, Azumazeki Oyakata, known in his wrestling
days as Takamiyama and before that as Jesse Kuhaulua, now presides
over his own stable. Neither, however, attained yokozuna status, a
failure that in Konishiki's case led to charges of discrimination
against the Sumo Association. Konishiki won two consecutive
tournaments in 1992, one of two ways in which a second-rank
wrestler becomes a yokozuna, but was never awarded the grand
champion's title. Two wildly popular yokozunas who preceded him,
Chiyonafuji and Kitanoumi, earned grand champion status with lesser
records, although legal under the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many believe Akebono's elevation to yokozuna in 1993,
although clearly backed by the required number and type of
victories, was in part a result of that criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Musashimaru's victory Sunday, achieved with a determined shove
that sent Akebono over the edge of the ring onto his back, gave him
the requisite two consecutive tournament victories.
</P>
<P>
   But some critics, including the association chairman, Katsuo
Tokitsukaze, questioned his qualifications, saying his latest
triumph was less than decisive because he had not had to face the
two other yokozuna, who were out with injuries. Tokitsukaze also
pointed to the weak tournament that Musashimaru had in January,
when he lost seven of 15 bouts.
</P>
<P>
   Musashimaru, who weighs 473 pounds, struggled throughout most of
last year, grappling as much with his fears of fame and the
spotlight as with his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a little worried about all of the responsibility
that goes along with being yokozuna,'' Konishiki said in an
interview at the time. ``I think his problem is as much in his head
as with his fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   After sumo wrestlers attain grand champion status, they cannot
have a losing tournament, which places tremendous pressure on them
to perform. In addition to addition to practice and workouts, grand
champions are the public face of sumo. As such, they face a
grueling schedule of personal appearances for charities and
benefits, as well as attending events on behalf of sumo sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``A yokozuna is a very busy guy,'' Adams of Sumo World said.
``He really needs a kind of a secretary to take calls, sort through
various requests and maintain a schedule.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
