<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL APPROVES STADIUM FINANCING DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The National Football League on &UR;  &LR; Wednesday approved a
plan to finance about half of the New England Patriots' $285
million replacement for Foxboro Stadium at no cost to team owner
Robert Kraft, who said construction on a state-of-the-art facility
could begin by the end of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Under the financing arrangement, the Patriots would have 15
years to repay the league up to $150 million using revenues from
luxury seating. If he sells the team before then, he must repay the
balance of the loan himself.
</P>
<P>
   Although the league granted the loan, and state legislation
authorizing $70 million in infrastructure funding was signed into
law Monday, there still are hurdles in the team's goal of
completing the open-air stadium by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Two local issues that need to be addressed by Foxborough town
officials: The new stadium would be taller than town zoning
currently allows, requiring a variance, and the town, which owns
the footprint of land beneath the stadium, would need to trade that
land for an adjacent parcel owned by Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   Also, NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue said he would travel to
Boston next month to make sure the sales of luxury seating at the
proposed stadium are on track -- a factor the league says is vital
to its financing plan, approved here 28 to 1, with two owners
declining to vote. The league wants all of the luxury seating
pre-sold because any shortfall in seating revenue that would repay
the loan would come from TV revenue, which all 31 teams share
equally.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft was all smiles Wednesday when he spoke publicly for the
first time since walking away last month from what would have been
a lucrative stadium deal in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling the years he and his sons spent in Section 217 as
season ticket-holders at Foxboro Stadium, Kraft was nostalgic about
keeping the Patriots at their home of nearly 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where my boys grew up,'' Kraft said. ``I have a great
emotional feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   The low-key events at a suburban hotel here were yet another
milestone in Kraft's five-year, politically-charged quest to
replace what has become one of the oldest and smallest football
facilities in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited because of the potential to bring to an end this
saga,'' Kraft said. ``I hope we can do it in a classy manner.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about his feelings toward Connecticut, whose attorney
general is threatening legal action based on suspicions that the
team was negotiating with Massachusetts while still engaged to the
Hartford deal, Kraft shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no comment on anything to do with Connecticut because
of the sensitivity,'' Kraft said.
</P>
<P>
   He said having a modern facility will have economic benefits --
including $15 million in taxes generated just from construction --
as well as psychic ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft, while acknowledging there are local issues that still
need to be addressed, said he is hopeful the rest of the process
will run smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been doing business with the town of Foxborough since
1985,'' he said. ``They've been cooperative with us.'' He did add,
however, that completing the facility by 2001 would be difficult
regardless.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft's son Jonathan said the new stadium will have 80 luxury
suites, 40 fewer than earlier projections put forth by the civic
group who rallied to keep the team in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   However, those suites will be among the largest in the NFL, with
some stretching to 1,800 square feet. The smaller ones will be 900
square feet, still larger than the biggest suites now at Foxboro
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue said the financing policy, formulated in March and
adopted Wednesday, will apply to Philladelphia, Denver, and New
England. The owner of the Cincinatti Bengals voted against the
measure. The owners of the Oakland Raiders and the Buffalo Bills
abstained from voting.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we did today inches toward a commitment we made to the
business community (in Boston) in return for their commitment to
us,'' Tagliabue said.
</P>
<P>
   About $6 million worth of luxury seating has been reserved so
far for the new Foxborough stadium, according to NFL figures.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, owners throughout the league said they were pleased
with Kraft's decision to stay in Massachusetts and happy the trend
of franchises fleeing to smaller markets with bigger stadium deals
was turning around.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and the family have a strong feeling for Massachusetts,''
Bob Tisch, owner of the New York Giants, said of Kraft's pulling
out of the $374 million publicly-financed Connecticut agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I obviously think it's a great financial sacrifice to the
Kraft family,'' added Jerry Richardson, owner of the Carolina
Panthers. ``I know he had a heartache over making that decision.
...It's a huge disappointment for the people of Connecticut.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
