<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUTALITY TRIAL RESUMES AFTER PLEA, DESPITE CALL FOR A MISTRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also NY-LOUIMA-VOLPE) 
(mk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A day after Justin Volpe interrupted his trial to
plead guilty to torturing Abner Louima in a Brooklyn police
station, the judge refused to declare a mistrial Wednesday and
resumed the testimony against three other police officers and a
sergeant also charged in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Before calling in the jury, which had not been at the courthouse
Tuesday, Judge Eugene Nickerson of U.S. District Court in Brooklyn
heard from a lawyer for one of the remaining defendants, Sgt.
Michael Bellomo, who said Volpe's guilty plea was grounds for a
mistrial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it has prejudiced my client's ability to get a fair
trial,'' said the lawyer, John Patten, who suggested that the
admission of guilt by Volpe could subconsciously persuade the
jurors to believe that if he had admitted guilt, the other
defendants must also be guilty. Joseph Tacopina, a lawyer for
another remaining defendant, Officer Thomas Wiese, said he was
joining the mistrial motion.
</P>
<P>
   Nickerson swiftly denied the motion without comment, instead
telling the jurors when they entered the courtroom that Volpe ``has
pleaded guilty to various counts of the indictment and, therefore,
he will not be present in court during the remainder of the
trial.'' He added that the fact that Volpe had pleaded guilty
``can't be used by you as evidence in determining whether the other
defendants'' are guilty of any of the charges against them.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors, who had been regularly instructed by the judge not
to read, watch or listen to news reports about the highly
publicized case, showed no reaction to the judge's words, other
than glancing at the defense table, where Volpe's legacy was
conspicuous in the empty chairs that he and his lawyers had
occupied.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution and all the defense lawyers except Patten had
asked the judge to make this statement to the jury. Later, the
lawyer for another defendant, Officer Charles Schwarz, told
reporters that they had all agreed on the need for such a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   The plea, he said, ``is so pervasive in the public mind that
rather than have it hanging in the air, the court should address
the fact that it happened and instruct the jurors as to its
significance involving the remaining defendants.''
</P>
<P>
   More typically, criminal lawyers say, when a defendant pleads
guilty in midtrial the judge will tell the jurors only that the
person is no longer in the case and will instruct the panel not to
speculate why.
</P>
<P>
   As testimony resumed Wednesday, the prosecution _ whose case
could end as early as Thursday with Volpe no longer a defendant _
questioned such witnesses as forensic experts who said that DNA
found in blood in a patrol car and on the pants Louima was wearing
when he was brutalized in Flatbush in August 1997 was consistent
with his DNA.
</P>
<P>
   In a case that sent shock waves through the city and raised
racial tensions, prosecutors say that Louima, a 32-year-old black
man, was beaten in a police car by four white police officers _
Volpe and Officers Wiese, Charles Schwarz and Thomas Bruder _ after
being arrested in a street melee outside a nightclub. They say that
when he was brought to the 70th Precinct station house, Volpe and
Schwarz tortured him in a restroom there, with Volpe ramming a
stick into his rectum, inflicting major internal injuries, while
Schwarz held him down. Bellomo is charged with trying to cover up
the beating in the police car.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many defendants who plead guilty in a case, Volpe, who
was immediately jailed and dismissed from the force after entering
his guilty plea Tuesday, is not expected to appear as a witness for
the prosecution. His guilty plea does not involve a deal with the
prosecution, which rejected his overture for a plea bargain last
week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
