<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICER SHOOTS YOUTH, 16, AFTER A CHASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An unarmed 16-year-old youth was shot and critically
wounded early Wednesday morning by a police officer from the
department's Street Crime Unit after a chase and a brief struggle
on a dark Bronx street, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said that the teen-ager, Dante Johnson, had run
from three police officers who wanted to question him and a
companion because they thought the youths might be armed.
Investigators said it was not clear whether the officer fired the
shot intentionally or his gun went off by accident during the
struggle.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Johnson was unarmed drew more criticism of the
Street Crime Unit, which has been under intense scrutiny since four
of its officers fired 41 bullets at Amadou Diallo, an unarmed
immigrant, on Feb. 4, killing him.
</P>
<P>
   The latest incident began around 12:20 a.m. Wednesday when three
uniformed officers from the unit saw a large group of people
gathered near Richman Plaza in the Morris Heights section of the
Bronx, the police said. The officers, who were in an unmarked car
but were in uniform, saw Johnson and a friend of his, Kyle
Thompson, standing apart from the crowd, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   As the officers watched, one of the youths adjusted something in
his waistband, leading the officers to believe he might be carrying
a gun, a police official said. When the officers approached the
two, though, one cursed and both fled, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Terrence O'Toole, 41, and Officer Michael Fraterrigo, 27,
jumped out of the car and gave chase, catching Thompson, 16, on an
overpass of the Major Deegan Expressway, the police said. Officer
Mark Conway, 32, drove after Johnson, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Conway caught up with Johnson near the intersection of Sedgwick
and Undercliff avenues, the police said, and reached out of the
driver-side window to grab him. Then, several witnesses told
investigators, there was a struggle. A bus driver who was parked
nearby told detectives that Johnson appeared to be trying to
wriggle out of his jacket, police officials said.
</P>
<P>
   During this struggle, Conway pulled out his service pistol,
Inspector Michael Collins, a police spokesman, said. A single shot
was fired, Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   The bullet struck Johnson in the abdomen, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   After the shooting, Johnson and his friend, Thompson, were
handcuffed and detained by the police, but by late afternoon their
arrests were voided, the police said. The Bronx district attorney's
office is investigating the shooting and will present the case to a
grand jury, said Steven Reed, a spokesman for the office.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a student at Evander Childs High School, was in
critical but stable condition at Lincoln Hospital on Wednesday
night, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   A police official said that Johnson had a sealed criminal record
for an arrest that occurred a few weeks before his 16th birthday in
April. The official said that the youth's mother, Sharon Johnson,
told detectives that he had recently missed several probation
appointments and that this circumstance might explain why he ran
from the officers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 2246EDT &QL; 
