A2647 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-CYCLING27-COX     05-26 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-CYCLING27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Given a black eye by Tour de France scandals, many hope cycling
is on the comeback trail
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Last year was a bumpy one for cycling. The
sport's showcase event, the Tour de France, degenerated into ugly
sideshows of police raids and rider protests. The sport's
top-ranked team, Festina, was given the boot, six others quit the
tour, and there was considerable concern that sponsors would also
start pulling out of the drug-tainted sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was bad for cycling,'' Lance Armstrong said. ``Perhaps it
was just a couple of bad apples in the group, but it wasn't good.''
</P>
<P>
   Optimism, however, has staged a quick rally.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hendry of the British Cycling Federation voiced the hopes of
many when he said, ``It's good news for cycling in the long term
and for future participants if it's seen to be a real new broom
sweeping the sport clean.''
</P>
<P>
   Rich Wanninger, a spokesman for USA Cycling, added, ``I think it
was a disappointment and it was unfortunate it happened. The Tour
de France is the crown jewel of the sport. But we're trying to turn
that negative into a positive. It's an opportunity to get everybody
out who isn't playing by the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Wanninger pointed out that the controversy overshadowed some
encouraging results in France. ``The U.S. had some of its finest
performances as a country,'' Wanninger said. ``Bobby Julich was
third. Every rider posted a career best.''
</P>
<P>
   Cycling in the United States is also still trying to overcome
the twin hits it took after 1996. That's when the final Tour DuPont
was held and when Motorola ended the sponsorship of its prestigious
cycling team. DuPont had sponsored its 11-day tour for six years.
It was the only international stage race in this country and was
cycling's third-richest race.
</P>
<P>
   USA Cycling, however, said that revenues are up in the most
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've picked up sponsors,'' Wanninger said. ``BMC is a case in
point. They've come on board as a title sponsor for $1 million.''
</P>
<P>
   The BMC Software Downtown Criterium will be held Friday night as
part of the weekend-long cycling festivities here. The
Houston-based software company will sponsor a race in that city in
September. BMC has a five-year commitment to cycling and will have
four events by 2000 as Boston and San Jose will be added to the
mix.
</P>
<P>
   The BMC criterium here is one of 15 events comprising the Saturn
USPRO Cycling Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an enhancement of what we had,'' Wanninger said. ``The
prize money has increased. It gives the younger riders and the ones
that don't have the connections or finances to ride in Europe an
opportunity to compete here against the elite. You'll see past
Olympians, ones who'll be competing in 2000 and others who'll be
competing in 2004.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some talent out there. I think the sport is on the
upswing,'' said Bill Stapleton, Armstrong's agent and chairman of
the U.S. Olympic Committee Athletes' Advisory Council.
</P>
<P>
   Stapleton said a couple of things would help determine the
health of cycling in the United States, including the performance
of Armstrong and whether any U.S. corporation will step up to
sponsor a major player in the Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong will ride for the U.S. Postal Service when he competes
in the Tour de France this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Postal Service does very good for what they spend,''
Stapleton said. ``They probably spend $3 (million) or $4 million
dollars. The top European teams spend $6 million or more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a professional sport. There's a lot of money involved,''
Armstrong said in explaining the drug problems on last year's Tour
de France. ``But it's no different than any other sport. I don't
think it's as bad as people made it out to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Stapleton said the drugs that have been used in cycling by some
include human growth hormone and erythropoietin (EPO). Those are
the same performance-boosters used in other sports. Currently there
are no tests in use that detect these substances. Even random,
unannounced testing doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   But at the world cycling championships in October, the sport's
international governing body said it planned to create a $1.4
million fund for research and increased testing. Festina, the
Spanish watchmaker's team that took the biggest hit, announced it
would spend $725,000 to fight doping while remaining as a sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been some questions about whether there's going to be
a full recovery,'' Stapleton said. ``There's some question about
whether the Spanish teams are going to race at the Tour de France.
But it's too important. They'll probably resolve the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The sport's health on an international level can't be fully
assessed until the Tour de France is completed this summer. But on
the homefront, some of the bumps are smoothing out.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
