u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT &LR;      05-26 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS TO USE CAMBY TO KEEP UP WITH PACERS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last June, when the Knicks sent their beloved Mr.
Hustle, Charles Oakley, to the Toronto Raptors for the gangly yet
graceful Marcus Camby, they named the Indiana Pacers as the
impetus.
</P>
<P>
   In eliminating the Knicks from the Eastern Conference semifinals
in five games a month earlier, the Pacers' younger, more athletic
forwards had sped around Oakley and his slow-footed teammates for
rebounds and dunks at crucial junctures.
</P>
<P>
   With their aging frontcourt players certain to lose yet another
step during the off-season, the Knicks' management moved to catch
the Pacers by acquiring Camby, a 6-foot-11-inch runner and jumper
with outstanding quickness and athleticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``What drove this was, `Are we a step behind or a step ahead of
Indiana?''' Dave Checketts, the president of Madison Square Garden,
said at the time. ``As much as Knicks fans are going to miss Oak,
they have to ask themselves that question too. We agonized over
this decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby's ascension into one of the Knicks' most dangerous players
during the playoffs has made it clear that the trade was a good
one. But just how good will be determined by the performance of
Camby, and more importantly, the team he was procured to energize,
in the upcoming conference finals against the Pacers that begin
Sunday in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to cause them problems because he can play multiple
positions,'' said Chris Childs, who plays in the Knicks' vaunted
second unit with Camby. ``The kid is just phenomenal at blocking
shots, helping defensively, being able to guard smaller guys,
adding an extra dimension on the fast break. He's a phenomenal
young player and he's going to play a big part in how this series
plays out.''
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, before Camby began dunking and blocking shots
with abandon, the third-year forward was no more likely to be one
of the team's key contributors than the Knicks were to make it past
the second round of the playoffs. Both player and team were
floundering, the player so badly that coach Jeff Van Gundy hardly
used him against the conference's best and most physical teams _
Miami, Orlando and Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Camby's early unwillingness to play with pain cost him playing
time against Indiana, as he totaled just 21 minutes in the teams'
three games this season. He missed the Pacers' 108-95 victory on
April 4 with a strained groin and played only eight minutes in the
Pacers' 94-71 victory on May 2 because of a bruised shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   But by the start of the Knicks first-round matchup with Miami
Heat, whose toughness kept Van Gundy from playing Camby at all
during an earlier meeting on March 2, Camby had shed much of his
soft and tentative image.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's had a very good year,'' Van Gundy said. ``The
main part was the mental part about staying strong when it wasn't
going exactly the way he had hoped.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Checketts saw Camby _ who looks like a stick-figure at
225 pounds _ as the answer to Indiana's forward tandem of Antonio
Davis and Dale Davis, the Knicks' coaches are not so sure. Camby
definitely enjoys an advantage in quickness and agility, but the
Davis' bruising style could render him ineffective if the series is
a plodding one decided in the halfcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely have to try and get out and run,'' Camby said.
``They're an old team. We have quicker feet. We have to take
advantage of that on the break.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their success against the Knicks in last season's
playoffs, the Pacers are reportedly glad that Oakley, who perhaps
banged even harder than the Davises, is gone. When Camby got wind
of that, he said: ``Well, we'll see. It's a long series. They have
to beat us four times. I'll be there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
