<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2649 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEACHER-PAY-RAISE27-C     05-26 1367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-PAY-RAISE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Low pay, burnout generating new dropout problem in Texas
 &HT;    By A. Phillips Brooks
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ McCallum High School math teacher Kim Meyer is
calling it quits after eight years of teaching.
</P>
<P>
   She is leaving the profession even as lawmakers are poised to
pass the biggest teacher pay raise in the state's history.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer says not even a $3,000 annual pay raise _ the amount the
Legislature is considering _ is enough. Her classes, she says, are
too large to properly educate students. Her pay is too low for the
12 hours a day she puts in, including morning and evening
tutorials. Her retirement and health benefits are not enough to
keep her in the profession her mother practiced for a lifetime. ``I
am very much overworked, stressed out and frustrated about pay and
working conditions,'' said Meyer, 34, whose geometry classes this
year averaged 30 students. ``The intangible rewards are not there
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer, who hopes to land a job in the high-tech industry, is not
alone. About 19,000 of 280,000 teachers will leave the classroom
this year, according to the Texas Education Agency _ either for
other jobs or to retire, and Texas already has a shortage of
teachers in some subject areas. The shortage is expected to worsen
as fewer college graduates choose the teaching profession and as
public school enrollment grows by 65,000 new students a year. Those
and other factors, such as retirement of baby boomers from
teaching, will leave Texas 66,000 teachers short by 2020, according
to projections by University of Texas researchers. Texas already
has a shortage of teachers in some subject areas _ mathematics,
science and foreign languages; in two decades the shortage will
span virtually all academic fields.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Paul Sadler, chairman of the House Public Education
Committee, has touted the proposed pay raise as a reward for
teachers who have helped Texas students improve their performance
on the state's standardized test. But he concedes the raise won't
be enough to make a dent in the worsening shortage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it enough? No, it will never be. Our society has placed a
premium on some crazy things,'' said Sadler, D-Henderson. ``We pay
more money for somebody to beat the brains out of somebody and call
himself a boxer than we pay for somebody who tries to educate the
brains.''
</P>
<P>
   A projected teacher shortage looms over Texas as researchers
increasingly point to the teacher as perhaps the most important
factor in student achievement or failure. Because Texas schools are
now more equitably financed, gaps in spending per pupil have been
closing. Furthermore, long-standing inequities in school
facilities, such as libraries, computers, science labs and
educational materials are disappearing. What now stands between a
good education and a poor one, many say, is the teacher.
</P>
<P>
   This is the third session in a row that lawmakers have raised
teachers' pay, though previous increases have mostly affected
teachers paid the state minimum salary. Even with those increases,
Texas teachers' annual average salary of $34,335 lags $6,000 behind
the national average, according to the National Education
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer says it would take a lot more than $3,000 a year to entice
her to stay. And, for her, money alone would not be enough.
``Seriously? About $5,000 to $10,000 more a year and class sizes
under 25 students would do it for me,'' she said. The Legislature
never seriously considered not paying for a teacher pay raise this
year. The debate was over how much the raise should be and how it
could be accomplished. The pay raise, part of a larger education
spending bill, is pending in a conference committee and still faces
votes in the full House and Senate. Though expected to pass, the
raise is not universally praised.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Levin, executive vice president of the American Freedom
Institute, a conservative policy group, says Texas teachers make
more than the average family in Texas. In 1996, Texas teachers'
average income was $33,468, while the average family's income was
$33,072. ``It is a myth that all teachers in Texas are sorely
underpaid,'' Levin said. ``It is far from clear that all teachers
should be automatically entitled to a raise regardless of their
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   But pay is not the only issue driving teachers from the
classroom, according to David Henderson, a professor of education
at Sam Houston State University who has tracked such issues since
1980. More teachers say working conditions _ large classes,
burnout, paperwork and hassles _ rather than pay are the reason
they are looking for employment elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The morale in schools is not very high, and the pay is not
either,'' Henderson said. ``Teachers have stress and burnout. They
are under tremendous pressure to raise students' scores, and they
are concerned that they are teaching the test. All for that little
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson's study found that most teachers, 46 percent, left the
profession in 1980 because of money, while 27 percent left because
of working conditions. By 1998, that had reversed, with 39 percent
citing working conditions and 26 percent citing pay. Meanwhile,
retirements have increased considerably, from 5 percent in 1980 to
28 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Former teachers responding to one survey said it would take
about $14,000 to draw them back to the classroom. The 500 teachers
in the 1999 survey of 500 commissioned by the state education
agency and education groups cited low pay and benefits, frustration
with their jobs and classroom discipline problems that hinder
teaching as reasons for leaving. Critics say teachers should not be
paid more money. After all, the argument goes, teachers work
shorter days than most _ 8 to 3 _ and only 10 months of the year.
Levin estimates teachers actually earn $43,235 annually when
adjusted for a 240-day working year. That infuriates teachers, who
say their profession has moved beyond being the second job for a
mom who wants to be home with the kids after school or during
summer break.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the toughest job on the planet. But you get the
feeling that most of society does not care,'' said Jackson Pace, a
teacher at the Austin's LBJ Science Academy.
</P>
<P>
   Pace, who has bachelor's degrees in education and biology, said
it took 15 years in teaching to match his base pay in private
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love teaching, but if I were the main breadwinner in my
family, I would be driven out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer said her day at school begins at 8:15 a.m. ``There are
kids waiting at my door for help with geometry,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her first class is at 9 a.m., then she teaches four straight
classes. After that, she takes a 40-minute lunch break in her
classroom so she can help students and answer questions. After
lunch, it's two more classes. That is followed by an hourlong
conference period, from 3:15 p.m. to 4:15 p.m. More tutorials or
meetings. She leaves school no earlier than 5:30 p.m., then spends
four more hours at home grading papers, calling parents and
planning future lessons. Her day is typical for a middle school
math teacher at a low-performing school. Her annual salary is
$31,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The job does not match the pay. That is why many younger
people are passing over teaching,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Teel Bivins, R-Amarillo, chairman of the Senate Education
Committee, is trying to do more to attract new people to teaching.
He has proposed a bill that would provide college scholarships to
students who work as teachers for five years after graduation. That
bill is on its way to the governor for his signature or veto.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dianne White Delisi, R-Temple, has proposed luring retired
teachers back to the classroom by letting them continue to collect
retirement pay while drawing a salary, if they work full time in a
critical-shortage area.
</P>
<P>
   But it all adds up to not enough, many say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because Texas teachers' pay lags so far behind their peers
nationally on average, the Legislature likely will be dealing with
compensation issues in future sessions,'' Sadler said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
