<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYBE PACERS PLAN TO KILL THE KNICKS WITH KINDNESS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ After their first full practice since sweeping
the Philadelphia 76ers Sunday, Reggie Miller and the Indiana Pacers
were on their best behavior Wednesday, offering nothing but
compliments for the rejuvenated Knicks, their opponent in the
Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams are peaking as they enter the series, which begins
Sunday; both teams swept their second-round opponents. The Knicks,
the lowest-seeded team in the East, handily beat the Atlanta Hawks,
while the Pacers, a preseason favorite to replace the dismantled
Chicago Bulls atop the NBA ladder, enter the series without a
playoff loss. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Miller, answering only a handful of questions after practice,
said his team was focused and that any personal satisfaction in
beating the Knicks would take a back seat to the team's goal of
winning the league championship. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great matchup,'' he said of the Knicks-Pacers
rivalry. ``They've always downplayed us, and we've always wanted to
show the big city that we can play in a small market. We kind of
take things to heart here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers want to extend their 11-game winning streak, which
included the last four games of the regular season during their
push to win the Central Division. In addition, the Pacers have not
lost at home in 12 playoff games, and they have the home-court
advantage over the eighth-seeded Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   But no one is making of predictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make a difference what number seed we are coming
into this series,'' said Mark Jackson, the Pacers' point guard.
``We have a lot of respect for them. They've done a great job and
we have to go in playing against a team that advanced to the
Eastern Conference finals, a dangerous basketball team.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, a former Knick, has roots in New York, as does guard
Chris Mullin, who played with Jackson at St. John's. But that does
not mean there is extra motivation to beat the Knicks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Same ol', same ol','' Jackson said. ``This is my third time
facing them in the playoffs, and I'm approaching it the same way I
approached the other ones: just another team in my way and in my
team's way from accomplishing our ultimate goal, which is winning
the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks and Pacers have developed a substantial playoff
rivalry during the 1990s. The Knicks ousted the Pacers in 1993 and
1994, while the Pacers returned the favor in 1995 and 1998. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the Knicks polished off Atlanta on Monday, the crowd began to
chant ``Reg-gie! Reg-gie!'' for Miller. But, despite saying he had
hoped to face the Knicks earlier in the week, Miller is not saying
anything to provoke the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   He complimented Latrell Sprewell and Allan Houston and the
offensive punch they add to a previously Patrick Ewing-centered
Knick offense, and noted the Knicks' improvements in the
post-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've always been known as a great defensive team, but I
think they're really starting to show it; especially now that
they're in the playoffs,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Pacers coach Larry Bird, said his team was looking forward to
playing in New York again in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, if you don't like to play in New York, you don't
like to play anywhere,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
