<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-ROBLEDO-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTENDANCE IS BIG CONCERN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although Major League Soccer's season-ticket sales are up 12
percent this season, the league's average attendance has increased
only half a percent to 14,456.
</P>
<P>
   The latter figure would be much better, but the Galaxy's
attendance is down 7,500 per game, to an average of 14,144.
</P>
<P>
   That is a major concern to MLS these days. While the Galaxy
continues to search for answers, the easy -- albeit expensive --
solution is a new stadium similar to the recently developed
Columbus Crew Stadium. The Galaxy will get a first-hand look at
that site when it plays the Crew Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Columbus owner Lamar Hunt spent a lot of time attending World
Cups and club games overseas before he agreed to build the only
soccer-specific venue in the country. He was attracted to the small
stadiums around the world because they were built so close to the
fields. They provide a fan-friendly atmosphere, which in turn is
appealing to television networks and sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Columbus Crew Stadium holds only 22,500, but touchline seats
make fans feel like they're sitting courtside at an NBA game. In
fact, 50,000 fans at the Rose Bowl couldn't rival the excitement of
a sold-out game in Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believed that if we were able to have a facility that
people would be proud of it would be well supported,'' said Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been able to see the game on an international level and
I was attracted by the crowds and their enthusiasm. I was attracted
to the shape of the field being so close. I saw a synergy there.
Over time, properly designed stadiums are going to be able to
handle a soccer game really well.''
</P>
<P>
   The stadium has already paid off. The Crew has an MLS-record
9,083 season ticket holders, up 60 percent from last year. In
comparison, the Galaxy has approximately 2,500.
</P>
<P>
   Columbus has already played two games in its new stadium. The
Crew sold out its inaugural game on May 15 and 20,782 were on hand
over the weekend against Tampa Bay in the rain. This is all
happening in a city that averaged 12,275 the year before.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans are right down on the field,'' said Columbus
president Jamey Roots. ``Having 22,500 seats provides an intimate
environment for the fans. That's what people fork over their money
for, is to have an exciting, interactive sporting event to
participate in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest benefit is to provide a European atmosphere with
the amenities that fans have come to expect. You see our ticket
base jumping 60 percent and our corporate base of support has
doubled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we are perceived in the community has changed
dramatically from last year to this year. We are truly perceived as
one of the major-league sports entities that will be in this
community for many years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Now it's the Galaxy's turn.
</P>
<P>
   If Denver-based billionaire owner Philip F. Anschutz and team
President Tim Leiweke have hopes of taking this organization to a
level that exceeds what previous owner Marc Rapaport and general
manager Daniel Villanueva were able to provide financially, it's
going to cost a pretty penny.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Los Angeles is handcuffed. Even with a billionaire
owner, new coach Sigi Schmid is bound by Major League Soccer salary
caps and trading guidelines that limit his ability to attract the
foreign marquee names of the past.
</P>
<P>
   And at half capacity, the Rose Bowl, as beautiful as it is, will
never create the excitement that smaller stadiums are capable of
generating.
</P>
<P>
   The attendance should get better with Mexican scoring champion
Carlos Hermosillo rejoining the team in another week, but the
long-term answer for the Galaxy's attendance problems is a
30,000-40,000-seat stadium -- which will cost roughly $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   If the new ownership wants to save the Galaxy, it will spend the
money. There are no salary caps standing in the way of that. If the
team wants to appeal to all classes of people, a new stadium is the
best good faith move it could make.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
