<SLUG> BC-GORE-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE LAYS INTO BAN ON GUN SUITS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Lining up against Gov. George W. Bush, Vice President
Al Gore criticized on Wednesday the move to stop cities from suing
gun manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   It was a whiff of a policy clash in a possible faceoff for
president next year, since Democrat Gore and Republican Bush are
the early front-runners for their political parties' presidential
nominations.
</P>
<P>
   Despite championing ``local control'' on a variety of issues,
Bush has said he plans to sign a bill that bans Texas cities,
counties and other government agencies from suing gunmakers unless
they have special permission from the Texas Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The bill has already passed the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, speaking at a Dallas forum on preventing the kind of
school violence that struck recently in Littleton, Colo., and
Conyers, Ga., said a lawsuit ban is a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's time to take steps to prevent the kind of
lawsuits that many cities are filing to protect themselves,'' Gore
said, without mention of Bush or the state. ``I think it's time to
protect schools and to protect families and to make sure it is more
difficult for children and convicted felons and those who are
unstable to get access to guns.``
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans and 17 other cities across the country have sued
gunmakers to recover the costs of dealing with gun violence,
following the path that Texas and other states have taken in suing
tobacco companies for health care money.
</P>
<P>
   Now Texas is on the verge of joining Georgia in blocking
anti-gun lawsuits by the cities. A Bush spokesman said Wednesday
the governor favors the ban because it would rein in frivolous
lawsuits _ and because the state attorney general, not cities,
should decide whether to sue over the use of legal products by
people with illegal intent.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has voiced opposition to any lawsuit ban at least once
before, in New Hampshire, according to an aide. But his remarks
Tuesday were delivered in Bush's state at a time when the
legislation awaits action by the governor.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time this month that the White House weighed
in on legislation pending in Texas. Two weeks ago, President
Clinton urged the passage of a bill to strengthen state laws
against hate crimes. The bill died in the Senate, however, with
Bush remaining out of the fray until the last few hours of failed
negotiations among the lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in Texas for a mix of policy discussions and campaign
fund-raising events in Dallas and Houston, also said that ``leaders
everywhere'' should reconsider laws that make it legal for trained
citizens to carry concealed handguns.
</P>
<P>
   Concealed weapons became legal in Texas with Bush's support,
during his first term as governor.
</P>
<P>
   In a forum with students and teachers at Dallas' Greiner Middle
School, Gore said restricting access to weapons, reducing the
violent content of movies and providing more parental supervision
of students are some of the ways to head off more school violence.
</P>
<P>
   Gore led the forum with his wife, Tipper, whose campaign against
references to explicit sex and violence in rock music sparked
controversy about 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   For Mrs. Gore, the forum was another step toward a higher public
profile as the couple prepares for the presidential campaign. After
revealing recently that she once suffered from clinical depression,
Mrs. Gore told the forum Wednesday that it is important for
depressed or troubled teens to have access to counseling.
</P>
<P>
   At a dinner in Houston, Gore spoke to a crowd of about 400
people who contributed $1,000 each to his presidential campaign. He
was introduced by Houston Mayor Lee Brown, a political supporter.
Gore pledged to bring ``revolutionary progress'' to public
education if elected president. Public pre-school programs should
be available to all children, and teachers should get higher pay
along with more professional training, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Portraying the Republican Party as too internally fractured to
govern the country with middle-of-the-road policies, Gore said that
during the Republican ``Reagan-Bush years,'' the national debt
quadrupled.
</P>
<P>
   But under the Clinton-Gore administration, he continued, the
federal budget was balanced and the value of the stock market
quadrupled.
</P>
<P>
   The reference was to Ronald Reagan and George Bush, the
governor's father. But it was a shot at Bush, nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
   Gore supporter Garry Mauro, the former Texas land commissioner
who lost last year's governor's race to Bush, told reporters at a
lunchtime fund-raising reception in Dallas that Gore is actually
benefiting from doubts about whether he could beat Bush in a
national race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whereas Gore's expectations are way down, y'all got Bush's way
up here,'' Mauro said. ``I'd rather be where we are than where he
is.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
