r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-DIRTBAGS-LADN-(SL     05-26 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-DIRTBAGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRTBAGS FEATURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ There was a game last year when Long Beach
State scored 17 runs. In one inning!
</P>
<P>
   There were home runs, triples, a slew of walks, all in all
something less than a primetime showcase for college baseball. The
Dirtbags ended up winning the game, 30-6, and, afterward, a
somewhat embarrassed, though certainly pleased, Coach Dave Snow
sifted through the damage left by the biggest single-game explosion
in Long Beach State history and finally remarked, ``Mike Hota ...
he's my secret weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hota? One guy had eight RBIs in the game. Two guys had
three hits in one inning. Another guy had six hits in the game.
Hota? Oh, sure, he had a double and a couple of singles ... but
everybody got hits. The Dirtbags got 30 of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Hota,'' Snow said at the time, flashing a devious smile,
``is the guy who got it all going.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Hota drove in the first run of that blockbuster round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone just seemed to rally around him,'' Snow added.
</P>
<P>
   Hota had only 11 runs batted in all last year, but he had three
of them in that game at Nevada. And he drove in another one in the
West Regional at Stanford, and two more at the College World
Series, and he even started two of the games in Omaha.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough to convince Mike Yuji Hota to return to the
Dirtbags in 1999 even though he knew he'd be a role player ---
again --- and he already had his diploma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't have lived with myself if I hadn't come back,''
Hota said, ``knowing I had one more year ... ''
</P>
<P>
   By his previous standards, Mike Hota, who's working at Balboa
Capital Finance in Irvine, has practically been an iron man this
year. After starting just five games his first three years, and
playing in only 11 his first two, Hota has played in 42 of the
49ers' 56 games this season, starting 29 of them. He's done well,
too, very well, hitting .321, the fifth-best average on the club.
</P>
<P>
   He'll likely be in there Friday when the Dirtbags take on
Mississippi in the first game of the NCAA Regional at Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to go back to the College World Series,'' said Hota,
who was 5 for 13 (.385) last year at Omaha. ``That was the
experience of a lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Hota has been around the Dirtbags far longer than most. He
redshirted his first year, then played the next four, even after
graduating.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a big decision to make, whether to come back this year,
knowing he'd be a role player,'' Snow said. ``He's a team guy, a
good, quiet leader. I've seen him talking to younger players at
different times, helping them.''
</P>
<P>
   What he's is telling them, Hota said, is to pay attention to
what Snow is saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a young team that's still learning what Coach is
teaching,'' said Hota, who turned 23 last week. ``The potential on
this team is enormous ... there's so much talent. Last year's team
didn't have as much talent, but it meshed very well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're starting to get the hang of it,'' Hota added.
``Those last two series (against Cal State Fullerton and Miami) we
started to come around. A couple of games ... New Mexico State and
Sacramento State ... we weren't as committed. There have been
Dirtbag teams like this before, that weren't so great, then finally
realized what Coach is telling them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Gallo, another senior, says Hota is ``like a father. He's
been through it all ... Omaha, the Regionals, you name it. Yeah,
he's a leader.''
</P>
<P>
   A quiet one, unlike Gallo.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not a rah-rah guy at all,'' said Hota. ``A rah-rah kind of
guy has to back up what he says, he has to perform. I'm a quiet
guy, but I still have to perform. I do speak out at team meetings.
I've been here a while, so I have an idea what we need.''
</P>
<P>
   He also has a pretty good notion he's no longer Snow's secret
weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get pitched a little differently now than I used to,'' Hota
said, laughing at the ``secret weapon'' tag.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it does a lot of good. Against No. 1 Miami last week
Hota was 6 for 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miami couldn't figure him out, they respected him,'' said
Snow, who's had to come up with a new tag:
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an unsung hero.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
