<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2725 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-HNS &LR;      05-26 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCNAIR LOSING PATIENCE AS NFL LOOKS TO EXTEND L.A. DEADLINE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The NFL is considering extending Los Angeles' deadline
for a viable stadium plan past the Sept. 15 date, which one league
official described as ``very soft.``
</P>
<P>
   And in Houston, businessman Robert McNair indicated he would
pull out of the running for an expansion franchise if Los Angeles
is given more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in wasting my time if they just keep extending
to keep extending,'' he said. ``I'm not going to keep chasing that
target. Either it's a deadline or it's not a deadline. Only the NFL
can make that decision.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair has submitted a proposal including a state-of-the-art
stadium with firm private and public financing, which NFL officials
want.
</P>
<P>
   But the league has deemed Los Angeles too important to pass up
because of its huge television presence and Hollywood shimmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything happening in Los Angeles is just talk, it's
speculation,'' McNair said. ``Houston has done it. Somebody needs
to come back to that.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL officials ended three days of meetings Wednesday with no
better idea on how to give Los Angeles a franchise than when they
started.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing was clear about the meeting: Houston was not
discussed.
</P>
<P>
   The owners left town still undecided between Hollywood agent
Michael Ovitz's plan, which is considered visionary but premised on
vague financing, or financier Eli Broad's achievable but less
imaginative proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The result? At least another month of study and talk, and likely
another meeting in late July.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue said an expansion
fee for Los Angeles might be less than $500 million, the amount he
stated earlier this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is talking about Houston, a nice town, by the way,''
said Pittsburgh Steelers owner Dan Rooney. ``The owners want to let
the process go to completion.''
</P>
<P>
   Denver Broncos owner Pat Bowlen said the deadline very well
could be extended ``if things remain like they are right now.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair said he is not surprised that his proposal for a 32nd
franchise isn't being discussed, and that the league needs to fully
examine Los Angeles first.
</P>
<P>
   But, he warned, it should not consider giving Los Angeles more
time.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has twice extended its decision-making _ last fall in
Kansas City, Mo., and this spring in Phoenix _ to give Los Angeles
more time to get its act together.
</P>
<P>
   McNair, the Job of NFL suitors, is losing patience and advised
against testing his endurance, though he will continue to persevere
through Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   He currently is considering a league proposal to have NFL
officials visit Houston next month, perhaps an attempt to goad Los
Angeles into action. But if league officials don't stand firm on
their self-imposed deadline, they are not welcome then, McNair
said.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is dangling McNair as a carrot before Los Angeles to get
some type of public subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   The Harris County-Houston Sports Authority has pledged $195
million of public monies toward a $310 million retractable-roof
stadium, with McNair and the Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo
providing the remainder.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Ovitz nor Broad has commitments for financial subsidies
despite plans that rely on some form of public assistance.
</P>
<P>
   If he drops his bid, McNair predicted, the league could not get
nearly as much in expansion fees from either Los Angeles bidder.
McNair has said he would pay up to $500 million, an amount Ovitz
and Broad have agreed to only grudgingly.
</P>
<P>
   If he drops seeking an expansion franchise, McNair said, his
only recourse would be to step up efforts to buy at least a 30
percent managing share of an existing franchise and move it to
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Such possible teams include the Arizona Cardinals, Minnesota
Vikings, Buffalo Bills and New Orleans Saints. All have either
uncompetitive stadium deals or are in smaller, declining cities.
</P>
<P>
   But in the meantime, McNair does not mind being used as an NFL
tool, because he is not sure either Ovitz or Broad can get a deal
done by Sept. 15. He still believes he can win the expansion
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at Los Angeles and think about the (Wendy's) commercial
where the lady asks, `Where's the beef?''' McNair said. ``All we
see out in Los Angeles is two buns with nothing between them.''
</P>
<P>
   As if to prepare for the possibility that McNair will drop his
expansion bid, NFL officials apparently solicited a proposal from
businessman Marvin Davis, who wants to place a tax-subsidized
stadium in Hollywood Park in Inglewood, Calif., near Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Such a bid, if firm, would give the NFL leverage against Los
Angeles officials, who continue to balk at public subsidies amid
firm taxpayer opposition to them.
</P>
<P>
   Before they started their meeting here, league officials had
hoped to gain more clarity about whether Ovitz or Broad should get
the 32nd franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Both plan to gut the 93,000-seat Coliseum and build
substantially smaller seating bowls inside.
</P>
<P>
   But a decision was postponed after Ovitz displayed a creative
design for turning the grounds around the Coliseum into 60 acres of
parkland atop garages to hold 27,000 vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz likened the project to New York's Central Park, a theme
Tagliabue carried as he all but endorsed the plan Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Broad's parking plan, which would require no public subsidies
but handle only 17,000 vehicles, is a much more meat-and-potatoes
idea lacking the pizzazz league officials want for transforming a
rundown sector of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue said league officials will work toward molding Ovitz's
plan into a workable solution, and that either he or Broad, or
both, could end up owning the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   In aiming at that goal, Tagliabue said the league will negotiate
an expansion fee for Los Angeles based on projected costs and
revenues rather than putting it out for bid as was done in
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't rule out a lower price (than $500 million),''
Tagliabue said.
</P>
<P>
   McNair said Wednesday he doubts Ovitz or Broad can get their
deals done and provide a $500 million expansion fee.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as if to add insult to Houston's injured franchise
hopes, NFL owners voted to provide funding for three stadiums in
Denver, Boston and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   As it does with about a third of the newer stadiums, the league
allows the home team to keep 40 percent of the revenue from club
seats if it is dedicated to repaying debt for a stadium. As a new
wrinkle, the league will back the payment, allowing owners to get
lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   In Denver, the arrangement will allow the Broncos to get
financing for about $44 million for their new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   NFL officials have told McNair not to seek such league funding.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
