<SLUG> BC-POW-SCHOLARSHIP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POW MEASURE KILLED IN TEXAS HOUSE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Legislation designed to help former prisoner of
war U.S. Army Spc. Steven Gonzales to complete college with a
special state scholarship was killed in the Texas House on
Wednesday when three fiscal conservatives talked the measure to
death.
</P>
<P>
   The three lawmakers, including Rep. David Counts, D-Knox City,
raised objections to the measure for only 10 minutes, but under
House rules, that was long enough to kill the bill before a vote
could be taken.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Bill 1902 by Sen. Eddie Lucio, D-Brownsville, was
tailored to help Gonzales, who was held captive in Yugoslavia for
more than a month before his release May 2. He attended Texas A&AMP;M
University before joining the service and alumni there have offered
to support him if he returns.
</P>
<P>
   The bill applied to a resident Texan taken as a prisoner of war
after Jan. 1. It authorized a public college or university to waive
fees and tuition for a qualifying former POW. It also allowed
colleges to accept gifts and grants to support Gonzales.
</P>
<P>
   But what caught Knox's attention was a provision stating that
the university must pay the student's lodging and board if he or
she chose not to live on campus.
</P>
<P>
   State fiscal experts said the bill would not have affected any
college's total budget, but Knox insisted that it was too
open-ended.
</P>
<P>
   The other two lawmakers who opposed the bill, Republican Reps.
Carl Isett of Lubbock, and Leo Berman of Tyler, claimed that
Gonzales was not a true prisoner of war because the United States
is not technically at war with Yugoslavia. They also said other
former prisoners would flock to Texas to get a free education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The argument against it was so stupid,'' said Rep. Bill
Carter, R-Fort Worth, the House sponsor. ``I just can't imagine why
those guys aren't willing to recognize a prisoner of war.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter said the legislation required a college to seek private
funds before expending its own on a former POW.
</P>
<P>
   ``His tuition bill has already been paid by an alumni, so
there's no fiscal impact on it,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
