<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS HOUSE OKS $98 BILLION BUDGET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A $98.1 billion state budget for 2000-01 won
final approval in the Texas House on Wednesday. But still
unresolved for the session's five final days was the politically
explosive question of how to divide $500 million in tax breaks
among businesses and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The partisan tax relief dispute was defused momentarily when the
Senate kept alive a research and development tax credit for
businesses that was aggressively sought by Gov. George W. Bush.
However, some House Democrats were poised to resume their attacks
on the largesse for corporations when the measure returns to their
chamber by week's end.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Senate is expected to sign off on the mammoth
spending plan, which devotes 75 percent of new revenues to public
and higher education. Overall, the budget represents an 11 percent
increase over the current two-year spending cycle that ends Aug.
31.
</P>
<P>
   The state's robust economy created a $6.4 billion surplus that
enabled lawmakers to bolster spending across the board at state
agencies, with increases ranging from 4 percent in health and human
services to 16 percent for public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most responsible budget I've ever been involved
in,'' said House Appropriations Chairman Rob Junell, D-San Angelo.
</P>
<P>
   The $31 billion outlay for public schools was a $4.3 billion
increase over the current biennium, but exactly how $3.8 billion of
that increase will be spent remains up in the air. A House-Senate
negotiating committee began work Wednesday to pin down details of a
planned $3,000 per year pay raise for every Texas teacher,
counselor, librarian and nurse, and to allot other payments to help
with old debt and force local school districts to lower taxes.
</P>
<P>
   While the school finance negotiating committee races to meet
Sunday's deadline for final votes on a compromise, several other
clusters of negotiators will be meeting to settle partisan disputes
over tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, a Senate bill designed to grant tax relief to
corporations was killed on a technicality, but by dawn Wednesday,
lawmakers from both parties were conferring on plans that by day's
end had rescued several key features of the original proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Still on the table were the franchise tax breaks for job
creation and research and development, and sales tax exemptions for
common purchases including nonprescription drugs, school-related
clothes and Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals were contained in three bills that each require
more votes in both the House and Senate and still added up to more
than the $500 million set aside by budget writers.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry, said the governor, who predicted that the dispute
would be resolved before the session ends Monday. But Bush
reiterated that he has the sole authority to summon lawmakers back
to work for a 30-day special session to complete the task, if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The test is not over. We have yet to give up. We'll see how it
goes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush supports sales and property tax relief, he's also
been pressuring lawmakers to find a way to implement the business
tax cuts he promised. But Democrats including Rep. Sylvester Turner
of Houston have objected to the business tax breaks as unnecessary
giveaways that will be hard to rescind when the economy is not so
rosy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what the financial condition of the state will
be two years from now,'' Turner said. He opposes the business tax
breaks, especially if not limited to a few years.
</P>
<P>
   A key Bush ally, Rep. Tom Craddick, R-Midland, predicted the
dispute would end peacefully before deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between now and Monday night, we'll work it out,'' he said,
adding that the final package would closely resemble the one that
Turner derailed late Tuesday by successfully challenging its
constitutionality.
</P>
<P>
   The unconstitutional provisions, which deal with tax credits for
targeted regions, were later stripped from the legislation when the
Senate added the endangered tax breaks to a similar bill, House
Bill 551 by Rep. Tony Goolsby, R-Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still time to keep hope alive,'' said House Ways and
Means Chairman Rene Oliveira, D-Brownsville, who shuttled between
chambers throughout the day to negotiate the tax relief package.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern now is the size,'' he said. Indeed, the Senate has
approved nearly $450 million in consumer tax relief alone. The
price tag on the business tax breaks has been pegged at nearly $200
million.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he'll monitor the negotiations to the deadline and
will remain close to the Capitol to give his blessing to any deals
that emerge.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mind is right here in Austin. We've got five or six days to
go to get the legislative session over with. It's a period of some
moments of high anxiety and long hours,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
