<SLUG> BC-COFFEE-WARS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COFFEE WARS WILL HEAT UP WHEN DIEDRICH OPENS 80 L.A. LOCATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles may soon have more coffee beans than
Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Diedrich Coffee Inc., an Irvine, Calif.-based specialty
coffeehouse chain that now operates 35 stores, said that it has
entered into an exclusive agreement with Los Angeles-based
California Coffee Co. to develop 80 franchises in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   According to Diedrich and California Coffee officials, however,
the plan calls for the stores to be developed over the next five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be slower in the beginning and ramp up,'' said Ann
Wride, chief financial officer for Diedrich.
</P>
<P>
   Diedrich Coffee operates 35 coffeehouses. Most are in Orange
County, with two in Los Angeles and a sprinkling in Colorado and
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles stores are part of a major expansion announced
by Diedrich last summer under which franchises also will open in
North Carolina, northern Florida and San Diego. Agreements call for
224 stores. But if various options are exercised, up to 372 would
open in the four areas.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with California Coffee Co. calls for 80 stores in Los
Angeles, with an option to open 103 in the San Francisco Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   But is the Los Angeles market already saturated? Not in the view
of the Long Beach-based Specialty Coffee Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our point of view, everyone should be able to walk
somewhere where they can get a properly brewed cup of coffee,''
said association spokesman Mike Ferguson. ``Until that happens, the
market isn't saturated.''
</P>
<P>
   The demand for coffeehouses is illustrated by the fact that
there are now some 12,000 in the United States, up from 1,500
brewed coffee retailers _ as opposed to whole bean retailers _ in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 2313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0464 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2782 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFINERY-SETTLEMENT-S     05-26 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFINERY-SETTLEMENT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFINERY AGREES TO PAY $4.4 MILLION FOR BLAST THAT KILLED SIX
WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT VERNON, Wash. _ The owner of an Anacortes, Wash., refinery
where six workers died in an explosion has agreed to settle a state
investigation of the accident by paying more than $4.4 million that
will cover safety improvements, college scholarships and a record
$1.1 million fine.
</P>
<P>
   State officials announced the unprecedented deal here Wednesday,
culminating the six-month investigation into the Nov. 25 explosion
at Equilon Puget Sound Refining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing can replace the lives of the friends and co-workers we
lost last November,'' Judith Moorad, the refinery's president, said
in a statement. ``But we believe these donations are appropriate
ways to memorialize them, provide benefits to the community where
we live and work, and enhance the safety and well-being of the
refinery work force.''
</P>
<P>
   But a Seattle lawyer who is representing the families of four
workers in their lawsuits against Equilon said the $1.1 million
fine is trivial to the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``A corporation can come in here, kill six workers and all they
have to pay is less than one day's earnings for that plant,'' David
Beninger said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators concluded that the accident _ the most deadly in
the 26 years the state has enforced worker safety rules _ could
have been prevented, said Gary Moore, director of the Department of
Labor and Industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The workers should not have died,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators pinpointed the accident to one of two coking units
at the refinery. Superheated oil is pumped into the six-story-tall
units. After 16 hours, workers remove coke, a charcoal-like
substance used as fuel in aluminum plants.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 25, a cascade of mishaps and errors _ most notably, a
decision by plant officials to allow the unit to cool for hours
instead of hundreds of days _ ended with a fireball.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Silverstein, who directs the state's worker safety
program, said a ``flaming mass broke out in all directions,''
killing six workers in seconds. ``These workers were trapped very
quickly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He traced the accident to Nov. 24, when a windstorm knocked out
power to the plant. The plant lost electricity one hour into a
16-hour process in which the coking unit is filled. Partially
refined oil heated at 900 degrees Fahrenheit goes into the unit,
vapors escape and water cools the unit before the coke is removed.
</P>
<P>
   The power outage caused clogged lines, Silverstein said. What's
more, the plant's boiler, which would have produced steam to unclog
the lines, was down.
</P>
<P>
   Even after steam was restored, little made its way to the coking
unit.
</P>
<P>
   Then Equilon made what Silverstein described as its ``fatal
decision'' to allow the outside air to cool the unit instead of
water.
</P>
<P>
   The company waited 37 hours for the unit to cool. State
investigators later determined that it would have taken 236 days
for it to be cooled by the outside air.
</P>
<P>
   When the workers opened the drum, they found hot liquid instead
of a congealed mass. The liquid poured out and ignited.
</P>
<P>
   The flames engulfed the two workers at the controls of the
coking unit and four men working below them.
</P>
<P>
   Equilon did not admit to any wrongdoing as part of the
settlement. The company's own investigation released a month after
the explosion pointed to problems with the coking unit. In recent
court filings, Equilon has blamed Western Plant Services, a
subcontractor that helped to operate the coking unit, for the
accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wish it hadn't happened,'' said Dave McKinney, an Equilon
spokesman. ``The circumstances at the time it occurred were
unusual. It hadn't happened before. The people involved used their
experience and best judgment to open that coke drum.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore and Silverstein said the agreement will allow state
investigators to make sure the company follows safety rules and
will enhance safety at the refinery.
</P>
<P>
   Equilon came to Labor and Industries officials two weeks ago and
asked to negotiate a settlement, officials said. Had the company
not reached an agreement, regulators could have levied a fine and
would have faced protracted appeals and court battles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to avoid long and costly litigation that would
have been involved,'' McKinney said.
</P>
<P>
   The union that represents refinery workers also praised the
deal. ``I think it's an exceptionally good settlement,'' said Tom
Lind, an international representative of the Oil, Chemical and
Atomic Workers union.
</P>
<P>
   He said the agreement will make the plant a safer place to work
and added that the company has already agreed to a union safety
program and to having a union safety officer at the plant.
</P>
<P>
   State regulators briefed the families of the six dead workers
Wednesday. They were pleased that the company agreed to a safety
audit and that state regulators will oversee it, said Beninger, the
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Fry, whose husband, Warren, died in the explosion, called
the agreement a first step.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most important one,'' she said. ``We're in favor of
everything they did in making it a safer workplace. If they would
have done it years ago, it wouldn't have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Beninger was sharply critical of the $1.1 million fine.
</P>
<P>
   He said the plant makes more than $500 million a year. Equilon
is a partnership of Texaco and Shell.
</P>
<P>
   Equilon's agreed fine of $1.1 million is five times larger than
any penalty Labor and Industries has ever levied, Silverstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators faulted the company for not keeping workers free
from hazards. Equilon did not follow typical procedures to open the
coking unit, failed to evaluate the procedures that were used and
did not train the employees who used the different procedure.
</P>
<P>
   The company agreed to the fine in exchange for the Labor and
Industries Department not assigning blame for the violations.
Typically, the agency characterizes violations as general, serious,
repeat or willful, which is the most severe. In this case, the
state listed the violations against Equilon as ``uncharacterized.''
</P>
<P>
   Beninger suggested that Equilon wanted to avoid blame for the
violations in hopes of not having its premiums for workers'
compensation boosted.
</P>
<P>
   Labor and Industries officials could not say Wednesday how much
the agency could have fined Equilon. The maximum fine for each
willful violation is $70,000. Unlike most other state-run programs
for worker safety, Washington state's cannot assess punitive
damages, Beninger said.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the $4.405 million will include:
</P>
<P>
   _$1 million to a union scholarship fund in memory of the six
dead workers.
</P>
<P>
   _$1 million to help to establish a workplace safety and health
institute in the state.
</P>
<P>
   _$350,000 to the city of Anacortes to buy a new firetruck.
</P>
<P>
   _$350,000 to hire an outside consultant to audit safety
management at the plant.
</P>
<P>
   The company already has spent $605,000 on equipment upgrades for
the coking unit, which went back into service in late March. The
equipment includes a remote-control device to open the unit from
200 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the accident, workers stood next to the unit and
removed bolts to open it.
</P>
<P>
   Labor and Industries has four other investigations at the
refinery involving Equilon or subcontractors. The settlement
doesn't affect those investigations. Five workers were injured in
an explosion at the plant in March and six were hurt in an acid
spill in April.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
