<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2783 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-BRUTALITY-A     05-26 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-BRUTALITY-ART-615&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO VIEWS OF POLICE AND RACE AT U.S. HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The yawning chasm between the Police Department and
many of the people it serves was evident Wednesday as Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani and other witnesses gave the U.S. Civil Rights Commission
two starkly divergent visions of how the New York City police treat
black and Hispanic people.
</P>
<P>
   Many witnesses at the commission's hearing in a Manhattan hotel
described how residents are routinely harassed by white officers,
many of whom live in the suburbs and, the witnesses said, display
an arrogant disregard for the neighborhoods they patrol.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor and police officials, meanwhile, depicted a dedicated
force of officers who, aside from a few isolated rogues, show
remarkable restraint and are too often shown disrespect by the
people they protect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their testimony seems to tell us that everything is fine,''
said Cruz Reynoso, the panel's vice chairman. ``Yet we will hear
from the community and citizens who tell us everything is
different.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission will consider both views of the police, and
thousands of subpoenaed documents, as it prepares a report for the
president and Congress on whether the aggressive police practices
that have been credited with producing New York's drop in crime in
recent years have also taken too great a toll on civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   The independent, bipartisan commission is conducting one of the
five inquiries under way into New York police conduct, inquiries
prompted by high-profile incidents like the police torture of Abner
Louima. The City Council, the state attorney general and federal
prosecutors in Brooklyn and Manhattan are also conducting
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Wednesday's one day of testimony, the commission,
a fact-finding but not prosecuting agency, will accept written
testimony and reports until June 25.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, the first witness on Wednesday, stressed in his
hourlong appearance that the police do not engage in a practice
known as racial profiling, an allegation that has arisen because
thousands of black and Hispanic residents are frisked each year,
even though only a fraction are ever arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the searches are conducted by the Street Crime Unit,
whose procedures have been scrutinized since February when four of
its officers killed an unarmed black man, Amadou Diallo, in a
fusillade of 41 bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and Police Commissioner Howard Safir said they could
show that officers selected members of racial minorities to stop
only because the race was part of the description given by crime
victims. The mayor cited statistics saying that 71 percent of crime
victims in precincts patrolled by members of the Street Crime Unit
had identified their assailants as black and that 63 percent of the
people stopped in those same precincts were also black.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stops are driven by the descriptions of the person who
committed the crime,'' not by racism, Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   But Attorney General Eliot Spitzer was one of several witnesses
who challenged the mayor's analysis, saying most police searches
were not prompted by information relayed to them by crime victims.
``In a very substantial number of cases, it is the police officer's
own observation that initiates the stop and frisk,'' said Spitzer,
whose office is investigating whether that practice has been
discriminatory.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton was point-blank in his condemnation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the closest thing I have ever heard to a public policy
of racial profiling,'' Sharpton said. ``What you are really saying
is because victims say they're black, then all blacks become
suspects.'' Sharpton told the panel that he wanted a federal
monitor appointed to oversee the police force.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Giuliani's testimony, which came one day after a white police
officer admitted to torturing a black man in a station house
restroom, was punctuated by constant heckling from a handful of the
100 people who crowded into the sixth-floor meeting room at the
Doubletree Guest Suites in midtown.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor seemed unruffled, however. When several spectators
scoffed at Giuliani's remarks on the rarity of police shootings, he
said sharply, ``All of that might be mind-boggling to emotion and
prejudice, but it's reality.''
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony, Public Advocate Mark Green blamed Giuliani for
setting a tone that allowed police abuses to go unpunished. ``One
of the problems with police misconduct in this city is the stone
wall around City Hall,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Safir said he was tired of hearing critics and the media
``smear the Police Department.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been characterized as badly trained, insufficiently
monitored, negligent in our selection and hiring of recruits, and
unwilling to tackle our problems honestly and directly,'' he said.
``That type of rhetoric is absolutely untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   James Savage, the president of the Patrolmen's Benevolent
Association, the city's largest police union, said distrust of the
police has been fostered by the department's overzealous pursuit of
lower crime rates and higher summons quotas. ``Cops never get a
favorable promotion for protecting someone's civil rights,'' he
told the panel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
