<SLUG> BC-AMTRAK-FATALITY-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TRAIN DEATHS, WRONG NAME GIVEN FOR A VICTIM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRFIELD, Conn. _ The police and railroad officials, continuing
their investigation into why a 48-year-old woman and her four sons
had been walking along a stretch of railroad tracks in the predawn
darkness on Tuesday when they were struck by an Amtrak train, said
Wednesday that the wrong boy was identified as the sole survivor of
the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a roomful of reporters and television cameras at the
Fairfield Police Department on Tuesday, Metropolitan Transit
Authority Police officials said that family members had identified
the only surviving boy as Angel Gabriel Urgiles Toledo, 6. But on
Wednesday afternoon, an MTA official said Angel had died in the
crash, and that the boy in the hospital was his 10-year-old
brother, Jose Francisco Urgiles.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, when the police had asked a family member to
identify the boy, who is in critical condition with severe head
wounds and an amputated left leg, the distraught man gave them the
name of the wrong child, said Tom Kelly, an MTA spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``A family member identified the injured child, and as a result
of the circumstances, a mistake was made,'' Kelly said. ``The
family member is obviously distraught about what happened. And in
his grief he mistook one kid for the other.''
</P>
<P>
   As early as Tuesday night, Kelly said, as other family members
came to visit the boy, they told police officials, ``That's not
Angel, that's Jose.''
</P>
<P>
   MTA officials, who with the Connecticut State Police and Amtrak
are investigating the crash, decided to wait for the state medical
examiner's report Wednesday to revise information on which of the
boys had survived, said the agency's chief of patrol, Peter
Loverso.
</P>
<P>
   The police also identified the other two dead brothers Wednesday
as Pedro Andres Urgiles, 3, and Carlos Enrique Urgiles, 11. Their
mother, Julia Toledo de Urgiles, was also killed in the 2:20 a.m.
crash, which occurred on a train trestle as she tried to pull one
son from the path of the 10-car Amtrak passenger train traveling
from Boston to Newport News, Va. All five were grouped together on
the tracks when they were struck, MTA police officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining mystery in the case centered on Ms. Toledo, an
immigrant from Ecuador and for the last two years or so a single
mother who had just moved her family out of an apartment and into a
temporary shelter for homeless families.
</P>
<P>
   That seemed to be the signal of new problems in her life,
friends and acquaintances said. For until recently, Ms. Toledo, who
friends and neighbors described as a good mother who walked her
children to school in the mornings and reported to her custodial
job at Fairfield University promptly every afternoon, had been
taking English lessons at Caroline House, a Bridgeport nonprofit
agency that teaches language and job skills to immigrant women.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people are saying is she had some kind of breakdown and
left,'' said Autumn Weintraub, an official with the union that
represents the university's custodial workers, who has spoken with
family members since the accident. ``A lot of family people are
saying it was a gradual thing,'' she said. ``It started slow and
was getting worse and worse.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Like many others who knew Ms. Toledo, Ms. Weintraub said she was
at a loss to explain why Ms. Toledo, who had earned a beautician's
certificate in Ecuador, had felt compelled to lead her four sons
out onto the train tracks in the middle of the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was obviously fleeing, but we don't know why,'' said
Sister Brenda Lynch of Caroline House. Ms. Toledo had been a
reliable student of English, she said. ``We wished we had known she
was in trouble, because we could have helped her.''
</P>
<P>
   The three oldest boys _ Carlos, Jose and Angel _ attended Luis
Munoz Marin Elementary School, a large school serving children from
predominantly Latino neighborhoods.
</P>
</TEXT>
