<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-TRIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILVERBULLETDAY JOINS FIELD FOR BELMONT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ She was fast in her workout on Tuesday, and
frisky in the stall afterward. And so her trainer, Bob Baffert, has
finally decided that his standout filly Silverbulletday is ready to
take on the colts. In New York. At the Belmont Stakes. Against a
strapping overachiever named Charismatic, who is 1 1/2 miles away
from capturing the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   So choose the most compelling drama for June 5.
</P>
<P>
   Can Silverbulletday win in a race that, in its previous 130
runnings, has been won only twice by fillies, with the last victory
coming 94 years ago? Or can Charismatic become the 12th horse in
history _ and the first since Affirmed in 1978 _ to sweep the
Kentucky Derby, the Preakness and the Belmont?
</P>
<P>
   And will Baffert and Charismatic's trainer, D. Wayne Lukas,
elevate their already fierce rivalry to an even higher level during
the next 10 days?
</P>
<P>
   Silverbulletday was the champion 2-year-old filly last year; has
won 11 of her 12 starts overall and in the last month has destroyed
members of her own sex in outings in the Kentucky Oaks and the
Black-Eyed Susan as she established herself as the best 3-year-old
filly in the country. Maybe the best 3-year-old, period.
</P>
<P>
   But this will be her first Triple Crown race. Baffert and the
horse's owner, Mike Pegram, skipped the Kentucky Derby because of
an unwieldy 20-horse field and then scratched from the Preakness
when she drew a bad outside post.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Baffert had gone back and forth over whether to put
Silverbulletday in a race that only 20 other fillies have even
attempted, but Wednesday he took the plunge.
</P>
<P>
   ``She cooled out good after a hard work,'' Baffert said
Wednesday morning. ``She looked real good. She was playing and
bucking. We're in.''
</P>
<P>
   For Pegram, those were the words he had been waiting to hear all
spring from his friend, trainer and ultimate decision-maker. All
week he made it clear that he wanted to return to the Belmont,
where last year his colt Real Quiet lost his bid for the Triple
Crown by a nose to the late-charging Victory Gallop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said all along she's a once-in-a-lifetime horse; if she
pulls it off, she'd prove it,'' Pegram said. ``She has nothing to
lose. The only regret is that I'd rather be running for the $5
million bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it is Charismatic who is racing for the money Visa has
promised for a Triple Crown sweep. The colt, owned by Bob and
Beverly Lewis, was running in claiming races only three months ago
and now is at the doorstep of racing history. Charismatic has also
become something of a folk hero because of his fondness for the
feed tub and affinity for hard work. The colt has raced four times
in the last eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The powerfully built chestnut was a 31-1 long shot in the Derby
and an 8-1 outsider at the Preakness. And no matter what odds
Charismatic goes off at in the Belmont, he has helped Lukas wrest
back the spotlight from Baffert who, in the last two years, came to
New York in June with an opportunity to win the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   Last year it was with Real Quiet, and two years ago it was with
Silver Charm, who is also owned by the Lewises. The Lewises split
their stable between Lukas and Baffert, and are now in the odd
position of having one of their trainers trying to spoil their own
Triple Crown quest.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert ran three horses in this year's Derby, finishing fourth
with Prime Timber, fifth with the filly Excellent Meeting and 11th
with General Challenge. Only Excellent Meeting ran in the
Preakness, and she was eased and did not finish after having
trouble breathing.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas understands Baffert's desire to take him on in the
Belmont, but could not resist unleashing a few gibes Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is obviously very talented and she has had a soft spring,
which is in her favor,'' Lukas said of Silverbulletday. ``Let's
face it; she has had a cream puff schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``This filly crop isn't as strong as it's been in recent years.
Let's see what happens when she gets in there with some
battle-tested colts.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas also conceded that Charismatic is not scaring any
competitors away. In fact, a colorful field of as many as 14 horses
is expected to add to the Belmont's drama and test Charismatic's
ability and desire.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Allen Jerkens, the Hall of Fame trainer, will bring Best of
Luck, who won the Peter Pan last Sunday. Ireland's Dermot Weld is
bringing Port Bayou over to try to duplicate Go and Go's victory in
the 1990 Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Another Hall of Famer, Bill Mott, will saddle the Illinois Derby
winner, Vision and Verse, and the trainer Patrick Byrne is entering
still another new Triple Crown face: Prime Directive. And then, of
course, there is Menifee, the Derby and the Preakness runner-up.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas, who was recently inducted in the Hall of Fame, said he
welcomes them all, including Silverbulletday, who will have Jerry
Bailey as her jockey because the regular rider, Gary Stevens, is
committed to racing in England.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want everyone who thinks he has a good horse in his barn to
be there,'' Lukas said. ``We don't want anyone looking back at this
and saying `if only he or she would have ran.' We want to beat the
best.''
</P>
</TEXT>
