<HEADLINE>
NFL MEETINGS END WHERE THEY STARTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ NFL owners muddled through the final hours of their
three days of meetings Wednesday without making any decisions on
the Los Angeles expansion franchise but gave Michael Ovitz a window
to prove his flashy Coliseum and site plans can work.
</P>
<P>
   Owners are expected to meet again on July 28, although they
might have to meet earlier if Los Angeles can be expected to meet
its Sept. 15 deadline to secure the league's 32nd franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Although hoping the Eli Broad-Ed Roski Jr. group can merge its
knowledge of the Coliseum site and working relationships with area
politicians with the favored ``vision'' of the Ovitz plan, the NFL
has given Ovitz to the end of June to prove his proposal is more
than colorful renderings and fancy schemes.
</P>
<P>
   NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue said both plans had positive
elements, but he clearly shifted the focus to the Ovitz and Ron
Burkle proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The critical thing is to take the vision presented in the
Ovitz-Burkle plan and make what modifications needed to be made,
and convert it into a reality,'' Tagliabue said. ``We just have to
be sensitive to the costs and the historical context of the
Coliseum.''
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz's site plan includes 27,000 parking spaces in seven
garages on the Exposition Park grounds that would have grass and
park areas built on top of the structures. The garages would cost
an estimated $225 million that Ovitz said would have to come from
public funding.
</P>
<P>
   NFL owners don't believe the state would come close to funding
the $225 million but remain impressed by Ovitz and his ideas and
continue straining to find a way to make his plans work.
</P>
<P>
   Now the league is promoting and unlikely merger of the two
groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they know what they're doing,'' said Raiders
owner Al Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Both Ovitz and Broad left the sessions Tuesday and did not
attend the final meetings on Wednesday. Both groups presented an
update of their plans to the expansion committee Monday night and
an abbreviated version to the full membership the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   But the expansion committee did not meet again after Monday
night and never took any action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just haven't had a chance to meet again as a committee to
discuss their presentations,'' said Carolina Panthers owner Jerry
Richardson, who heads the committee. ``It takes time. I'm sorry,
but it takes time.''
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue said the projected costs and revenues would have to be
examined more closely in the six-week-old Ovitz plan during the
next month, something already done in the two-year Broad plan for
the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a Plan A and a Plan B and they may evolve into
a Plan C,'' Tagliabue said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
