<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J., N.Y.)  
 PROVENZANO NEPHEW INDICTED FOR RACKETEERING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SELWYN RAAB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Daniel Provenzano has dabbled in an assortment of businesses,
from delivering fish to producing a movie called ``Vampire Vixens
From Venus.'' On the surface, his investments seem lucrative; he
lives with his wife and infant son in a 15-room New Jersey home
valued at more than $1 million and motors around in a Mercedes-Benz
and a Ferrari.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators say his real ambition was to follow in the
Mafia footsteps of his uncle, Anthony ``Tony Pro'' Provenzano, who
was identified as a notorious leader of the Genovese crime family
in New Jersey before his death in 1988 from a heart attack while
serving a prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
   In a 44-count racketeering indictment, a state grand jury in
Trenton, N.J., charged Wednesday that Provenzano, 35, headed an
organized crime gang that used strong-arm tactics and kidnappings
to extort $1.4 million from businesses in New Jersey and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Zoubek, New Jersey's acting attorney general, said that
Provenzano and eight co-defendants ``conducted a reign of terror''
against executives from 13 companies involved in business deals
with him from 1991 to last year. The indictment accused Provenzano
of threatening to kill an executive with a baseball bat in an
attempt to extort $390,000. He is also accused of conspiring to
murder witnesses to conceal the gang's activities.
</P>
<P>
   Provenzano, who is free on $1 million bail, has an unlisted home
telephone number in Upper Saddle River, N.J., and could not be
reached Wednesday. After the attorney general's office disclosed in
1997 that his activities were under investigation, Provenzano
denied that he was linked to organized crime and characterized
himself as a hard-working businessman.
</P>
<P>
   But law enforcement officials said that Provenzano, in secretly
recorded tapes, boasted that he worked for Liborio Bellomo, a
high-ranking member of the Genovese family. The officials described
Provenzano as an associate in the family who was striving to become
a ``made man,'' or inducted member.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said Provenzano was also heard on the tapes
warning an insurance company executive that he would be killed
unless he paid him $100,000 as ``homage.'' The indictment charged
Provenzano with evading New Jersey income taxes and asserted that
he used his own companies to launder extortion payoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s and early 1990s, Provenzano supplied seafood
to New Jersey restaurants from the Fulton Fish Market in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, he has described himself as the lead producer in
1995 of ``Vampire Vixens From Venus,'' a film about alien females
who travel to earth to remove the brains of young men.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
