<SLUG> BC-NY-GOP-EXTORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP COUNTY CHAIRMAN IN NEW YORK ACCUSED OF EXTORTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The chairman of the Dutchess County, N.Y., Republican Party was
arrested by federal authorities Wednesday on charges that he forced
developers to make payments to the local party and himself in
exchange for permits and tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors allege that the chairman, William L. Paroli Sr.,
arranged to delay or defeat projects of developers who failed to
make the payments, which amounted to tens of thousands of dollars
over the last decade. Paroli is also accused of spending public
money on new tires for his car and using Poughkeepsie municipal
employees to do landscaping and electrical work at his home.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities said that even the architect and contractor
who built the city's courthouse from 1995 to 1997 were required to
contribute more than $35,000 to the party, which has long held an
unshakable grip on Poughkeepsie and the county.
</P>
<P>
   Agents from the FBI and the New York State Commission of
Investigation arrested Paroli at his home in Poughkeepsie on
Wednesday afternoon. Paroli, who was arraigned in U.S. District
Court in White Plains, was charged with conspiracy and extortion
and released on his own recognizance.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, he faces a maximum sentence of 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at his home Wednesday night, Paroli said he could not
comment. His lawyer, Andy Rubin, could not be reached Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jo White, the U.S. attorney for the Southern District of
New York, said she hoped the prosecution of Paroli would help clean
up the city's government. Two other Poughkeepsie officials were
recently convicted of bribery and extortion as part of the federal
and state investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should send a strong message to public and political
officials that they will face serious consequences if they attempt
to use their positions to enrich themselves,'' she said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1990, investigators say, Paroli was able to force
developers to pay for the smooth sailing of their projects. With
the help of the city's tax assessor, Bill Raucci, some developers
had their assessments reduced _ in one case by $100,000 _ on their
projects in exchange for payments of up to $10,000. Others were
told to pay up if they wanted to receive the necessary permits, the
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Raucci was found floating in the Hudson River in 1997.
Investigators have ruled his death a suicide.
</P>
<P>
   When the developer of Vassar Oaks, a condominium project, failed
to make the payment on time, Paroli threatened to have water meters
in each house removed, prosecutors said. Much of that money ended
up as contributions to the Republican Party, but some of it went
directly to Paroli, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   A former Poughkeepsie policeman, Paroli, 71, is chairman of the
Republican Party in both Dutchess County and Poughkeepsie and is a
commissioner of the county's Board of Elections. Residents say that
his power was so great, he was reported to control hiring and
promotions in the Police Department. His son, William Paroli Jr.,
is the county clerk.
</P>
<P>
   Few people said they were surprised by the charges. ``The
dimensions of the charges are stunning but there have been
suspicions of irregularity floating around for a long time,'' said
Molly Shanley, a political science professor at Vassar College.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
