<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-VOLPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLPE SEGREGATED FROM OTHER INMATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Justin Volpe, the former New York police officer who
confessed on Tuesday to torturing Abner Louima, is spending his
first days in custody segregated from other inmates for his own
protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing as well as can be expected under the
circumstances,'' said Volpe's lawyer, Marvyn Kornberg, who spoke to
his client by telephone Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe, 27, is being held at the Metropolitan Correctional
Center, a federal jail with about 900 inmates on Park Row near
police headquarters in lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   It may not be until early next week before friends and relatives
are able to visit, because it will take time for officials to
approve a list of people he is entitled to see, Kornberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prison authorities provide more rigorous oversight of
inmates who are former law enforcement officials, including special
screening and counseling, because they are considered prime targets
for assaults by other inmates. ``Their former status makes them
vulnerable,'' said Todd Craig, spokesman for the Federal Bureau of
Prisons.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Craig said, 575 former law enforcement officials
were in the federal prison system, a fivefold increase from 1994,
when there were 107 inmates with law enforcement backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   One potential threat for Volpe is from inmates who may seek
status among their peers by attacking an infamous former police
officer. ``It's very, very rough,'' said Joel Rudin, a lawyer for
Zaher Zahrey, a detective in the New York Police Department who
spent eight months in the Metropolitan Correctional Center before
he was acquitted of corruption charges last year.
</P>
<P>
   Rudin said Zahrey was ``emotionally devastated'' by the
experience of going from a position of authority to a position of
complete subjugation, where strip searches are routine, every move
is watched and telephone calls are monitored.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was held in protective custody, which is extremely
restrictive, and he was jeered and taunted by other inmates who
found out that he was a police officer,'' Rudin said.
</P>
<P>
   The worst moment, he said, came one day during Zahrey's exercise
hour on the roof of the jail. Two inmates suspected in the 1996
shooting death of a New York police officer, Kevin Gillespie,
jumped Zahrey, who was in handcuffs. A correction officer waited
for reinforcements before intervening, Rudin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what saved him was that fortunately there were no
sharp objects around,'' Rudin said of the beating. ``After eight
and a half months he was a wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   Volpe, who pleaded guilty to six federal crimes, faces up to
life in prison. He admitted in U.S. District Court on Tuesday that
he had rammed a stick into Louima's rectum in the bathroom of a
Brooklyn police station.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the violence of his assault on Louima and the length
of his expected sentence, Volpe may be placed in a high-security
federal penitentiary, where inmate movements are carefully
controlled, prison officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The closest high-security prison to New York City is the U.S.
Penitentiary in Lewisburg, Pa., near Harrisburg, Craig said. Often,
though, former law enforcement officials are dispatched to prisons
outside their ``sphere of notoriety'' to decrease the chance of
assault, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
