</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-POLICE-PROFILING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.J. DISMISSES 24 CASES DUE TO TROOPERS' RACIAL PROFILING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. _ A state judge dismissed drug, assault and
weapons charges against 24 people Wednesday because the two state
troopers who arrested them have been charged with singling out
black and Hispanic drivers for stops and then trying to cover it
up.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen of the 24 had been indicted on first-degree
drug-distribution charges. Others were charged with lesser drug and
weapons counts. New Jersey Superior Court Judge Robert Longhi
dropped all counts without comment.
</P>
<P>
   The first-degree drug-distribution counts, the most serious
under New Jersey's criminal code, involved possession of at least 5
ounces of cocaine or at least 25 pounds of marijuana. Those crimes
normally carry jail terms of 10 to 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   All the cases arose from stops by two state troopers, John Hogan
and James Kenna, on the New Jersey Turnpike in late 1996, 1997 or
early 1998. In April 1998, the two troopers were involved in the
shooting of three unarmed black and Hispanic men during a traffic
stop on the turnpike. A grand jury is still investigating that
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   After a five-minute hearing, Lawrence West, first assistant
Middlesex County prosecutor, said in a statement that if those 24
cases had gone to trial, defense lawyers might have raised the
issue of indictments filed in April against Hogan and Kenna for
falsifying records to make it appear that they had stopped more
white drivers. Most of the people whose cases were dismissed
Wednesday are black or Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   West also said in his statement that if the cases went to trial,
Hogan and Kenna might invoke their Fifth Amendment rights against
self-incrimination and decline to testify for the state.
</P>
<P>
   Kenna's lawyer, John Arseneault, denounced the attorney
general's office and the Middlesex prosecutors for dropping the
cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's outrageous,'' Arseneault said in a phone interview. ``The
very guardians of our criminal justice system are ignoring the
presumption of innocence. At a minimum, the people of New Jersey
should be afforded the opportunity of seeing if Troopers Kenna and
Hogan are credible before these cases are dismissed.''
</P>
<P>
   Arseneault said he had previously told the attorney general's
office that Kenna ``was more than willing to continue testifying to
make these cases.''
</P>
<P>
   When West filed a motion for the dismissals last Friday, it
originally contained the names of 21 defendants. The indictments
his office released Wednesday contained 3 additional names.
</P>
<P>
   Arseneault said that Kenna had arrested 3 of the 24 people. They
included a Bronx man, Damian Steplight, who was accused of seizing
Kenna's patrol car after the trooper had stopped Steplight and two
friends on March 18, 1998. Steplight was charged with stealing the
car and with aggravated assault for driving it at Kenna, who was
not hurt in the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Before Wednesday's hearing, Steplight was the only defendant of
the 24 who had remained in the Middlesex County Jail, unable to
post bail. His release was expected shortly.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan's lawyer, Robert Galantucci of Hackensack, did not return
phone calls left at his office.
</P>
<P>
   After Wednesday's dismissals, Middlesex County Public Defender
Thomas Scully said he and his staff had started reviewing hundreds
of files, looking for any cases of clients who had pleaded guilty
to or been convicted of charges filed by the two troopers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to take action to have pleas vacated or seek new
trials,'' he said. ``But I don't have any idea of the number we'll
find.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
