</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CLINTONS-HOME-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REAL-WORLD LOCALE FIT FOR A FIRST COUPLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LISA W. FODERARO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ As Hillary Rodham Clinton ponders life
after 1600 Pennsylvania Ave., Westchester County has popped up on
the radar screen. And why not? It offers such amenities as leafy
privacy, relative proximity to the restaurant Le Cirque 2000 and,
perhaps most important, something to occupy her husband: golf.
</P>
<P>
   Westchester, which would give Mrs. Clinton a requisite New York
address if she runs for the U.S. Senate, was abuzz this week after
reports that the first lady had asked aides to begin looking for a
home here. But the president's favorite pastime could,
paradoxically, end up handicapping the county in the selection
process. Though Westchester does have lots of private golf clubs _
50 to be exact _ it turns out that the best courses are hard to
crack.
</P>
<P>
   Winged Foot Golf Club in Mamaroneck, which ranks in the top 10
on Golf Digest's annual list of the greatest courses in the United
States, has a 15-year waiting list. When asked whether members
would let the president jump to the front of the line, Colin Burns,
the club's general manager, said: ``Honestly? Probably not.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the brand new and highly touted Hudson National
Golf Club in Croton-on-Hudson, which has six member slots
available. But membership there would really set the Clintons back.
The initiation fee is $317,000.
</P>
<P>
   So much for golf. There is always sailing on Long Island Sound
and horseback riding in northern Westchester. And while local
politicians were cheering the news and image-makers cautioning the
Clintons not to go too upscale, real estate agents were debating
which areas of the county would give the Clintons the most for
their money.
</P>
<P>
   To the south, gracious towns like Rye, Scarsdale and Harrison
would put Clinton within chipping distance of the best courses
(where he could presumably play as a guest) and would give the
couple a fast commute into New York City. Westchester County
Airport is nearby, too, for easy access to Buffalo, Rochester and
Albany _ important stops for any conscientious senator.
</P>
<P>
   But the densely populated southern end of the county would mean
that the Clintons' neighbors would be ho-hum type-A professionals,
as opposed to the worldly residents of Westchester's horse country,
where Glenn Close and Ralph Lauren live. Another drawback is the
scarcity of land, with a million-dollar-plus house typically
squeezed onto a scant acre _ not the sort of space conducive to
permanently stationed Secret Service agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``For privacy and all, she would have to be somewhere where
there's acreage, and that's why my feeling was that it would be
northern Westchester rather than southern Westchester,'' said Ruth
Chizzini, a real estate agent who, like others, referred to the
first lady with a chummy personal pronoun.
</P>
<P>
   An agent who is in charge of relocations for Julia B. Fee Real
Estate, Ms. Chizzini hated to steer Mrs. Clinton away from the
south because that is her territory. She then scrambled to come up
with an estate or two in places like Harrison and Rye.
</P>
<P>
   Big properties are out there, to be sure, and although they
might make a nice transition from the 132-room White House to the
real world, they might not fit the Clintons' budget _ given their
legal bills and relatively modest public-service salary of late.
</P>
<P>
   In Harrison, for example, there is a brick-and-stone colonial on
13 acres, with a guest cottage, caretaker's cottage,
``entertainment house,'' pond, tennis court, pool and formal
gardens _ all behind electronic gates. The price tag is $5.25
million; the tax bill is $51,481.
</P>
<P>
   That property would put the Clintons in the same town as Rep.
Nita Lowey, the Westchester Democrat who is considering her own run
for the U.S. Senate _ but only if Mrs. Clinton demurs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Of course, there are those who simply do not believe reports
that the Clintons have designs on Westchester. Mrs. Clinton's
friends told The New York Times Magazine that her representatives
were looking at potential locations in Westchester, and the couple
are said to be considering both security and proximity to golf
courses. A spokeswoman for Mrs. Clinton would say Wednesday only
that the couple planned to move to New York after leaving the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Sale, a health-care executive in New York City and a
native of Arkansas who has known the president and the first lady
since college, said, ``I'm absolutely flabbergasted that anyone
would move from downtown Washington to the suburbs, even such
glorious suburbs as those in Westchester County.''
</P>
<P>
   Another scenario for the Clintons would be a pied-a-terre in
Manhattan and a country place in the Bedford area, which is fast
becoming Hollywood-on-the-Hudson. Golfing opportunities there are
good but not great, with Waccabuc Country Club and the Bedford Golf
and Tennis Club cited as having fairly challenging courses.
</P>
<P>
   Towns like Bedford, Pound Ridge and Lewisboro would give the
Clintons privacy and rolling countryside, and the opportunity to
rub elbows with celebrities like Susan Sarandon and Tim Robbins,
but without the microscope of the news media in places like the
Hamptons.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether the Clintons could actually afford a home
in one of these places, some experts in political appearances say
it would be a mistake for Mrs. Clinton to move into a mansion if
she plans to run for office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here you'd have someone moving out of the big White House into
the big Westchester house, and if she's running for U.S. Senate,
the average person might say, `How does she understand our
problems?''' said a Westchester resident who has worked with the
Clintons in politics but who spoke on the condition that his name
not be used.
</P>
<P>
   Such political considerations were far from the mind of Andrew
Spano, the Westchester County executive and a fellow Democrat. For
him, rumors that the first couple were Westchester-bound were the
ultimate stamp of approval on his domain. ``We're ecstatic,'' he
crowed. ``This is probably one of the most traveled couples in the
United States, and with all the places, they chose Westchester.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
