<SLUG> BC-FBN-REPLAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL UNVEILS INSTANT-REPLAY SYSTEM TO CORRECT WRONG CALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The 16 newest teams in the National Football League
will not wear uniforms, run, catch, or block. But in the
unglamorous positions of communicator, technician, replay assistant
and video operator, they may be crucial to every game each week.
</P>
<P>
   They are the four-member instant replay teams that will operate
the league's $10 million plan to right on-field wrongs with greater
speed and accuracy than the previous system, which was used from
1986 to 1991. A series of high-profile, disputed calls last season
led to an outcry for instant replay's return in a modern form,
which the league approved in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is designed to correct mistakes the world knows was a
mistake except to officials on the field because they might have
been blocked,'' said Dennis Lewin, the league's senior vice
president for broadcasting. ``Everyone at home is saying, `How can
that be the call?'''
</P>
<P>
   Under the system, coaches will be able to challenge two plays
each game, though none in the final two minutes of each half. A
coach will alert the referee or umpire to a challenge by pressing a
two-button buzzer. The referee will announce the challenge, and the
replay team in a stadium booth with three monitors and a digitized
replay retrieval system will arrange the replays fed by the network
broadcaster in order of potential importance.
</P>
<P>
   From the time the referee begins watching the tapes on a monitor
(with a headset with which he can communicate with the replay
team), he will have 90 seconds to uphold or deny a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   If the coach's challenge is denied, the team loses a timeout.
Coaches will have until the start of the next play to request a
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Within the last two minutes of each half, only the replay
assistant in the booth will be able to initiate a review. Again,
the replays will be arranged and the referee will rule on the
challenge. There can be an unlimited number of reviews during these
crucial periods of the game and no timeouts will be charged.
</P>
<P>
   A demonstration of the system at league meetings yesterday
showed how the replay team would have operated when a quarterback
sneak by the Jets' Vinny Testaverde with 20 seconds left against
Seattle last Dec. 6 was incorrectly ruled a touchdown. The Jets
won, 32-31.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's look at that spot,'' Mike Pereira, a league referee
supervisor who played the role of a replay assistant, said as he
watched the play as shown live by CBS. ``He might have gone down,
but No. 40 is blocking me out. Let's see if there are any
replays.'' In real time, the first replay comes up. ``Replay!''
said Dick Maxwell, another league official, playing the
communicator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ball's down, ball's down!'' said Pereira, seeing a replay that
showed Testaverde was stopped before the goal line. ``Stop the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, he buzzes me,'' said Jerry Seeman, the league's senior
director of officiating, portraying the referee down on the field.
``And I'll say, `We are reviewing the ruling on the field.''' After
looking at the replay on a monitor, Seeman said, ``I can see the
ball is short. It's on the half-yard line. And now I'll say, `After
reviewing the play, the ball is short of the first down. Seattle
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The system won't always operate seamlessly. It cannot review
replays shown after another play begins. The replay teams will
sometimes have to rush to analyze plays when teams are in no-huddle
offenses. Sometimes, the replay assistant will have enough time
only to look at the live play before deciding it's worthy of review
during the last two minutes of a half.
</P>
<P>
   The replay teams will be limited to the number of replays shown
by the networks, which can have as few as five videotape machines
at certain games.
</P>
<P>
   And, inevitably, the time spent reviewing replays will lengthen
each game, a bugaboo when instant replay was last reviewed, as
officials sometimes huddled for minutes to review plays.
</P>
<P>
   Pereira said, ``Anytime I shut it down, it's going to be
two-and-a-half minutes from start to finish.''
</P>
<P>
   In other action taken here, the league approved interest-free
loans to New England, Philadelphia and Denver to finance a portion
of the private cost of building new stadiums. The NFL will lend
$112 million to the Patriots, $54 million to the Eagles and $43
million to the Broncos, to be repaid from club seat revenues that
otherwise would have been paid to visiting teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots expect to move into the $225 million stadium in
Foxboro in 2001. Earlier this week, a Massachusetts measure to
provide $70 million in roadway and other improvements was signed
into law. ``Life is all about compromise for big things and the
Legislature stepped up and did what they had to do,'' said Patriots
owner Robert Kraft, who walked away from a plan to build a $374
million stadium in Hartford.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 2338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
