<SLUG> BC-NY-JAIL-BEATING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG ISLAND JAIL GUARDS CHARGED IN INMATE'S BEATING DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ Three guards at the Nassau County jail were
charged Wednesday with violating the civil rights of an inmate who
prosecutors say died from a vicious beating at the hands of two of
the guards in January. Prosecutors say the third guard acted as a
lookout during the beating.
</P>
<P>
   The three correction officers named in the attack could face
life in prison, and a fourth, charged with preparing a fake report
saying the inmate suffered his injuries slipping in the shower,
could receive up to 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The inmate, Thomas Pizzuto, was beaten in his cell a day after
he began serving a 90-day sentence for driving while impaired.
Several days later he died of a ruptured spleen and quickly became
a symbol of what many former inmates and prisoners' advocates say
is a long history of brutality inside the county jail. Between 1991
and 1998, officials received more than 100 complaints of assaults
by guards, and still more allegations have surfaced since Pizzuto's
death.
</P>
<P>
   In the months since Pizzuto's death alone, Nassau County has
paid $3 million to settle three civil rights lawsuits by former
inmates.In one of those cases, a former president of the correction
officers' union was found liable for severely beating a mentally
retarded man.
</P>
<P>
   According to an indictment unsealed Wednesday in federal court
in Uniondale, Pizzuto was beaten by Patrick Regnier, 36, and Edward
Velazquez, 32, both of Farmingdale, while the third officer, Ivano
Bavaro, 32, of Valley Stream, acted as a lookout just outside
Pizzuto's cell. Investigators have said that the guards were
annoyed by the repeated demands of Pizzuto, a heroin addict, for
methadone.
</P>
<P>
   The three guards were charged with depriving Pizzuto of his
constitutional right to be free of cruel or unusual punishment.
Corporal Joseph Bergen, 47, of Bethpage, who began his shift after
the attack took place, is charged as an accessory after the fact
for drafting and signing the false accident report.
</P>
<P>
   The four officers are being prosecuted by the U.S. attorney for
the Eastern District of New York, Zachary Carter, who is also
investigating whether a ``pattern and practice'' of civil rights
violations exists at the jail, which is overseen by the Nassau
County sheriff. Such a finding could eventually mean court-ordered
reforms or even a federal takeover of the jail.
</P>
<P>
   The four guards were arrested at their homes at 5 a.m. At an
arraignment Wednesday before U.S. District Court Judge Jacob
Mishler, the men were required to post $500,000 bond secured by
their homes and to surrender their passports. Sheriff Joseph
Jablonsky said all four had been automatically suspended without
pay Wednesday because of the indictments.
</P>
<P>
   Until their arrests, Jablonsky said, the defendants had clean
records. ``All of them have very good work records,'' he said. ``We
went to their work folders, and there were no disciplinary reports
against any of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff rejected suggestions that abuses were common at the
jail. ``I know the atmosphere for law enforcement out there right
now is very negative, because of everything that's going on,'' he
said, alluding to the cases of Abner Louima and Amadou Diallo in
New York City. ``But this is an isolated incident, and these
officers deserve their day in court.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the four accused guards said their clients looked
forward to trial and hinted at a possible defense strategy. ``
Pizzuto was not a picture of physical health'' before he arrived at
the jail, said Edward Jenks, the lawyer for Bavaro. ``I say they're
going to have a difficult time linking a homicide to these
defendants.''
</P>
<P>
   Family members at the news conference broke down in tears as
they remembered Pizzuto as a hard working man who had been disabled
more than a decade ago, had battled back from a heroin addiction,
and had tried his best to provide for his wife and 15-year-old son,
Thomas Jr., who has Down syndrome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
