<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SHURMUR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS' ASSISTANT LEAVES TEAM FOR UNSPECIFIED ILLNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARSNWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Fritz Shurmur is ill. Seriously ill.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Seahawks' new defensive coordinator had his annual
physical this week and left Wednesday for Green Bay, Wisc., where
he will begin receiving treatment for an unspecified illness.
</P>
<P>
   Details of Shurmur's condition are being withheld at his
request.
</P>
<P>
   The news was a shock to Mike Holmgren, who brought Shurmur to
Seattle in January after the former Packers coach was named
Seahawks general manager and head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was stunned, big time,'' a visibly shaken Holmgren said. ``I
knew the tests were going to take place. I knew that there was the
potential for something pretty serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the results of those tests caught Seahawks staff members
by surprise. Many of the other assistant coaches were in Atlanta on
Wednesday for a coaching symposium. Holmgren flew back to Seattle
Wednesday from the NFL owners meetings, also being held in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Shurmur, 66, had participated in the team's minicamp two weeks
ago and appeared to be himself, cajoling players during practice
and joking with reporters afterward.
</P>
<P>
   But he started feeling out of sorts last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fritz said, `I feel kind of crummy,' '' Holmgren said. ``I
said, `Well, we're getting our physicals (next week). Hang on.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Shurmur underwent tests Monday and Tuesday and informed Holmgren
of his illness Tuesday night. Shurmur's wife, Peggy, and son,
Scott, who is a cardiologist, flew to Seattle so they could
accompany him back to Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Shurmur was given the OK to receive treatment in Green Bay after
consulting with doctors in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fritz has been diagnosed with a serious illness that will
require a period of extensive treatment,'' Holmgren said. ``It is
the hope that the treatment will allow him to resume his coaching
duties sometime in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Shurmur's illness was life threatening, Holmgren
offered, ``I can't go into that.''
</P>
<P>
   Shurmur has earned a reputation as one of the game's most
innovative defensive minds during his 24 years as an assistant with
the Lions, Patriots, Rams, Cardinals, Packers and Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, his return to coaching is a minor concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Number 1 thing is Fritz taking care of himself and his
family,'' Holmgren said. ``The football part of it is really very
secondary at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   If forced to replace Shurmur, Holmgren named three assistants
who could be candidates _ linebackers coach Jim Lind, a former
college head coach; defensive line coach Larry Brooks, a former Pro
Bowl player with the Rams who has been on Holmgren's staff since
1994; and defensive backs coach Ken Flajole, who was a college
defensive coordinator before joining Holmgren's staff in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 2340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0482 </DOCNO>
