<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME BIG THUNDER IN BIG SKY COUNTRY  
 PUTTING FAMILY FIRST IN A LOUISIANA RACE  
 WITH ELWAY FREE, IT'S SPECULATION TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Hill, a conservative Republican who is sparsely
populated Montana's sole House member, won his first two elections
by fairly comfortable margins of about 10 percentage points. But
his third campaign is shaping up as a much closer contest _ and
maybe one of the most mean-spirited in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Hill's only challenger so far is Nancy Keenan, who is a Democrat
serving her third term as state school superintendent and before
that was a special-education teacher and a state representative.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Keenan announced her candidacy last week, accusing Hill of
being a political slave to the right wing and predicting that she
would beat him next year because, she said, she had already
demonstrated exceptional vote-pulling ability by winning three
statewide races in a Republican-leaning state.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, Hill counterattacked, saying he intended to
win by focusing his campaign on Ms. Keenan's ``lifestyle'' choices
and how they might affect her work as a lawmaker, a campaign issue
that most candidates assiduously avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Ms. Keenan is 47 and single, the congressman, who is
52, twice married and the father of three adult children, told Roll
Call, the Capitol Hill newspaper that specializes in congressional
issues: ``I'm a family man. I'm a grandparent. I'm a small-business
man. Nancy has never been married and obviously has no children. If
you haven't been there, you don't know what it's like, that
lifestyle. She's basically been working for the government all of
her life.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Hill in the attack on Ms. Keenan, Sue Aleksich-Akey, the
chairwoman of the Montana Republican Party whose husband, Larry
Akey, is Hill's congressional chief of staff, said, ``She really
doesn't fit in with the lifestyle of mainstream Montana.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Keenan called the remarks by Hill and Ms. Aleksich-Akey
``ridiculous'' and said they were typical of Republicans who have a
``far-right'' agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they can't defend their record,'' she told Roll Call,
``they immediately hit you on the lifestyle slander issue. I don't
think Hill knows how to deal with a smart woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, on Monday, Ms. Keenan told Montana reporters that she had
always wanted to have children but could not, because she had been
forced for health reasons to have a hysterectomy, an experience she
described as ``devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It changes your perspective in life, so then you adopt 150,000
kids,'' she added, alluding to her 25 years of service as a teacher
and state superintendent of schools.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she was worried that Hill might delve into her private
life in search of possibly embarrassing detail _ something he has
said he will not do _ Ms. Keenan replied that she had nothing to
hide and added: ``I'm a single woman. Period.''
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, she said, she would not make an issue of Hill's
past, a reference to the 1996 congressional race in which reports
surfaced that Hill had left his first wife after an affair with a
cocktail waitress and then had engaged in an eight-year legal
battle over child support. His response at the time: ``I've lived
up to my responsibilities every step of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Putting Family First in a Louisiana Race
</P>
<P>
   The special-election runoff on Saturday in Louisiana's 1st
Congressional District is still too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   A new poll conducted for WSDU-TV of New Orleans found David
Treen, the former governor and congressman, leading David Vitter, a
former state representative, by only three percentage points. That
is essentially a meaningless margin, given that about a third of
the voters polled remained undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Treen and Vitter ended up in the runoff after finishing first
and second in a May 1 special election that was called after the
1st District's veteran Republican congressman, Bob Livingston,
resigned. The field in the special election was so crowded that
nobody was able to garner the 50-percent-plus margin that would
have headed off a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of Saturday's vote was thrown even more into doubt
earlier this week when Treen canceled all personal appearances
after learning that his 20-year-old grandson, Jason Neville, was
missing while hiking in Oregon over the weekend. Treen flew to
Oregon on Tuesday to help in the search, saying, ``For the time
being, I'm putting my family first.''
</P>
<P>
   Neville was found on Wednesday, in good health, and Treen was
expected to return to Louisiana as soon as possible to resume
campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   With Elway Free, It's Speculation Time
</P>
<P>
   When John Elway, the All-Star quarterback for the Denver
Broncos, started talking about retirement a couple of years ago, it
was as sure as a pass on third-and-long that speculation would
follow about whether he would run for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Once the guessing began, the personable, movie-idol-handsome
Sunday afternoon hero showed that he understood how to play the
political game, too. He flew to Washington to chat up members of
Colorado's House delegation, a trip that led to talk that he had
fixed his postretirement eye on representing Colorado's 6th
Congressional District, his home district.
</P>
<P>
   But then he decided to stick with football for a few more years,
fixing his eye instead on a Super Bowl ring and saying he had to
stick around Denver to keep an eye on his lucrative automobile
dealerships, all 17 of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats buy cars, too,'' said Elway, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Now, two Super Bowls later, he has his ring _ two of them, in
fact. And as of a few weeks ago, he is also retired.
</P>
<P>
   So will his next run be a political run? Or will he pass?
</P>
<P>
   He's not saying. But the speculation has begun again, and over
the weekend The Rocky Mountain News fueled it by publishing a poll
indicating that Coloradans think John Elway ``hung the moon,'' as
the paper put it. Six of every 10 people polled said they held a
``very positive'' view of him.
</P>
<P>
   Of the other public figures tested _ President Clinton, Charlton
Heston and Colorado's three top elected officials, Gov. Bill Owens
and Sens. Wayne Allard and Ben Nighthorse Campbell _ none was able
to win a ``very positive'' rating from more than two of every 10
Coloradans.
</P>
<P>
   How did the Elway numbers strike Sean Murphy, executive director
of the Colorado Republican Party?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tremendous amount of hope that he'll run for
office,'' Murphy said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
