<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-EDIT-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GUNS IN THE HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, May 27:
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans can read the polls as well as anyone. Thus GOP
leaders who just a week ago were adamant about blocking any action
to curb guns are now planning to graft an array of gun-control
measures onto a juvenile crime bill due to hit the floor next
month.
</P>
<P>
   But if Speaker Dennis Hastert and his colleagues want to
persuade Americans that they are finally serious about keeping guns
away from juveniles and criminals, they will have to do a lot
better than the meager menu of changes currently being considered.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most important steps was ignored by the Senate and is
not part of the current discussion in the House. Congress needs to
mandate a move to ``smart-gun'' technology _ computer chips and
other features that make guns inoperable by anyone other than the
weapon's owner.
</P>
<P>
   This is the aim of a ground-breaking measure now advancing in
the New Jersey Legislature. Opponents question the ``commercial
viability'' of smart guns. But there are already about 30 patents,
ranging from devices that read fingerprints and compare them with
those of authorized users to radio-controlled or magnetic systems
that match a mechanism in the gun with a remote unit carried by the
authorized users.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey bill would give gun makers up to five years to
switch to smart guns. But with a prod from Congress, personalized
guns that are truly childproof could be on the market before that.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans aim only to replicate the disappointing
package passed by the Senate with a few new twists, some of them
quite troubling. For example, there is talk that Republican leaders
may water down the Senate gun-show provision by limiting the period
for conducting background checks to just 24 hours, instead of the
72 hours approved by the Senate. That is hardly enough time for law
enforcement officials to track down convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Americans eager for congressional action on gun control deserve
more from House Republicans. Hastert should announce that he
intends to allow full debate and recorded votes on vital
gun-control steps the Senate either rejected or ignored. These
include requiring smart guns, subjecting Internet gun sales to
background checks, reinstating the Brady waiting period for
purchasing guns and limiting gun sales to individuals to one per
month to deter large-scale gun trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the disappointing package under consideration has a
lot in common with the glass-front gun cabinet from which the
sophomore in Georgia took the weapons he fired at his schoolmates
last week. It may look good, and it may be better than nothing. But
it won't deter determined teen-agers from obtaining firearms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
