<SLUG> BC-OBIT-RUBIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMON RUBIAL, 92, SPANISH SOCIALIST LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ramon Rubial, a veteran of the Spanish Civil War who spent
nearly 20 years in prison under the Franco regime, died Monday at
his home in Bilbao, Spain. He was 92.
</P>
<P>
   Rubial, widely respected as the living memory of Spanish
socialism, still held the honorary title of president of the
Spanish Socialist Workers Party at his death. According to the
Spanish news agency EFE, King Juan Carlos and all of the country's
political parties joined in honoring him for having spent much of
his life in the defense of liberty and the rights of working
people.
</P>
<P>
   Born in an industrial town in the coastal Basque province
Vizcaya, Ramon Rubial Cavia was the son of a metalworker and a
presser. When only 5, he attended a meeting in Bilbao with Pablo
Iglesias, the founder of both the Spanish Socialist Workers Party
and a socialist labor union.
</P>
<P>
   He took up his father's trade while in his teens and joined the
union at 14 and the Socialist Party two years later.
</P>
<P>
   Rising to prominence in both organizations, Rubial fought on the
side of the government against the military uprising led by Gen.
Francisco Franco in 1936. The following year he was taken prisoner
on the front lines.
</P>
<P>
   After the defeat of the government defenders in 1939, Franco
seized power and dealt ruthlessly with his opponents. The union and
the Socialist Party were banned by the new government, and Rubial
served several stints in jail for a total of nearly 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   After his release in 1957 he became ``Pablo,'' the party's
leader in the underground. With Franco's death a new generation of
socialists came to the fore under Felipe Gonzalez, a future prime
minister, in the mid-1970s. Rubial became their titular president
and served as a senator from Viscaya and chief of the Basque
regional government since then.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0485 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2828 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      05-26 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Wales: Queen Opens New Parliament
</P>
<P>
   In a ceremony with notably less pageantry than the annual
opening of the British Parliament, Queen Elizabeth officially
inaugurated the new Welsh Assembly, describing it as a ``creative
response to changing times and aspirations.'' The legislature in
Cardiff and the just elected Scottish Parliament in Edinburgh were
created under Prime Minister Tony Blair's program to shift power
over regional matters from London to the two capitals.
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Viagra Ruling Voided
</P>
<P>
   England's High Court ruled that the government's decision to
restrict prescription of the impotence drug Viagra was unlawful.
Health Secretary Frank Dobson had ordered the limited prescribing,
saying that otherwise the National Health Service would be
bankrupted. The case was brought by Pfizer Ltd., maker of the drug,
which said it might now sue for loss of profits. The government is
expected to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Britain, Argentina: Falkland Optimism
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Guido Di Tella of Argentina met over dinner in
London with representatives of the Falkland Islands in the first
direct talks since Britain and Argentina went to war over the
islands in 1982. The talks will continue over the next couple of
days, encouraging hopes in Buenos Aires that commercial flights
between Argentina and the islands might be restarted for the first
time in 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland: Nazi Fund Advances
</P>
<P>
   The government has taken the first step to sell off its gold
reserves and use the proceeds, in part, to finance a fund to aid
needy victims of the Nazis. The idea for the fund grew out of the
controversy over Switzerland's wartime role as a financier for
Germany. The government sent Parliament legislation to follow
through on last month's nationwide vote to end the pegging of the
franc to gold, clearing the way for the national bank to sell some
of its considerable reserves.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   Israel: Netanyahu Appears
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu made his first public
appearance since losing the election on May 17, greeting 100
refugees from Kosovo at Ben-Gurion Airport. But he made no
statements, ignoring questions from reporters. Stung by Israeli
press reports that he had effectively ceased working, Netanyahu met
with security ministers for the first time since the victory by
Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Cambodia: Pol Pot Murdered?
</P>
<P>
   An imprisoned Khmer Rouge leader, Ta Mok, has reportedly
asserted that the Communist movement's chieftain, Pol Pot, was
murdered in April 1998 and did not die of heart failure as
originally claimed. Without disclosing a name, Ta Mok's lawyer,
Benson Samay, said he had been told ``everything about who ordered
the killing.''
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia: Suharto Inquiry Broadened
</P>
<P>
   President B.J. Habibie assigned two top officials to visit
Switzerland and Australia to see whether his predecessor, Suharto,
had hidden millions dollars in foreign bank accounts. The order,
more than a year after Suharto resigned, comes two weeks before an
election in which Habibie's opponents are accusing him of leniency
toward the former president.
</P>
<P>
   Cambodia: Talks with Vietnam
</P>
<P>
   Meeting with officials in Vietnam, Cambodia's National Assembly
chairman, Norodom Ranariddh, said the two countries were determined
to solve longstanding differences including border disputes and the
role of ethnic Vietnamese who live in Cambodia. Particularly
difficult are disputes over sovereignty and fishing rights.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Mayoral Hat in the Ring
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Silva Herzog, a former Treasury minister and former
Mexican ambassador to Washington, said he intends to seek the
governing party's nomination for mayor of Mexico City. The post,
currently held by Cuauhtemoc Cardenas of a leftist opposition
party, is the country's most important elected office after the
presidency. Silva Herzog will compete in a primary on Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Opposition Might Unite
</P>
<P>
   The two major opposition parties have begun formal meetings to
see if they can forge an alliance to run a single candidate in
presidential elections next year. Polls consistently show that the
National Action Party, which is center-right, and the social
democratic Party of the Democratic Revolution must unite to beat
the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party. But deep
ideological differences persist.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina: Opposition Platform
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Fernando de la Rua of Buenos Aires, the opposition
coalition's presidential candidate, released details of his
campaign platform, pledging to continue President Carlos Saul
Menem's policy of pegging the peso to the dollar and halving the
unemployment rate, now more than 13 percent. But he also vowed to
investigate corruption in the current government, even if it meant
jailing former officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
