<HEADER>
A2830 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-SABRES-PECA-745&AMP;A     05-26 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-PECA-745&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SABRES' NICE GUY NEEDS TO TOUGH IT OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Many of Michael Peca's Sabres teammates were
still on the ice Wednesday, working through practice in Marine
Midland Arena. Among them were Dominik Hasek, the superb goalie
with the severe groin pull, and Miroslav Satan, the high-scoring
forward with the badly bruised foot.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek missed the last two playoff games and Satan has missed the
last month. Both hope to play Thursday night when the Sabres face
Toronto here in Game 3 of the Eastern Conference finals. Satan's
chances are better than Hasek's.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday's practice was optional and Peca chose not to
skate, with permission of his coach, Lindy Ruff. He left early,
walking through the parking lot on a gray, chilly day, the wind
brisk off Lake Erie and the Niagara River.
</P>
<P>
   The captain of the Sabres, who is tied with Jason Woolley for
the team lead in the playoffs with 11 points, Peca played his worst
game of the tournament Tuesday night in Toronto. He was minus-three
in the plus/minus ratio, meaning the Maple Leafs had success when
Peca was on the ice. Toronto won by 6-3, evening the four-of-seven
game series at one victory each.
</P>
<P>
   Peca, a center, didn't put any shots on goal. Assigned to check
the Maple Leafs' top forwards for three rounds, and slightly built
at 5 feet 11 inches and 181 pounds, he seemed weary. Buffalo fans
fear that fatigue has drained his energy and diminished the Sabres'
chances of reaching the Stanley Cup finals against Dallas or
Colorado. Peca smiled at this thought Wednesday and answered in an
ironic tone of voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that one game, I think it's all over, it's nothing but
downhill,'' he said. ``I think everybody gets a little tired.
Obviously, with the minutes and everything else, from here on out
it would probably be best if I don't skate the days in between
games and just rest up a little bit. We haven't had any days off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one bad one,'' he said of Tuesday night's game, ``one
where the legs weren't there. By no means do I feel I haven't got
anything in the tank. I feel very good today and I expect to be
great again tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Peca also said the heat in Air Canada Center might have been a
factor in his lack of energy. ``It's a matter of getting off your
feet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He wore jeans, a sweatshirt and sneakers. His glasses, with
silver-wire rims, had small lenses. His cheeks and chin showed a
thick, dark stubble of beard. At 25, he is in his sixth National
Hockey League season and second as a captain. Peca has matured
rapidly. The day before, in Toronto, he had talked at length about
an athlete's duty as a role model and how he has to take care of
his image as well as his body when off the ice.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, after a few polite answers to a few leading
questions, he apologized for making reporters follow him to the
parking lot. Then Peca climbed into his sports utility vehicle and
drove home to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Since October, Peca has played 82 regular-season games and 12 in
the playoffs. He scored a career-best 27 goals and 56 points this
season. In the tournament, four of his 11 points have come on
goals.
</P>
<P>
   Peca has become one of the league's premier two-way centers,
able to stop top foes with smart positioning and hard hitting. He
said he and his linemates must return to their forechecking ways
and ``get a few big hits early in the game.'' They need to avoid
trying to ``make the fancy play over the blue line,'' he added,
``instead of getting it deep and doing what we do best, and that's
cycle the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   Dixon Ward, one of Peca's close friends on the Sabres, said
after practice Wednesday: ``He plays a lot of hockey. He plays a
very physical style. He's going to get a little bit tired, no
question. He was a little tired last night. He was a little short
on energy. `Pecks' is the kind of guy who can take one day and
bounce back and rehydrate and get himself back to high energy. We
need him. He's going to be there tomorrow night, no question.''
</P>
<P>
   From a business point of view, the league also needs Peca, as an
outspoken example of moderation. One of the major stories of this
spring's tournament was the death of Steve Chiasson, the Carolina
defenseman, in a car crash May 4 while he was driving drunk after a
postgame party.
</P>
<P>
   Without referring directly to Chiasson, Peca talked of drinking
in the hockey culture that sometimes begins at age 16, when players
leave home to play as juniors. Peca still drinks, moderately and
occasionally, but said he has cut back in recent years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Alcohol is a drug like anything else and it affects your body
whether you are willing to believe it or not,'' Peca said. ``When
you come into the league, at first, it's like it's supposed to be a
party, the peer pressure to hang out with the guys until the bar
closes. It's a tag, attached to hockey players, that they are
drinkers. You feel you need to be like that. You look back on that
and it's a pretty sad thing. It's sad when guys say they can drink
and play without it affecting them. I think it's an ignorant
statement because it does affect you. You just don't realize it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another type of legal drug, steroids, is not specifically
forbidden in hockey, but Peca said he steers clear of steroids.
``For a guy like me, it would be obvious if I took steroids,'' he
said. ``It's cheating. It's something you are doing to cheat the
system. There are natural ways to benefit your body and enhance
performance. Steroids are for people trying to gain an edge the
short way and often the wrong way.''
</P>
<P>
   Peca was born and raised in the Toronto area. His father works
for a parcel delivery service and his mother is in the day-care
industry. Although he did not admit it, he might have felt some
pressure to perform in this first-ever playoff match between his
current team and his home-town team. He seems self-aware and
discussed public behavior and public image.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take it very seriously,'' Peca said. ``Not just because
people are watching and kids may be looking for an idol or a role
model. But people just like to keep an eye on you so they can say
something negative about you at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife work with charities such as juvenile diabetes, a
children's hospital and the Big Brothers/Big Sisters organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times people feel athletes get involved with
charities to bolster their image,'' Peca said. ``But once you spend
a couple days with some of these kids, it makes you feel really
good and that's what it's all about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
