<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-INDIA-PAKISTAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FLARE-UP IN KASHMIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, May 27:
</P>
<P>
   The snow has usually melted in the Himalayan foothills by this
time of year, and it is not uncommon for India and Pakistan to
engage in artillery fire across their disputed border. On
Wednesday, however, tensions between these two nuclear powers
escalated sharply with an Indian air attack on alleged infiltrators
from Pakistan in Indian-held territory in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   The new hostilities are dangerous. Both nations should exercise
military restraint, pull back from their confrontation and renounce
the use of force to settle their conflict.
</P>
<P>
   India and Pakistan have fought three wars since their
independence and partition 52 years ago. But since both nations
tested nuclear devices a year ago, any flare-up is reason for
concern.
</P>
<P>
   Though preoccupied by Kosovo, the United States and other
countries should make clear that India and Pakistan cannot afford
this kind of brinkmanship. They should return to the cooperative
spirit of February, when Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee of
India visited Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif in Lahore and the two
leaders pledged to redouble their attempt to reach agreements on
nuclear and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Muslim-dominated state of Kashmir has long been the scene of
rebellion by guerrillas seeking independence from India. India has
long asserted that Islamic militants from Pakistan and Afghanistan
have infiltrated with aid from the Pakistani military, a charge
that Pakistan denies. There is credible evidence, however, that in
the last week or two several hundred invaders have intruded on the
Indian side of the 50-year-old border.
</P>
<P>
   Both India and Pakistan are going through domestic political
turmoil. Sharif has been cracking down on dissent and Vajpayee's
government lost a vote of no confidence last month, clearing the
way for an election.
</P>
<P>
   But neither Sharif nor Vajpayee can afford to be distracted by
internal politics. They need to do more to exchange information,
defuse the tension on the border, halt the testing of weapons and
pull back forces before hostilities spin out of control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-26-99 2351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990526.0488 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 00:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2836 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-SPENDING-1STLD-     05-26 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-SPENDING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE ACTS TO PROTECT SOCIAL SECURITY SURPLUS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: SUBS headline; TOPS with five grafs on Social Security vote)  (rk) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Keenly aware of the political volatility of Social
Security, the House Wednesday overwhelmingly passed legislation
that would put new hurdles in the way of spending any surpluses
that come from the program.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-backed legislation passed 416 to 12, with most
Democrats supporting it as well. ``Workers should have the
confidence that the money they pay into Social Security and
Medicare is used only for Social Security and Medicare,'' Speaker
Dennis Hastert said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although this bill will probably not make things any worse, it
won't make them any better,'' said Rep. Joe Moakley, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A stricter version of the bill has been languishing in the
Senate because of Democrats' objections, and the legislation faces
a veto threat from President Clinton. Only last week, Congress
approved and the president signed an emergency spending bill
financed with nearly $13 billion in excess Social Security
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Before the vote on Social Security, whose financing and future
stability are nearly always hot political issues and often
misunderstood ones, conservatives in the House mounted a challenge
to Hastert by trying to derail the year's first spending bill on
the floor of the House.
</P>
<P>
   The House was tied in knots as Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., used
legislative guerrilla tactics that stopped a Republican-approved
$60.8 billion agriculture bill cold.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, the first of 13 spending measures that will come to
the House floor this year, was supposed to be easy to pass. But it
was threatened with death by a thousand cuts _ or 119, to be
precise.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn vowed to submit 119 amendments, one by one, until a
quarter-billion dollars is cut from the agriculture bill, bringing
it down to last year's level. He and his allies intend to force
Hastert to devise a grand strategy for financing the government
without dipping into surplus Social Security money.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn has solid backing from many House conservatives. The two
Texas Republicans who lead them _ the majority leader, Dick Armey,
and the majority whip, Tom DeLay _ voted for some of his
amendments, signaling their support.
</P>
<P>
   The ranking Democrat on the House Appropriations Committee, Rep.
David R. Obey of Wisconsin, said those votes showed that ``the
leadership of the House on the Republican side is cooperating in
the destruction of its own ability to produce any progress on
appropriation bills for the rest of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   What is happening here has little to do with whether the
Agriculture Department spends an extra $300,000 on wool research,
money that would be cut by one of Coburn's myriad of amendments. It
will directly affect Republican plans to cut billions of dollars of
social programs, Democratic efforts to thwart them, and both
parties' vows to hold down federal spending.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn, an obstetrician by trade, is delivering a harsh message.
He says Hastert has ``no appropriations strategy'' and ``no plan to
control spending'' _ and no way to avoid repeating last year's
spectacle of a last-minute spending bill that included $21 billion
in extras.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert ``respects Coburn's resolve'' and did not oppose his
amendments, one of the speaker's spokesmen said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Coburn said he was not attacking Hastert's
leadership. But, he said, ``my team's got to have a game plan, and
we don't have one right now. The speaker doesn't feel he has a
strategy yet that'll work.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon, debate on the agriculture spending ceased.
Instead, the House began debating Republican legislation aimed at
locking away surplus Social Security and Medicaid funds. Only last
week, Congress approved and President Clinton signed an emergency
spending bill financed with nearly $13 billion in excess Social
Security revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn said Wednesday that he intended to keep trying to talk
the agriculture bill to death. ``My intent is to re-establish the
integrity of the House, to make them do what they said they were
going to do,'' namely, ensure the sanctity of Social Security
surpluses, said Coburn, who will retire next year.
</P>
<P>
   Though Democrats on the House floor called the parade of
amendments ``a spectacle'' and ``a circus,'' Coburn said, ``I think
the American people benefit from seeing the debates on how we spend
money, and the closer that we put the magnifying glass to it, the
better we are as a country.''
</P>
